A2226 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC--SUPERINTENDENT-CANDI     07-16 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC--SUPERINTENDENT-CANDIDATE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTRACT NEGOTIATIONS CONTINUE WITH KC SCHOOL CANDIDATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PHILLIP O'CONNOR  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Board of Education continued to negotiate
Thursday with superintendent candidate Benjamin Demps Jr. on an
annual contract that could pay him as much as $200,000, including
incentives.
</P>
<P>
   Board members are scheduled to meet at 6 p.m. Friday to vote on
a final agreement. If it is approved, Demps would travel to Kansas
City to sign the deal.
</P>
<P>
   An attorney for the district spent much of Thursday exchanging
proposals by telephone with Demps, who lives in Oklahoma City. He
is a retired Federal Aviation Administration official who served as
director of the Oklahoma Department of Human Services in the early
1990s. He is now semiretired and operates an aviation consulting
business.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said they were not sure when he would start work.
</P>
<P>
   Reached at his home Thursday afternoon, Demps, 65, said he was
pleased to receive the offer but added: ``This is the ticklish
part. I've got to take it one step at time. I hope things go well.
Maybe I'll get to Kansas City.''
</P>
<P>
   Demps would be the 19th interim or full-time superintendent in
30 years. He is the third person to be offered the job in the last
three weeks. The school board voted 7-2 late Wednesday to make the
offer.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, board member Lance Loewenstein disputed a statement
by board member Fifi Wiedeman that the majority of board members
voted for Demps because they were ``more concerned about being
removed from power than doing what is best for this district.''
</P>
<P>
   The school board is under orders from U.S. District Judge Dean
Whipple to reach agreement with a finalist by Monday. If it
doesn't, the court-appointed Desegregation Monitoring Committee
wants to appoint an interim superintendent while the school board
continues the search. The interim superintendent would report to
the committee, not the school board.
</P>
<P>
   Loewenstein said he thought the committee's proposal had little
effect on the board.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I was the only one who was afraid of the DMC's idea,''
Loewenstein said. ``I viewed the DMC's letter as nothing short of
receivership.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said any doubts he and others had about Demps were
relieved by positive reports from Oklahoma. Four board members
traveled there Wednesday to interview Demps' associates and former
co-workers at the Department of Human Services. They also met with
lawmakers, the administrator overseeing the state employees'
personnel office and representatives of several minority groups. In
addition, they met with the publisher of a minority-owned
newspaper, The Ebony Tribune, an Oklahoma City Board of Education
member and others.
</P>
<P>
   Most praised Demps' strong leadership and management skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this guy could have been hired without the deadline,''
Loewenstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Board member Sandy Mayer, who made the trip with Lee Barnes Jr.,
Connie Clark and Helen Ragsdale, said she was pleased to learn that
Demps had a strong record for promoting women within the Department
of Human Services.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good-old-boy network, and that was a very hard thing
for him to do _ to move the incompetent males out,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes said most of those he interviewed called Demps an
effective administrator.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he has clear goals and objectives from the board, he can
carry out those goals,'' Barnes said.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes also inquired about comments by the president of the
Oklahoma City NAACP, who criticized Demps in a television interview
as being uninvolved in minority affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Demps told Barnes that he did not have much personal involvement
with the NAACP but supported its efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes noted that the NAACP official is an employee of the
Department of Human Services, which Barnes said could have been a
factor.
</P>
<P>
   Other department employees told Barnes that Demps was ``as
aggressive as he could be on affirmative action in a merit
system.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes said he initially was concerned that Demps got most of
his management experience in large bureaucracies and in positions
that limited his contact with the public. The visit changed his
mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's more than willing to listen to those groups to see how
things affect their community,'' Barnes said.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike some other finalists, Demps was not being promoted
from the start.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was not an inclination to like this guy,'' Loewenstein
said. ``He was nobody's favorite. I think that indicates the
strength of his candidacy _ the fact that he came in not being
anyone's golden child and turned out to be the golden child. That
is the magic of this process. I really think we got the right
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   District officials are negotiating a salary package worth about
$200,000. The amount is similar to that received by the previous
superintendent, Henry Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The package would include Demps' car allowance and insurance and
annuity premium payments. In addition, board members are requesting
that part of the package be tied to performance in certain areas.
</P>
<P>
   Among them are his ability to improve teacher training, testing
and evaluation of students and accountability of students, teachers
and administrators. Many of those programs are a year behind
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Demps is being asked to review all of the
district's programs and services, quickly overhaul the Human
Resources Department and develop plans for employee recruitment,
evaluation and training.
</P>
<P>
   He will be expected to increase student attendance and reading
ability and reduce the dropout rate.
</P>
<P>
   He also could get more money by increasing the percentage of
students taking college placement tests and college-level courses.
</P>
<P>
   Some district patrons are skeptical that Demps' management
skills can work at an urban public school district. They question
whether a non-educator can tackle the job, given that improving the
academic performance of Kansas City district students remains the
top priority for the next leader.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes dismissed those complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understood that when we began talking to nontraditional
candidates.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
