<SLUG> BC-SWI-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTHERHOOD INSPIRING FOR QUANCE-JULIAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ On the starting blocks, swimmer Kristine
Quance-Julian is the same as she ever was. The way she stares at
the still water, it's a wonder the whole pool doesn't start
bubbling.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when the intensity Quance-Julian brings to her
swimming boiled over into other areas of her life. A bad workout
could agitate her for hours; a poor meet would leave her seething
for days.
</P>
<P>
   Then on Dec. 9 she had her first child, Trenton. Seven months
later, all the physical changes that her pregnancy wrought have
vanished. The extra 55 pounds are gone, leaving the same swimmer
but a noticeably different person.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have this renewed drive and I have a little boy, too,'' said
Quance-Julian, a 1996 Olympian who is one of the featured
competitors this weekend at the Janet Evans Invitational at USC.
``He is so much fun. He makes me forget all the stupid little
things I used to obsess about.''
</P>
<P>
   The old worries _ of beating her Chinese counterparts, of
meeting her own imperial standards _ have given way to graver
concerns. Trenton, a bouncy, babbling baby, has been slow to use
his arms and at seven months already is a veteran of physical
therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Their baby's hardships have given Quance-Julian and her husband,
Jeff, also a former world-class swimmer, a new appreciation for
their own bountiful physical gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Trenton is a trooper; it's Quance-Julian who seems to be
suffering. The former Granada Hills High standout has a guilt
attack every time she returns from swim practice and Jeff has gone
with Trenton to his therapy sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I feel like I'm such a bad parent,'' said
Quance-Julian, who looked nothing of the sort on this fine day as
she cooed at her gurgling son and enticed him with one of his plush
toys.
</P>
<P>
   In a little while, she and Trenton would be settling in for
their afternoon nap. That's part of the pact Quance-Julian and her
husband made after the baby's birth. For the next 14 months,
through the 2000 Olympics in Sydney, Quance-Julian's full-time job
is to concentrate on making her second Olympic team and winning the
individual gold medal that eluded her in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff quit his full-time gig as a financial planner in May
because the long and inflexible hours needed to set his clients up
with long-term peace of mind were threatening Trenton's short-term
security.
</P>
<P>
   So Jeff became Mr. Mom and Quance-Julian, I.M. Mama.
</P>
<P>
   Another Olympian, Angel Martino, has resumed her career after
giving birth. The difference is, she's a sprinter. Quance-Julian
excels in events such as the 400-meter individual medley and
200-meter butterfly that require easily twice the fortitude.
</P>
<P>
   No U.S. woman has made an Olympic swimming team in an event
longer than 100 meters after having a baby. If anybody is capable
of pulling it off, it's Quance-Julian, whom her coach at Trojan
Swim Club, Mark Schubert, describes as ``a compulsive
perfectionist.''
</P>
<P>
   It can be exhausting, aiming so high. Quance-Julian admits she
started mentally straying from her target after finishing far
behind two Chinese swimmers in the 400 I.M. at last year's World
Championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pregnancy looks like the best thing that could have
happened to her,'' Jeff said. ``It forced her to take a step back
and she realized she loved the sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Quance-Julian hadn't taken a break from racing in a decade, not
since she made her first senior-nationals standard at the age of
15. So it startled her almost as much as that first contraction
would when, confined to a bed in the last month of her pregnancy,
she actually started to crave the 400 I.M. as though it were some
pickle-and-pistachio-ice-cream combination.
</P>
<P>
   Understand: As far as combinations go, there are few less
appetizing than a brisk 100 meters each of butterfly, backstroke,
breaststroke and freestyle. Heartburn has nothing on the lung-burn
and limb-burn that settles in around the 300-meter mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't realize how much I missed racing,'' said
Quance-Julian, who has done well in the handful of meets she has
entered since May.
</P>
<P>
   She already has posted an unshaved, unrested time of 4 minutes,
52 seconds in the 400 meter I.M. If she can shave off another
second per lap at next month's nationals in Minneapolis, she'll
likely represent the U.S. at the Pan Pacific Games. They will be
held at the Olympic pool in Sydney in August.
</P>
<P>
   It matters less to Schubert how Quance-Julian swims this summer
than next. But for Quance-Julian, making the Pan Pacific team
matters a lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't say that's not my goal, even though my coaches say
it's no big deal,'' Quance-Julian said. ``I want to make (the team)
because I know there are plenty of people who think I'm stupid for
trying to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth? Probably the only one who thinks Quance-Julian has
something left to prove is . . . Quance-Julian.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the way she's wired,'' Schubert said with a shrug.
</P>
<P>
   A live cord dropped into the water _ that's Quance-Julian all
right. She's electrifying.
</P>
</TEXT>
