u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-SAFECO-SPI &LR;      07-16 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SAFECO-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTHING WAS GOING TO STOP FIRST FAN INTO SAFECO FIELD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ELLIS E. CONKLIN AND ALAN SNEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ They came ready to fall in love and few were
disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   On a mild summer evening, Safeco Field was flooded with
superlatives from a legion of fans. Words such as beautiful,
outstanding and unbelievable floated in the light breeze.
</P>
<P>
   The new ballyard's first fan surged into the glistening
turnstile at 4 p.m., three hours before the first pitch. When the
turnstile arm wouldn't budge, Joe Cox, 50, of West Seattle, scooted
around the metal contraption and joyfully skipped up stairs to the
main concourse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Incredible. I can't wait to get a look at that concourse,''
screamed Cox, who had camped overnight outside the ballpark to be
the first one in.
</P>
<P>
   A half-dozen fans, including his daughter, Christina Roeun, and
son-in- law, Vu Roeun, hugged him and traded high-fives.
</P>
<P>
   Later, after elated mobs of smiling fans poured into the
palatial, 47,000-seat venue, Cox sat in section 333, row 24 _ one
row down from the rim.
</P>
<P>
   ``The turnstile didn't turn, so I thought I was pretty adept at
zipping around it. Nothing was going to stop me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clear across the stadium, in section 313 above the right field
wall, the Gill family could not see the warning track below, but
Donnie Gill, 28, of Tacoma, soaked up a vista of a ship being
unloaded in Seattle's port.
</P>
<P>
   Gill said the venue was worth every penny of the $517 million it
cost to build, including $100 million of costs unanticipated when
the construction budget was set in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to be any cheaper than it is now,'' Gill said.
``We deserved it. We've been good baseball fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocky Ruddy of Seattle breathed in the spectacle from the swanky
club level.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like something no one has ever seen before in
Seattle,'' Ruddy said. ``This is great. Outside baseball at last.''
</P>
<P>
   Paddy Freeman, whose father-in-law, Stan Golub, was an original
Mariners owner, was all smiles as he posed for pictures with his
family atop the third-base dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is wonderful,'' Freeman exclaimed. ``This is going to be
a great home for baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Up in the high expanses of deep left field that is section 346,
Jim Rhynard sat happily with his wife, Kathy, and thought back to
Seattle baseball of decades past.
</P>
<P>
   ``This brings back memories of Sicks' Stadium when I was a kid
in the '50s _ the fresh air, the grass _ everything,'' Rhynard
said.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of happy mayhem, there were glitches:
</P>
<P>
   A brief pre-game power outage knocked out upper-level concession
stand cash registers, but that didn't stop buddies Brian Land and
Doug Jones, both of Everett, from quaffing some cold suds, munching
fresh-grilled hot dogs and sponging up diesel fumes wafting up from
a freight train rumbling below.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mind a little diesel fuel. It's part of the
ambience,'' said Land, a 20-game season ticketholder.
</P>
<P>
   To celebrate the nautical theme _ the wheels that move the roof
are shaped like ship's wheels _ hundreds of sailors stood ready to
launch blue-and-white confetti into the crowd that packed the
stadium by 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the Mercedes-Benz of stadiums,'' said usher John
Zuberbuhler of Kent.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone is happy with the Benz price. Outside the
stadium, protesters waved signs critical of the Mariners for asking
for another $60 million in public money to help pay off extra
construction costs.
</P>
<P>
   Tim McDonnell of Seattle stood at the left-field entrance with
his hand-drawn sign that read ``Never have so many been taxed to
enrich so few.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a few people come by and say that it's a good sign
and it had a good message,'' McDonnell said. ``Then there've been
some people who got liquored-up at the local bars and have flipped
me the bird.''
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, as if to prove that point, Cliff, a 38-year-old
metal worker and fan, confronted a man carrying a sign that read
``$372 M is enough.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you think this is?'' Cliff berated the man. ``This is
the free enterprise system. Public governments and private industry
need to work together.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the street from the protesters, a rarity: Someone
believed the Mariners deserved to have the county pay for the cost
overruns.
</P>
<P>
   Vic White of Grants Pass, Ore., was paid by ``People for a Fun
City,'' to come up to Safeco and circulate petitions asking the
county to pay more. His sign read ``Junior, A-Rod and (team
Chairman John) Ellis deserve a raise.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a big fan of the Mariners, and I think they should stay
here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And those fans embraced not only their heroes, but their new
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it, man,'' said Matt Lockwood of Issaquah as Bruce
Springsteen's ``Glory Days'' filled Seattle's newest outdoor venue.
``I've been waiting for this day all year.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle Post-Intelligencer reporter Judd Slivka contributed to
this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
