   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAFIRE-COLUMN (Washington) _ William Safire examines mistakes
made by the FBI and the Justice Department in the ``Asian
connection'' case.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TOURDEFRANCE-ARMSTRONG (Alpe d'huez, France) _ It would be a
remarkable athletic comeback in any arena, but the feats of Lance
Armstrong this past week seem almost Herculean. The 27-year-old
Texan is on course to become only the second American to win the
Tour de France. Even more surprising is that he is leading the race
just two and a half years after underdoing chemotherapy. Yet
because cycling and the Tour de France have been battered by a
year-old drug scandal, his accomplishment in taking a commanding
lead midway through the three-week race has generated as much
skepticism as it has excitement. By Samuel Abt.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-ANDERSON-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports column on the major
league umpires, who are unhappy with the way they are being treated
and are now planning to resign on Sept. 2, just as regular season
kicks into its final crucial weeks. By Dave Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEEKEND (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   EYES-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Eyes Wide Shut'' provides a
stunning epiphany for the summer of the dirty joke. This final film
by Stanley Kubrick is a dead-serious film about sexual yearnings,
one that flirts with ridicule yet sustains its fundamental eeriness
and gravity throughout. Reviewed by Janet Maslin.
</P>
<P>
   NY-VIDEO-FESTIVAL (New York) _ Aside from several special
programs, including a videographic journey by the Russian filmmaker
Aleksandr Sokurov and an analysis of contemporary music videos
chosen by the critic Armond White, the weeklong New York Video
Festival, which begins Friday, is divided into nine thematic
programs exploring everything from the family, to the relationship
between people and animals to the relationship between humans and
technology. By Stephen Holden.
</P>
<P>
   MAINE-LANDSCAPES (Undated) _ Visitors to Maine have the unusual
prospect of absorbing the 19th-century landscape experience through
a fine exhibition of landscape paintings in Rockland and of then
continuing up the coast to view the same majestic land formations
as preserved in Acadia National Park on Mount Desert Island. Along
the way, it is also possible to see man-made landscapes and gardens
that draw on the traditions of Maine and enrich local community
life. By Paula Deitz.
</P>
<P>
   AGING-ART-REVIEW (New York) _ ``The Time of Our Lives,'' an
exhibition at the New Museum of Contemporary Art, ignores most
esthetic issues and instead brings together a broad array of art
and artifacts _ from paintings to television commercials _
pertaining to a complex human and social theme: growing old. The
result is less an art exhibition than a multifaceted learning
experience; therein lie its weaknesses as well as its intermittent
strengths. Reviewed by Roberta Smith.
</P>
<P>
   PLACID-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ Despite the DOA nature of the
genre it satirizes, the demon crocodile movie ``Lake Placid'' finds
a good deal to work with in newly reptile-plagued Maine. Reviewed
by Janet Maslin.
</P>
<P>
   WOOD-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``The Wood,'' a savvy, good-natured
comedy that follows the 13-year friendship of three black friends
who met in junior high school in Inglewood, Calif., is reviewed by
Stephen Holden.
</P>
<P>
   LOSING-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``I'm Losing You,'' reviewed by
Janet Maslin.
</P>
<P>
   PLOT-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``This Blessed Plot: Britain and
Europe from Churchill to Blair,'' by Hugo Young. Reviewed by Samuel
Hynes.
</P>
