<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BB0-RANGERS-D'BACKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS WIN WITH 3 RUNS IN NINTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ None of the Rangers' three left-handed
hitters started last night's game with Arizona's Randy Johnson on
the mound.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the trio helped finish it.
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Greer, Rafael Palmeiro and Lee Stevens drew three
consecutive two-out walks as ninth-inning pinch hitters against
Arizona closer Matt Mantei, and that set the stage for Mark
McLemore's game-winning, bases-clearing double that catapulted the
Rangers to a stirring, 3-2 victory at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   McLemore, a switch hitter, lined a 2-2 pitch into the gap in
right-center field. Right fielder Tony Womack could only knock down
the drive, and Stevens chugged home from first base with the
winning run on the game's final play.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all due respects to the young man, and I know they
brought him over here to close,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates said
of Mantei, ``but any time Randy Johnson leaves the game and I can
get my left-handed hitters into the game ... well, it worked out
well for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Mantei, whom the Diamondbacks acquired July 9 in a four-player
trade with the Florida Marlins, replaced Johnson after the
intimidating left-hander pitched eight scoreless innings.
</P>
<P>
   Mantei (1-3) retired third baseman Todd Zeile and center fielder
Ruben Mateo before Oates sent Greer to the plate for shortstop
Royce Clayton. Greer worked the count full before drawing a walk,
and Palmeiro _ who pinch hit for second baseman Luis Alicea _
followed by drawing a walk on a 3-1 pitch.
</P>
<P>
   That brought Stevens to the plate for first baseman Jon Shave,
and that produced a classic, 10-pitch battle with Mantei. Stevens
fouled three consecutive 1-2 pitches before working the count full
and fouled a 3-2 offering before drawing the Rangers' third
consecutive two-out walk. With the three consecutive pinch-hit
walks, the Rangers did something that had been accomplished only
seven other times in major-league history.
</P>
<P>
   McLemore's at-bat produced the Rangers' third two-strike,
two-out plate appearance, but Mantei could not slam the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``One like that makes even me smile,'' Oates said. ``You know
you're going up against Randy. Now, I really don't believe in it,
but I thought he was due for a win _ and it looked like he was
going to win one. It looked liked the two runs were going to stand
up there.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson entered last night's appearance with a five-game losing
streak despite surrendering only five earned runs and accumulating
54 strikeouts during a span of 32 innings in his previous four
starts.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Johnson suffered the loss during each of those games while
the Diamondbacks failed to score en route to being no-hit, one-hit,
two-hit and three-hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel we can score on anybody,'' Rangers starter Rick
Helling said. ``Mantei is a great closer, and he can do the job,
but we just had good at-bats, which is the most important in that
situation. That was the impressive thing tonight. We made hteir
pitcher work an honest inning.''
</P>
<P>
   It appeared for eight innings that Helling would borrow a page
from Johnson's tough-luck manual for starting pitchers. A
first-inning walk to right fielder Tony Womack and an eighth-inning
curveball to second baseman Jay Bell would be enough to condemn
Helling to the type of loss Johnson understands all too well.
</P>
<P>
   A first-inning single by third baseman Matt Williams and Bell's
eighth-inning home run produced the evening's only runs in a
pitchers' duel until the Rangers' bottom-of-the-ninth heroics.
</P>
<P>
   Helling did not figure in the decision despite allowing only two
runs on five hits and three walks during his eight-inning,
117-pitch appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got a great lineup, a typical American league
lineup,'' Helling said. ``When you face Randy, you just want to
keep it close. I was able to do that. I was just happy to keep us
in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, left-hander Mike Venafro (3-1) earned the victory by
pitching a scoreless ninth inning and then witnessing the
improbable.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was as an exciting win as we've had all season,'' Oates
said. ``We beat a good pitcher even though he was in the dugout
when the game ended.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
