<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990716.0009 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 00:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2245 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-BRITISH-LEDE-HNS &LR;      07-16 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH-LEDE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
CARNOUSTIE, Scotland _ On the 12th hole Thursday at Carnoustie,
young Sergio Garcia made two trips into the scruffy patches of
gorse. The first was to hit a wayward shot.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The second was either to curse loud enough and not draw
attention or to do what sometimes must be done during four or five
hours on the golf course. Either way, he summed up the feelings of
all players about the place that lived up to its nickname of
Carnasty during the opening round of the British Open.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody broke par, but a few players broke down during a cool,
windy day along the Scottish seaside. The average score was 78.312.
More than a third of the field _ 57 players _ failed to break 80,
and two shot in the 90s as the wind blew at 30 mph for much of the
day with gusts higher and lulls that only served to tease and
confuse the players. There was a who's who of swatters thrilled to
escape the opening round with rounds of 74, 75 or even 77.
</P>
<P>
   It is the first time in any round of a major championship that
nobody has broken par since the British Open in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take my 74 and run,'' Colin Montgomerie said. ``I'll take
three more of them, too. That would be plus-12 (for the
tournament). It sounds crazy to say that. (But) that could be the
winning score. As long as you're one less than the rest of them, it
doesn't matter how many over par you are.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the battle cry as players will put on their full metal
jackets for the rest of this survival test. Many players got ahead
of par briefly early in their rounds. But none could sustain it.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, little-known Rodney Pampling, an Australian, was
the best at coping with the bad conditions, shooting even-par 71 to
lead by a stroke over Germany's Bernhard Langer and American Scott
Dunlap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it's been a thrill so far,'' Pampling said. ``It's
a tough course to get there (on the greens). But once you get
there, you can save a bit if you're putting well.''
</P>
<P>
   Pampling had nine putts through eight holes and finished with
only 25, which was a big reason he wasn't suffering the fate of
most players Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But this was a day for the marquee players not to shoot
themselves out of the tournament. Montgomerie's 3-over total was
matched by Ernie Els. Hal Sutton shot 73, as did Justin Leonard.
Tiger Woods (74), Lee Westwood (76), Greg Norman (76), Darren
Clarke (76), Vijay Singh (77) and Nick Price (77) all were happy to
take a limited number of lumps and get off the course.
</P>
<P>
   Worst of all, Montgomerie said, things could get worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can blow worse than this, that's for sure,'' he said.
``This was a breezy summer's day here. Nothing more than that.''
</P>
<P>
   That is not exactly what befuddled players like Garcia, Mark
O'Meara, Lee Janzen, Steve Elkington and David Duval want to hear.
</P>
<P>
   None of them could shoot lower than 79, and Garcia fired his way
out of the tournament with an 18-over 89, the third-highest score
of the first round.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of good players blown away today,''
Montgomerie said. ``They will be tomorrow, too, and Saturday and
Sunday if it remains this way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't overcome it (the course). But I've done OK. I haven't
thrown it away. Some have. I haven't thrown it away in this round.
I haven't won it. But I haven't lost it. And that's key.''
</P>
<P>
   Monty was much like everybody else in that he had a lot of
bogeys _ five _ plus a double bogey. But he also had four birdies.
And he is thrilled to be hovering near the leaders. He won last
week at the Loch Lomond tournament near here, but he has missed the
cut in five of the last seven British Opens.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best position I've been in here,'' he said. ``Mind
you, that's not saying very much, is it? I don't have much of a
record to go on here, so anything is a damn improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   Els agreed with Montgomerie that the goal was simply not to blow
sky high and eliminate oneself. Els was asked what he would think
if he could get three more 74s.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it stays like this, I will be happy with it,'' he said. ``I
played to my expectations. And if it stays like this, I'll take 74
each day.''
</P>
<P>
   Els had five birdies, six bogeys and a double bogey.
</P>
<P>
   ``For three holes, I thought if the breeze stayed the way it
was, we'd actually have a chance to shoot par,'' he said. ``But
then it really started picking up on the fourth hole. So it was
really, really tough. It's just unbelievably tough. Anything under
76 is playing really well.''
</P>
<P>
   What happened to some players was almost comical, as long as you
weren't those guys. Some of the lowlights:
</P>
<P>
   Davis Love III whiffed a shot in the hayfield they call No. 12.
The resulting double bogey knocked him out of the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia's 89 whacks to get around Carnoustie included five double
bogeys and a triple.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Gump went double-quadruple-double on the bogey scale on
Nos. 7-9 en route to a front-nine 49. He recovered to shoot 85.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Lyle shot 85 _ with an eagle.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the wind wasn't the only thing howling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's different, and it's nice to experience _ but you hope
only once,'' Duval said. ``When you hit a pitching wedge 200 yards,
there are too many variables. But you have to take pleasure in it.
If the average player had to play out there, he'd probably quit the
game. A lot of pros, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the Open will be coming back here. I don't know
what they are trying to accomplish. The U.S. Open was very
difficult. But it was enjoyable. It shouldn't necessarily be
stress-free. But if you can't enjoy an event like this, then you've
got to question what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Norman: ``Starting with (No.) 6, I felt like I was
climbing Mount Everest. Anything in the mid-70s has to be a good
score.''
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps it was Lee Westwood who capsulized things best.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a slog,'' he said, ``from start to finish.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there's no denying that somebody will win this event,
regardless of how ugly the victory might be.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm there on Sunday and I have shot 300 and won the
tournament, I don't care what number I put up, as long as I get the
cup,'' Els said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
