<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS FANS, AT LAST, CAN GO OUT TO THE BALLGAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The American flag in left centerfield was blowing in
last night.
</P>
<P>
   Now there is something you never saw once at a Mariners game.
</P>
<P>
   During 22 and a half seasons in the Kingdome, no fresh air ever
swirled. The only breeze we ever felt was the aftermath of a Ken
Griffey Jr. homer or a Harold Reynolds stolen base or, yes, a Randy
Johnson fastball.
</P>
<P>
   But there was the flag in the evening air on Thursday night,
fluttering as every small gust kicked off Puget Sound, showing us
for certain we are in a whole new place.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Safeco Field.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to a whole new era, where last night there was light and
noise and where now there is plush green grass and the
peculiarities of weather.
</P>
<P>
   And so what about a little weather?
</P>
<P>
   Bring on the rain. Or let it shine.
</P>
<P>
   As the ceremonies kicked off, with the Seattle Symphony letting
loose with a ringing rendition of ``Also Sprach Zarathustra'' _ the
opening theme from ``2001: A Space Odyssey'' _ the wheels started
rolling and the roof was peeled back and there we all sat _ 44,000
bathed in Northwest marine fresh air.
</P>
<P>
   No one appreciated open skies more than Layne Nixon and Tim
Harder. The two 20-year-old Navy men are machinists stationed on
the U.S.S. Carl Vinson at Bremerton, Wash..
</P>
<P>
   ``We work in the propulsion room,'' Nixon said. ``It's the
bottom of the ship. When we come up on deck, everyone knows who the
machinists are. We're the ones who look like zombies. We're all
white and pasty. Our eyes don't open. We hardly ever get outside.''
</P>
<P>
   In a way, every one of us who has spent time in the Kingdome is
like Nixon and Harder: just a bunch of propulsion room toilers
dying to see the light of day.
</P>
<P>
   That's why maybe we thought Safeco Field might not need a
retractable roof. But there it was _ waiting like a trusty, albeit
expensive, umbrella in the stand.
</P>
<P>
   There were other concerns coming into this new place, such as
how up in arms we were originally that we wanted Randy Johnson on
the mound.
</P>
<P>
   But Jamie Moyer did the honors last night and let's let bygones
be bygones.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is scheduled to pitch here Tuesday with his new team
from Arizona and there is no question that the Big Unit, despite
his troubled final weeks in Seattle, will get the standing ovation
worthy of a Cy Young Award winner whose strikeout sidearm heat
helped make Safeco Field possible.
</P>
<P>
   We also thought the new yard was going to cost $415 million, but
the price ballooned to $517 million as the project was rushed to
make sure the midsummer grand opening would take place on schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Home runs, not overruns,'' protesters out on Royal Brougham
Way chanted before the game, the utilitarian Kingdome in the
background, gray, tired and empty.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters' hand-written signs told the other side of the
Safeco Field story, the one that reminds us how foolish a game can
make us act.
</P>
<P>
   ``You gotta love these guys. You never hadda choice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Millionaire owners and players on the public dole. Pathetic.''
</P>
<P>
   And they are mostly right, of course, and God bless those with a
fiscal conscience for coming out to tell their version of the
truth.
</P>
<P>
   But, happily, there is something communal and thrilling about
coming out to the old ballgame. That is what the swarms of fans
snaking down Occidental Avenue demonstrated.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Cox of West Seattle was the first through the turnstiles
Thursday night. The 50-year-old baseball fan waited 26 hours to
gain the honor. Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the game. I played when I was a kid. It's a way for
people to get together and dump some of the facade you normally
have around you and just get out there and see the real person in
there,'' Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   If much of what has surrounded this new outdoor stadium has been
contentious and expensive, Cox's reason for remaining a diehard fan
provides a decent explanation about why Safeco Field has a place in
Seattle's life.
</P>
<P>
   There is time now for all of us to test out the $7 bleacher
seats.
</P>
<P>
   There is plenty of time to go around and use the dozens of
Safeco Field bathrooms and their hundreds of stalls _ a luxury for
anyone who ever had a few too many ounces of beer or soda in the
Kingdome, then realized the lines were backed out to King Street.
</P>
<P>
   Amenities galore.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, this place called Safeco Field is capable of stirring
envy.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Seattle Symphony found the new ballpark so intriguing,
maestro Gerard Schwarz will go back and demand that a retractable
roof and green grass be installed in Benaroya Hall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
