<HEADLINE>
HEROES INSPIRE SHEFFIELD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Gary Sheffield got just one at-bat in
Tuesday's All-Star game, but he left Fenway Park with a lifetime of
memories.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Dodgers outfielder, who grounded to short as a
pinch-hitter for Jeff Bagwell, said the pregame ceremonies
involving former Boston great Ted Williams will never be forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   ``There you have 40 of the greatest players who ever lived; Hank
Aaron, Willie Mays, and they are all standings there with their
mouths open over Ted,'' Sheffield said. ``Having them there with
today's All-Stars, (it) was so incredible to be part of that group
on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at them and they're looking at Ted. It was very
emotional. That was the history of the game right out there on the
mound.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield, who left for Boston on a redeye after Sunday's 14-3
victory over Seattle, got back to town Wednesday afternoon and was
excused from the club's workout at Dodger Stadium. Pitcher Carlos
Perez was the only other player to miss the workout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did a lot of sleeping after that,'' Sheffield said. ``But I
wouldn't have missed that for anything.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Setback for Osuna: Reliever Antonio Osuna hoped to return to
the Dodgers this weekend after missing most of the season due to
surgery for bone chips in his right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Osuna experienced discomfort in his elbow Wednesday night during
a one-inning outing for Single-A San Bernardino's game at Modesto.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wanted to be back by now,'' said Osuna, who might be
activated when the Dodgers play a brief three-game series
(including a doubleheader Thursday) vs. Colorado at home. ``I feel
great, just little things that keep popping up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-99 0117EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990716.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 01:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2262 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-TIGERS-ASTROS-HNS     07-16 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-TIGERS-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The biggest hit Thursday for Derek Bell didn't come in the
seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   It was the one he took when he was demoted to the sixth spot in
the batting order.
</P>
<P>
   Angered over the decision to move him down in the order, Bell
took out his frustrations on the Detroit Tigers. Bell hit a
go-ahead two-run single in the seventh as the Astros rallied from a
six-run deficit for an 8-6 victory in manager Larry Dierker's first
game back since undergoing brain surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a slap in the face dropping me all the way down to
the sixth spot,'' said Bell, who entered the game batting .244 with
a National League-leading 92 strikeouts. ``It ain't right. I've
been battling all year. Yeah, I strike out a lot, but I've still
done a lot of things for this team.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way the fans are treating me, I probably don't expect to
be here next season. For them to turn on me and boo every time I
swing and miss is not right. I think I may have worn out my
welcome.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros welcomed Dierker back to the dugout with their fourth
straight win to remain in a virtual first-place tie with Cincinnati
in the National League Central. Dierker missed 27 games after
suffering a grand mal seizure June 13. He required brain surgery
two days later.
</P>
<P>
   The comeback was the Astros' biggest since overcoming a six-run
deficit July 23, 1998, at Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something we haven't done in a long time,'' said Jeff
Bagwell, who hit his 29th home run in the fifth inning. ``We
battled and got the big hits.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros scored three runs in the fifth, two in the sixth and
three in the seventh to wipe out the huge deficit.
</P>
<P>
   With the Tigers leading 6-0, Bagwell hit a three-run homer off
Dave Mlicki. The Astros continued chipping away at the lead,
pulling within 6-5 in the sixth when Bell reached on an error and
scored on a triple by Tim Bogar. Pinch hitter Matt Mieske drove in
a run with a groundout.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers' pitching staff fell apart in the seventh. Reliever
Willie Blair (1-8) walked Bill Spiers and Bagwell to start the
inning, and Doug Brocail walked Richard Hidalgo to load the bases.
</P>
<P>
   Bell, who batted second or cleanup for most of the first half,
hit a one-out single up the middle to give the Astros their first
lead of the game. Bogar followed with an RBI grounder.
</P>
<P>
   Bell was informed of the decision that he would hit sixth prior
to the game. Dierker said a possible lineup switch had been
discussed for some time. He hoped the move would light a fire under
Bell, who struggled during parts of the first half and had only a
.298 on-base percentage to go with his numerous strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to see Derek look at this as a challenge to work
his way back to hitting fourth or second,'' Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   That's not how Bell interpreted the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said, `We're dropping you to the sixth spot because
you're striking out too much to be the fourth hitter,''' Bell said.
``There's already a lot of pressure on me to go out there and do
everything right so people won't boo me. I feel like I'm not
wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Several of Bell's teammates came to his defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shouldn't be the fans' choice to get on him,'' Carl Everett
said. ``If you're a Houston Astros fan, you should cheer instead of
booing. I don't want to say anything profane, but they (the fans)
need to keep their mouths closed.''
</P>
<P>
   Trever Miller (1-1) pitched a scoreless seventh inning for the
victory, and Billy Wagner pitched the ninth for his 23rd save. Doug
Henry, making his first appearance since undergoing elbow surgery
in mid-May, along with Jay Powell, Wagner and Miller combined to
limit the Tigers to four hits over the final four innings.
</P>
<P>
   Shane Reynolds allowed all six Detroit runs and eight hits in
five innings. He drew a warning from home-plate umpire Ed Rapuano
after throwing a pitch behind former Astro Brad Ausmus in the
fourth.
</P>
<P>
   On the Astros' side, Bagwell and Bogar were hit by pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their team understood it,'' said Reynolds, who had seven
strikeouts. ``We had a couple of guys get hit. Bags goes out and
busts his tail and works hard. You have to protect him _ not being
a headhunter and trying to hurt guys. It's over and done with.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
