<SLUG> BC-BB-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECOND HALF BEGINS WITH BANG FOR RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-PHILLIES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The All-Star break apparently is the pause that
refreshes, at least for every Red Sox player in the lineup except
the starting All-Star shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   With leadoff man Jose Offerman going deep on the third pitch he
saw from Phillies starter Paul Byrd, the first of three home runs
the Sox hit to start off an inning, and rookies Brian Daubach and
Trot Nixon collecting three hits apiece, the Sox came out swinging
against the Philadelphia Phillies in a 6-4 win Thursday &UR;  &LR; night
before a sellout crowd of 32,397 on Yawkey Way.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox, who had lost five out of six just before the break,
drew within three games of the New York Yankees in the American
League East, even though Nomar Garciaparra was shut out at the
plate and made a throwing error in his return to the starting
lineup after a nine-game absence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt my timing was off a little bit,'' said Garciaparra,
whose 17-game hitting streak came to an end after he failed to get
the ball out of the infield in four trips, popping out three times
after grounding into a double play on which he ran half-speed in
the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to do anything stupid,'' Garciaparra said of not
running all out. ``I only play one way, but that's where you can
tell it's come along, where you do some things instinctively but
you can still hold up on others. I know that now.''
</P>
<P>
   The win, only the fourth in 13 interleague games for the Sox and
the first in almost a month (June 16) for rookie Brian Rose, was
not assured until Tim Wakefield left the bases loaded in the eighth
and the tying runs on base in the ninth for his 11th save in 12
chances.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox had put up four runs on two home runs and two doubles on
their first pass through the order, but still required a bailout
from Wakefield. A white-knuckle save?
</P>
<P>
   ``I know my knuckles were white,'' said catcher Jason Varitek,
who joined Offerman and Daubach in hitting home runs
Thursday &UR;  &LR; night, and also tagged out Scott Rolen at the plate after
Wakefield grabbed Mike Lieberthal's chopper and threw home for the
biggest out of the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to be when he's on the mound,'' Varitek said.
``There's some serious concentration going on, any time there's two
strikes and anybody's on base.''
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield, who had entered the game in the eighth with runners
on second and third and one run already in after Garciaparra's
error, pounced on Lieberthal's chopper to the left of the mound and
threw out Rolen, who slid head-first into Varitek's tag.
</P>
<P>
   A demonstration of Wakefield's cat-like reflexes?
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess so,'' Wakefield said, ``if you can't think of another
animal slower than a cat.''
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield walked the next batter, Rob Ducey, to load the bases,
but retired Alex Arias on a grounder to Garciaparra.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra's obvious frustration _ he flung his bat and slammed
his helmet after his second popup _ may have carried over into the
field, a rare occurrence. He made a throwing error in the eighth
inning, one in which first baseman Mike Stanley, flat on his
stomach and squarely in the path of runner Rolen, was forced to
duck for cover as Rolen leaped over him.
</P>
<P>
   Another Garciaparra throw pulled Stanley off the bag on Doug
Glanville's infield hit with one out in the ninth, and Wakefield
walked Ron Gant. The next batter, Bobby Abreu, already had homered
and tripled, but second baseman Offerman ended the night with a
fine defensive play, charging Abreu's grounder, tagging out Gant,
and flipping to Stanley for a double play.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only chance I had, especially the way Abreu runs,'' said
Offerman, whose home run into the bullpen marked a fresh start for
a man who ended the first half with just two hits in 38 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Because he was an All-Star, Offerman didn't get much of a break.
``Even yesterday, I was in a park, watching my daughters (Joseann
and Jealynn) play baseball,'' he said. ``But it was fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose, who gave up a home run to the first batter of the game,
Glanville, then was lifted two batters into the sixth after Abreu's
two-run home run made it 5-3, did better getting away from it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I signed the papers for my house, went furniture and appliance
shopping, and spent time with Tara and Ben,'' Rose said, referring
to his fiancee and her 2-year-old son, with whom Rose has been
close since birth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really know much about it, since this is my first full
year,'' Rose said, ``but personally, I think getting a break,
spending some time with our families, was good for all of us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
