<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 01:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2267 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-DIERKER-HN     07-16 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-DIERKER-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NEIL HOHLFELD  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
After 32 days of what he termed ``being grounded,'' Astros manager
Larry Dierker was flying high again Thursday night.
<TEXT>
<P>
   He was at his usual post in the home dugout as the Astros played
the Detroit Tigers, the memory of his terrifying grand mal seizure
during a June 13 game, the brain surgery two days later and
subsequent recuperation pushed aside for the moment.
</P>
<P>
   To the manager's delight, the Astros responded with an 8-6
victory after falling behind 6-0 in the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a comeback for a (Dierker's) comeback,'' the manager
said. ``I can't remember a game that we were that far down and came
back to win this season. That's the kind of thing we did last
year.''
</P>
<P>
   For Dierker, the win capped an evening he won't soon forget.
After the media crush had left his office following the game, he
reflected on events of the last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have all this, to be the manager of a major-league team and
to have played and been a broadcaster, I've had a life that most
guys could only dream about,'' Dierker said. ``Then, after this
situation (his seizure and surgery), I really feel I've sailed
through it pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know a lot of guys have made a lot more money and seen a lot
more of the world, but I wouldn't trade what I've got for
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Dierker stood at home plate, going over the
ground rules and exchanging small talk with the umpiring crew and
Detroit manager Larry Parrish. In the background, Cheeseburger In
Paradise was playing.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, life was beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   ``The little things that we all take for granted at times seem
more important now,'' Dierker said. ``Just walking out on the field
(for batting practice) and getting ready for a game, it's something
to savor.''
</P>
<P>
   Just more than one month ago, Dierker was rushed off the
Astrodome field in an ambulance after suffering the seizure. After
surgery to remove a mass from his brain that caused the seizure,
Dierker missed 27 games. When he returned Thursday, there was a
sense of relief and outpouring of emotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, the last month has been like being in the Twilight
Zone,'' Astros general manager Gerry Hunsicker said. ``It's been
surreal. This club has overcome so many unusual adversities, and
we're still in first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now to see Larry back, I think it's going to be a big
psychological lift to the club. Everything starts with leadership
at the top, and Larry's the leader. No matter who (interim manager
Matt Galante) stepped in there, it was a change. It's different. To
have him back gets everybody feeling like we're back on track,
we're back to normal and let's go get 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   In the seats, many in the crowd of 32,573 wore Hawaiian shirts,
which are favored by Dierker, to honor the manager. The Astros
handed out leis to the first 10,000 fans, adding another festive
element to the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could feel the fans throughout the game,'' Dierker said.
``Every time I looked up in the crowd, somebody would point to
their shirt to show they were with me. But most of the time, I was
just trying to win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Just before the start of the game, Dierker jumped into the box
seats and presented his wife, Judy, with a lei made of fresh
flowers. The Dierkers celebrated their 24th wedding anniversary
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   On his way back to the dugout, Dierker stopped to sign
autographs for a few fans, a gesture he says he will repeat more
often in the future. He received more than 1,000 get-well cards and
letters, an outpouring of how the city feels about a man who has
been part of the Houston franchise as a player, broadcaster and
manager for 34 of the last 35 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel a lot more sympathetic toward the fans,'' Dierker said.
``I know that getting 1,000 get-well cards doesn't mean that
hundreds of thousands of people are all as sensitive and concerned
and caring as the people who sent the cards, but I got some really
touching things.''
</P>
<P>
   Once in the dugout after the exchange of lineup cards, Dierker
took off his baseball cap for a helmet. He said he would wear the
helmet while in the dugout the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker also was touched by the emotion of his players, who
prayed for him on the day of his seizure and who eagerly welcomed
him back Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It says a lot about Larry's character, and it says a lot about
modern medicine,'' Astros second baseman Craig Biggio said. ``To go
through what Larry's gone through and what his family has gone
through and for him to be back today is really incredible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
