<SLUG> BC-BB-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARCIAPARRA BACK _ FOR REAL
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-GARCIAPARRA-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By SHIRA SPRINGER 
c.1999 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The wait was longer than usual. The infielder ate his
postgame meal slowly, out of necessity using only his left hand.
His thowing arm _ the right arm _ hung stiff and straight by his
side. Large bags of ice were wrapped tightly against his right
elbow and shoulder. The training staff secured another icy package
to his left hamstring and groin. He shared a few laughs with
teammates at the training table that seats three comfortably, he
finished his dinner, and then disappeared again into the far
reaches of the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Nomar Garciaparra reappeared, free of ice packs and
Ace bandages and ready to talk, most of the Red Sox clubhouse had
cleared out. The crowd that surrounded his locker stall close to an
hour after the game asked only a few questions. Some performances
require little comment, especially on those nights when there is
little good to comment upon.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night against Philadalphia, Garciaparra returned to the
Boston lineup . . . and his timing was all off. In his first at-bat
after a nine-game regular-season layoff, he hit into a double play.
Everyone watching knew that a truly healthy Garciaparra, a player
without his healing groin on his mind, would have run out the throw
from second. The cleanup hitter popped out in the second, fourth,
and seventh innings, finishing 0 for 4 and snapping a 17-game
streak.
</P>
<P>
   The shortstop committed an error in the eighth, thowing wide of
first base and pulling Mike Stanley off the bag. It was only
Garciaparra's second error in his last 24 games. In the ninth, the
All-Star again took Stanley off first base with an imperfect throw,
but the play was ruled a hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt all right,'' said Garciaparra. ``I felt like my timing
was off a little bit. But as far as the injury is concerned, it
felt all right. So that's good . . . Definitely, (in the first
inning), I had to hold back a step. But you've got to be smart
first game back. I didn't want to do anything stupid. The first
inning was a good example. I usually beat that out, but you go out
there, and it's not good blowing out in the first. It puts me out
again. I've definitely got to be aware and be smart. Like I said
before, I'm definitely a lot better than I was a week ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The All-Star Game Tuesday afforded Garciaparra the luxury of a
rehabilitation start without leaving home. It put the shortstop in
a game situation without placing the pressure to win on his
shoulders. He played three innings and went 0 for 2 in the
midsummer classic. But more importantly, he got back some feel for
the game and proved wrong local baseball pundits who were concerned
the infielder would reinjure his groin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helped me go out there and get to see a couple pitches _ I
hadn't seen any in nine days,'' said Garciaparra, who's batting
.361 and hit .394 in June during the streak and before the injury.
``It was a good time to go out there and see how I felt. It felt
good. It felt good enough to play. You go out there in a game
situation and everything. It was great. That's what I was saying
all along. It seems like people don't listen to me. They think they
know more.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Thursday night's error and cautious play showed the
shortstop was far from 100 percent healthy. Garciaparra doesn't
worry about the groin injury that kept him out since July 2
becoming a nagging injury, but he knows that it's too much to ask
for perfect health in the second half of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't come from an injury and be 100 percent,'' he said.
``We play baseball. We play every day. Give me five months off, and
maybe I'll be at 100.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Garciaparra, some waits take longer than
others. After all, timing is everything.
</P>
</TEXT>
