<SLUG> BC-BKL-SPARKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPARKS HAVE YET TO PEAK?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ This is the time of season when the Sparks
are usually looking to replace their coach. But not this time.
Under the direction of coach Orlando Woolridge, the team is 10-5,
the best start in their three-year history in the WNBA. At this
pace, they are a cinch to advance to the playoffs for the first
time.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks have won seven of their last eight games and are tied
with Sacramento for second place in the Western Conference. But
while their record indicates success, they have yet to become the
dominant team they hope to be down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're happy with the record we have now, (but) we all would
like for it to be better,'' Woolridge said. ``The great thing about
it is ... we haven't peaked yet as a basketball team. I think the
better part of our game has yet to come. If I looked at us as
(potentially) 100 percent effective, I would say we're about 80.
There's a lot of room for improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Leslie, who returned from the inaugural WNBA All-Star game
with the MVP trophy, has yet to reach her stride, Woolridge said.
Her scoring and rebounding averages are both down from a year ago
(15.8 from 19.6 and 8.0 from 10.2, respectively).
</P>
<P>
   ``I can go down the list to everyone on team and there's so much
room for improvement, and they realize it,'' Woolridge said.
</P>
<P>
   Recent changes in the lineup have inspired the Sparks as well.
Forward La'Keisha Frett, who was hampered with tendinitis in her
left knee in training camp, has come on strongly lately and
provided the Sparks with another threat. She replaced Tamecka
Dixon, who has been struggling offensively. Mwadi Mabika replaced
Allison Feaster and Ukari Figgs, the rookie point guard from
Purdue, is expected to return to the court Saturday when the Sparks
resume play at Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks released general manager Rhonda Windham for
``philosophical reasons'' after the team fell to 3-4. Since Sparks
president Johnny Buss assumed responsibilities and sought to solve
player disenchantment, the team has gone 7-1.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to the wisdom of his father, Lakers owner Jerry Buss,
Johnny got involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lent an ear, listened to problems and the gripes and
understood,'' Johnny Buss said. ``I agreed with them. And once I
became aware, not only of the problems and the gripes, I couldn't
understand how anybody could play under those circumstances. So we
changed it. It didn't take long to figure out where they were
coming from. It didn't take long to understand how to fix it. Once
that happens, it's still going to be a step-by-step process.''
</P>
<P>
   Attendance is also a problem. The Sparks are second-to-last in
the league, averaging 6,799. It's enough for Buss to renew his
contract with the league (6,000 is the minimum) but not enough to
keep him happy. He poured $1 million more into the
advertising-promotion budget this year, but it hasn't translated at
the box office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm certainly concerned, the league office is certainly
concerned,'' Buss said. ``I really can't figure it out as a
promoter. We provide great entertainment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
