<HEADER>
A2277 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-DODGERS-LADN-(SLA     07-16 0499
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-DODGERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MO DELIVERS WIN FOR ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ An ex-Anaheim Angel and a guy named Angel
helped the Los Angeles Dodgers rally from a four-run deficit, but
Mo Vaughn's 10th-inning single gave the Angels a 7-6 victory
Thursday night before a sellout crowd of 43,911 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn's hit came off Dodgers reliever Onan Masaokaand scored
Randy Velarde from second base.
</P>
<P>
   Devon White's three-run homer off Angels starter Chuck Finley
gave the Dodgers their first lead of the night at 6-5 in the fifth
inning. Earlier in the game, Dodgers catcher Angel Pena had a
two-run single.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the home run, White also had a double and two singles
and is 9 for 17 with two homers and nine RBI in four games against
the Angels this season. His grand slam keyed a 7-4 win over the
Angels on June 5.
</P>
<P>
   But White's big hit didn't stand up because Pedro Borbon,
pitching in relief of starter Kevin Brown, couldn't hold the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Velarde had to be happy to see Brown gone when he came up in the
seventh. After looking bad in three at-bats against Brown, striking
out twice, Velarde homered off Borbon, tying the game at 6.
</P>
<P>
   It also increased Velarde's hitting streak to 11 games.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams had their ace throwing, but neither Brown nor Finley
pitched like it.
</P>
<P>
   Brown gave up five runs and five hits in 51/3 innings, striking
out six and walking three. Finley gave up six runs and eight hits
in five innings, striking out six and walking four. Neither was
involved in the decision.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels got on the scoreboard first, scoring four runs in the
second inning against Brown. And the key to the inning came because
Orlando Palmeiro couldn't get a bunt down.
</P>
<P>
   With runners on first and second and none out, Palmeiro fouled
off two bunt attempts. On a 0-2 pitch, he slapped a grounder just
inside first and down the right-field line for a double, scoring
Garret Anderson from second for a 1-0 Angels lead.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Huson, in the DH spot for the second time this season,
followed with a single to right to score two more and give the
Angels a 3-0 lead. Huson went to third on Gary DiSarcina's flyout
to right, and after a walk to Matt Walbeck, scored when Darin
Erstad grounded into a fielder's choice.
</P>
<P>
   The 4-0 lead was tenuous at best, as Finley struggled in the
first few innings before the Dodgers broke through for three runs
in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   They scored one run and had the bases loaded with one out
without hitting the ball out of the infield. Three infield singles
and a walk resulted in their first run before Pena's two-run single
narrowed the Angels' lead to 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   Huson's RBI double in the bottom of the fourth increased the
Angels' lead to 5-3, but it only lasted until White batted in the
top of the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   White blasted a three-run homer, his eighth of the season to
give the Dodgers a 6-5 lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-99 0147EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
