<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 01:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2285 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SUMPRO-LADN-(SLAN     07-16 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUMPRO-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRUGGLING TO LEARN THE TRIANGLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE STEVENS  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ The Los Angeles Lakers played their
triangle more like a team of Ed Grimley's than a newly inspired
Phil Jackson troupe.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, this was a Thursday in July. Jackson wasn't behind
the bench, and even though his signature triangle offense
continually sputtered, it didn't matter in this exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   A crew of young Lakers and hopefuls lost to a similar group of
Portland Trail Blazers 109-81 in the NBA summer pro league at the
Pyramid. Tyronn Lue, Ruben Patterson and Travis Knight were the
marquee players for the Lakers, but it was apparent winning wasn't
their main objective.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know for me I have to take my time, learn the offense and
make sure to rest my ankle,'' Lue said.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the Lakers fell to 1-3 in this summer's exhibition
season is irrelevant. But other facts, such as Devean George's
performance, could be relevant. George, a swingman from Augsburg
(Minn.) and the Lakers' first-round draft pick, looked especially
loose and showed an array of offensive skills with 14 points and
five rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to show the Lakers I can play hard, be relaxed and not
worry when I'm out there,'' George said. ``I think I can fit in on
this team coming off the bench as a good role player.''
</P>
<P>
   Another role player is Ruben Patterson, who missed part of this
shortened season with tendinitis in his right knee.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson also could be a part of a good matchup tonight at 7:30
p.m. at the Pyramid when the Lakers meet the Celtics. Patterson
likely will have the assignment of guarding Paul Pierce, who scored
46 points on Wednesday and was one of the top rookies this season.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce, from Kansas, and Patterson, from Cincinnati, played
against each other in college and are friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can shoot the ball better than me,'' Patterson said. ``But
I have quickness and can play tough defense. I'm going to put the
glove on him.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Giant small forward? The Dallas Mavericks' Dirk Nowitzki is a
unique player in the summer pro league. Nowitzki, a native of
Germany, is 7-feet tall and plays small forward. He just finished
his first season with the Mavs, averaging 8.2 points and 3.4
rebounds and starting 24 games.
</P>
<P>
   Considering Nowitzki's atypical style of play, some questioned
his selection at ninth in the draft, one pick before Pierce.
Nowitzki, however, might work out after all.
</P>
<P>
   He received substantial playing time at the beginning of the
Mavs' season, but after having several rough games, had his playing
time cut. Near the end of the season, he received a second chance
and became a frequent contributor to the Mavs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game is so different here than Europe, there definitely
was an adjustment,'' Nowitzki said. ``Europe plays much more team
basketball. Here the athletes are much better.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowitzki, 21, is developing and seems to have a strong
understanding of his skills. He said his biggest problem is that
typical NBA power forwards are too strong for him to guard under
the basket, while small forwards sometimes are too fast for him.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, Nowitzki could be on his way to a strong NBA career
and could develop into a player similar to his idol, Scottie
Pippen.
</P>
<P>
   In the Mavs' game on Thursday, Nowitzki scored 22 points to help
lead the Mavs over the Vancouver Grizzlies 107-105. His teammate,
guard Anthony Carter from Hawaii, outshined him with 29 points and
10 assists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
