<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990716.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 01:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2288 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-16 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WHAT'S a Hawaiian holiday without a few simmering volcanoes?
</P>
<P>
   This was a night when Astros manager Larry Dierker was supposed
to sit back and drink in his triumphant return as if the Astrodome
had a giant paper umbrella stuck through the roof.
</P>
<P>
   Strains of Parrothead music wafted through the Astrodome on
Thursday night as Dierker carried the lineup card to the umpires. A
sea of Hawaiian shirts clashed disgustingly with the orange and
yellow Dome seats.
</P>
<P>
   And welcome-back banners were everywhere for the man who
underwent brain surgery barely a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could feel the crowd the entire game,'' Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   But during it all, the triumphant part for Dierker looked to be
in serious doubt and nearly everywhere else things were more than a
bit sticky.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a good tester for Dierk's ol' noggin,'' Astros third
baseman Bill Spiers said.
</P>
<P>
   Yup, it was. And some of the brain strain was self-inflicted,
albeit necessarily so.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Dierker demoted Derek Bell to the six hole in
the lineup in an attempt to stir the right fielder's bat.
</P>
<P>
   The move might not seem like a big deal, but the finicky Bell
would give the FUBU shirt off his back for a chance to bat second
every day.
</P>
<P>
   No one knew how Bell would react to such a demotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it was something he embraces,'' Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A slap in the face,'' Bell called it.
</P>
<P>
   Simmer, simmer.
</P>
<P>
   Also before the game, Dierker said his only big concern was
being able to come through with the right call in the clutch, which
apparently was not also the umpiring crew's big concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm wondering if the decision-making is going to be the same
when situations come up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But consider Dierker's brainpower tried, tested and proven.
</P>
<P>
   There were situations and challenges almost every step of the
way, and Dierker and the Astros couldn't have responded better on
the way to an 8-6 win over the Detroit Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   First, the Astros fell behind the Tigers 6-0 going into the
bottom of the fifth inning, which in itself is enough to strain any
brain.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Jeff Bagwell twice was brushed back from the plate by
Tigers hurlers, once getting hit by a pitch, causing Astros starter
Shane Reynolds to retaliate with a fastball behind former teammate
Brad Ausmus.
</P>
<P>
   More than a few players in both dugouts sat up on their bench as
tensions mounted and plate umpire Ed Rapuano warned Reynolds for
the tight pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Simmer, simmer.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the umpiring crew, which by the end of the night
had some 32,573 fans willing to pen the first draft of their
proposed letters of resignation in protest of labor issues.
</P>
<P>
   As the Astros mounted their seventh-inning comeback for the win,
Carl Everett slapped a high-hopping grounder up the middle and
clearly beat out shortstop Deivi Cruz's throw to first.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone but first-base umpire Charlie Williams knew Everett
should have been called safe. Dierker hopped out of his seat ready
to argue the call.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandmother's dead, and she could have seen that (I was
safe),'' Everett said. ``I have no idea why he made that call.''
</P>
<P>
   Worst of all, Everett strained a hamstring stretching for the
bag on the play and crumbled to the ground in pain, packing yet
more worries into the head of a skipper familiar with putting
players on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   ``Losing Carl is going to be one of the tougher things,''
Dierker said. ``But it was a wonderful win _ a comeback for the
comeback.''
</P>
<P>
   The skipper passed so many tests so well.
</P>
<P>
   Even the game-winning hit proved Dierker's risky strategy smart.
</P>
<P>
   It was Bell, batting in the No. 6 hole, who smashed a two-run
single through the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone left the building happy, dancing to Jimmy Buffett
music.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker and the Astros drank it all in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being his comeback, we didn't want to lose this one,'' Spiers
said. ``When we started scoring and won it, I had that feeling like
last year: `Wow, we haven't done this in a while.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we'll get going real good now.''
</P>
<P>
   Just like old times.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
