<DOCNO> NYT19990716.0030 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 01:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2290 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-UMPREAX-LADN     07-16 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-UMPREAX-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEAM RISING AS UMPIRES STEW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Major-league umpires expected to get booed
when they took the field Thursday night and they were right.
</P>
<P>
   But Los Angeles Dodgers outfielder Gary Sheffield, who has
learned a little about getting booed during his 11-year career,
said being right is more important than public opinion in the
umpires' dispute with the commissioner's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without unity they don't have a chance,'' Sheffield said.
``Umpires have to stay together in their beliefs. That is how the
players have done so well against the owners. The game wouldn't be
the same without them.''
</P>
<P>
   The umpires certainly hope so, especially during pennant races
and postseason play. Tension, which has been growing for nearly
three years, bubbled over Wednesday when Richie Phillips, head of
the umpires' union, said 57 of the 68 umpires would resign
effective Sept. 2
</P>
<P>
   The umpires are fearful the owners are attempting to break the
union and install high school and college umpires next season. The
collective-bargaining agreement between the two sides expires in
December.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not a lot of baseball being played in December,'' said umpire
Joe Brinkman, crew chief for the Dodgers/Anaheim Angels series at
Edison Field. ``The decision to resign was made to protect our
interest and the season is our leverage.''
</P>
<P>
   Brinkman arrived in Anaheim on Thursday morning after attending
a five-hour meeting of major-league umpires in Philadelphia. Owners
have said they will address the proposal, but no plans have been
set to begin negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to resign was presented because the umpires have a
no-strike provision in the existing agreement. If they went on
strike, the umpires would forfeit more than $15 million in
termination pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would be voiding the terms of our contract and I would
assume they could void the rest of the agreement, too,'' Brinkman
said.''
</P>
<P>
   The termination pay scale runs from $150,000 for a 10-year
umpire to $400,000 for an umpire with 20 or more years of service.
</P>
<P>
   But Dodgers first baseman Eric Karros, an active member of the
players association during the 1994 work stoppage, wondered if the
umpires aren't giving the owners too much time to make contingency
plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that much about the whole thing,'' Karros said.
``But I would say, `Don't back yourself into a corner.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Brinkman admitted that the umpires want to get the issue
resolved without a disruption. Under Phillips' plan, the umpires
would resign, form their own company, and be contracted back to
baseball without working under the umbrella of the commissioner's
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year when the NFL officials were getting a lot of heat
for some calls, what was the first thing (commissioner) Paul
Tagliabue did,'' Brinkman said. ``He ended the issue by saying,
`These guys are the best in the business.' He backed them up. We
never see that.''
</P>
<P>
   Brinkman said the umpires are united in their plan, although it
has been reported that there is a group within the union that wants
to oust Phillips and bring in noted players' agent Ron Shapiro.
Some believe Phillips, who used to represent former Dodgers catcher
Mike Scioscia, often acts more like a bully than a negotiator.
</P>
<P>
   If or how the umpires' threats affect the final 4{ weeks of the
season remains to be seen. In 1995, umpires missed the first 86
games of the regular season when they were locked out by owners.
They went on strike in 1979 and missed the first seven weeks. They
also missed the first seven games of the 1985 playoffs because of a
strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to wait and see how it turns out,'' said Angels
manager Terry Collins, who went to Eastern Michigan University with
AL umpire Rocky Roe. ``I don't' worry about that stuff. I've got
enough problems of my own.''
</P>
<P>
   ((Joe Haakenson of the San Gabriel Valley Tribune contributed to
this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
