<HEADER>
A2297 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARNER-RESIGN-LADN     07-16 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-RESIGN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEPARTURES MARK END OF ERA AT STUDIO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
LOS ANGELES -- Shock rolled through Hollywood on Thursday as the
co-chiefs of Warner Bros., Robert A. Daly and Terry Semel,
announced their resignations after two decades of running the
industry's top studio.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Daly and Semel, who have been both the longest-serving and
most-consistently successful executives in one of the world's
most-volatile businesses, will leave by the end of the year to
pursue unspecified ``new opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   The low-key pair, who eschewed publicity in a business that
craves it, said they reached the decision during a recent vacation.
The resignations caught Hollywood -- typically rife with rumors --
completely off guard; the mood at the Warner lot in Burbank, where
close to 10,000 people work, was described as ``absolutely sober''
by a longtime employee.
</P>
<P>
   ``This came out of the blue,'' said David Davis, an analyst with
Houlihan Lokey Howard and Zukin in Los Angeles. ``It really is the
end of an era.''
</P>
<P>
   The clout of Daly, 62, and Semel, 56, has been so overwhelming
that no clear successor exists. Internal candidates include WB
Network's Jamie Kellner, HBO's Jeff Bewkes and New Line's Robert
Shaye, while others could be one-time Sony chief Mark Canton and
former Universal executive Frank Biondi.
</P>
<P>
   Daly and Semel pledged to work with Time Warner Chairman Gerald
Levin and President Richard Parsons for a smooth transition. ``This
is being handled in a very straightforward and gentlemanlike way,''
said PaineWebber managing director Christopher Dixon.
</P>
<P>
   Observers said Daly and Semel, both New York natives, have
inspired a high level of loyalty as subordinates are holdovers from
the days when Warner was a stand-alone company prior to its
landmark 1990 merger with Time Inc. The duo, who often work in New
York, have accumulated a staggering amount of power in the movie,
TV and music businesses -- all volatile enterprises prone to wild
swings in fortune due to rapid-fire changes in customer tastes.
</P>
<P>
   More than any other studio, Warner relied on big-budget
``tent-pole'' productions, superstars like Mel Gibson and
recognizable vehicles like the ``Batman'' and ``Lethal Weapon''
franchises. ``Bob and Terry really defined what Warner was all
about, and they did a superb job,'' Dixon said.
</P>
<P>
   The collaborative style served them well, according to Brad
Marks, head of an executive recruiting firm. ``They really had
complementary skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``When there's friendship and trust, two people can be very
effective. Daly is a great big-picture kind of guy, while Terry is
more the operating guy overseeing the day-to-day business.''
</P>
<P>
   Daly and Semel also were regarded as gifted at relationships
with stars like Gibson, Clint Eastwood, Harrison Ford and Kevin
Costner. Both often journeyed with stars in a corporate jet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty unusual to see that kind of sharing of power,''
said Steve Cesinger, managing director at Greif &AMP; Co. ``If you look
at top people in Hollywood, sharing the glory is not high on the
list. It's a good structure for executives to get second-guessed on
$100 million decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the duo will be remembered best for ``Batman'' and
``Lethal Weapon,'' their credits include landmark films with
commercial and critical successes such as ``Chariots of Fire,''
``Arthur,'' ``The Killing Fields,'' ``Driving Miss Daisy,''
``GoodFellas,'' ``Unforgiven,'' ``The Fugitive'' and ``L.A.
Confidential.'' TV hits include ``E.R.'' and ``Friends,'' and the
WB Network has topped expectations with successes like ``Buffy, the
Vampire Slayer.''
</P>
<P>
   The pair's reputations were tarnished two years ago amid a box
office slump that led to carping about over-reliance on outdated
formulas. Other trackers complained that Levin's 1995 decision to
give Daly and Semel control over music stretched their abilities
too thin.
</P>
<P>
   But the studio's performance has turned around with Time Warner
stock up 250 percent since the start of 1998. Shares fell $1.4375
to $75.875 on Thursday, the day after Time Warner posted
better-than-expected profits in all divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Warner is third in film share this year behind 20th Century Fox
and Universal with $480 million in domestic gross, and its latest,
the much-awaited ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' opens today with solid
prospects. Its next three films -- ``Deep Blue Sea,'' ``Iron
Giant'' and ``Mickey Blue Eyes'' -- should perform well, according
to Robert Bucksbaum, president of the Reel Source forecasting
service.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they've done a good job of adjusting to the shift
toward the teen-age market becoming so powerful. Warner has been
the single most consistent performer, and that's the key in this
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Several industry trackers compared Thursday's decision to the
retirement of basketball superstar Michael Jordan. ``Daly and Semel
are going out on a high note,'' said Barry Hyman, market strategist
with Ehrenkrantz King Nussbaum. ``It's hard to see what else they
could have accomplished.''
</P>
<P>
   The pair did not indicate whether they will continue their
partnership, but several trackers suggested Daly and Semel might
move into an Internet venture. ``I would be shocked if they just
rode off into the sunset,'' Cesinger said.
</P>
<P>
   When the two started with the company 20 years ago, the film and
television group had revenues of less than $1 billion; by the end
of 1998, it reported revenues of approximately $6 billion. Their
partnership began in 1980 when Daly was hired as chairman after
working as chief CBS programmer while Semel was working as vice
president and chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   Marks said Levin and Turner should move quickly to find a
successor or successors, but they should start by first agreeing on
Warner Bros.' strategic direction. ``In a peculiar way, Daly and
Semel leaving is very opportune,'' he added. ``Time Warner can
develop a job description without an individual in mind and then
find the best person.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
