<SLUG> BC-SUPERIOR-EARNINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPERIOR'S PROFITS DEFY FORECASTERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY ENRIQUE RIVERO  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Superior Industries International Inc. reported
Thursday that second-quarter earnings jumped 56 percent compared
with the like year-ago period, easily beating Wall Street's
forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   The Van Nuys-based maker of aluminum wheels for vehicles and
auto accessories earned $19.2 million, or 71 cents per diluted
share, vs. $12.3 million, or 44 cents per diluted share, in the
comparable period last year. Revenues were $155 million, up 12
percent from $138.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Seven analysts surveyed by First Call had predicted earnings
averaging 64 cents per share.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Tadross, senior auto parts analyst for Prudential
Securities Inc. in New York City, said he had initially predicted
earnings of 63 cents per share. But he upped it to 70 cents Tuesday
following the company's announcement that it expected to end the
quarter at 69 cents.
</P>
<P>
   The company has kept costs under control and increased gross
profits, resulting in the strong results, he said. Some significant
new contracts with automotive manufacturers also helped.
</P>
<P>
   ``They saw some good internal growth -- 3 percent to 5 percent
-- and I think they're reducing their costs faster than they're
giving price concessions,'' Tadross said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he has a ``hold'' recommendation on the stock, in part
because the company's internal growth, while good, was ``slower
than the average.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I expect that to pick up toward the end of 2000,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Superior's stock rose 12.5 cents Thursday to close at $28.375.
</P>
<P>
   Unit shipments were up 20 percent and Superior's plants were
operating at ``very high utilization capacity,'' said R. Jeffrey
Ornstein,company vice president and chief financial officer.
Earnings had been running about 64 cents per share earlier in the
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quarter just picked up a lot of momentum as it went,''
Ornstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Superior also said that during the quarter it bought about
169,000 shares of its stock and has now acquired 1.154 million
shares under its 2 million-share repurchase authorization.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
