<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-DODGER2-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MO GIVES ANGELS WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (QUICK WRITETHROUGH) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Mo Vaughn's single off Onan Masaoka in the
10th inning scored Randy Velarde from second base to give the
Anaheim Angels a 7-6 victory over the Los Angeles Dodgers before a
sellout crowd of 43,911 Thursday night at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was the Angels' fifth in six games and allowed them
to keep pace with the Texas Rangers, who also won Thursday, 6 1/2
games back in the A.L. West.
</P>
<P>
   For the Dodgers, the loss snapped their winning streak at four
and dropped them 11 games behind first-place San Francisco in the
N.L. West.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Petkovsek (9-2) pitched two scoreless inning in relief to
earn the victory and become the winningest pitcher on the Angels
staff. Alan Mills (2-2) got the loss for the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Dodgers manager Davey Johnson would even pitch to
Vaughn was curious. With Velarde on second base, first base was
open and his run meant nothing. Also, Vaughn went into the game
hitting .393 vs. lefties, compated to .239 against right-handers.
</P>
<P>
   So it couldn't have come as a surprise to many that Vaughn lined
a 2-2 pitch past Mark Grudzielanek at short and into left field,
easily scoring Velarde for the Angels win.
</P>
<P>
   Former Angel Devon White's three-run homer off Angels starter
Chuck Finley gave the Dodgers their first lead of the night at 6-5
in the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   White, who also had a double and two singles, is hitting .529 (9
for 17) with two homers and nine RBIs in four games against the
Angels this season. His grand slam keyed a 7-4 win over the Angels
on June 5.
</P>
<P>
   But White's big hit didn't stand up because Pedro Borbon,
pitching in relief of starter Kevin Brown, couldn't hold it.
</P>
<P>
   Angels second baseman Randy Velarde had to be happy to see Brown
gone when he came up in the seventh. After looking bad in three
at-bats against Brown, striking out twice, Velarde homered off
Borbon, tying the game at 6.
</P>
<P>
   It also increased Velarde's hitting streak to 11 games.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams had their ace throwing, but neither Brown nor Finley
pitched like it.
</P>
<P>
   Brown gave up five runs and five hits in 5 1/3 innings, striking
out six and walking three. Finley gave up six runs and eight hits
in five innings, striking out six and walking four. Neither was
involved in the decision.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels got on the scoreboard first, scoring four runs in the
second inning against Brown. And the key to the inning came because
Orlando Palmeiro couldn't get a bunt down.
</P>
<P>
   With runners on first and second and none out, Palmeiro fouled
off two bunt attempts. On a 0-2 pitch, he slapped a grounder just
inside first and down the right-field line for a double, scoring
Garret Anderson from second for a 1-0 Angels lead.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Huson, in the DH spot for the second time this season,
followed with a single to right to score two more and give the
Angels a 3-0 lead. Huson went to third on Gary DiSarcina's flyout
to right, and after a walk to Matt Walbeck, scored when Darin
Erstad grounded into a fielder's choice.
</P>
<P>
   The 4-0 lead was tenous as best, as Finley struggled in the
first few innings before the Dodgers broke through for three runs
in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   The scored one run and had the bases loaded with one out without
hitting the ball out of the infield. Three infield singles and a
walk resulted in their first run before Angel Pena's two-run single
narrowed the Angels' lead to 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   Huson's RBI double in the bottom of the fourth increased the
Angels' lead to 5-3, but it only lasted until White batted in the
top of the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   White blasted a three-run homer, his eighth of the season to
give the Dodgers a 6-5 lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
