<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-NOTEBOOK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAERGA REMEMBERS '95 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It was nothing against the city, Carlos Baerga said.
When the San Diego Padres infielder played for the Cleveland
Indians, he always enjoyed coming to the Northwest. But the
Kingdome was such a downer, he couldn't wait to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``You didn't see that many fans in the ballpark,'' Baerga said.
``They were losing all the time. It's a beautiful city, but you
only wanted to be there a couple of days and then go.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything changed in 1995, when it took Baerga's Indians _ a
powerhouse that went 100-44 in the regular season _ to finally halt
the Mariners' postseason joyride.
</P>
<P>
   Baerga said the hardest time he ever had concentrating on a
field was in the '95 playoffs, because of the noise. He reflected
on that postseason Thursday with teammate Jim Leyritz, the Yankee
catcher Ken Griffey Jr. slid past to win the Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the '94 strike, that did so much for baseball in
general, much less the Seattle Mariners,'' Leyritz said. ``And I
think the job Randy Johnson did that series and the sacrifice he
made going out there that day really generated a lot of interest
and support here.''
</P>
<P>
   If not for that victory, Seattle wouldn't have opened a new
ballpark Thursday night _ and would never have become the baseball
town it is now.
</P>
<P>
   ``In New York, you walk down the street and they know who you
are,'' said Mariners third baseman Russ Davis, a Yankee in '95.
``And now, that's what it's like here. You get recognized
everywhere you go. People understand it here, and they know their
baseball. New York fans are true baseball fans, they absolutely
love it. They got a taste of that up here, and hopefully it's just
going to get better with the new stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   Baerga saw what happened in Cleveland after the Indians moved
into Jacobs Field in 1994. The Tribe has made the playoffs every
season and sold out more than 300 games in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a new life for this team, this city and for
everything around it commercially,'' Baerga said. ``It happened in
Cleveland. Cleveland was nothing before they built that ballpark.
That ballpark was the best thing that ever happened there.''
</P>
<P>
   Safeco Field, Baerga said, ``is like a gift on Christmas. You
love it and you can't stop playing with it. I think the fans here
in Seattle are going to have something to love for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   GWYNN SCRATCHED: Padres outfielder Tony Gwynn was in the
original lineup for Thursday night's game, batting second and
playing designated hitter. But Gwynn's strained left calf, which
has kept him out of action since June 19, stiffened up on him
during warm-ups Thursday. He was available for pinch hitting.
</P>
<P>
   THERE AT THE START: In 1992, Padres broadcaster Rick Sutcliffe
threw the first pitch at the ballpark that started baseball's
stadium craze, Baltimore's Oriole Park at Camden Yards. Months
before that game, when he visited the unfinished park as a free
agent, Sutcliffe realized he was seeing the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked down the left-field line, and it reminded me a little
bit of Shea Stadium,'' Sutcliffe said. ``I looked above the
first-base dugouts, saw the rafters and that reminded me of Wrigley
Field. Everywhere I looked, it reminded me of old-time ballparks _
and yet, everything was new. That ballpark was not built for
baseball players; it was built for the fans. And I sense it's the
same way with the ballpark here.''
</P>
<P>
   Sutcliffe also is a former teammate of Jamie Moyer, who threw
the first pitch at Safeco Field Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try to keep it as normal as possible, but it's not
possible,'' Sutcliffe said. ``The first pitch is always messed up.
Normally you try to throw it down the middle, but here, you want to
put it on the outside corner or miss outside. The last thing you
want to do is give up a hit on the first pitch in a new park.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time, you know you're going to get a little more
leeway from the umpire. The crowd's on its feet, and they want to
see that right arm go up for strike one.''
</P>
<P>
   Moyer indeed threw a called strike one.
</P>
<P>
   GREAT TIMING: Ozzie Timmons woke up at 4:40 a.m. Thursday, a few
hours after going 1 for 4 at the Triple-A All-Star Game at Zephyr
Field in New Orleans. He had no clue he'd be in Safeco Field
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   When he got off the plane, Timmons saw Greg Hunter, the Mariners
assistant farm director.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was here to pick up some media guys from Tacoma.
I almost walked right past him,'' Timmons said.
</P>
<P>
   Good thing he didn't. Hunter was there to tell Timmons he'd been
called up to Seattle, the result of injuries to Charles Gipson and
Brian Hunter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a thrill to get called up,'' said Timmons, an
outfielder who was batting .273 with 21 homers and 66 RBIs for
Tacoma. ``And then to find out it was opening day of a new stadium,
that was great, too. This is a beautiful place.''
</P>
<P>
   A career National Leaguer, Timmons last played in the majors for
Cincinnati in 1997, a year before Bank One Ballpark opened in
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ALL NERVES: Jordan Zimmerman didn't play in the All-Star Game
Tuesday. But it sure felt like he did.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman, the Mariners' rookie left-hander, watched from his
Seattle apartment as brother Jeff of the Texas Rangers hurled a
scoreless seventh inning for the American League. It wasn't easy
for Jeff _ or Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he walked that first guy, I could not watch,'' Jordan
said. ``I closed my eyes and asked my wife to give me the
play-by-play.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he wasn't nervous, but I know he was. You could see
him shaking out there; I would be, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan is getting one souvenir from his brother _ an All-Star
cap with Jeff's signature stitched to the side. But you won't catch
Jordan wearing it around Safeco Field. The hat has a Rangers logo
in front.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-99 0211EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
