<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 02:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2303 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      07-16 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WALK IN THE PARK: M'S LOSE SAFECO FIELD OPENER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It was not supposed to happen like this. This was a
day for streamers from the rafters, for a dreamy Kinsella recital,
for the heavens to watch a major league baseball game in Seattle
for the first time in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   New beginning. Old nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   For everything the Mariners changed when they moved to Safeco
Field Thursday night, they kept the same bullpen they had in the
Kingdome. Closer Jose Mesa, brought in to save a come-from-behind
thriller, walked four of the five San Diego Padres he faced. It
doomed the Mariners to a 3-2 loss before 44,607 fans.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle has lost six in a row and is in sole possession of last
place for the first time since April.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 1-0 with two outs in the bottom of the eighth, the
Mariners offense awoke. Dan Wilson doubled off the wall in right
field. David Bell doubled down the third-base line _ his third of
the game _ to tie the score. David Segui rifled an opposite-field
double to right, bringing in Bell to give the M's a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Then, disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa, pitching for the first time since last Wednesday in
Anaheim, came in to relieve Jamie Moyer, who allowed one run and
struck out nine in eight innings.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa walked leadoff hitter Ruben Rivera, who stole second.
Pinch-hitters John Vander Wal and Ed Giovanola then walked,
prompting a mound visit by Lou Piniella. The Mariners manager
stayed with Mesa, drawing the first sustained booing in Safeco
Field history. Mesa rewarded Piniella for one hitter, striking out
Dave Magadan.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa fell behind Quilvio Veras, 2-and-0, then got a called
strike and a foul ball. His 2-2 pitch missed down and in, and the
full-count pitch missed to the same spot. Veras flipped his bat,
skipped to first, the tying run came in and Mesa came out.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's my closer,'' Piniella said. ``I thought he had a better
chance of striking them out than (Paul) Abbott. What can I say?
It's a shame the way we lost it.''
</P>
<P>
   Piniella called on Abbott, the hottest hand in the bullpen
lately, and Eric Owens lofted his first pitch to right. The
returning Jay Buhner gave chase, dropping the ball after he crossed
into foul territory. Heady move: had Buhner caught it, Vander Wal
almost surely would have tagged up and scored.
</P>
<P>
   He ended up doing so anyway. Owens lined out to Butch Huskey in
left, bringing in the go-ahead run. After Reggie Sanders grounded
into a force out to end the inning, the Padres had scored the tying
and go-ahead runs without getting a hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Jose's out there doing his darndest,'' Moyer said.
``He's not trying to throw the game away. ... It's frustrating, but
I feel for the guy. I'm not upset at him.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the game, one threatening forecast held true, and
another held off. As predicted, the ball didn't have the same carry
at Safeco Field as it did across the street. Ken Griffey Jr. sliced
a fly ball to the left-center field gap in his first at bat, and
the crowd gasped. Griffey had homered to that spot in his first at
bat in the Kingdome. He had hit the last Kingdome home run, and 196
others there over the years.
</P>
<P>
   But this ball reached only the warning track, where Owens caught
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball that Junior hit to left-center field, that might have
been out in the Kingdome,'' Moyer said.
</P>
<P>
   The other forecast called for rain. When it never came, it made
for the greatest slide in this town's history when the ballpark's
roof slid open an hour before Moyer's first-pitch strike.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego scored its only run off Moyer in the third inning,
when DH Phil Nevin's two-out grounder hopped over the glove of
third baseman Russ Davis, bringing in Veras with the ballpark's
first run. Veras had led off the inning with a single and advanced
to second when an off-balance Moyer shoveled Owens' sacrifice bunt
from his glove to Segui's at first.
</P>
<P>
   Owens was batting second in place of future Hall of Famer Tony
Gwynn, whose calf strain kept him out Thursday night and has him
listed as doubtful for Friday night's game. Owens singled to right
field in the first inning for Safeco Field's first hit.
</P>
<P>
   Bell's leadoff double to left was the M's first hit, but fly
outs by Segui and Griffey and a strikeout by Alex Rodriguez
stranded him at second.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey doubled to lead off the ``Louie, Louie'' inning (it's
still played at stretch time), and went to third on Rodriguez's
ground out. Edgar Martinez then struck out, and Buhner _ playing
for the first time in nearly two months _ grounded to second
baseman Veras, who ranged to his right, fell to his knees for the
ball, and threw Buhner out to end the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego moved above .500 with the win. The Mariners, who went
quietly in the ninth inning against Dan Miceli, the Padres'
emergency closer because Trevor Hoffman is sick, slipped to four
under. The Padres heard those boos in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just the way things have gone since we've been playing
well lately,'' said Nevin. ``(Mesa) is one of the best closers in
the game. Our hitters were just good at making him throw the ball.
No one's gonna be perfect all the time. The fans here need to
remember that.''
</P>
<P>
   Mariner fans have years of memories of bullpen failures.
Thursday night, they got their first on the other side of Royal
Brougham Way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
