<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 02:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2305 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      07-16 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST NIGHT PLAYED TO PERFECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ No heartstring went unplucked Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   From the baserunning of the 5-year-old grandson of Fred
Hutchinson to the ceremonial first pitch from teary-eyed Dave
Niehaus, over the sounds of the Seattle Symphony and under a sky
free of concrete, the new ballpark swung on and belted.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball's commissioner, Bud Selig, was even imported to do what
he does best _ in launching a passionate, eloquent pre-game defense
of the Mariners owners' audacious tax-money plot, he justified the
unjustifiable.
</P>
<P>
   All the way around, a vivid evening for the 44,607 brave outdoor
baseball pioneers, even if the overwhelmed concession lines were
longer than in the Kingdome's worst day. So alive was the Guilty
Pleasure that the alert fan could come away with souvenir smudge of
wet green paint (just add the cleaning bill to the cost overruns).
</P>
<P>
   Far as I could tell, only one important thing was missing: the
statue at the main entrance of Marcel Lachemann, without whom
Seattle's leap into Rolls Royce baseball would not have been
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Lachemann wasn't exactly a central figure, but he was symbolic.
After all, it wouldn't very well do to have a statue of the entire
1995 California Angels at the threshold of baseball's most
grandiose extravagance.
</P>
<P>
   So a figure of their beleaguered manager, slightly stooped and
face in hands, would capture all the poignant irony.
</P>
<P>
   Had his Angels not fallen from a 13-game lead, one of the most
ghastly swoons in baseball history, to allow the Mariners into the
1995 playoffs, the local nine likely would have been without the
baseball momentum that built the $517 million colossus now dividing
trains from ships in downtown's industrial flats.
</P>
<P>
   Though much has been made, justifiably, of the political,
financial and psychological derring-do that beat the astounding
odds, fact is that the fundamental most vital to creating the park
was winning baseball.
</P>
<P>
   So it is no surprise that the requirement for sustaining the
park and its monumental investment is the same.
</P>
<P>
   Without a thriving ballclub, the Guilty Pleasure is merely an
epic pile of steel and concrete.
</P>
<P>
   Splendid as was the inauguration of gray, blue and black skies
and green grass into the local sporting consciousness, the Mariners
still lost their sixth in a row with yet another bullpen
disintegration.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the Mariners crossed Royal Brougham Way with all
their baggage.
</P>
<P>
   Difference is, after the 3-2 loss to the San Diego Padres, the
newly audible train whistles seemed mournful. Also perhaps fateful.
Losing reliever Jose Mesa, who walked four to allow the
game-deciding runs in the ninth, needs to know that Burlington
Northern's nightly 10:05 chugging behind the stadium usually has a
few empty box cars.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, with the offense having scored six runs in the past
four games, Mesa could have any number of teammates to keep him
warm in the open car.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners' skid at such a moment in civic sports history
points up a grim baseball first: The team is nowhere near as good
as its house. But don't feel any extra pressure, guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I hadn't even thought of that,'' said Edgar
Martinez, echoing the sentiment of several teammates.
</P>
<P>
   One of the virtues of great players is the ability to be
unreflective. This is, after all, mostly a game of see-ball,
hit-ball, catch-ball. It's just as well that the players don't
ponder the psychological tonnage that comes with the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I play the game, regardless,'' Ken Griffey Jr. said. ``What
else do you want me to do?''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners folks who are paid to be reflective are management
and ownership, a bunch who lately have seemed a little light on the
virtue.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Mariners president Chuck Armstrong paused long
enough in the frenzy of his dream-come-true to reluctantly ponder
the implications of putting out a team that matches what the
taxpayers have put out for the yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard some of that sentiment, so maybe that's there,'' he
said. ``Consciously or subconsciously, maybe it's a part of
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Though asserting the usual platitudes about ownership's
commitment to winning, Armstrong acknowledged that because of lower
Kingdome attendance in the season's first half, the team is behind
the 1999 business plan to break even. He estimated the move to the
new field will generate $8 million to $10 million in additional
revenue this year, ``although we'd like not to spend it all on
player payroll. We don't want to go hog wild.''
</P>
<P>
   That sounds like something less than a resounding call to
baseball arms. Probably not a surprise for a franchise whose most
enduring, compelling figure is their broadcaster.
</P>
<P>
   If ever there were a citizenry and a fan base deserving of a
William Wallace-like call to the castlemounts, it is one that just
spent $517 million for the castle on the night the team fell into
the basement of the smallest division in the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
