<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 02:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2338 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-NEWDODGE-LADN-(SL     07-16 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NEWDODGE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WRITETHROUGH 
MO GIVES ANGELS WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ It was one small step in the standings but one
giant leap for the Anaheim Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Mo Vaughn's single off Onan Masaoka in the 10th inning scored
Randy Velarde from second base to give the Angels a 7-6 victory
over the Los Angeles Dodgers before a sellout crowd of 43,911
Thursday night at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was the Angels' fifth in six games and allowed them
to move out of last place in the AL West for the first time since
May 25. They kept pace with the Texas Rangers, remaining 6{ games
back in the AL West and moving ahead of the Seattle Mariners, who
fell seven games out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's big,'' Vaughn said. ``You come in a look at the standings
and see you're at the bottom. I've told people I haven't been in
last place in a lot of years. Getting over that hump is a big deal.
Now we've got to get over .500 and start moving forward.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Dodgers, the loss snapped their winning streak at four,
but because the Giants also lost, they remained 10 games back in
the NL West.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Petkovsek (9-2) pitched two scoreless innings in relief to
earn the victory and become the winningest pitcher on the Angels
staff. Alan Mills (2-2) got the loss for the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Dodgers manager Davey Johnson would even pitch to
Vaughn in the 10th inning was curious. With Velarde on second base,
first base was open and Vaughn's run meant nothing. Also, Vaughn
went into the game hitting .393 vs. lefties, compared to .239
against right-handers. So it couldn't have come as a surprise to
many that Vaughn lined a 2-2 pitch past Mark Grudzielanek at short
and into left field, easily scoring Velarde for the Angels win.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, though, said he wasn't surprised the Dodgers pitched to
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no outs, and you can't walk everybody,'' he said.
``The number of outs dictate how they're going to come at you. I've
been intentionally walked enough in this game and pitched around a
lot, so I've learned when to be aggressive and when not to.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Johnson: ``I was shooting craps out there. Leadoff double
with the middle of the lineup coming up. We were going to walk him
if we got behind, but we got two quick strikes. I was shooting
craps there. I don't feel good about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Angel Devon White's three-run homer off Angels starter
Chuck Finley gave the Dodgers their first lead of the night at 6-5
in the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   White, who also had a double and two singles, is hitting .529 (9
for 17) with two homers and nine RBI in four games against the
Angels this season. His grand slam keyed a 7-4 win over the Angels
on June 5. But White's big hit didn't stand up because Pedro
Borbon, pitching in relief of starter Kevin Brown, couldn't hold
it.
</P>
<P>
   Velarde was happy to see Brown gone when he came up in the
seventh. After looking bad in three at-bats against Brown, striking
out twice, Velarde homered off Borbon, tying the game at 6. It also
increased Velarde's hitting streak to 11 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the happiest guy in the world when I saw (Brown) walk
off the field,'' Velarde said. ``I saw (Borbon) throw fastballs,
87-, 88-mph, batting- practice fastballs.''
</P>
<P>
   Both teams had their ace throwing, but neither Brown nor Finley
pitched like it. Brown gave up five runs and five hits in 51/3
innings, striking out six and walking three. Finley gave up six
runs and eight hits in five innings, striking out six and walking
four. Neither was involved in the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Finley continues to struggle _ his ERA rose to 5.89
_ Angels manager Terry Collins hasn't lost faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're going to get back in this, Chuck Finley is going to
be one of the guys driving the bus,'' Collins said. ``When he gets
it going, we're going to hop on that big back and ride it for a
while.'' &UR; !dlim!!end! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
