r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-`SPACEPORT'-STATE-RIV     07-16 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-`SPACEPORT'-STATE-RIVALS-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATES VIE FOR STARDOM AS AMERICA'S SPACE INDUSTRY HUB  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: FLORIDA, TEXAS...also Montana, Nevada, New Mexico)   (This excellent 825-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 17 July 1999) ECONOMIST magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, TEXAS AND WASHINGTON, D.C. _ In his science-fiction
classic ``From Earth to the Moon,'' Jules Verne tells the tale of a
group of American entrepreneurs who had the crazed notion that it
was possible to send humans to the moon.
</P>
<P>
   After working out what size of cannon and how much gunpowder
would be needed to propel the capsule into space, all that remained
was to decide where the launch should occur.
</P>
<P>
   It was narrowed down to either Texas or Florida, inciting a
battle royal between the two states. Texans dismissed Florida as a
``wretched little strip of country''; Florida's representatives
decried Texas as a remote wasteland teeming with Mexican bandits.
</P>
<P>
   More than 130 years after Verne wrote his novel, the arguments
have become a bit more sophisticated and the stakes a bit more
serious in the battle over where to put the future hub of the
American space industry.
</P>
<P>
   Texas and Florida are currently the front-runners among 15
states pitching plans to aerospace manufacturers for futuristic
``spaceports'' in a bid to capture a slice of the burgeoning
commercial satellite market (expected to be worth $120 billion by
2010).
</P>
<P>
   The worldwide demand for Internet and cellular telephone service
has created the need for communications companies around the globe
to get hundreds of satellites into orbit as quickly and cheaply as
possible. The proposed spaceports are seen as one answer.
</P>
<P>
   Several companies are developing space vehicles that could take
off from a domestic spaceport and carry cargo into space with
almost the frequency of a jumbo jet.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the current Space Shuttle, these Reusable Launch Vehicles
(RLVs) would be able to go up and come down entirely under their
own power, making disposable fuel tanks and rocket boosters
unnecessary. The turnaround time between launches would thus be
dramatically cut.
</P>
<P>
   This would be an obvious boon to the commercial space industry,
which is expected to account for roughly 75 percent of all launches
ten years from now, with the government down to a quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The jewel of the proposed RLVs, and the project the competing
states are most eager to land, is Lockheed Martin's VentureStar.
</P>
<P>
   According to Lockheed officials, VentureStar will be able to
take cargo into space at a tenth of the current cost, and could be
ready to fly every two or three days.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to commercial interest in the project, the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) has also indicated that
VentureStar could ultimately replace the Space Shuttle and become
the primary courier to the International Space Station.
</P>
<P>
   NASA has put up most of the money for a VentureStar prototype
that will be ready for testing next year. If the tests are
successful, Lockheed will decide where to base the project among
the 15 competing states.
</P>
<P>
   It could begin operating by 2005, though many scientists think
RLVs will not really get off the ground for another 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   The interested states have stepped up their efforts to reel in
VentureStar. State officials print glossy proposals and fly
Lockheed officials in helicopters over the proposed spaceport
sites.
</P>
<P>
   Wooing VentureStar has a special urgency for Florida, which has
seen money for Cape Canaveral dry up as companies have begun to buy
launch services from sites outside the country.
</P>
<P>
   According to Edward Ellegood, an official at the Spaceport
Florida Authority, losing VentureStar and other RLV projects could
bring the end of the space industry in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Governor Jeb Bush and the Florida legislature were so alarmed by
the thought that they recently set aside millions of dollars to
improve the state's launch infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   This new influx of money could give Florida a leg up in the
space race, yet Tom Moser of the Texas Aerospace Commission will
not entertain such an idea.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in an office adorned with model spaceships, he argues
that the proposed Texas spaceport would neither depend on federal
money nor require the use of federal air space, two factors he
believes will entice aerospace companies that want to minimize
bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   But other states would like a piece of the action, too. Since
the new RLVs will not discard any equipment after being launched,
it is no longer necessary to send them up from coastal sites.
Landlocked states like Montana, New Mexico and Nevada may also land
spaceport contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Those directing each state's efforts are quick to point out
that, even if they are unsuccessful with Lockheed's VentureStar,
there are several other RLV projects in the works that could give
them a stake in the new space industry.
</P>
<P>
   Kistler Aerospace and Space Access, two of Lockheed's rivals,
are also developing reusable spacecraft and are shopping around for
launch sites.
</P>
<P>
   With 1,700 satellites being prepared for launching over the next
decade, a state does not want to be left out of the multibillion
dollar market. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
