<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 03:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2351 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTER-INNOVATION-S     07-16 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-INNOVATION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSCOPIC SWITCH COULD SHRINK COMPUTERS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARL T. HALL 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In what could be a big step toward making
computers faster and smaller than ever, layers of individual
molecules have been forged into tiny computer switches, scientists
announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers plan to assemble these switches and other diminutive
components into futuristic devices called ``chemically assembled
electronic nanocomputers,'' or CAENs _ machines that would be
billions of times more powerful than today's personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to use chemistry and clever software to overcome the
inherent limits of current computer-building methods. Experts say
that while many strategies are being tried, none has proved
successful so far.
</P>
<P>
   The latest results, reported Friday in the journal Science, are
``a step in the right direction,'' said Ray Muriella, director of
microtechnology at Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's another route to further miniaturization of logic, which
is something people have been fretting about for at least 10
years,'' Muriella said.
</P>
<P>
   The new switches are the handiwork of computer scientists and
chemists at Hewlett-Packard Laboratories in Palo Alto, Calif., and
at the University of California at Los Angeles. Their goal is to
get the first CAEN components up and running within two years.
</P>
<P>
   Reporting their latest experimental results, scientists showed
how a synthetic ``electronically active'' molecule called rotaxane
could function as a binary switch when suspended between
electrodes.
</P>
<P>
   Such a switch is a device capable of being in either of two
positions, which gives rise to the rudimentary elements of computer
logic. The Hewlett-Packard and UCLA team showed how it is possible
to configure the switches into what are known as ``logic gates''
signifying either ``and'' or ``or.''
</P>
<P>
   Plans envision wiring such logic gates into a radically
different type of computer architecture, based on what is called a
``defect-tolerant'' design amenable to commercial production.
</P>
<P>
   By designing molecules that function as electronic components,
chemists can cook up submicroscopic computer parts by the
beakerful. It would then be a fairly simple matter to spread the
parts in a thin film onto wafers of silicon.
</P>
<P>
   The result would be a sort of mess by design, the framework for
what the experts call ``electronically configurable'' logic.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to use software and scanning techniques to analyze
each chip after it has been coated with the molecular components
and tiny wires.
</P>
<P>
   The software searches out the functional switches and wires,
bypassing the defective ones, until a complete circuit is created.
It works only when there are plenty of alternative pathways and
redundant switches to start out.
</P>
<P>
   Experts liken it to the natural process in which the brain makes
complex neurological circuits from a seemingly haphazard patchwork,
tapping some nerve cells while ignoring others as the need arises.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came up with a way to make a lattice of wires and switches,
then electronically configure those resources into something that
can do a computational task for you,'' said UCLA chemist James
Heath.
</P>
<P>
   The scheme sidesteps the manufacturing problems posed by
super-small printed circuitry using conventional methods. Although
bacteria-sized computers are still a long way off, the new methods
may be capable of building computer microcircuits much more compact
than is now possible, and for much lower manufacturing costs,
because the software takes care of fixing the defects after the
chips are built.
</P>
<P>
   Before the new assembly scheme could get past square one,
however, the computer scientists first had to show that a workable
switch could be produced in a chemistry lab.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the part of the project that had the greatest risk
and made us the most nervous,'' said Philip Kuekes, a computer
architect at Hewlett-Packard.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers are conducting experiments in an effort to make
the wires smaller. Those used in the new switch are conventional
metal wires, many times thicker than the smallest carbon-based
``nanotube'' wires now available.
</P>
<P>
   These metallic carbon tubes can be stretched into long strands
as thin as a single nanometer _ just a billionth of a meter, a
dimension used to measure atoms and viruses.
</P>
<P>
   Encouraged by their progress so far, the Hewlett-Packard and
UCLA researchers said they are confident that the first CAEN
prototype will be completed by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a clear line of sight now to do it,'' said UCLA
chemist Heath.
</P>
<P>
   One problem yet to be solved is how to make switches that can be
set and reset repeatedly. The rotax-ane molecules used in the
experiments can only be set once, meaning they could be used for
making ``read-only memory,'' known as ROM, but not the more common
``random access memory,'' or RAM.
</P>
<P>
   Even if such technical problems can be solved within the
two-year schedule, the first machine will be nothing special
compared with the capabilities of the average desktop computers now
being sold. The researchers said all they intend to do initially is
produce a functioning prototype, capable of performing simple
arithmetic functions, to demonstrate the potential of the new
technology.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of this prototype venture is expected to be an
assembly of two to five logic gates within a space no bigger than
about 200 nanometers.
</P>
<P>
   But the ultimate goals are much more ambitious miniature
machines.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewed this week at Hewlett-Packard's Palo Alto campus,
Kuekes predicted computer components so small and inexpensive they
could be mixed like pigment into paint or embedded in virtually any
device that could benefit from so-called smart capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, researchers are still struggling to perfect the
essential building blocks _ electronic components and wires far too
small to be produced effectively using straightforward
manufacturing methods and standard quality control.
</P>
<P>
   The UCLA and Hewlett-Packard team used synthetic, Y-shaped
molecules of a substance called rotaxane, sandwiched in a
single-molecule-thick layer between lattices of ordinary metallic
wires.
</P>
<P>
   One of the arms of the ``Y'' has a ring-shaped structure looped
around it like a doughnut on a stick. The switch capabilities
derive from current-induced changes in the position of the
doughnut.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, the molecule is held between two wires in such a way
that a current can flow only if the molecule provides a platform
for the moving electrons. The electrons have to jump first onto a
rotaxane molecule to get across, a move Heath likened to a hiker
stepping onto a stone to get across a river.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a stone is there, the switch is closed, so the electrons
can hop and current flows,'' he explained.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-99 0328EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
