<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 03:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2352 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHEVRON-WAIVER-SFCHRO     07-16 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEVRON-WAIVER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CHEVRON WINS VARIANCE TO SELL LESS-CLEAN GAS  &HT;     By REBECCA SMITH 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In an unprecedented move, the California Air
Resources Board Thursday granted Chevron permission to sell
gasoline that violates the strict environmental guidelines of a
1996 state law.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron petitioned the agency late Tuesday for an emergency
variance, arguing that an explosion Saturday at its Richmond
refinery had slashed gasoline production to only 30 percent of the
normal amount.
</P>
<P>
   Without the waiver, Chevron said the state would experience a
gasoline shortage that would drive prices up sharply.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 law requires refiners in California to produce a
special formula gasoline that is less polluting. The variance
represents the first time an oil company has asked for and
succeeded in getting that law set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Critics fear other refineries might use this decision as
precedent in the event they face production problems.
</P>
<P>
   But Jerry Martin, a spokesman for the air board, said, ``The
variance was granted to avoid a supply disruption'' that could push
gas prices up.
</P>
<P>
   As part of Thursday's variance, Chevron now can import and sell
up to 3.5 million barrels of gasoline that meet federal, not state,
standards and sell them during a 45-day period.
</P>
<P>
   By law, Chevron would be required to pay 15 cents into an
environmental fund for each gallon of non-CARB gasoline sold. If it
sells the full amount allowed, some $22 million will flow into a
fund and will be used to get older, more-polluting vehicles off the
roads.
</P>
<P>
   Without the variance, Chevron said it would have had to reduce
gasoline deliveries to its service stations by the middle of next
week.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental advocates reacted angrily to the variance which
they said rewards Chevron for bad management. They also said they
were mad that less than 24 hours elapsed between the time Chevron
filed its emergency petition and when the agency conducted its
public hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state not only is allowing Chevron to profit from being an
unsafe refinery operator, but they've allowed themselves to be
pushed into this decision without allowing the public time to
react,'' said Denny Larson, director of the nonprofit group,
Communities for a Better Environment in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are mad as hell and we think everyone in California should
be,'' he continued. ``It sets a terrible precedent, especially
considering how often California seems to have refinery
explosions.''
</P>
<P>
   For economists, the question is not whether gasoline prices will
rise _ they already are rising _ but whether the additional supply
will do enough to ease the shortage and push prices back down, said
Severin Borenstein, head of the Energy Institute at University of
California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the next couple of weeks, we'll see prices going up,''
said Borenstein. ``What the Air Resources Board does won't stop
that because there's already been a supply disruption. And one
problem with prices going up is that there's a certain stickiness
that hinders their coming back down again.''
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear whether Chevron will pass the 15-cent-a-gallon
surcharge along to motorists. It's also possible other vendors,
whose wholesale prices also are rising, could raise gasoline prices
to match Chevron's.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion at the Richmond refinery already has had an impact
on the commodities market. Gasoline prices on the New York
Mercantile Exchange with an August delivery date rose 2.18 cents
Thursday, or 3.7 percent, to 61.7 cents a gallon. That's the
biggest increase since March 26 and the highest closing price in 21
months.
</P>
<P>
   The Richmond refinery is important to California gasoline
supplies because it produces more than 10 percent of the state's
cleaner-burning gasoline. Its troubles have cost the state 8
percent of its supply overnight.
</P>
<P>
   It's the second major problem at the refinery this year.
</P>
<P>
   An explosion and fire at the refinery last March temporarily
slashed production. The oil giant was able to make up for all but
15 percent of the normal refining production by buying partly
refined fuel elsewhere that it could finish refining.
</P>
<P>
   It had hoped to return the refinery to full production this
summer, but on Friday workers discovered a leak in a steam
generator. On Saturday, that leak led to a natural gas explosion
which rocked an electrostatic precipitator, a piece of equipment
that cleans particles from flue gas before it is exhausted into the
atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   There were no injuries but the refinery's production capacity
got knocked back to 30 percent of the normal 240,000 barrels of
crude a day.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Air Resources chief Michael Kenny, who granted
Thursday's emergency variance, Chevron said it will take several
weeks to get the precipitator back to half-operation and several
months to regain full use of the equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Summer is the peak driving season, which means there isn't a lot
of excess inventory that can be tapped to make up for the
shortfall. That's why Chevron proposed that it be allowed to go
outside the state, most likely to the Gulf states, to obtain
substitute gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron told Kenny that gasoline inventories, in the Western
region, slid to 26.9 million barrels in early July. That's close to
a five-year low.
</P>
<P>
   At Wednesday's hearing, there was only limited opposition to the
variance, but that could be because many groups were unaware of the
explosion, the variance request or the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not happy about Chevron's request because it sets a bad
precedent,'' said Roland Hwang, transportation director for the
Union of Concerned Scientists. ``It makes the point that the state
has become too dependent on gasoline and is vulnerable to
disruptions.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the fact that a single refinery problem can send a
tremor through the entire state should be a jolt that the state
needs better funding of mass transit, particularly systems that
rely on fuels that aren't petroleum based.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
