<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CELL PHONES ARE FOR THE BIRDS  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ I didn't set out to be the journalistic Carrie
Nation of cell phones, but it is my duty to report alarming news
when I stumble across it, as I was saying just this morning to the
people washing my car, the former staff of KPFA.
</P>
<P>
   And I have nothing against cell phones. Cell phones don't annoy
and endanger others,  &LR; people  &LR; annoy and endanger others. With cell
phones.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, here's today's alarming news:
</P>
<P>
   Down in Los Banos, Calif., there are many mockingbirds. One of
them regularly perches in the tree across the street from the home
of Joel Whitehurst Jr. Thursday morning, Joel strolled out to his
driveway to fetch his Chronicle and made a terrible discovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``That bird is usually a source of beautiful music,'' Joel says,
``but it has learned to imitate very precisely the ring of a cell
phone. Do you think he will stop when his battery runs down?''
</P>
<P>
   What do I look like, an ornithologist? (See mug shot. Good God,
I  &LR; do  &LR; look like an ornithologist.)
</P>
<P>
   This certainly gives a new meaning to ``bird calls.''
</P>
<P>
   All I know, Joel, is if your mockingbird is expecting to hear
from a crow, he'll need caw-waiting.
</P>
<P>
   Also, you might be stuck with the bird. He'll probably stay in
that tree to avoid costly roaming charges.
</P>
<P>
   Coming soon to Fox TV: ``When Birds Impersonate Annoying
Electronic Sounds.'' Today: My parrot thinks he's a smoke alarm.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever you do, Joel, don't take that bird to dinner at Moose's
Restaurant in San Francisco's North Beach. Ed Moose's joint has
gone cell free, because Ed found that many diners are annoyed by
Mr. Bigshot at the next table speaking in typical cell-yell,
closing a deal. So there are stern warnings on the menus and on the
tables.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, Ed asked cell phonies to take/make their calls in
the bar area, but this was annoying to the drinkers, many of whom
are already edgy because they can't smoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looks like we're headed for side-by-side outdoor compounds,''
Ed says, ``one for smokers and one for cell-phoners. Maybe we could
do a mixer.''
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe Ed could send the cellies to City Hair and Nails in
Seaside. Bruce Carlen got his hair cut there and reports:
</P>
<P>
   ``The barber was on her cell phone through most of the haircut.
I don't know what she was talking about, because she was speaking
in Vietnamese, but I'm glad it wasn't something infuriating.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe she was talking to her bird.
</P>
<P>
   FREE SPEECH is becoming less free and more costly.
</P>
<P>
   The KPFA situation is such an easy call, it barely rates
commentary. Clearly an unclear-on-the-concept. You start a radio
station based on free speech, then you order the speakers not to
speak freely?
</P>
<P>
   This whole thing would have blown over in two days if management
had told staff, ``We fired your beloved general manager because
we're desperately trying to build our audience so we can stay in
business and continue to employ all of you. We insist that you not
only report this firing on-air, but verbally rip us to shreds for
it. We hired you to tell the audience what you think. Do your
job.''
</P>
<P>
   A gag order at a hippie radio station in Berkeley. It would be
hard to think of a worse idea. A cell phone at a funeral, maybe.
</P>
<P>
   MAYBE a worse idea would be to film a TV commercial for beer,
featuring gay guys, make a big deal out of how progressive you are
for daring to target a gay audience for a macho product, then get
cold-filtered feet and shove the commercial back in the closet.
</P>
<P>
   Thus offending homophobes by doing the commercial, gays by not
running it and everyone else by being so wimpy and wishy-washy.
</P>
<P>
   First the gays get shoved around by the religious
fundamentalists, then the Mormons, then the Catholics, now the
Miller Brewing Co.
</P>
<P>
   It's starting to look like a vast Christian-Alcohol-wing
conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   The politics gets confusing. Tom Ammiano, president of the San
Francisco Board of Supes, is bringing heat on the Mormons for
violating the separation of church and state by using their clout
and money to support California legislation against gay marriage.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Trinity Episcopal Church, which celebrates its
150th year in San Francisco tomorrow, is proud of its public
support for such political issues as same-gender marriage, funding
for HIV research and opposition to capital punishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are concerned for social action as well as social
service,'' says Robert Warren Cromey, the rector.
</P>
<P>
   Which is great. Cromey's crew is an absolute rock of the
community for gays and straights and those who fluctuate. But how
is that kind of committed social and political activism
fundamentally different from what the Mormons are doing? Except
that the Mormons have more money.
</P>
<P>
   I don't have the answer to that question, by the way. I'm an
ornithologist, not a theologian.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
