<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 10:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2541 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HADASSAH-LIPTON-PROFI     07-16 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HADASSAH-LIPTON-PROFILE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN DEEP ADVERSITY, CHOOSING A LIFE DEVOTED TO JUDAISM AND ITS
CAUSES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bonnie Lipton's first words as a candidate for the presidency of
Hadassah came from Deuteronomy, and her heart: ``I have set before
you life and death,'' she said to her national board, quoting Moses
speaking to the Jews. ``Therefore choose life, that both thou and
thy seed may live.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Lipton understood the words better than she had ever
expected, or wanted. On Jan. 11, 1998, her husband, Alan, 59, had a
catastrophic skiing accident at Jiminy Peak, in Massachusetts _
five months after she was told that she had breast cancer and one
week after she began radiation.
</P>
<P>
   In the car on the way to the hospital to see her husband, she
turned to the friend with her and said, ``Do you realize that we
don't know if Alan is alive or dead, and I have to go for radiation
tomorrow either way?''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Lipton lived, but he is in a nursing home with severe brain
damage, unable to care for himself or remember what happened five
minutes before. Bonnie Lipton, who in 39 years of marriage
succeeded her husband as the leader of three other Jewish
organizations, has decided to carry on. She has chosen, as if it
were a choice at all, life.
</P>
<P>
   ``After what we both went through, I decided I was going to
channel all my energy into working for Hadassah and for Israel,''
Mrs. Lipton said. ``Because that was the core of what we both
believed in. And if something happened to me tomorrow _ you can't
help it, you realize this _ I would like it to be said that I made
a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   On July 27 in Washington, Mrs. Lipton, who is 59, is to take
over as Hadassah's new president. The same day, the organization is
to give Hillary Rodham Clinton an award, which was the cause of a
small but well-documented (by local television cameras) protest
outside Hadassah's West 58th Street headquarters on Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   About two dozen women and men _ Mrs. Lipton said she was
relieved the numbers were small _ burned a huge Hadassah card to
protest Mrs. Clinton's support for a Palestinian state. The First
Lady and likely New York Senate candidate has repeatedly said she
was only expressing the views of Israel's former Prime Minister,
Yitzak Rabin. Many polls show that most Israelis accept Palestinian
statehood as inevitable and even desirable, but opposition is
widespread among conservative American Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a nonpartisan organization,'' Mrs. Lipton said early
Thursday at Hadassah's headquarters. ``We are not honoring her as a
political candidate. We are honoring her as the first lady.''
</P>
<P>
   Brushing aside the protest was only one item on Mrs. Lipton's
schedule Thursday. By midmorning she was on the shuttle to
Washington to attend a lunch for Nava Barak, the wife of Prime
Minister Ehud Barak of Israel. Mrs. Lipton was planning to be back
in Washington on Sunday for a White House state dinner for Mr.
Barak. Meanwhile she was working on the speech she has to make on
July 27. And of course, worrying about the future of Hadassah,
which with 306,000 members is the largest women's and Jewish
organization in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But the Zionist and social service group has shrunk from its
high of more than 350,000 members in the 1980s, and has tried in
recent years to attract younger women and reinvent itself. (The
comedian Sarah Bernhard is a member, but more than half of
Hadassah's women are over 61, and 20 percent of the membership are
over 75.) ``The women for whom Hadassah was their life, and who
brought us where Hadassah is today, they're dying,'' Mrs. Lipton
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Lipton herself joined only when her mother-in-law gave her
a lifetime membership. It was 1961, she was 21, and she felt no
real need for the organization until 1971, when she moved to
Pittsfield, Mass., her husband's hometown and the base of his
family's steel and then used-machinery business. In 1975 she
visited Israel for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just felt this is going to be my career, this is who I am,''
Mrs. Lipton said.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years she volunteered her way upward at Hadassah,
raised two children and accompanied her husband on his quests.
``We'd see a rusty piece of something in the backyard of some
company and he would light up,'' Mrs. Lipton said.
</P>
<P>
   Her world fell apart in the summer of 1997, when she learned she
had breast cancer, underwent a lumpectomy and began chemotherapy.
Then it fell apart again with her husband's accident, a week after
Sonny Bono and Michael L. Kennedy, a son of Robert F. Kennedy, died
on the slopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't take risks,'' Mrs. Lipton said of her husband. ``He
wasn't out to jump the highest mogul. And he was wearing a
helmet.'' She still doesn't know what happened, whether he slipped
making a turn, or hit a tree, or both.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Lipton now divides her time between Pittsfield, where her
husband lives, and a midtown Manhattan apartment that she shares
with two women. She visits her husband regularly, and sometimes
talks with him on the phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can speak,'' she said. ``He's sometimes quite appropriate.
Yes, he knows who I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Lipton then smiled. ``And he knows I'm going to be the
president.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
