r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRIMROSE17-COX     07-16 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIMROSE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Early learning: Cradle to classroom touted
 &HT;    By Chris Reinolds
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Worried that her son wouldn't be academically
competitive, Lisa Ramsay moved her 3-year-old from a traditional
day care center to a preschool where academics win out over
unstructured playtime.
</P>
<P>
   Ramsay, a Sugar Hill resident, enrolled her son in a Primrose
school, which promotes the still-controversial educational
philosophy that structured learning begins at birth. Infants listen
to classical music, are taught simple concepts and learn to follow
directions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went to Primrose in 1995,'' said Ramsay, a financial
portfolio manager. ``They had the discipline to get the kids ready
for life.''
</P>
<P>
   Both of Ramsay's sons, Stephen, now 7, and Matthew, 2, attend
Primrose's recently accredited school outside Atlanta. Ramsay said
accreditation provided a stamp of approval that reassured her that
her children are getting the best.
</P>
<P>
   Primrose accepts children from 6 weeks old to 5 years with
after-school programs for older children. The academics-from-birth
approach led Primrose schools to seek and gain accreditation by the
Southern Association of Colleges and Schools.
</P>
<P>
   Primrose CEO Jo Kirchner said it took several years to convince
the SACS and other regional accreditation groups that preschools
should be academically accredited. The SACS, best known for its
accreditation of elementary and high schools and colleges,
previously reviewed educational programs only down to 4-year-old
pre-kindergarten.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (SACS) were not interested in the preschool area,''
Kirchner said. ``We stayed in touch and encouraged them to look at
early childhood. There's so much emphasis put on the first five
years of a child's life.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Steve Baker, SACS executive director of the commission on
elementary and middle schools, said Primrose is the first
for-profit franchise group the organization has evaluated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started this because there was interest in the public for
these types of institutions,'' Baker said. Other SACS-accredited
companies include Sylvan Learning Centers, which offer
supplementary education for schoolchildren.
</P>
<P>
   The SACS based its approval of Primrose on its evaluation of the
company's business plan, financial status, method of educating
students and quality control.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have development programs. It's not just a matter of
baby-sitting,'' Baker said. After he reviewed two of the accredited
schools, Baker said: ``Both were places I would put my
grandchildren.''
</P>
<P>
   Most early childhood organizations are accredited by the
National Association for the Education of Young Children. Kirchner
said Primrose officials agree with many NAEYC philosophies, but
they did not seek the group's accreditation because it emphasizes
child-initiated learning. ``We believe in a blend of
teacher-initiated and child-initiated,'' Kirchner said.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Glowacki, NAEYC director of accreditation programs,
said with parents, there seems to be two camps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear parents say, `I don't want baby-sitting. I want them to
be learning something,''' she said. ``But I also talk to parents
who say, `I don't want my child to be stressed out. I don't want
academic stuff crammed down their throat.' In reality what parents
want is a combination of care and education.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Henry, research director for the Council on School
Performance at Georgia State University, said he did not know SACS
accredited preschools but that studies have shown that programs
like those at Primrose are among the least effective.
</P>
<P>
   Henry acknowledged that Primrose's approach is popular with
parents concerned that their preschool children aren't being
academically prepared, but said it's better to let children
progress at their own pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should follow their natural curiosity, so that you're
building on the natural assets of children,'' Henry said.
</P>
<P>
   He said parents looking for a child care center should ask how
the day is organized and what activities are planned. Also, find
out how much of the day is set aside to allow the child to choose
what he or she wants to do, Henry said.
</P>
<P>
   Baker said the trend in child care programs is toward learning
rather than baby-sitting. He said SACS accreditation allows
children to be prepared for the standards of the schools they will
be entering. ``The accreditation allows a seamless system, if you
will, of trying to assure the public that the quality and a lot of
the safeguards are in place in schools,'' Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   Six of 65 Primrose schools nationwide are now SACS-accredited.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
