<SLUG> BC-LATHAM-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The frustrating differences between government and business
 &HT;    By Phil Latham
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARSHALL, Texas _ I wouldn't know a trihalomethene if I drank
one which, of course, is exactly the problem. I am drinking them
and so is almost everyone else who gets water from a surface water
source, that is, a river or a lake.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Marshall, we get the opportunity to drink them at levels
higher than the Environmental Protection Agency says we ought to
be. Mind you it is only ever so slightly higher than the standard,
but higher it is, make no doubt about it.
</P>
<P>
   The standard itself seems unbelievably small. The law allows
trihalomethene _ let's call it THM before I misspell it _ at levels
no more than six parts per billion.
</P>
<P>
   To show you how small that is, there are roughly 5 billion
people on earth. If we named 35 of them THM for a day, there would
about be as many people named THM in the entire world population as
there is the actual chemical in the Marshall water supply.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I think we would all agree that there are some things we
don't want any parts per billion of in the water. Furthermore, the
fact that the standard is so stringent for THM is a clue that it is
nasty stuff.
</P>
<P>
   But, actually, this is not a column about THM or environmental
standards at all. It is about the most important way that
government differs from business and why I think people get so
infuriated with government. Here's an clue: It has nothing to do
with how much money government spends or how much tax it levies.
</P>
<P>
   Here is what is happening with the latest THM scare _ something
very similar happened about two years ago. The TNRCC sends a letter
to Marshall water customers saying the THM level in Marshall water
is too high. The newspaper calls the city and is told _ essentially
_ that the letter is balderdash. The water is safe for everyone to
drink and there is nothing to worry about. The newspaper then calls
the TNRCC _ the people who sent the letter, remember? _ and is
essentially told the same thing: The water is safe.
</P>
<P>
   So why send out the letter? Is anybody running this show, or is
it on automatic pilot? You all know the answer: It is on automatic
pilot.
</P>
<P>
   If THMs are bad _ and I suspect that they are _ then the
standard ought to be the rule and the person (whom we all pay) to
see that the standard is met should be jumping through every
possible hoop to see it is done.
</P>
<P>
   This is where government is different than business. Permit me
to illustrate.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has ever bought a cheap wrench knows that standards
count. In wrenches, for instance, it is important to know that the
size marked is that size that you have. How much tolerance do you
suppose, say, Craftsman has for its wrenches? I don't know, but I'm
sure it is tiny.
</P>
<P>
   This is just a guess, but I'd say when a Craftsman wrench
doesn't meet the standard, it isn't even offered to the customer.
Furthermore, if a bunch of wrenches at a plant don't meet the
standard, somebody takes radical action.
</P>
<P>
   No representative from Craftsman will ever tell a newspaper not
to worry about a standard. They will promise that customers get
great wrenches and somebody behind the scenes will do whatever is
necessary to see that they meet that promise.
</P>
<P>
   To make an exact comparison, if the Coca-Cola company were found
to have an excessive amount of THMs in one of their products, the
company would go into overdrive to see that the problem was fixed.
A company spokesman might try to put a positive spin on the
problem, but no one would rest at Coca-Cola until the mission had
been accomplished. I suspect that Coca-Cola has standards that far
exceed what any outside source might require. That is good
business.
</P>
<P>
   And Coca-Cola would never assume that people would simply keep
using a product that did not meet the standard. To do so would be
fatal to their business.
</P>
<P>
   But government _ all kinds of governments and at all levels
everywhere _ just shrug their collective shoulders and give us a
goofy grin. Why, shucks, they're doing the best that they can.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, we know better than that. Most of us work at
businesses where we have to do more with less every day. Excuses
are why people get so frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   Please don't whine about unfunded government mandates. Paying
customers set the highest unfunded mandates of all and businesses
learn to deal with it.
</P>
<P>
   Don't pat our heads and tell us not to worry ourselves about
those mean old THMs, tell us what you are doing to fix the problem.
Tell us that you intend to meet the standard now and in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Latham is editor and publisher of the Marshall (Texas) News
Messenger. His email address is platham(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
