<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Child and grandparent a prefect match for a fishing expedition
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ This was a Sunday out of the past. Perhaps
swayed by the latest scientific revelation that a daily glass of
iced tea makes you practically immune to heart attacks, my wife
decided to temporarily ignore her high position with the fat
police. She actually fried chicken in grease and fixed thick gravy
to pour over the rice.
</P>
<P>
   I was ready to stretch out under the oak tree in the back yard
when our granddaughter announced she and some of her friends
planned to go fishing. We were appalled when her irresponsible
parents told her to go ahead, casually reminding her to be home in
time for youth fellowship at the church.
</P>
<P>
   Our granddaughter is only 14 years old, for goodness' sakes! She
doesn't know about snakes and wasps and quicksand; or how fish
hooks can put out an eye, or get caught in skin and require
emergency surgery; or how lightning strikes around water; or how
easy it is to fall in and drown.
</P>
<P>
   It's frightening the way today's parents just turn kids loose in
the world without a smidgen of supervision. It's so bad in our case
we've considered alerting the authorities responsible for
investigating child neglect.
</P>
<P>
   Ignoring accusations about being overly protective and a
worrywart, and causing embarrassment to a young lady practically
ready for college, I changed into my fishing clothes and appointed
myself chaperon.
</P>
<P>
   Fishing expeditions that include teen-age girls aren't as simple
as they sound. We had to get creaky rods and reels operating, check
out the tackle box, stop by the store for red wigglers and soft
drinks, and wait around while Sunday dresses were swapped for more
appropriate attire. I was surprised when Stephanie and Mary Ann and
Kelli, who only hours earlier had looked so prim and proper in the
choir loft, dug into the box of red wigglers and began sticking
them on hooks like veteran anglers.
</P>
<P>
   Our expedition grew to include John, Cole and Danny, three
cousins, and David, a newcomer to the community who, although only
a fifth-grader, obviously did some serious fishing where he lived
before.
</P>
<P>
   I wouldn't say our stringer was heavy when we headed home, or
that David wasn't a little disappointed with his luck, but we
weren't skunked.
</P>
<P>
   I wondered if going fishing is as big a thing with kids now as
it was with my generation. I thought about the first fish I ever
caught. It came out of the Flint River, a few hundred yards from
where Stephanie and her friends fished her uncle's pond on this
Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   My grandfather had taken me, for the first time, to his favorite
spot on the river. Our red wigglers, transported in a tomato can,
were dug from behind the barn. My pole was a cane cut from a creek
bottom. I hoped someday to own tackle like my grandfather's
shellacked sections of cane with metal fittings on the ends. His
rig could be taken apart and quickly reassembled, the only
store-bought fishing pole I'd ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   My cork was a stopper taken from an empty syrup can, not a
plastic ball from Wal-Mart. After all these decades, I can still
see it bob under water, and remember the gush of adrenaline when I
realized what was happening. I can still see that fish coming out
of the water and onto the bank as I frantically held onto my pole
while walking backward. Trembling with excitement, as I recall. Not
the best technique, as my grandfather explained, but it worked.
</P>
<P>
   My virgin catch was the size of a grown man's hand, a bream with
a bright red belly. My grandfather said we'd have a fine supper
when my grandmother fried it and fixed hush puppies. He was right.
One can visit the great restaurants of the world, but one will find
no fish to match a red-bellied bream caught on your own hook,
scaled and cleaned by your grandfather, and fried by your
grandmother on the wood stove in her kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   I was silently lamenting the fact that with times and things so
different, a fishing trip with Grandpa likely won't make much of an
impression on today's kids.
</P>
<P>
   Then Stephanie asked the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you remember the first time you took me fishing?'' she
asked. Of course I did. She was 3 years old. It was a warm Sunday
afternoon in March, and we were mostly out to enjoy the sun. She
was sitting in my lap. I had a ceremonial hook in the water.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly the line went taut and the pole bent. Together we
started to reel. Nearing the bank, a big bass jumped and, with huge
mouth gaping, shook furiously, trying to throw the hook. Stephanie
screamed, jumped out of my lap, ran for her tricycle parked on the
driveway, and began frantically pedaling for home.
</P>
<P>
   I was surprised she remembered, and that despite her inglorious
departure from the scene, she considers that old bass her first
catch, and the episode one of her strong memories of childhood.
</P>
<P>
   If I wrote a column of helpful hints for grandfathers, my
premier advice would be to never pass up a fishing trip with a
grandchild.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Minter is a former editor in chief of The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
