<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Our days as knuckle-draggers linger longer than we thought
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ At the rate that science is unraveling life's
mysteries, it shouldn't be long before humans achieve total
enlightenment.
</P>
<P>
   It has appeared that way over the past few weeks as scientific
revelations shattered the faith-based beliefs of many people.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to understand why inflexible religions condemn
scientific conclusions that demystify holy doctrines. The same goes
for individuals. No one wants to hear that deeply felt beliefs are
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study that has upset a lot of people reported that
Neanderthals aren't just for textbooks anymore. Neanderthals now
are for mating, going fishing with and electing to high public
office.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Neanderthals are us to varying degrees, which
might explain why some people act the way they do.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Erik Trinkaus, a paleoanthropologist at Washington
University in St. Louis, recently reported the discovery of the
24,600-year-old skeleton of a boy in Portugal that has the facial
features of modern humans but the unmistakable body of a brutish
Neanderthal.
</P>
<P>
   Since Neanderthals were supposedly extinct for 4,000 years by
the time the boy was born, scientists have concluded that the boy
was the product of interbreeding.
</P>
<P>
   This finding fits in with earlier DNA research that came to the
same conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   In the future, DNA tests to detect Neanderthal heritage might be
required before people apply for certain jobs.
</P>
<P>
   NFL teams would pay extra for players who come from a long line
of knuckle-draggers. On the other hand, a strong Neanderthal
lineage might be a drawback for a customer service manager.
</P>
<P>
   Congress can be viewed as Neanderthals on one side of the aisle
and Cro-Magnons on the other side. The side you pick may say a lot
about your ancestry. This subject requires additional scientific
study.
</P>
<P>
   Another recent scientific study found that humans are not the
only animals that develop cultural customs. The results of 151
years of chimpanzee research concluded that these ape relatives
invent and learn cultural behavior patterns among groups that are
separated, a characteristic once thought to be an insurmountable
dividing line between humans and all other animals.
</P>
<P>
   This shouldn't be terribly surprising since science already
showed humans and chimpanzees, who share 98 percent of the same
DNA, trace back to a common ancestor.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another recent scientific study reported that the internal
clocks of humans and other animals work just the same, which was a
blow to human-centric people who have long maintained that humans
are unique in their ability to adjust their sleep-wake cycles.
</P>
<P>
   Nope, wrong again. As Charles Darwin said years ago, the
difference between humans and animals, particularly higher animals,
is one of degree, not of kind.
</P>
<P>
   Then we have a new scientific study that found women
subconsciously change their mating strategies during their
menstrual cycles.
</P>
<P>
   Many studies have shown that women routinely choose men with
more feminine features for their long-term partners. The new
cross-cultural and cross-ethnic study found that women select more
rugged-looking men for short-term sexual relationships at the most
fertile point of their cycle.
</P>
<P>
   Although these studies are not tied together, I'm guessing that
the study that found how a woman's menstrual cycle guides her
choice in men is why we've got Neanderthals in our family tree.
</P>
<P>
   On the subconscious level, apparently it's all right to date a
Neanderthal, just don't marry one. Kinder, gentler pretty men can
raise the kids. That's probably fine with Neanderthals who are just
happy to be alive.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: rnethaway(at)wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
