r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD17-COX     07-16 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Taking on the treehouse
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ I suppose that with an animated Tarzan stirring the
imaginations of young and old alike, things like this are occurring
to a lot of folks these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am about to attempt to build a treehouse, mainly for the
kids,'' writes an electronic correspondent. ``I am an amateur, so I
need all the advice I can get. Do you have any helpful info?''
</P>
<P>
   Being a devotee of the Johnny Weismuller school of Tarzaning, no
wasp-waisted cartoon character can get my blood aboil. And I'm
certainly not a professional treehouse contractor. However, I have
built a couple in my career _ I think Weismuller was still The Man
then, too _ and I tried to dredge up what I could from the mists of
failing memory.
</P>
<P>
   The result wasn't really enough to be helpful. So I did the next
best thing _ which, presumably, my correspondent could have done _
and went to the World Wide Web and its many search engines. There
are thousands of hits for treehouses, most of them having nothing
to do with building one, but some engines allow a more defined
search.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few of hits to get you going.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.uniquetreehouse.com is a commercial outfit that will build
it for you. Failing that, they will consult you on building it
yourself. Of course, they want money for this.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  www.btinternet.com/''fulton/treehouse.htm appears to be
British in origin, and is a fairly broad discussion of how to build
your own treehouse.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  pages.prodigy.net/magiix/treehouse/index.html is the snazziest
personal Web page I've seen. This fellow has cooked up animated
plans and diagrams for the treehouse he made for his son.
</P>
<P>
   Let this be a lesson, folks. If you are hooked into the
Internet, you have available information on virtually any subject
under the sun _ and any subject that avoids the light, too, for
that matter. You have to exercise judgment _ all the information on
the Web is not necessarily good information. You have to exercise
patience _ chances are that your searches will turn up tons of
stuff that's irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, you can go to a place like www.amazon.com and
find out what books are available on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not all books are going to be worth your time,
either. Back in the dark days, virtually all the available books on
woodworking were either useless and full of bad information, or
dull, depressing vocational school texts. There are, probably,
hundreds of very useful books on woodworking available now, but
still the awful ones keep getting published.
</P>
<P>
   One came to my desk the other day. It's ``Great 2X4 Accessories
for Your Home,'' published by Lark Books. The title is somewhat
misleading _ the projects use all kinds of dimensioned pine lumber.
``Great,'' of course, is in the eye of the beholder. I find most of
the projects greatly disgusting.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, however, are their construction methods. For instance, in
building a coffee table, we are told to buy a ready-laminated pine
table top and trim it to size. Then we cut four pieces to make a
frame around this top and glue everything together, cross-grain
construction, end-grain gluing, all that.
</P>
<P>
   Then as a finale, we ``center the tabletop over the base. Apply
glue to the meeting surfaces, and nail through the Sides (G and H)
into the Base Sides (D and E) using 1 1/2-inch nails spaced every 5
inches.''
</P>
<P>
   And then, it might continue, we can sit back and watch the
Center Top (F) come apart when it tries to expand in wet weather.
In the meantime, we can contemplate all those handsome nailheads.
This is the sort of thing that drives people out of woodworking.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
