<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 11:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2556 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-CANDIDATES17     07-16 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-CANDIDATES17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `MoveOn' voters put money where grouch is
 &HT;    By Dan Moffett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Each morning, political neophyte Jean
Elliott Brown turns on her computer to see how much her
congressional campaign has raised overnight.
</P>
<P>
   She's got mail. She's got money.
</P>
<P>
   There's $25 from Katherine in Seattle. ``I'm still angry and I'm
putting my money where my hostility lies,'' she writes.
</P>
<P>
   Tom in Albuquerque, N.M., sends $20. ``I dislike the
Republicans' position on guns,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Dick in San Antonio gives $50. ``I generally don't trust
politicians,'' he writes, ``but good luck.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past six weeks, 1,700 people from 50 states have donated
an average of $37 to raise $52,000 for Brown's bid to unseat
incumbent Republican Mark Foley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only three of the contributors are people I know,'' she said.
``I hope to raise $1 million by next year's election.''
</P>
<P>
   How does somebody in Nebraska come to write a check for an
unknown, untried candidate from Palm Beach Gardens?
</P>
<P>
   The Internet makes it possible, of course. And the common
contempt for lawmakers who voted for the impeachment of President
Clinton makes it necessary, donors say.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, 48, is harvesting the proceeds of dissent created by what
touts itself as the nation's first grass-roots cyberspace political
movement. Born last fall during the height of the impeachment wars,
MoveOn.org is the creation of two Silicon Valley computer software
entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Blades and Wes Boyd spent $89.50 to build a Web site where
Clinton defenders could muster on line. About 500,000 did, and many
pledged contributions ranging from $25 to $2,500 to a ``We Will
Remember'' campaign to defeat impeachment supporters in the 2000
election.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Blades and Boyd sent a mass e-mailing to those who
pledged, telling them it was time to put up their money. Thousands
have.
</P>
<P>
   ``We raised more than $250,000 the first five days,'' Blades
said, ``and 92 percent of the contributions were under $50.''
</P>
<P>
   MoveOn has targeted five races, and Internet visitors to the Web
site can click their mouse to select the candidate they wish to
back and the amount they wish to send. Donations by credit card or
checks are accepted, and MoveOn distributes the money weekly to its
five candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Foley (R-West Palm Beach), others targeted for
cyber-ambush are Rep. James Rogan (R-Calif)., Rep. Rick Hill
(R-Mont.), and Sen. John Ashcroft (R-Mo.). MoveOn also is
supporting Rep. Rush Holt (D-N.J.), against an undetermined
Republican opponent.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Foley's office said the congressman was among
only a handful of Republicans who voted to exonerate Clinton on two
of the four articles of impeachment. Kirk Fordham, Foley's chief of
staff, questioned MoveOn's motivations and Brown's, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most Floridians will find it somewhat puzzling that (Brown)
would launch her campaign bragging about how much money she
collected out of state from donors who can't even vote in
Florida,'' Fordham said. ``Most people in our district have moved
on from impeachment and are interested in other issues.''
</P>
<P>
   What is unquestioned is that money played a significant role the
last time Foley was challenged for his 16th District seat. In 1996,
Democrat Jim Stuber wound up $26,000 in debt after raising $77,000;
Foley took in $710,000 and cruised to victory with 60 percent of
the vote.
</P>
<P>
   A Foley spokesman said the congressman will enter next year's
race with ``at least $1 million'' in his coffers _ ``most all of it
donated by Floridians.''
</P>
<P>
   Blades and Boyd plan to put the names of more candidates on
their Web site for the MoveOn faithful to support. They say the
vulnerability of the incumbent and the strength of the opponent
will dictate which races they enter. Brown's relationship with
MoveOn goes back to October when she signed up with the group and
distributed petitions condemning independent counsel Kenneth
Starr's investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``MoveOn is showing its viability as an alternative to the
$1,000-a-plate fund-raisers,'' Blades said. ``This is a whole new
way for ordinary people to become involved in the political
process.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who owns a public relations company, is attending a
Democratic leadership conference in Baltimore this week.
</P>
<P>
   While she was out of town Wednesday, another $311 was e-mailed
in from seven Internet contributors.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are so eager to participate it's unbelievable,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
