<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 11:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2584 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-DRIVEIN-$ADV17     07-16 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-DRIVEIN-$ADV17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SULTRY SUMMER NIGHTS, A GOOD FLICK _ AND VODKA?
 &HT;    934. Moving on (i) International wires.
 &HT;    w/photos.
 &HT;    By Charles W. Holmes
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW It is not a Chevy sedan, but a boxy, Soviet-designed
Lada, that has pulled into the choice spot in front of the
40-foot-wide outdoor movie screen.
</P>
<P>
   The two couples inside, who've come to Russia's first drive-in
movie to watch the Hollywood disaster flick, ``Deep Impact,'' are
not munching popcorn and sipping sodas, but meat pies and shots of
vodka.
</P>
<P>
   Completing the cultural contrast, they intend to remain upright
in their seats and actually view the film. Really, they insist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard about what Americans do at the drive-in. We were
just curious about this place and came just to watch the movie.
Nothing else,'' said Mikhail Anisymkin, 28, giving a furtive glance
and a smile to his girlfriend, Oxana Dubavitskaya.
</P>
<P>
   More than six decades after its rise and eventual decline in the
United States, the drive-in movie has made it to Russia, opening
three weeks ago on the outskirts of a fashionable Moscow
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Kinodrome,'' (''kino'' means film in Russian) is a
peculiar blend of quintessential Americana and ``Russky
eksperimyent.''
</P>
<P>
   Curious Russians at $16 a carload for movie and snacks pricey in
the depressed Russian economy have been cruising into the Kinodrome
to sample Moscow's newest attraction. And there are more cars
outside the fence than inside, filled with interested onlookers
who've parked alongside the road to get a free peak at the movies.
</P>
<P>
   But if the drive-in catches on in Russia, it will be against
great odds.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, Moscow has a latitude problem. The city's location
on the globe means the summer sun does not set until 11 p.m. The
first showing begins soon after, and the second feature begins at 2
a.m. and ends about 4, just as the sun begins to rise.
</P>
<P>
   Geography also leads to the second difficulty for the owners
winter. It arrives early and hard, lasts for months and will make
it difficult to attract customers who are willing to bundle up
inside an icy car.
</P>
<P>
   But Alexander Volkov, one of the founding partners, remains
undeterred. To hear Volkov tell it, the drive-in isn't merely a
place, but a state of mind and a way of life or should be _in
post-Communist Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We give the feeling of freedom and open space. Like Americans,
more and more Russians feel more comfortable in their cars. People
like it because it is new. It's a very hot summer, and there's a
nice breeze and a good movie here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The amorous aspect of the American drive-in is not lost on
Volkov, either. The second showing, which begins at 2 a.m. and
attracts a slightly older crowd, is usually a romantic film, if not
erotic. Given the late show times, the drive-in seeks to attract
young adults, not the teen-aged American-Graffiti set associated
with America's drive-in culture.
</P>
<P>
   Most customers are 19 to 27 years of age (driving age in Russia
is 18), and more women than men come to the theater, which is in
the parking lot of a derelict bicycling track built for the 1980
Summer Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Volkov and his partners have added other touches of America.
In-line skating waiters help direct the cars to their spots before
the screening and then take orders for beers, vodka and cabbage
pie.
</P>
<P>
   At the outdoor cafe behind the projection booth, the popcorn
machine was an afterthought. The small meat and vegetable pies,
called pirozhki in Russian, are more popular than popcorn.
</P>
<P>
   In America, a New Jersey businessman is credited with inventing
the drive-in in the 1930s, when he mounted a projector to the roof
of his car and discovered that neighbors would pay to see a movie
beamed onto his garage door.
</P>
<P>
   As Hollywood entered its heyday and the automobile industry
boomed, about 5,000 drive-ins sprouted throughout the United States
in the '40s and '50s. But they have fallen on hard times since,
their numbers now down to fewer than 500 as America turned its
attention to TV and the more comfortable, shopping-mall cinema
multiplexes.
</P>
<P>
   Motion pictures as art and entertainment have always been
immensely popular in Russia. The demise of communist rule brought
more American and Western movies to Moscow. And though strained by
the poor economy, Russia still has its own active film industry.
</P>
<P>
   When the Soviet Union collapsed in 1991, restrictions on
personal freedoms evaporated and car ownership has increased
10-fold in Moscow to about 2.5 million cars. That sounds like an
encouraging statistic for the Kinodrome entrepreneurs, except that
seven out of every 10 Muscovites are still without cars.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing the limitations of the drive-in, Volkov and his
partners plan to open a discotheque, a restaurant and outdoor
skating rink on the property to diversify their offerings and
create a sort of outdoor playground for the twenty- and
thirtysomething crowd.
</P>
<P>
   That will be fine with Serafin Semyachkin, 23, who came with two
other friends not so much to see astronauts battle an Earth-bound
comet in ``Deep Impact,'' as to savor a warm midsummer night.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, it's where we can drink beer and vodka and enjoy
ourselves, sort of a summer substitute for a bar,'' said
Semyachkin. ``That's not more important than the movie. But one
doesn't hurt the other, does it?''
</P>
<P>
   He and his friends had only one gripe about their first drive-in
experience. As they drained their beer bottles, one asked: ``In
America, are the screens mounted that high? It kind of hurts your
neck to have to look up like that.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
