<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 12:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2630 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-EYES-1-HN     07-16 1292
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-EYES-1-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KUBRICK'S FINALE MARRED BY AMERICAN SENSIBILITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Stanley Kubrick died on March 8, he left behind 13 films of
high art and obsessive craft. ``2001: A Space Odyssey,''
``Lolita,'' ``Dr. Strangelove,'' ``A Clockwork Orange'' the list
goes on and on, just as the director went on and on, crossing
genres and subverting expectations with each new work.
</P>
<P>
   Elegant, menacing and often cold as a scalpel, Kubrick's best
films dissect emotions without engaging them: There's something
both clinical and dreamlike about them, like an autopsy filmed
through the gauze of LSD.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' Kubrick's extraordinary,
flawed last movie and a fitting coda to a career built on astral
visions. Based on ``Traumnovelle'' (``Dream Novel''), by Austrian
writer Arthur Schnitzler, the film stars real-life spouses Tom
Cruise and Nicole Kidman as a young Manhattan couple who become
obsessed with infidelity. More accurately, they become obsessed
with the idea of infidelity and with the substance of temptation,
which hounds them throughout the movie in fantasy and in flesh. It
is the great, unseen protagonist in a film with two huge stars.
</P>
<P>
   Set mostly at night in the week before Christmas, Kubrick's film
leads its characters on a bizarre nocturnal ramble not unlike Kyle
MacLachlan's netherworld descent in ``Blue Velvet.'' The film opens
as Dr. William (Tom Cruise) and Alice (Kidman) Harford are rushing
out the door to a ritzy holiday party at the home of one of Bill's
patients, Victor (Sidney Pollack). Shortly after arriving, they
peel off to flirt with other people: Alice with a slick Hungarian
ladies' man, Bill sandwiched between models. But Alice resists the
urge to cheat, and Bill is pulled away to tend to a prostitute who
has inconveniently OD'd in Victor's bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   The next evening, egged on by a fat joint, Alice confronts Bill
about the models _ did he boff them? No, he says. Did he want to
boff them? No, he says.
</P>
<P>
   The conversation then morphs into an addled discourse on
temptation and fidelity, wherein Bill declaims that men are
obsessed with sex while women, occupied with the finer matters of
hearth and home, are not.
</P>
<P>
   ``If ... you ... men ... only ... knew,'' whispers his wife, who
confesses to an idee fixe of her own. It seems Alice almost did it
with a naval officer in Cape Cod.
</P>
<P>
   This single confession not of an action, but a fantasy seizes
Bill's imagination and propels him into the night. His ramble takes
him from temptress to temptress (among them a slack Lolita, played
by Leelee Sobieski) on a path illuminated at every turn by surreal
curtains of Christmas lights; everything throbs with the depraved
glow of a carnival. The climax of his wandering (and the film) is a
minutely choreographed, pseudo-Satanic orgy sequence in which
Saturnalian partiers copulate vigorously and gymnastically under
the gaze of austere hooded figures.
</P>
<P>
   This is the scene that's caused all the buzzing, and justly so.
It's graphic. Less so, somewhat, for the cloaking digital effects
that transformed the film from an NC-17 into an R, but still: This
isn't Shirley Temple on the Good Ship Lollipop. Yet Kubrick clearly
meant the scene not as titillation but as metaphorical counterpart
to Alice's own carnal rove, which she experiences in dreams and
describes to her husband in full detail. Alice's dreams are never
portrayed on screen, but you wish they were; they might have given
``Eyes Wide Shut'' an added sense of balance. They might also have
given Nicole Kidman more to do than act drunk, or drugged, or
half-asleep on the lip of a nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   Cruise is convincing in a complex and elusive role, though it's
hard to shake the suspicion that he's done better work in
less-ambitious movies. For all the shuddering epiphanies in ``Eyes
Wide Shut,'' ``Jerry Maguire'' was, in many ways, a more genuinely
moving picture. And while it's fascinating to watch Cruise and
Kidman in a mock-up of their own marriage, in the end it's not
quite enough; their hungry foreplay (familiar to anyone who saw the
trailer) is beautiful and remote, lacking in the messy realities of
love.
</P>
<P>
   There's an aimlessness to Kubrick's film, a sense that he wasn't
entirely sure where his characters were headed or where his
audience might follow. The orgiastic centerpiece is never explained
to anyone's satisfaction, Bill's or ours, and the film's final
scene seems startlingly abrupt. Yet where ``Eyes Wide Shut''
succeeds, it succeeds profoundly: as a meditation on sex and
jealousy, as a dreamscape of desire, as a surprisingly moral look
at the fight to stay faithful to one's spouse. For all its graphic
bump-and-grind, the film is more about the lure to sin than the sin
itself.
</P>
<P>
   And it is a ramble, after all. It isn't in a rush it's 155
minutes long and maturely paced, all pauses and glances and fulgent
moments of insight. Like Kubrick's other films, ``Eyes Wide Shut''
uses music as effectively as light, emphasizing the film's oom-pah
dreaminess (and Viennese source material) with a teetering waltz
from Dmitri Shostakovich's ``Jazz Suite.'' He also includes a stark
piano excerpt from Gyorgy Ligeti, who popped up on the soundtracks
for ``2001'' and ``The Shining.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a word about ratings. And orgies.
</P>
<P>
   Before Kubrick died, he decided to skirt the thorny matter of
on-screen intercourse by agreeing to blur portions of the party
scene and release the film stateside with an R. The original would
be released untouched overseas. A press screening earlier this week
featured the unexpurgated European version, followed by a brief
clip of the computer-manipulated bacchanal as it will appear on
American screens.
</P>
<P>
   To put it bluntly, it looks like junk. Rather than rub out or
fuzzy-focus the naughtiest couplings, computer wizards in Warner
Brothers' employ have whipped up a bunch of sexy avatars to stand
in front of them _ men in black cloaks and nude women who, whoops!,
just happen to block our view. The clip wasn't quite finished at
the screening and might look better now, but even so, it's a bad
idea. Besides being so ridiculously fake that a theater full of
critics burst into guffaws, the computer-generated figures affront
the care Kubrick took with lighting and the minute visual
adjustments he made to each scene.
</P>
<P>
   Digital humanoids do not reflect light. They do not look real.
And they do not belong in Kubrick's movie, glue-sticked onto a sex
scene just to appease the ratings board. Anything, even big red
X's, would have been preferable to this weak trickery. Better yet,
Warner Brothers might have bitten the bullet and released ``Eyes
Wide Shut'' with (gasp) an NC-17 rating not, after all, such a wild
idea for a film with a central orgy. Why was an R so necessary? To
dupe the unsuspecting masses into watching highbrow erotica? To
separate Aunt Fanny from her $8.25?
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, anyone who cares about Kubrick's legacy would pay
to see ``Eyes Wide Shut'' regardless of an NC-17 rating; and anyone
who's offended by nudity and explicit sex will still find plenty of
cause for alarm, bowdlerized stand-ins notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   R rating or no R rating, Kubrick's final film offers a
disturbing ferry ride into an ink-black sexual underworld. ``No
dream is ever just a dream,'' says Cruise's alter ego,
half-hopeful, half-shattered, in the movie's sudden close. There's
no better epitaph to Kubrick's career.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Amy Biancolli is the film critic for the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. Her electronic mail address is
abiancolli(at)timesunion.com, or call 518-454-5738.)
</P>
</TEXT>
