<SLUG> BC-TEST-NYT </SLUG>
 
 TEST OF TRANSMISSION FOR MENLO PARK
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is a test of The New York Times News Service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-99 1319EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990716.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2658 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-EYES-2-HN     07-16 1375
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-EYES-2-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOMESTIC TURBULENCE CLOUDS `EYES WIDE SHUT' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``If you men only knew,'' says a stoned Alice Harford (Nicole
Kidman) after her physician husband, Bill (Tom Cruise), tells her
that he doesn't think women act on sexual impulse, that they can't
give into adulterous depravity.
</P>
<P>
   Alice then shrinks down to the bedroom floor of her Central Park
West apartment and spins for Bill the erotic Wonderland of
infidelity she fantasized about but never committed. She's trying
to make him jealous, but she only sets her hubby up for his own
trip through the looking glass that is ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' Stanley
Kubrick's final film and his last foray into the arctic circle of
the American male subconscious.
</P>
<P>
   More like an unfinished work than any kind of obvious or
immediate masterpiece, ``Eyes Wide Shut'' is a long, strange,
uncertain, and bizarre Steadi-cambulating odyssey in conjugal
paranoia, with Gyogy Ligeti's horror-film piano drip providing the
humor. It's seemingly preoccupied with Kubrick's ``The Shining''
and works more as an object of pop curiosity than as a work of
popular entertainment. (Read: It's not the onanistic Hollywood
porno you've been dying for.)
</P>
<P>
   It took an over-documented 15 months to shoot, and a hunk of the
film's intrigue has to do with the fact that the only evidence of
those days is the 155 minutes it takes for the film to unspool.
</P>
<P>
   Kubrick's never been a specialist in brevity, but where before
his time warps were hung over with a cavernous, subversive quality,
``Eyes'' feels hollowed out, narrow and wandering in an
incomplete-experiment fashion. But it's hypnotic, anyway _
especially in Kubrick's exploitation of a splashy Hollywood
marriage to play games with ideas of faith and fidelity.
</P>
<P>
   A series of naked or sexually needy goddesses spring from
Alice's pot-laced fury like an anorexic-Botticelli sideshow and
welcome Bill into their libidos. He makes a nighttime house call on
a dead patient whose daughter (Marie Richardson, replacing Jennifer
Jason Leigh) breaks down before her father's deathbed and tells
Bill she's in love with him. ``You barely know me,'' he says, but
it doesn't matter, the film offers her as an emblem of the
repetitive-stress disorder of Bill's mind.
</P>
<P>
   Early, Kubrick gives us snatches of Kidman nude from the rear,
glimpses of her breasts and the dimpled small of her back. Each
woman _ and in Leelee Sobieski's case, girl _ who tries to make
herself available to Bill is a different replica of Alice, so as to
ask Bill if he still thinks women don't want to give it. ``Eyes
Wide Shut'' may be the longest, strangest man-and- wife spat ever.
</P>
<P>
   And like any love quarrel, it takes Bill the better part of 155
minutes to come around to his wife's way of thinking. But as Cruise
tells Kidman, who's at her awkward-accented, glacial and most
insinuating, that's a gross oversimplification. But it's one
complicated by Bill's obsession with Alice's never-actualized
affair with a naval officer, something Bill imagines happening as a
soft-core table-top encounter shot in silent-film blue.
</P>
<P>
   That image flickers in Bill's overheated imagination as he
spends the minutes following their argument and most of the film
wandering through mansion and hospital hallways and through the
streets of Manhattan like Kubrick's yuppie lab rat trying to find
his way to the end of this labyrinth and over the rainbow. That's
something Kubrick suggests when he has Bill wind up at a costume
shop named for Dorothy's musical wish to be in a way more exciting
place than her Depression-era farm.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas for Kubrick under these circumstances seems to be
marriage and its stagnation after nine years, and infidelity, not
divorce, is the Oz _ that fantasia you can abandon after it turns
out to be less fantastic than thought.
</P>
<P>
   Adapted by Kubrick and Frederic Raphael from German playwright
Arthur Schnitzler's 1926 novella ``Traumnovelle'' (``Dream
Story''), ``Eyes Wide Shut'' maintains a remarkable structural
faithfulness to Schnitzler's book, right down to the clan of frat
boys who bum-rush Bill on the SoHo streets. (Though, here they've
weirdly become a drunken posse of Yale meatheads who call ``fag''
to an ever-besieged Cruise.)
</P>
<P>
   But where Schnitzler's story was about the curious indiscretion
of an Austrian doctor who may be sleepwalking though the
underworlds he's moving through, Kubrick focuses the book's dreamy
vagueness into a mildly savage riff on the repression of yuppie
indulgence and the dangerousness and casual impersonality of sex.
</P>
<P>
   It's a similar distillation that David Hare made of Schnitzler's
``La Ronde,'' which became the play ``The Blue Room,'' for which
Kidman bared her butt as well as some of her best acting, also on
remote display here in a role considerably smaller than her
husband's.
</P>
<P>
   (Coincidentally, Kidman picks her fight while standing in the
threshold of their bathroom, which glows indigo behind her.)
</P>
<P>
   By the time Bill talks his lounge-piano med-school buddy Nick
(Todd Field) into giving him the password to the location of his
ultra-cryptic gigs, ``Eyes Wide Shut'' has become ghoulishly
de-eroticized and supernaturally stagy. Nick plays blindfolded at
the console of a haunted-house-y estate _ another of the film's
fits of ``Shining'' deja vu _ populated by masked men in capes and
tuxedos while topless, masked women (all of whom are built like
Kidman) engage in the nudie cotillion ritual that goes on in the
mansion's crypt-like ballroom.
</P>
<P>
   Kubrick shoots all this with the slow-drag creepiness of a Russ
Meyer episode of ``Night Gallery.'' Apparently, Bill has
infiltrated the Jay McInerney Paradise of Iniquity and only an
automaton with a plumed mask can rescue him from being found out.
</P>
<P>
   The hoopla over what he sees _ doggie-styling, live-nude-girl
fondle-sessions _ as he drifts through this soulless Saturnalia
encouraged Warner Bros. to digitally insert more nude mannequins
and men in cassocks to obstruct the copulation as if the action
were pornographic.
</P>
<P>
   But there's nothing arresting about it. Kubrick doesn't play any
of this for titillation, rather to emphasize how oddly boring it
is. Old-money Manhattanites and fresh-scrubbed yuppies getting off
on watching their ilk screw anonymous has jokey implications, but
it smacks more of Kubrick's exploitative tendencies.
</P>
<P>
   Bill gets caught and is forced to remove his mask in front of
all the fornicators, but when the masked automaton offers herself
as a sacrifice for him to escape unharmed, the moment is seized
with the inconsequence and staginess of a really amateur
performance of some Greek tragedy. It's as if Kubrick were aiming
for some inversion of ``The Shining'' in which Bill really wants to
be a part of this exclusive, decadently boring world, but they
don't want him. There is no metaphysical component here and any
indulgences in some sort of wild side are kept under Kubrick's
clinical thumb.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, while bit players such as the divine Alan Cumming as
a concierge who falls madly in love with Cruise and the rhapsodic
Rade Serbedzija as the Over the Rainbow owner walk off with scenes,
Cruise and Kidman are victimized by Kubrick's refusal to let them
unwind. They both speak deliberately with torpid points of ellipsis
beached between each world.
</P>
<P>
   Try Kidman's line this way: ``If ... you ... men ... only ...
knew ,'' then multiply that by every time she and Cruise deliver a
line. Though, it's edifying that they could take Kubrick's
direction, which even turns Chris Isaak's ``Baby Did a Bad, Bad
Thing'' into commentary.
</P>
<P>
   But that, too, feels like a forced attempt to do something cool
with a couple in whom he seems to have trouble finding inspiration
and excitement. Cruise in particular appears daunted, restrained
and matter of fact, as if the dream of this adventure were lost on
him and maybe on Kubrick, too. The ambiguities recede and
everything is precisely what it looks like.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wesley Morris is a film critic for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic mail address
is morris(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
