   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-PROTESTS (Tehran) _ At main Friday prayers, the United
States is blamed for recent unrest. The Interior Ministry says no
more demonstrations are likely to be allowed. A debate is emerging
over who owns the legacy of the revolution: the mullahs or the
young protesters. By Elaine Sciolino.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-U.S. (Washington) _ The Israeli prime minister meets with
the secretaries of state and defense, then moves on to New York. By
Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   NY-BARAK (New York) _ The Israeli prime minister's day in New
York. By Adam Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-CHINA (Beijing) _ Talks fail to produce a settlement on
compensation by the United States for the bombing of the Chinese
embassy in Belgrade, a major issue for China in U.S.-China
relations. By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-CHINA ( Hong Kong) _ With rumors of Chinese military
action, the Hong Kong stock market has its worst one-day drop in
nine years. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-KASHMIR (Undated) _ Indian soldiers give Muslim burials to
their dead enemies on a mountaintop since Pakistan, denying the
presence of troops in the area, doesn't claim the bodies. By Barry
Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-PEACE-ASSESS (Belfast) _ News Analysis on the stalled
peace effort. While there has been a clear loss of momentum, so
much has changed in last two years that the process is not dead
yet. By warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-REMEMBER (Paris) _ Prime Minister Chirac confronts
France's WWII past at commemorative event. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   SALINAS (Mexico City) _ Swiss High Court says Swiss government's
seizure of Raul Salinas' funds was illegal, since only states have
jurisdiction in the case. By Julia Preston.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-TARIFF (Washington) _ The House is to vote and likely
pass a bill to eliminate duties on apparel and textiles from
Africa, if the countries commit to economic reform and improve
human rights. The measure, which the Senate has yet to take up, has
divided the black caucus, some of whose members fear the move will
hurt business here. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-ASSESS (Washington) _ With the defeat of the health bill,
the Democrats get a campaign issue, the Republicans get some
political cover by passing their own health measure and the
American people will probably get nothing because President Clinton
will veto the measure. This is the same political calculus that has
governed the congressional session so far. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-HEALTH (Washington) _ Explaining how the Senate bill
will change the landscape for people in health maintenance
organizations. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-TAX (Washington) _ The Senate releases its tax bill,
the Democrats reveal their plans and the White House talks about
the Republican plan. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   WEST-VRGINIA-AGED (Dunbar, W.Va.) _ West Virginia has surpassed
Florida as the state with the oldest per capita residents in the
union, and no one knows this better than Ken Hechler, the
84-year-old elected secretary of state who has decided he can be
the wave of the future and is running for his old House seat that
he retired from in the '70s. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   STADIUMS-REACT (Seattle) _ As the the most expensive single-use
stadium opens here amid protest by taxpayers, more questions are
being raised about using public money to help sports team owners.
By Timothy Egan.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   HELL-INFERNO (Undated) _ An editorial in a Rome-based Jesuit
magazine, supervised ``in the Vatican at the highest levels of
doctrinal competence, according to Corriere della Sera, says Hell
isn't an Inferno after all. A look at changing Catholic thinking on
what Hell is, and isn't. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON (Undated) _ President Clinton travels to Iowa for
education event and fundraiser for Sen. Tom Harkin. By Melissa
Henneberger.
</P>
<P>
   PENMEN-CONVENTION (Rochester, N.Y.) _ In an age where e-mail and
faxes are the preferred form of communication and where home
printers cost $150, the future seems a bit grim for the
International Association of Master Penmen, Engrossers and Teachers
of Handwriting. By Paul Zielbauer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BIZDAY &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CHEERLEADER-INDUSTRY (Oxford, Miss.) _ More than 400,000
cheerleaders from all over the country are attending camps on
college campuses this summer to learn new moves, perfect old ones
and check out the competition. These camps _ which usually last
three or four days and cost $150 to $200 per person _ combine with
regional and national cheerleading competitions and uniform sales
to make up what insiders call ``the spirit industry.'' And a
thriving industry it is, with over a million active participants,
tens of millions in revenue and nationwide television coverage. By
Emily Yellin.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   CATERPILLAR-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Caterpillar Inc. unexpectedly
warns that earnings will fall more than forecast this year as it
reports a sharper-than-expected decline in second-quarter earnings.
Profit this year will be 20 percent to 25 percent below last year's
earnings, more than the 15-percent decline the company forecast in
March.
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINE-PILOTS (Undated) _ American Airlines and its pilots
union have settled the disagreement that led the pilots to stage a
sickout earlier this year that inconvenienced hundreds of thousands
of passengers and led to a huge fine against the union. By Laurence
Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-ECON (Sao Paulo) _ Twenty-five of Brazil's 27 state
governors meet to step up pressure on the central government to
ease the states' financial problems by renegotiating their federal
debts.
</P>
<P>
   FORD-CANADA (Toronto) _ Ford Motor dealers in Canada are suing
the auto maker, accusing it of taking their Lincoln Mercury
franchises and selling them to other dealers. By Timothy Pritchard.
</P>
