u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-DAVIS-TV-COLUMN-B     07-16 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVIS-TV-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOURNAMENT HAS FOUND AN IDENTITY WITH ESPN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nineteen years ago, upstart network ESPN televised what was then
the longest live sports telecast in TV history _ a 9-hour 17-minute
Davis Cup quarterfinal match between the US and Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of coverage _ 6 hours and 32 minutes _ was devoted to
a slugfest between John McEnroe and Mats Wilander. McEnroe won,
9-7, 6-2, 15-17, 3-6, 8-6.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem was less than a half-million viewers saw
arguably one of the most thrilling matches ever played.
</P>
<P>
   Cliff Drysdale, a former South African Davis Cup player, wants
to change all that. Drysdale is in Boston as ESPN's play-by-play
commentator for the centennial Davis Cup. He called the
McEnroe-Wilander match for ESPN and said that the Davis Cup ``is
the best thing tennis has going for it.''
</P>
<P>
   This weekend's action at the Longwood Cricket Club in Brookline
features the quarterfinal match between the US and Australia, the
two countries with the most Davis Cup championships.
</P>
<P>
   The first Davis Cup match was at Longwood in 1900, when Dwight
Filley Davis, a Harvard student, challenged the world to compete in
an international tennis tournament. Only Great Britain answered the
call.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all the tennis matches that I have seen over the years,
Davis Cup play has been the most memorable, the most exciting,''
Drysdale said.
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale has been around the Davis Cup since the early 60s when
he played for South Africa. He said the Davis Cup format should be
changed to build a larger following. Instead of playing the matches
over the course of a year, Drysdale said the tournament should be
completed within a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a workable solution,'' he said. ``Hopefully it'll
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The relationship between ESPN and the Davis Cup has been
mutually beneficial. Over the years, ESPN's coverage has helped
rekindle interest in the Davis Cup, especially when John McEnroe
and Jimmy Connors, two of America's most impetuous players,
competed.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, for instance, McEnroe played Boris Becker in another
memorable shootout. ESPN was scheduled to carry the US Women's Open
golf tournament, but rain suspended play. ESPN switched to the
Davis Cup, and stayed for six hours until the final point at 11:20
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The match was only seen in 874,000 homes, but for those who
watched, it was a patriotic scene. McEnroe was an underdog,
competing against the awesome young Becker. ``ESPN has treated the
Cup very royally,'' Drysdale said.
</P>
<P>
   The Davis Cup is one of the few international sporting events
that American teams have competed in on a regular basis. ``America
is so parochial when it comes to sports,'' Drysdale said.
``Football, baseball, basketball, they are all pretty much played
here with limited international involvement.''
</P>
<P>
   With Pete Sampras playing only doubles, Drysdale said the US has
a 50-50 chance of beating the Australians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The US has their best player sitting on the bench,'' Drysdale
said. ``I understand all of the reasons, but I'm disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale stressed the importance of the first singles match
between American Todd Martin and 18-year-old Lleyton Hewitt.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he can win that first match, I like the US's chances,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale will call the match along with Patrick McEnroe, Fred
Stolle, and courtside reporter Mal Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The first televised match is (July 16) at 2 p.m. The second
singles match is on ESPN2 at 4 p.m. ESPN will also air the doubles
match Saturday at 5 p.m. and a singles match on Sunday at 3 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Howard Manly writes about the sports media for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
