<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2666 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-DAVIS-100YEARS-3T     07-16 1480
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVIS-100YEARS-3 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMORIES STILL SPILL FROM CUP'S CENTURY 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A black-and-white file photo of Dwight Davis is being
sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Bjorn Borg is rising, higher and higher,
above a tennis court in Stockholm. Up he goes . . . then down, to
be caught in a blanket . . . and then up, pitched toward the
ceiling again. Over and over, as the usually restrained Swedish
crowd roars with delight and the pitchers _ his comrades in
groundstrokes _ grin impishly and give him one more toss.
</P>
<P>
   This celebratory hurling is called a hissening. It is 1975, just
after the 19-year-old Borg has almost singlehandedly defeated
Czechoslovakia, 3-2, to earn Sweden the first of its seven Davis
Cups.
</P>
<P>
   Sweden has just joined a victors' club that had been limited to
the United States, Australia, Great Britain, and France before
1974, when South Africa won by default over India. (The Indian
government, protesting apartheid, refused permission for its team
to partake of the championship round.)
</P>
<P>
   But a year later, after a genuine final, Sweden is in the
exclusive lineup. All through the night the Swedes and their guests
will guzzle champagne from the venerable tub, making another
stopover in its global wandering that began in 1903. To the victors
go the hangovers.
</P>
<P>
   Who could have imagined at the sterling basin's 1900 unveiling
on two unbearably hot August afternoons in Boston that the trophy _
dubbed ``Dwight's pot'' by the donor's good-natured cronies _ would
be so determinedly and passionately pursued around the planet for a
century and counting? Probably not even Dwight Filley Davis
himself, a rich Harvard kid who paid jeweler Shreve Crump &AMP; Low
about $1,000 to hatch his dream.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since, his silver brainchild, conceived in the hope of
advancing international sportsmanship and understanding through a
game, has been on the go incessantly, growing in stature,
spiritually and physically. With the names of the final-round
players annually engraved thereon, Dwight's baby has enlarged from
the Cup itself to encompass a tray holding it and then raised atop
an ever-expanding base. His infant has put on years and inches.
</P>
<P>
   Expanding with it is the legend, the litany of wins and losses,
joys and sorrows that go with playing for your country and being
caught up in nationalism, champagne, and tears. There are stories
of no-names becoming kings-for-a-weekend by adrenalizing to
momentous victories _ such as Ecuadorans Miguel Olvera and Pancho
Guzman beating the US in 1967. Or big names being cut down to
serfdom, succumbing to the pressures of a debut _ such as Pete
Sampras tumbling at Lyon in 1991 as France jolted the US.
</P>
<P>
   Or even the tragic surrender to the burden of carrying his
country's colors suffered by 26-year-old Jiro Satoh, Japan's
finest, in 1934. Although he had led the Japanese to the semifinals
the prior year, Satoh continued to be despondent over that 3-2 loss
to Australia. On the way to England for a season-opening Cup
encounter, he leaped from a ship into the Strait of Malacca,
leaving a suicide note: ``I would have been unable to help . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Ralston, a Cup winner both as US player and captain,
says, ``Even if your country doesn't know or care that you're
representing it, you do. It's a big load, but a great one.''
</P>
<P>
   No fiercer competitor has lived than Pancho Gonzalez, who played
merely two singles matches for the US, winning both in the 1949
victory over Australia. Yet he remembered, ``I was never so nervous
before a match. Couldn't sleep. I was scared to lose when I was
playing for the USA.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-two years ago, eight years before Borg was flung skyward
within the Kungliga Hallen, the pitchers in Guayaquil were throwing
rocks _ over the fence enclosing the small stadium. The missiles
were landing on the court where Ecuador's unknown Guzman and Olvera
were perpetrating perhaps the Cup's hugest upset, 3-2 over a US
team stocked with four world-class guys: Arthur Ashe, Cliff Richey,
Marty Riessen, and Clark Graebner. It wasn't an anti-American
demonstration. The rock chuckers were angry because the joint was
sold out and they couldn't get in to witness the miracle wrought by
their otherwise ordinary compatriots.
</P>
<P>
   It is a beautiful feature of Davis Cup and its best-of-five
format of four singles matches and a doubles _ devised by Davis's
Boston mentor, Dr. James Dwight _ that a small country with only
two players can overturn the largest.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This happens over and over again in a competition in which
reputations and computer rankings mean zilch once the firing
begins. Ask Sampras about Cup jitters. Ask another great, Stefan
Edberg, who while ranked No. 1 in 1992 was beaten by No. 238,
Canadian rookie Daniel Nestor. Or an American top-10 guy, Jimmy
Arias, beaten by No. 282 Hugo Chapacu as the US crumbled in, of all
places, Paraguay in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Their numbers are legion. They are all part of the fun and
tension of a competition that sprung from a humble start at the
corner of Brookline and Longwood avenues _ the original Longwood
Cricket Club _ 99 years ago as three Brits battled three Harvard
dudes. Formally, it was the British Isles vs. the United States in
the inaugural competition for the expensive hardware that the
modest Davis had baptized ``International Lawn Tennis Challenge
Trophy.'' Fortunately for headline writers, and scribblers and
babblers like me, it was soon to be referred to as the just plain
(though ornate) Davis Cup.
</P>
<P>
   From an event matching two countries to one now involving 129
(eight currently remaining in the elite World Group), Dwight's baby
has come a long way, all right. And the countries that have made
the most of the bauble's journeying _ Australia and the US _ are
ready to pounce for a 45th time. Appropriately, this happens in the
100th year of the priceless Cup (insured for $250,000 but
considered unduplicable) at the (sort of) birthplace, a relocated
Longwood just up the road.
</P>
<P>
   Aussies and Yanks. They are the Montagues and the Capulets in a
netted rectangle _ but with a smile and a handshake after the
uncompromising feud. Twenty-nine times they've clashed in the title
round _ the Aussies lead, 15-14, although the US leads the overall
series, 25-19, going back to 1905. The victor of this weekend's
quarterfinal will next play the Russia-Slovakia survivor.
</P>
<P>
   Australia is a country the size of the US but population poor.
For the first five of its 26 triumphs, the island of only a few
million had to rely on help from another island, New Zealand. The
team, called Australasia, was manned by Norman Brookes, a
lefthander from Melbourne, and the dashing Tony Wilding from
Christchurch. Wilding was a pre-Hell's Angels hog-riding hunk whose
four-year Wimbledon reign was ended by Brookes in 1914, a year
before his life was ended in France by World War I.
</P>
<P>
   Even by 1939, the last Cup in the life of Davis _ who died in
1945 after a civic-minded career (Secretary of War,
Governor-General of the Philippines), there were only about 5
million Aussies. Nevertheless, that was the year of their unique
two-man triumph, 3-2, over the US in Philadelphia. Down, 0-2, after
the opening day, Adrian Quist and John Bromwich rebounded to take
the doubles over 18-year-old Jack Kramer and Joe Hunt, who would
win the US title in 1943, then die at 25 as a Naval pilot in World
War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a confusing time,'' recalls Bromwich, now 80 and living
in Port Lonsdale, outside Melbourne. ``We'd made the three-week
boat trip to California, then taken a train to the East Coast. A
day before the matches, war was declared. We were in it and didn't
know if we should even play, but were given approval.''
</P>
<P>
   Bromwich lives quietly, beset by several diseases yet cheerful,
and looking forward to the telecast of this weekend's engagement
even though it begins at 2 a.m. Saturday Down Under. As curious as
a duckbilled platypus in his tennis style, Brom, a lefthander,
served righty and struck a southpaw forehand but used both hands on
the other side, a distinct oddity in that ante-Evert-Borg-Connors
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd won the US Doubles at Longwood,'' Bromwich recounts, ``so
we were confident of beating Kramer and Hunt, a new pairing. On the
third day, Quisty told me he'd beat (Bobby) Riggs if I'd promise to
follow up by beating (Frank) Parker. That's just what happened,
although his was close, five sets. I won in straight.''
</P>
<P>
   Never before or since has the Cup been won from 0-2. ``We were
very proud,'' says Bromwich. ``Not only because we hadn't won for
25 years, but this was the first time it was just Australia, no
longer Australasia.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
