<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-BLAIR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOCKUMENTARY DOES GOOD HORROR ON A BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE BLAIR WITCH PROJECT 
Written and directed by: Edouardo Sanchez, Dan Myrick 
Starring: Heather Donahue, Michael Williams, Joshua Leonard 
Running time: 87 minutes 
Rated: R (language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hollywood is going to be throwing a lot of high-budget horror at
us in the weeks ahead. But it's easy to believe that when all the
dust settles, a low-budget mock documentary, ``The Blair Witch
Project,'' will be remembered as the scariest of them all. Like so
many truly effective horror movies _ ``Night of the Living Dead,''
``Texas Chainsaw Massacre,'' ``Last House on the Left'' _ it's both
cheesy and primal. It's as primal as it is partly because it's so
cheesy and minimalist. And it shrewdly substitutes dread for gore.
The film, by Daniel Myrick and Eduardo Sanchez, is a long improv by
three young actors in the Maryland woods, playing film-school
students shooting a film about a gory local legend. They're
nervously camping out in tents, growing progressively unhinged as
they're awakened by the cries of children and unnerved by
mysterious lights and primitive artifacts hanging from trees.
</P>
<P>
   We are told that they disappeared after eight days. What we see
is said to be the footage they shot, discovered long after the
unsuccessful search for them. With ironic humor, Heather Donahue's
team leader compulsively films all their kibitzing and bickering as
they stumble deeper into the woods. En route to the Blair Witch of
legend, they learn of horrific subsequent crimes on the site,
encounter other scary things, diligently documenting all the while
their own unraveling when the dynamic crumbles as nerves and
tempers fray. Hysteria and dislocation march hand in hand until it
becomes apparent that the three are in over their heads. It begins
to dawn on them that their tight little filming schedule is a joke
and they may be in grave danger.
</P>
<P>
   As the driven director, Donahue convincingly embodies the
single-mindedness she knows she needs if the project is to be
completed. She also is aware of a male-female power situation, in
which Joshua Reynolds, the actor playing the cameraman (who
actually shot most of the film), and Michael Williams's sound man
repeatedly test her. But at a certain point it becomes clear that
power plays are irrelevant, that any idea that they are going to
wield any power or control is only an illusion. There's something
in the woods that's bigger and stronger and more malevolent than
all of them. The only questions are what it is and whether it's
going to get them, as Donahue's director compulsively camcords her
thoughts and observations to the end.
</P>
<P>
   The framing device and central conceit work almost perfectly. In
the film's last third, slack and self-consciousness set in as we
become aware that we're watching actors trying to improvise their
way through what suddenly has become dead space. When an improv
fails to rise, it's flatter than a ruined souffle, and there is a
zone where the air goes out of the faux amateurishness and
roughness. That being said, however, ``The Blair Witch Project''
rights itself with a horrifying impact that carries through to as
heart-stopping a climax as any the genre has seen in years. ``The
Blair Witch Project'' makes virtues of graininess, blurriness, and
jerky camera movements. By the end, the freak-outs and the
creepiness are as real and as terrifying as you could hope for.
``The Blair Witch Project'' casts a clammy, unnerving spell.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
