NYT-07-16-99 1334EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990716.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2672 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-DAVIS-100YEARS-3R     07-16 1356
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVIS-100YEARS-3RD </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 BROOKLINE, Mass.: ... the homeland.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Certainly the cosmopolitan Italian, Nicky Pietrangeli, who
played more Cup matches than anybody else (120-44 in 66 series from
1954-1972), found a few lire from the tooth fairy. But after
leading Italy to the finals of 1960-61, he accepted a rich contract
from pro promoter Jack Kramer. But it was soon repudiated. As
Kramer remembers, ``Nicky told me he couldn't join me after all
because Italy had raised his salary. I tore up the contract. How
could I outbid a country that cared so much for Davis Cup?''
</P>
<P>
   In '73, with probably the greatest of all teams _ Rod Laver, Ken
Rosewall, John Newcombe, Mal Anderson _ the Aussies took away the
Cup, smashing an American monopoly of five years built mainly by
Arthur Ashe, Stan Smith, and Bob Lutz. Newcombe, captaining this
weekend's Aussie team, and Laver played all the matches in a
reverberating 5-0 triumph.
</P>
<P>
   The Aussies were back, though briefly. Not like the days of
Capt. Harry Hopman, chief embalmer of the Down Undertakers. Such an
era of Cup dominance is unimaginable now, as players and their
agents run the show, subservient to no captain. Hopman, slight,
nimble, and fit _ ``with the power of life and death over us,''
recalls Fred Stolle _ knew how to train and inspire champions,
working on their pride in representing an out-of-the-way country
and beating up on the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   He won his first Cup in that 1939 Bromwich-Quist revival, gave
way to others, then was desperately summoned to the captain's chair
again in 1950 to try to dam the US post-war flood of four wins by
Jack Kramer, Ted Schroeder, and Pancho Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Presto! Blessed by a gusher of Hall of Famers named Laver,
Rosewall, Newcombe, Stolle, Frank Sedgman, Ken McGregor, Lew Hoad,
Ashley Cooper, Neale Fraser, Roy Emerson, and Tony Roche plus
Anderson, Rex Hartwig, and Mervyn Rose, Captain Hop directed the
Aussies shrewdly and won 15 more Cups, the last in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Hop's first year, 1938, he guided Australia to the final, but
Quist and Bromwich weren't up to dealing with the US, alias John
Donald Budge. Nobody was. In 1937, Budge had been a welcome
cloudburst of magnificent shot-making in busting the longest US
drought, 11 years. Don's tour de force, the five-set extravaganza
over Germany's elegant Baron Gottfried von Cramm, has been talked
and written about ever since _ the most resounding of Davis Cup
victories if the barrels of ink devoted to it are any measure.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't televised, however, so tapes of Courier's splendid
five-set decisions over Tim Henman and Greg Rusedski in April at
Birmingham, England, may be contenders. Like Courier's setting,
Budge's wasn't the final. Budge and von Cramm collided in the semis
at Wimbledon, with the winning country expected to defeat
Cup-clutching Britain (which the US did).
</P>
<P>
   Budge and his redoubtable sidekick, Gene Mako, won the doubles
for a 2-1 lead, but Henner Henkel started the third day beating
tiny Bitsy Grant. It was 2-2, leaving the verdict up to Budge and
the Baron. Budge says that just before they went onto the court von
Cramm, an avowed anti-Nazi, received a phone call from Adolph
Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gottfried kept saying, `Jah, mein fuhrer. Jah, mein fuhrer,'
'' relates Budge. ``He was being ordered to win for the fatherland
and was pale and serious. He played as if his life depended on
every point.''
</P>
<P>
   Now there's a touch of Davis Cup pressure, wouldn't you say? And
the Baron almost won. Later, von Cramm went to jail under
trumped-up charges, an ordeal he probably would have avoided had he
beaten Budge and grabbed the Cup for Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Budge, reeling from the loss of the first two sets, regrouped to
win the next two but was pummeled into the abyss again, 1-4, in the
fifth. At the changeover, the willowy redhead, who would score the
initial Grand Slam the following year, told US captain Walter Pate,
``Don't worry, Cap. I'll win.''
</P>
<P>
   So he did, 6-8, 5-7, 6-4, 6-2, 8-6, although von Cramm kept the
suspense going by canceling five match points. Budge never saw the
last _ a running, diving forehand winner that landed Don on his
face.
</P>
<P>
   Budge, 84, still reveres his close friendship with von Cramm,
whom he calls ``an unsurpassed sportsman. After I beat him, he
said, `Don, that's the finest match I've ever played.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the sportsmanship spectrum, Budge also
enjoys a friendship with John McEnroe. ``John was such a great
player,'' said Budge, ``and I liked the way he was always ready to
play Davis Cup even when others weren't.''
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe, a two-way wizard who often handled both the singles and
doubles, played more years (12) and series (30) than any other
American. He was 41-8 in singles, 18-2 in doubles, and had a solid
left hand in five Cups from 1978-1992, a US longevity mark. Fred
Stolle is among those who believe Mac, even at 40, should have been
selected for this match's doubles alongside Sampras, with whom he
combined for two wins, including the 1992 final.
</P>
<P>
   When you talk about sportsmanship, amid all the conniving that
goes on in court surface selection and making the most of home site
advantage, the name of Ed Turville, winning US captain in 1970-71,
shouldn't be overlooked. Romania, with Ilie Nastase and Ion Tiriac,
fought to the '71 final in Charlotte, N.C. And Turville, while he
wanted to win, also wanted ``a good, entertaining match for the
fans, something good for tennis.'' He felt the 5-0 US win over the
Romanians in 1969 on a souped-up hard court in Cleveland had been
one-sidedly dull, unfair. ``The Romanians are used to clay, so
we'll play on clay,'' said Turville.
</P>
<P>
   Promptly his best player, Cliff Richey, quit the team, calling
Turville a traitor who'd given the Cup away. The Romanians were
ecstatic and confident. Turville, needing a body, went searching
and found a retread, spidery 28-year-old Frank Froehling, who
hadn't been on the team in six years. Froehling, from two sets
down, beat Tiriac, 8-6, in the fifth, and Stan Smith, no happy
camper on dirt, upset Nastase. The US won and Turville is still
smiling, believing that sportsmen can win.
</P>
<P>
   Smith proved that many times over with his big right hand in
helping the US win seven Cups _ same as Tilden _ never more so than
in Bucharest in 1972, my nomination for greatest US performance
overseas and in a hostile environment. Too bad there are no tapes.
</P>
<P>
   Bucharest was a very drab, sad place, life hard under the thumb
of the dictator Nicolae Ceausescu. But those two men, Nastase and
Tiriac, gave their countrymen great pride. People lined up for
blocks and paid 10 cents to view the Cup on display in a downtown
store. Nastase had guaranteed the hopeful that it would stay in
Romania.
</P>
<P>
   No problem, thought Nastase. This was crimson European clay,
slowed for the weekend to mire the Americans, and Nasty was the
world's boss on that stuff. Smith was even less sure than he'd been
sliding on the Charlotte version. Much of it was out of giraffeian
Stan's control because the local umpires and line judges were super
patriots. Realizing he had to smack winners well within the lines,
Stan did just that to save a set point while beating Nastase in
three and Tiriac in an enthralling five sets to clinch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I concentrated so hard I had a headache for days,'' Smith
recalls.
</P>
<P>
   It was more than a headache that Patricio Cornejo suffered when
Chile had its chance of a lifetime, the 1976 final against Adriano
Panatta's Italians. It occurred in Santiago, where a bugler
constantly ran up and down the stadium steps, rallying the crowd.
Alas, the first day's singles went badly for the Chileans. Cornejo
and Jaime Fillol were beaten by Corrado Barazzutti and Panatta,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   The second night was worse. Not because the Chileans had lost
the doubles, but because Cornejo almost lost his life. Heart attack
in the hotel. When help arrived at his room, the doctors found him
fully dressed in tennis gear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was going to die,'' he said. ``I wanted to go as a
player.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis Cuppers would understand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
