<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-NOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU CUT YOUR LETTUCE? OH, NO! 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When in France, eat as the French do. And that goes for other
countries around the globe, too. Here, from Travel Holiday, are
examples of how table etiquette can change with geography:
</P>
<P>
   --In France, never cut your lettuce. Instead, use your knife and
fork to fold the leaves into bite-sized pieces. And don't order
soft drinks with your meal. That's considered close to barbaric.
</P>
<P>
   --In India and Malaysia, it's all right to eat with your hand _
but not your hands. You pass dishes with the left hand but eat with
the right only.
</P>
<P>
   --Slurping soup or noodles in Japan shows appreciation, not
rudeness. It is rude, however, to refill your own glass; dining
partners take turns refilling one another's. And finally, you'll
insult the cook if you put soy sauce on your white rice.
</P>
<P>
   Travel Trivia: In which of these cities would you be most likely
to find a philocubist: Salt Lake City, Las Vegas, Boston, or
Orlando? (Answer at end of column.)
</P>
<P>
   In a name: In Korea, you can buy Independence Cola, with the
numbers 815 writ large on the can or bottle. (Korea's independence
day is on 8/15.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
And speaking of Independence Day: We learn from Old Sturbridge
Village that the Fourth of July was so important to 19th-century
New Englanders that they did what would be unthinkable on any other
summer day _ interrupted haying and other farm work to celebrate.
Just how joyously they celebrated will be made evident in special
events at the village today.
</P>
<P>
   Quotable: ``It'd be a great country if it had a roof over it!''
_ comedian Noel V. Ginnity, on Ireland. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Today's loopy law: You need a $5 permit to go barefoot in Texas. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Advice to go (and we do mean go): You're on vacation or on the road
and you need a doctor, have a health question, lose a prescription,
or suffer from an illness such as, ahem, diarrhea. Kmart Corp. and
the makers of Immodium are sponsoring a toll-free number _
800-866-0086 _ that lets you speak to a pharmacist. Last year the
most frequently asked questions concerned lost prescriptions,
potential drug interactions, diarrhea (the most common vacation
ailment), and how to find a physician in the area. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? Las Vegas. A philocubist is a dice player. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpen(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
