<DOCNO> NYT19990716.0090 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2675 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-DAVIS-100YEARS-2N     07-16 1357
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVIS-100YEARS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 BROOKLINE, Mass.: ... longer Australasia.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brookes, the early stalwart who'd become head man of Australian
tennis, carted the Cup back to Melbourne, where it languished in a
bank vault for seven years of war until the tournament resumed _
and Yanks Jack Kramer and Ted Schroeder lifted it. There was an
eerie air to the '39 Aussie triumph, saddened in retrospect by
Hunt's wartime death, a postscript to KIA Wilding in World War I.
</P>
<P>
   A quarter-century before, on the eve of that war, Brookes and
Wilding defeated the US, 3-2, at New York. Wilding, then 31, was
playing the last tennis of his bright young life before being
killed in combat. He led off by beating Dick Williams, the miracle
man of tennis. A Longwood member, Williams had somehow braved icy
waters for six hours in surviving the Titanic sinking 28 months
previously, and would become a valorous warrior himself in the US
Army. But Brookes prevailed on this day, and the Cup moved Down
Under for a long wartime stay at his home. It was such a casual
addition to the Brookes household that his wife used it as a flower
pot.
</P>
<P>
   Hans Redl, a soldier in the German Army, was luckier than Joe
Hunt and multitudes of others in World War II. He lost an arm, but
it was his left _ and Hans was a righthander playing for Austria
before the war. Was his Cup career over? Nein. One-armed, he was
even better, posting 3-10 singles and 3-8 doubles marks. In 1947,
at age 33, he made the fourth round at Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A remarkable comeback, but Cup history is packed with them,
loaded with guys who, as Davis Cup maestro Jim Courier said
Thursday, ``either play way above or below their standard. It's
rare when somebody maintains his normal standard.''
</P>
<P>
   Above is why Arnaud Boetsch _ who? _ was riding in an open
convertible along the Champs-Elysees in 1996 as 100,000 Parisians
cheered him and his teammates madly, and the president of France
awaited with personal congratulations. Boetsch, one of the more
improbable Davis Cup weekend wonders _ guys super-charged by the
occasion, or overcome _ had given France its eighth Cup as a
Houdini in short pants. Only once in all the years of these
best-of-five match series has a man in the ultimate match, the
fifth, escaped Cup points to win. Boetsch, not to be heard from
again, is that man.
</P>
<P>
   With all Sweden anticipating a home triumph at Malmo as Nicklas
Kulti needed but 1 point to seize the sterling prize, Boetsch
somehow wriggled out of triple Cup point _ serving at 6-7, 0-40 _
to win, 7-6 (7-2), 2-6, 4-6, 7-6 (7-5), 10-8, in 4 hours 47
minutes. They'll probably put stubby Arnaud in the Pantheon when he
dies.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, France has nurtured numerous fine players. A bloc of
them known as the Four Musketeers _ Renee Lacoste, Henri Cochet,
Jean Borotra, and Jacques Brugnon _ emerged in the 1920s to wrest
the spotlight and the Cup away from the man who symbolized it in
the US, having turned American attention toward tennis: Big Bill
Tilden.
</P>
<P>
   Tilden, imperious, cool, and a late-maturing, stroke-making
virtuoso in long flannels, led the US to the Antipodes in 1920 to
recover the Cup in New Zealand. He was 27 and had just won the
first of six straight US titles. He and his countryman and usual
rival, Little Bill Johnston, beat Brookes and Australasia, and kept
winning and winning until the US streak lengthened to a record
seven years.
</P>
<P>
   After two final-round misses, the French caught up and paid the
Bills back, 3-2, in 1927. ``It took four of us to beat Beeg Beel,''
said Lacoste, who brought down Tilden to deadlock the series at
2-2. Whereupon Cochet beat Johnston as Lacoste and Tilden sat
together watching Big Bill's empire disintegrate. Borotra and
Brugnon had done their softening-up part well, pushing Tilden to
five sets in doubles (with Frank Hunter), though losing.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, these magnetic Gallic guys, each with a widely known
nickname, took over. ``The Crocodile'' Lacoste, ``Toto'' Brugnon,
``Bounding Basque'' Borotra, and the diminutive Cochet, ``the
Ballboy of Lyon,'' created a tennis version of their country's
Reign of Terror, holding on to the Cup for six years.
</P>
<P>
   Although Lacoste, designer of the universally adopted
short-sleeved polo shirt (still around, bearing his reptilian
logo), retired soon, the momentum continued until Britain's last
championship gasp. Fred Perry and Bunny Austin took over in 1933
for a four-year run that might be called Roper Barrett's Revenge.
</P>
<P>
   You see, Herbert Roper Barrett had been one of those Englishmen
_ ``the Dauntless Three,'' London newspapers called them _ who had
accepted that challenge from the US in 1900 and had stepped onto
Longwood sod, much to their distress. They were undaunted sports
who had picked up their own tabs. You couldn't find anybody to play
today, in this professional era, if that precedent of 1900
prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans this weekend are getting in the neighborhood of
100 grand from the US Tennis Association, and the Aussies won't
starve, either. But Brits Roper Barrett, Arthur Gore, and Ernest
Black paid their own way on steam ships to and from a 3-0 defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, they showed a certain inquisitiveness that would seem
odd to campaigners today. Black, Gore, and Roper Barrett decided to
explore. They took the long way 'round to Boston _ a train journey
to gawk at wondrous Niagara Falls _ and arrived at Longwood just a
day before before the hostilities were to begin, with time for only
a brief practice.
</P>
<P>
   Viewing all that cascading water may have prepared the Brits for
the soaking they got from the Harvard Three _ Davis, Malcolm
Whitman, and Holcombe Ward. They didn't know what hit them, because
they couldn't hit the wildly spinning and bounding ``American
twist'' serves, new to their experience, a weapon developed by the
stubby Ward and common nowadays.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, a tall lefty, was the US captain. After all, it was his
idea and Cup, wasn't it? He lost the opening set to Black, but
after that the American procession was on for nine straight sets.
</P>
<P>
   The Brits, who had come far to show the Colonials how the game
should be played, moaned and groaned about the lousy courts, balls,
and net _ and the casual attitude of their hosts in insisting on
taking a break after each set. The tourists were probably right.
However, Roper Barrett did salute the gathering of 1,200, saying
that ``the female portion was not unpleasant to gaze upon'' _ more
smashing than the Brits' performance.
</P>
<P>
   Men in suits and hats, and women in long gowns, hats, and
parasols filled a covered stand ($2.50 for shade). The remainder of
the seats in the searing sun cost $1, for which at the time you
could also purchase five pounds of coffee or 12 pounds of lamb, or
even a bottle of Dr. William Brown's White River Remedy that
``cures drunkenness.''
</P>
<P>
   Not finding a cure for the weekend grogginess induced by the
Colonials' serves, Roper Barrett did acknowledge, ``Their game is
too hard for us.'' But, 33 years after, sweet revenge. He found a
way to win from the bench as the captain of Britain's four-time
champs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the three-quarters of a century between the Cup's christening
and Borg's high-flying hissening, the event had attracted adherents
and players on every continent but Antarctica, where the penguins
tend to incur tennis elbow flapping for fish.
</P>
<P>
   It went professional in 1973, a traumatic year for some in that
the final became a hothouse presentation, inside Cleveland's Public
Hall. Iconoclastic promoter Bob Malaga had previously shocked
tennis purists by staging the 1964 final on Cleveland clay,
declaring that sod was dead. His abandonment of grass, after all 20
title rounds in this country had been played on the sod, was one
thing. But then Malaga took away fresh air. Now indoor finals are
routine.
</P>
<P>
   If Davis Cuppers desired to earn cash from tennis before 1968,
they had to turn pro, whereupon they were barred from the
substantial events. Obviously, some of the alleged amateurs in more
realistic, practical Europe received stipends to play for the
homeland.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
