<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2680 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV18     07-16 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV18-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE DIVERSIFICATION, AND PLEASE, NO MORE DELL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 18, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am 34 and self-employed. I have a wife and two kids and
plan on retiring when I reach age 50 with $5 million in assets. I
currently have $81,000 in a SEP-IRA invested in stock mutual funds,
an additional $50,000 in taxable mutual fund accounts, and $263,500
in nine common stocks, with the portfolio dominated by $210,000 in
Dell Computer. I currently make in excess of $200,000 a year and
contribute $22,500 to the SEP account annually. I also invest
$3,000 a month in various stocks. Do I have the right
diversification, and will I meet my target?
</P>
<P>
   K.B., Orion, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   A. The computer shows you would fall less than $1 million shy of
your target, presuming you continued saving at your current rate of
$4,875 a month and that your investment returns averaged 10 percent
a year. And since more than half your savings is going into taxable
accounts, you would have to find other money to pay any tax
liabilities resulting from those investments just to get to the
$4,014,011 projection.
</P>
<P>
   The computer shows that the sequence of equal savings payments
required to get you to $5 million over 16 years calls for $7,068 a
month, more than 42 percent of your pretax income, which is more
than most of us can save.
</P>
<P>
   My first suggestion is this: Since your current savings
represents 29.25 percent of your income, maintain your savings at
that percentage level, adjusting the amount of dollar savings each
year as your income changes.
</P>
<P>
   Second, look into variable annuity accounts so as to defer the
tax liability on the growth of your savings. A very efficient
variable annuity account, to my way of thinking, is one offered by
Vanguard which invests its assets so as to track the Standard and
Poor's 500 index. Because of a small insurance element which is
required to get the tax deferral, returns tend to run one-half of 1
percentage point less than Vanguard's Index 500 fund.
</P>
<P>
   Your fund portfolio is reasonably well diversified, although I
like to see some representation of heatlh care and technology
sector funds in addition to the large-cap, mid-cap, small-cap and
international growth funds you are now using. But that huge
position in Dell Computer, currently representing more than half of
your total savings, renders any discussion of diversification a
little silly. Yes, Dell's a great company, and I'm guessing that
you've held this position so long that you can't sell without
turning a tidy amount of the proceeds over to Uncle Sam. But for
goodness sake, don't buy any more.
</P>
<P>
   On the fund side, besides the sector funds, I'd like to see you
bump up the holdings in Oppenheimer Enterprise, your small-cap
fund, and in Putnam International Growth and Oppenheimer
International Growth.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, to get to a broader diversification, I'd direct at
least two-thirds of your non-IRA savings to the fund portfolio
rather than to the stock portfolio. Your stock selections are solid
_ besides Dell, you have WalMart, Home Depot, Microsoft and similar
issues. But putting most of your savings into individual stocks is
not an approach which will lead to broad diversification. Remember,
the markets of the last couple of years have been very kind to the
kind of individual stocks you hold, but markets come and go, and in
the long run you'll be better served with a broader portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. How does an investor balance a 401(k), IRA and additional
investments? I am 34 and contribute 20 percent of my gross income
to my 401(k), which has five investment options. I do not
contribute to a Stable Value fund or a US Treasury securities fund.
I put 10 percent into Vanguard Wellington, 50 percent in Vanguard
Total Stock Market Index, 30 percent in Vanguard U.S. Growth, and
10 percent in Vanguard International Growth. Is this the best
distribution for my long-term goal of retiring at age 60? I also am
interested in opening a Roth IRA. Should I view this IRA as a
separate portfolio or as part of my 401(k). I would like to begin
the Roth with an investment in Vanguard's Index 500. Also, should I
open the account with the minimum $1,000 and then use dollar-cost
averaging to reach the $2,000 maximum? Finally, I would like to
invest toward buying a house and retirement. What's best?
</P>
<P>
   D.G., Chula Vista, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A. To start with the 401(k), I think you've made about the best
you can of a pretty skimpy menu. Since all of the funds you're
using except the international offering concentrate on large-cap
domestic stocks, it's important to view your 401(k), your Roth IRA,
and your proposed taxable account _ all of which are earmarked for
retirement _ as elements of a single retirement program.
</P>
<P>
   And since you will be setting up the Roth IRA and the taxable
account on your own, you can use these vehicles to make up for some
of the shortcomings of the 401(k) menu. Since you already have that
heavy concentration on domestic large-cap stocks, you probably
won't want either Vanguard's Index 500 or its LifeStrategy Growth
funds, since both of them would just be buying you more of the
same.
</P>
<P>
   If I were you I would put the Roth IRA _ where the money will be
tax free once it's finally withdrawn _ in an investment where you
might reasonably expect to achieve your greatest growth. My
suggestion would be Fidelity Select Health Care, moving from
Vanguard only because that company has closed its excellent heath
care offering. In the taxable account, I would begin with
Vanguard's Small-Cap Index, and in subsequent years add its Mid-Cap
Index fund. These moves, when taken together with the 401(k)
holdings, will give you a lot more diversification among market
sectors than you could ever achieve through the 401(k) menu.
</P>
<P>
   To dollar-cost average or not? My approach when you're dealing
with an IRA account is to consider that a regularly-funded IRA is
inherently a dollar-cost averaging discipline from the start. I
would probably decide how you're going to fund it next year _ with
a lump sum or by contributing $166 a month. If the former, I'd go
ahead with the lump sum to open the account. If the latter, I'd
start with the $1,000 contribution and distribute the final $1,000
among what's left of this year and then pick up on the $166-a-month
discipline at the start of the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the proper investment for your real estate savings
depends on how long you think it will take before you're ready to
buy. If it's likely to take you about a decade to save the down
payment, I'd use Vanguard GNMA as my initial savings vehicle. If
it's a closer to five years, you might use a very conservative bond
fund such as Vanguard Short-Term Corporate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
