<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVIS-STOLLE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOLLE IS AUSTRALIA'S RISING SON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RUPEN FOFARIA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Sandon Stolle sits alongside the court at
Longwood Cricket Club, watching Pete Sampras and Alex O'Brien _
members of the American Davis Cup team _ hit balls to one another.
His attention is diverted to his own left arm, where the symbol of
a phoenix is tattooed near his shoulder blade. His voice grows
quieter and more cautious, but still he discusses his rise from the
depths of tennis frustration _ which at one point had him convinced
he was through with the sport _ to the peak of becoming the fourth
and final member of the Australian Davis Cup team.
</P>
<P>
   When the year began, Stolle knew he wanted to be a part of the
Davis Cup. The feeling of camaraderie in team tennis intrigues him,
so he wanted to play a part, no matter how small. Last week, after
successful doubles competitor Todd Woodbridge announced his
withdrawal, Stolle was named the replacement, promoting him from
practice partner to participant in the historic tie, the second
year in a row he has risen from the shadows to take center stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tennis is a funny game,'' said the 29-year-old Stolle. ``Sport
is in general. You think you're through with it and you've had
enough, and then you hit a vault and you're back in love with it.
Just live day by day and enjoy it while you're on top.''
</P>
<P>
   Stolle has garnered world rankings as high as 50 in singles play
and 14 in doubles. Last year, paired with Cyril Suk, he won the US
Open doubles title. This year he made his third Davis Cup team.
</P>
<P>
   Stolle has enjoyed much success in professional tennis _ a game
he was taught by his father, Australian legend Fred Stolle _ but he
has had to wade through a pool of injuries and disappointment
before any of it set in.
</P>
<P>
   He should be used to it, though. The script read almost exactly
as it did when he was playing as a junior.
</P>
<P>
   Stolle is a late bloomer in the world of tennis, a sport in
which Jennifer Capriati enjoyed professional success at age 15.
Stolle was struggling in juniors at the same age.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're a kid and you don't really know what's going on and you
wind up at a tournament as Fred Stolle's son,'' he said. ``But as
years go on people know you for who you are, and I think I've made
a little name for myself now. And people, they're never going to
compare me to what my dad did _ he had so many incredible
achievements. To me, tennis has been great to my family and myself,
and I'm just going to appreciate all the days I have playing.''
</P>
<P>
   At 15, Stolle attended Harry Hopman's tennis camp, and his life
changed. He played tennis every day until it got dark, and suddenly
he started winning. Suddenly a sport that had never been a top
priority became fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was definitely a late developer as far as not being the best
junior player, and it definitely wasn't the No. 1 thing I wanted to
do,'' he said. ``I just hit a vault along the way, which was a
great thing, and when I saw my window of opportunity, I took it.''
</P>
<P>
   That vault didn't last long, though. His skills got him a
scholarship to Texas Christian, where he played for two years,
earning All-America honors in 1990. He moved back to Australia and
turned pro. Stolle finished his first year ranked tied for 813th.
He realized then that this was going to be a long road. And it was.
He didn't crack the top 200 for another two years (1991) and the
top 100 until 1992. He finished the year No. 71 and was poised for
a run at the top 50.
</P>
<P>
   He couldn't find his stroke, though, and despite enjoying minor
successes, Stolle finished 199, 182, and 182 over the next three
years, respectively. He was confused. He worked hard, played hard _
did all the things that had brought him to success when he was
younger.
</P>
<P>
   That was the first time the thought crossed his mind: I want
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we all have those times,'' he said. ``I've had a few
injuries through the years that I've been playing and a lot of ups
and downs. I remember sitting down with dad _ on I know one
occasion but probably twice _ and saying, `I don't know if this is
what I want to do anymore. I've had enough.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But his father convinced him to stay in the game. It was a tough
sell for someone who was never completely focused on tennis in the
first place. When he had trouble breaking into the junior circuit,
the outdoors would call louder than the tennis court. He wanted to
ski or hike or snowboard or just sit in the mountains and think.
Now, here he was, falling on hard times again at a place where he
was forcing himself to be. His mind and heart, he thought, were
ready to let go. So why come back?
</P>
<P>
   ``There didn't seem to be a reason to,'' he said. ``But then I
come into contact with a few people along the way that sort of
inspired me to have another crack at it. And that's what it's all
about: coming across these people that can all of a sudden change
your outlook.''
</P>
<P>
   The first of these people was his physical trainer back in
Australia in 1996, Brett Stephens, with whom he no longer works but
maintains a strong friendship. Stephens, who plays Australian Rules
Football, clicked with Stolle's love for the outdoors. They had a
common bond, and over the next 2 1/2 years, Stephens was able to
completely turn Stolle's career around.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really got me thinking in ways I hadn't thought before and
he really got a lot out of me for 2 1/2 years, where I felt like I
was going to play,'' Stolle remembers.
</P>
<P>
   Stolle finished 58th in 1996, and after climbing as high as 50
in 1997, he finished the year at 84. Things were going well. But
not half as well as they would in 1998, when he won two tournaments
and made the quarterfinals at three others.
</P>
<P>
   But he soon noticed an ache in his arm. He thought it was just
wear and tear, so he didn't think too much of it until he started
having more trouble and his ranking began to drop. When he finally
went to see a doctor, he found out it was a stress fracture.
Translation: six months away from tennis, just when he was starting
to catch fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was having my best year yet,'' Stolle said. ``I was still
working with Brett and I got up to top 50 in singles, and then that
was it. I got injured, played half the year, and was out. After all
of that, I was out.''
</P>
<P>
   Those six months were quite long. So long, in fact, that those
thoughts began creeping back. Was it time to leave?
</P>
<P>
   If it was a hard sell to bring him back before, it would be
virtually impossible this time. But he met a young woman whose name
was too personal to reveal, he said. This spiritual girl gave him
another outlook on tennis _ and on life itself. By the time he was
back from injury, he was ready to take on the world. Which he did,
at the US Open, and emerged successful in doubles play.
</P>
<P>
   He looks down at the tattoo once more and touches it. The symbol
was on a ring that he wore through the Open. It offered comfort and
protection. When he went into the finals of the Open, he told
himself he would have it with him permanently if he won. That
night, he celebrated the win by attending a Pearl Jam concert at
Madison Square Garden. But afterward he went home and got the
tattoo. As for the ring, he passed it along to his cousin in
Australia, who was going through some tough times herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``You play these matches and sometimes you get so involved that
it means everything,'' Stolle said. ``It is why you are happy when
you win and not so when you lose. The phoenix is a symbol that sort
of looked over me when I was going through a tough time. So when I
won, I got the tatoo.''
</P>
<P>
   The symbol of Stolle's career should be a tattoo of a roller
coaster. Tennis went from something he had to do to something he
wanted to do when he was young. His career went from the 800s to
the 100s and back again before he finally captured his first Grand
Slam. He has gone from practice partner for the Davis Cup to a team
member. A team member who will be vital to the Aussie's success.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we can win regardless of who we put on the court
because, just as far as Australian history goes, maybe we're not
the better players _ but we just have spirit when we come together
and everyone just fights for everything,'' he said. ``It's all
everyone knows to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
