<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2687 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-US-MENS-BOS &LR;      07-16 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-US-MENS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TOURNEY' POINTLESS FOR US TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JUAN _ This is and will be a tournament for second place. No
one is making any suggestions to the contrary.
</P>
<P>
   This so-called pre-Olympic qualifying tournament amounts to a
glorified, 10-game exhibition for the United States and a scrum for
everyone else. Two teams will emerge from this tournament to
qualify for the 2000 Olympics in Sydney. The US will be one and
good luck figuring out the second, although the Puerto Rican hosts
may have the edge. Why the United States has to even go through the
motions is a matter that the powers of international basketball
ought to revisit.
</P>
<P>
   At some point down the road, although it doesn't appear it will
be anytime soon, a country may emerge with a basketball program to
rival that of the United States. Yugoslavia was getting there until
politics and war got in the way. The USSR was getting there until
nationalism and perestroika got in the way. Now, there is no one.
</P>
<P>
   If that point needed to be driven home, it was done last summer
in a most roundabout way. The United States was scheduled to send
an NBA team to the world championships in Athens for what would
have been an easy gold medal and an automatic berth in Sydney. But
the lockout intervened and the players stayed away. Even still,
with a team assembled at the 11th hour and composed mostly of CBA
players, the US still almost won the gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   That they didn't meant they'd have to come here to finish the
job and officially qualify for Sydney. It's the equivalent of
sending Duke or UConn to the Indiana High School tournament. Many
NBA scouts and general managers aren't even bothering to attend,
convinced that it isn't worth the time. There's not even CBA talent
here.
</P>
<P>
   After Arnold Palmer won one of his British Opens, he suggested
to the Royal &AMP; Ancient folks that it might be a good idea if the
defending champ was treated differently and spared the rigors of
qualifying, which everyone had to do back then. The R&AMP;A considered
the matter, looked at Palmer's popularity, and said, ``sure.''
Since then, the British Open champ has been exempted.
</P>
<P>
   Why that isn't the case with the Olympics is a mystery, made
even more so by the byzantine rules governing the qualifying
process as well as the ongoing dominance of the Yanks. The host
country gets an automatic berth, but the defending Olympic champ
doesn't?
</P>
<P>
   There simply is no reason why Kevin Garnett, Tim Duncan, and the
rest of these gents should have to try and get psyched to walk over
their brethren from the Americas and earn a berth. But over the
next 10 days, Puerto Rican hoop fans (and basketball krishnas in
the US via TNT) will have the opportunity to see what amounts to
nightly ritualistic slaughters.
</P>
<P>
   Garnett summed up the tournament thusly: ``For us to lose a
game, Hurricane Hugo would have to come back.'' He's right.
</P>
<P>
   The tournament format itself is ludicrous; after four games,
only one team from each of the two groups is eliminated. And the
biggest games are the two semifinals; the winners of those games
get the two Olympic spots. You can imagine what the gold medal game
will be like with nothing on the line.
</P>
<P>
   The United States opened against Uruguay Thursday night, which
is, like everyone else here, simply hoping not to be too
embarrassed and maybe to get a shot at the qualifying games. This
was a first for Uruguay; it had not played against a US team of NBA
players in international competition. Its last Olympic meeting with
a United States team resulted in a 36-point loss in Los Angeles in
1984.
</P>
<P>
   This US team lacks the cachet and star power of the original
Dream Team (and its successors) but is still, by far, a collection
of rock idols by comparison. They came out for warmups some 40
minutes before the game began and the crowd buzz was unlike
anything before.
</P>
<P>
   The organizers must be happy they're here, although the Roberto
Clemente Coliseum has been more empty than full. Tourists at the
Westin Rio Mar Resort can tell their family and friends that they
shared poolside and tee times with some celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   But from a pure basketball standpoint, this is an exercise in
futility. The US team doesn't need to be here, shouldn't have to be
here, and maybe it's time the folks who decide these things figured
that out as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-99 1343EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
