<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV18-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRY SPONGE CLEANS FLOCKED WALLPAPER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 18, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. How can I clean flocked wallpaper?
</P>
<P>
   WORRIED OVER PAPER
</P>
<P>
   A. That's a good question, until now, because until now it was
impossible. I suppose you could wash it with detergent and water,
but that could ruin thehe flocking. And if you ever tried the
old-fashioned dough type paper cleaner, I can only have nightmares
over what it would do to the flocking.
</P>
<P>
   But as I said, until now. This is what you can try: There are
two new dry sponges on the market. One is the Gonzo Wonder Sponge
made by the Gonzo Corp. in Canton, Mass. The other is Soil &AMP; Soot
Remover, a dry sponge made by Block/New England in Worcester, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Both are sold in hardware and building supply stores, and both
are used dry. When the sponge gets dirty, wash it in detergent and
water, rinse and let dry.
</P>
<P>
   Still another is Dry Magic, a pad made to clean wallpaper. And,
if all else fails, you could soak a regular sponge in a a strong
solution of baking soda and water, squeeze it out as dry as
possible, and try that on the paper.
</P>
<P>
   As always, try these techniques on an obscure area of the paper
to make sure it doesn't adversely affect the paper. No guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I had a butcher block cutting board made. It looks great. How
can I finish it so it will stand up to wear and tear and be safe
for handling food on? Would olive oil do? Mineral oil?
</P>
<P>
   CHARLES BENEDICT, Newton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Olive oil or any other vegetable oil is not ideal because it
can get rancid. Mineral oil is a fair choice because it has a low
toxicity. Boiled linseed oil is out because it has a considerable
amount of toxicity.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockler Woodworkers Store catalog sells two finishes it
claims are safe for surfaces that come in contact with food. One is
Butcher Block Oil that the catalog says meets all FDA requirements
for surfaces that contact food. The other is Salad Bowl Finish,
claimed to be safe for food contact 72 hours after applying. Call
800-279-4441.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My basement family room is circa 1959, with 9-inch by 9-inch
tiles on the floor, probably vinyl asbestos. I would like to cover
them with 12 x 12 self-stick tiles. Can I do that? The dark brown
paneling looks pretty awful, but is still intact. How can I lighten
it up?
</P>
<P>
   LYNNE VITI, Westwood, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes, you can cover the vinyl-asbestos tiles with the
self-stick tiles. Avoid lining up seams. Get the old tile squeeky
clean first. Covered, the old tiles will be out of harm's way. In
fact, they may or may not contain enough asbestos to be a hazard.
Some tiles contain a small fraction of asbestos, and if it less
than 1 percent they are safe to remove and dispose of by you. But
covered, they are safe. They are safe as long as they are not
abraded, sanded, broken, sawn, punched, drilled or otherwise
disturbed.
</P>
<P>
   As for the paneling, whether it is plywood (real wood veneer),
solid wood, or the photographic paper-covered paneling, you can
paint it. First, sand it to reduce gloss and roughen the finish. If
it is paper, don't sand too heavily because if you do, you will
turn the paper into a fuzzy mess that is difficult to paint
properly.
</P>
<P>
   Wash with paint thinner or a strong solution of Spic and Span
and water. Again, if it is that paper stuff, don't get it too wet.
Let dry, and apply one coat of a latex enamel undercoater (also
called primer-sealer), and finish with two coats of any finish
paint you like.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The clapboards on the front of my old house were painted with
an oil primer and oil house paint. The painter caulked all the
clapboards. A year later they are peeling to the bare wood. The
sides and back of the house were treated with a primer and solid
stain, and look good after 10 years. How can I keep paint on the
front?
</P>
<P>
   B.S., Cohasset, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. The peeling was caused by moisture, and caulking the
clapboards made things worse by trapping moisture behind the
clapboards. I suggest you remove the caulking; there may be enough
space between the clapboards to let that water vapor escape before
it pushes off more paint. To allow more water vapor to escape,
insert little plastic wedges (sold in hardware and building stores)
under the clapboards to open them up a bit more; the clapboards
will remain weathertight. Scrape and sand off loose paint; then
apply a coat of latex or oil exterior primer and finish with two
coats of a solid color stain. The primer and solid stain on the
sides and back of your house are a good indication that this
technique will work.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Does a fir deck need protection? Do I have to sand before
putting on a protectant?
</P>
<P>
   ROBERT BROTHERS, Orleans, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes, it does, probably more than any other decking material.
Forget about clear sealer; it is good for only a year or two when
you have to do it all over again. Use a semitransparent house
stain; no sanding is needed if the wood is clean. Ony one coat of
stain is needed, and will last for three to five years. When it
begins to wear off, give it another coat; jut one coat.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
