<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-WOOD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO REASON TO KNOCK `WOOD' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Luther Vandross' 1985 slo-jam, ``If This World Were Mine,'' is
laid out in all its back-in-the-day glory in ``The Wood.'' The song
made a minor national dent at the time, but it's a Vandross staple
and the unofficial love theme of writer-director Rick Famuyiwa's
``Thriller''-era period piece that manages to apply a black
sensibility to the high-school high life that's been the domain of
white-male memories all year.
</P>
<P>
   Part after-school sex comedy, part wedding-blues slapstick, part
cornball friends-are-family moralization, ``The Wood'' exists as a
seldom represented American time capsule, and it's all good.
</P>
<P>
   Famuyiwa evokes an age of Members Only jackets worn by boys
debating which ``Purple Rain;; temptress they'd rather be with _
Apollonia or Vanity. The boys _ Mike, Roland and Slim (Sean Nelson,
Duane Finley and Trent Cameron) _ are insta-homies, looking like a
trio of New Edition castaways trying to get sex education in the
pre-hip-hop Inglewood neighborhood for which the film is named.
</P>
<P>
   But to get to the movie's schoolyard nostalgia, teen-age sexual
ripening and Eric B. 'n' Rakim and Mtume on the soundtrack, ``The
Wood'' has to hang with Mike, Roland and Slim as grown men, one of
whom is on the verge of a trite pre-matrimonial breakdown. Roland
(Taye Diggs) says he doesn't want to spend the rest of his life
wondering ``what if'' he married the wrong girl. (Shhh, but Ro's
bride is played by Lisaraye, the bloodthirsty stripper from Ice
Cube's ``Player's Club.'' He may have a point.)
</P>
<P>
   Roland's nervousness, which leads to his drunken stupor _ that's
how Mike (Omar Epps) and Slim (Richard T. Jones) find him _ is
nothing more than an excuse for Diggs to demonstrate that he's one
of the few legitimately charismatic guys waiting for a
breakthrough. But like the boys from ``American Pie,'' and the
young men from ``Cooley High'' and ``Diner,'' these are friends
whose fear of commitment is a mutation of their being afraid to be
without each other, as Roland confesses. Their familiar, fluffy
brotherly love gives way to the more original mid-'80s flashbacks
that really deserve a movie of their own.
</P>
<P>
   That's where Famuyiwa unleashes his flair for crafting engaging
situations from hysterical passages in his own adolescent memories.
A run-by booty-pinch is played as life-or-death bullfight; a high
school becomes an urban soap opera of scheming and scoping with
more bubbles and less froth than its colorless counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   And Nelson (``Fresh'') as the teen-age Mike is all charm and so
thankfully low key that he makes Epps' take on the adult character
look studied. Nelson's especially good in his scenes with
take-no-mess Malinda Williams as the fuming victim of that butt-tap
who sics her gangsta brother, Stacy, on him. Stacy bloodies his
nose, then blesses Mike's crush on his sister by telling him that
Vandross treasure will be their song. As played by De'Aundre Bonds,
he's ``The Wood's'' revelation: a throwaway stereotype given
``Godfather''-ly weight that's as juicy as his Jheri curl.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wesley Morris is a film critic for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic mail address
is morris(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
