<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVIS-DYNASTY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
'50S-'60S WERE THE AUSTRALIAN DYNASTY DECADES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ It didn't matter who was playing. Sedgman or
McGregor, Hoadie or Muscles, Cooper or Anderson, Fraser or Rocket,
Emmo or Fiery, Rochie or Newk. For nearly two decades, whenever
Australia's tennis team took to the courts (usually against the
bloody Yanks), the Aussies could take the Davis Cup to the bank.
Or, rather, leave it there, in the Melbourne vault where they
stashed it for safekeeping between defenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the mid-'60s, it became a bit expectant,'' remembers John
Newcombe, who played on four Cup winners and is captaining
Australia in this weekend's quarterfinal with the United States at
Longwood Cricket Club in Brookline. ``Now, if we were to get
through to the final, it would be huge. Then it was, well, that's
what we're supposed to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Between 1950 and 1967, when Australia won the Cup a monopolistic
15 times, losing the Cup was like missing Christmas. In fact,
playing for the Cup was a Christmas tradition during the Challenge
Round era, when the champion needed only face the survivor from the
rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world has changed,'' says Rod Laver, who played on four
straight Cup winners from 1959-62. ``We always waited for a
challenger. We weren't obligated to spend any time getting to
ties.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless they'd lost the Cup, which they did (by 3-2 scores to the
US) in 1954, 1958, and 1963, the Aussies were always holding court
in (their) high summer in Kooyong Stadium in Melbourne or White
City Stadium in Sydney or Memorial Drive in Adelaide against some
poor blokes (usually the Yanks) who'd come halfway around the world
by propeller plane.
</P>
<P>
   And whenever they lost the Cup, the Aussies went to Forest Hills
or Cleveland the next year and grabbed it back. Their
sneaker-footed dynasty survived everything but the Yankee dollar
that siphoned off the Oz varsity to the pro ranks in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   But during tennis's postwar ``shamateur'' days, when only
nonpros were eligible to knock about for Dwight Davis's ornate
punch bowl, Australia ruled with captain Harry Hopman's homegrown,
handpicked stable of thoroughbreds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were probably ahead of the rest of the world at the time,''
says Newcombe. ``We hadn't had war on our territory; we had tennis
courts all over the place. And the sport attracted our best
athletes.''
</P>
<P>
   Hopman, the iron-handed sportswriter and former Cupper himself,
knew every one of them from Victoria to W.A. It was Hopman who
brought Australia back to glory after the US had hammered the
Aussies four straight times from 1946-49. It was Hopman who scouted
out the talent, kept the pipeline flowing, chose who got to compete
overseas, and picked the Cup team. ``We had selectors,'' Laver
says, ``but Hopman almost always told the selectors what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Aussies went to Forest Hills in 1950 and ripped the
Cup away from the Yanks with Frank Sedgman and Ken McGregor, nobody
was going to argue with Hopman or his methods. It didn't matter
whose names Hopman put into the draw _ Sedgman and McGregor,
teenagers Lew Hoad and Ken Rosewall, Ashley Cooper and Mal
Anderson, Neale Fraser and Rod Laver, Roy Emerson and Fred Stolle.
The dynasty kept rolling. ``Hopman was grooming players all the way
along,'' Laver says.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody was as deep as the Aussies. Nobody was as fit. Nobody was
as hungry. Nobody was as competitively honed. ``The whole year was
just to set the wheel in motion to get your two singles players for
Davis Cup,'' Laver recalls. And nobody had more esprit de corps,
forged by years of traveling together thousands of miles away from
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you went overseas, you were away for seven months and you
never came home,'' Newcombe says. ``That was one of the reasons why
we had that team spirit, the all-for-one-and-one-for-all feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Prima donnas and attitude cases were kept home. It was an honor
to play for Australia, whenever the call might come. ``Nobody was
jumping up and down, saying, `My turn, I should play,' '' says
Laver, who waited three years for his Cup debut. ``The feeling was,
Australia's got to win the Davis Cup. So Australia had to come
above the individual.''
</P>
<P>
   Down Under, the Cup was sporting's Holy Grail. Matches were
televised and broadcast on radio, and the stands were jammed for
the Challenge Rounds against the Yanks. ``I remember when I was 10
years old in 1954, sitting in White City Stadium with my Dad and
dreaming about playing,'' says Newcombe.
</P>
<P>
   Hopman already knew about him. By 16, Newcombe was going
overseas. At 19, he found himself in the lineup for the 1963
matchup with the US in Adelaide. ``I was sort of the nobody thrown
in against Dennis Ralston and Chuck McKinley,'' Newcombe says.
``And even though I lost both my matches, I was a national hero
because I'd put up a good fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Only two men got to play Cup singles for Australia. If that was
a burden, it was also a privilege. ``You wanted it,'' says
Newcombe. ``There was pressure, but you were seeking it.''
</P>
<P>
   There was always someone stepping in when the top men turned
pro, always someone to keep the fire stoked, always a couple of
teenaged acolytes brought along as sparring partners so they could
learn what had kept the country Down Under on top. ``You hang
around champions, you start thinking like a champion,'' says
Newcombe.
</P>
<P>
   But when the dynasty ended, it ended abruptly, halted by the
advent of open tennis and lucrative professional options. ``Nobody
realized it then, but that was definitely what happened,'' says
Newcombe.
</P>
<P>
   The last hurrah came in 1967 at Brisbane, where Australia rubbed
out Spain for its fourth straight Cup. Soon after, Newcombe and
Roche signed as contract pros with World Championship Tennis and
Emerson joined Laver, Rosewall, and Stolle in the National Tennis
League.
</P>
<P>
   The Yanks, on a ``quest'' with rising stars Arthur Ashe, Clark
Graebner, Stan Smith, and Bob Lutz, came to Adelaide a year later,
buried the Aussie second string, 4-1, and took the Cup home, where
it remained for five years. In 1969, Australia lost the opener to
Mexico and missed the final for the first time in 32 years. The
chain had been broken.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new guys had never traveled in a team with us, so they
never got the opportunity to learn what we'd learned,'' says
Newcombe. ``All of a sudden they were playing for Australia, and
they weren't ready.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was open tennis, the rise of the Association of Tennis
Professionals, and the abolition of the silly rule banning contract
pros from Cup play that eventually brought the Aussies back to
glory.
</P>
<P>
   With everyone eligible for 1973, the call went out to the
38-year-old Rosewall (who hadn't played for the Cup in 16 years),
the 38-year-old Anderson, the 35-year-old Laver, and the
27-year-old Newcombe. ``We were the Geritol squad,'' laughs Laver.
</P>
<P>
   But the ``Antique Show'' ripped through everybody that year, and
Newcombe and Laver blanked the Yanks, 5-0, in Cleveland to bring
the punch bowl back home.
</P>
<P>
   The only man missing was Hopman, who had left for the States a
few years earlier to start his own tennis academy on Long Island _
and groom a future Cup titan named McEnroe.
</P>
</TEXT>
