<HEADLINE>
WHEN THE PIE GETS DIVVIED UP, BAY STATE GETS A RAW DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On one hand, this is only an argument about 11 cents. On the
other hand, it's the story of how taxpayers in Massachusetts get
shortchanged about $4 billion a year by the Sun Belt commandos who
have captured Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Because if you pay taxes in the Commonwealth, for every dollar
you send to Washington, you get back the equivalent of 92 cents.
That was the number two years ago, the latest available. But the
number at the start of this decade was $1.03.
</P>
<P>
   So who clipped us for the 11 cents? The short answer is Uncle
Sam. The long answer is the congressional system of apportioning
federal largesse via the committee structure. But the really long
answer is the relentless drift of the political center of gravity
south and west, further from the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Northeast states tend to have higher incomes, pay
more in taxes, have higher housing and energy costs, grow less
food, and house fewer military installations, we don't get as much
back as we send to the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   The folks at MassINC, the new nonpartisan think tank that
publishes the CommonWealth quarterly, and the Heinz Foundation,
commissioned an aptly named number-cruncher named Andrew Sum of the
Center for Labor Market Studies to examine the economic entrails.
``Massachusetts gets a raw deal,'' is one headline over the sum of
Sum's conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   Last time I checked, the mythical population center of the
United States was somewhere west of Kansas City and trending
southwestward. Eight of the top 10 Republicans in leadership
positions in the US House and Senate are Southerners or Westerners.
Of the serious candidates for president, most are from Southern,
Western or border states.
</P>
<P>
   What this means is that when that great big pie gets divvied up
in D.C., the guys with the tall hats, cowboy boots, and drawls get
more and more, and we get less and less. Senate majority leader
Trent Lott's Mississippi got back $1.59 in federal dough for every
buck sent.
</P>
<P>
   But one intriguing wrinkle uncovered by the MassINC study is
that the federal formulas used to distribute poverty-fighting money
discriminate against the Northeast. Why? Congressional formulas
don't factor in the high cost of living here, half of it
attributable to costly housing.
</P>
<P>
   What follows is no bulletin to recent arrivals in Beantown: It
costs between 14 and 17 percent more to live in Massachusetts
generally than in the rest of the United States, and if you move to
Boston or the immediate suburbs, it's upwards of 30 percent because
of the housing shortage and high rents.
</P>
<P>
   But Uncle Sam calculates simply that if you live in, say,
Mississippi, it costs you the same as if you live in Boston. No
way. The Bay State per capita income falls from 4th-highest to only
22d-highest among the states when these extra costs of housing (50
percent of the surcharge) and higher taxes (25 percent of the extra
hit) are figured in.
</P>
<P>
   If Congress would only adjust poverty grants to the states by
factoring in the higher rents charged in the Northeast, argues
MassINC's policy director, Mike Gritton, we would get a tremendous
jolt of new housing and education money that would help reduce the
shortfall between what we are taxed and what we get back.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1997 sweepstakes, New Mexico taxpayers got back $1.90 for
every buck they chipped in. Do you think that might have something
to do with the fact that Senator Pete Domenici runs the Senate
Budget Committee? West Virginia got back $1.62. Think Senator Bobby
Byrd, the former Senate leader, had anything to do with that?
Arkansas got $1.32. That's four bucks back for every three they
send in. Think having a president for two terms helped? While our
wedge of pie gets skinnier, every Southern and Rocky Mountain state
got a fatter slab. With the passing of the speakership of Tip
O'Neill and the glacial shift of clout to the Sun Belt, our elbow
room at the trough has been considerably diminished.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans hereabouts argue that if we didn't have an
all-Democratic congressional delegation, we might get a few more
crumbs from the federal Treasury. Of course, if the GOP managed to
elect more than one state legislator out of every five or six, they
might have more luck in running for federal office.
</P>
<P>
   Of more substance to Gritton and the number-crunchers are the
trends of the past decade: ``The substantive ones are defense cuts,
cuts in research and development money, and Medicare and Medicaid
cuts over the past six to eight years,'' which slammed Bay State
outfits like Raytheon, Mass. General, the medical schools, etc.
``All that worked to our detriment, not to our benefit.'' While we
got more than our share of transportation dough over the years for
the Big Dig, overall we are getting sliced-and-diced on the poverty
handouts because of our high housing and tax burdens. Yo, Trent: I
want my 11 cents back.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
