<HEADLINE>
SAY GOODNIGHT, HENRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One wonders, idly, if WGBH operated in the Real World, whether
station boss Henry Becton would still be employed. In recent
memory, Becton has chalked up an impressive array of gaffes:
</P>
<P>
   _ He gutted the ``Ten O'Clock News,'' the only decent
non-commercial newscast in the city. 'GBH's local news
``commitment'' was transfered to ``The Group,'' a well-meaning
flop. Emily Rooney is gradually finding her footing on her
still-uneven public affairs show, ``Greater Boston.'' But let's
face it, she's no Chris Lydon. Say what you will about my effete
friend Chris, he's the Babe Ruth of Boston public broadcasting, and
Becton lost him to crosstown rival WBUR.
</P>
<P>
   _ 'GBH shut down Ron Della Chiesa's popular ``MusicAmerica''
radio show to take a flyer co-producing ``The World'' with the BBC.
The Anglo-phony allure is all but irresistible at 'GBH, e.g.,
``Masterpiece Theatre,'' but ``The World'' remains as goofy and
irrelevant as ever.
</P>
<P>
   _ Becton personally oversaw the debacle of the Margret Rey will.
Even though he was warned about the potential negative fallout that
might arise from contesting a dying woman's request to re-direct a
portion of her $8 million legacy to religious charities, Becton
battled Rey's legatees for her money. After the inevitable PR
Waterloo, 'GBH accepted a compromise solution that had been
available before the negative publicity.
</P>
<P>
   None of this really matters. As the nabobs of Boston's major
nonprofits _ Neil Rudenstine of Harvard, Malcolm Rogers of the
Museum of Fine Arts, Nick Zervas at the Boston Symphony Orchestra _
know, the small stuff doesn't count. Rudenstine abdicates the
traditional leadership role of the university president; Rogers
fires a couple of curators and tees off the Beacon Hill lockjaws;
the BSO gets into a tangle at Tanglewood. Nothing matters as long
as the money keeps rolling in.
</P>
<P>
   But now 'GBH has touched the third rail of public broadcasting.
By sharing its mailing lists with the Democratic Party, and then
dissembling the extent of the station's involvement, it has
jeopardized not only its own funding but the congressional
appropriation for public radio and television stations across the
country. It's hardly surprising to find 'GBH in bed with its
ideological soulmates in the Democratic Party. But to play footsie
with the Democrats when Republican Party chairmen hold the purse
strings for millions of dollars of badly needed subsidies _ that's
just plain stupid.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's time for new judgment at the top.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
BU's Loss, BC's Gain
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, someone put the question to Boston University
president Jon Westling: BU houses many a prominent conservative
intellectual; Does it have any great thinkers on the left? Westling
demurred, and finally blurted out: ``Alan Wolfe!''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe, a renowned social scientist and author of ``One Nation
After All,'' is hardly a man of the left, but at BU these terms are
relative. And, as of two months ago, he's no longer at BU. With
some fanfare, Boston College persuaded him to change zip codes and
take charge of its newly created Center for Religion and American
Public Life.
</P>
<P>
   As is often the case at BU, there were ``circumstances''
surrounding his departure. Wolfe ran into trouble when he assumed
the chairmanship of BU's fractious sociology department. He clashed
not only with his predecessor, the wife of prominent conservative
Peter Berger, but also with the left-wing relics still haunting the
corridors. Says Wolfe of his adversaries: ``There's nothing more
conservative than a left-wing sociology department.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe managed to rally the department around a faculty
appointment that was important to him, only to see it shot down by
Westling, who deemed Wolfe's candidate to be unqualified. After the
turndown, Wolfe says, ``I felt my position was pretty
uncomfortable. I made enemies in the process.'' Wolfe asked to
resign his position in the sociology department (he also had a
political science appointment), and ``there was no effort to make
me stay.''
</P>
<P>
   So who does Westling have left, so to speak?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
