<HEADLINE>
EXPLORING THE MYTH OF THE `ECOLOGICAL INDIAN' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE ECOLOGICAL INDIAN 
Myth and History 
By Shepard Krech III 
Norton, 352 pp., $27.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The hostile reaction of West Coast environmentalists to this
spring's whale hunt by members of the Makah tribe _ an event
memorialized by the televised harpooning and shooting of a gray
whale _ illustrates the conflict between the myth and the reality
of ``the ecological Indian.''
</P>
<P>
   Shephard Krech III, a professor of anthropology at Brown
University, says his carefully argued _ and thoroughly fascinating
_ study was meant ``to determine the extent to which Indians were
ecologists and conservationists (as is commonly understood
today).'' The evidence Krech marshals suggests that _ much like
present-day Americans, native or not _ they were ecologists when it
suited their needs and despoilers when it did not.
</P>
<P>
   One issue that concerns Krech is whether the Indians were so
exploited by European traders that they hunted animals such as deer
and beaver close to extinction in order to supply skins to trade
for European goods. The figures for the Southern trade in deerskins
are astounding: In the 1750s, some 175,000 skins were being
exported yearly from Charleston and 150,000 from Savannah.
</P>
<P>
   The ``conventional wisdom,'' Krech notes, is ``that Europeans
alone understood the true value of merchandise and pelts, and that
Indians, the `natural' residents, neither understood nor
profited.'' The problem with that, he writes, is that Indians
``leapt at the chance to exchange what was mundane and common (furs
and skins) for what was not (goods of new technological and
symbolic value).'' There are numerous accounts of Indians greeting
Europeans as they came ashore ``by waving pelts in their hands,
signaling unambiguously . . . their keenness to obtain the rare and
useful objects the Europeans possessed.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, as in their use of fire, the Indians were both
ecologists and despoilers. They burned ``often and for myriad
ends,'' Krech writes. Most often they set fires ``to improve
subsistence'' by clearing land for cultivation. Indeed, ``so
important was fire in the maintenance of grasslands that after
Indians died from disease or abandoned them, these clearings
quickly reverted to forest.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Indians also used fire to make it easier to travel
through forested areas and to assist in hunting of large animals.
One contemporary account cited by Krech reported that the Sioux
would encircle a herd of buffalo and then, after setting the grass
on fire to press the herd into the shrinking circle of fire, ``the
Indians, rushing in with their arrows and musketry, slaughter
immense numbers in a short period.''
</P>
<P>
   And also, ``as men and women of European descent soon
discovered, many Indians unhesitatingly used fire as an offensive
and defensive weapon,'' setting fires upwind of traders and
trappers to drive them into a waiting ambush.
</P>
<P>
   While it is not fully certain that the Indians understood ``the
ecological consequences of fire,'' what is clear to Krech is that
``by the time the Europeans arrived, North America was a
manipulated continent.'' It was not the seemingly virgin
wilderness, the ``Eden'' that so amazed early colonists, for ``the
Indians had long since altered the landscape by burning or clearing
woodland for farming and fuel.''
</P>
<P>
   So how, Krech asks, could America ``be simultaneously a paradise
seemingly untouched by human hands,'' yet inhabited by people who
had ``exploited lands and animals in order to live''?
</P>
<P>
   Krech suggests that this seeming Eden ``resulted both from
aboriginal demography and _ darkened by epidemic disease and death
_ from post-European epidemiology. In the first case, population
growth overstressed natural resources, prompting the region's
Indians to abandon the depleated territory and move elsewhere. In
the second, entire communities fell victim to smallpox and other
infectious diseases.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians, Krech writes, ``were fully capable of
transformative action in ecosystems they knew intimately,'' but
their populations were too small and too widely dispersed ``to have
made much of a difference.'' And when they became even fewer as a
result of disease, ``the lands they had burned, cleared and
planted'' _ whether for agriculture, for hunting or for warfare _
``rested and recovered'' in relatively short order, in time to
appear as an Eden to early Europeans.
</P>
<P>
   ``This paradise, this Eden,'' Krech writes, ``was mainly an
artifact of demography and epidemiology.'' And the actions of
Native Americans, whether they were ecologists or despoilers, may
not have been as important as the myth, which has flourished as
richly as the land itself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
