<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-BLAIR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HORROR FILM BLURS LINE BETWEEN DOCUMENTARY, MAKE-BELIEVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're looking for the telltale sign that ``The Blair Witch
Project'' is no-joke terrifying, you need look no further than the
shrieking kid trying with all his 2-year-old might to cover his
mother's mouth as she tells an amateur film crew about the myth of
the Blair Witch.
</P>
<P>
   His mother tries to dismiss the horror that breaks over her
son's face, but she's talking about the hirsute lady nymph who
snatches children and then kills them. You can tell that the boy
might wet himself if she doesn't shut up.
</P>
<P>
   That moment comes minutes into Daniel Myrick and Eduardo
Sanchez's unsettling sylvan nightmare about three filmmakers who
trek to the Maryland woods to shoot a documentary about the title
figure. It's a trip from which they never returned.
</P>
<P>
   The footage has been assembled from a camcorder and the stock
from a 16-mm camera into what we see as ``The Blair Witch
Project,'' and if you watch the film under the assumption that the
makers have ``disappeared,'' the effect of blurring the distinction
between documented terror and the kind you conjure is as
organically creepy as anything you've seen.
</P>
<P>
   The deceptive technical artifice basically boils down to the
film's three actors (Heather Donahue, Michael C. Williams, Joshua
Leonard) making a film that turns out to be the very film you're
watching about the film they were making.
</P>
<P>
   They're brought together by Heather, a terribly poised,
twentysomething folklorist, whom you'd suspect of incredibly
romanticized (and ironic) notions about trading her life for her
art.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to make her into verite-girl and allowing her and
her partners Josh and Mike to film every minute of their trip is an
obvious gimmick. But we become disarmed as the trio hikes farther
away from ever getting out of the woods.
</P>
<P>
   At some point, all they have is their two cameras and the
increasing, tacit reliance upon an audience of witnesses to share
their horror as it's clear that something doesn't want them in its
forest.
</P>
<P>
   By the second night of camping, their tent is flanked by
cracking noises, and one morning three piles of rocks are left in
an equilateral triangle around their site.
</P>
<P>
   Staying lost another day means having to pitch a tent for
another night, a dreadful matter of fact that becomes more
frightening as their fear and revulsion of the woods has them
swapping common sense for insanity.
</P>
<P>
   Crucial to the film's eeriness is the use of natural sound.
</P>
<P>
   We're desperately listening inside that tent for those kiddie
yelps and the crescendo of broken branches and crushed leaves with
the same freaked-out paranoia as Heather, Josh and Mike.
</P>
<P>
   The forest has always been an anti-Walden dystopia for horror,
from the ``Deliverance'' rapists to goalie-masked summer-camp
psycho Jason. But ``Blair Witch'' forgoes a literal bogeyman in
favor of the unseen, which, in this case, is as scarily
bone-chilling as anything they could show you.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wesley Morris is a film critic for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic mail address
is morris(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
