<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAKED-CITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NAKED CITY, NEW YORK IS NOT: AT LEAST THIS JUDGE SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Naked bodies in the street don't exactly fit this
city's image just now.
</P>
<P>
   So when Spencer Tunic applied for a permit to photograph 75
people lying naked in a street in downtown Manhattan, it came as no
surprise when the city turned him down.
</P>
<P>
   But Tunic and his lawyer, Ron Kuby, made a clever move _ so
clever, it looks as though a federal judge is about to rule in
their favor.
</P>
<P>
   Before applying for the permit for the naked shoot, they asked
permission to shoot 75 clothed models at the same site, same time _
which, by the way, is 5:30 Sunday morning. The city assented.
</P>
<P>
   Then, when the ``No way'' came back on the request to shoot the
models naked, Kuby appealed on free speech principles. ``This is a
content-based restriction,'' Kuby argued Thursday before federal
Judge Harold Baer Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Blocking traffic or disturbing the peace _ the city had no
problems on these grounds when the models were going to be clothed.
The only issue is that now they would be naked.
</P>
<P>
   New York State has laws against public exposure, but there is a
clause exempting art and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might think it strange,'' Kuby told the judge. ``I find it
strange. I said to myself, `There's got to be a law against this.'
'' But New York City never passed such a law. ``They could have,''
Kuby said, ``but they didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Tunic has made a name in artistic circles for taking pictures of
naked people _ stark, haunting shots that contrast, as Kuby put it,
``the vulnerability of the human body and the anonymity of public
space.'' He photographed 28 naked people on the steps of the Boston
Public Library at dawn two years ago with no particular incident.
</P>
<P>
   But Mayor Rudolph Giuliani _ who has taken great strides to shut
down porn shops and strip joints _ seems to see red when Tunic
takes out his camera in his town.
</P>
<P>
   New York City police have arrested Tunic or his models four
times. In all cases, the charges have been dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   The first time happened in 1995, when he photographed a nude
model on an 8-foot-tall Christmas ornament in Rockefeller Center.
The second took place in the stormy winter of 1996 when he shot a
naked woman lying on a snowbank under a sign that read ``Frozen
Fantasies.'' Last year, he was arrested in Central Park for taking
pictures without a permit.
</P>
<P>
   Most famously, in April, Tunic was handcuffed and dragged away
after getting 175 people to lie down naked in the middle of Times
Square at 6 one Sunday morning _ before he could manage to take the
picture (though photographers for the daily newspapers snapped
dozens of shots).
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a dozen police officers were waiting for Tunic at a
photo shoot and warned that they would arrest anyone who disrobed.
He called the gig off.
</P>
<P>
   Kuby said that unless the judge intervened in this case, Tunic's
shoot Sunday morning would be similarly preempted _ and, thus, his
First Amendment rights denied.
</P>
<P>
   The city's lawyer, Sherrill Kurland, argued that this was a case
of ``common sense,'' but Baer wasn't buying it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he has a constitutional right, that may override that
objection,'' Baer said. ``That's what it's all about, isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   Kurland then switched tactics, only to end up in another corner.
The real issue, she said, was that Tunic wanted to shoot on a
``densely residential'' street. People _ children _ could randomly
look out their windows and see naked bodies. People object to this
sort of thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you taken a poll?'' Baer asked.
</P>
<P>
   No, she replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you talked at all about trying to find a more appropriate
location?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   No, she said, but added, ``We would entertain that discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   Baer called the lawyers to his chambers. Kuby called the city's
bluff, offering to move the shoot to an emptier block.
</P>
<P>
   Kurland and her four associates went to make a phone call. They
were gone 15 minutes. When they came back, as Kuby described it
afterward, she said, ``We need more time'' _ till 10a.m. Friday _
to consider ``alternatives.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Alternative sites?'' Baer asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alternatives,'' Kurland said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless I hear from you by noon,'' Baer said, ``I'll issue a
decision, probably one you will not like.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
