<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MELODY MAKERS LISTEN TO THE `SPIRIT' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ziggy Marley and the Melody Makers _ all children of the late
reggae king Bob Marley _ have toiled in their father's shadow for
years. They've been praised or criticized in reference to that
shadow, but on their new album, they step daringly into a new
light.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really opened the door on this one,'' Ziggy says of the new
``Spirit of Music,'' a surprising, singer-songwriter-slanted disc
coproduced by Don Was, who has worked with the Rolling Stones and
Bonnie Raitt.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of reggae textures, or the slickly produced, urban
crossover sound that the Melody Makers have tried in previous
outings, the new disc is a marvel of spare, acoustic-based tunes,
cut with a touch of the blues and with fresh philosophical insights
from Ziggy, now 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``The record is based on just me on the acoustic guitar, with
everything else complementing that,'' says Ziggy. Expect a lot of
these new, more meditative songs, as opposed to the party reggae
typically featured by the Melody Makers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to let the physical side take a break right now. I want
to go to the spiritual side,'' says Ziggy. ``I want to head in that
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   The new album, which was glowingly reviewed in Time this week,
was an outgrowth of a meeting with Was in Miami. Was listened to
Ziggy play new songs on acoustic guitar _ and suggested that should
be the approach to the record.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to keep the essence of the songs, so we added very
little in the studio,'' says Ziggy, who also broke away from the
band's familiar reggae studio musicians (``some of them were upset
with me'') to use players new to him, such as drummer Jim Keltner
(who has played with John Lennon and Roy Orbison) and bassist Hutch
Hutchinson, from Raitt's band.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome is magical on such tracks as the
country-blues-steeped ``Keep the Faith,'' the jazzy ``13 Months,''
and the pensive ``Many Waters,'' with Ziggy singing, ``Love is
stronger than death.'' His brother, Steven, adds two cover songs by
their father (including the rootsy reggae of ``You Got My Love All
Night Long''), but the main thrust is Ziggy's exploration of
quieter, more introspective, but no less compelling, sound
textures.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, there is not enough creativity (in the current reggae
scene),'' says Ziggy. ``We need to move to another level of the
music. That's what we tried to do.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sevendust at Vans Warped: The Vans Warped tour is unlike any
other summer rock tour. In a democratic gesture, the bands flip
coins each morning to determine the order of the day's acts. Thus,
a different band usually ``closes'' the festival each day (the word
``headlines'' is not used on this tour). Ideally, that keeps both
bands and fans sharp, eliminating the complacency that can set in
at the more rigidly scheduled fests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it. This is my favorite tour of anything we've done,''
says Sevendust drummer Morgan Rose, whose group was on Ozzfest last
year. ``At Ozzfest, we played at the same time every day, but there
were a lot of empty seats. On this tour, the kids get there early
because they don't want to miss their favorite band. It's cool,
because we usually go on about 3 or 3:30 before the kids are too
beaten up by the other bands. Hey, it's non-stop carnage out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The tour is really diverse this year,'' says Rose. ``It's not
totally punk-driven like it used to be. The bands go from hard
rock, like us, to rock 'n' roll and hip-hop. There are more sides
of the spectrum.''
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based Sevendust will have a new album out in August
(``Home'') that was recorded at Longview Farm Studio in Carlisle,
Mass. ``It's a little bit darker than our last one, a little bit
heavier,'' says Rose. ``And we did more with electronics, but it's
still aggressive rock.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bits and Pieces: The average rock concert ticket costs $38.46 _
up $5 since last year and $13 since 1996, according to a suvey by
Pollstar.
</P>
</TEXT>
