<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-EYES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO LUST FOR LIFE IN `EYES' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
EYES WIDE SHUT 
Directed by: Stanley Kubrick 
Screenplay by: Kubrick and Frederic Raphael, based on Arthur
Schnitzler's ``Traumnovelle'' 
Starring: Tom Cruise, Nicole Kidman, Sydney Pollack, Marie
Richardson, Todd Field, Julienne Davis, Thomas Gibson, Leelee
Sobieski, Vinessa Shaw, Rade Sherbedgia, Sky Dumont 
Running time: 159 minutes 
Rated: R (strong sexual content, nudity, language, and some
drug-related material) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It would be gratifying to report that ``Eyes Wide Shut'' finds
the late Stanley Kubrick going out on top. But no. Although the
year's most eagerly anticipated film is ambitious as few films are,
it falls conspicuously short in realizing those ambitions.
Sometimes laughably short. It's a movie about sex made by _ and, I
suspect, for _ people who are afraid of sex. It at least answers
the question of why Tom Cruise and Nicole Kidman were cast, apart
from their box-office potential. They have what it takes to embody
an uptight and almost lethally naive married couple who allow their
dissatisfactions to nudge them into dangerous waters. In the case
of Cruise's upscale doc, this takes the form of sidling into an
orgy after his ego takes a buffeting. With Kidman's onscreen wife,
it takes the form of following her mind into a dream of illicit sex
hooked to a fleeting encounter and a degree of desire long absent
in her marriage.
</P>
<P>
   But because it is a movie about the least controllable of human
impulses made by the most controlling of directors, what should be
its tensions are stifled by its central contradiction. It's a too
obviously calculated and schematic chess game, too deadly earnest
to permit what could otherwise have been the humor in its moves to
save it from seeming stillborn. ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' especially in
what minimal degrees of taste forbid me from describing as its
climactic orgy scene, has the sexual energy of a dead battery.
There's a lot of smoke and mirrors in it, especially mirrors. The
scene of the doc fondling his nude wife, the one that has generated
so much hoopla via the film's trailers, is seen in a mirror in a
film that's launched on a series of nude images of Kidman.
</P>
<P>
   The film's chilliness is just right for the rich man's party
scene that follows, in which Kidman plays out a corny seduction
scene with a stock Hungarian lothario who seems a parody of the
Zoltan Karpathy stereotype of ``My Fair Lady,'' the one who, in the
peevish words of Professor Henry Higgins, oiled his way around the
floor. He never does have his way with her in the sculpture
gallery, although his attentions arouse her husband's ire. Her
displeasure, meanwhile, is ignited when she can't account for his
whereabouts after seeing him with a couple of models. In fact, he
has been hurriedly called upstairs by his host, Sydney Pollack's
evil ringmaster, to help out with a woman who has overdosed on
drugs after he had sex with her.
</P>
<P>
   Its big thematic link isn't between its stars and obsessive sex,
but between sex and death, especially death from a man's point of
view in which a woman is punished for sexual promiscuity. Time and
again, images of sex are shoved up against images of death,
including cadavers. Perhaps shaping the role to match Cruise's
narrow expressive range, Kubrick has written the doc as clenched
and intense, also dim, opaque, lacking in self-awareness, shaky in
self-esteem. After he's excited by an unconsummated advance made by
the daughter of a patient lying dead in the background, he slides
into the night and another interrupted sexual interlude with a
prostitute. A few chance encounters and a $74 cab ride into Long
Island later, he's at the orgy in cape and mask.
</P>
<P>
   Soon afterward, he's in danger as it is realized he's not one of
the regulars. The real problem, though, is the orgy. It's not
mind-blowing, it's mind-numbing, heavy, deadly earnest. The
energies that fill the screen are leaden and studied, devoid of
anything suggesting real abandon. This is not a good thing in a
film based on a literary work by a Freudian womanizer arguing that
sex can be liberating. Once the film arrives at the orgy with
Cruise, it stops being Schnitzler and begins playing like Hogarth's
``The Rake's Progress,'' drops from a level of dreamlike
stylization to something more ordinary. Far from depicting lustful
uproar, it sinks into a panorama of jadedness, of people ashamed to
show their faces, trying to flog themselves into sexual arousal.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the doc returns home to discover that his wife may have
outdone him without having left her bed. Only when her character
speaks with a fierce sexual candor does Kidman come fully to life.
Otherwise, she seems either to be sleepwalking through her role or
embarrassingly brittle in her coyness. The only thing that keeps
``Eyes Wide Shut'' from seeming a dispiriting exchange of
Schnitzler's rueful world-weariness for the cautionary
antisexuality of the Age of AIDS is the hint, however
conventionally teasing, of ominous mystery in the aftermath of the
orgy. When the doc's detective work into the dire fates of a few of
the orgy's attendees attracts some threatening attentions, the
energy level momentarily quickens, only to yield to another cloud
of smoke when the doc finds himself again confronting Pollock's
slimy Mr. Big.
</P>
<P>
   It can at least be said that ``Eyes Wide Shut'' isn't boring,
even though Cruise never makes it to the dark side. And Kubrick's
sense of humor remains slyly intact. Also, his often opulent
visuals remind us that he was one of film's great stylists. He
flaunts the film's studio artifice in the Greenwich Village street
scenes. And he piquantly invites the speculation that the gated
estate where the orgy takes place, if not actually his own gated
English estate, evokes it in its seclusion and security
consciousness. But there's that word, security. That's what's wrong
here. There's too much of a feel of security consciousness in a
film that's supposed to be about the essential irreconcilability of
security and sex.
</P>
<P>
   Kidman's character comes closest to Schnitzler when she tells
her hubby to not use the word forever. When Cruise's character
narrows his eyes and tells us, with a would-be force of revelation,
that a dream is more than just a dream, he embodies what's wrong
with the film, namely its emptiness, its post-Freudian datedness,
its failure to regenerate the angst of fin de siecle Vienna in fin
de siecle Manhattan a century later. Bizarre as it sometimes is on
the surface, the problem with ``Eyes Wide Shut'' isn't that it's
wild, but that it's devitalized. In ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' Eros
doesn't stand a chance against Thanatos. If the Grim Reaper threw
an orgy, this is what it would play like.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
