<HEADER>
A2717 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-CHER-BOS &LR;      07-16 1229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-CHER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR CHER, THE BEAT GOES ON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cher knows what it means to ride rock 'n' roll's wild
rollercoaster. Over the years, she has zoomed to the top and
plummeted to the bottom, but she's philosophical about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had my choice of the two places, the top is better. But,
for me, it doesn't change who I am,'' she says, speaking from a
tour bus earlier this week. ``It doesn't change my position in the
community. The people that I am friends with don't care too much
about that kind of stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently that rollercoaster is at a peak _ what with the
phenomenal success of ``Believe'' (a single and CD), a tour, and
the acting accolades she's won for the recent film, ``Tea With
Mussolini,'' in which she plays a rich American singer living in
Italy on the verge of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Cher admits she's feeling the cool breeze of fame in her face
again, while viewing it with a certain detachment. Cher knows fame
is transitory _ ``We all have what's in front of us at the moment,
what is making the biggest noise'' _ but she knows she occupies
this unique niche in stardom's pyramid. ``It's not like the old
days when people went on forever,'' she says of stardom. ``I think
I'm old-fashioned in that way. I mean I have a foot in the past,
and a foot in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   And, sometimes, a foot in her mouth?
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of time,'' she laughs. ``I'm like the god, Shiva, only I
have feet instead of hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care about that stuff,'' she adds, about her missteps
or mistakes and any ridicule they might engender. ``You put
everything out and sometimes those things that aren't really
successful, you're still happy doing them. If you are going to be
an artist _ yeah, it is really great to be successful _ but you
have to do the things that make you happy as well. A lot of times
they work and sometimes they don't.''
</P>
<P>
   And that, too, is part of her appeal. Her blunt nature and
down-to-earth persona don't allow people to put her on a pedestal
too long. Women who speak with her immediately call her
``girlfriend.'' Her sexy, silly costumes allow for people to laugh
at her, but with her, too _ she knows what she is doing. She knows
how to handle David Letterman. And, if she misspeaks _ well, so be
it. If she releases a total kitsch bomb of a record called ``Allman
and Woman,'' with the then-love-of-her-life Gregg Allman, so be it.
If she fills career downtime with infomercials, well, OK. If she
chooses to date KISS's Gene Simmons, so be it. If she dates Bon
Jovi's Richie Sambora and her music moves toward arena-rock
bombast, oh, well, it's Cher. She's entertaining. She is a mixture
of confidence and insecurity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah,'' she says, ``I think that somehow those two
personalities live in equal force at the same time, and it is an
art of temperament.''
</P>
<P>
   Cher _ born Cherylin Sarkasian 52 years ago _ has had No. 1 pop
hits in each of the past four decades. For most of 1999 you've been
hearing her sing ``Believe'' _ ``Do you believe in life after
love?'' _ a hooky, defiant, beat-fest of a song she had to be
coerced into recording. Why so?
</P>
<P>
   Rob Dickens, executive producer of Warner Bros. UK at the time,
approached her and said, `` `How would you like to do a disco
album?' and just the idea of it being a disco album sounded so
weird to me,'' she recalled. Been there, done that. He sent her the
songs; she was turned around and even contributed lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   It became a hit, first with gay male audiences in Europe. Then,
it spread to the States and became ubiquitous on the pop radio
airwaves. It made her the oldest female pop artist to ever hit No.
1 on the Billboard singles chart, and propelled the album of the
same name to double-platinum status (signifying sales of 2 million
copies.) She lip-synched it at the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   On this tour, she has a six-piece band, backup singers, a
bells-and-whistles production. It will not be an evening of
subtlety and songcraft, but bombast and beats. ``It's not a show
with, like, just plain singing,'' Cher explains, perhaps
needlessly. ``It's very theatrical, like a rock 'n' roll circus.''
Opening is Cyndi Lauper, who's got a few Cher-isms in her work, as
well.
</P>
<P>
   So, it's a charmed life?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, sort of. Cher survived her cheeseball goofy-hippie '60s act
with then-husband Sonny Bono to carve out a unique career as an
actress, who makes smart choices about roles, and a singer who has
scored with hard rock, pop, disco, and schmaltz, who puts the top
in the phrase ``over the top,'' especially when she takes to the
concert stage. ``Someone has to draw the line for me where
over-the-top is concerned,'' she says, with a laugh, ``because then
and only then can you know when you are going over it. I just do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   But she suffered with the death of Bono. She was calling him
``the best partner I ever had'' well before his ski accident last
years. Asked whether she wants to talk about him now, she parries,
``it depends on what you want to ask.'' She is asked about his
spirit, and if she somehow still feels his presence. ``Well, I just
do,'' she says, ``It is difficult to explain it, a closeness.'' She
is not pushed further. She did get nailed by Bono's widow, Mary,
for her televised eulogy, who accused Cher of pulling a star turn
for the camera.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, the people who criticized'' the eulogy, Cher says,
``I don't have any patience or time for that . . . It wasn't said
to please anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   She has suffered from chronic fatigue syndrome. ``I don't have
it right now, knock on any kind of wood,'' she says, ``but once you
have had it you become a little more susceptible to it. The thing
that really kills you is being on the road or just going from
project to project without any rest. I am going to rest after this
(tour) because I have been working a year and a half straight and
I'm pretty much at my limit.''
</P>
<P>
   Is Cher the canny architect of her career or a passenger on the
her express train?
</P>
<P>
   She pauses. ``I would say both . . . But I definitely feel
responsible. I don't know if architect is the right word, but I
feel the responsiblity is definitely mine.'' She will say she rates
herself higher as an actress than singer.
</P>
<P>
   Once the rest is over, she has two projects _ an album and a
film _ awaiting. She has already recorded the album, but postponed
the film because of the success of ``Believe.'' The album, ``Not
Commercial,''will only be available through her Web site,
www.cher.com.
</P>
<P>
   ````I wanted to put it out, but the record company (Warner
Bros.) said it was not commercial,'' she says. ``So, I called it
`Not Commercial.''' She depends largely on outside writers for her
big-time Cher albums. For this, she says, ``I wrote it more as
poetry, it's not the music I would usually sing. It comes from me,
so I feel totally comfortable with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The film, called ``Happy Jack,'' after a song by the Who, is
about a crazy Irish guy that comes to America. ``He's thinking that
if he can just get to Hollywood somehow, it will be a magic place
for him,'' Cher says. ``But he gets there and discovers old
Hollywood wasn't there anymore so he comes to grips with that. It's
funny and sad, just like life. I'm trying to fit it in in next year
because it's something I really want to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-99 1400EDT &QL; 
