<HEADER>
A2719 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-IRONMAIDEN-BOS &LR;      07-16 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-IRONMAIDEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRON MAIDEN RETURNS TO BASICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bruce Dickinson, the once-and-again singer of British heavy
metal veterans Iron Maiden, scopes out the musical landscape and
licks his chops. The aggressive, attacking type of music his band
makes is the rage once again, getting played on active and modern
rock formats, albeit played mostly by younger bands. That's where
wily old Iron Maiden comes in. And, partially, why Dickinson, who
left the group in 1993, put his solo career on hold to rejoin his
mates in Maiden.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going back with Maiden means there's a huge opportunity to do
several things,'' the singer explains, from a tour stop in Quebec.
``One, to revitalize this whole area of music that used to be metal
and is now fragmented all over the place, an opportunity to provide
a focus for what is becoming an upsurge of demand. There's genuine
on-the-street interest, but nobody seems to get it quite right in
terms or seizing the public imagination, and me re-joining Maiden
has seized everyone's imagination. We have a chance to be the No. 1
metal band on the planet. That's a great reason for rejoining the
band.''
</P>
<P>
   If he feels that way, why did he leave? ``Without seeming
churlish about it,'' Dickinson says, ``it was a nice routine to be
in, but it was nevertheless becoming a routine.'' (He was replaced
by Blaze Bayley; Maiden's fortunes faded.) ``I know a lot of people
think it's a routine they'd like to have, but to me, there was a
challenge missing. I went in and created my own challenge, by
starting again from scratch.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickinson calls his early solo years being ``out in the
wilderness in terms of big commericial success,'' but says, ``it
got to the point where it was going great in my solo career and
then the Maiden issue came up. (Rejoining) was not just as an easy
option.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickinson plans his own live album in September and a studio
album of unreleased material next year. But, right now, it's Iron
Maiden on all burners.
</P>
<P>
   The band's tour, which has sold out the Orpheum Sunday with
Monster Magnet, is the biggest in terms of production the band has
done in eight years: There will be pyrotechnics, video screens, the
full load. This, by the way, will take place in a theater that
lacks air-conditioning. ``I hate air-conditioning,'' Dickinson
says. ``I like to sweat. (When there is air-conditioning) I request
it be shut off at my show. I hate drafts. I like a nice, warm moist
environment in which to sing.''
</P>
<P>
   Iron Maiden is not touring behind what Dickinson calls a
``real'' record _ i.e., new _ but a 20-track, two-CD best-of called
``Ed Hunter,'' which features a bonus CD-ROM where the Maiden fans
get to pursue Eddie, the rotted corpse that has long been Maiden's
mascot, through seven levels, all of which correspond to an Iron
Maiden album sleeve. That is, they chase Eddie through a graveyard,
the south end of London, Egypt, and other places.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's basically an arcade shoot-'em-up game,'' says Dickinson.
``You get your gun, or in this case a mouse, and you go through
worlds and baddies come up and throw things at you. I've never
caught Eddie; I always get taken out by the zombies in the
graveyard. It's a great stress reliever, just don't take it too
seriously.'' In the wake of the Columbine High School schoolyard
shootings, it's become almost de rigueur to say that, which
Dickinson acknowledges, adding most kids are smart enough to
separate reality and fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   ``My kid who's going to be 9 loves the game and he tells me off
all the time, says I'm getting too serious. I have three kids and
we tried to get them to stop playing with guns, so they used sticks
or the end of the garden sprinkler in place of a gun. One day, they
were playing cops and robbers and I said, `You gotta watch it with
this gun stuff,' and one of them looked at me, and said, `Jeez, dad
it's a plastic sprinkler and I'm pretending it's a gun. It's a
game, dad.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Co-founding guitarist Adrian Smith (who left in 1988) also
rejoined Maiden, giving them a total of three axmen, co-founder
Dave Murray and Smith's replacement Janick Gers being the others.
Dickinson said it was never a question of giving Gers the boot, so
they just made room. How do they work out rhythm and lead roles?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' says Dickinson. ``They figure it out
themselves. . . . They lock themselves in a room for a day and a
half and come out say `OK, we got it figured.' They tag-team it.
They are the most mellow people for lead guitarists.''
</P>
<P>
   After this tour concludes in Greece in early October, Iron
Maiden begins to assemble the pieces for a new album. ``We've
written a good chunk of it,'' says Dickinson, ``but we're not gonna
start recording until November and hope to have the record out by
late spring.''
</P>
<P>
   What direction will the boys be headed in, musically? ``It's
kind of a no-brainer for us,'' Dickinson says with a laugh. ``It's
gonna be heavy. We're not gonna do a politically correct Iron
Maiden record. One thing the band has never done has been to
compromise its integrity, ever, making it almost unique. (Our
label) Sony is convinced there is a real place for Maiden, that we
can get on radio with what we do. If Maiden gets a sniff of getting
a record on radio, it'll go stratospheric. We're all only getting
started.'' If that happens, Dickinson promises, ``the mother and
father of all Maiden tours.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a mission now, a cause,'' he adds. ``The metal
thing, which is important, but more being the band you're in. When
I go on stage and grab the audience, what makes me push myself to
work harder, to yell and scream, it's not the thought that I'm
bringing metal back, it's pure self-gratification.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-99 1401EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990716.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2723 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-WOOD-BOS &LR;      07-16 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-WOOD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WOOD' A COMEDY THAT LIGHTS THE FIRE OF FRIENDSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VANESSA E. JONES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE WOOD 
Directed and written by: Rick Famuyiwa 
Starring: Omar Epps, Taye Diggs, Richard T. Jones, Sean Nelson,
Trent J. Cameron  and Duane Finley. 
Running time: 106 minutes 
Rating: R 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not often that moviegoers get to see films about
African-American life that go beyond the hood or hip-hop comedies.
The last one was Maya Angelou's ``Down in the Delta,'' released
earlier this year. But its box office failure, along with that of
``Beloved'' and ``Why Do Fools Fall in Love'' in the last year,
reportedly has made Hollywood decision makers less inclined to fund
challenging black dramas or love stories.
</P>
<P>
   So when an African-American romantic comedy like ``The Wood''
comes along, one is tempted to light a candle to give it some good
karma. Unfortunately, that candle probably should be saved for a
more worthy candidate.
</P>
<P>
   On the positive side, ``The Wood'' is a pleasant film blessed
with charismatic performances by a talented group of young black
actors who cannily evoke their complex characters. However, the
screenplay, by Rick Famuyiwa (a 26-year-old newcomer who segued
from Niketown employee to film director), is plagued by too many
unoriginal comedic situations.
</P>
<P>
   The film is essentially a coming-of-age story about three young
men growing up in the ``Wood'' _ the predominantly black
middle-class neighborhood of Inglewood, Calif. We meet the guys as
adulthood bears down on them. Former ladies' man Roland, played by
yummy-looking Taye Diggs (Angela Bassett's boy toy in ``How Stella
Got Her Groove Back''), has disappeared two hours before he's to
say his wedding vows.
</P>
<P>
   Friends Mike (Omar Epps) and Slim (Richard T. Jones) track the
drunken groom down and dry him out. As they do, flashbacks, cued by
classic 1980s songs from Eric B &AMP; Rakim, Luther Vandross, and Run
DMC, explore the roots of their friendship.
</P>
<P>
   The story was inspired by Fumuyiwa's real-life experience. ``A
couple of years ago a buddy told me he was getting married and we
immediately started talking about our childhood,'' says the
writer/director. ``Two hours later we were still talking. You can't
help but look back when you reach milestones in your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Three younger actors play Roland, Mike and Slim in their teenage
years and look nothing like their adult counterparts. They jauntily
sport shell toed Addidas and one even wears the most humiliating
hair trend of the '80s: Jheri curls.
</P>
<P>
   It's in these segments that the film disappoints. Young Mike
(Sean Nelson) gets excited looking at the cutest girl in class,
Alicia (Malinda Williams), who is asked to speak in front of the
class. Mike, Slim, and Roland bet on who will loose their virginity
first. Mike must learn how to dance so he won't embarrass himself
at a school party.
</P>
<P>
   These scenes have been reenacted ad nauseum in television
sitcoms and films. The difference is, of course, that viewers
rarely get to see African-Americans act out these moments of life
on the big screen.
</P>
<P>
   Other scenes work well, such as when Stacey, Alicia's
gangbanging brother, offers the trio a ride after he has robbed a
local convenience store. The boys haltingly accept and the group
gets stopped by the police. But it's not teenagers Mike, Slim or
Roland who break down, it's Stacey's gangsta friend, who quietly
bawls in the front seat.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is held together by Epps, Diggs, and Jones. They have
an easy cameraderie that makes their long-term friendship
believable. Nelson (who debuted in the indie film ``Fresh'' several
years ago) and Williams stand out in the young cast _ their
tumultuous relationship becomes the heart of the flashbacks and
ultimately the film.
</P>
<P>
   But the person who may get a career boost out of ``The Wood'' is
Luther Vandross. The singer's stellar 1980s classic, ``If This
World Were Mine,'' gets played at least three times on the
soundtrack.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
