<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Saturday, July 17,
1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   APOLLO-MAIN _ CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ Thirty years after men
first left Earth to walk on the moon, most of the surviving
moonwalkers gathered here to remember the event. Apollo 11
astronauts Neil Armstrong and Buzz Aldrin are among at least seven
Apollo astronauts who were scheduled to appear at a 5:30 p.m. press
conference on Friday. They were also scheduled to speak at an
evening dinner, which will include many of the people who worked on
the Apollo program. But there was a twinge of sadness to the
occasion: one of their members, Apollo 12 astronaut Pete Conrad,
died last week when he crashed his motorcycle. Now only nine of the
12 men who walked on the moon are still alive. (Gaffney, Dayton
Daily News). 30.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Main story will be filed between 7-8 p.m. EDT and updated
around 9 p.m. EDT with any quotes he gets from Armstrong or the
other astronauts.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   APOLLO-SIDE _ CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ While the astronauts
reminisced, NASA started the countdown for the space shuttle
Columbia, namesake of the Apollo 11 command module. Columbia is set
to carry the Chandra X-ray observatory into orbit. Its crew
includes the first woman shuttle commander, Eileen Collins, and
Catherine G. ``Cady'' Coleman, a former Wright-Patterson Air Force
Base scientist. (Gaffney, Dayton Daily News). 10.
</P>
<P>
   WEISS _ BOCA RATON, Fla. _ Mel Weiss, one of America's premier
lawyers in class-action litigation, will speak in Boca today about
the settlement proposal for Holocaust survivors. For more than
three decades, Milberg Weiss Bershad Hynes &AMP; Lerach has represented
plaintiffs in some of the biggest and most complex cases in the
history of United States antitrust, consumer, insurance,
environmental and securities fraud class actions. Some are quite
well-known: the Exxon Valdez oil-spill case, which resulted in a
$5.3 billion verdict; the Prudential Insurance deceptive sales
practices case, in which policyholders stand to get back $2
billion; and the Lincoln Savings &AMP; Loan scandal, where Weiss sued
and recovered $240 million lost by stock investors. Weiss now
representing Holocaust survivors in their $20 billion claims
against three Swiss banks accused of storing fortunes plundered by
the Nazis during World War II. His class-action suit led to the
creation of the compensation fund. (Sorentrue/Mack, Palm Beach
Post).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   BARAK-PALESTINE - HEBRON - U.S. President Bill Clinton and
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak would find a good reality check
for their peace talks in the Street of the Martyrs in Hebron. Here,
the United States literally tried to pave the way to peace and
failed. The 400 meter stretch of road was beautified with $2.5
million in American aid money, but the Israelis, who control this
area of the city, don't allow Palestinians to drive there. The
fortified road blocks on the street divide the city, drag the local
Palestinian merchants into bankruptcy and make them distrust
American intentions, as well as the peace process itself. ``I don't
trust the American administration. They do things just for the
Israelis,'' says shop keeper Monther Shahin. ``This street is a big
example.'' It's not the only example. Throughout the West Bank,
Palestinians are getting impatient waiting for items _ land, roads
and economic perks _ listed in old agreements. (Kaplow, Cox News
Service). 20. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-DRIVEIN _ MOSCOW _ A Russian businessman recently opened
the country's first drive-in theater outside of Moscow. Because of
Russsia's summer latitude, the movies don't begin until after 11
p.m., when the sun goes down. On some nights, they have double
features until 4 a.m., when the sun starts coming up. No popcorn
served, but they do offer cabbage pies. (Holmes, Cox News Service).
30. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in the (i) International nd (l) Lifestyle
categories.
</P>
<P>
   VIRGIN-TURTLES _ ST.CROIX, VIRGIN ISLANDS - The U.S. Virgin
Islands is expecting a bumper crop of visitors to its beaches this
year. Hopefully, the kind that lay plenty of eggs. Nesting
leatherback turtles flocked to the island in 1997. The world's
largest turtles breed once every two to three years, so scientists
expect another pea number of turtles in 1999. The nesting season
should peak in June. Leatherback turtles, an endangered species
worldwide, grow to seven feet long and weigh 1,200 pounds. (Emling,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TURTLE-BOX
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   CISNEROS _ WASHINGTON _ After listening to closing arguments in
a pretrial hearing, a federal judge said Friday he was likely to
allow the jury in the upcoming fraud trial of former housing
secretary Henry Cisneros to hear audio tapes made by Cisneros's
former mistress. (Malone, Cox News Service). 16.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS _ DAYTON _ The big guys are coming to Ohio to kiss our
women and take our money: George W. Bush is in Cincinnati on
Thursday and organizers say folks are lining up to give him money;
then, Friday Clinton returns to Stan Chesley's house, again, to
gather money and the following week, Al Gore comes to Cleveland.
(Hershey, Dayton Daily News). 20.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-CANDIDATES _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Each morning,
political neophyte Jean Elliott Brown turns on her computer to see
how much her congressional campaign has raised overnight. She's got
mail. She's got money _ and it's coming from across the country.
How does somebody in Nebraska come to write a check for an unknown,
untried candidate from Palm Beach Gardens? The Internet makes it
possible, of course. Brown is harvesting the proceeds of dissent
created by what touts itself as the nation's first grass-roots
cyberspace political movement: MoveOn.org. (Moffett, Palm Beach
Post) MOVED
</P>
