<SLUG> BC-KOSOVAR-REFUGEES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT MANY KOSOVAR REFUGEES IN SEATTLE PLANNING TO RETURN HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN IWASAKI  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MERCER ISLAND, Wash. _ If Sabahudin Muharremi doesn't seem eager
to accept an offer by the U.S. government of a free flight home to
Kosovo, there's a sorrowful reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``His home is destroyed,'' said Besim Krasniqi, his friend and
fellow refugee. ``He doesn't have a home to go back to.''
</P>
<P>
   That is a typical response by uprooted Kosovars, officials of
several Seattle resettlement agencies said this week as they helped
explain the government offer to refugees.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department announced this week that the United States
will give free trips home on commercial and charter flights to
refugees evacuated during the Kosovo conflict. Nearly 10,000
refugees have been brought into the country over the past few
months, with about 80 resettled in the Seattle area by four
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Even as refugees here consider whether to head home to Kosovo,
where U.N. peacekeepers from different nations are stationed, other
Kosovars still are arriving because of the upheaval in their
homeland. At least four more refugees were expected Wednesday night
(July 14) from Macedonia, with five scheduled to come next week.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees do not have to return home and can stay permanently
here. They would be eligible for a ``green card,'' signifying
permanent residency, after one year and could apply for citizenship
after five years.
</P>
<P>
   Those who wish to fly home on the government's dime must do so
by May 1.
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Gjoni, a translator for the International Rescue Committee
in Seattle, has not talked to many refugees who are planning to
return home soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The general response is no,'' Gjoni said. ``Houses are burned.
They don't want to go back, at least for now, because they don't
feel safe. Even though NATO forces are there, they think they'll
always be under the Serbian regime.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they say is, they want to go back for a visit someday,
but not right away.''
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Koser, director of the resettlement office for Catholic
Community Services in Seattle, said refugees have a variety of
reasons for hesitating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some are in mixed (Albanian-Serbian) marriages. Some have run
from the KLA (Kosovo Liberation Army) and have refused to
participate in any war and may be shunned,'' Koser said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, some refugees are separated from immediate
family members.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no easy putting-it-back-together process yet'' for
families separated by the war, said Bob Johnson, director of the
International Rescue Committee in Seattle. In some cases, refugees
may have more incentive to stay if they can bring missing family
members to America, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Many refugees, including the 40 or so Kosovars who are allowed
to live rent-free for 90 days at the Shorewood Apartments on Mercer
Island, have spent the past month learning English and taking
classes on work skills and job searches.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 27 refugees assisted by the International Rescue
Committee, three women are working as hotel maids and some men have
applied for jobs as supermarket baggers or office janitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to try to find employment for them rather than
find welfare,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees helped by his agency include Muharremi, 22, and
Krasniqi, 24, who were studying economics and law, respectively, at
the University of Kosovo in Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   Florent Istogu, 23, another law student in Kosovo, speaks fluent
English and is helping Johnson with translation work. Istogu came
to the United States with his girlfriend and did not know the fate
of their families.
</P>
<P>
   ``For three months, we didn't know anything about them,'' he
said. ``If they were not killed by Serbian forces, they would have
died from hunger. But I hear now they are fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Istogu longs to return to his university studies, ``but it's
better to stay here for one year or two years to earn money, to
send money home,'' he said. ``But if there's any chance, I'd like
to go to (a Washington) university also.''
</P>
<P>
   Gazmend Bytyqi, who worked as a mechanic in Kosovo, also will
delay his trip home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to go back,'' he said, as Istogu translated. But first,
Bytyqi said he wants to work and save money to build a new home for
his parents, sister and brother, who are living in a tent in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   With Bytyqi, 31, are his wife, Blerta, and their 2-year-old
daughter, Arlinda.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether his wife wanted to go home soon, Bytyqi replied,
``She says, `We came together and we want to go back together.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
