u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-LAKEPLACID-BOS &LR;      07-16 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-LAKEPLACID-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREDICTABLE `LAKE PLACID' TOO DEEP FOR REAL CHILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
LAKE PLACID 
Directed by: Steve Miner 
Screenplay by: David E. Kelley 
Starring: Bridget Fonda, Bill Pullman, Brendan Gleeson, Oliver
Platt, Betty White 
Rated: R (violent creature attacks and related gore, and for
language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No summer allotment of scare movies would be complete without
the usual ``Jaws'' and ``Jurassic Park'' wannabes. On July 30,
we'll see ``Deep Blue Sea,'' with smart sharks as the gimmick.
Today, we've got a film whose cement-handedness begins with the
intended irony in its title, ``Lake Placid.'' Not to be confused
with the real Lake Placid, N.Y., it's named for a fictional lake in
Maine, where a boatload of squabbling investigators figures out
that the thing that's been biting the heads off various unlucky
fools who insist on immersing themselves in its depths is a
30-foot-long crocodile that has somehow migrated there from Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Bloodthirsty though it may be, it genuflects to the Hollywood
convention of never scarfing down anyone from the A list, although
stars Bridget Fonda, Bill Pullman, Oliver Platt, and Brendan
Gleeson predictably take turns dodging the croc's gnashing teeth.
Creature designer Stan Winston gets star billing, too, which is
only fair. There are moments when the big croc seems almost alive,
or at least not much less so than the characters. They face far
more danger from the snapping jaws of cliches than the lively
mandibles of the bad-news reptile willing to settle for cows and
bears when no human is available.
</P>
<P>
   The filmmakers assure us that no cow was injured in the making
of the film, which is more than they can say for dramatic
credibility. ``Lake Placid'' wastes no time settling into
stereotyped setups. Paleontologist Fonda, blue over being dumped by
her boss for a co-worker and called upon to identify a large tooth
that turns out to be not prehistoric, figures it's time she got
away from the museum for a while, even though she hates the
outdoors. Fish and game warden Pullman is the guy she's obviously
going to wind up with, while Gleeson's thin-skinned blue-collar
sheriff and Platt's rich, eccentric prof who flies his own
helicopter are obviously destined to embark upon ongoing class
warfare as comic antagonists. Betty White, as a secret-keeping
widow living on the shore of the lake, gets the best the script has
to offer.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``Lake Placid'' can get only so much mileage out of its
sole plot device, namely
there's-something-down-there-and-it-wants-you-for-lunch _ and skip
the fava beans and a nice Chianti. The actors mostly emerge
unscathed, in both senses of the word. Pullman keeps a low profile,
and Fonda generates appeal despite the patronizing view of her
character. Platt survives being assigned more dumb lines than the
others. And Gleeson smoothly makes the jump from Ireland to
Hollywood, even incorporating into his alert performance a few
mannerisms from ``The General.'' The lake isn't bad, either,
looking lush and capable of harboring more than a few subsurface
secrets. But it's hard not to think of ``Lake Placid'' as ``Lame
Placid.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-99 1404EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
