<HEADER>
A2730 &Cx1f; tth-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANFORD-WORKERS-SPI &LR;      07-16 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANFORD-WORKERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANFORD SETS UP BERYLLIUM SCREENING FOR WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL SMITH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Thousands of Hanford workers who may have been exposed
to beryllium, an element used in nuclear weapons production, could
be compensated by the U.S. government for illness related to their
exposure under legislation proposed Thursday by the Clinton
administration.
</P>
<P>
   The Hanford Nuclear Reservation in Eastern Washington has
already set up a beryllium screening program for current and former
workers, said Mike Talbot, Hanford spokesman. So far, 196 former
workers have volunteered for the screening, and 16 current workers
are being tested for potential exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Between 4,000 and 13,000 former production workers and as many
as 36,000 former construction workers may have been exposed to
beryllium over the course of Hanford's operating history, said Dr.
Tim Takaro, co-principal investigator with the University of
Washington's Hanford Former Worker Program.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nature of the operations and the secrecy means many people
may have been inadvertently exposed,'' Takaro said. No complete
lists of former workers exists, so the program is relying on
outreach and partial lists of workers to identify those potentially
at risk.
</P>
<P>
   Of those tested so far, four current workers have shown
beryllium sensitization, an immune condition that puts them at
higher risk for developing chronic beryllium disease, Takaro said.
One current worker has developed chronic beryllium disease.
</P>
<P>
   The compensation plan, which must still be approved by Congress,
marks the first time the government has acknowledged that its
nuclear weapons production programs during the Cold War may have
made thousands of workers sick.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. government is acknowledging that we made a mistake,''
said Energy Secretary Bill Richardson in announcing the
compensation plan. ``We need to right this wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Beryllium is a hard, grayish metal found in mineral rocks, coal,
soil and volcanic dust. Because of its unusual properties, which
include high thermal conductivity and resistance to corrosion,
beryllium compounds are mined and purified for use in various
industrial products, including nuclear weapons. Beryllium is also
used in spark-proof tools.
</P>
<P>
   Exposure to beryllium dust or fumes over time can result in
chronic beryllium disease, an inflammatory lung condition that is
potentially disabling and sometimes fatal, Talbot said. The disease
is highly variable, sometimes developing over a period of months.
In other cases, it can take up to 30 years for symptoms to develop.
</P>
<P>
   Symptoms of the disease include coughing and shortness of
breath, abnormal scarring in the lungs, and abnormal lung sounds
heard with a stethoscope.
</P>
<P>
   Beryllium was used at Hanford from about 1960 until 1986,
primarily in the production of reactor fuel rods. Although there
are no active beryllium operations under way currently at Hanford,
there may still be beryllium present at some locations, Talbot
said.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to employees in January 1998, the company stated:
``Based on available personal/area monitoring data, it is believed
that nearly all employee exposure to beryllium was below the
permissible exposure level.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the letter continues, ``For very sensitive individuals,
it appears that they may develop beryllium disease even though
beryllium levels are within permissible limits.''
</P>
<P>
   About 5 percent of people who work around beryllium develop
sensitivity to the metal, and about 2 percent eventually develop
the disease, Takaro said. People who work around higher
concentrations, such as machinists, are at higher risk.
</P>
<P>
   Hanford is in the process of identifying all the locations where
beryllium was used in the past, and where it may still be present.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's proposed plan initially limits compensation
to workers whose illness can be traced to their exposure to
beryllium. Most of the workers were at sites in Colorado, Illinois,
New Mexico, Ohio, Pennsylvania, Tennessee and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of such compensation is estimated at about $13 million
a year for 10 years. Under the plan, eligible workers could be
reimbursed for medical costs, compensated for lost wages, and given
vocational assistance. As an option, they could take a $100,000
lump-sum benefit payment. If the worker has died, survivors'
benefits would be provided.
</P>
<P>
   Workers and their advocates are trying to expand the plan to
cover illnesses from other toxic and radioactive materials used at
weapons plants.
</P>
<P>
   The UW Hanford Former Worker Program is also looking at exposure
to noise and asbestos, Tadaro said.
</P>
<P>
   This report includes information from The Associated Press.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
