<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM COLORADO SHOOTING GROWS A FRIENDSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ After suffering numerous gunshot wounds at
Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo., including a shotgun
blast to the face, Lance Kirklin came as close as one can come to
dying.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's living the high life in San Francisco for a week with
his new friend Rashad Williams, who collected pledges for running
The Examiner Bay to Breakers race, so far raising $40,000 to help
pay Lance's medical bills.
</P>
<P>
   Lance not only looks great after extensive facial reconstructive
surgery, (``Only five plastic surgeries to go,'' he said
matter-of-factly), but he wants to do everything there is to do in
San Francisco. And he's out-wisecracking our mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Lance, 16, and Rashad, 15, were in the City Hall rotunda, facing
dozens of television cameras, when Mayor Willie Brown presented
Lance with a San Francisco street sign saying ``Lance Kirklin
Blvd.''
</P>
<P>
   Lance leaned toward the microphone and said, ``Mr. Mayor, do you
have your own boulevard?''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, I told Lance that the mayor would love to have a
boulevard of his own. He said, ``Yeah, I know.''
</P>
<P>
   As Rashad said of Lance, ``He's funny all the time. He's a
wonderful friend to have.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of kids in Littleton are very depressed and a lot are
scared,'' said Lance's dad, Mike Kirklin, who accompanied his son.
``But Lance is such a good example. He gets up in the morning and
he's ready to go. And he's getting back to his knucklehead self.''
</P>
<P>
   Inspiration comes in interesting forms, and here's a big
restorative dose, in the form of two teen-agers and their families,
who have become part of one big ``extended family,'' as Rashad's
mother, Sheila Burton Harrison, put it.
</P>
<P>
   Lance's father said he hopes Rashad's family can visit them
again in Denver, as they did in June, ``keeping this relationship
extended for a lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   The elder Kirklin, who lost his other teen-age son, Nolan, to
suicide five months before Lance was shot, had tears in his eyes as
he told the crowd about his new bond with Rashad's family.
</P>
<P>
   Some city workers and tourists in City Hall had tears in their
eyes, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fantastic,'' said George Awad of Lake Placid, N.Y., who
was recording the scene on his home video camera behind the TV
photographers. ``It's very inspiring to see the city of San
Francisco celebrating these kids, making them feel important, not
only to the town but to the whole country.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, and if we must have media circuses, it was nice to see one
about something positive for a change.
</P>
<P>
   The reporters crushed Lance and Rashad as they stood on the
stairs of City Hall, but they spoke quietly and seriously into
every mike shoved in their faces, talking about people's amazingly
generous response to Rashad's fund-raising run.
</P>
<P>
   Lance and Rashad really are going to do everything arranged for
them, and more. They have boundless energy. They're kids. And they
really do like each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talk about movies, fishing, sports, all the things kids
talk about,'' Rashad said.
</P>
<P>
   They were a little late to the media circus because they'd slept
in at the luxury suites the Nikko Hotel managed to find for both
their families at the height of tourist season. Then the two young
guys got up and watched the Mel Gibson movie ``Payback'' together.
</P>
<P>
   They deserve a break, even from being celebrated. After all,
we're celebrating them because they're two kids who gave us a break
from despair.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind talk of despair this week, though. Rashad will throw
out the ceremonial first pitch to Lance at Sunday afternoon's
Oakland A's/Colorado Rockies game.
</P>
<P>
   Stand up and give our kids a cheer.
</P>
<P>
   Lance's hospital bills amount to nearly $1 million and he has no
health insurance. For those who want to help, checks may be made
out to the ``Lance Kirklin Fund'' c/o Everen Securities, 8005 S.
Chester St., Suite 300, Englewood, CO 80112.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
