<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-GASOLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEVRON TO TAP GASOLINE FROM OUTSIDE CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GEORGE RAINE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ California regulators have granted an
extraordinary request by the Chevron Corp., allowing the company to
sell gasoline that does not conform to the state's stringent
clean-air standards.
</P>
<P>
   An explosion Saturday at the Chevron refinery in Richmond
severely limited production, and Chevron took its request for a
variance from state law to the state Air Resources Board. The
accident was barely perceptible outside the gates of the complex.
</P>
<P>
   The state said sales of gasoline that does not conform to
California standards would be limited to Northern California and
the Central Valley. The exemption took effect Friday and will last
45 days.
</P>
<P>
   Sales are prohibited in Sacramento or Southern California, areas
that have the most severe smog problems.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron may sell up to 3.5 million barrels of gasoline obtained
from nearby states that is not as clean-burning as that required in
California. But the exemption comes at a price. The state is
charging San Francisco-based Chevron 15 cents for each gallon of
non-conforming gas _ a fee that could reach $22 million.
</P>
<P>
   Gas sold in California cuts hydrocarbon emissions by about 17
percent. The gas of other states cuts emissions by about 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The variance was granted to avoid a supply disruption caused
by unforeseeable problems at Chevron's Richmond refinery,'' said
Jerry Martin, a spokesman for the Air Resources Board in
Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first variance the Air Resources Board has granted
for gasoline under terms of the 1996 Clean Air Act, which required
oil companies to sell only reformulated gas. Similar action was
taken in 1993 and 1994 to relieve a shortage of diesel fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Teresa Lee, spokeswoman for the Bay Area Air Quality Management
District, said district officials were disappointed with the
decision, particularly coming during the high smog season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will add 9 tons a day of hydrocarbons, a real chunk of
pollution,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The refinery process for producing reformulated gasoline,
depending upon production criteria, adds 5 to 15 cents per gallon
to the cost of California gasoline, which is among the most
expensive in the nation. Fifty cents per gallon of California gas
is for federal and state taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron has about 20 percent of the California market.
</P>
<P>
   The money the state is charging Chevron will go into an account
used to reduce air emissions by funding repair or scrapping of
older, high-polluting automobiles, Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   The accident was the third at Chevron's Richmond refinery since
March.
</P>
<P>
   On March 23, a fire shot an 18,000-pound plume of sulfur dioxide
into the air and sent more than 350 area residents to hospitals
with ailments including eye and throat irritation, breathing
trouble, dizziness and nausea. On June 2, a chemical release that
gave some nearby residents headaches and made them nauseous led to
a temporary shutdown of the plant.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
