<DOCNO> NYT19990716.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 14:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2771 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARAK-PALESTINE17-COX     07-16 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARAK-PALESTINE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LIFE ALONG HEBRON STREET UNDERSCORES U.S. PEACE EFFORTS IN
MIDEAST
 &HT;    880. Moving on (i) international categories.
 &HT;    w/photos.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEBRON, West Bank _ Despite the optimism of this week's meeting
between President Clinton and Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak,
residents of a Hebron street that was meant to symbolize peace
doubt if it will come.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the United States literally tried to pave the way
to peace on Shuhada Street and failed. It's one of many places
where Palestinians wait impatiently for the peace agreements with
Israel to be implemented.
</P>
<P>
   The 1997 U.S.-brokered Hebron agreement turned over most of the
Palestinian city to the Palestinian Authority. It also specified
that about 800 yards of Shuhada, or Martyrs, Street would be paved
and beautified by the Americans right down to painting the shop
doors, installing lampposts and laying brick sidewalks.
</P>
<P>
   The $2.5 million project was completed in October 1997. But the
Israelis have reneged on their promise to open the road to
Palestinians. They can walk or ride donkeys, but, with a few
exceptions, Palestinians cannot drive on the street. Meanwhile,
vans carrying Jewish settlers whisk down the narrow, but central,
artery.
</P>
<P>
   Shuhada Street was first closedto Palestinian motorists in 1994,
when a Jewish settler killed 29 Palestinians praying nearby.
Israeli authorities said Palestinian drivers would seek revenge on
the settlers who live along the road.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Israeli army road blocks choke off the street of Spanish
lamps, turquoise awnings and closed shops. Palestinian merchants
have been forced to close their shops because customers in the city
of more than 200,000 people can't reach them. The road blocks also
are eroding some Palestinians' trust in America and the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't trust the American administration. They do things just
for the Israelis,'' said shopkeeper Monther Shahin as he looked
down Shuhada Street. ``This street is a big example.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's not the only example Palestinians see. Throughout the
West Bank, they are impatient for land, access to roads and
economic perks that are promised in stalled agreements. A poll
conducted last month by a West Bank organization showed that 66
percent of Palestinians said they did not trust Barak's new
government to keep peace agreements.
</P>
<P>
   Most pressing are the provisions in the Wye River agreement,
brokered by Clinton last October but later abandoned by former
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu. Israel has yet to hand
over about another 10 percent of the West Bank to the Palestinians.
Perhaps even more important to Palestinians, the Wye agreement
required Israel to provide them with travel routes between the Gaza
Strip and the West Bank. Such routes would reunite families and
allow merchants to market their goods.
</P>
<P>
   Israel is also late in allowing the Palestinians to begin work
on a port in Gaza, which would create thousands of jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The waiting game is visible in Halhul, a city of about 26,000
near Hebron. Civil affairs are governed by Palestinians but the
Israeli military still patrols the city. Two years ago, residents
expected to receive full control. In anticipation, they hung
banners and painted graffiti, but today they still wait to fully
control the city.
</P>
<P>
   Halhul Mayor Mohamad (cq) Milhem wonders why the United States
gives $3 billion a year to Israel, mostly for military purposes,
when he can't get $7 million for a sewage system. He worries that
the stalled peace process is undermining confidence in Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat, who sought peace with Israel, and fueling
groups opposed to the peace agreements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Israelis, Palestinians and Americans must make the best use of
every second,'' Milhem said. ``Time is important because of the
other forces of both Israeli and Palestinian opposition.''
</P>
<P>
   The American CIA has trained and equipped Palestinian police to
deal with Palestinian opponents. But the CIA support is barely
tolerated publicly. Graffiti in Arabic across the street from
Milhem's office states, ``Security cooperation with the CIA is
garbage.''
</P>
<P>
   In Hebron, the leaders of the 52 Jewish families on Shuhada
Street also are suspicious of U.S. involvement in the peace
process. Here, and in a nearby settlement of Kiryat Arba, many
still revere the settler who killed the 29 Arabs and was then
killed himself.
</P>
<P>
   To them, Shuhada Street, which they call King David Street, is a
symbol of American naivete a pointless fantasy of peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American dreams about peace are in vain. They don't
understand the situation here. They don't understand the hatred the
Arabs have against the Jews,'' said Noam Arnon, chairman of the
Hebron Jewish community. He warns of a violent ``disaster'' if
Palestinians are allowed to drive down the street.
</P>
<P>
   Hebron Mayor Mustafa Natshe (cq) said Arafat, when he met with
Barak last week, requested the street be opened to Palestinian
motorists. It would be a welcome gesture for a people losing hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't do anything,'' said 90-year-old Nadi Al Jundi as he
hobbled with his cane past the closed shops on Shuhada Street.
``Why not open it? It's a street!''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
