<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANIMALS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIS LIFE HAS BEEN FOR THE BIRDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VICKI CROKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   European swifts are so at home in the air, they even sleep and
mate on the fly.
</P>
<P>
   The albatross, with its 6-foot wingspan, is willing to travel
1,000 miles to bring home the birdie equivalent of the bacon for
its chicks.
</P>
<P>
   And the lyre bird of Australia, which mixes medleys of other
bird songs with its own, is such an adept and even modern mimic
that it often folds the sounds of chainsaws, car alarms, and camera
shutter clicks into its already elaborate repertoire.
</P>
<P>
   These are but a few of the remarkable animals you'll meet in Sir
David Attenborough's new 10-part series ``The Life of Birds'' for
PBS, which starts Tuesday at 8 p.m. It's a wild flight through
avian diversity.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Attenborough himself is a pretty fascinating bird. He
is a pioneer of natural history filmmaking for TV. He's the
godfather. In fact, if the field of nature documentaries were
structured like the Mafia, Attenborough would be the capo di tutti
capo.
</P>
<P>
   But that, of course, is a funny image of the consummate British
gentleman. The kind of fellow who says things such as ``he's a
flash chap'' or ``jolly nearly.'' A man who has been knighted. The
brother of famed filmmaker and actor Sir Richard Attenborough.
</P>
<P>
   David Attenborough, 73, has been leading the pack in nature TV
for 46 years through his films on the BBC. And he is nothing like
our blown-dry, painted-up American on-air ``talents.'' He writes
his own scripts. He doesn't use a teleprompter. There are
exclamation points aplenty in his delivery.
</P>
<P>
   Attenborough, a trained biologist, simply cannot contain his
enthusiasm on camera.
</P>
<P>
   He wriggles his body, bobs his head, and flashes his eyes in an
elaborate and enchanting courtship dance with the audience. Who can
resist?
</P>
<P>
   In this series, he appears at sundown before a bat cave in Texas
as millions of the winged predators mob the sky. He sneaks up on a
takahe, a nearly extinct native of New Zealand. A massive golden
eagle flies to his gloved fist. And we watch him crawl on his belly
on a dark beach in New Zealand as he trains his ``torch'' on a
foraging kiwi. In one scene, Attenborough stands near a tree in
Japan where shearwaters patiently queue up to climb and then launch
themselves into the air. Here, he is almost unrecognizable _ and
you realize it's because his hair is combed.
</P>
<P>
   It's only natural that he gets a little disheveled. He's braved
heat, cold, tsetse flies, and more. He's been chased _ on camera _
by angry animals, including massive elephant seal bulls. But he
dismisses the danger. By phone from New York City, he says, ``Well,
if you stand in front of the No. 11 bus, you're going to get run
over. Seriously, the only danger I face is because of my own
extreme foolishness or that of other human beings. There is just no
need to be silly.''
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing silly about this new series, which is as
engrossing as it is encyclopedic. It took three years, 48 camera
people, and more than $12 million to make. It involved 70 trips to
42 countries on all seven continents.
</P>
<P>
   More than 9,000 species of bird were captured _ on film that is
_ by night-vision cameras, micro-cameras, and by ``ultra-slow
motion'' photography. One cameraman had to lie in a pit for three
weeks to record the mating practices of the hedge sparrow.
</P>
<P>
   As we learn about the big issues _ ``To Fly or Not to Fly,''
``Signals and Songs,'' ``Finding Partners'' _ we watch vivid
vignettes.
</P>
<P>
   --The bee eater who, true to its name, nabs a sting-bearing
victim and, with a sharp nip, gets it to release its venom
harmlessly into the air _ spraying out in a slow-motion arc of
sparkling beads.
</P>
<P>
   --The albatross, who is so lyrical in the air, approaches the
beach, legs akimbo, and then plows the sand with its breastbone in
a landing that is ``scarcely better than a controlled accident.''
</P>
<P>
   --The plump grebe pair who put the hippos of ``Fantasia'' to
shame with their upright, perfectly synchronized, above-water pas
de deux.
</P>
<P>
   Attenborough's enthusiasm certainly seems justified. And it's
pretty easy to provoke. Just ask him his favorite bird.
</P>
<P>
   His love of birds of paradise, he says, ``is obsession to the
point of lunacy.'' Once, filming in New Guinea, Attenborough and a
cameraman crawled through thick, wet forest in an attempt to film
the rarely seen courtship display. His producer waited 100 feet
below during the dicey moments of stalking the quarry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fan-TAS-tic!'' Attenborough shouts. They got the
activity on film. And as soon as it was over, Attenborough ran down
the hillside to his producer. `` `Dickie! Dickie!' I cried, `We got
it! We got it!' ''
</P>
<P>
   I know you did, he was told. But how could you know from down
here? Attenborough asked.
</P>
<P>
   The producer reported that he could hear Attenborough's
heartbeat through the microphone and it was racing ``at double
speed.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(``The Life of Birds'' will run in one-hour episodes Tuesdays at 8
p.m., from July 20 to Sept. 28, except Aug. 10)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
