<HEADER>
A2835 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES1     07-16 0195
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHORTTAKES: The perfect gesture
 &HT;    By Arnold Rosenfeld
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Brandi Chastain whipped off her shirt in celebration of her
winning penalty kick in the World Cup soccer match against China,
there was an immediate _ and predictable _ complaint. ``More
filth!'' some cried. Still are.
</P>
<P>
   Male athletes tear off their shirts all the time. Few notice,
except when the men are excessively hairy. Men also spill huge
containers of Gatorade on unsuspecting coaches in moments of joy,
and everybody thinks that's just good, old-fashioned American fun.
There is no longer any excuse for any coach anywhere to be
surprised by a victory shower in orange juice.
</P>
<P>
   Let a grown woman expose her sports bra, and people begin
blacking out from coast to coast. I thought it was the perfect
gesture that combined the joy of victory with the special joy in
that moment of being a woman.
</P>
<P>
   Who's got the dirty minds here?
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld is editor-in-chief of the Cox Newspapers.
E-mail: arnold.rosenfeld(at)cox.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
