<DOCNO> NYT19990716.0131 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 15:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2862 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-BRUCE-BOS &LR;      07-16 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-BRUCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RETURN TO SPRINGSTEEN'S GLORY DAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Bruce Springsteen may not always like being
called the Boss, but how else do you describe someone who has
smashed box office records everywhere this year? He and his E
Street Band sold out 15 shows and 300,000 tickets in one day (for a
reported gross of $18 million) in his home state of New Jersey,
where he launched his US tour with a three-hour, sweat-drenched
rock 'n' roll bliss fest Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Springsteen came to ``regenerate you and re-sexualate you,'' he
said in a preacherlike mode as fans raised their hands toward this
rock hall of fame evangelist. And during an encore, he described
the tour as a ``rebirth and a rededication of the band _ and a
commitment to serve.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Excuse me while I testify!'' he said repeatedly, echoing an
old R&AMP;B refrain, as he raced around like a man possessed. He was
exhausting to watch _ nothing new there _ and he again gave his
all, venturing through the back streets of his darker songs, the
party ethic of his happy-hour tunes, and the social conscience of
his working-class anthems that have stood the test of time.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the Springsteen we know and love is back. And
what a difference from his last tour with a band _ the 1992
experience with studio musicians whose names only a few diehards
can even remember. This time, he was reunited with his E Street
brothers for the first time in 12 years _ and the bonhomie was
evident from the first, crackling number, ``My Love Will Not Let
You Down,'' from Springsteen's boxed set, ``Tracks.'' They pushed
him, he pushed them, and there was none of the tentativeness that
marred the '92 tour.
</P>
<P>
   What made it more special was the pairing for the first time of
guitarists Nils Lofgren and Miami Steve Van Zandt, who had
previously been in the band at different times. They came out arm
in arm and they played that way, giving more muscle to the
harder-rocking songs, while staying out of each other's way
beautifully on softer numbers.
</P>
<P>
   During the first half of Thursday night's show, the normally
loquacious Springsteen said barely a word, preferring just to play
music. If you had a band that handled like a Ferrari, wouldn't you
drive it? As Springsteen sang in the tumultuous ``Out on the
Street'': ``I'll drive the way I want to drive.''
</P>
<P>
   And he drove ferociously early on, belting through ``Promised
Land,'' ``Two Hearts,'' ``Darkness on the Edge of Town'' (still as
apocalyptic as ever), and an archival treat, ``Darlington County.''
</P>
<P>
   He then changed the mood radically, offering the Hank
Williams-style country of ``Mansion on the Hill'' and an artful
reworking of ``The River,'' with Lofgren on pedal steel and Van
Zandt on mandolin. It showed that Springsteen is not treating his
music like a collection of fossils, but is determined to bring new
life to it. And he ended the song with a keening wail that
transfixed the crowd and showed that his vocal range has grown, not
ebbed, in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   He picked things up with the blue-collar ``Youngstown'' and
erupted on ``Badlands'' (playing his own raging lead guitar solo)
and ``10th Avenue Freezeout.'' The latter brought his first verbal
reminiscence about his Jersey boyhood, ``when I walked down the
avenue of lust . . . fear . . . hope . . . despair . . .
self-interest . . . and the avenue of sexual pleasure, a popular
avenue.'' He later revisited his youth in a new tune, ``Freehold,''
a sardonic, coffeehouse-style, ``Whitmanesque'' solo ditty that
recalled his Catholic grammar school education and his ``first kiss
in a YMCA canteen on a Friday night.''
</P>
<P>
   Springsteen's softer side was marked by a solo ``Ghost of Tom
Joad'' and a haunting ``Streets of Philadelphia,'' but he soon
revved up again with ``Backstreets'' (with saxophonist Clarence
Clemons blowing feverishly), a metallic ``Light of Day,'' and
delirious encores spanning ``Hungry Heart,'' ``Bobby Jean,'' and
``Thunder Road.'' It was just the thunder the crowd had waited all
these years to hear.
</P>
</TEXT>
