<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-OIL (Washington) _ Mexico's energy secretary says
accusations by small U.S. oil producers that Mexico is dumping oil
on U.S. markets are ``irrational and completely unwarranted.'' The
small oil producers have asked the Commerce Department to impose
tariffs on oil from Mexico and three other countries. Large U.S.
oil producers and U.S. Energy Secretary Bill Richardson dismiss the
claims. By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-DIVIDE (Washington) _ Calling access to the Internet
the next great civil rights battle, Sens. John D. Rockefeller,
D-W.Va., and Bill Frist, R-Tenn., say the federal government must
increase funding for programs to help get minorities and people
living in rural areas get on line. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   CISNEROS-HEARING (Washington) _ The federal judge handling the
conspiracy case against former Housing Secretary Henry Cisneros
hints that he may allow the jury in the upcoming trial to hear at
least portions of the tapes made by Cisneros' former mistress.
Defense lawyers sought to suppress the tapes as evidence,
contending the recordings had been copied or altered. By GARY
MARTIN.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-2000 (Des Moines, Iowa) _ As Texas Gov. George W. Bush
walked away, Gregg White assessed his performance: ``He was good.
He's a natural.'' Good politician? Natural campaigner? No. Good,
natural pancake flipper. And baby kisser, and hand shaker, and
autograph signer and patient listener _ even when a young man
insists on discussing the esoteria of soil conservation. By CRAGG
HINES.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SERIAL-KILLER (Houston) _ Accused serial killer Angel Maturino
Resendez was scheduled to meet with Mexican government officials to
seek their help with his case. His lawyer met with the officials
for two hours Thursday night. By STEVE BREWER and MARIA LUISA
PEREZ.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WORKING-COLUMN (Houston) _ For the most part, performance
evaluations are pretty painful. Most managers hate talking about a
subordinate's shortcomings and no employee likes to get the word
that he's anything short of perfect. But there are ways to turn
evaluations into useful tools to improve employee performance. By
L.M. SIXEL
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (Houston) _ The Houston Astros try for their fifth
consecutive victory as they face the Detroit Tigers tonight at the
Astrodome. By JOSEPH DUARTE.
</P>
<P>
   With: BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   BBN-EVERETT (Houston) _ We look at Carl Everett's injury and who
will be called up to replace him for the Houston Astros. By NEIL
HOHLFELD.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-BRITISH (Carnoustie, Scotland) _ Full coverage of the second
round of the British Open golf tournament. By EDDIE SEFKO.
</P>
<P>
   TEN-DAVIS (Boston) _ Full coverage of the opening singles
matches at the Davis Cup quarterfinal match between the United
States and Australia. By JODY GOLDSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY-SENATE (Washington) _ U.S. military pilots practice
their bombing skills on a remote tropical island off Puerto Rico, a
long way from New York and the burgeoning Senate campaign of
Hillary Rodham Clinton. But the first lady will soon confront a
political dilemma: Will she support Puerto Rico's demands for
permanent cessation of training on Vieques to help her win the
political support from 2 million Puerto Ricans in New York state?
Or will she support the U.S. Navy's insistence that the training is
needed to protect America's military readiness. Lawmakers with ties
to Puerto Rico are calling for the first lady to take a stand. By
STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   CLINICAL-CANCER-TRIALS (Washington) __ The patients' rights
legislation that the Senate passed last week would help cancer
patients in federal clinical trials get more financial aid from
their managed care providers. Clinical trials are often viewed as
the last beacon of hope for seriously or terminally ill people for
whom traditional therapies have failed. By JUDY HOLLAND..
</P>
<P>
   GOD-BILLBOARDS (Washington) _ God is speaking to commuters from
billboards across the country. With Madison Avenue cleverness, the
Lord is delivering brief messages designed to amuse _ and prod the
fallen back to their pews. One message in Florida, cast in large
white letters against a stark field of black, asks, ``You think
it's hot here?'' and is signed ``God.'' By ERIC ROSENBERG. (Filed
Thursday.)
</P>
<P>
   TEACHING-HOSPITALS (Washington) _ With a boost from Hillary
Clinton, the plight of the nation's 400 teaching hospitals is
becoming a hot-button issue not only in her New York campaign for
the Senate but also in the nation's capital as Congress debates the
future of Medicare. By DAN FREEDMAN. (Filed Thursday.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ By traveling to poverty-ridden
areas of the country recently , Bill Clinton, the ``New Democrat''
who has aligned himself with the aspirations of the middle class,
sought to strengthen his link to the old Democrats who were
concerned with the welfare of the downtrodden. By ROBERT E.
THOMPSON. (Filed Wednesday.)
</P>
