</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-MELONS-ART-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: what hit you.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MELON AND GOAT CHEESE SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Berkeley Bar and Grill
</P>
<P>
   Time: 12 minutes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   36 balls ripe yellow watermelon
</P>
<P>
   16 balls ripe red watermelon
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons soft fresh goat cheese
</P>
<P>
   8 teaspoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   8 large basil leaves, julienned
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Place 9 yellow watermelon balls in center of each of four
plates, and top with 4 red watermelon balls. Sprinkle bits of goat
cheese around plate.
</P>
<P>
   2. Whisk oil and vinegar, and spoon over melon and cheese. Strew
basil leaves around, and season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   CHILLED MELON AND YELLOW TOMATO SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Chianti
</P>
<P>
   Time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   3 large ripe yellow tomatoes, about 1 pound
</P>
<P>
   1 ripe cantaloupe, 2{ to 2} pounds
</P>
<P>
   12 fresh mint leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   \ cup lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon lime juice
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Cook onions over very low heat in olive oil until soft, about
5 minutes. Coarsely chop 2 tomatoes, and add to onion to warm
slightly.
</P>
<P>
   2. Remove skin from cantaloupe, seed and coarsely dice,
reserving \ cup of dice. Place tomato mixture and some of the diced
cantaloupe in blender, and puree, adding more melon until mixture
has the consistency of pureed soup, adding water if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   3. Add 4 mint leaves, Worcestershire sauce, lemon juice and lime
juice, and puree until smooth. Season with salt and pepper, and
chill well.
</P>
<P>
   4. Finely chop reserved cantaloupe. Finely chop remaining tomato
to yield { cup. Julienne remaining mint. Garnish each bowl of soup,
placing chopped cantaloupe and chopped tomato in center and
strewing with mint.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   CALAMARI, WATERMELON AND AVOCADO SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Union Pacific
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4 cups fresh cilantro, plus { cup for garnish
</P>
<P>
   \ cup rice wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon grape-seed oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces cleaned squid, cut into rings, including tentacles
</P>
<P>
   1 egg white, beaten
</P>
<P>
   1{ teaspoons ground coriander
</P>
<P>
   1} tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1{ teaspoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1{ tablespoons finely chopped shallots
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fines herbes (mixed chervil, tarragon,
chives and parsley)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces baby salad greens, washed and dried
</P>
<P>
   16 thin slices of watermelon, rind and seeds removed, cut into
1-inch squares
</P>
<P>
   8 \-inch-thick slices of avocado. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Prepare cilantro vinaigrette: Fill saucepan half full of
water, and bring to boil. Set aside a bowl of ice water. Place 4
cups cilantro in boiling water, and immediately lift out with
slotted spoon and transfer to ice water. Squeeze cilantro dry. In a
blender, combine cilantro, rice wine vinegar and grape-seed oil.
Puree until smooth. Transfer to a bowl, and season with salt and
pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   2. Prepare calamari: In medium bowl, combine squid, egg white
and ground coriander; mix well. In large saute pan over medium-high
heat, heat 1 tablespoon olive oil until it is smoking. Add squid
mixture, and saute until it is translucent, about 2 minutes. Add
butter, and stir until melted. Add 1 tablespoon shallots, stir, and
remove pan from heat. Add fines herbes and salt and pepper to
taste. Toss to mix well.
</P>
<P>
   3. Prepare lemon vinaigrette: In small bowl, combine lemon
juice, remaining olive oil, and salt and pepper to taste. Set
aside.
</P>
<P>
   4. Grate zest from lemon and reserve. Remove white pith and
seeds, and cut lemon into segments. In mixing bowl, combine lemon
zest, lemon segments, salad greens, remaining shallots, calamari
and lemon vinaigrette. Toss quickly to blend well.
</P>
<P>
   5. To serve, spread calamari mixture in center of large serving
platter. Arrange watermelon and avocado decoratively on top. Pour
ring of cilantro vinaigrette over salad, and drizzle vinaigrette
decoratively around edge of plate. Garnish with cilantro leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   MELON AND ORGANIC STRAWBERRY SOUP WITH FRUIT SORBET
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Bouley Bakery
</P>
<P>
   Time: 15 minutes, plus 1 hour for chilling  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 small melon (Cavaillon, cantaloupe or honeydew), skin and
seeds removed, cut into 1-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon acacia or other good-quality honey
</P>
<P>
   [ teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons flat mineral water
</P>
<P>
   1 pint organic strawberries, washed and hulled
</P>
<P>
   1 pint strawberry sorbet
</P>
<P>
   { pint raspberries
</P>
<P>
   { cup skinned and seeded fresh litchis, or { cup canned litchis
(available in Asian markets and specialty food stores).
</P>
<P>
   1. In blender, combine melon, honey, salt and mineral water.
Blend until smooth and creamy, and then transfer mixture to a bowl.
Rinse container of blender.
</P>
<P>
   2. Puree strawberries until smooth. Strain through fine sieve to
remove seeds, and then transfer mixture to a bowl. Cover both bowls
of pureed fruit, and refrigerate until chilled, at least 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   3. To serve, pour 3 tablespoons of melon puree into each of six
chilled soup bowls. Pour 3 tablespoons of strawberry puree into
center of each bowl, to make concentric circles of fruit puree.
Place a scoop of sorbet into center of each bowl, and garnish with
raspberries and litchis. Serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 small servings.
</P>
<P>
   With the simplest embellishment, a melon can be transformed into
a light dessert or refreshing first course. Here are a few
suggestions:
</P>
<P>
   _ Cut a small melon like a Cavaillon in half, remove the seeds
and make a few slashes in the flesh. Fill the cavity with port wine
or moscato d'Asti, and refrigerate for eight hours or more. Or do
what Le Cirque 2000 does: serve a glass of port on the side, or
pour it in.
</P>
<P>
   _ For James Beard's Drunken Melon, cut a 2-inch-square plug in a
watermelon deep enough to go into the cavity. Deeply prick the
flesh with an ice pick, and fill to near the top with light rum,
Cognac, Champagne or gin. Replace the plug, and seal with heavy
tape. Refrigerate the melon for 24 hours, turning it over four or
five times. Serve sliced.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sprinkle slices or chunks with lime juice and dash of cayenne.
</P>
<P>
   _ Serve thin slices with prosciutto and figs, or with capocollo
or Smithfield ham and freshly ground black pepper.
</P>
<P>
   _ Drizzle wedges with hazelnut or orange liqueur, or sprinkle
with powdered ginger or finely cut candied ginger.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gently toss watermelon cubes in a mixture of lime juice,
tequila, hot pepper sauce and salt.
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind that room-temperature melons have the best flavor
but that in the heat of summer, the well-chilled melon is most
appealing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
