A2927 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINICAL-CANCER-TRIAL     07-16 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINICAL-CANCER-TRIALS-$ADV18-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATIENTS' RIGHTS BILL BOOSTS HOPE FOR CANCER PATIENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 18)   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The patients rights' legislation that passed the
Senate last week held some good news for cancer patients seeking to
participate in federal clinical trials.
</P>
<P>
   In some instances, the bill would require managed care providers
to pay for costs related to the trials.
</P>
<P>
   A patient in a clinical trial agrees to undergo an experimental
treatment so researchers can test a new drug, device, or
combination of already approved treatments that have shown promise.
Such trials are often the last recourse for patients who haven't
been helped by traditional therapies.
</P>
<P>
   While the drug company or the manufacturer picks up the cost of
the new treatment, other expenses such as hospitalization, extra
tests and additional doctor visits often are not paid for by either
the drug company or the patient's managed care plan.
</P>
<P>
   Many would-be trial participants are deterred from taking part
because those extra expenses _ for an extra CT scan or a surgical
procedure that might be needed to monitor potential affects of a
new treatment _ can run into the thousands of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate measure would require some managed care providers to
pay ``routine patient costs'' of cancer clinical trials sponsored
by the National Institutes of Health, the Department of Veterans
Affairs or the Department of Defense.
</P>
<P>
   Federal researchers are now conducting more than 2,000 cancer
clinical trials. Such trials may have as few as a dozen
participants or as many as 30,000.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Connie Mack, R-Fla., the prime sponsor of the proposal,
claimed that cost is the primary reason that only 2 percent of
cancer patients agree to take part in clinical trials.
</P>
<P>
   Mack is a survivor of melanoma. His wife, Priscilla, is a breast
cancer survivor and their daughter, Debbie, is a cervical cancer
survivor. Mack lost his younger brother, Michael to melanoma, his
mother died of esophageal cancer and his mother died of kidney
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., complained that valuable medical
research is being jeopardized because, she said, HMOs are cutting
back on paying costs associated with clinical trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are starting to see fewer clinical trials because HMOs
won't pay,'' she said. ``That not only hurts the patients but
stands in the way of research.''
</P>
<P>
   Mack likens participants in clinical trials to astronauts who
are willing to risk their lives to push science into new frontiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cancer clinical trials are one of the most beneficial ways
doctors can determine which treatments are most effective against
cancer,'' Mack said. He said the new bill ``breaks down the cost
barrier and ensures that our family, friends and loved ones are not
shut out from receiving promising new treatments simply because of
cost.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate measure would apply to 48 million people who receive
health care coverage through large employers who insure themselves
by funding their own claims and hiring a managed care provider to
administer the plan.
</P>
<P>
   It would not apply to 113 million people with private insurance.
And it would not apply to hundreds of clinical trials conducted by
pharmaceutical companies and academic medical centers.
</P>
<P>
   The House has yet to consider patients' rights legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Mary McCabe, director of the office of clinical research
promotion for the National Cancer Institute, the nation's chief
cancer funding agency, said the Senate legislation is ``very
important good news for the oncology community. It's an opportunity
both for patients and for researchers to conduct clinical trials
and get important answers to cancer questions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate rejected a proposal sponsored by Sen. Christopher J.
Dodd, D-Conn., that would have required health plans to pay costs
connected with all federally sponsored clinical trials, including
clinical trials of diseases such as AIDS, Parkinsons and Alzheimers
disease, multiple sclerosis, diabetes and Lupus.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sens. Bill Frist, R-Tenn., a physician who takes a leadership
role on almost all health-related legislation, said Republicans
decided to limit the coverage to cancer patients because they
didn't ``want to impose exorbitant costs'' on managed care
providers.
</P>
<P>
   Frist said the Democratic proposal ``opens the door so broadly
it has the potential for premiums to skyrocket.'' He said there
isn't enough data on clinical trials for diseases other than cancer
to know how much the associated costs could be.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP legislation would set up a panel to determine by 2000
which ``routine patient costs'' should be paid by insurers.
</P>
<P>
   Carmella Bocchino, vice president for medical affairs for the
American Association of Health Plans, which represents the managed
care industry, says it's unclear how much money is involved in
``costs associated with routine patient care.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You could put five people in a room and ask them to define
routine patient care and you'd get six different answers,'' she
said. ``There could be a whole slew of tests'' needed to take part
in a trial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-99 1657EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990716.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2935 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALGERIAN-EXILES-760(2     07-16 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALGERIAN-EXILES-760(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPLANTED IN FRANCE, ALGERIAN ARTS BLOOM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: France)  (js) 
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ As Algeria's civil war escalated through the 1990s, the
demise of the country's cultural and intellectual life seemed
almost incidental compared to a civilian death toll rising above
50,000 and an economy in disarray. Culture, however, was not an
accidental casualty of war. In a carefully orchestrated campaign to
smother intellectual freedom, artists, movie and theater directors,
writers, singers and journalists were singled out for death threats
and murder.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding the terror, it was never clear who was ordering the
killings. Islamic fundamentalists who took up arms in the early
1990s were blamed for most attacks on what they considered decadent
Western-influenced culture, but the army-backed regime and its
shadowy allies were also infamously intolerant of criticism. ``Not
only the Islamists kill, that's for sure,'' Karim Sarroub, a young
Algerian novelist, said in an interview. ``Neither side likes
intellectuals.''
</P>
<P>
   The murder of some 70 journalists over an eight-year period
decimated Algeria's tiny independent press, while the assassination
of prominent cultural figures _ among them the revered popular
singers Cheb Hasni and Matoub Lounes, the playwright Abdelkader
Alloula, the poet Tahar Djaout and the director of the national
theater, Azzedamine Medjoubi _ demonstrated that no one was safe.
Soon, a good part of the surviving cultural elite had fled the
country, with most of them seeking exile in France.
</P>
<P>
   What followed, though, was not what the enemies of artistic
expression in Algeria might have hoped. Instead of fading away,
contemporary Algerian culture is now very much alive and well _ in
exile.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crisis has led to an extraordinary explosion of energy,''
said Rachida Krim, a French-born Algerian movie director whose
recent films, ``Sous les Pieds des Femmes'' (``Under Women's
Feet'') and ``La Femme Devoilee'' (``The Unveiled Woman''), have
focused on Arab women. ``Algerian writers, musicians, painters,
moviemakers and actors have never been so active. They have an
energy that children of immigrants rarely show. They work hard with
the intention of learning what they can.''
</P>
<P>
   Leila Marouane, a former journalist in her early 30s whose life
was repeatedly threatened in Algeria, is just one writer who has
seen her career blossom since she settled here six years ago. Her
first novel, ``La Fille de la Casbah,'' was published in 1996 and
short-listed for the prestigious Prix Goncourt, while her second,
``Ravisseur,'' published here last year, will appear in English as
``The Abductor'' next year. ``If I can return to Algeria, I will do
so with pleasure,'' she said. ``But only when it is really safe. I
don't want to find myself chopped up into pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   Exile is of course a path taken by generations of independent
artists determined to escape persecution and preserve their
creative freedom. Just this century, for example, untold thousands
fled Hitler's Germany, Communist governments in Europe, Cuba and
China, and right-wing dictatorships in Spain, Latin America, Greece
and South Africa. Some, like the black American writers who came to
Paris in the 1950s, simply felt more welcome abroad. And frequently
their best work was done in exile.
</P>
<P>
   The Algerians' choice of France as a safe haven is logical. For
one thing, it is Algeria's former colonial ruler and already home
to close to 1 million Algerian immigrants. For another, educated
Algerians are French-speakers and familiar with French culture,
which, even after independence in 1962, continued to exercise
influence in Algeria. ``The French I speak is part of my Algerian
cultural identity,'' said Hamid Tassili, 31, a movie director who
moved here three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   France also has other attractions. While cultural activity in
Algeria was limited as much by the economic crisis as by political
threats, France provides huge government subsidies for the arts,
above all for museums, the movie industry, theater, classical music
and dance. Further, French publishers have shown special interest
in foreign authors writing in French. In France Algerian artists
have found a structure within which to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could not have lived off my writing in Algeria,'' explained
a journalist turned novelist known only by the initials Y.B., whose
latest book is called ``L'Explication'' (``The Explanation'').
``There was no way a writer could dedicate two years to writing a
book and stay alive. Here, if you are careful, you can live off
royalties.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The greatest success story, though, involves Algerian rai
singers because their success is truly commercial. Some already had
big followings in Algeria and across North Africa before the
crisis, but in exile they have been snapped up by international
record companies and turned into stars. They have a natural
audience in Western Europe's vast North African immigrant
population, but rai love songs have also benefited from the growing
popularity of world music. ``Rai is almost middle-class French
music now,'' said Y.B.
</P>
<P>
   Khaled, a handsome and charming performer now in his 40s who
sings in French as well as Arabic, is the best-known Algerian
singer today. But many others, among them Cheb Mami, Rachid Taha
and Cheba Fadela, routinely draw thousands to their concerts. One
of the youngest stars, Faudel Belloua, was in fact born in France
of Algerian parents, but his music, a mixture of rai, rap and
world-music pop, also has its roots in the Algerian tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Other exiled artists also use Algeria as raw material for their
creative work. Ms. Marouane's ``Abductor,'' for instance, portrays
the isolated universe of Algerian women through the story of a
middle-aged couple whose love for each other is undermined by
Islamic law. Amin Zaoui, who was supported by the Strasbourg-based
International Writers' Parliament after he fled Algeria in 1994,
uses Algeria's violence as the background for the two stories in
his 1998 book, ``Le Sommeil du Mimosa'' (``The Sleep of Mimosa'').
Abdelkader Djemai named his new novel, ``31, Rue de l'Aigle'' (``31
Eagle Road'') after the fictional address of a secret police unit
in Algiers.
</P>
<P>
   The theater world has also brought Algeria's problems to the
French stage. One of the first of a slew of plays, Slimane
Benaissa's ``Fils de l'Amertume'' (``Sons of Bitterness''),
illustrates the divisions in Algeria through Farid, a rootless
young man who becomes an Islamic extremist, and Youcef, a veteran
journalist whom Farid is ordered to murder. Another play, ``Algerie
en Eclats'' (``Algeria in Pieces''), set in a theater during a
rehearsal, uses texts from 21 Algerian writers, six of whom have
been murdered. An Algerian actor known only as Fellag has also
toured his one-man show around France.
</P>
<P>
   French-speaking Algerian actors have been able to find work in
French movies or on television, albeit invariably playing Arabs.
Some Algerian movie directors, eager to make films about Algeria,
occasionally return home to work, although they assume great risks
when they go on location. On the other hand, French production
companies have been willing to back a few Algerian movies, aware of
residual French interest in what for almost two centuries was
France's most important colony.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the least visible of exiled Algerian artists are
painters and sculptors, if only because visual arts education in
Algeria was traditionally limited. Nonetheless, a few like Slimane
Ould Mohand and Mahdjoub Ben Bella have been picked up by French
galleries and have had one-man exhibitions. The abstract painter
Ali Silem and the sculptor Abdel-slam Graine have also begun to win
recognition.
</P>
<P>
   That said, except for those with families already in France,
exiles often face economic difficulties and adjustment problems.
``For the first few months, I was depressed,'' recalled Tassili,
who worked with Ms. Krim on ``La Femme Devoilee.'' ``Then I
thought, `I can express myself through my work and can remain in
touch with my culture and my country.'''
</P>
<P>
   French society can also be unwelcoming toward Arabs. ``In my
building, there is only one person who treats me without
condescension,'' Ms. Marouane said with a laugh. ``She is blind.
She can only hear my voice.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, given the horrors regularly convulsing Algeria, the mood
of the exiled artists here is upbeat. They are safe, and many of
them are enjoying more success than would have been possible in
Algeria. Unsurprisingly, they have no immediate plans to return
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Algerian culture is going through a period of great
vitality,'' said Y.B., ``but it's happening outside our
frontiers.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
