<HEADLINE>
SENATORS WARN OF GAP IN INTERNET USE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Calling access to the Internet the next great civil
rights battle, two senators promised Friday to fight for programs
aimed at helping minorities and rural residents get online.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John D. Rockefeller, D-W.Va., said a recent Commerce
Department report showing growing gaps in Internet use between
whites and some minorities and between urban and rural Americans
was a ``threat'' to the country's political system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our democracy is based on informed voters and on the idea that
each citizen has the same opportunities to succeed,'' he told a
meeting of the Senate Science and Technology Caucus that was
studying the report's findings.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Unless we change these trends, opportunity to use
the Internet will become this country's next great civil rights
fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bill Frist, R-Tenn., said many parts of American society
have been left out of what he called the ``phenomenal'' growth of
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to make sure that when the free market fails to
service a group of people that they are not forgotten and left
without the same opportunities as everyone else,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A Commerce Department study released last week showed that black
and Hispanic families were less than half as likely as non-Hispanic
whites to explore the Internet from home, work or school.
</P>
<P>
   The study, the third and most comprehensive to be conducted by
the Commerce Department over the last three years, reinforced the
fear that minority-group members are increasingly at a disadvantage
in competing for the hottest entry-level jobs in the nation, which
require a knowledge of computers and comfort in using the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Among the study's findings:
</P>
<P>
   _ College graduates are nearly three times as likely to use the
Internet as high-school dropouts.
</P>
<P>
   _ Households with incomes of $75,000 or higher are more than 20
times as likely to use the Internet than those of the lowest income
levels, less than $15,000, and more than nine times as likely to
have a computer.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nearly one-third of non-Hispanic white households had Internet
access in 1998, compared to 12 percent of black households and 13
percent of Hispanic households. Thirty-six percent of
Asian-American households had Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   _ Except for those with incomes of $75,000 or more, people
living in rural areas are 50 percent less likely to be connected to
the Internet than people in urban areas.
</P>
<P>
   Commerce Secretary William M. Daley told the caucus that the
federal government could help lower the nation's ``digital divide''
by investing in community computer training centers to make
technology more accessible.
</P>
<P>
   He added that all schools and libraries should provide Internet
access to ensure that every person has the opportunity to go
online.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that education and access are the keys to getting
people to use the Internet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rockefeller, whose state ranked 48th in Internet use, said he
would push Congress to fund programs that shrink the digital
divide. He added that Congress and the Clinton administration
should begin implementing these programs immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to wait five years to do something and watch
West Virginia fall so far behind it can't catch up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Frist, whose state ranked 42nd in Internet use, agreed, saying
``minorities and people living in rural areas need help immediately
to compete in the information age.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-99 1705EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990716.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2947 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANDBAG-MANIA-ART-$AD     07-16 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDBAG-MANIA-ART-$ADV18-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: 15 bags.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Luxury labels like Givenchy, Gucci and Chanel have long looked
to logo-bearing accessories for the bulk of their sales. A $600
Gucci bag costs a fraction of a $3,000 designer outfit. Clothing
sells a house's image on the runway and in glossy advertising, but
it's the more affordable accessories (and perfume) that ring up
profits. ``You get the name out there, like Gucci, but the image is
the bag,'' Ms. Steele said. ``It is a hot object that everyone will
covet.''
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Sheik, a Gucci spokeswoman, said that bags, wallets and
other leather goods (excluding shoes) accounted for 43.9 percent of
Gucci's $1 billion in sales in 1998. The slice for apparel, 12.1
percent, was much smaller.
</P>
<P>
   In the last five years, traditional fashion houses have
reinvented themselves by hiring hip young designers _ Tom Ford at
Gucci, John Galliano at Dior, Marc Jacobs at Louis Vuitton _ and
their accessories, in turn, have acquired a new cachet. In January
1997, after Galliano showed his first Dior collection, sales of the
Lady Dior bag _ quilted and adorned with the house's jangling, gilt
letters _ increased 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a clubbiness to bag ownership,'' said Josh Patner, a
partner in the New York clothing label Tuleh. ``Who are you? A
Fendi girl? A Kate Spade girl? The bag says everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Charting the history of status bags, Ms. Steele identified the
Chanel quilted, gilt-chain purse, first created by Coco Chanel in
1955, as the pre-eminent signifier of luxury in the early 1980s. In
1985, Prada supplanted Chanel when it introduced its now-legendary
black nylon backpack. ``It revolutionized everything,'' Ms. Steele
said. ``It became the iconic thing that made all other handbags
seem dowdy. It made you look automatically young and hip, like blue
jeans in the '60s. It had a non-fashiony appeal. It drew on
military and sporting prototypes. It was small, stripped down, sexy
and made of high-tech materials.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is the Fendi baguette, the artful little shoulder bag
bedazzled with everything from sequins to mother-of-pearl and so
named because it can be carried under the arm like a loaf of French
bread, that is credited with the current bag mania. ``Fendi started
the buying-a-bag-a-day habit, having the pink one, the mirrored
one,'' Ms. Kessler of Vogue said. ``There are about 300 bags. It's
impossible to choose, so you want more than one.''
</P>
<P>
   Fendiphiles like Ms. Donahue describe their habit in the
language of 12-steppers. ``Fendi is a sickness, an addiction,'' she
admitted feebly. ``I feel like I need AA for bags, and my husband
is my enabler. He doesn't stop me.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the fall of 1997, when the baguette was introduced, there
have been 500 variations, ranging from a $475 black nylon bag to a
$12,000 hand-loomed version of which only a handful were made. Once
a design has been fabricated, it is never repeated, imparting to
the baguettes the status of collectibles.
</P>
<P>
   The hype surrounding the Fendi baguette began after the company
held a legendary sample sale in December 1997. The bags had yet to
take off, and the company offered them to fashion insiders,
including many magazine editors, for the staggeringly low price of
$50 apiece, $100 for the fur variety, with no limit on how many
could be bought. Not long after, during the European fashion
collections in March 1998, legions of fashion editors, who showed
up with their cheaply acquired baguettes, were widely photographed,
and a trend was born.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the cleverest sample sale in terms of the timing,''
recalled Sally Singer, fashion director of New York magazine, who
will become fashion news director of Vogue next month. ``That's how
Fendi primed the market to make their bags and logo impossibly
chic.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, handbag chic has broadened and deepened to encompass many
labels, including less expensive and unfamiliar ones. Young handbag
designers with a whimsical touch are thriving in the current
climate. At Intermix, the Upper East Side and downtown stores,
beaded, embroidered pashmina shoulder bags by Mandala are in high
demand at $250. In the last month and a half, the stores have sold
100 bags. Jane Burley, a designer for Buzz by Jane Fox, whose
canvas bags are decorated with an embroidered bumblebee and sell at
Barneys for $160 to $200, said: ``People are buying the bigger
brands. But they're also seeking out smaller brands to be more
individual. To have a bag that isn't Gucci or Fendi is also
happening right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Lambertson Truex, a handbag line started in March 1998 by
Richard Lambertson and John Truex, ranging from $335 for a wool
felt bag to $6,000 for an alligator design, grossed $1.2 million in
its first year, and the company has already earned close to that
from fall orders alone. At Bergdorf Goodman, one of the 42 stores
where the collection is available, the latest totes in animal
prints are sold out, and there is a two-month waiting list.
</P>
<P>
   The fashion designer John Bartlett, who carries a Lambertson
Truex briefcase, explained why the line has taken off. ``In
America, there's not too many people doing what they're doing,
which is to bridge American simplicity with Italian
craftsmanship,'' he said. ``They bring new meaning to the idea of
American luxury.''
</P>
<P>
   The unavailability of a bag sometimes makes it even more
coveted. When Marc Jacobs designed his first runway collection for
Louis Vuitton for fall 1998, he created a snappy line of
accessories in patent leather, in a youthful palette of baby blue
and beige, bearing the famous logo.
</P>
<P>
   But the bags were at first only available in Paris and London.
It drove some American women crazy. They clamored to get on a
waiting list. Even today, when the bags are easier to come by,
there is an average of 100 people waiting for a phone call saying
the latest model has arrived, a company spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   To ensure exclusivity and heighten the buzz, designer bags may
be released in limited editions or they may be named after fashion
icons, like Tod's Lady Di tote or Gucci's Jackie bag (inspired by
Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis, who carried an earlier version of the
single-strap shoulder bag in the '60s.)
</P>
<P>
   Gucci's Jackie bag is so popular _ more than 30,000 have been
sold worldwide since it was reintroduced in October 1998 _ that in
January, when the flagship store in New York held a spring trunk
show introducing a new turquoise Jackie bag, a customer wanted his
girlfriend to be the first woman in the city to have it. He offered
to pay three times the price of $575. But the bag was a sample, so
the store declined. Naturally, the customer was put on a waiting
list.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
