<SLUG> BC-NITEOUT-PLATT-ART-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NIGHT OUT WITH OLIVER PLATT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 18)  
 (af)  
 By LINDA LEE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Look out, it leaks,'' Oliver Platt warned his
companions as his 1985 Jeep Wagoneer went through the pulsing jets
of the Broadway-Houston Car Wash in downtown Manhattan. On July 7,
the night before, Platt had been chatting with David Letterman
about his part as a pompous crocodile expert in the horror spoof
``Lake Placid.''
</P>
<P>
   On this night, looking somewhat more disheveled, he was escaping
from his East Village household to run errands before the family's
drive to Maine the next day.
</P>
<P>
   With him was his best friend, the screenwriter David Schwab (as
in the Schwab drugstore Schwabs). The two men are the kind of
buddies who finish each other's burgers.
</P>
<P>
   First order of business: getting the Jeep (120,000 miles on the
odometer) through the carwash in one piece. The experience was as
wet and rollicking as a theme-park ride. The Jeep, which Platt
bought used after filming ``Indecent Proposal,'' and had modified
by ripping off the fake wood paneling, emerged from the wash a
surprising, gleaming black.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daddy drives the stuff car,'' Platt said, ``where you carry
the stuff, maybe one kid.'' Everyone else _ the nanny; his wife,
Camilla; his children, 5, 2{ and 6 months _ would ride to Maine,
where they would spend the rest of the summer, in the family car.
</P>
<P>
   Walking down University Place, the men hashed over Tom Junod's
chat with Nicole Kidman (in bed) in Esquire. This led to the theme
of bad behavior. Platt, perhaps best known for his role as the
cocaine-sniffing political aide to Warren Beatty in the movie
``Bullworth,'' confessed, ``I was thrown out of three schools in
the ninth grade in Japan.'' (Platt's father was a career diplomat.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to 12 schools before I graduated from high school,'' he
said. In ninth grade he bottomed out. The offense: smoking
marijuana. Eventually, he found his way at a progressive boarding
school in Colorado, and earned a degree in theater arts from Tufts
University.
</P>
<P>
   Off to Metro Drugs, where the Rabelaisian Platt said he needed
``beauty products'' for himself. Though a casual observer might
have said he could use a lot of them, all he got was a Citre-Shine
shampoo. Then he launched into the children's aisle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cheesy toys are essential as a last line of defense in a
car,'' Platt said. ``Tattoo You _ that's a good one. Your Robo Man,
your Lipstick Surprise Kit.''
</P>
<P>
   A whole $59.51 later and with the hard work over, the two walked
to the 3 Z Cafe. Schwab was going with the ``famous'' rice pudding.
Platt settled on the barbecued cheeseburger with mushrooms. ``Taste
this,'' Schwab commanded. ``This is the best rice pudding I've ever
had.''
</P>
<P>
   Platt sampled it. ``Taste this barbecued burger,'' Platt said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That IS good,'' Schwab said, as he moved in on the remaining
portions. Platt, who was raised the middle of three sons, looked
prepared to protect his food with sharp cutlery. He shared the
secret of making a horror film in which you spend a lot of time in
the water in British Columbia ``looking'' for a crocodile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neoprene bodysuit,'' he said. ``It traps the air and makes you
buoyant.'' Almost as if he were a crocodile himself. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
