<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-FRENZY-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMER TIME AND THE HYPE IS HOPPING  
(DW) 

</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bathed in the glow of a giant television screen in the Virgin
Megastore at Union Square, a couple stood watching Madonna's latest
video, ``Beautiful Stranger,'' last week. As the ever-trendy singer
cavorted with a snaggle-toothed 60s throwback in a velvet suit and
ruffled shirt, one turned to the other and said, ``This is that
Austin Shag guy or whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   Somehow these two Megastore shoppers missed the mega-blitz
surrounding ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me'' _ the Virgin
Atlantic billboards and bus shelter ads, the collectible action
figures, the box office boasting (it toppled ``Star Wars: The
Phantom Menace'' in its opening weekend), and this Madonna song,
the first single from the movie's soundtrack. This oblivious couple
apparently had never used the word ``shagadelic'' in their lives.
What rock had they been under, I wondered. More important, is there
room under that rock for me?
</P>
<P>
   This summer, hype _ the marketing of popular culture _ has
reached a fever pitch. ``Star Wars,'' Ricky Martin, ``Eyes Wide
Shut'' _ there has been a next-big-thing every week, and often a
Time magazine cover to ballyhoo it. Whether camping out for
science-fiction movie tickets, screaming behind police barricades
as a Latin singer dazzles a ``Today'' show audience, or waiting
with baited breath for a glimpse of a Hollywood power couple in the
buff, we are in the middle of ``mania mania.'' It is a cultural
frenzy leading up to New Year's Eve 1999, the party to end all,
perhaps literally if Y2K horror stories are to be believed.
</P>
<P>
   It's all too exciting.
</P>
<P>
   The upside of all this enthusiasm, of course, is that there's
always somewhere fabulous to be these days: Cher's sold-out concert
at Madison Square Garden last week, Bruce Springsteen's 15-night
stand at the Meadowlands, Bette Midler's millennial blowout at the
Mandalay Bay hotel on Dec. 31 in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, there are corn-flavored ice creams to eat and ginger
cosmopolitans to drink, and new boutiques in uncharted parts of
14th Street to plunder. There's always a hot new movie to line up
for: ``Tarzan,'' ``Big Daddy,'' ``Wild, Wild West,'' ``American
Pie,'' and whatever opened biggest this weekend. Everything is a
blockbuster, so why wait until it's at Blockbuster?
</P>
<P>
   Go, go, go!
</P>
<P>
   But all this activity, and the accompanying pressure to have a
good time, is exhausting. In the rush to be part of the moment that
marketers have told us is going on _ to be there, see it all, and
buy the T-shirt _ we end up smothered. Anything good _ Cher's
comeback album, Martin's gyrating hips, Mike Myer's randy superspy
_ becomes so ubiquitous, we end up hating it in a week. Never
before has the jump from ``in'' list to ``out'' list been so swift.
</P>
<P>
   Teen-agers and twenty-somethings _ advertisers' demographic
darlings _ can ride every breaking wave and shout one giant
collective ``Next!'' They have the energy to keep craving the new.
The rest of us, however, feel the need to retreat to the relative
calm of old records and old movies. Who needs Missy Elliot when you
can have Petula Clark?
</P>
<P>
   Why run out to the new ``Haunting'' when you can watch the
original on Turner Classic Movies? At the flea market or on Ebay,
longtime collectors like myself are asking, ``What can I collect
that everyone else doesn't?''
</P>
<P>
   Faced with a glut of mass promotion and mass consumption,
personal taste becomes the lifesaver, but it's harder and harder to
chart your own course. At a time when hype has taken the fun out of
discovering something for yourself and then slowly watching it
catch on, the question has become where is the least hip place to
be? A friend, a French-born restaurateur, has found an answer. He
spends his weekends in a house on a lake in an unappreciated town
in that least fashionable of states, New Jersey. It is the
anti-Hamptons, the anti-Fire Island, he says, and that is precisely
why he bought a place there. He doesn't have to dress before going
to the supermarket because he never runs into anyone he knows.
Manhattanites don't beat a path to his door because the only buzz
is from the bugs.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting on his patio, away from it all, one can reminisce about
the days when hype caught up with a performer or a movie or a place
only after you were already bored with it, a time when you had
something to yourself for a while. Those were the days, baby.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-99 1706EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
