</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIRLS-FASHION-2TAKES-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAUGHTERS OF AMERICAN EVOLUTION  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 18) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)   (af)  
 By MICHELLE WILLENS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I distinctly remember being 11 and preparing for Come As You
Wish You Were Day at school. In baggy jeans and a boy's flannel
checked shirt and with my face strategically smudged, I proudly
announced that I was Scout of ``To Kill a Mockingbird.''
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, my 11-year-old daughter had a similar experience,
only for her Come as Your Hero Day, she donned tight Capris, black
platform shoes, a tank top and a bra-strap headband. She was, of
course, that great American icon Jennifer Love Hewitt.
</P>
<P>
   What concerns me here is not that teen-age films have replaced
literature as the source of youthful inspiration (that's another
story), but rather that neither of our outfits was far removed from
our usual garb. Which brings me to the problem many of us find
ourselves with who are parents of ``tweens'' _ the name some
marketers have coined for youngsters between childhood and
teen-agerdom.
</P>
<P>
   With daughters between the ages of, say, 9 and 12, we are torn
between pride at how our little girls are blossoming and migraines
over how to teach them about the messages they may be sending.
</P>
<P>
   My friend Katherine was so appalled when her 12-year-old emerged
one day _ in tight skirt, high shoes and a tank top showing her
recently arrived cleavage _ that she stood her in front of a
full-length mirror. When the girl still didn't get it, Katherine
tried another approach: cold experience. Sure enough, two blocks
and a dozen catcalls later, her slightly freaked daughter said,
``Mom, I want to go home and change.''
</P>
<P>
   Ask any mother what her earliest mother-daughter battles were
about, and the answer is likely to be, ``Getting dressed.'' Most of
us ultimately accepted that we should save the battles for the
important stuff, hoping that strong wills in girls would benefit
them later, and let the little tykes wear their party shoes to
school.
</P>
<P>
   Still, party shoes at 5 are age-appropriate and hardly pose a
threat to the wearer. Ten- or 11-year-olds dressed as mini versions
of Demi Moore raise the question: When is she too young for Mace?
</P>
<P>
   That these mother-daughter battles should pick up again during
the tween years should not be surprising, especially given today's
children, who seem so eager to skip straight into teen-agerhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``That age group is so difficult and so opinionated,'' said
Russell Helfer, an owner of the Ragg Tattoo stores in Los Angeles,
which clothe actresses like Lacey Chaubert of ``Party of Five'' and
the Olson twins. Happily for tweens _ and unhappily for parents who
would like to see them linger a minute longer in childhood _ the
cultural and consumer landscape is tilting them toward adolescence.
</P>
<P>
   Prime-time television is being taken over by teen-age shows. A
world-class female soccer victory becomes, in the end, a freeze
frame of a great body in a sports bra. And just as filmmakers have
more or less given up on making appropriate fare for tweens,
figuring the kids will be dragged along with older siblings, the
fashion industry has, as far as I can see, given up on them as
well.
</P>
<P>
   There are precious few stores that even attempt to cater to
tweens, who are too young for department stores but too sassy for
precious children's boutiques with imported-from-France petticoats
and equally stiff personnel. Even at the Gap there seems to be
little expressly for them, meaning they head to younger or older
aisles _ and guess which wins?
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Ellwell, fashion editor for YM, a magazine that is
supposedly for teen-agers but is devoured by daughters like mine,
said she did not think that tweens had been abandoned by the
apparel industry. ``It's a really important age group because
they're just coming into how they look and dress,'' she said. ``I
think they're viewed as tame versions of 16- to 18-year-olds.''
</P>
<P>
   I rest my case. The gap between 12 and ``16 to 18'' is not a few
degrees of tameness. Except I can't rest, because I must face the
uphill struggle of shopping with my tween. While I think she's as
cute as a button and potentially maybe even a dish, I prefer not to
see her as a junior version of girls much older and more sexually
aware.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   I had to practically wrestle her to the ground recently to
prevent her from buying tube tops (those provocative no-strap,
over-the-head tops) and midriff-baring T-shirts, two items
``everyone else has.''
</P>
<P>
   Even a store like Marsha D.D. in New York City, one of the very
few designed just for tweens and one that I applaud, offers stuff
that often seems a bit too low or too high in the wrong places.
Here one finds bra-strap headbands craved by girls who don't yet
wear a bra, bathing suits cut unusually upward along the sides and
the above-mentioned tops that come in snug and snugger.
</P>
<P>
   Marsha Drogin Dayan, the owner, says she is conscious of the
differences between those who are 10 and those who are teen-agers,
and tries to distract the former from items she considers too
risque.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are things I will not buy because I feel a
responsibility to the parents as well as the kids,'' she said,
adding that fashions suited to the tween customer are out there, if
retailers bother to look for them. ``I think clothes are being made
with the difference in mind, taking the influence of the older
girls but not quite going over the edge,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   One thing she certainly can't help is the fact that tweens are
wildly different in physical development. Katherine's daughter was
upset when a friend was allowed to wear a tight dress with a sheer
top, while Katherine had rejected the same exact outfit for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``This girl, while the same age, is totally undeveloped, while
mine is downright voluptuous,'' Katherine said. Mothers can't win.
Even when we try to stay firm, others often conspire against us. My
friend Susan Korowitz was taken aback when her 10-year-old, Sascha,
received a dress from her aunt with a note reading, ``Here's one
Mom won't buy you.'' (It had spaghetti straps.)
</P>
<P>
   Susan, in fact, didn't mind the dress. She's more dismayed that
the five pairs of overalls that Sascha liked six months ago have
not been touched since a classmate said they were not cool anymore.
Her friend, Sascha tells me, is the most popular in her grade, and
she's into tight jeans these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all into tight everything,'' said Helfer of Ragg
Tattoo.
</P>
<P>
   My young friend Makenna, who is 13, maintains that ``there is a
huge difference in being 12 and 13,'' having been both. ``At my
age, we all try to dress older and sexier than we are,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Well, sorry, but as I see it, even the preteen-agers _
encouraged by the magazines they read, the shows and movies they
see and the merchandise before them _ are into dressing older. They
are charmingly oblivious to the sex appeal they may be exuding.
Charming if this were ``Pleasantville.''
</P>
<P>
   Herein lie the dangers for these walking contradictions,
children who simultaneously talk back and cuddle up, hold Elmo in
one hand while tapping into computer chat rooms with the other.
Does someone who just turned 11 really need to know why nubile
little bodies are the wrong kind of turn-on? Or why certain clothes
may be OK in contained situations but not for everyday wear?
</P>
<P>
   Many of us concerned moms share the blame for our precocious
daughters' tastes. My daughter has seen far too many films she
shouldn't have, evidenced by the fact that her walls are covered in
Ben Affleck and Ryan Phillipe. (Mine at that age were full of
Hayley Mills.)
</P>
<P>
   I confess that after keeping her away from ``There's Something
About Mary'' for more than a year, I found her watching it on a
hotel cable service one night and didn't turn it off.
</P>
<P>
   It's probably too late to go back to when tweens were allowed to
be tweens. But I often wish that those with some real clout in the
fashion world would give us a little help. Maybe designers could
exchange some of their labels for those saying ``R,'' ``PG-13'' or
(fat chance) ``PG.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
