<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERFECT-LAWNS-ART-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GRASS IS GREENER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn.)  (For release Sun., July 18) 
(ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By TOM CONNOR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can I walk on it?'' first-time visitors often ask Robert Esernio
as they stare at his property in Mahopac, N.Y. There's no mistaking
Esernio's lawn. In a development of similar new houses with mostly
burnt, brown lawns lumpy from the excavator's backhoe, his is the
really green, rolling, luxuriant one, the one with mowing lines
like straight brush strokes up and down a fine piece of suede.
</P>
<P>
   The question strikes Esernio as both absurd and entirely
appropriate. ``Of course, they can walk on it,'' he says. ``It's a
lawn.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yet this is more than a lawn. It's as nearly perfect an expanse
of uniformly green turf as one is likely to find outside of
England, and for the last seven years it has been his passion.
</P>
<P>
   Riding a John Deere GT275 sitdown mower with a 48-inch cutting
deck, thatching and aerating attachments and hydrostatic drive (for
easy turns and straight lines), Esernio cuts his lawn seeded with
rye and bluegrass every five days, not once a week. (``It's happier
when it's cut every five days,'' he says.) He keeps it
three-and-a-half inches high.(``Any shorter, and the roots would
burn out,'') In the pool area and around the perimeter, he pushes a
Sears 22-inch hand mower. (``I need the workout.'') He fertilizes
with the Scott four-step program four times a year. (``The most
important thing about lawns is feeding them'').
</P>
<P>
   An accountant with three children, Esernio, 40, has spent
thousands of hours and tens of thousands of dollars _ including a
$3,500 underground sprinkler system _ to recreate, in effect, a
portion of the outfield at Yankee Stadium. ``I like the straight
lines,'' he says. ``I'm a little perfectionist about it. I find
myself turning the tractor around behind trees so as not to wear
out the same areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawns, once again a suburban status symbol, are bigger. As John
Henske, a landscaper in Fairfield, Conn., says, ``To quote a former
employer, `For some guys it's the biggest thing they own.'''
</P>
<P>
   This may not be the case with Esernio, of course, but he's far
from alone in his obsession. In the waning summer evenings of the
millennium, suburban men seem as devoted to their lawns as their
fathers were in the golden age of lawn maintenance, the 1950s, the
era of suburban migration, the crew cut and conformity.
</P>
<P>
   If middle-aged sons today have less time than their fathers did,
they have more money and more lawn and perhaps more hubris. Despite
environmental concern with pesticides and herbicides and a brief
fling with prairies and meadows in the 1980s, many suburban males
want their lawns to look like ballparks and putting greens.
</P>
<P>
   Real lawn guys no longer call their lawn ``lawn,'' of course.
``If you're serious about your lawn, if you're an aficionado of
grass, you refer to it as `turf,''' says Edmund Hollander, a
landscape designer in New York City with clients in the Hamptons
and other suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   In the spring, Village Hardware, a narrow, 80-year-old store in
Southport, Conn., was stacked to its tin ceiling with bags of Green
Power fertilizer and moss-killing lime. The stack disappeared
quickly. ``Sales were up big time from a few years ago,'' says
Glenn Oesterle, the store's owner. ``Customers are looking for a
better-looking lawn without spending a fortune. Also, a lot of
people have gone back to buying fertilizers in the bag and doing it
themselves because they're displeased with the lawn services.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Garden Association, which has been conducting an
annual survey of homeowners for the Gallup Organization for 20
years, reports a significant increase in home-owner spending on
lawn care products, from $6.5 billion to $8.5 billion between 1993
and 1998. Bruce Butterfield, market research director for the
association, which is based in Burlington, Vt., attributes the
increase to the strong economy, but also to a change in lawn-owner
attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people are starting to have a little more respect for
their lawns,'' Butterfield says. ``It's a lot like putting your
best face forward in the neighborhood. There's kind of a domino
effect. If your neighbor is using a Scott's four-step program and
your lawn looks like hell, you're going to want to do something,
too.''
(more) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-99 1715EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
