<DOCNO> NYT19990716.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2977 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PERFECT-LAWNS-2NDTAKE     07-16 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERFECT-LAWNS-2NDTAKE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
 
Undated: something, too.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the Eisenhower era, they called this keeping up with the
Joneses, and something of the same materialism and competitiveness
has returned in a decade of similar prosperity and political
complacency.
</P>
<P>
   The 1980s and 90s have also seen the second coming of suburban
sprawl. The relentless march of American suburbs _ gobbling up
farmland in Pennsylvania, encroaching on forests outside Seattle _
has made sprawl an unlikely campaign issue for Vice President Al
Gore and has no doubt also spurred lawn-product sales. At the Scott
Company, the country's biggest producer of lawn fertilizer, sales
have skyrocketed in three years, from $228 million to $442 million.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Reed, a landscape architect in Cambridge, Mass., traces the
90s resurgence of lawn fixation to the latest wave of migrants from
the cities. ``I've noticed with urban clients that the lawn plays
an important role in their pursuit of a kind of idealized country
living,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Especially for guys who didn't know from lawns growing up. ``On
the old estates out here, the lawn wasn't the focus,'' says Jim
Kiley, who has a degree in turf management and who works for
Whitmores, a landscaping contractor in Amagansett, L.I. ``But the
clients we have now want it to look like springtime year-round.
It's a guy thing. A lot of investment bankers grew up in Brooklyn
and never had a lawn, so it means everything to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitmores sprays fussy clients' lawns with a concentration of
iron two or three days before a party, turning the grass a desired
shade of bluish green.
</P>
<P>
   Where 1950s fathers and 90s sons differ is that many
lawn-obsessed men today seem content to pay others to create turf
perfection for them. When grass is another commodity, fast grass
beats slow grass by a mile. Most guys want lawns now.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Alfredo, a landscaper in Armonk, N.Y., put a 20-man crew to
work hand-laying sod over a seven-acre parcel in Bedford. ``Here's
the problem in our business _ the best lawn is a seeded lawn, but
nobody wants to wait three to four months for the lawn to grow
in,'' Alfredo says. ``What they're buying is a sod farmer's time
and efforts to produce a seeded lawn. Sod is instant lawn.''
</P>
<P>
   During this summer's drought, which landscapers say damaged even
sprinklered lawns and cut into their crews' productivity, Alfredo
has made deliveries of 6,000 gallons of water, at about $1,000 a
tanker load, to a number of customers' lawns.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest Agriculture Department survey, the sale of
farm-raised sod rose almost 70 percent in 1997 over 1992. The
demand may help explain something of a sod shortage this summer at
the Delea &AMP; Sons sod farm in East Northport, N.Y., which sells 400
to 500 acres of sod a year to exterior designers and landscapers in
the Hamptons, as well as to Yankee and Shea stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone wants to pay someone else, even those who can
afford to. For an increasing number of the turf obsessed, no green
is as good as the green you tend yourself. At Home Depot, the mecca
of the do-it-yourselfer, with more than 820 stores nationwide, the
lawn and garden department has seen ``a double-digit increase over
last year,'' says Jerry Shields, the chain's senior public
relations manager. For Home Depot, he says, ``it's probably a
billion-dollar business.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Brooks, 51, a partner in an East Hampton insurance agency,
put himself through college by working on the greens and grass
tennis courts at the Maidstone Club. For 25 years, Brooks has
reseeded and mowed his own quarter-acre lot himself. ``You just
take pride in the property and the look of the property,'' he says.
He adds that he cuts the lawn ``because the phone doesn't ring when
I'm mowing.''
</P>
<P>
   For some men, mowing connects them with childhoods when they
spent summer evenings in the backyard with their fathers. ``I'm
drawn deeper into the lawn with each pass, nearly identical to the
previous,'' writes Warren Schultz in his new book, ``A Man's Turf:
The Perfect Lawn'' (Clarkson Potter, $35). ``I'm working over old
ground. I'm lifted out, transported back to other lawns and the
aura that rises from them. This lawn is thick with memories of
every lawn I've ever cared for. And every lawn is marked with the
footsteps of my father.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, some men would just as soon forget the lawns of
their youth. Christopher Rosow came of age on four acres in the
Greenfield Hill section of Fairfield, Conn. ``My father was more
into not mowing the lawn,'' he recalls. ``He was more interested in
me mowing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Now 28, Rosow lives in a tiny, 1822 house in Southport Village,
not far from his parents' home, with a 6-by-20-foot yard. He laid
the lawn with sod from Home Depot _ ``I like instant
gratification,'' he says _ which he cuts with a secondhand Scott
reel mower, the acoustic kind of mower that makes a satisfying
clicking sound when you push it. ``It takes maybe 6 minutes to mow
and 10 minutes to trim with the weed whacker,'' Rosow says.
</P>
<P>
   Another recent development and realization is that turf may not
be exclusively a guy thing at all. ``I think women are catching
onto our little secret,'' Schultz says. ``In the course of writing
the book, I talked with women who said, `You know, growing up I
never really got the lawn. But I really like it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Minikes and her husband, Michael, who live in Manhattan
during the week, bought a weekend home on five undeveloped acres in
East Hampton nine years ago. Before Mrs. Minikes knew it, she was
planning lawns, installing a putting green and overseeing their
care. ``I was born in the Bronx,'' she says. ``I didn't know from a
lawn. But the more I got involved, the more I wanted it to be
perfect. I can't help it. My husband loves it, but it's my charge.
So we don't fight over it. We don't discuss it. I tell him what I
want to do, and he rolls his eyes, and that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   Henske, the Connecticut landscaper, maintains Martha Stewart's
three-acre Turkey Hill property in Westport, which could stand up
to any man's in a turf competition. ``For an unirrigated lawn, it's
as close to perfect as you can get,'' he says. ``She has a bunch of
guys full time, and they do a good job. But what keeps the lawn
from perfection is that there's constant activity and change. There
are footsteps all over the lawn, and she has dogs.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the obsession with lawns seems overwhelmingly a male
prerogative, maybe the next big guy thing after smoking cigars and
swilling martinis. Women already have other outlets for
self-expression.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was pregnant the first time,'' says Kathy Esernio, the
wife of Bob Esernio, he of the sitdown mower with the 48-inch
cutting deck in Mahopac, ``I remember him coming to me and saying,
`I feel it's almost time for me to start the lawn.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
