<HEADER>
A2979 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV18-     07-16 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIAGE STRATEGY FOR A DRY SPELL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 18)  
(lh) 
 By CASS PETERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the whole of June there was less than an inch of rain, and
half of July had passed with little more than an occasional
spiteful mist that encouraged mildew but did nothing to assuage the
thirst of my garden.
</P>
<P>
   Government authorities changed the ``drought watch'' in my
south-central Pennsylvania county to a ``drought warning,'' one
step below the point where the watering of lawns and gardens
becomes a violation of community spirit, if not an outright
violation of the law.
</P>
<P>
   Dry spells are a given for gardeners, even those in climates
where plenty of heaven-sent moisture is the norm. That's why
sprinklers, soaker hoses and watering cans were invented. But every
so often a dry spell extends into a drought _ a prolonged period
without rain, or with only sporadic light showers that barely
settle the dust.
</P>
<P>
   If you're not suffering one this year, rest assured that you
will, sooner or later. Droughts are as inescapable as aphids.
</P>
<P>
   If the drought is severe enough, local authorities will request
_ or demand _water conservation measures, and it's tough to argue
that keeping the Kentucky bluegrass green is a reasonable use of a
scarce resource. Even if the water supply from the tap isn't
threatened, it's difficult to keep up with irrigation chores when
the rainless days stretch into weeks and months.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, it's time to practice triage among the flora. At
my place, where the water comes from a deep well that is losing
pressure steadily as the ground-water table recedes, I've been
applying battlefield priorities for several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The first to be cut off from the watering hose were those plants
that are likely to survive without assistance, even if the dry
spell goes on for most of the summer. The Oriental poppies, for
example, are dormant and will rest comfortably under their mulch
without irrigation. Most other perennials with taproots or fleshy
roots _ like baby's breath, liatris and day lilies, and in the
vegetable garden, asparagus and rhubarb _ will also endure without
help.
</P>
<P>
   They will look as if they are dying, of course, because they
will withdraw moisture from their leaves into their roots, turn
yellow or brown and settle into out-of-season dormancy. It's a
survival tactic, and I applaud their resourcefulness. My goal is
not to keep the garden looking lush, which is not possible. It is
to assure the survival of as many plants as possible, so that they
may bloom again next year, when rainfall returns (I hope) to
normal.
</P>
<P>
   The next to lose dibs on the sprinkler were those annuals that
simply require too much water to be kept looking presentable. I'll
keep watering the moisture-loving perennials, like Japanese iris
and monkshood, but the lobelia, sweet alyssum, impatiens and balsam
are goners. I'll mulch the spot where they were growing and, if the
rains return in time, plant fall-blooming chrysanthemums or
marigolds there.
</P>
<P>
   Having left the strong plants to their own devices and bidden
farewell to the weak, I still have to make some decisions about the
plants in the middle. Many of these are in the vegetable garden,
where I will get no harvest unless I supply water to the crops.
</P>
<P>
   Priority goes to plants that are in blossom. If sweet corn in
silk and tassel goes dry for long, the cob will be snaggletoothed
with poorly formed kernels. Beans, tomatoes, and peppers, too, need
water most critically when they are blossoming.
</P>
<P>
   It's better by far to water deeply once a week than to water
frequently for short periods. Shallow watering is a waste of both
time and water. The moisture will barely penetrate the soil
surface, it won't reach the roots and it will evaporate quickly,
doing practically no good at all.
</P>
<P>
   If the dryness goes on, I will wave goodbye to some of the
thirstier vegetables. Lettuce, cucumbers and summer squash are
little more than water molecularly rearranged in the shape of a
vegetable. For the same amount of irrigation water, I would get a
far better return from kale, chard and cabbage. Celery may survive
drought stress, but it would be so stringy that I could use it for
dental floss. Without copious irrigation, eggplant would be seedy
and taste bitter.
</P>
<P>
   Like perennials that sink into dormancy under drought stress,
annuals have some coping mechanisms for dryness and heat. One is to
wilt or cup their foliage, which reduces the amount of water being
transpired from the leaves. Don't be alarmed if the vegetable
plants droop during the day, even after you've watered the garden.
It's a natural reaction. If they don't perk up in the evening, you
should haul out the sprinkler first thing in the morning. Watering
is best done in the morning to avoid wet foliage overnight, which
can invite mildew.
</P>
<P>
   I will water the berries. Blackberries and raspberries will
produce dry, crumbly fruit if not amply supplied with water;
strawberries are now sending out runners and forming the crown buds
that represent next year's crop. Blueberries are shallow-rooted. If
I don't keep their roots moist, I will lose the bushes, and it
takes five or six years to grow a blueberry bush to the point at
which it will produce a decent crop.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other plants that will get a ration of my limited
water supply are newly transplanted trees and shrubs. Established
trees and shrubs are likely to survive, as long as they don't
succumb to some pest or disease problem in their drought-weakened
state.
</P>
<P>
   When it rains again, I will be glad, and I will also keep
watering. An extended dry spell depletes soil moisture to a very
great depth, disrupting the capillary action that brings moisture
up from the subsoil. It can take weeks of steady rain to recover
from prolonged dry spells. They don't occur overnight, and they
aren't cured overnight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
