<HEADLINE>
NATIONAL GEOGRAPHIC CD-ROMS SET YOU OFF IN THE RIGHT DIRECTION
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LONNIE BROWN   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Think of travel to exotic places, and you might think of a past
issue of National Geographic magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Think of traveling across the county and National Geographic
would like you to think of National Geographic Trip Planner
Platinum (Windows; about $45 to $50).
</P>
<P>
   There are many reasons to consider paying the $49 for the three
CD-ROM package. There are searchable street-level maps for major
U.S. cities. The maps can be printed, as can driving instructions
and itineraries.
</P>
<P>
   The CDs contain more than 100,000 points of interest, as well as
information on 20,000 hotels and restaurants. The establishments
have also been rated by Frommer's Travel Guides.
</P>
<P>
   The program offers more than just road directions and maps.
Users can find scenic and historic tours, as well as driving and
walking tours.
</P>
<P>
   Information is included on hiking trails, campgrounds and park
maps. Many locations have been reviewed by National Geographic
writers and photographers.
</P>
<P>
   Video clips of scenery and regional events are also in the
program.
</P>
<P>
   Routes can be selected for fastest route or scenic appeal. The
routing uses the same engine used on MapQuest's popular Internet
site (www.mapquest.com). The million-plus miles of roads includes
every street in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   New to this version is support for global positioning system
receivers. Users who have them can let the CD-ROM graphically track
their latitude, longitude, bearing and speed using the GPS
satellite system.
</P>
<P>
   National Geographic Trip Planner Platinum includes information
from the Geographic's extensive library of travel books and
magazines, including: National Geographic Driving Guides to
America; Guide to Scenic Highways and Byways; Guide to America's
Historic Places; Crossing America _ National Geographic's Guide to
the Interstates; National Geographic Road Atlas of the U.S. and
Canada; State Parks of North America; National Parks of North
America; and Guide to National Parks.
</P>
<P>
   For information visit the National Geographic Web site
(www.nationalgeographic.com) or Broderbund Software's Web site
(www.broderbund.com).
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
