<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2988 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-OIL-HNS &LR;      07-16 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-OIL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN OFFICIAL SAYS OIL DUMPING CHARGES IRRATIONAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (Filed in the ``f'' and ``w'' categories.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A top Mexican government official on Friday said
accusations made by small oil producers that his country is dumping
oil on U.S. markets are ``irrational and completely unwarranted.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Prices are determined by global conditions,'' said Luis
Tellez, Mexico's energy secretary. ``We don't fix prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Tellez made his comments during a Washington news conference to
discuss a complaint filed two weeks ago against his country by the
small oil producers.
</P>
<P>
   The Oklahoma-based group, which formed an organization called
Save Domestic Oil, filed a complaint with the federal government
alleging that Mexico, Venezuela, Iraq and Saudi Arabia sold crude
oil at prices below fair market value between March 1998 and March
1999. The complaint also is being backed by the Independent
Petroleum Association, a Washington-based group representing more
than 8,000 independent oil producers.
</P>
<P>
   Such oil producers were hurt by a steep decline in oil prices
last year, causing the loss of an estimated 100,000 jobs. Crude oil
prices reached historically low levels of near $11 per barrel, but
have since recovered to about $20 per barrel.
</P>
<P>
   Save Domestic Oil has asked the federal government to impose a
tariff of $6.18 per barrel on oil produced by the four countries.
Iraq, which remains a pariah in the international community, is
periodically allowed by the United Nations to sell oil in exchange
for food and medical supplies.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department has until Aug. 9 to determine whether
the complaint made by the small oil producers has merit and can
move forward.
</P>
<P>
   Large oil producers and U.S. Energy Secretary Bill Richardson
disagree with the small producers' complaint, saying there is no
evidence that Mexico dumped oil, or sold it at below-market prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``In good times and bad, the price of oil around the world is
dictated by supply and demand,'' said Red Cavaney, president and
chief executive officer of the American Petroleum Institute, a
Washington-based group representing large oil producers.
</P>
<P>
   He explained that last year's low oil prices were caused by the
Asian financial crisis and an unusually warm winter in 1998, which
depressed demand, causing a glut of oil and a drop in prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone in our industry has suffered from low prices,''
Cavaney said.
</P>
<P>
   But Harold Hamm, an Enid, Okla., oil producer who organized Save
Domestic Oil, said he believes the Asian financial crisis caused
the four countries to dump oil because their overseas markets dried
up.
</P>
<P>
   Cavaney said the tariff sought by the small producers would
disrupt world oil markets, likely raising oil prices and the prices
U.S. consumers pay for gasoline and heating oil.
</P>
<P>
   But Hamm said even if the entire $6 tariff were imposed, it
would only raise gasoline prices by about 15 cents per gallon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gasoline is cheaper than bottled water,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson told reporters this week that he would try to resolve
the dispute before the Aug. 9 deadline. If the Commerce Department
were to decide the case has merit, an investigation of the alleged
dumping practices would likely take several months. If Mexico and
the other countries were found to have dumped oil on the United
States, federal authorities could decide to impose penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Tellez, who met with Richardson this week, said Mexico won't
negotiate with the small oil producers or U.S. officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are sure we have the economic and legal tools to prove we
are not dumping oil,'' Tellez said.
</P>
<P>
   Tellez said Mexico had no interest in selling oil at low prices
because the industry is vital to the continued improvement in the
Mexican economy, which the U.S. helped rescue after the peso
meltdown in late 1994 and early 1995. He said the government
receives 30 percent of its total revenue from oil sales.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico, the world's fifth largest oil producer, has already
retaliated against the United States because of the small
producers' complaint by reversing a decision to scrap the 4 percent
tariff on U.S. natural gas imports.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Tellez announced he would lift the tariff July 1, four
years ahead of the timetable established by the North American Free
Trade Agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't take the gas tariff out until this is resolved,''
Tellez said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Jennifer Corbett Dooren can be reached at 202-298-6920 and by
e-mail:jennifer(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-99 1720EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
