<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2997 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV18-B     07-16 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV18-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BALK, WITH ULSTER ACCENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 18, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the endearing traits of emigres is their hankering to
revisit the old country after making it big in America.
</P>
<P>
   Jews go back to Israel, the Italians to Italy, and the Irish go
you-know-where. Between that old Yank can-do attitude and a liberal
dose of the long green, the returning immigrant aspires to making
some kind of improvement on the old sod.
</P>
<P>
   That's endearing. But even more enduring is the temptation of
the people still living on the old sod to say, ``Yep, we'll take
your money, we'll listen to your advice, and then we'll do it the
way we deamn well please, the old way, and please pack your sloppy
American sentimentalism in your suitcase when you leave.''
</P>
<P>
   The tendency of the Irish of Northern Ireland to take our money
_ but not our advice _ is again ascendant in Ulster, where the
peace agreement brokered so painstakingly by a two generations of
American good will just collapsed in a sea of Hibernian hypocrisy.
</P>
<P>
   Little men carrying too heavy a load of history has been
Ireland's curse for centuries. Belfast has the mindset of the
Balkans _ blood obscures all blame for whatever outrage is
perpetrated in the name of redressing another greivance.
</P>
<P>
   All the little steps that had been taken toward peace in the
province have been betrayed by the pygmies of the political
process. We tried to build them up, to pretend they were bigger men
than they really are, treating them to pomp and primacy.
</P>
<P>
   We had them to the White House, we lobbied the Swedes
successfully to give them yet another set of Nobel Peace Prizes, we
dispatched our businessmen and entrepreneurs with investment dough
and new factory orders, we showered them with honorary degrees.
Bill Clinton had them over for so many St. Patrick's Day parties
that the Unionists and Sinn Fein qualified for reduced rates on
their hotel rooms.
</P>
<P>
   And what happens? At the end of the day, David Trimble and Gerry
Adams don't deliver. Trimble is no real leader, but a hollow front
man, a herd-follower, mouthpiece for the common herd of Ulster
refuseniks whose ultimate answer is ``no.''
</P>
<P>
   And Adams is the frontman for Sinn Fein, but never was the top
man. A bearded poet, a talker, a seizer of microphones and peddler
of soundbites, Adams was the trained monkey sent out by the organ
grinder to do his turn for the journalists, who dutifully jotted
down his cryptic crossword puzzle answers, and then tried to
explain them to the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Americans have always been slightly baffled by the Ulster agony,
and all the intricate sophistry spun by men who looked and sounded
like rapscallions of the same tribe, but whose religious and class
prejudices override all the other common bonds of culture,
geography, history, and common sense.
</P>
<P>
   With their Ulster accents, the lilting ending of phrases on that
curious uptick, and their specious insistence on rephrasing every
simple sentence into some tortured anagram of equal parts history
and histrionics, the political tunesmiths of Northern Ireland could
not overcome their pettiness. Small men never can.
</P>
<P>
   They'll never call Trimble ``the big fella,'' as the Republicans
called Michael Collins. Trimble is an empty suit, no matter what
sayeth the citation on the Nobel Prize on his mantelpiece. His
opposite number, Adams, is more articulate, a bit quicker on his
feet, but no better a man when it comes to delivering the goods.
</P>
<P>
   The hard men of both sides, the shooters and bombers and
kneecappers, never had a real stake in the peace process. How could
they? These are, in the main, underclass ruffians, small-time thugs
and kneecappers, tailgaters, boozers and dopers and beaters of
women, who lacked anything substantial in the way of education,
training, discipline, or the self-respect of holding down a regular
job.
</P>
<P>
   They were never going to be pounding computer keys or inserting
silicon chips into mother boards, or greeting tourists at the B &AMP; B
with a cheerful hello and a room key. That kind of work is not
their thing. They do the other thing, the dirty work, at night, in
the alley, shooting through lit windows, kidnapping unarmed
civilians, sending unsigned threats, planting bombs to harm the
unsuspecting.
</P>
<P>
   For two decades, American politicians who, because of their
Irish heritage or out of sympathy with the effort, worked
unceasingly to help Ulster, Britain, and the Republic of Ireland.
The late Tip O'Neill and Hugh Carey, Daniel Patrick Moynihan and
Ted Kennedy, through the presidencies of Carter, Reagan, Bush, and
most expecially Clinton, the American political establishment bent
to the task of kindling peace in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Helpful moves in Congress were sparked by Chris Dodd of
Connecticut, Joe Moakley and Joe Kennedy of Boston, Peter King of
New York. Trade missions were swapped, grants and loans arranged,
summer camp scholarships and academic exchanges flourished. Kennedy
took Gerry Adams to the Clinton administration, initially through
the back door, and connections were made.
</P>
<P>
   Through the frost of the Thatcher years, the thaw of the Major
years, and the heightened diplomatic offensive of Tony Blair,
successive British governments were encouraged to move Northern
Ireland up the priority list. Then came George Mitchell, Clinton's
deal-closer, to midwife the talks that resulted in the Good Friday
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   To the vast relief of the citizens of both Irelands and the
United Kingdom, the deal was struck, and the principals on the
ground, John Hume and Trimble, shared the Nobel Prize. But the old
enmities rekindled. Decommissioning, the surrender of hidden arms
caches, had been papered over in conciliatory language to get the
deal signed, but no arms were surrendered.
</P>
<P>
   The Unionists balked, the IRA instructed Adams to remain firm,
and entreaties from Clinton and Blair were unavailing. There we
stand. Talks are suspended. We await the first bombing. The
shootings never actually ceased, just diminished. And the midgets
of Ulster still have their shelves of trophies and prizes and
newspaper scrapbooks hailing them as men of peace.
</P>
<P>
   It's time to face hard facts. Trimble and Adams cannot deliver
peace. Both are in thrall to hard men, whose talents are in terror,
not in tradeoffs. It was always going to be a test of leadership,
of finding men who could deliver their hard-liners. No matter the
flowery language of the Nobel Prize speeches, these two took the
prize money, and ran, and failed to deliver in the end.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first thing to remember for American politicians and
business types when the Irish come calling, as they continually do,
looking for handouts. Next time, let's make them swallow some
advice before we fork over the cash and the honorary degrees.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
