<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3013 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANN-NANCY-WILSON-$ADV     07-16 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANN-NANCY-WILSON-$ADV18-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST THE TWO OF THEM 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL DEAN   The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Letting the heart of Heart shine: That's Ann Wilson's plan for
the first tour featuring just her and sister Nancy Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Heart, of course, was the multiplatinum rock group that put
Seattle on the map in the 1970s and 1980s when Pearl Jam and
Nirvana were still teething guitar picks.
</P>
<P>
   But while Ann and Nancy Wilson, Heart's lead singer and
guitarist respectively, led the group through a 20-plus year career
that boasted 20 hit singles, the two have never toured by
themselves _ until now.
</P>
<P>
   That's a prospect replete with challenges and rewards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boy howdy, yeah, we feel really exposed,'' Wilson said over
the telephone from a Buffalo, N.Y., hotel room.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't mean vulnerable to failure. We feel really
confident about it because we've been playing together all of our
lives since we were children, though it is different ... than doing
it in your childhood bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's my natural musical collaborator,'' said Ann, 49, about
her 45-year-old sister. ``And because of that we feel real good out
there together.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can talk together between songs in a natural way, and it's
different every night.''
</P>
<P>
   As opposed to a strictly ``unplugged'' or acoustic tour, the
Wilson sisters are drawing on their full range as musicians for the
10-week tour, which runs through the summer.
</P>
<P>
   That means each will play several instruments and take turns
singing lead, although Ann will carry the lion's share of vocals
and Nancy will no doubt do the same on stringed instruments.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 24 instruments, expect Ann to play bass, rhythm
guitar, piano and flute, and Nancy everything from electric and
acoustic guitars to mandolin, dulcimer, dobro, blues harp bass and
piano.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're definitely plugged in,'' Wilson said. ``But we do play
acoustic guitars on some of the songs, and on some we play
electric.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we have these things called atomic boot boxes. It's
basically a wooden hollow box with pickups inside it and you stomp
on it and it sounds like a kick drum.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we're going all over the place with it. It's not really a
folkie thing; it's got a lot of range.''
</P>
<P>
   Songwise, the two will mix new material _ which they will
include on a duo studio album after the tour _ and older Heart
songs, such as ``These Dreams,'' ``Dog and Butterfly'' and
``Barracuda.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with pleasing old and new fans, the mix of songs should
serve as a yardstick between the full-blown band sound of Heart and
the more scaled-down approach of Ann and Nancy Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good metaphor would be food,'' Wilson said. ``With Heart, it
was a great big, rich, heavy duty meat-stew. And with us, I'd say
it's probably more like something Creole. It's spicy, simple and
sophisticated.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's preference for the sisters' new musical direction
instead of the more rocking Heart hints that the days of the group
may be behind them.
</P>
<P>
   As it stands now, the group is not active. And while Wilson
doesn't completely rule out a full reunion tour, she doesn't
exactly pour fuel on the Heart fire either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like it's a car up on blocks in the back yard,'' Wilson
said about Heart. ``It's not in the junk yard yet. It's being
preserved; waiting for the time to be right to put it back together
and put it on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we're not feeling right now like we want to go out and do
one of those funky reunion things.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said ``the money is huge'' for reunion tours.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fleetwood Mac got so rich off of that one last spin they took,
even though they had to grit their teeth to do it,'' she said.
``And that's not appealing to me.''
</P>
<P>
   What about The Eagles' reunion tour that packed stadiums a few
years ago?
</P>
<P>
   ``They called it `When Hell Freezes Over,' '' Wilson said,
adding with a laugh, ``And hell froze over all right. And it was
really icy.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
