<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, July 17, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Uncomfortably hot and humid air will grip the Northeast this
weekend as high pressure over the Atlantic Ocean directs sultry air
into the region. Amid abundant hazy sun, temperatures will soar to
near 100 degrees across portions of southern New England and the
northern Middle Atlantic states. An exception will be near the
south-facing coastlines where gentle sea breezes import
ocean-chilled air to the shore. Farther west, similar conditions
will prevail over the eastern Great Lakes and upper Ohio Valley,
though it will not be as oppressively hot.
</P>
<P>
   Thunderstorms will erupt in the humid air covering the Southeast
Saturday. Storms will be most numerous near the Gulf and Atlantic
coasts where developing sea breezes undercut and lift the damp air.
Another cluster of thunderstorms will be found over southern Texas
as a upper air disturbance spirals inland from the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   A corridor of humid air streaming northeastward through the
Plains will fuel showers and thunderstorms across the western Great
Lakes Saturday. Local rainfall amounts of an inch are possible. A
few thunderstorms will also form near a slow-moving front
stretching from the western Dakotas to Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   The sun's uneven heating of the undulating terrain of the
southern Rockies will induce spotty thunderstorms Saturday,
particularly in eastern New Mexico. Meanwhile, a cold disturbance
at 20,000 feet will cross the Pacific Northwest, setting the stage
for isolated showers and thunderstorms. The remainder of the far
West will stay mainly sunny and seasonably warm.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Russian Heat
</P>
<P>
   For the second time this month, Moscovites are sweltering
through a heat wave. Just before a midday thundershower, the
temperature reached 86 degrees Fahrenheit on Friday. This was
preceded by a maximum of 90 degrees on Thursday. Earlier this
month, the mercury rose to 93 degrees on July 8 and 9. The normal
high temperature is 72 degrees, a temperate reading for a location
well inland. The routine progression of marine air from the Baltic
Sea usually produces enough clouds to temper the summer warmth in
Moscow. Additional clouds this weekend will help to cool the
Russian capital.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
