<HEADER>
A3021 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABOUT-CARS-PANOZ-ROAD     07-16 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-PANOZ-ROADSTER-ART-2TAKES-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(REPEATING, ADDING ART NOTE) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Attn: Ga., W.Va., Calif., Fla.)  
 AT PANOZ, DAYS OF WINE AND ROADSTERS  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 18)  
 (af)  
 By PETER PASSELL c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   So what does the nicotine skin patch have to do with wine, golf
champions and, yes, really cool sports cars? Royalties from the
transdermal patch have helped to pay for the Panoz family's
delightfully decadent conglomerate, a host of enterprises that
includes Georgia's only serious winery and the company that builds
a car Parnelli Jones has dubbed ``the great American roadster.''
</P>
<P>
   The story really begins in the backwaters of West Virginia,
where Donald Panoz, the son of an Italian-born professional boxer
was born. By his late 20s Don Panoz, an entrepreneurial sort, had
acquired a couple of drugstores in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Then in 1960, with financial backing from friends who played for
the World Series-winning Pittsburgh Pirates, he started Mylan
Laboratories, a pharmaceutical company that would become a power in
the generic drug business.
</P>
<P>
   Rolling the dice again in 1969, he took his wife, four daughters
and son to Ireland to start another drug company, this one
pioneering in transdermal delivery of medications. He struck gold:
The Elan Corp.'s market capitalization is now close to $8 billion;
it was in the news this month after scientists at one of its
subsidiaries said they had developed a potential vaccine for
Alzheimer's disease.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia connection dates from 1981, when Panoz was scouting
locations for a new facility for the drug maker. The ever-restless
entrepreneur decided to combine pleasure with profit, and in the
process managed the nearly impossible: making potable wines from
European varietal grapes grown in the hot, humid hills of the
mid-South.
</P>
<P>
   Chateau Elan's first offerings were marketed in 1985. An art
gallery, hotel, golf courses and conference center followed in
short order on the 3,300-acre site in Braselton, 35 miles north of
Atlanta. Next came a spa and a line of bottled waters (both
projects of Donald's wife, Nancy), along with the Gene Sarazen
World Golf Open.
</P>
<P>
   And what would a great golf course be without a lot of affluent
retirees and weekend duffers camped near the fairways? Building
lots in the Panoz-sponsored development start at $75,000, and
finished houses run $1 million or more _ real money in the Atlanta
market.
</P>
<P>
   Never one to think small, Panoz has since bought 33,000 acres of
undeveloped land near Modesto, Calif., with plans to offer a
similar package of winery, golf and indulgences to San Franciscans
with quality time and money to burn.
</P>
<P>
   But back to the cars: For all his fascination with the
consumables of the good life, Panoz has never admitted any
enthusiasm for fast iron. Indeed, he once told a reporter that he
didn't know how to open the hood of his Lexus.
</P>
<P>
   But his son, Danny, is definitely a gearhead. While working with
the family business in Georgia, he dreamed of building a
high-performance sports car. Others have climbed this mountain
without success, partly because the finished product was too
expensive to sell at a profit.
</P>
<P>
   Danny Panoz planned to make his car both affordable and reliable
by purchasing most components off the shelf from the big auto
makers.
</P>
<P>
   He got his chance in 1989, adopting an innovative chassis design
from a tiny, failed Irish sports-car startup called TMC opening a
modest factory down the road from Chateau Elan. The first vehicle
from Panoz Auto Development, a somewhat austerely finished open-top
roadster that Danny Panoz describes as ``perfect for bikers,''
rolled off the assembly line in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   With an outlandish hot rod-retro body reminiscent of the
all-show, not-much-go Plymouth Prowler, and a monster Ford V8 for
muscle, the Panoz Roadster was bound to turn a few heads. And of
course, it graced the covers of car-buff magazines with lots of
pages to fill each year.
</P>
<P>
   But curiosity quickly morphed into respect, with the early
reviews ranging from encouraging to ecstatic. Car and Driver called
it ``the best street-legal, turn-key, cottage-industry roadster
available in the United States.'' Today, a few dozen Ford dealers
sell a more refined version of that original Panoz Roadster, and
many more can service it, since the drivetrain comes largely from
the Mustang.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
