<HEADER>
A3027 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABOUT-CARS-PANOZ-ROAD     07-16 0509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-PANOZ-ROADSTER-ART-2NDTAKE-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(REPEATING, ADDING ART NOTE) 
</HEADLINE>
   UNDATED: the Mustang. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Danny Panoz started Phase 2 of his operation,
designing a less playful-looking and far more polished ``grand
touring'' sports car with plenty of room for two well-fed Americans
and even a trunk that can handle a couple of sets of golf clubs.
</P>
<P>
   The aluminum-bodied Esperante convertible, with a 320-horsepower
V8 from Ford's Special Vehicles Team; a handcrafted, heavily
leathered interior, and styling cues from Jaguar and a half-dozen
other European sports cars, is set to go on sale later this year
for about $80,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Esperante will almost match the performance of a
12-cylinder Ferrari, yet cost $200,000 less,'' Danny Panoz
promised. The people in Armani suits from Maranello may not be
losing much sleep over the competitive threat from rural Georgia.
But the auguries are promising.
</P>
<P>
   This story hardly ends here. In 1995, Papa Panoz, who was about
to retire as chairman of his pharmaceutical house, was searching
for another challenge. He decided to plunge into the race car
business with all the enthusiasm, smarts _ and deep pockets _ that
he had brought to Chateau Elan.
</P>
<P>
   Panoz Motorsports hired Adrian Reynard, the racecar designer, to
build a carbon-fiber car, and Jack Rousch, the maven of sports car
engines, to produce the innards for a vehicle that superficially
resembles the Esperante. It added a team of drivers recruited from
racing's top echelons and instantly became a power to reckon with
in the take-no-prisoners world of motorsports.
</P>
<P>
   Panoz race cars hold their own with the best from McLaren,
Ferrari and BMW, placing 7th and 11th at Le Mans last month. And
they are pushing the envelope of racing technology, developing the
first electric-gasoline hybrid car for the track.
</P>
<P>
   ``This much success, this quick, is just amazing,'' said Brock
Yates, an automotive writer whose books include a biorgraphy of
Enzo Ferrari.
</P>
<P>
   Does racing make economic sense for the Panoz dynasty? The money
spent on vroom and zoom largely come from multi-millionaires with
too much time on their hands, or from oil, tire, auto and cigarette
companies with mass-market products in need of racing's reflected
glory. Think of Cadillac, now heading back to Le Mans.
</P>
<P>
   The $10 million-plus that Don Panoz admits to spending on his
racing program will no doubt sell a few more Esperantes. ``Building
successful race cars gave our sports cars instant credibility,''
his son said.
</P>
<P>
   But with that kind of money, you could probably convince NASA to
launch an Esperante into orbit. If there is any commercial method
to Panoz's racing madness, it's probably in the sale of tickets
rather than cars.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Don Panoz purchased Road Atlanta, an ailing track in
Georgia, and Sebring, the legendary race circuit in Florida. With a
few home-team winners, Panoz Motorsports may yet fill the
bleachers. And who wants to second-guess a man who made a fortune
on the nicotine patch?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-15-99 2205EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
