u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-NYT     07-16 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS WALK TIGHTROPE IN DEBATE OVER PATIENTS' RIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Southern Exposure is the weekly political notebook from the
Washington Bureau of the New York Times Regional Newspapers) (lh) 
 By CARL HULSE and SEAN LOUGHLIN   
 NYT Regional Newspapers  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With their eyes on the 2000 elections, Republicans
treaded oh-so-carefully as the Senate adopted a patients' bill of
rights over Democratic complaints that it fell short of providing
consumers needed protection.
</P>
<P>
   While they are leery of offering sweeping government guarantees
for health care, Republicans don't want to appear indifferent to
the plight of Americans who can't get the medical help they need
because of cost-cutting restrictions in their managed-care plans.
Polls show health care is a chief concern for many Americans, and
it could be a potent political issue in the upcoming elections.
</P>
<P>
   So Republicans pushed through a measure that makes it easier for
patients in HMOs to get needed medical treatment. But they rejected
broader Democratic proposals that would have granted patients
greater access to health care and expanded their ability to sue for
malpractice.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we need to do is try to improve it incrementally,'' said
Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Republicans approved an amendment that makes it
easier for women to stay in the hospital after a mastectomy. But
they voted down a Democratic proposal that would have made it
easier for patients to see medical specialists. And many parts of
the Republican plan exclude people who buy insurance on their own.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans argued that the more comprehensive Democratic bill
would amount to government meddling, inflate medical costs and
result in more lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patients should be receiving treatment in their doctors'
offices, not waiting for their case to be heard by a judge in
court,'' said Sen. Connie Mack, R-Fla.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. John Edwards, D-N.C., signaled the political fight to
come as he passed judgment on the measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Insurance companies have won, and American families have
lost,'' said Edwards. ``It's like passing a law against stealing
but not having a police force or court system to enforce it.''
</P>
<P>
   A NEW CHOICE?
</P>
<P>
   Trying a new tack on the abortion debate, Republicans are
rallying around a bill that would force family planning clinics to
talk about adoption with pregnant women.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim DeMint, R-S.C., believes such clinics too often turn to
abortion in the cases of unwanted pregnancies. ``We want to make
sure these mothers know that adoption is an option,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Adoption Awareness Act of 1999 would create a new $7 million
grant program to train health care workers on adoption counseling.
</P>
<P>
   While DeMint is a staunch anti-abortion vote in the House, his
bill won the support of the group Republicans For Choice, which
supports abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   MILKING THE ISSUE
</P>
<P>
   Southern lawmakers are solidly behind a proposal to aid
struggling dairy farmers in the region by forming a new dairy
compact.
</P>
<P>
   Under a measure that could hit the Senate floor in the next few
days, Southern states would be allowed to band together and
establish a regional commission that would set a floor for milk
prices now determined nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Dairy farmers say the compact would lessen the volatility in the
milk market, eliminating drastic price swings that are putting
dairymen out of business. North Carolina, for instance, has lost a
whopping 4,500 dairy farms over the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't slow this rate of decline, consumers will see
their local supply of fresh milk dry up, and we will be forced to
rely solely on milk being shipped in from other regions of the
country,'' warned Jim Graham, North Carolina's agriculture
commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   The compact is opposed by Upper Midwest dairy farmers, who hope
to retain dominance in the milk market. Southern states eligible
for membership in the compact include the Carolinas, Alabama and
Louisiana. Florida must still pass enabling legislation at the
state level.
</P>
<P>
   PARTY POOPER
</P>
<P>
   A Republican U.S. senator running for president abandons his own
party and denounces its platform as ``not worth the paper it is
written on'' in a scathing speech on the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   What do his GOP colleagues have to say? Not much.
</P>
<P>
   The defection of Sen. Bob Smith of New Hampshire from the GOP to
the Independence Party drew barely a yawn on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's his decision,'' said Sen. Richard Shelby, who grabbed
headlines in 1994 when he left the Democratic Party to join the GOP
it they won control of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Smith blasted his party as more concerned with ``winning
elections'' than fighting for principles, saying Republicans
candidates are wishy-washy when it comes to fighting gun control or
opposing abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The party, to put it bluntly, is hypocritical,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Smith's comments, Shelby said, ``He's got his First
Amendment rights, but I disagree with him.''
</P>
<P>
   (Sean Loughlin and Carl Hulse are in the Washington Bureau of
the New York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
