<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NEWSROOM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MORE TEARS': THE PAYOFF IS WORTH YOUR EFFORT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(lh) 
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The truth doesn't have to be accurate,'' says George Findlay.
He should know. As a television news producer with nary a crumb of
ethics, professional or personal, George manipulates the truth
whenever he can.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately George is a fictional character. But he raises
disturbing questions about the meaning of reality in this
media-soaked age. And he does so while offering a chillingly
fascinating tour of his own empty soul.
</P>
<P>
   Actually (to the extent that anything is actual), the questions
are raised and the tour is conducted by George's creator and alter
ego, Ken Finkleman. Finkleman, who introduced George in the
Canadian Broadcasting Corp. series ``The Newsroom,'' brings him
back in a darker CBC satire, ``More Tears,'' which Channel 13 in
New York is showing Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Even those who relished ``The Newsroom,'' which Channel 13 is
rerunning on Sunday nights beginning July 25, may find the
three-hour ``More Tears'' a marathon. While ``The Newsroom,'' a
kind of northern cousin to ABC's fine ``Sports Night,'' was a
series of wry half-hour dramas about the team that puts together a
nightly news program, this is a different animal. Three half-hour
stories build to a 90-minute television film about the making of a
television film in which reality is dissected, reassembled and then
hurled out the window so it lands kersplat at George's feet. And
yours.
</P>
<P>
   The payoff is worth your effort. But this project might be
better appreciated in two sittings. Think of this as an opportunity
to use the VCR.
</P>
<P>
   Finkleman _ the show's writer, director and star _ really has
taken George out of ``The Newsroom.'' He is now a roving news
producer, pursuing the most inanely viewer-friendly drivel with a
vacuous reporter named Diane (Leah Pinsent) and a camera crew.
</P>
<P>
   When first glimpsed, they have gone to a remote farm as part of
a media swarm chasing the tale of a baby girl trapped in a well.
George carefully coaches the willing local politicians and the
girl's compliant young mother about just what to say on camera.
Then the videotape rolls as Diane smarmily asks the mother how she
feels and tells her: ``You're a symbol. Do you know that?'' A
symbol of what? You'll find out.
</P>
<P>
   The on-air blather from Diane and the other television reporters
on the scene is dead on. And George's priorities are clear. He
barks into his cell phone about the baby, ``All we can do is hope
and pray that she comes up in a decent time slot.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing is ever uncomplicated for George, who is pursued as well
as pursuer. He has been followed to the farm by both his glum wife,
Andrea (Arsinee Khanjian), and his longtime girlfriend, Nikki (Lou
Thornton), a frequent failure at stand-up comedy and suicide. They
both know he has others. One, who is met later in the proceedings,
is the most appealing character in the series: a free-spirited
artist, played by Larissa Laskin, who is never addressed by name.
She expects no fidelity, so she is the only person, including
himself, to whom George isn't constantly lying.
</P>
<P>
   The other two half-hours follow George and Diane on their
tabloid-type assignments, while George keeps bumping into women who
are only too glad to offer themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Now that you've learned to love loathing George, you're ready
for the main event, in which he throws off the life of an
incompetent television news producer to become the incompetent
writer-director of a television drama about an incompetent news
producer named George. He has written characters based on Andrea
and Nikki, and he has hired Diane the reporter for the role of the
reporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really think I can play this part?'' she asks. ``She's a
funny, mindless broad.''
</P>
<P>
   George replies, ``Play yourself, and you'll be perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Diane never guesses she's been insulted. If indeed she has been.
</P>
<P>
   Confused? You will be, as the film within a film within a film
spins out of control. But you will finally learn why the series is
called ``More Tears.'' And you'll have cynical fun watching
George's movie unravel, along with his love life and possibly his
mind.
</P>
<P>
   When the actor playing the actor who's playing George tells the
auteur that he wants to ``get inside your head,'' George says:
``Well, it's kind of small and messy. And I'm not sure you'd like
the view.''
</P>
<P>
   Things get a bit heavy at the end. But by the time Finkleman
gives you your own mind back, you'll thank him for shaking it up.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward you may refuse to believe anything you haven't seen
for yourself. Doubt that? Well, see for yourself.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `MORE TEARS'
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. Sunday on PBS
</P>
<P>
   Ken Finkleman, writer, director and executive producer; Jan
Peter Meyboom, producer. A Canadian Broadcasting Corp. production.
</P>
<P>
   With: Ken Finkleman (George Findlay), Leah Pinsent (Diane),
Arsinee Khanjian (Andrea), Lou Thornton (Nikki), Larissa Laskin
(The Artist) and Hrant Alianak (Shaffik).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
