<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELDER SWEAT HAS HEALING PROPERTIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., N.J.)   (For release Monday, July 19)  
(js) 
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you've been feeling blue, despondent or just generally in a
bad mood, the cure could be to thrust your nose into the armpit of
an elderly woman.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at Monell Chemical Senses Center in Pennsylvania and
Rutgers University in New Jersey believe the body odors of older
people, particularly women, can put others in a happy mood.
</P>
<P>
   The scent, which the researchers called ``l'eau de grandmere,''
could explain the warm, reassuring feeling that elderly women and
grandmothers seem to convey.
</P>
<P>
   According to a Reuters story, scientists tested their theory by
collecting underarm odors on gauze pads from 30 volunteers ranging
from toddlers to 70-somethings and asked more than 300 students to
assess their mood before and after sniffing the samples. (Another
good reason not to volunteer for anything.)
</P>
<P>
   Smells from older people and females in general produced a more
positive mood. Baby odors did not improve moods, and scents from
young men and boys were associated with aggression.
</P>
<P>
   Call me crass and insensitive, but I see a great financial
opportunity here for Florida's huge population of elderly women.
Instead of just sitting around waiting for their next Social
Security check and complaining about the high price of prune juice,
Florida's grannies can get rich selling their sweat.
</P>
<P>
   This being summer, we are in the peak of the ``season,'' so to
speak, which means that your average granny could produce several
quarts a day of high-quality, euphoria-inducing perspiration simply
by performing a little light outdoor exercise such as laying a few
acres of sod or tarring a roof.
</P>
<P>
   For a small piece of the action, say 25 percent, I would gladly
permit a few enterprising grannies onto my property, where they can
work toward financial independence by weeding my garden and digging
post holes for my new fence.
</P>
<P>
   The nice thing is, if I start to feel sad or guilty watching
them do all that work, I can just plunge my face into one of their
armpits and become instantly dizzy with happiness and well-being.
</P>
<P>
   (Of course, I would have to take care not to plunge so
vigorously that I break a sweat as the grannies might get a whiff
of it and start fighting among themselves or, even worse, with me.)
</P>
<P>
   I see a day in the not-too-distant future when Florida's elderly
women become a tourist attraction every bit as big as our white,
sandy beaches and world-class array of speed bumps. Tourists from
Ontario will gladly pay $5 ($10 Canadian) just to sit for a few
minutes in an un-air-conditioned room with an 80-year-old woman.
</P>
<P>
   There are some risks in all this, of course. Kidnappings or, in
this case, granny-nappings, would surely increase once the world
became aware of the restorative qualities of geriatric
perspiration. Females over the age of 70 might need bodyguards
every time they venture out into public or else they could try
disguising themselves as young men. There would also, undoubtedly,
be an increase in broken clavicles caused by scent-crazed
individuals ramming headfirst into elderly women's armpits. To
protect themselves, Florida's grannies may want to familiarize
themselves with a few basic karate moves or else invest in a set of
high-quality shoulder pads.
</P>
<P>
   It will not be long, surely, before a factory begins churning
out the first bottles of ``l'eau de grandmere'' perfume, not to
mention the related line of colognes, bath oils, scented talcs and
air fresheners. The term ``sweatshop'' will take on a new and even
grimmer meaning on the day the Herald-Tribune breaks the story of a
heartless, greedy industry that collects the drippings off feeble
grandmothers who are forced to stand for hours in the hot sun so
that pleasure-seeking yuppies can get a buzz off their sweat.
</P>
<P>
   It all might turn out to be a wonderful thing for Florida's
grandmas, but if I were a 70-year-old woman, I think I'd be
stocking up on deodorant.
</P>
<P>
   (The Herald-Tribune in Sarasota, Fla., is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
