<HEADLINE>
NOTES FROM THE TV CRITICS TOUR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ The flap over the lack of decent roles for
minorities on the big TV networks came up again Friday at a press
briefing on ``Introducing Dorothy Dandridge,'' an HBO film about
the black actress/singer/dancer who enjoyed stardom in the '40s and
'50s but died mysteriously, probably a suicide, when she was 42.
</P>
<P>
   Halle Berry, who has wanted to tell the Dandridge story for
years, stars in the film and also served as an executive producer.
To the NAACP's charge that the networks are racist, Berry said:
``They're not saying anything I don't already know. Living as a
black woman in everyday society, I'm very much aware of the racism
... so it's disheartening.''
</P>
<P>
   But Berry says the racial divide is not unique to TV. ``I still
don't feel there is a space for a (black) leading lady in Hollywood
because now that I've done this amazing role of a lifetime, ... for
the last six months I've not been able to find a project that can
even compare to the role I've just been able to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Berry shows an amazing capacity for patience in the wait
for colorblind casting.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't see it in my lifetime, I'm confident that my part
is very important,'' she said. ``I must live out this moment in
time and, later on down the line, whether I'm here to see it or
not, somebody like me and Dorothy will see that brand new shiny
day.''
</P>
<P>
   _Geraldo Rivera says he's a ``high energy'' guy. Besides his
duties as an NBC News correspondent and as host of ``Rivera Live''
and ``Upfront Tonight'' on CNBC, Rivera host has been sailing the
globe in fits and starts since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever his schedule allows, he and his family hop a plane to
wherever it is they last moored their sailboat, Voyager, and sail
it until events warrant a return to TV for the tillerman.
</P>
<P>
   A two-part film of Rivera's circumnavigation, ``Sail to the
Century,'' will air in mid-December and early next year on Travel
Channel, one of the new kids in the Discovery Networks family.
Rivera's goal is to be among the first to ring in the year 2000 at
the International Date Line.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera says his lust for leaving the office has nothing to do
with the fact that some of the luminaries at NBC News weren't
thrilled when he was named a correspondent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will never be `one of the guys' over there,'' Rivera
admitted Friday. ``But NBC is big enough that Brokaw and I can
co-exist.'' After some reflection he added: ``Hopefully, in the
future, the Kosovars and the Serbs will get along.''
</P>
<P>
   _Dan Patrick and Chris Berman each had a say in determining
ESPN's greatest athletes of the century, but neither anchor knows
who will be No. 1 at the end of the year. ESPN this week reached
No. 27 (San Francisco 49ers receiver Jerry Rice) in its countdown
of the top 50. It'll reach the top 10 in December, and the top two
will be announced in a two-hour show on ABC Dec. 26.
</P>
<P>
   Asked for their personal picks, Berman said he'd have Babe Ruth
No. 1, followed by Muhammad Ali and Willie Mays. Patrick also likes
Ruth for first place, with Michael Jordan and Jim Thorpe close
behind.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick said the most vocal reaction of viewers is to the
``SportsCentury'' ranking of Secretariat at No. 35. Even athletes
are keeping score. Berman said he saw former hockey star Bobby Orr
last week, and Orr's first comment was: ``Geez, at least I beat the
horse.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
