<DOCNO> NYT19990716.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3042 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEW-NOVELIST18-COX     07-16 1726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-NOVELIST18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shellman's ex-Mayor Sonny Sammons crafts novels as carefully as
he makes furniture
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday, July 18.
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHELLMAN, Ga. _ It is midafternoon in Southwest Georgia, and
former Mayor Sonny Sammons is conducting a tour of the town that is
at the heart of his two novels.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter that half of the brick stores along the
railroad tracks are vacant, and the name on the water tank is
partially obscured by rust.
</P>
<P>
   The town and characters, as they once were, are burned into
Sammons' memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a bowling alley across the road,'' he says,
maneuvering his SUV along the narrow street, ``and there used to be
a service station on the corner. We had two dime stores and a movie
theater. You know the last picture show they showed there?'' He
pauses and grins. ```The Last Picture Show.'''
</P>
<P>
   Driving past a building that used to be a horse-and-mule auction
barn, Sammons recalls his adventures on a runaway horse when he was
6. Nearly every landmark, every house triggers a story about a
person or event from his childhood.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these stories are woven into his 1995 autobiographical
first novel, ``The Keepers of Echowah'' (Cherokee, $18.95), the
story of twin brothers growing up on a hunting plantation in South
Georgia. Still more appear in his latest book, ``Then Sings My
Soul'' (Cherokee, $23.95), a novel based on a true story of
domestic abuse and rural justice in the 1940s. The narrator is a
young boy who is raised by his widowed mother and two grandfathers.
When Grandfather Alex's daughter is brutally abused and her husband
is later found shot to death, Alex is sentenced to die in Georgia's
electric chair.
</P>
<P>
   ``This really happened to one of my uncles,'' Sammons says,
declining to name him. ``When his daughter was beaten up pretty bad
_ I think her husband broke both her arms _ my uncle went over to
his son-in-law's house and blew his brains out with a shotgun.''
</P>
<P>
   What was amazing, Sammons says, is that the sheriff never locked
him up and allowed him to go back to work on his farm. About three
days before the scheduled execution, the sheriff sent him a ticket
and he caught the bus to Reidsville State Prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was supposed to be electrocuted at midnight on a Sunday,''
Sammons says, ``but (then-governor) Herman Talmadge called about 15
minutes before they pulled the switch and commuted his sentence.''
He smiles. ``There might have been a campaign contribution made, I
don't know. There were a lot of sentences commuted back then.''
</P>
<P>
   Sammons, 57, sturdily built and sunburned, admits that he began
writing simply to make extra money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read something about how much money John Grisham was making,
so I started reading the best sellers to see what worked. Most of
those guys, like Grisham or Robert James Waller, all they want you
to do is turn the page. I wanted to write like Cormac McCarthy or
Larry McMurtry. With them, you can close your eyes and almost smell
what they're writing about.''
</P>
<P>
   He found it wasn't as easy as it looked.
</P>
<P>
   He was working on ``The Keepers of Echowah'' (pronounced
EK-O-WAH, it's a Creek Indian word for ``where sleeping deer lie'')
in his store in Highlands, N.C., five years ago when Atlanta public
relations writer Patrice Dickey walked in.
</P>
<P>
   ``She asked me what I was doing,'' Sammons says. ``I said,
`Wasting my time writing a manuscript.' She asked to read it and
said she had a friend who was a movie producer.''
</P>
<P>
   The friend was Don Daniels, who was in Atlanta at the time
producing ``Kleptomania'' with Amy Irving. Daniels liked the
manuscript and bought the rights. A year later, Cherokee Publishing
Co. of Marietta picked up the publishing rights for an undisclosed
sum. (Plans for a film are still pending, Sammons says.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me two months to write the first draft and three
months to correct the spelling,'' says Sammons, who flunked out of
every college he attended. ``I wore out two copies of Strunk &AMP;
White making sure I got the structure right.''
</P>
<P>
   Free-lance editor Alexa Selph, who worked with Sammons on the
book, was impressed with his raw talent. ``He hasn't had that much
formal education, but he's incredibly well-read. The only problem I
had with his writing was keeping him from sermonizing.''
</P>
<P>
   Publishers Weekly, the book industry's trade magazine, praised
the novel's ``lovely balance of lyrical nostalgia and gleefully
coarse humor.'' Others described it as a cross between Olive Ann
Burns' ``Cold Sassy Tree'' and Ferrol Sams' ``Run With the
Horsemen.''
</P>
<P>
   The novel sold more than 8,000 copies _ surprisingly well for a
first novel _ and, at one book signing in Blytheville, Ark., more
than 140 people showed up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We loved the book,'' says Mary Gay Shipley, owner of That
Bookstore in Blytheville. ``A lot of the people liked it because of
the nostalgia. The two boys in the book had free run of the hunting
lodge. I think there's a real longing for that sense of freedom for
children. And it was a real good little story.''
</P>
<P>
   While Sammons has mastered many skills, he admits he is as
surprised as anyone that he became a writer. Born and raised in a
four-room log house that once served as a stagecoach stop, Sammons
spent his early years roaming the woods and helping his father
farm.
</P>
<P>
   His present house, a 1906 Georgia cottage that he restored, is a
far cry from his rustic childhood home. The hardwood floors are
polished to a soft lustre, the high ceilings are trimmed with crown
moulding, and all of the original plaster has been redone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was 9 or 10 when we first got electricity,'' says Sammons,
sitting at an enormous heart pine table that he built himself and
munching on a barbecue sandwich. ``We never did get indoor
plumbing. My father put all of the money he made back into the
farm.''
</P>
<P>
   After his ill-fated college career, Sammons was drafted and
served a hitch in the Army. He came back home, started a peanut
warehouse business, then opened a children's apparel manufacturing
firm and a string of auto parts stores. In 1980, friends talked him
into running for mayor. ``There's not that much prestige in being
mayor of a town of 1,200,'' says Sammons, who held the office for
10 years. ``People call you at 11 o'clock at night complaining
about a dog barking in their yard.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, he was a good mayor, says childhood friend Jimmy
Martin. ``He got a lot of grants for the town. He always could do
anything he set his mind to. He did not make top grades, but he
could have. He had a rough time when his wife got leukemia. She was
a super nice lady.''
</P>
<P>
   The death of Sammons' wife, Chris, in 1986 nearly destroyed him.
Left with a teenage son and two daughters, he was so distraught he
considered selling everything and taking his children to Venezuela,
simply to escape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to retire and sit around feeling sorry for myself,
until the people I sold one business to went bankrupt, and all of a
sudden I owed the bank a million dollars and I had a $500,000 lien
from the IRS.''
</P>
<P>
   Sammons settled his debts by selling his land and all of his
assets. Starting from scratch, he decided to become a custom
furniture maker, partly because it was something he was interested
in, and partly because it helped him deal with his grief.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd always enjoyed working with my hands, and I'd started
making furniture as a hobby, so the transition was real easy. The
good thing about it was I didn't have any set hours. Every other
business I'd owned had held me captive. When I ran the peanut
business, I had to be there from 7 in the morning until 7 at night.
They owned me. And,'' he adds, ``when you're working on a piece of
furniture, it takes your mind off other things.''
</P>
<P>
   As he did with his writing, Sammons learned to make furniture
simply by doing it until he got it right. ``I busted my thumb a lot
in the early days,'' he says, grinning. ``I stole a lot of designs.
I'd see something I'd like and add some of my own touches.
</P>
<P>
   Using heart pine from old barns, churches and abandoned
buildings, he crafted chairs, cabinets, and tables for customers in
Atlanta and Highlands. He closed his stores in Buckhead and
Highlands when he moved into the construction business, and now he
takes custom orders only and operates the company, Southern Pine,
out of a workshop in Shellman. Demand is so great they are a couple
of months behind, he says.
</P>
<P>
   He made by hand nearly all of the pieces of furniture in the
house _ from an oak secretary to a heart pine hunt board. All are
meticulously crafted and finished, with none of the plywood that is
used in a lot of mass-produced furniture. He rubs his hand along
the polished patina of the table and drapes his arm over a sturdy,
straight-backed dining chair. ``Our furniture is built to last for
generations. These chairs I built, they're uncomfortable as hell,''
he jokes. ``But they look real nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Remarried after his wife's death, Sammons and his wife, Joy, 31,
have adopted a 2-year-old daughter, Laura Joy, an energetic child
who makes Sammons' face light up every time she bounds into his
lap.
</P>
<P>
   Joy, a slim, dark-haired woman who met Sammons at Panama City
Beach nine years ago, laughs shyly about their age difference. ``I
just thought he was nice-looking. I didn't know how old he was.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Age has not been a factor in our relationship,'' Sammons adds.
``We like to travel. Joy likes to work in the yard. Now she wants
to go to Georgia State and get her doctorate, so we have to think
about moving. I'll do whatever she wants to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Sammons has turned the furniture-making business over
to his son, John, and plans to continue working on his writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to go back and read authors like Eudora Welty and
John Steinbeck to get some idea of how they did it,'' he says
between sips of homemade lemonade. ``I'd like to keep improving.''
</P>
<P>
   But if he never becomes famous as a writer, at least he has his
political legacy. His proudest accomplishment during his 10-year
stint as mayor, he deadpans, was adopting the motto, ``Shellman,
Georgia: We Have Never Heard of You Either.''
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
