<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Journal explores growth of plant biotechnology
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday July 18.
 &HT;    By Rachael Kennedy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You can't tell by look, smell or taste, but that delicious cob
of corn you're eating may not be the same corn you're used to
eating.
</P>
<P>
   Once considered a thing of science fiction, genetically modified
foods are a growing part of the world's food supply _ even though
many consumers are not sold on their safety or usefulness, new
research shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plant biotechnology is exploding. There are issues with
production; there are a lot of societal questions coming up,'' said
Brooks Hanson, deputy managing editor of the journal Science, which
explored the pros and cons of GMF in a special edition last week.
``We felt it was time to update the state of the science
surrounding the changes.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the findings from three articles in Science:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  GMF are becoming commonplace. In 1996, 2 million acres
worldwide were planted with transgenic crops. By 1998, that number
had escalated to 67 million acres. Seventy-four percent of those
acres were in the United States. The only other countries with
large croplands planted with GMF were Argentina, with 15 percent of
the world's production, and Canada, with 10 percent. The five
principal crops include soybeans, corn, cotton, rapeseed/canola and
potato, and 1998 sales amounted to $1.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Plant biotechnology is not only being used to improve the food
supply, by allowing for bigger and faster crop production, but
recent advances have also led to the development of plants that may
be able to safely remove high levels of toxic metals from soil.
Scientists are also investigating ways plants can be modified for
industrial use.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Americans are more open to GMF than Europeans. A 1997 poll of
more than 1,000 U.S. citizens by the London School of Economics
found that 30 percent support GMF, 11 percent oppose GMF and
another 19 percent are uneasy with their use. A separate poll of
16,500 Europeans by the school found 16 percent support GMF, 22
percent oppose and 15 percent are uneasy with their use.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, Americans are more opposed to genetic testing on
humans and genetic medicines than bioengineered food sources, the
school found. Researchers also said that Americans are less
scientifically literate than Europeans and expressed greater trust
in the government regulatory bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Iceland banned GMF altogether and Prince Charles and
the European Community publicly called for more regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Other articles in Friday's special edition of Science explore
the ethical debates surrounding GMF, patent issues, the science
behind modification and how developing nations may benefit from
wider use of GMF.
</P>
<P>
   Rachel Kennedy writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
