A3044 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUMMY16-COX     07-16 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUMMY16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mummies and mystery at Egyptian art unveiling
 &HT;    By Catherine Fox
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In the basement of Emory University's Michael C.
Carlos Museum, an ancient coffin case, its head swathed in towels,
appears to be primping for its debut in the third floor galleries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's aromatherapy,'' kids Kate Singley, a free-lance
conservator.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Singley is trying to shore up the frail surface of the
head so that it can make it through its Atlanta unveiling without
further damage. On Monday, for one day only, the public can see the
mummies, coffin cases, canopic jars (limestone containers for
internal organs) and other objects that the Carlos purchased this
year from a Niagara Falls, Ontario, curiosity museum. A public
campaign helped raise $2 million to buy the 83 objects, some of
which are at least 3,000 years old.
</P>
<P>
   For this much-anticipated first viewing, several objects will
join the permanent collection of Egyptian art on the first floor
for a six-month rotation. The Carlos also has installed _ again,
for Monday only _ a small sampling of the acquired objects on the
third floor, including three coffins, a mummy still in the crate in
which it traveled to the Carlos in May, a bronze falcon and a
mummified cat.
</P>
<P>
   Like Cinderella, these objects will return to the conservation
lab Tuesday for further work. There is much to do before they are
shown in a large temporary exhibition planned for 2001. In addition
to restoration, the objects will be carefully studied.
Conservators, working with Peter Lacovara, Carlos curator of
ancient art, will shine a black light on the coffins and canopic
jars to see if the varnish and paint is old or new. (New paint
fluoresces.)
</P>
<P>
   ``If the paint on the canopic jars is old, then they are very
rare,'' Lacovara says. ``I only know of a few in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston Egyptologist Joyce Haynes will work to decipher the
hieroglyphs. One of her goals is to figure out the identities of
some of the mummies in the coffins. This will help Lacovara to work
out their genealogy. Emory art history professor Gay Robins will
study the painting styles.
</P>
<P>
   The mummies will go through medical hoops _ CAT scans, X-rays
and DNA testing. In an uncanny coincidence, the mummies have ended
up at one of the few places in the world where such DNA testing is
possible _ in the lab of molecular biologist Douglas Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kismet,'' says Lacovara.
</P>
<P>
   Because they suspect that one of the mummies may be Egyptian
royalty, research will require DNA testing on royal mummies in
Egypt as well as contemporary Egyptians. If the remains turn out to
be Ramses I, the Carlos has promised to return him to Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   You can be sure of one thing: The Carlos will make every effort
_ in Monday's display and in its 2001 show _ to avoid any of the
ghoulishness or sensationalism that has always been part of mummy
mania.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to display the remains respectfully,'' says Therese
O'Gorman, the Andrew W. Mellon conservator at the Carlos, ``and we
want to use them as a hook to get people to learn more about
ancient art and society.''
</P>
<P>
   First Impression: A Preview of the Collection of Egyptian
Antiquities
</P>
<P>
   11 a.m.-7 p.m. Monday. Suggested donation: $3. Emory
University's Michael C. Carlos Museum, 571 S. Kilgo St. N.E.
404-727-4282. Large crowds are expected. Parking will be available
at Emory West, 1256 Briarcliff Road N.E., formerly the Georgia
Mental Health Institute, where specially designated shuttles will
provide round-trip rides to the museum. Additional parking may be
available at on-campus parking lots, but space is limited.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Fox writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
