<HEADER>
A3045 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSEUMS-SIDE17-COX     07-16 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSEUMS-SIDE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Interest grows in artifacts of slavery
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A large hand-woven seed basket, made either by slaves
or by emancipated African-Americans just after the Civil War, sits
atop an old bookcase in Nathaniel Norman's antiques shop on
Bankhead Highway. He also has an intricately carved mahogany cane,
whittled either in Africa or by African-Americans. And a one-string
musical instrument popular ``in slavery times.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman, 49, is one of the few black antiques dealers in Atlanta,
catering to blacks who no longer consider their ancestors' history
a time to forget. He's not yet a big bug in the flea market
business, but he has become a go-to guy for Atlanta-area
African-Americans who, while abhorring the oppression of their
forebears, nevertheless want to own reminders of slavery and the
Jim Crow era.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our people are getting interested in collecting because it
gives you a sense of who we are and where we came from,'' Norman
says.
</P>
<P>
   To stock his store, Norman's Antiques and Collectibles, he
employs a legion of ``hunters'' who bring in everything from canes
and old banjos to swords picked up on Civil War battlefields.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our people don't throw away nothing,'' he says, holding the
seed basket, which he bought from a 97-year-old woman whose
ancestors were slaves. ``And look at this cane. It's definitely
African. My people have stuff everywhere. There are treasures all
over, still hidden.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Thomas Jr., a 47-year-old Atlanta lawyer, collects
anything he can find from slavery times. He owns a deed describing
the sale of a little boy and a little girl, as well as slave
shackles used in the 1830s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than being a source of embarrassment, there's a
tremendous source of pride to see how far we've come as a people,''
says Thomas, who uses the items as props in frequent talks to
school groups. ``To deny history is not good for our community, or
our kids. If we accept it and explain it, it creates a much
healthier environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Seeing the shackles makes children ``really sit up,'' Thomas
says. ``They find it a little hard to believe this really
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Browsing in Norman's cluttered store, John Burrison, 56, a
professor of culture at Georgia State University, is immediately
impressed.
</P>
<P>
   Gently touching the seed basket, Burrison, who has a permanent
collection of folk art at the Atlanta History Center, says, ``I've
never seen anything like it.'' Then he sees a hand-carved mahogany
cane, which leaves him breathless. ``It's distinctly
African-American,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Growing interest in relics of slave times has created a market
nationally. Shackles can be purchased on the Internet, and one Web
site recently advertised an ``extremely rare female slave collar''
for nearly $9,000.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, slave deeds and bills of sale could be had for as
little as $50, but those days are gone. Today, such items bring
five to 10 times as much.
</P>
<P>
   ``And this stuff is just now starting to come out,'' says
Norman. ``Some are just now finding it. And a lot have it but don't
know what to do with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hendrick writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
