<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990716.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3046 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSEUMS17-COX     07-16 1563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSEUMS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    From attic to basement, atlantans' homes are full of intriguing
artifacts
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Gingerly, Paul Hineman opens a weathered cardboard
box, slowly unfurling a tattered Old Glory, with 38 stars, that he
says draped the coffin of Ulysses S. Grant in 1886.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Brown, manager of Red Baron's Antiques in Sandy Springs
(Ga.), is _ ahem _ more than a tad dubious. One of the South's
premier experts on antiques, he's constantly fending off excited
patrons trying to peddle valueless junk that they think is
priceless.
</P>
<P>
   But this time it's different.
</P>
<P>
   Hineman, 34, offers documentation: yellowed newspaper clips,
family letters and a 1936 Good Housekeeping magazine article about
the flag, which he inherited from his grandmother. Brown studies
the flag and documents, then scribbles out a $7,000 check.
</P>
<P>
   There may no longer be gold in the hills of Dahlonega (Ga.), but
there's definitely a heap of gold in them thar attics, basements
and long-stored cedar chests all around Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Americans, and especially Southerners, are keepers, Brown says.
Which is why, whether you live in a mobile home or a million-dollar
mansion, the odds are that many of your neighbors could show you
relics you'd be hard-pressed to find in a museum.
</P>
<P>
   Interest in historical artifacts has been heightened by eBay, an
Internet auction site, and PBS's popular ``Antiques Road Show.''
They've sent millions of people rummaging through barns, attics and
basements looking for reminders of the past, to sell or to preserve
for themselves. Dealers such as Brown spend lots of time eyeballing
objects for people who want someone to authenticate, or perhaps
buy, interesting items that they've had for decades or picked up at
garage sales.
</P>
<P>
   Take Henry W. Grady III, 37, an investment specialist and the
great-great-grandson of Henry W. Grady, famous for his editorship
of The Atlanta Constitution in the 1880s. The first Henry Grady's
father, Maj. William S. Grady, was a Confederate cavalryman, and
his Tiffany sword has been passed down for five generations.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Grady took the sword to Frank Walsh, co-owner of
Yesteryear Book Shop in Atlanta and a sometime appraiser for the
``Road Show.'' Walsh said it would fetch somewhere between $5,000
and $10,000 at auction.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it was only curiosity,'' says Grady. ``Obviously, I
wouldn't sell at any price.''
</P>
<P>
   He plans to pass the sword down to his three daughters or donate
it to the University of Georgia, his alma mater.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Grady and Hineman were among several hundred people who
responded to a notice in The Atlanta Journal-Constitution inviting
owners of pre-World I relics to call us. What metro Atlantans told
us they own ran the gamut, from a 15th-century German prayer book
to the diary of former Georgia Gov. Hoke Smith, from a slightly
used 1800s coffin to a teapot from the Great London Exposition of
1851.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just monetary value that drives most people to hold on
to heirlooms or buy historical relics. Many, like Grady, do so for
sentimental reasons, to maintain a connection with the past.
</P>
<P>
   John Crosswell, 77, of Covington still has a July 2, 1863,
edition of the Vicksburg Daily Citizen that he traded ``a no-good,
broken-down bicycle for'' 65 years ago. ``It's a piece of
history,'' he observes.
</P>
<P>
   Brown says the country is full of such relics, though many
aren't as well cared for as Crosswell's Civil War newspaper has
been.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a tremendous amount out there,'' Brown says. ``People
die and move on, go from bigger to smaller houses as they age. They
give things to the grandaughter or son or whatever. And they put it
in the basement because people don't realize its value, or it
doesn't fit in with their lives. It's unbelievable, the things you
see.''
</P>
<P>
   Many people, however, do realize the value. That's why estate
sales often attract lots of potential buyers. Walsh, of Yesteryear
Book Shop, believes that nostalgia is being fueled partly by the
approaching millennium, which makes many baby boomers feel old, as
they realize that many of their childhood toys, such as original
Mickey Mouse hats, are now considered antiques.
</P>
<P>
   Interest in collectibles is so keen that the Atlanta History
Center has scheduled a collectors' day Sept. 18, at which experts
such as Walsh and Brown will examine relics. And on Aug. 5, when
the American Political Items Collectors hold their national
convention in Atlanta, thousands of owners of old political
ribbons, buttons and posters will converge here from around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we move around so much, and as so many Americans are cut
off from neighbors and ordinary friendliness in daily life, we
treasure these objects that help us feel connected,''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Paul Brown, son of the Red Baron's manager, who also works
for the store: ``With the relics we own, we all become portals to
the past, portals which everyone, whether they are aware or not, is
drawn into. Part of the human condition involves, often on a
subconscious level, being a part of something greater than the sum
of its parts.''
</P>
<P>
   One recent morning, Bob Linzey, an executive with the
Ritz-Carlton Hotel Co., proudly showed Walsh a 431-year-old German
prayer book, printed with carved wooden blocks. The antiques expert
was almost at a loss for words.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is marvelous,'' Walsh whispered. ``Look at this date in
Latin, `MDLXVIII' _ 1568. Look, someone has written in the margins.
The covers are made of wood, and it's bound with brass hinges.
Remarkable!''
</P>
<P>
   Linzey wasn't interested in selling, and though Walsh is an
expert on antique books, he was hesitant to put a value on this
one, suggesting that someone at Emory University's Candler School
of Theology should take a look. Linzey got the thick volume,
containing several thousand pages, from a long-dead friend who had
found it in the eaves of a bombed-out house in Germany during World
War II.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   In the South, Civil War relics are always hot.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes they're even too hot to handle, says Brown. ``I've had
people sell muskets that go off _ they didn't know it was loaded.
And artillery shells are still dug up.''
</P>
<P>
   Herman James, 58, of Newnan (GA.) found his Union artillery
shell on his great-grandfather's farm near the site of the 1864
Battle of Kennesaw Mountain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was plowed up back in the '50s,'' he says. ``I keep it in
my closet. This one was a dud, but it still had black powder in
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Shells and cannonballs can be found in most antiques stores,
says John Sexton, owner of Stone Mountain Relics, and some can be
worth several hundred dollars to museums or collectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The emotion in those things is important, especially in the
South,'' he says. ``That's one reason Confederate swords can go up
into the tens of thousands of dollars, easily. They're much more
valuable than Union swords, which aren't as rare.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Kohlhoff's Civil War-era collection includes two
unredeemed Confederate $1,000 bonds _ which, had the Confederacy
endured, would each be worth $2.6 million today.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the South ever rises again, I'll be in high cotton,'' jokes
Kohlhoff, 51. He also owns a quilt made by slaves, a first edition
of ``Alice in Wonderland,'' published in 1865, and Confederate
10-cent scrip printed by Mechanics Bank in Augusta.
</P>
<P>
   Even discharge papers from the Civil War era can fetch several
hundred dollars, Kohlhoff adds, and a copy of the parole issued to
the 30,000 men who surrendered at Appomattox with Robert E. Lee is
easily worth $3,000 or more. Even at that price, he adds, ``they
are almost impossible to find,'' because their owners aren't
interested in selling them.
</P>
<P>
   Case in point: Kasey Walter, 51, of Marietta (GA.) says,
``There's some things you can't put a price on,'' such as her
husband John's collection of 39 letters, eloquently written in 1864
by his great-great-grandfather, Charles Shepard, a Union soldier
who encountered the legendary Confederate unit Mosby's Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``He describes raids by Mosby's Raiders, and what's interesting
is, my great-grandfather was in Mosby's Raiders. They probably
fought against each other!''
</P>
<P>
   Many relics that people consider priceless, however, have little
value on the open market.
</P>
<P>
   The 19th-century coffin owned by Harriet Rowland of Forest Park
(GA.) is ``very strange,'' she says. ``It's made of oak with a
cedar lid. At one time there was a body inside. You can still see
bloodstains. I keep it in my barn because there's a ghost that came
with it.''
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the private-collection spectrum are items
that many museums would love to have, such as a bronze spoon, now
owned by Jessica Simmons, that was once used by a soldier in the
army of Oliver Cromwell, who led a revolution in 17th-century
England. Her grandfather found it while digging in his garden in
Kent, England, in 1953 and had it authenicated by the British
Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Or the 1st century A.D. bowls and jars that Joseph Hassell, 78,
of Acworth (GA.) brought home from Turkey in the 1950s and had
authenticated by the Corning Museum of Glass in New York. Says
Hassell: ``I've had them in a shoe box in my closet ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hendrick writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
