<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3048 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIGITAL-LA-LADN     07-16 1243
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-LA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOULD-BE GAME PLAYERS TAPPED OUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
By DAVID BLOOM 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ They came. They saw. Their credit cards bounced.
</P>
<P>
   It was a nearly perfect ending for Hollywood Video and Sega, who
combined this week for a late-night promotional gimmick at the
video rental company's Westwood store and four others around the
country as it began renting its Dreamcast gaming machine.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time a new videogame console had ever been
offered for rental before the machine was available for sale, said
Sega of America president and chief operations officer Bernard
Stolar. Dreamcast goes on sale Sept. 9.
</P>
<P>
   About 150 people formed two lines outside the store, where they
waited for up to several hours to be among the first to rent the
next-generation gaming machine at 12:01 a.m. Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The companies tried to make their wait worthwhile, with pizza
and soft drinks, appearances and autographs by a few pneumatically
generic TV starlets, giveaways (including two Dreamcast machines)
and more.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, when it came right down to actually renting the
machines, for many the spirit was willing but the credit limit was
weak.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood Video is requiring a $350 deposit to rent the machine
for two nights (along with $19.99 for the game rental).
</P>
<P>
   For a lot of the scruffy game freaks who'd been waiting for
their chance at the hot new machine, this was way more freight than
their slender credit line could bear.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood Entertainment president Jeffrey Yapp said the stout
charge covers the cost of the machine, two controllers and game,
along with a little bit more, to make sure it all comes back.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, nearly a fourth of the roughly 1,300 Hollywood
Video stores won't even have the game machines, solely because
customers in those neighborhoods aren't very good about bringing
stuff back, Yapp said. The machines should be widely available in
Los Angeles outlets, however.
</P>
<P>
   The stout credit requirements whittled the crowd quickly by
midnight, leaving Megan Koplin-Panzer of Beverly Hills and her
family second in line, even though about 20 people had been ahead
of her husband and son when they first showed up around 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Soon enough, however, her son, D.J., was brandishing the black
plastic briefcase holding the game equipment as they marched out of
the store.
</P>
<P>
   Though only Sonic Adventure was available for rental on
Thursday, three other titles are coming before the machine goes on
sale, said Stolar.
</P>
<P>
   Ready 2 Rumble, a boxing game, and Powerstone, a hybrid
adventure and fighting game, will come out within a few weeks,
Stolar said. And just before Sept. 9, the much-awaited football
title, NFL 2000, will roll out.
</P>
<P>
   The rental package includes the basic Dreamcast machine, two
controllers and an RF converter to connect the machine to a TV set.
Additional rental games will go for $4.99, the same price Hollywood
charges for Nintendo 64 and PlayStation games. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Local waves
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I know the Internet is supposed to make everything global.
But lately, I've run across a raft of Los Angeles-based or
-oriented Web sites that are worth checking out. Remember the old
political adage: Everything is local.
</P>
<P>
   One of the new sites is really new. In fact, LA2Nite.com (at
www.la2nite.com) officially opens for business today.
</P>
<P>
   The brainchild of three youthful Princeton grads, the site is
led by chief operations officer Elizabeth Peterson, a long-time
veteran of the Los Angeles music scene as a booker and promoter at
prominent clubs.
</P>
<P>
   The site, she said, will focus on an array of local music
scenes, including Latin, jazz, electronica, pop and more.
Peterson's four-person editorial staff also will report on local
art and culture, particularly in under-covered areas such as the
Eastside and gay scenes, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The preview site is handsome enough, and the site is
aggressively marketing itself by giving away tickets and a car, and
co-sponsoring a July 25 concert of dance-music performers at the
John Anson Ford Amphitheatre.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson said the site plans to make money by selling tickets to
shows at medium-sized and smaller venues in Los Angeles, and will
be involved in many concerts itself.
</P>
<P>
   I wish them luck, though they'll have plenty of competition for
business, starting with Ticketmaster, the ticket-selling giant
whose offices ironically are just across the courtyard from
LA2Nite's mid-Wilshire office building.
</P>
<P>
   Another site that particularly caught my eye is Inside DVD
(atwww.insidedvd.com), in Altadena. If you're a DVD fan, you should
like this one.
</P>
<P>
   Register for its magazine on-site and you'll be sent a DVD full
of game demos, movie trailers, DVD news, music samplers and, on the
back side of the disc, a complete movie. The films aren't
particularly big-time ones, of course, but they're legitimate
theatrical releases and the price
 &UR; !ital! &LR; is tough to beat.
</P>
<P>
   I had some qualms about information requested in the
registration process, but unlike so many other Web sites, at least
there was a clear return of something of value for my investment.
</P>
<P>
   You can check out the site without getting the magazine, and
there's an array of odds and ends there that may be of use to the
DVD-oriented.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of DVDs, disc seller/renter DVD Express
(www.dvdexpress.com) just cut a deal with the Hollywood
Entertainment Museum to create what it's calling the Hollywood
Backlot, an area where entertainment-oriented memorabilia is
auctioned off.
</P>
<P>
   Recent goodies for sale included an autographed guitar from Soul
Asylum (fetching an inexplicably high $1,500 bid at last glance), a
film poster from ``Boogie Nights'' autographed by star Mark
Wahlberg, a ``Home Improvement'' script signed by star Tim Allen,
the uniform Denzel Washington wore in ``Courage Under Fire,'' and
autographed items from William Shatner and Bill Cosby.
</P>
<P>
   The non-profit museum, located on Hollywood Boulevard, and the
Web site are splitting auction proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   DVD Express is branching out a bit, too, selling games for
PlayStation, Game Boy and Nintendo 64, computer games and DVD-ROM
software, and even some gadgets and gizmos that may appeal to DVD
enthusiasts.
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of concerts, LA Live (at www.lalive.com) remains a
good choice, especially if you have a faster connection and the
right streaming media plug-ins to enjoy their live concert
transmissions from 15 affiliated venues in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, another recent local startup is L.A. Woman magazine
(lawomanmagazine.com), based in Beverly Hills.
</P>
<P>
   Publisher Marjorie Padorr said she wants to make the site a
forum for women with articles, discussion areas, a calendar
section, interviews and more.
</P>
<P>
   A book author and Peabody Award winner for radio reporting,
Padorr said she hopes to publish a hard-copy version of the
magazine someday soon, but will concentrate on the online version
for now.
</P>
<P>
   The site's writing is still a bit raw and the look is
graphically unsophisticated. But the site pointed out films that
may appeal to women and offered tips, for example, on how to
organize the endless paperwork of what was supposed to be a
paperless technology revolution.
</P>
<P>
   To reach David Bloom with stories, tips and other information on
the intersection of art, entertainment and technology, e-mail him
at davidbloom(at)earthlink.net or call (818) 713-3678. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
