r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-$ADV19     07-16 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-$ADV19-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVANCE FOR MONDAY JULY 19 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
 SECRETS OF THOSE DOLES 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Elizabeth Dole &LR;  reveals in ``What You Didn't Know About
Elizabeth Dole,'' a story in the latest issue of Ladies' Home
Journal, that she and Bob ``may get another dog, but we're having
work done on the apartment.''
</P>
<P>
   The dearly departed dog was  &UR; Leader &LR; ; the apartment work is
breaking through to the former Lewinsky apartment next door, to
expand the Doles' residence.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BOWSER EFFECT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The latest issue of the gone-upscale Berkeley periodical The
Bark includes ads for:
</P>
<P>
   K9 party cakes for dogs; Camp Winnaribbun ``summer camp for you
and your dog''; handmade winged urns for the cremains of pets and
people; ``acupressure/laser-puncture'' therapeutic massage for
dogs; guided walking tours of the Monterey Peninsula for dogs and
their humans; classes in Pet CPR; ``unique jewelry for pets''; and
counseling for humans who wish to ``have your canine companion
accompany you to therapy to provide the support you need.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ The National Press Club has released its attendance figure for
speakers this year and found that the biggest audience draw, by
far, was Minnesota Governor  &UR; Jesse Ventura &LR; , who addressed 381
members and guests. Last place was held by writer  &UR; Tom Clancy &LR; , who
beat out Miss America,  &UR; Nicole Johnson &LR; , by six people. She drew
77.
</P>
<P>
   _ The latest edition of International Who's Who includes
designer  &UR; Donatella Versace &LR;  and suspected bomber &UR; Osama bin &LR; 
 &UR; Laden &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   _ In Lexington, Ky., miniature golf course based on Scripture,
described in the Los Angeles Times, includes: a Noah's Ark hole,
where players putt around concrete animals; a recorded voice that
repeats ``He's alive''; Moses and the burning bush; and Jesus
turning water into wine.
</P>
<P>
   _ Glamour magazine kindly provides the ``secrets for staying
young'' of  &UR; Drew Barrymore  &LR; and  &UR; Leonardo DiCaprio &LR; , both 24 (she
wears butterfly clips in her hair; he fiddles with his Sony
PlayStation).
</P>
<P>
   _ In honor of Juror Appreciation Week, reports California
Lawyer, Placer County jurors received books of poems and Ventura
County jurors were treated to a magic show put on by a court
employee who moonlights as a magician.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Washington Monthly reports that the Selective Service
system is accepting Internet registrations. If you're a guy between
18 and 25 years old, you can register at http://www.sss.gov/.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; David Letterman  &LR; staffers will be auditioning at the Santa
Clara County Fair on August 7 and 8 for Stupid Pet Tricks and
Stupid Human Tricks.
</P>
<P>
   _ Belgian artist  &UR; Wim Delvoye &LR; 's work is the tattooing of live
pigs, but it won't be shown in America. ``The United States was
very paranoid about letting in pigs from Belgium,'' Delvoye told
Stuff magazine, ``because of disease.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Cleanliness is next to Gratefulness:  &UR; Helen Stein &LR; , who used
to be married to  &UR; Howard Stein &LR; , owner of rock clubs in New York,
told  &UR; Baird Jones &LR;  at the premiere party for ``Twin Falls Idaho''
that many of the bands stayed at their home. ``Some of the groups
were really filthy. Amazingly, the Grateful Dead turned out to be
the neatest. When they left the house, it looked like no one had
even lived there. They may have had Pig Pen in the group, but when
they left, even the toilets were spotless.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Los Angeles magazine, which keeps track of everything
important, notes that not only does Cedars-Sinai Hospital in L.A.
have an excellent reputation, but ``that's nothing compared to
being known worldwide as `the hospital of the stars` _ the place
where  &UR; Frank Sinatra &LR;  died,  &UR; Elizabeth Taylor &LR; 's brain tumor was
removed and  &UR; Jodie Foster  &LR; gave birth.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't look at it as bottoming out. I spent six years going
inside myself in a way that people who are stuck with the idea that
they have to accomplish something with their lives never get a
chance to do. I was able to do what I was dreaming about, which was
to just sit there and do nothing _ to feel no obligation to do
anything for anybody. Or for myself.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Guitarist John Frusciante of the Red Hot Chili Peppers,
telling Spin magazine of his formative years as a drop-out.
</P>
</TEXT>
