<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3072 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CISNEROS17-COX     07-16 0524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CISNEROS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CISNEROS JUDGE HINTS HE'LL ALLOW SOME TAPES AS EVIDENCE
 &HT;    BY JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ U.S. District Judge Stanley Sporkin strongly hinted
Friday that he would allow some secretly recorded tapes of former
housing secretary Henry Cisneros discussing alleged ``hush
payments'' with his ex-mistress to be used as evidence in
Cisneros's upcoming trial.
</P>
<P>
   Concluding a 13-day pretrial hearing that stretched over four
weeks, Sporkin told both sides that he expected to take the
``middle road,'' accepting some, but not the most altered,
recordings made by Linda Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of this is going out,'' Sporkin said of the tapes. ``I
can't buy your argument in total,'' he told the prosecution. ``And
I can't buy their argument in total.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for Cisneros argued vigorously that the tapes were
``inauthentic'' because only duplicate recordings exist and Jones
deleted parts of at least four.
</P>
<P>
   Holding a typed letter high in the air, defense lawyer Brendan
V. Sullivan Jr. dramatized his argument by calling the paper
``evidence.'' He tore out the middle paragraphs of the paper and
patched up the rest with cellophane tape, and then asked if what
remained should be accepted in a court of law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tapes, as we know, are very powerful evidence,'' Sullivan told
Sporkin. ``And tapes that are altered are powerfully misleading.''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan also blasted the contention that Jones, who has
admitted to lying repeatedly to officials, could reliably testify
about the conversations she left out.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot rely upon a liar,'' Sullivan told the judge.
Turning up his energy, he later added, ``It's an insult to the
court that she has been brought into this case.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking for the prosecution, Jim Fleissner, a professor at
Mercer Law School in Macon, Ga., argued that the tapes fall under
the rules for the best possible evidence available. He asked
Sporkin to let the jury to hear both the tapes and Jones's
testimony and make its decision.
</P>
<P>
   Fleissner cited one edited tape, saying that the court can hear
Cisneros ``talk about his fear of being in contempt of Congress for
making false statements.''
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros, former mayor of San Antonio, is charged with lying to
federal officials about paying Jones a total of $250,000 in alleged
``hush money.'' At the time, Cisneros was undergoing a security
background check before he was selected by President Clinton in
1993 to head the Department of Housing and Urban Development.
</P>
<P>
   The case dates to a 1997 indictment that followed a probe by
independent counsel David Barrett. Defense appeals and the
difficulties of assembling a summer jury in Washington have delayed
the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros did not attend the pretrial hearing. He is currently
head of Univision, a Spanish-language TV network based in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Jones is now serving 3 1/2 year sentence in a federal prison in
Carswell, Texas, for bank fraud after using the Cisneros payments
to purchase a house in the name of relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
