<HEADER>
A3075 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HILLARY-SENATE-$ADV18     07-16 1217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-SENATE-$ADV18-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY CLINTON FACES DISPUTE OVER BOMBING RANGE IN PUERTO RICO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 18)   (EDS: Filed in ``w'' and ``p'' categories)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A remote tropical island off Puerto Rico where Navy
and Marine Corps pilots practice their bombing runs may seem a long
way from New York politics and the burgeoning Senate campaign of
First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But just wait.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will soon face a ticklish political dilemma in her
exploratory Senate campaign: whether to support Puerto Rico's
demands that U.S. pilots permanently halt bombing the island of
Vieques or the U.S. Navy's contention that the bombing is essential
to America's military readiness.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton goes forward with her bid to succeed retiring Sen.
Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., her decision in the Vieques
controversy could determine whether she wins the enthusiastic
support of two million Puerto Ricans who live in New York state.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jose E. Serrano, D-N.Y., the Bronx-based lawmaker who is
the most senior Puerto Rican native in Congress, said Friday that
Puerto Ricans in New York are watching Clinton closely on this
issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to hear an agenda for my district, for my state and for
my nation,'' said Serrano, whose congressional district is 60
percent Hispanic. ``I also want to hear about Vieques.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Robert Menendez, D-N.J., said the outcome of the Vieques
dispute has become a make-or-break issue for Puerto Rican voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all talk about it,'' said Menendez, whose congressional
district is 42 percent Hispanic. ``The bottom line is that this is
a major issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Carlos Romero-Barcelo, the former governor of Puerto Rico
who represents the territory's 3.8 million residents as the
non-voting member of Congress, says the future of military
maneuvers on Vieques is ``a defining moment in Puerto Rico's
relationship with the rest of the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   The island is located eight miles east of mainland Puerto Rico,
a former Spanish colony seized by the United States in the
Spanish-American War in 1898. Residents of Puerto Rico are U.S.
citizens but they pay no U.S. taxes and do not vote for president.
However, if they move to the mainland, they can vote when they meet
local election eligibility rules.
</P>
<P>
   Navy pilots have used a 24,000-acre bombing range on the
33,000-acre island to prepare for every major military operation
since World War II, including the Persian Gulf War and the U.S.-led
bombing campaign against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   But Vieques has become a litmus test for many Puerto Ricans
since two Marine Corps' FA-18 pilots mistakenly dropped two
500-pound bombs about a mile off-target during night training on
April 19. The bombs killed security guard David Sanes Rodriguez,
35, a civilian employee of the Navy, and injured four others.
</P>
<P>
   Navy Secretary Richard Danzig suspended live fire training on
the island of 9,300 pending the outcome of a Pentagon review
ordered after the mishap.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Rican demonstrators have occupied the bombing range ever
since the accident. Nearly 50,000 residents protested the Navy's
use of Vieques outside the gates of the Roosevelt Roads Naval Base
in Puerto Rico on July 4.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Rico's political leaders are demanding the Navy's
withdrawal. Romero-Barcelo vows to join the protesters occupying
the training range if live fire training is resumed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not accept bombing under any circumstances,''
Romero-Barcelo said. ``We will do whatever we have to do to stop
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Serrano says he will use his powers on the Republican-led House
Appropriations Committee to ``make the point that dollars should
not be spent on bombing'' Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton will make a decision next month on whether to
resume live fire exercises after he receives the recommendations of
a four-member Pentagon review panel appointed at his request on
June 9.
</P>
<P>
   Serrano said that the first lady should weigh in with the
president after he receives the Pentagon report.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you are running for the Senate in a state that has
more Puerto Ricans than most cities in Puerto Rico, you definitely
have a role to play,'' Serrano said. ``I really think she should be
alerting the president to the fact that (Navy withdrawal) is
something that should happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Serrano added: ``It certainly would look good to Puerto Ricans
in New York state if she were to help us with this.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither the first lady nor the president has taken a public
position on the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Marsha Berry, the first lady's White House press secretary, said
that Mrs. Clinton awaits the report.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wants to have the process proceed and see what the
findings are from the testimony,'' Berry said. ``At some point she
will have an opinion on it and will play a role in the
deliberations.''
</P>
<P>
   Cmdr. Brian Cullin, a spokesman for the secretary of the Navy,
says the Navy anticipates that the White House decision may trigger
congressional hearings into the dispute, no matter what the
outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers representing Puerto Rican voters in congressional
districts vowed to press for congressional hearings if bombing is
resumed _ a course that assures that the issue will remain in the
spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton decides to run for the Senate, campaign strategists
say that she must sweep the Hispanic vote in New York City to
offset her Republican rival's expected support in upstate New York
and in the New York City suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   But recent New York elections show Clinton could face
difficulty.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanic support helped re-elect New York Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani, a Republican, who carried 43 percent of the Hispanic vote
in New York City in 1997. Hispanics, including Puerto Ricans, made
up 20 percent of the New York City vote in that election.
</P>
