<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3078 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIRELAND-PEACE-ASSESS     07-16 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-PEACE-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: NEW, YET HOPEFUL, TWISTS TOWARD A DELAYED PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ Unremarkably, the Rev. Ian Paisley
was on his feet with an objection. His voice rumbled with biblical
fury, his body shook, his finger shot out along its accustomed
accusatory trajectory.
</P>
<P>
   Why, he asked the chair, was he not permitted to speak first?
Across the blue-carpeted well of the Northern Ireland Assembly
chamber stood the man who had been recognized, Gerry Adams, the
president of Sinn Fein, the largely Roman Catholic party that
represents the Irish Republican Army.
</P>
<P>
   Adams saw his opportunity. With a genial smile, he offered to
yield to Paisley, his sworn enemy, who leads the hard-line
Protestant Ulster Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The response came thundering back: ``I will not speak on the
grace and favor of a member of the IRA military council.'' Paisley
sat down, and Adams told him he was ``disgraceful.''
</P>
<P>
   This mean-spirited little burlesque typified the demeaning
spectacle on Thursday with which the Northern Ireland Assembly held
the most momentous session of its year-old existence and then
promptly shut down indefinitely as fulfillment of the peace
agreement that created it ground to a halt.
</P>
<P>
   But the histrionic moment also illustrated changes in the public
life of this conflicted British province that give the current
breakdown a chance of ending up as more of a loss of momentum than
an abandonment of purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Any kind of dialogue between foes in the same room represents
progress. When Adams and his party joined the talks that led to the
Good Friday Agreement of April 1998, Paisley and his party walked
out.
</P>
<P>
   That the two men should choose to devote their brief quality
time together to rebuking one another is simply dealing in the
local currency. David Ervine, leader of the Progressive Unionist
Party, once remarked, ``Northern Ireland is the only place I know
where someone will drive 100 miles out of his way just to receive
an insult.''
</P>
<P>
   Progress in putting into place the new political arrangements
mandated by the peace settlement ended Thursday when the main
Protestant party, the Ulster Unionists, boycotted the Assembly
session that was to nominate the 10 members of the Cabinet to run
the new Ulster government.
</P>
<P>
   David Trimble, the leader of the Ulster Unionists and the first
minister of the Assembly, said his party had decided that it could
not enter government with Sinn Fein as long as the IRA refused to
turn over its weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Establishing the joint Catholic-Protestant leadership would have
led to the transfer of legislative powers from the British
Parliament to the Assembly on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   That step represented to the sponsors of the peace accord, Prime
Minister Tony Blair of Britain and his Irish counterpart, Bertie
Ahern, the assurance of an irreversible stabilization of public
life in Northern Ireland. In the last 30 years the province has
been regularly convulsed by violence that has taken more than 3,200
lives.
</P>
<P>
   The smoke clearing from Thursday's crash disclosed a political
vacuum that is particularly feared here because of the
opportunities such spaces have always offered Ulster's men of
violence.
</P>
<P>
   But it also showed a reassuring new stability that is a product
of two years of false starts and tortuous negotiations:
paramilitary groups have maintained their cease-fires, and there
has been no saber-rattling from their political representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Construction cranes dot the skyline of Belfast, with growing
business activity creating jobs for the working-class men who, when
unemployed, were easy targets for paramilitary recruiters.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Gillespie, chairman of the Northern Ireland Industrial
Development Board, said on BBC Ulster Friday morning that foreign
investment had doubled in the last year because of the perception
of peace. The politicians may pause, he said, ``but business goes
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinn Fein has transformed itself into a credible and
increasingly powerful force, attracting growing numbers of voters
and fielding candidates in elections for the British, Irish and
European parliaments. An IRA return to violence would put all that
at risk.
</P>
<P>
   The Ulster Unionists now speak directly to Sinn Fein delegates,
something they refused to do through the entire negotiation on the
agreement. In a statement directed at Sinn Fein on Thursday night,
Trimble said, ``We know this can't work without you,'' an
unimaginable comment to come from a Unionist leader only a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in London, Blair said: ``People now talk; that is
itself an extraordinary event. Peace is not perfect, but compare it
to five or six years ago and the progress is immense.''
</P>
<P>
   Confidence has always been scarce in Northern Irish politics,
and the frantic recent weeks of missed deadlines, new proposals,
amendments and marathon negotiations have strained even the limited
trust that was evolving.
</P>
<P>
   Blair is widely praised for the energy he has devoted to
Northern Ireland, but he is seen as having overreached and lost his
normally disciplined way in trying to come up with a deal. He
angered the Unionists by forcing Thursday's deadline on them, and
he infuriated Sinn Fein by offering last-minute concessions to the
Unionists.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble's rejectionist stance has strengthened him within his
party, many of whose members are unenthusiastic about the peace
agreement, but it may cost him his job as first minister. It has
diminished the prestige he once enjoyed outside Northern Ireland as
the winner of the 1998 Nobel Peace Prize with John Hume, the head
of the moderate Catholic Social Democratic and Labor Party.
</P>
<P>
   Hume's closest associate, Seamus Mallon, resigned his post as
deputy first minister on Thursday to protest Trimble's boycott.
</P>
<P>
   The confidence building over the next months is essential
because when the parties return to the task of peacemaking they
will almost certainly be facing the same impasse over guerrilla
disarmament and sharing government power with Sinn Fein that
blocked their way this week.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Sinn Fein promised that it would seek IRA
handovers of weapons if it got its Cabinet seats first. The
Unionists promised that they would let Sinn Fein have its
ministries if the IRA turned in some guns first. Their summer job
is to come up with something to make those promises more
trustworthy in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
