<SLUG> BC-CISNEROS-HEARING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE LIKELY TO PERMIT TAPES IN CISNEROS CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GARY MARTIN  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal judge signalled Friday that he would
allow secretly recorded conversations into evidence against former
Housing Secretary Henry Cisneros, but would throw out some of the
most heavily altered tapes.
</P>
<P>
   The tapes are crucial to Independent Counsel David Barrett's
case and damaging to Cisneros, whose lawyers had urged the judge to
throw out all the cassettes because they are duplicates.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros is charged in a 21-count indictment with orchestrating
a conspiracy to conceal the $250,000 he paid to Jones to protect
his nomination to head the Department of Housing and Urban
Development under President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tapes, we all know, are very powerful evidence,'' said Brendan
Sullivan, a lawyer who is defending Cisneros against the conspiracy
charges. ``And tapes that are altered are powerfully misleading.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor James Fleissner argued that the government should be
allowed to use the tapes produced by Linda Jones, with whom
Cisneros had an affair and who worried that the $4,000 he was
paying her each month would be cut off if he became secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Fleissner argued that Cisneros' own statements on the tapes were
key to the government's case, including the recorded admission that
he feared he would be ``in contempt of Congress'' if he lied about
the payments to FBI agents conducting a background investigation
into the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors want to use 26 tapes, but U.S. District Judge
Stanley Sporkin was clearly troubled by four cassettes that were
edited to eliminate details embarrassing to Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of this is going out, as far as I am concerned. It's a
matter of fairness,'' said Sporkin, who must still rule on the
admissibility of the tapes.
</P>
<P>
   The judge told prosecutors and defense lawyers he couldn't
accept either sides' ``argument in total.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the 13-day pre-trial hearing, Sporkin said he could
not find that Jones, also known by her married name, Linda Medlar,
violated federal wiretap statutes.
</P>
<P>
   If she had made the tapes with the criminal intent to commit
blackmail or extortion, Sporkin could have thrown out the entire
batch of 88 cassettes she made of conversations with Cisneros.
</P>
<P>
   Sporkin agreed Friday to listen to some of the 26 tapes,
portions of which the government wants to play to jurors when the
conspiracy trial begins on Sept. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Jones pleaded guilty to charges in a 28-count federal indictment
in Texas that outline her role in the conspiracy and acceptance of
funds funneled from Cisneros to her through relatives, who then
bought a home for Jones in Lubbock, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Jones is serving a 3 1/2-year prison sentence at a medical
center in Fort Worth. She agreed to testify against Cisneros in
exchange for a reduction in her sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros was San Antonio mayor from 1981 to 1989 and was housing
secretary from 1993 to 1996. He is currently the president of the
Spanish-language television network Univision in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The defense lawyers sought to make Jones the focus in the
pre-trial hearing, bringing in witnesses to testify that she lied
over and over to prosecutors and judges in Texas and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Jones testified that she tampered with several of the tapes at
the direction of her Lubbock lawyers, Bruce Magness and Floyd
Holder. Both men took the stand and denied those charges.
</P>
<P>
   She also lied to the independent counsel, an action that landed
her in prison after prosecutors pulled their original immunity deal
for her cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' lies about the tapes and the unknown portions that have
been tampered with, altered or erased were used by Sullivan to urge
Sporkin to rule against admissibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't rely upon the liar, the government's chief
witness!'' Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the hearing, the judge separated the trials of
co-defendants _ John Rosales and Sylvia Arce-Garcia, two Cisneros
aides at HUD _ who pleaded not guilty to the conspiracy charges
brought by Barrett. Sporkin severed the cases after Barrett
announced he would drop the charges against the aides within six
months.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros is the second Clinton Cabinet member to face trial on
charges of unethical behavior. Former Agriculture Secretary Mike
Espy was acquitted in December 1998 on charges of bribery and
accepting illegal gratuities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
