<SLUG> BC-WEB-TELEPHONE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANY SAYS ORDINARY PHONE CAN BE WEB BROWSER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Engineers at SpeechWorks International Inc. say
they've found a way to make any telephone work like an Internet Web
browser. But instead of pointing and clicking with a computer
mouse, users of the company's SpeechSite software could do their
on-line shopping or researching merely using voice commands.
</P>
<P>
   The product will hit the market late this year. Open Market
Inc., a leading maker of Internet retailing software from
Burlington, Mass., has struck a deal to customize SpeechSite for
use with Open Market software. This will make it easy for hundreds
of Internet retailers to add speech capability to their sites.
</P>
<P>
   SpeechSite, which will sell for $50,000 to $150,000, is a
software interface that will enable existing Web sites to recognize
voice commands. ``It's a do-it-yourself speech version of a Web
site,'' said SpeechWorks chief executive Stuart Patterson, whose
company is in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   SpeechSite will let Web surfers visit their favorite sites
without using a computer. For example, a bank could use SpeechSite
to voice-enable its Web site. A customer could telephone the bank
and have access to all of the features on the bank's Web site,
driven by voice commands instead of a keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can say, not only look at our Web site, but also call our
speech site and ask for information,'' Patterson said.
</P>
<P>
   A caller to a SpeechSite service will hear a recorded voice
telling him which options are available. Each option is similar to
a hyperlink on a Web page. But instead of pushing buttons, the
caller will simply say which option he wants. The options are
designed to be simple and easy to remember, so that regular callers
won't have to listen to them over and over again. Indeed, the
software allows the caller to speak at any time, interrupting the
instructions to go directly to the desired service.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson says SpeechSite will also make it easy for companies
to create speech-controlled services, because SpeechSite is linked
to the firm's existing customer databases. There's no need to
duplicate the services, because the Web page and the
speech-controlled service both connect to the same data and merely
present it in different formats.
</P>
<P>
   Open Market's vice president of marketing Jeffrey Bussgang said
customers who shop regularly at particular Web sites will find it
easy to use SpeechSite, because its voice commands are much the
same as the links on the company's Web page. In effect, they'll be
able to ``see'' the Web page in their mind's eye as they're being
talked through the SpeechSite. ``To be able to have that visual
image in your head while you're navigating by voice . . . is
extremely powerful and exciting,'' Bussgang said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a terrific idea,'' said William Meisel, president
of TMA Associates in Tarzana, Calif., a market research firm
specializing in speech-control software products. Meisel said
SpeechWorks and other companies have had only modest success with
speech-controlled telephone products. But he said SpeechWorks may
have found a clever way around this, by designing a system that
works like the World Wide Web, which is now routinely used by about
100 million people in North America.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-99 1820EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
