<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-TOUR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMSTRONG CLINGS TO YELLOW JERSEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAINT-FLOUR, France _ For the fifth day in a row, American Lance
Armstrong held on to the leader's yellow jersery in the Tour de
France.
</P>
<P>
   And for the second year in a row, the topic of drugs was raised
at the world's most prestigious cycling race.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong rode aggressively Friday but didn't risk any
breakaways over the hilly, 126-mile 12th stage from Saint-Galmier
to Saint-Flour in the Massif Centrale region of France. Spaniard
David Etxebarria left the pack going up the final climb, 14 miles
from the finish, and won in 4 hours 53 minutes 50 seconds. He was
26 seconds ahead of Frenchman Francois Simon and 12 minutes ahead
of most of the pack.
</P>
<P>
   So it was a good day for second-time Tour participant
Etxebarria, who had never won a stage and will celebrate his 26th
birthday next Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't a good day for Armstrong. Despite the fact he
extended his comfortable overall lead over Abraham Olano by two
seconds to 7 minutes 44 seconds, Armstrong once again was embroiled
in drug talk.
</P>
<P>
   French racer Christophe Bassons, who has repeatedly spoken out
against drugs and has been writing a daily diary in a French
newspaper, quit the race before Friday's stage, claiming he had
been told by other riders to keep quiet. Bassons had written
Thursday that Armstrong had suggested he drop out.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong told reporters in the morning, ``I told him there is a
right way and wrong way of dealing with this and that he should
just worry about himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year's race became a subplot to a doping controversy in
which the entire Festina team was thrown out of the race and six
other teams withdrew. (Bassons is one of three Festina riders who
tested negative). The drug story persisted over the winter and
reached a crescendo last month when the winner of last year's Tour,
Marco Pantani, was bounced from the Tour of Italy for testing
postive with a high count of red blood cells.
</P>
<P>
   The Tour de France has stepped up its drug testing this year and
has thus far conducted three sets of random tests. Armstrong's US
Postal Service team was among 40 riders tested Friday, all of whom
were negative.
</P>
<P>
   But the leader has been a target of skeptical French press
coverage, where he has been called ``Hallucinating Armstrong'' and
``from another planet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's incredible that they print this. Why do they print
this?'' Armstrong told the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   The US Postal Service team's director of operations, Dan Osipow,
said that despite all the talk of drugs, Armstrong doesn't consider
it a distraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's focused on winning the race, and nothing is going to get
in the way of that,'' Osipow said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong's lead is causing the American press corps here to
swell. It is a headache for them _ in terms of finding hotel rooms
in already booked small villages_ and for Tour organizers. ``We
usually don't give out credentials in the middle of the Tour, but
we do make exceptions,'' said assistant press officer Sophie Del
Rizzo. At the beginning of the three-week Tour July 3, credentials
had been issued to 750 print journalists, only 15 of whom were
American. Del Rizzo said she expects to have a dozen more requests
from American journalists by the end of next week. Such is the draw
of the yellow jersey . . . Friday marked the first time the town of
Saint-Flour (pop. 10,000) was a host city to finish a Tour stage.
The honor, which attracts thousands of tourists and garners
national attention, does not come cheaply or easily. A city must
pay about $42,000 to host the start of a stage, $75,000 for the
finish, and $116,000 for both . . . Addendum to Wednesday's
spectator story: The fan with the camera who ran in front of
Guiseppe Guerini, almost costing the Italian a stage win, went to
the team's hotel that night to apologize and shake Guerini's hand.
The case is closed, according to race director Jean-Marie LeBlanc .
. . Correction: Tyler Hamilton's bruise from last week is under his
left (not right) eye.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
