<SLUG> BC-DE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCO DE VITA EXPLORES NEW TERRITORY IN `IGUAL' 
</HEADLINE>
 VITA-MUSIC-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDY CORDOVA  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - It probably isn't a coincidence that ``Nada Es
Igual,'' the title of Franco De Vita's seventh studio album, means
``nothing is the same.'' The 45-year-old troubadour seems
determined to shake things up this time around.
</P>
<P>
   The Venezuelan singer/songwriter has been a Latin-music mainstay
for more than a decade, with a penchant for piano-based ballads and
socially conscious paeans that straddle the border between pop and
rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nada Es Igual'' is his first offering after a three-year
layoff following the acclaimed, acoustic-flavored ``Fuera de Esta
Mundo.'' And while De Vita's songwriting prowess is as sharp and
vivid as always _ even Ricky Martin has covered some of his tunes _
the musical textures are completely different. Bachata rhythms and
splashy Latin horns replace the jazzy brass section and arena-rock
guitar solos that De Vita usually employs.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is immediately apparent. The album opens with
``Si Tu No Estas,'' a moving confessional in which the protagonist
faces life alone. But while the song begins as a straightforward
ballad, it's soon laced with Spanish guitars. By the time De Vita's
smooth voice hits the chorus, a jaunty horn section kicks in, and
the mood is completely transformed as the song becomes a
understated salsa.
</P>
<P>
   His exploration with different rhythms and textures is exciting,
making this his own little ``Graceland.'' He's never been in a rut,
but he's never seemed this eager to venture to new musical
territories before. It adds up to one of the most intriguing
releases in a career full of fine albums.
</P>
<P>
   ``Te Recordare'' features a distinctive reggae groove, with a
Jamaican-style rap offered by Charlie Rou. Bachata king Juan Luis
Guerra co-produces the lovely ``Te Veo Venir Soledad,'' and the
gentle percussion and lonesome harmonica add an extra layer of
melancholy to the winsome lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   That is one thing about the disc: De Vita's songs continually
circle around the subject of loneliness, which makes you wonder if
everything's OK in the guy's personal life.
</P>
<P>
   But things are brighter lyrically _ somewhat _ on the dazzling
``Traigo Una Pena,'' which throws acoustic guitars, horns, burbling
percussion and all-star salseros Gilberto Santo Rosa, Cheo
Feliciano and Victor Manuelle into a vibrant stew that is
thoroughly contagious. De Vita's free-wheeling vocal is delightful,
as he trades off lines with his guest stars.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the genre-busting going on, it's not a complete
world-beat travelogue. The title song and ``Cuento Con Maria'' both
use Beatles-esque harmonies, with the latter even tossing in some
mind-bending chord progressions that seem very '60s. De Vita is a
boomer-aged rocker at heart, after all.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
Randy Cordova can be reached at (602) 444-8096 or at (602) 253-3734
by fax. Or write him at ``The Arizona Republic,'' P.O. Box 2245
NF-19, Phoenix, AZ 85002; or at randy.cordova(at) pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
