<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUSTERY COURSE CONTINUES TO WINNOW BRITISH OPEN FIELD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARNOUSTIE, Scotland _ Perhaps, as promised, this major
championship crucible will reveal the cream of the golf world by
Saturday night. If so, it will be whipped cream.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing with more bluster than the wind tearing through
Carnoustie Golf Club from the North Sea has been the players'
reaction to this 7,361-yard funhouse with its skyscraper rough,
shoestring fairways, and manhole bunkers. Between complaints, many
of the game's most prominent names have been sent drifting out of
here like dead leaves in an autumn gust. Which describes the
conditions here in County Angus on a tame day.
</P>
<P>
   While we're still waiting for greatness to assert itself, the
leaderboard looks as fluky as the climate, a veritable Who's He? of
golf. France's Jean Van de Velde, whose name sounds as if he should
be making action films, fired the round of the tournament, a
3-under-par 68, and assumed sole control of first place at 1-over
143.
</P>
<P>
   Van de Velde, a 33-year-old journeyman who has won once in eight
years on the European Tour _ the 1993 Roma Masters _ carded four
birdies against a lone bogey in posting matching nines of 34.
Included were two birdies and two pars on the last four holes, a
stretch in which he surrendered four strokes to par during his
first-round 75.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday was a tough finish,'' he said. ``It drains you a lot
to be out there all day, and the holes are playing at least as
difficult downwind as they are into the wind.''
</P>
<P>
   So what in the world is he doing up in the stratosphere?
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard there's always a first time,'' he said. ``I know it's
a major championship, but it's only a golf tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Right behind Van de Velde is the equally well-known Argentine
Angel Cabrera, who shot a 69 for a 144 and actually benefited from
the wind _ it blew in his par putt that seemed to have died on the
lip at the 18th.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very fast putt and the wind was pushing,'' said
Cabrera, 29, who has won 15 tournaments in South America but none
in four years on the European Tour, though he was runner-up in the
Irish Open two weeks ago. ``So I touch it and I thought that it was
in. And it was a little short. I was very surprised. And then the
wind came and threw it in.''
</P>
<P>
   Van de Velde and Cabrera supplanted Thursday's one-day wonder,
Rodney Pampling. The only man to match par in the first round
returned to his proper place in obscurity with an 86_157. He earned
a place in history as well, becoming the only first-round leader to
miss the cut in the 128 renditions of this event.
</P>
<P>
   Lurking behind the vaunted 1-2 punch are some names you might
actually recognize.
</P>
<P>
   Sweden's Jesper Parnevik, twice a runner-up in this event and a
shoo-in to make the European Ryder Cup team that will face the
United States at The Country Club Sept. 26-28, came in at 71_145.
He shared second before bogeying 17, then salvaged par for the last
hole and the round when he chipped from behind the green to within
5 feet and sank the putt.
</P>
<P>
   Like his colleagues, Parnevik considered his round a survival
test, but he meant it literally. He's running a fever, his hand is
bothering him, the heather is wreaking havoc with his allergies,
and he almost walked off the course after five holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt terrible,'' he said. ``I was sneezing constantly. I
just had to time putts and shots between my sneezes. I thought I
was going to shoot 90 or something. To shoot 71 in the end is
beyond my dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he can catch pneumonia overnight and run away with the
title.
</P>
<P>
   The group at 146 includes Greg Norman (70) and Tiger Woods (72),
both poised to make a weekend run. Patrik Sjoland of Sweden (74)
joins them at 4 over, and 1997 British king Justin Leonard (74) is
among those another stroke back.
</P>
<P>
   Norman's round typified the competitors' lament about this
course. After a run of three straight birdies from the 12th through
the 14th, he came to 17 alone at the top at 1 over. But he
proceeded to crisscross the notorious Burma Burn, even fanning on
his second shot, and took a triple-bogey 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``My tee shot was basically three paces off the fairway, and I
never moved the ball with my second shot,'' said the two-time
British champion. ``I don't think hitting a tee shot off the
fairway by 9 feet deserves something like that. In my estimation, I
don't think that's the way the game of golf should be played.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Woods, who bogeyed two of the last three holes, may
be as much masochist as maestro.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always enjoyed playing in terrible conditions, rain,
wind,'' he said. ``You have to be more creative. You have to use
your repertoire of shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Those sentiments weren't shared by a host of luminaries whose
repertoires have been canceled or rendered irrelevant for the
weekend. The likes of world No. 2 David Duval (75) and two-time US
Open champion Lee Janzen (74) are hanging around only because the
cut for the top 70 and ties fell at an astronomical 12-over 154.
Gone are Phil Mickelson (76_155), Nick Faldo (79_157), Masters
champion Jose Maria Olazabal (79_157), and Billy Mayfair (80_161),
among others.
</P>
<P>
   At least they have nothing to complain about. They've escaped.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
