<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-SALINAS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JUDGE REDUCES MURDER SENTENCE FOR BROTHER OF FORMER MEXICAN
PRESIDENT
 &HT;    554. Moving on (i) international wires.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY An appeals court judge in Mexico on Friday nearly
cut in half the 50-year homicide sentence given to Raul Salinas,
the brother of former Mexican president Carlos Salinas.
</P>
<P>
   The reduction in sentence was the latest twist in the legacy of
Carlos Salinas, who lives in self-exile in Ireland and is widely
blamed by Mexicans for leading the country into a devastating
economic crisis and spreading corruption during his 1988 to 1994
presidential term.
</P>
<P>
   Raul Salinas who used to direct a national supplemental food
agency was sentenced in January to a 50-year term for arranging the
1994 killing of Jose Francisco Ruiz Massieu, one of his political
rivals within Mexico's Revolutionary Institutional Party, or PRI.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Judge Tomas Hernandez Franco reduced Salinas' sentence
to 27 years and six months. No reasons for the reduction were
immediately announced, but Salinas' lawyers had argued that
evidence against their client was weak because some witnesses were
paid and evidence fabricated an argument some legal experts here
said was not far-fetched.
</P>
<P>
   Also, some legal experts say the 50-year sentence given to
Salinas exceeded the norm in similar cases. Salinas is appealing
his conviction before Mexico's Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's decision was announced just one day after another
Salinas court case was successfully appealed.
</P>
<P>
   The imprisoned Raul Salinas is currently under investigation for
taking millions of dollars in bribes from drug lords. The case is
bolstered by a Swiss investigation into whether $114 million
deposited in Swiss bank accounts by Raul Salinas came from bribes.
</P>
<P>
   But on Thursday Switzerland's highest court ruled in favor of an
appeal by Salinas' lawyers and found that Swiss prosecutors acted
beyond their reach when they confiscated Salinas' accounts last
year. The court said only local Swiss governments could freeze such
assets.
</P>
<P>
   The money, which Salinas argues is an investment fund, will
remain frozen pending further investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinary Mexicans' wrath is reserved more for Salinas' alleged
misuse of public funds he controlled and allegations that he took
millions of dollars in bribes from drug lords he aided.
</P>
<P>
   But his murder conviction pleased many here because the Salinas
family is so reviled and because of the perception that powerful
Mexicans' crimes usually go unpunished.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Salinas, who once was hailed by the international elite
as a democratic reformer, is frequently mocked in Mexico in
cartoons, and dolls exaggerate his bald pate and have dollars
clutched in their hands.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Carlos Salinas caused a stir in Mexico when he made his
first visit since he left in the country in 1995. He told reporters
at a news conference that one of his motives was to check on his
brother's welfare.
</P>
<P>
   The visit may have also yielded positive results for Raul
Salinas.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Salinas submitted a petition requesting that his brother
be transferred to a lower-security prison. The request was granted
after it was reviewed by a chain of command that led up to the
administration of current president Ernesto Zedillo, according to
Mexican news reports.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
