<HEADLINE>
MITCHELL ASKED TO TRY TO HELP RESTART IRISH PEACE PRCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The British and Irish governments have asked former US
senator George J. Mitchell of Maine, who chaired negotiations that
brought about the now-stalled political settlement in Northern
Ireland, to meet informally with the various parties there to coax
them to find a new compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell is scheduled to meet Tuesday at 10 Downing St. with
British Prime Minister Tony Blair and his Irish counterpart, Bertie
Ahern, as the two governments assess how to breathe life back into
the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, that process was dealt its most serious blow since
the April 1998 signing of the Good Friday Agreement, presided over
by Mitchell. The Northern Ireland Assembly, which was supposed to
be the institution on which a new, more equitable society was
built, was suspended indefinitely when Protestant unionists refused
to form a power-sharing government with Catholic nationalists.
</P>
<P>
   The largest unionist party, the Ulster Unionists, boycotted the
session, saying it will not sit in a government with Sinn Fein, the
Irish Republican Army's political wing, until the IRA begins
disarming.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell's patience is widely credited with winning respect from
the various parties in Northern Ireland, but it was his
decisiveness in setting a deadline that brought about the Good
Friday Agreement, which created the political institutions aimed at
ending the conflict that over 30 years has killed more than 3,500
people.
</P>
<P>
   Blair and Ahern have been less successful using deadlines in
trying to get the parties in Northern Ireland to compromise and
create a power-sharing government before the IRA begins to disarm.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, 65, who was in London Thursday to receive an award
from Queen Elizabeth, said he did not want to comment ahead of
Tuesday's meeting. But he issued a statement that said: ``The prime
ministers of the United Kingdom and of Ireland have invited me to
attend a meeting with them on Tuesday in London. I look forward to
discussing with them the current situation in Northern Ireland. If
the prime ministers conclude that I can usefully play a role at
this time, I will do all I can to be helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   The governments have decided that Mitchell might appeal directly
to the party leaders, especially David Trimble, the Ulster Unionist
leader.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking on the condition he not be identified, a spokesman for
Blair said Mitchell will be used ``more as an interlocutor, rather
than heading something up,'' such as a commission.
</P>
<P>
   Having given four years as an unpaid volunteer to the peace
process, Mitchell bade Belfast farewell in April 1998, saying he
needed to devote time to his Washington law practice to earn money
for his wife and his son, now 1 year old.
</P>
<P>
   Both London and Dublin are aware that Mitchell, given his
responsibilities, is not available for the full-time service he
previously gave.
</P>
<P>
   Blair spoke Friday by telephone with President Clinton for about
20 minutes, updating the president on the situation and about the
plans to use Mitchell as a troubleshooter, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   While each meeting between the parties and Blair and Ahern has
been high-profile, the two governments envision Mitchell being used
in a more low-key manner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mitchell can do things behind the scenes, talking to people,''
said the Downing Street spokesman. ``We expect the temperatures to
dip a bit. We got to the stage where every time one of the prime
ministers engages with a party, it was called an Ulster summit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-99 1833EDT &QL; 
