<HEADER>
A3115 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT &LR;      07-16 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
(jt)
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Saturday, July 17. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Henry Warnken; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
lyhoog(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-F-22 (Washington) _ The House will vote next week to
cut off funds to produce the $70 billion Air Force F-22, an act
unprecedented in modern times, House leaders said Friday. By Tim
Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-TARIFFS (Washington) _ The House is to vote and likely
pass a bill to eliminate duties on apparel and textiles from
Africa, if the countries commit to economic reform and improve
human rights. The measure, which the Senate has yet to take up, has
divided the black caucus, some of whose members fear the move will
hurt business here. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-HEALTH (Washington) _ Despite all the talk about
protecting people in health maintenance organizations, most people
in HMOs would derive no tangible benefit from many of the
consumer-protection standards approved by the Senate this week as
part of a comprehensive bill to define patients' rights, lawyers
and health policy experts said. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   NY-HEAT (New York) _ With summer trundling its twin siege
engines of heat and humidity back to the metropolitan region for a
prolonged weekend assault, New Yorkers braced for near record
temperatures and hoped to avoid another severe blackout. The city
put its crisis management services on prolonged alert, opening its
Emergency Operation Center, as its combined bunker for police, fire
and medical crisis teams is known, as well as special cooling
centers for anyone who might be afflicted by the heat. By Neil
MacFarquhar.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-VERDICT _ Microsoft Corp. won a convincing courtroom
victory Friday when a jury in Bridgeport, Conn., found that the
company had not violated federal antitrust laws in its dealings
with a small local software maker. The private suit in Connecticut
has no direct impact on the government's antitrust case against
Microsoft. But antitrust experts said the verdict would certainly
hearten the Microsoft legal team in Washington. By Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-WILDWEST (Aksu, China) _ South of this one-time camel stop
on the Silk Road, bulldozers and men with spades flounder in the
wickedly fine sand, leveling dunes into fields in China's own
version of the taming of the West. Soon, a stretch of the
Taklamakan Desert will be transformed into an oasis of cotton and
rice. And another enclave of ethnic Chinese will spring up in the
mainly Muslim frontier region of Xinjiang. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   PBS-DONOR-LISTS (Washington) _ The Corporation for Public
Broadcasting said Friday it was trying to determine how many public
television stations had swapped donor lists with the Democratic
National Committee after reports that stations in Washington, New
York and Boston had done so for years. By Katherine Q. Seeyle.
</P>
<P>
   WVA-AGED (Dunbar, W.Va.) _ West Virginia has surpassed Florida
as the state with the oldest per capita residents in the union, and
no one knows this better than Ken Hechler, the 84-year-old elected
secretary of state who has decided he can be the wave of the
future: he's running for his old House seat that he retired from in
the '70s. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   Refers:
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-U.S. (Washington) _ The Israeli prime minister meets with
the secretaries of state and defense. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-TAX (Washington) _ The Senate releases its tax bill;
the Democrats reveal their plans; and the White House talks about
the Republican plan. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-U.S. (Bogota) _ Alarmed by recent advances by
guerrillas here who are also involved in drug trafficking, the
Clinton administration's top anti-drug official is asking that the
United States make nearly $1 billion in emergency assistance
available to Colombia to strengthen its counter-drugs efforts. By
Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
