<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUFFY17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Huffy reports profits
 &HT;    By Lynn Hulsey
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Huffy Corp. reversed losses from last year and
reported a profit for the quarter ended June 30, but still laid off
140 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Huffy said it earned nearly $5.3 million, or 50 cents a share,
compared with a loss of $26,000 during the second quarter of 1998.
Sales for the quarter dropped 5 percent to $172 million.
</P>
<P>
   The company fell short of analysts' expectations. Analysts
surveyed by First Call Corp. had a consensus estimate of 55 cents
per share.
</P>
<P>
   An increasingly competitive bicycle marketplace has Huffy
consolidating suppliers, streamlining manufacturing, reducing
administrative expenses and upgrading its distribution network to
cut costs and improve service.
</P>
<P>
   During the second quarter, 120 jobs were eliminated at the
Farmington, Mo., plant, and 20 salaried employees lost their job in
Miamisburg, Springboro, Farmington and South Haven, Miss., said
Thomas Frederick, vice president of finance and chief financial
officer.
</P>
<P>
   Huffy's service segment saw net sales grow to a record $67
million, a 19.4 percent increase over the same period a year ago.
The company's sporting goods segment, which includes bicycles and
basketball systems, reported a 16.5 percent decline in sales to
$105.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Don R. Graber, chairman, president and chief executive, said
that while the company service segment enjoyed strong sales and
earnings growth, the bicycle unit faced intense competition from
Asian imports.
</P>
<P>
   ``This combined with the overall softness of the sporting goods
market made for a challenging quarter in our Sporting Goods
segment,'' Graber said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
