<HEADLINE>
TENNIS' PROMOTIONAL EFFORTS PAYING OFF 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The Davis Cup matches at the Longwood Cricket Club,
just outside of Boston, this weekend sold out in 52 minutes. Not
bad, considering that for most of the 1990s fans, observers and
corporate sponsors have been searching for tennis's vital signs.
</P>
<P>
   A headline in Sports Illustrated a few years ago asked
plaintively, ``Is Tennis Dying?'' While it appears the patient has
survived, the prognosis is not yet for a full recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Tennis organizations and promoters have been trying a variety of
marketing techniques _ including the old standby, sex appeal _ and
changes in the structure of the game to entice fans, young players
and the all-important corporate sponsors in an attempt to secure
the sport's future.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one time tennis was really big, the driving sport in this
industry in the late 70s and perhaps early 80s,'' said Dave
Fogelson, the director for public relations at Reebok International
Ltd., in Stoughton, Mass. ``I'm not sure that will ever happen
again, but there are some encouraging signs, especially among the
women. We're certainly thrilled, for example, with our relationship
with Venus Williams.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennis, as both sport and business, is a much limper image than
the vital enterprise that loomed on the sport scene 20 years ago.
Then, tennis rivaled golf as ``the fifth major sport,'' and much of
the country enjoyed watching players like Evert and Connors, while
even those who did not much care for the game wondered if Chrissy
and Jimmy were still in love.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a story line then that the game lacks today,'' said
Bob Williams, president of Burns Sports Celebrity Service, a
Chicago company that links advertisers with athletes for
endorsements. ``If you looked at golf in the late 70s and early 80s
it was struggling sponsor-wise, ratings-wise, just not pulling it
all together, and tennis had the marquee names of Connors and
(John) McEnroe and (Bjorn) Borg, and it was extremely popular. And
now, you look the 1990s have been a role reversal.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of requests and contracts coming through this office,
Golf is way up and tennis is way down,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, participation levels have suffered. The Sporting
Goods Manufacturers' Assocation says US participation rates
declined by 17 percent for the 10 years beginning in 1987 _ and by
8 percent from 1996 to 1997 alone. Other analysts say the decline
has been much more precipitous, as much as 40 percent in the
current decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst part of all of this is we are all noticing lots of
empty tennis courts in the neighborhoods as we move around the
country,'' said an executive in one of the major sports marketing
firms. ``We can all remember a time in the early '80s when you just
couldn't reserve court time, and they could not build them fast
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials charged with organizing and promoting tennis have
launched a number of strategies recently, trying to bring the game
back. One initiative began at the grass-roots level, on the empty
courts.
</P>
<P>
   The US Tennis Association joined forces with a number of other
groups in September 1997 to launch USA Tennis Plan for Growth, a
five-year, $50 million, industry-wide initiative to get players _
especially young beginners _ back on the courts. This week in
Boston, marketing officials from the USTA, the ATP Tour for the men
and the WTA Tour for women pressed the results of their survey on
participation into the hands of reporters covering the Davis Cup.
</P>
<P>
   According to their survey, the number of frequent tennis players
_ defined as playing more than 20 times a year _ increased by 10.2
percent to 5.4 million from 1996 to 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, according to the USTA, tennis ball sales were up 11
percent and racket sales up 8.5 percent in the first quarter of
1999, good news for the $1 billion international market in tennis
equipment, which had been in decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entire US tennis industry has joined forces to make growth
in the sport possible,'' said USTA President Judy Levering.
</P>
<P>
   The women's tour also is trying to capitalize on it stable of
young, competitive stars _ Martina Hingis, Venus Williams, Serena
Williams, Lindsey Davenport and Anna Kournakova. The WTA Tour has
ginned up a marketing program unlike anything in the history of the
sport.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis has appeared on the cover of GQ in a tight, shoulderless
dress with the headline, ``The Champ is a Vamp.'' The Williams
sisters, enveloped in American flags, posed for Vogue.
</P>
<P>
   Serena designs her outfits for Reebok that turn heads on the
circuit. And the appeal of Kournakova has assumed Hollywood-starlet
proportions. The young Russian may have difficulty cracking the
tour's top 10 ranking, but People magazine has named her one of the
50 most-beautiful people in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't help it if I'm beautiful,'' the pouty Kournakova said,
disarming critics.
</P>
<P>
   The WTA Tour has hired a marketing director, Susan Marenoff, for
the first time, and its television rights were acquired last year
by Arnon Milchan's Regency Enterprises, the producer of the movie
L.A. Confidential. Milchan publicly touts a strategy of merging
sports and entertainment by arranging for screen tests for the
sisters Williams, and inviting some of the women players to the
Cannes Film Festival and Hollywood parties.
</P>
<P>
   Although it all has set off a debate, with some commentators and
former stars like Martina Navratilova urging a focus on skill, the
WTA Tour has turned the corner much faster than the men. An
attendance record of about 3.7 million was set in 1998, and WTA
officials say they are running ahead of that by about 8 percent
this year. Television numbers are up, too.
</P>
<P>
   But even with that success, corporate support remains a tough
pull. When tennis was strong, the name Virginia Slims was almost
more readily associated with tennis than tobacco. But since the
Canadian software manufacturer Corel Corp. dropped its sponsorship
of the tour in 1997, other companies have hesitated to take up the
cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corporate America is concerned about the staying power of the
young stars,'' said the marketing executive. ``The quick fades,
like Tracy Austin and Jennifer Capriati, are legendary and no one
wants to associate their brand with a huge, public failure.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the men's tournament seems to have trouble just
volleying.
</P>
<P>
   Andre Agassi provided a glimmer of hope that an old rivalry
would be rekindled earlier this year, winning the French Open and
meeting Sampras in the Gentlemen's Final at Wimbledon. But
Sampras's destruction of Agassi at center court only reinforced the
fact that the men's tour has but one star _ and Sampras is famously
reticent, and incapable, of publicizing the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is no knock on Pete Sampras, who may be the greatest of
all-time,'' Williams said, ``but he would not make anyone's list of
charismatic athletes, and he's said before that endorsements are
not important to him.''
</P>
<P>
   The ATP Tour has been forced to sign a costly marketing contract
and to restructure the competitive rules of the tour.
</P>
<P>
   ATP inked 10-year, $1.2 billion marketing agreement with ISL,
the Swiss-based marketing firm that is lauded for its work on the
Olympics and last year represented the Men's World Cup soccer
tournament. The contract is perceived as a frank admission that the
sport is malingering. After all, it's marketing strategy once
consisted of simply having Connors and Borg, or Borg and McEnroe on
the court.
</P>
<P>
   And in 2000, the men's tour will drastically alter the rules
that govern its rankings, dumping the current point system that
even some dedicated fans find imponderable. Instead, players will
compete in the four Grand Slam events, nine other tournaments _
designated as the Super 9 _ and five tournaments of their choice to
determine the rankings.
</P>
<P>
   The Super 9 events will be mandatory, helping the men's tour
overcome the problem of players choosing their own schedules, with
the frequent result that person best positioned to beat Sampras
opts out of some tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   While ATP officials tout the new competitive scheme and the
marketing initiative as sufficient to produce a renaissance, others
wonder to what extent the situation is salvaegable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The group of young women, including Venus, has been the
perfect antedote to some of the staleness in the industry,''
Reebok's Fogelson said. ``And it would certainly be nice to see
someone come along, in the mold of a McEnroe or maybe a Connors,
who would lend some passion to the men's side, again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, that said, I think that even if that did happen, you
probably would not see tennis return to the heights of the time
when it was a really driving business,'' he said. ``Most people do
not think that would happen.''
</P>
