<SLUG> BC-DEMS-ANDREWS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DEMOCRATS TO LAUNCH HIGH-TECH MESSAGE
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As he stood in a Des Moines hotel parking lot last
month, Joe Andrew flipped open his sleek silver laptop, fired up a
cellular modem, and downloaded a video file from the Internet site
of George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the hotel, the Texas governor was telling supporters that
he favors federal subsidies for ethanol, a grain-based additive to
gasoline and a political priority for Iowa farmers.
</P>
<P>
   His advisers circulated among national reporters, seeking to
assure them that Bush's pro-ethanol stance could be safely ignored
as ``old news.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so, insisted Andrew, chairman of the Democratic National
Committee. He showed the reporters the material from Bush's Web
site, evidence that the front-running Republican presidential
candidate had never before broached the ethanol issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly,'' Andrew said Friday, ``the reporters were more taken
with my ability to access all that stuff in a parking lot minutes
after he spoke than with the fact that the Bush people had just
tried to take them for a ride.''
</P>
<P>
   But the cherubic-faced Andrew, who took over the chairmanship
last March, has a wider agenda than being a one-man response team.
If Andrew has his way, the Democrats will enter the 2000 campaign
armed with political cybertools never employed on such a scale in a
national campaign.
</P>
<P>
   As the youngest state party chair ever to serve in Indiana,
Andrew blended voter registration files with detailed data about
age, race, income, religion and the like to create a detailed
picture of the state's voting population.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 and again in 1998, he supplied the state's Democratic
county chairman with a steady stream of CD-ROM disks. The local
leaders used the disks to organize targeted mailings and
door-to-door canvassing, substantially increasing Democratic
turnout from prior years.
</P>
<P>
   That helped the party elect more new officeholders last year in
Indiana than in any year since Franklin Roosevelt's landslide
victory in 1932.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at this,'' Andrew said, striking a some keys on his
desktop computer to bring up a voter database that covers all 92
counties in his native state.
</P>
<P>
   Typing in the name ``John Smith'' as a handy example, Andrew
soon determined that this particular Smith and his wife are both
swing voters who have moved between the Republican and Democratic
camps in successive primaries. Although that makes them unlikely
party volunteers, they are good prospects to receive a series of
highly customized political messages.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Andrew intends to employ the same blend of technology and
targeting on a national scale.
</P>
<P>
   ``The technology really needs no translation from what we have
done in Indiana,'' Andrew said. ``As you know, the presidential
race is not a national race. It is 50 state races. So we'll try to
use that type of technology across the country.''
</P>
<P>
   In practice, a few dozen counties will get most of the attention
from what the Democrats have dubbed the ``Internet Center
Project.'' That name translates into a targeted blizzard of
personalized letters, e-mail, telephone calls, and visits from
like-minded neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's what you're doing,'' Andrew explained in his modest
office, which overlooks the main Amtrak rail line between
Washington and points south. ``You're simply using the Internet to
rebuild a commonality of interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew holds that with the breakdown of urban neighborhoods,
civil society, and the ethnic-based ward system, the old politics
of geography has been supplemented by a new politics of shared
interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``All politics is local, but local has been redefined,'' Andrew
recently told The New Republic magazine. ``Now people will
associate with fellow gardeners or car enthusiasts wherever they
are, often through the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And while the use of the Internet tends to skew toward white,
high-income persons,'' he adds, ``that's rapidly changing.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew did not disclose how much the Democrats plan to spend on
the their project. But it's clear that Andrew has already reached
out to untapped pool of contributors to help fund the high-tech
effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a whole new community of people that are willing to
invest in technology because they have made their money in
technology,'' Andrew said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've created something like between 200,000 to 300,000 new
millionaires in the technology community in the last six and a half
years. When you go to people who have made money in this area and
you ask them to make a contribution to the Democratic National
Committee, what they like to see and hear is that their dollars are
going to these kind of projects,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew took over a party organization with financial troubles,
and ``the DNC far exceeded everybody expectations of what we'd be
able to do here,'' he said. ``You have a rookie from the minor
leagues like me coming up _ how the heck, people asked, can he
possibly get the debt paid off?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we've clearly exceeded those expectations. One of the
reasons for that is that we have a significantly higher number of
contributors from the technology area. And at least in part that's
because that's my base. I am technology person. I speak the
language that resonates in that community.''
</P>
<P>
   At 39, Andrew remains a practicing intellectual property lawyer
as well as a favorably reviewed author of a post-Cold War thriller
novel. He is a partner in the Anson Group, an Indianapolis-based
biotechnology firm that in turn owns several Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
