A3124 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINDSPRING17-COX     07-16 0379
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINDSPRING17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MindSpring shares rise again on Dell rumor
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Shares of MindSpring Enterprises were up slightly
Friday, again fueled by rumors of a possible deal with Dell
Computer.
</P>
<P>
   MindSpring closed at $48.75, up $1.75. The stock went as high as
$49.18 3/4 earlier in the day, fueled by a comment by Dell Computer
Chief Executive Michael Dell at the computer maker's annual
shareholders meeting in Austin, Texas, on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Answering a question about a potential linkage with MindSpring,
Dell said the companywill ``aggressively enter the market for
Internet access'' in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   However, he did not say he was in the market to acquire an
Internet service provider.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure buying is the way to go,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dell already offers its own branded Internet service in Europe.
Dell pays a wholesale price for access through a deal with
Excite.com.
</P>
<P>
   Vice Chairman Kevin Rollins said Dell.net in the United States
would ``follow the European model.''
</P>
<P>
   The company says it will roll out Internet access whether or not
it acquires a U.S. service provider. An announcement on Dell's
plans could come as soon as next week.
</P>
<P>
   MindSpring refused to comment on any speculation regarding any
possible ``business combinations'' with Dell or anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   MindSpring has been fending off rumors about possible mergers,
acquisitions and other ``business combinations'' since it released
a cryptic announcement June 24 saying it was talking with
unspecified companies about unspecified business deals.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors of merger deals are fueled by the fact that both computer
makers and Internet service providers such as MindSpring are facing
stiff competition within their respective industries.
</P>
<P>
   Companies such as Free-PC.com, Micron Electronics, IBM and
others are offerering free or deeply discounted PCs to users who
sign up for Internet services such as CompuServe or Prodigy
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile several new start-up companies such as 1stUp.com,
NetGenie and NetZero are offering free Internet access to customers
who agree to view advertisements while they're online.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
