<SLUG> BC-MA-JOBS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNEMPLOYMENT IN BAY STATE AT 3 PERCENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HEATHER KAMINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The unemployment rates in Massachusetts dropped to 3.0
percent in June and the number of residents working hit another
high as the state's economy continued its steady expansion..
</P>
<P>
   The national unemployment rate edged up to 4.8 during the same
period, marking 52 consecutive months that the Massachusetts
unemployment rate has fallen below the national average.
</P>
<P>
   The unemployment rate has hovered around 3 percent for the last
six months, reaching a low of 2.8 percent in March and a peak at
3.2 in May.
</P>
<P>
   If current trends hold for the second half of the year, the
annual unemployment figures would be the lowest recorded since the
state began keeping figures in 1970. In 1987, the annual average
unemployment rate came in at 3.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a difference between booms and bust and a real steady
prosperity,'' said Andre Mayer, senior vice president for
Associated Industries of Massachusetts. ``Having a good labor
market for a long time makes a real difference in bringing people
into (the state), getting the youth unemployment rate down, and
pushing the economic benefits in the core area of Boston out to the
greater metropolitan area.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayer said the last time Massachusetts had a year as good as
this was in early 1988, until the recession hit.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, things look much more stable, said Fred Breimyer,
chief economist for the State Street Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no immediate clouds on the horizon,'' Breimyer said.
``In fact, some of the news has improved as the effects of the
Asian crisis have diminished.''
</P>
<P>
   Job levels in Massachusetts hit an all-time high last month at
3,221,000, as 3,300 new jobs were created. The state has posted
record high employment levels in each of the last five months.
</P>
<P>
   ``The growth has been very strong in all sectors except in
manufacturing,'' said Elliot Winer, an economic analyst with the
state Division of Employment and Training.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturing jobs fell by 700 in June, and are off 3.4 percent
since June 1998. The manufacturing sector, which deals mostly with
exports, was badly hurt by problems in the Asian economy.
</P>
<P>
   The retail sector posted the largest gain in June, adding 1,700
jobs, with a huge gain in specialty retail stores. In the past
year, retail has added 14,500 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Job growth in the service sector slowed a bit, but the number of
jobs increased by 2.4 percent in the past year. Winer said these
numbers have remained strong, though, because these jobs are
usually higher paying.
</P>
<P>
   Construction jobs rebounded a bit in June, adding 700 new
positions, but Mayer said this number is much lower than it was 10
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question that we are seeing an evolution into a
more service-oriented economy,'' Mayer said. ``You see fewer good
jobs for non-college-educated people. This economy does place a
premium on a certain level of education.''
</P>
<P>
   The only negative in the Massachusetts economy, analysts said,
is the shortage of labor.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there were more people to work, there would be more jobs,''
Mayer said. ``Three percent (unemployment) for Massachusetts is
like a full-employment economy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-99 1852EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
