u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBITUARY-BORDEN-BOS &LR;      07-16 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-BORDEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICHARD BORDEN, 89; WILDLIFE PHOTOGRAPHER, WAS AFFILIATED WITH
DISNEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Richard Borden, a wildlife photographer who contributed footage
to many motion pictures and TV shows, died Monday at his home in
Santa Barbara, Calif. He was 89.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Borden had a long affiliation with the Disney Studios. He
contributed segments to many of the studio's films including ``The
Vanishing Prairie'' and ``The Living Desert.'' He also contributed
to the studio's TV shows and, in 1964, was featured in a segment of
``The Wonderful World of Disney'' in which he was referred to as
``probably the world's foremost bird photographer.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Borden's nature work led to commissions to produce films for
several baseball teams. As he explained in 1958, ``In 1951, I was
invited to Fenway Park to appear on television between the halves
of a Red Sox doubleheader. I showed some duck film taken with the
camera gun, which I invented. With the tool of my trade in hand, I
photographed some of the ensuing game with quite exciting results.
After following birds in flight, following a baseball was much more
predictable.''
</P>
<P>
   The appearance led to films on the Red Sox, the Kansas City
Athletics and the Detroit Tigers. He also shot several official
World Series films.
</P>
<P>
   He was the president of the Massachusetts Audubon Society during
the 1960s. For more than 40 years, he lived on an estate in
Concord, Mass. and maintained his 50 acres of ponds, rolling
meadows and woods as a wildlife preserve that is still open to the
public.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Borden was born in Fall River, Mass. He graduated from
Harvard College in 1933 and served in the Navy during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, instead of joining his family's textile business,
he joined the staff of the National Audubon Society in New York for
a year, before becoming executive director of the National Wildlife
Federation in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1949, I decided to expand my avocational motion picture
actvities into a full-time business,'' he wrote in the 25th
anniversary report of his class at Harvard. ``The advent of
television opened new areas for wildlife photography and with more
enthusiasm than technical knowledge, I embarked on the project of
producing 30 15-minute television shows under the series title
`Wonders of the Wild. '
</P>
<P>
   ``Somewhat to my suprise,'' he wrote, ``the series sold well
enough to keep the infant company, Borden Productions, Inc., going
until I could expand to other fields.''
</P>
<P>
   He was a charming man, who ``always had a twinkle in his eye,''
his daughter, Beatrice Knox-Johnston, said Friday. His contribution
to his Harvard anniversary report may explain why. ``I am working
at the thing I have always wanted to,'' he wrote, ``and my business
allows me to travel to Europe, both for work and pleasure, to shoot
grouse in Scotland, ducks in Manitoba and our grouse and woodcock
in Vermont in the fall. ''
</P>
<P>
   Besides his daughter Beatrice of Nantucket, Mass., he leaves his
wife, Beatrice (Brown); three other daughters, Jane Chermayeff of
Santa Fe, Betsy Carlson of Santa Barbara, and Patricia DuPont of
Rowayton, Conn; four sons, Spencer of Concord, William Sweney of
Santa Barbara, Michael Sweney of Los Angeles, and John Sweney of
Houston; 15 grandchildren; and eight great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-99 1855EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990716.0227 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3130 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WATER-DISEASE17-COX     07-16 0524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WATER-DISEASE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Recreational lake linked to deaths closes indefinitely
 &HT;    By Jenna Hunt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. _ An area recreational facility closed its lake
Thursday because of a microscopic organism linked to the deaths of
two swimmers.
</P>
<P>
   Owners of Twin Lakes in Beaufort County shut down the swimming
lake Thursday to research the presence of naegleria fowleri, an
amoeba that causes a rare but deadly form of meningitis.
</P>
<P>
   A Pitt County teen became infected with the disease and died
after swimming there last July, health officials said. A 3-year-old
girl from Pitt County contracted the disease and later died after a
swim at the lake in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to do the responsible thing,'' said Twin Lakes
spokesman Herman Gaskins. ``It's closed indefinitely. The owners
made the decision _ they said they were not going to take a
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   The disease, called primary amebic meningoencephalitis, killed
five people in the United States in 1998: two cases in Texas, one
in Oklahoma, one in Florida and one here on July 24.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 100 cases have been reported in the United States
since the disease was discovered 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Meningitis is a potentially fatal inflammation of the membranes
covering the brain and spinal cord. Several types exist, some of
which are extremely contagious and deadly.
</P>
<P>
   The amoebic form of the disease is not contagious, but it is
almost always fatal, said Dr. John Morrow, Pitt County health
director.
</P>
<P>
   The waterborne amoeba forms in any body of freshwater where the
temperatures climb higher than 80 degrees _ especially in still or
slow-moving lakes, ponds and streams.
</P>
<P>
   The amoeba infects people when water is forced deep into the
nasal cavity, usually through diving, jumping or falling into
freshwater. It enters the brain through the nasal tissues.
</P>
<P>
   Beaufort and Pitt county health departments are conducting
public awareness campaigns to inform residents of the risks of
infection from the rare disease. But neither county currently
monitors the quality of water in lakes and ponds, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The Regional Division of Water Quality in Washington, N.C.,
monitors river basins in 20 counties in eastern North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do the river basins and it doesn't include smaller lakes or
ponds,'' said Kim Cole, a division environmental technician. ``I
don't know how we determine which waters are monitored.''
</P>
<P>
   Cole said the agency's current methods would not detect the
presence of the microscopic amoeba.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials warn residents to hold their noses while under
water or use nose clips while swimming in any freshwater swimming
areas.
</P>
<P>
   Twin Lakes owners, Jesse and Ottis Crisp, are going to study the
lake with county and state public health officials to decide which
actions to take to ensure the health and safety of swimmers,
Gaskins said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twin Lakes is an unusual place. They know all their guests on
a first name basis _ the safety of our guests is the most important
thing,'' Gaskins said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
