<SLUG> BC-FORD-CANADA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANADIAN DEALERS SUE FORD OVER OUTLET CONVERSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ko) 
 By TIMOTHY PRITCHARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Canada's Ford dealers are suing Ford Motor Co. of
Canada for breach of contract over its plan to convert more than
100 Lincoln-Mercury outlets to the Ford name, creating 25 percent
more Ford dealers across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, filed Thursday in Ontario Superior Court by the
Canadian Ford Dealers Association on behalf of its members, does
not seek financial damages but demands that the company honor its
franchise agreements.
</P>
<P>
   Some dealers said this was only one reason they were unhappy
with Ford's Canadian subsidiary. They are angry about steps they
say Ford Canada has taken to gain more control over their
businesses, including taking minority equity stakes when
dealerships are sold.
</P>
<P>
   In their suit, the dealers contend that when Ford's blue oval
sign goes up over Canada's Lincoln-Mercury outlets in October,
dozens of existing dealers will have new competition within the
10-mile radius of exclusivity specified in their sales agreements.
</P>
<P>
   One plaintiff, Del Bedard, president of Thorncrest Sherway Ford
in Toronto, said he would have four new Ford dealers within his
franchise area, one about a mile away. ``The issue in Toronto is
that they are doubling the number of Ford dealers, to 32,'' Bedard
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Canada says the move is part of its effort to simplify the
dealer system and eliminate customer confusion over Ford products,
which include Lincolns and Mercurys. The company argues that what
the dealers are calling new competition has been in place for
years. Lincoln-Mercury dealers sell 86 percent of the Ford line,
said John Arnone, a spokesman for Ford Canada. To deal with
confusion among consumers, he said, ``we are just formalizing an
existing situation.''
</P>
<P>
   After World War II, Ford Canada established three types of
dealer chains, with some product overlap, to build market share.
Mercury dealers once sold a car called a Meteor, which was a Ford
with different chrome trim.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the company's dealers now operate under the Ford-Mercury
banner, but some are pure Ford and some are Lincoln-Mercury.
Lincoln-Mercury dealers, however, sell Ford minivans, sport utility
vehicles and trucks.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit came after Ford's decision to eliminate the Mercury
brand name as of Oct. 1, 1999, and to allow existing Mercury
dealers to sell all Ford products.
</P>
<P>
   While Ford dealers have taken the unusual step of filing a suit,
many Canadian dealers of other brands are just as unhappy with
their manufacturers. Canada has about 3,500 dealers, giving it
twice the dealer-to-sales ratio as in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Sonja Falkenberg, director of the Ford dealers association, said
one result of putting all dealers under the Ford banner would be
that more would fail.
</P>
<P>
   A Ford of Canada spokesman, Joe Arnone, said the company was
merely responding to customer demands that Ford represent itself
under one banner in the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our customers tell us today there is way too much confusion
about where to buy a Ford. This is a simple way to lift this veil
of confusion,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-99 1856EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
