u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-U.S.-CHINA-NYT &LR;      07-16 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.S.-CHINA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALKS ON CHINESE EMBASSY BOMBING REACH STALEMATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ko) 
 By SETH FAISON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Chinese and U.S. officials wound up two days of
negotiations on Friday, unable to agree on compensation for the
NATO bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade in May.
</P>
<P>
   Another round of talks was scheduled for later this month.
</P>
<P>
   The stalemate was a disappointment to officials who had hoped an
agreement would clear a persistent stumbling block in relations
between the two as a potential military conflict brews over Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Presidents Clinton and Jiang Zemin have each expressed a desire
to recover some of the good will that was lost over sharply
diverging views of the NATO air campaign in Kosovo, and was further
eroded by the embassy bombing. Yet the deadlock, after inconclusive
bickering about money, appeared to represent a clash of midlevel
officials who represent the less forgiving sides of their
respective governments.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. official familiar with the talks described the officials'
sharply different approaches as a ``complete disconnect.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was lawyers' talking at lawyers,'' the official said.
``Entirely different mind-sets.''
</P>
<P>
   If money was the topic, the underlying issue for China seemed to
be an obsession with regaining national pride that it feels was
wounded in the bombing and harmed further by what it regards as an
utter lack of remorse by the Americans. Beijing has rejected U.S.
explanations that the bombing was an accident.
</P>
<P>
   On the U.S. side, lawyers in the delegation were most worried
about setting a precedent for future compensation cases, to the
extent that they even refused to use the term ``compensation'' in
the talks, saying ``humanitarian payments'' instead.
</P>
<P>
   A legal adviser to the State Department who headed the U.S.
team, David Andrews, issued a short statement that called the
substance of the talks sensitive and complex. Progress was made,
Andrews said, but he did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   What is so sensitive and complex appears to be the starting
point that Chinese officials still see the bombing as a deliberate
attack on the Chinese nation, making them unwilling to discuss
other bilateral issues until the bombing question has been
resolved.
</P>
<P>
   A senior Chinese official, Zhao Qiz-heng, elaborated on the
Chinese view on Thursday at a news conference. He ridiculed the
U.S. explanation that they had hit the wrong target because of
defective intelligence and outdated maps, comparing the odds that
three outdated maps were used simultaneously to rolling dice and
getting triple snake eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chances of throwing a one, that's 1 out of 6,'' said Zhao,
who heads the Information Office of the State Council, or China's
Cabinet. ``If you roll three dice, it is 1 out of 216. If you add
in other errors, that is like rolling 10 dice. The chances are
close to nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Chinese officials have demanded compensation for the families of
three Chinese who died in the bombing and for 20 who were injured,
as well as for damage to the building. They have also asked that
those responsible for the bombing be identified and punished.
</P>
<P>
   In response, the Americans have demanded reciprocal compensation
for damage to the U.S. Embassy in Beijing, where rock-throwing
broke most windows. The U.S. consulate in another city, Chengdu,
was burned in a riot.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States hopes to make these payments as soon as
possible,'' Andrews' statement said. ``Both sides also raised their
respective property claims.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the U.S. Embassy said that Andrews would leave
Beijing on Saturday and that he or someone else would resume talks
at the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   Without a resolution over the bombing, officials say, it may be
difficult for Washington and Beijing to regain footing on another,
arguably far more significant, issue, China's entry to the World
Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   China's effort to join the organization, desired both by China's
leaders and by the Clinton administration, now looks increasingly
vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   For a deal to go through this year, an agreement between the
United States and China would essentially have to be worked out
before Presidents Clinton and Jiang meet in September at the Asia
Pacific Economic Conference in New Zealand. If this year's deadline
is not met, China's entry may be delayed for several years, a
potentially serious setback to China's ability to effect
much-needed reforms in its state-owned industries.
</P>
<P>
   China's top trade negotiator, Long Yongtu, said again this week
that China would not resume trade talks until the bombing issue had
been resolved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-99 1905EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
