u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV18-B     07-16 1522
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV18-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FOURTH BEST NEWSPAPER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 18, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I agreed last spring to talk to a group of bankers. But as I
drove past Fenway Park on my way to the newspaper, it struck me
that droning on about developments in economics was unlikely to
deeply engage the audience after dinner. On the other hand, a
newspaper is at least as interesting as a baseball club. So I
talked about the future of newspapers in the Internet age instead,
and only one fellow fell asleep.
</P>
<P>
   That meant talking about The Boston Globe. It is the fourth best
newspaper in the United States, I said, and the only one of those
published in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   I quickly explained there are two or three other papers that can
easily lay the ``fourth best'' claim in any given year. There is a
fairly stable hierarchial structure in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   In the top tier are the two fully national papers, the New York
Times and the Wall Street Journal, so well differentiated that they
compete for the same audience only at the very top of their
enormous markets. Most readers choose one or the other. That means
these papers are highly stable; there is no great liklihood of
readership ``tipping'' from one standard to the other as with, say,
computer software.
</P>
<P>
   There is a hybrid, too: the Washington Post, a highly
profitable, well-run regional paper that happens to be published in
the nation's capital, and therefore has a national audience. It is
no accident that all three papers are family-owned.
</P>
<P>
   The next tier consists of very successful regional papers which,
for reasons of geography and destiny, possess a national voice.
They are the Los Angeles Times, the Chicago Tribune, the Globe and
the Philadelphia Inquirer.
</P>
<P>
   For many years these papers too were family enterprises. Each is
somewhat less personally chartered now, the creatures respectively
of a family feud, a foundation, and a pair of newspaper chains.
There is always a horse race among them: Who's getting better?
Who's getting worse? What paper in the next lower tier is bidding
to join the club?
</P>
<P>
   The metric here is size and complexity. (That's why I'm omitting
the Christian Science Monitor, an otherwise excellent paper.) To
play in this league, you have to formulate a sufficiently large and
attractive paying audience of readers, plus advertisers who want to
reach them, to field a team of 400 or more reporters and editors.
They must interact daily with readers, each other and the
competition, in order to deliver a distinctive version of ``all the
news.''
</P>
<P>
   There are no narrative engines of comparable power anywhere in
radio, television, the ``info-tainment'' industry or the Internet.
Nor, it seems to me, are there likely to be any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   How did the Globe become one of a handful of brand names in
American journalism? My favorite stop on a tour here used to be the
third floor corner of the building where a series of commemorative
pages from around the turn of the last century were displayed. The
Globe's publishers routinely grouped themselves among the other
``quality'' papers of the day: Greeley's Tribune, Bennett's Herald,
Sulzberger's Times, Pulitzer's World, Medill's Tribune. Even when
they were just starting out, the ambition to be among the best was
always present.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, General Charles H. Taylor, the builder of The Boston
Globe, the man who edited it for 50 years, early on made common
cause with the wave of immigrants. Indeed, for many years during
Boston's Gilded Age, the Globe was know as ``the maid's paper,'' in
contrast to the Yankee Transcript and the commercial Herald. Taylor
had been midwest as a private soldier during the Civil War. He had
some sense of how the opening of the West would shrink New
England's importance in the nation's scheme of things; he
understood how cohesion among its classes could restore some
measure of it.
</P>
<P>
   The first half of the 20th century was not a good time for
Boston. In the 1940s and 1950s, the city's papers reaped much
scorn. Boston was ``the poor farm of American journalism,'' gibed
one critic, at a time when New York was downtown and Chicago its
gaudy shopping district. The Globe for many years, preserved some
of the old British ways, with ads on page 1 and editorials signed
``Uncle Dudley.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until Davis Taylor and John I. Taylor, two cousins who
shared an office for 30 years, ``took the lid off'' in the 1950s
that the strategy really began to pay off, as the maids'
grandchildren moved to the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe moved its operations to the edge of town and became
the low-cost producer, then acquired talent as the Post and
Traveler failed. The paper broke the Herald's cross-ownership of a
lucrative television station, and appointed a new editor, Thomas
Winship. It reinvested profits in the business. That meant
investing in people.
</P>
<P>
   A newspaper is rather like a large symphony orchestra. Its basic
elements are the same from place to place. The editor is like a
conductor, except that he or she requires a raft of deputies,
subeditors, and telephone operators to help cater to the tastes of
the town. Each big paper is distinctive in its own way. Let me
briefly mention a few elements unique to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Alone among the states, Massachusetts' capital was never moved
to a central place from its commercial hub. As a result, politics
may be more intertwined with daily life in Boston than almost any
other place. A cadre of more than thirty editors, reporters and
columnists cover it with zest, campaign to campaign, from the White
House to the State House to City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Sports is the other half of the franchise. Aficionados know that
the Globe's experts _ often three or four deep _ rank at the top
nationally in football, baseball, basketball, hockey, tennis, golf,
soccer, boxing, rowing, skiiing, yachting, high school and Olympic
sports.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe covers culture, high and low. An unusally large number
of staff and part-time critics (twenty five) follow art,
architecture, drama, books, dance, music (classical, jazz and
rock), movies, television, magazines and restaurants. Even more
reporters keep tabs on developments in modern living.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is unusual profusion of Globe columns. Ellen Goodman
is the one everyone knows. (She is carried in more than 300
newspapers.) The late lamented Mike Barnicle and Patricia Smith
were the next best known, before they came to grief. But a strong
new crop has taken root, including Alex Beam, Eileen McNamara,
Michael Holley and Hiawatha Bray.
</P>
<P>
   There is a large and versatile metro staff. A half-dozen
suburban zones. A talented business department. A platoon of
science writers. A corp of investigative reporters big enough to
staff an FBI field office. A small, blue-chip group of foreign
correspondents, many of whom move up to the national papers. A
distinguished editorial page to cogitate and make endorsements. A
lively op-ed page. Photographers and designers galore. And now the
Web heads.
</P>
<P>
   Because it evolved out of an interest in periodical magazines,
the Globe still maintains a separate Sunday department. Besides the
usual magazine, television guide and funnies, there is a seperate
book review, a travel section, a handyman columnist, a food writer,
an automobile writer, a personal finance specialist, and someday, I
hope, a computer writer. These specialists are at the top of their
trades. Add to these news sections containing the cream of the
week's efforts of the rest of the staff and the enormous cornucopia
of advertising. When these three pounds thump on the porch in the
morning, it can seem almost too much to bear.
</P>
<P>
   All four of these fourth-best dailys are losing circulation. So
is the Washington Post. Nobody really knows why. Nor is it clear
when it will stop. The Internet is part of it, so is the rest of
the variety of modern life. The Wall Street Journal, the New York
Times and the Post (with its weekly national edition) are all
expanding in the weekend market against them. Technology is making
it easier to slice away classified and help-wanted advertising to
cheaper more targeted forums. So in all liklihood the cost
structures of these big newspapers will have to change. Nobody
knows how much.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years from now, these regional papers may resemble local
versions of today's Financial Times of London, which circulates
around the world: sleek, slim, packed with high-quality information
and _ this is the key point _ great or even greater in the variety
of coverage.
</P>
<P>
   With any luck, the fourth-best papers will saturate their local
markets. They will serve as complements to the national papers for
some readers, substitutes for most. They will trade their memories
of huge mass markets for a proportionately smaller, richer, more
enthusiastic audiences _ just as professional baseball has done so
successfully amid the sports explosion of these last 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
