<SLUG> BC-SPRINGSTEEN-CONCERT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NIGHT OF MANY RETURNS FOR THE BOSS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By NEIL STRAUSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ It would have been very difficult to
leave the Continental Airlines Arena disappointed on Thursday
night, when Bruce Springsteen began his first American tour with
the E Street Band in 10 years. If Springsteen's work is a journey _
and it is, not just in his close relationship with his fans but
also for the characters whose development he follows from album to
album _ then the three-hour, 26-song show stopped at nearly all
points on the map.
</P>
<P>
   The show was in many ways a return for Springsteen. It was a
return to his home state, New Jersey, and in dedication he
performed a rarely heard song, ``Freehold,'' a funny yet pointed
confessional folk song in which the Boss returns to the town that
still remembers him as a baby.
</P>
<P>
   It was also a return to the Continental Airlines Arena, where he
performed the inaugural concert when the arena opened in 1981 under
its precorporate sponsorship name, the Brendan Byrne Arena.
Thursday's show was the first of 15 sold-out concerts _ the most a
single act has performed at the arena _ in a tour that wraps up on
Aug. 12.
</P>
<P>
   It was a return to the E Street Band, most of whose members
Springsteen has been playing with since he was a teen-ager in
Asbury Park, N.J. Though he laid off the band in 1989, he keeps
returning to it, as if it were the only way to provide a
counterbalance to his more introspective, psychological solo work.
When the group tried to tackle one of those ballads, ``The Ghost of
Tom Joad,'' it had difficulty. The E Street Band isn't an outfit
that is very good at not rocking. The band, as Springsteen has
said, is a symbolic bridge between him and his audience.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, it was a return to Springsteen's fans. His career has
tended to cycle between those introspective albums that document
his internal battles with cynicism and despair and the full-band
rock ones that his audience craves. So after he released an
audience-pleaser with new E Street Band songs, ``Greatest Hits,''
in 1995, he turned inward with ``The Ghost of Tom Joad.'' Turning
right back around, during the last year he has given his fans two
things they've been asking for most: ``Tracks,'' a four-CD set full
of the songs he hadn't released over the years, and this tour.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed all in black (even his shoes, belt and wristbands _
everything except his gray hair), Springsteen, 49, didn't just lead
his band, he led people in the crowd, making them believe in the
great illusion of live rock-and-roll: that their participation _
their yelling, clapping, singing along _ is necessary to complete
the music. In ``Tenth Avenue Freeze-Out'' he egged on the crowd
with several minutes of James Brown-like soul-preacher testimony.
``Look out Ricky Martin,'' he joked as he shook his hips. ``I'm
filled with the spirit of the ghost of Tom Jones.'' In ``Murder
Inc.'' he took time for Nils Lofgren, Steve Van Zandt and himself
to solo on guitar after standing aside momentarily for Clarence
Clemons, the master of the rock saxophone solo.
</P>
<P>
   Springsteen returns when rock 'n' roll needs him most, when
arenas are filled with manufactured teeny-bopper bands or music for
older teen-agers, white rock bands whose idea of classic pop is
gangsta rap. But what most of these bands, from 'N Sync to today's
Rolling Stones, lack is depth, the quality that keeps three hours
with Bruce Springsteen and the E Street Band from being nostalgia.
As a man who has always sung of borders psychological and physical,
Springsteen is aware that he stands on this border, and to stay on
the right side he waited until he was 10 songs into the set before
playing an actual hit, ``Badlands.''
</P>
<P>
   The opening of the show leaned heavily on the 1978 album that
contains ``Badlands,'' ``Darkness on the Edge of Town.'' It was the
perfect way to avoid being a nostalgia act: by sidestepping
nostalgia, going back to the album overshadowed by his surrounding
breakthroughs. It was those songs that contained the keys that
unlocked the themes he has wrestled with throughout his career:
characters balanced on the brink of a decision, staring at the
abyss, ready to jump in with the slim hope that just maybe their
dreams might await them at the bottom. ``I believe in the faith,''
he sang in ``Badlands.'' ``And I pray, that someday it may raise
me/Above these badlands.''
</P>
<P>
   The two recent unreleased songs that he performed Thursday
night, ``Land of Hope and Dreams'' (the show's gospel-derived
closer) and ``Freehold,'' bore out his belief that, yes, he could
rise above it. Springsteen's gift has always been that no matter
how far he has risen, he has never left the ground he is rooted in.
</P>
</TEXT>
