<HEADLINE>
MAKE EVALUATIONS LESS OF A STRUGGLE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the most part, performance evaluations are pretty painful.
Most managers hate talking about a subordinate's shortcomings and
no employee likes to get the word that he's anything short of
perfect.
</P>
<P>
   But there are ways to turn evaluations into useful tools to
improve employee performance.
</P>
<P>
   It begins with setting goals and then measuring the results,
said Dick Grote, author of ``Discipline without Punishment: The
Proven Strategy that Turns Problem Employees into Superior
Performers.'' Grote is a human resource consultant who lives in
Dallas and recently spoke to a group of managers at a seminar
sponsored by the outplacement firm Drake Beam Morin.
</P>
<P>
   Once goals are set, the talking part _ which everyone thinks is
the hardest part _ actually is easier.
</P>
<P>
   Before doing the evaluation, ask each employee to jot down his
accomplishments for the year, Grote suggested. That way, key
details won't be forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   There aren't many things more embarrassing than when a boss
forgets a major effort and is reminded during an evaluation when
the employee says, ``What about that Tompkins contract I did?''
</P>
<P>
   It's also really important to explain what it takes to get a
``distinguished'' rating, Grote said. Too often, companies explain
what it takes to get a middling rating but not a top one.
</P>
<P>
   And all that talk about performance evaluations being bogus
because they're subjective? Don't worry, advised Grote.
</P>
<P>
   When it's time for your appraisal, you don't want data, he said.
You want the answer to the question: How am I doing? And that takes
description, he said.
</P>
<P>
   After all, we don't use data when we choose a mate, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Focus on one or two main messages you want the employee to hear,
Grote suggested. No one can remember 15 different subjects next
month.
</P>
<P>
   And eliminate some of the pre-evaluation anxieties by giving an
employee a copy an hour before the meeting so he can digest it, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BASE EVALUATIONS ON GOALS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Evaluations should be based on goals set with input from
individual employees. That's especially important in managing
younger employees because empowerment is so important to them, said
Melanie R. Webb, personnel officer with the Harris County Appraisal
District in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   And it's important to have a midterm review to check an
employee's progress toward meeting goals, Webb said.
</P>
<P>
   That way, any shortcomings can be addressed, she said. If a
manager waits until the end of the year, it's not proactive.
</P>
<P>
   The more specific a manager is, the more helpful the information
is to employees. To make it easier for managers to provide details,
Enron, for example, has coaching sessions for its managers.
</P>
<P>
   Managers are given scenarios and asked to write evaluations that
include a lot of concrete examples, said Kathleen Fenninger, senior
director of staffing for Enron Corp. Then they practice explaining
the evaluation to an ``employee.''
</P>
<P>
   During the training sessions, several of the managers discover
exactly what is meant by detail, said Fenninger. Doing an employee
evaluation isn't something that's intuitive, she said. It has to be
learned.
</P>
<P>
   It's also important to talk about career goals at the annual
evaluation, said Len George, executive vice president of NCI
Building Systems, a manufacturer of metal buildings and components.
</P>
<P>
   That way, a production line employee who wants to go into sales
can talk about making a switch, he said. And if the company has its
eye on moving an employee into plant management, the manager can
suggest some skills or courses the employee might need to make the
move.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good motivator, George said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A DIFFERENT APPROACH &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PolySpec Corp., a Houston maker of floor coatings and sealants,
does the traditional evaluations each year but recently added a
quickie quarterly evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   Every three months, employees are asked to appear before a
three-member management panel to explain what they've done to
contribute to the success of the company, said company President
M.W. ``Buddy'' Ellisor Jr. The meetings, which last only about five
minutes, were designed to divvy up the quarterly profit-sharing
funds that PolySpec sets aside.
</P>
<P>
   Ellisor said the panel also asks each employee who, with the
exception of himself, contributes to the success of the company.
The answers have been real surprises, said Ellisor, who said five
production employees all identified the same colleague and raved
how great he was.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't aware of it,'' said Ellisor, who said the employee
got a big bonus and raise as a result. And you can bet that Ellisor
is keeping a close eye on his star performer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all look at him differently,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
