<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3150 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-COLUMN-$ADV18-     07-16 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-COLUMN-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BOUNCE FROM STOCK BUYBACKS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 18) 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Please note that the word AT in parentheses has been used in
the final graf instead of the symbol, which is non-transmittable to
some newspaper systems.) 
(af) 
 By MARK HULBERT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Burned once, shame on you; burned twice, shame on me. That
variation on an old saying explains much investor behavior. It
takes a lot to persuade investors who have already lost money in a
given stock to keep believing in it if it keeps falling, no matter
what its fundamentals.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the market's typically tepid reaction when a company
says it will be repurchasing its stock on the open market; many
such stocks have taken multiple hits, and are at depressed levels
as the announcements are made.
</P>
<P>
   Officemax, which traded early last year near $20 a share, took
two blows last fall: The overall market had a sharp correction, and
the company missed Wall Street's third-quarter earnings estimates
by a 4 cents a share. The stock fell to below $7.
</P>
<P>
   Though the shares jumped a little after the company announced
two repurchase programs, one late last year and another earlier
this year, the stock is still trading at not much more than half
its 1998 high.
</P>
<P>
   Such a lukewarm reaction notwithstanding, it is difficult to
imagine a more unambiguously bullish sign than a company's decision
to use its spare cash to buy back its shares. After all, when a
company puts its own cash on the line, it must be confident that
the stock will climb. And it often does, beating the market in a
pattern known as the repurchase effect.
</P>
<P>
   Studies have demonstrated the effect. One, covering all U.S.
stocks from 1980 to 1990, found that the average company announcing
a repurchase plan will beat the market by a cumulative 12.6
percentage points for the four years after the announcement. The
average value stock with such a plan does even better,
outperforming the market by 45.3 points, on average, over the next
four years.
</P>
<P>
   For investors, the repurchase effect has another advantage: You
don't have to be a day trader to exploit it. Many other strategies,
by contrast, require almost immediate action. To capitalize on a
surprise announcement in a company's earnings, for example, you
often have to trade within hours of the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Not so with stock repurchase plans. Because the market's initial
reaction is so muted, there is generally plenty of potential
remaining for investors who act several weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   It seems too good to be true. So, naturally, a number of
skeptical professors have speculated in recent years that the
repurchase effect is nothing more than a statistical fluke, and
have predicted that it will disappear when studied in other places
and times.
</P>
<P>
   That is why another recent study is good news. Three professors
_ David Ikenberry of the Jones Graduate School of Management at
Rice University, Josef Lakonishok of the University of Illinois and
Theo Vermaelen of Maastricht University in the Netherlands _
focused on another place and time, Canadian stocks in the 1990s,
and found the repurchase effect alive and well.
</P>
<P>
   Another confirmation of sorts is seen in the reverse image of a
repurchase: a corporate decision to issue shares, either through
initial public offerings or secondary offerings. Study after study
has shown that companies issuing shares lag behind the market for
several years thereafter. Moreover, the pattern holds not only in
the United States, but also in several other countries.
</P>
<P>
   An investment newsletter, too, shows the positive results of the
repurchase effect. The Buyback Letter, edited by David Fried, is
the only one that I know to base its approach solely on the effect;
it has had a 32.2 percent return, annualized, from the beginning of
1997, soon after its birth, through May of this year, according to
The Hulbert Financial Digest.
</P>
<P>
   That compares with a 25.3 percent return for the Wilshire 5000,
a broad market index. In contrast, New Issues, published by the
Institute for Econometric Research and perhaps the best-known IPO
newsletter, produced a 19.9 percent annualized return over that
period. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mark Hulbert is editor of the Hulbert Financial Digest, a
newsletter based in Alexandria, Va. His column on investment
strategies appears every other week. E-mail:
strategy(AT)nytimes.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
