<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAKED-RULING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE ALLOWS NAKED PHOTO SHOOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ You can call it the Naked City once more.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge ruled Friday, over the protests of City Hall,
that photographer Spencer Tunic can indeed snap pictures of 75
people lying naked on a street in downtown Manhattan Sunday at 5:30
in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the city had argued on Thursday that Tunic's act
might offend the people who live on the block where the shoot would
take place.
</P>
<P>
   But the judge, Harold Baer Jr., ruled: ``The privacy interests
of the residents of this neighborhood, who can avert their eyes,
cannot outweigh the rights of others to exercise their First
Amendment right to artistic expression.''
</P>
<P>
   The city's attorneys immediately went across the street to ask
the 2nd Circuit Court of Appeals to stay Baer's ruling, but the
judges there saw no reason to reverse Baer's stand.
</P>
<P>
   Tunic, who is well-known and much-lauded in artistic circles for
his stark photos of naked bodies against empty urban backdrops, has
been arrested by the New York City police four times for his
efforts in recent years _ most famously on a Sunday dawn last
April, when he was handcuffed and dragged away after getting 175
people to lie down naked in the middle of Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   New York State has a law forbidding public nudity _ but
explicitly makes an exception for art and entertainment. Baer ruled
that Tunic's photography fits the exemption.
</P>
<P>
   The city had approved Tunic's application for a permit to
photograph 75 clothed people at 5:30 a.m. Sunday _ but then
rejected another request to take pictures of naked people in the
same place and the same time.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the city's lawyer, Sherrill Kurland, at first
argued that the case was about ``common sense.'' When Baer seemed
to be taking Tunic's side on the constitutional issue, Kurland
shifted tactics and said the real issue was that the proposed photo
site was a ``densely residential'' block. She further said the city
would consider negotiating for a different block.
</P>
<P>
   Tunic's lawyer, Ron Kuby, called Kurland's bluff and said Tunic
would be willing to move the site a few blocks over, to a much
emptier street.
</P>
<P>
   Baer asked Kurland if this was acceptable. She asked for more
time. By Friday morning, she had not come back with an answer, so
Baer ruled in Tunic's favor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
