<SLUG> BC-SENEGAL-ELAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON NAMES ELAM AMBASSADOR TO SENEGAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Harriet L. Elam arrived in the nation's capital 36
years ago, a Simmons College graduate, and she took a job as a
secretary in the Army. She wanted to leave her native Boston, she
said, ``because I was tired of being the little Elam girl, Harry,
Clarence and Charles' little sister.''
</P>
<P>
   Kid sister Harriet, now 57, has just been nominated by President
Clinton as the next US ambassador to the Republic of Senegal.
</P>
<P>
   The ambassador-designate must go before Senate confirmation
hearings in the next month.
</P>
<P>
   From a Roxbury family with many stars, including brother Harry,
who was a longtime Boston judge, and late brother Clarence, who
once ran a campaign of former US Senator Ed Brooke of
Massachusetts, she has made her own distinction in years of work
overseas and in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Elam, whose fascination of the ``world beyond Boston'' grew out
of a summer college undergraduate program in France, now is acting
deputy director and counselor of the US Information Agency.
</P>
<P>
   She has served in Greece, Turkey, France, Senegal, Mali and the
Ivory Coast. She learned Greek and Turkish on the job. The Greek
and Turkish governments separately gave her awards for improving US
cultural relations with both countries.
</P>
<P>
   And she was thinking about retiring this fall, more than a
little unnerved by the dangers of being a diplomat overseas. She
had seen colleagues killed in terrorist acts in Greece and Turkey,
and then came the bloody US embassy bombings in Kenya and Tanzania
last August.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department had talked to her about other
ambassadorships, but she had passed. Then they asked her about
Senegal, and she couldn't say no. Senegal was her first posting
overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a particular affinity for Senegal,'' she said Friday
from her home in Arlington, Va. ``And I thought there was something
I could do to allow the Senegalese to know that when President
Clinton went there last year it wasn't just to window dress. He has
a genuine commitment when he talks about trade and not just aid to
Africa.''
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, Elma Lewis, the founder of the National Cener of
African American Artists, was overjoyed with the news of Elam's
nomination. Lewis is a friend of the Elam family and has known
Harriet since the day she was born.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was born the day I turned 20. That was my birthday
present,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said the nomination was long overdue. ``I can't even have
imagined how they waited this long,'' she said. ``She is a Roxbury
girl from the beginning, from the time she was born, from Roxbury
Memorial High School, from St. Mark's Congregational Church, from
Simmons College, she's been a beacon in this community. I love
her.''
</P>
<P>
   John P. Dwyer, deputy associate director of information at USIA,
said many in Washington feel similarly. ``She has a tremendous
number of friends. Harriet is a very principled person,'' he said.
``She is very traditional, very strict, very sort of
work-your-way-up type of attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Elam now is preparing for her Senate confirmation hearings and
studying issues relating to Senegal and Africa. Vast numbers of
African-Americans have traveled to Senegal especially in the past
two decades to learn more about their heritage. For many of the
slaves in bondage for America, the last African stop was the
Senegal island of Goree.
</P>
<P>
   She left Senegal in 1974 as a junior officer. If confirmed, she
could take up her post in October. Such a return, she said, ``would
be particularly sweet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
