<SLUG> BC-BUSH-FILINGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEC DENIES TELLING BUSH CAMP NOT TO FILE CAMPAIGN REPORT
ELECTRONICALLY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush's aides said his record $37
million presidential campaign finance report was not filed
electronically this week because the campaign was discouraged from
doing so by the Federal Elections Commission.
</P>
<P>
   But FEC officials said that was not the case at all and that
Bush had actually been encouraged to file electronically.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not discourage the Bush campaign from filing
electronically,'' said FEC spokesman Ron Harris. ``We had been
looking forward to them filing electronically.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of his campaign finance reform package, Bush has said he
favors instant disclosure of campaign contributions on the Internet
as soon as a candidate receives them.
</P>
<P>
   Harris said Bush filed paper copies of his report and said the
cover pages have been scanned in for voters to view at the agency's
Internet site: www.fec.gov. But Harris said it will take several
weeks for staffers to type the Bush report into a searchable
database of individual donors.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush campaign spokesmen Mindy Tucker and Scott McClellan
said the FEC discouraged the campaign from filing electronically
because of ``glitches'' in the FEC software and what impact the
massive report would have on the FEC computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were concerns at both ends because of the enormous size
of it,'' McClellan said. ``Apparently there were some concerns
about the download time.''
</P>
<P>
   McClellan noted the report is available on the campaign Internet
site: www.georgewbush.com.
</P>
<P>
   However, that report on the Bush site is a jumbled mess that has
city names in the columns for zip codes; zip codes in the columns
for occupation; and contributions listed in the column for dates of
the donations.
</P>
<P>
   The report also cannot be searched by various categories; for
example, a researcher could not figure out what contributions came
from a particular city or from people of a particular occupation.
</P>
<P>
   A searchable electronic database of Bush's contributions had
been given to the news media by the campaign Thursday, but not to
the FEC or the public at large.
</P>
<P>
   This is not Bush's first flap over campaign finance reports.
</P>
<P>
   In his 1994 campaign for governor, Bush had promised to file
campaign reports electronically with the Texas Ethics Commission.
But he quit immediately after the election. Bush only filled in the
gaps in his electronic filings after being challenged by the
Houston Chronicle on his failure to keep a campaign promise.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had promised in April to file his July presidential
campaign finance report electronically after he missed filing his
first report electronically with the FEC.
</P>
<P>
   McClellan said Bush will file his next presidential campaign
report electronically.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
