<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3165 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLITICS17-COX     07-16 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Candidates head to Ohio
 &HT;    By William Hershey
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ When U.S. Rep. John Kasich withdrew from the
presidential race this week and endorsed George W. Bush, it sent a
signal to other Ohio Republicans that Jeff Jacobson heard loud and
clear:
</P>
<P>
   Get on the Bush bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   Kasich, from Westerville near Columbus, dropped out Wednesday.
On Thursday, Jacobson, who had endorsed Kasich, switched to Bush,
the Texas governor and son of former President George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe it's all over,'' said Jacobson, chairman of the
Montgomery County Republican party and a state representative from
Phillipsburg. ``The (county) party does not officially endorse in
presidential races, but I endorsed him as party chairman and as a
state representative.''
</P>
<P>
   Before ``it's all over,'' Bush still must survive a gauntlet of
caucuses and primaries to win the GOP nomination and then defeat
Vice President Al Gore or whomever the Democrats nominate in the
November 2000 general election.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, however, Ohio Republicans are treating a Bush
fund-raiser in Cincinnati on July 22 almost like a coronation.
</P>
<P>
   It's Bush's first campaign visit to the state and the goal was
to raise $500,000 _ a goal that had been exceeded by the middle of
this week, said Buck Niehoff, Hamilton County Republican chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's visit is also the first of three major political
fund-raisers in Ohio within in seven days. President Bill Clinton
will be in Cincinnati for a fund-raiser Friday, July 23, and on
July 29, Gore will be in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, Republicans are saying they expect Bush to leave
Cincinnati with $1 million. Tickets are $1,000 a person for the
fund-raiser to be held at the Omni Netherland Plaza.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually with fund-raising we're begging and kicking and
twisting their arms,'' Niehoff said.
</P>
<P>
   Not this time, he added. ``It's a seller's market.''
</P>
<P>
   While Bush fever has captured the political headlines in Ohio
and across the country, Democrats, too, have stepped up their
campaigning and fund-raising in the state.
</P>
<P>
   A day after Bush's trip, Clinton will be in Cincinnati to raise
money for the Democratic National Committee at the home of attorney
and prominent Democratic fund-raiser Stan Chesley. The event
originally was scheduled for March but was postponed because of the
war in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Then on July 29, Gore will be in Cleveland for a fund-raiser at
the home of industrialist Michael Siegal. Former U.S. Sen. Bill
Bradley of New Jersey, Gore's only current opposition for the
nomination, plans to be in Columbus on Sept. 2 for his own money
raising event.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, said political scientist John Green,
presidential politics are settling into their normal pattern in
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ohio is as important as it's always been,'' said Green,
director of the Ray C. Bliss Institute of Applied Politics at the
University of Akron. ``If your campaign plays in Ohio, it probably
will play nationally.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing Kasich's departure did was loosen up the pocketbooks
of Ohio Republicans, Green said. ``With Kasich stepping out, the
floodgates opened,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are ready to open their hearts as well as their bank
accounts, said Jacobson. There's an enthusiasm and feeling that
Bush is a winner. That attitude was lacking in 1996 with former
Sen. Bob Dole, Jacobson said.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, he said, Republicans felt: ``Well, it (backing Dole)
is the only way to go to the convention. At least the convention
will be fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's path to the March 7 primary in Ohio will not be obstacle
free, said Ohio Secretary of State J. Kenneth Blackwell, national
chairman for Republican publisher Steve Forbes' presidential
campaign. By the primary, the Republican race in Ohio will be
between Forbes and Bush, Blackwell predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll have a clear choice between a status quo-oriented,
establishment candidate (Bush) and an independent tree shaker and
thinker (Forbes),'' Blackwell said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, not surprisingly, also are unconvinced of the
inevitability of a Bush victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``You mean George W. `Muskie' Bush?'' joked former Ohio
Democratic Chairman Ruvolo. He was referring to former secretary of
state and Sen. Edmund Muskie, who appeared to have the 1972
Democratic nomination locked up only to falter and drop out,
leaving the Democrats with George McGovern.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has a network of Ohio supporters _ including contributors _
developed during the 1992 and 1996 Clinton-Gore campaigns, said
Richard Cordray, a former state representative and, with Ruvolo, a
key Ohio contact for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democrats feel good about the fact that this president-vice
president team has brought the Democrats back to being
competitive,'' Cordray said.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean all of them want Gore to be the nominee, said
Bob McAllister, a Columbus attorney and long-time Democratic
activist. McAllister is helping put together the Sept. 2 event for
Bradley, whose talk on race in America particularly impressed
McAllister.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is there's going to be a (Democratic) primary in
Ohio,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
