<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3166 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHEERLEADER-INDUSTRY-     07-16 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEERLEADER-INDUSTRY-ART-960words(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPIRIT INDUSTRY THRIVES AS CHEERLEADING BOOMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ko) 
 By EMILY YELLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OXFORD, Miss. _ On a recent steamy day at the University of
Mississippi here, the Prince song ``1999'' blasted from
loudspeakers as high-pitched yells of ``go'' and ``fight'' rose
from a sea of nearly 1,000 brightly clad teen-agers scattered in
clusters in the middle of campus.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In one cluster, 21 girls from Mount Pisgah Middle School in
Cordova, Tenn. _ wearing identical yellow shorts, white tops
emblazoned with their school logo, and maroon bows in their hair _
sprang into action. The cheerleaders danced, jumped, back-flipped,
and formed a human pyramid in sync with the music, smiling so
intently that some looked as if their braces might burst through
their cheeks. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The scene will be repeated many times this summer as more than
400,000 cheerleaders attend camps like this one on college campuses
around the country to learn new moves, perfect old ones and check
out the competition. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The camps, which usually last three or four days and cost just
$150 to $200 per person, combine with regional and national
cheerleading competitions and uniform sales to make up what
insiders call ``the spirit industry.'' And a thriving industry it
is, with more than a million active participants, tens of millions
in revenues and nationwide television coverage. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps 95 percent of the participants are girls, although there
are plenty of male cheerleaders. In fact, their ranks include
notables like the two U.S. senators from Mississippi, Trent Lott
and Thad Cochran (both cheered at the University of Mississippi),
Steve Martin, Ronald Reagan and Dwight D. Eisenhower.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the national spotlight turns to women in sports like
soccer, volleyball or basketball, cheerleading's popularity does
not seem to have wavered. For in the last 20 years or so, the
spirit industry has evolved into a dynamic business, with
cheerleading growing more athletic, more competitive and more
expensive.
</P>
<P>
   The industry has also come to include school dance teams and
pompom squads as well as dance studio participants and cheerleading
squads called all-stars, who do not actually cheer for a team but
exist only to compete. All those groups need uniforms, and many
attend a summer camp at one time or another.
</P>
<P>
   ``The camps create the market for us,'' said Jeffrey G. Webb,
49, chief executive of the Varsity Spirit Corporation, based in
Memphis, an industry leader. ``It's a virtual circle of
cross-marketing. We know from our research that most kids enter
that circle through the camps. And we use our camps to promote our
special events _ our competitions. And while we don't sell uniforms
at camps, our sales reps come there, meet with customers and make
presentations.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The strategy has clearly worked on the Mount Pisgah squad. For
six years they have come to camps run by Varsity's camp and
competition division, the Universal Cheerleaders Association. They
buy all their uniforms and gear from the Varsity catalog, and they
compete in the association's national competition every winter at
Disney World in Orlando, Fla., telecast on ESPN. In 1995, they were
the champions of the junior high division. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Smith, 42, one of the mothers who accompanied the squad
to camp this year, along with their coach and their faculty
adviser, said it cost about $5,000 a year for her daughter,
Christie, 12, to be a cheerleader. That includes summer camp, camp
clothes (different matching outfits for each day), uniforms,
warm-up outfits, coaching, gymnastics classes and travel expenses
to regional and national cheerleading competitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spend most of the year fund raising,'' Ms. Smith said. ``We
do car washes, baby-sitting, sell poinsettias, anything to offset
the cost. Each girl's parents have their own account, and we each
put in at least $200 per month. It is like a car note.'' In her
case, two car loans, since her 16-year-old daughter, Casey, is a
cheerleader at Cordova High School.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Getting a handle on the actual size of this industry and its
market is difficult.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   First, while many companies run camps and competitions and many
others sell uniforms and equipment, Varsity Spirit and its main
rival, the National Spirit Group, of Dallas, are the only two that
do all three and have a nationwide scope. Varsity Spirit was bought
in 1997 by Riddell Sports Inc., which makes football helmets (and
whose chairman is Robert Nederlander, of the Broadway
Nederlanders). In 1997, Varsity's last year as a separate company,
its revenues were $90 million, and National Spirit's were estimated
at $80 million.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Next, no one is sure just how many cheerleaders are out there.
American Sports Data, a research firm in Hartsdale, N.Y., estimates
3.3 million. That includes all children 6 and older, but Varsity
and the others see their market starting at 11 or 12, the age when
children generally join school squads and are old enough to go to
overnight camps and competitions. Varsity puts the number of
cheerleaders and other spirit team members in that market at 1.5
million. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Finally, asking spirit companies about their size or their
markets is not always much help. In typical cheerleader fashion,
they all claim to be the best, the leader, No. 1.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But another indication of the size of the market is a
five-year-old company, Lifestyle Ventures in New York City, which
publishes six related magazines, including American Cheerleader,
with a circulation of 200,000 and a readership of 1.2 million.
Michael Weiskopf, the publisher, said the industry had grown more
sophisticated in the last decade at finding ways to tap into the
spending power of cheerleaders and dance team members, who are
influential within their larger peer group of teen-age girls. &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Weiskopf said the corporate cultures at Varsity, National Spirit
and their smaller rivals had peculiarly good and bad aspects. ``You
get the sense the employees, who are mostly former cheerleaders,
would do anything for their company,'' he said. ``They are very
loyal. There is an organic enthusiasm. It is fun. It could be the
model for an IBM. The downside to that is they have that
cheerleading mentality of let's go out and kill the competition, so
there is not a lot of cohesion or coming together for the good of
the industry.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Webb, Varsity's chief executive and a former University
of Oklahoma cheerleader, used to work for his main competition. He
was hired out of college by National Spirit's founder _ the man
credited with creating the spirit industry, Lawrence Herkimer,
known in the cheerleading world as Herkie. Herkimer started the
first cheerleading camps in the 1940s, and in the '50s he came up
with the idea of the pompon and patented it, propelling him into
the uniform business. For years, in fact, his company was the sole
producer of pompons. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Webb left National Spirit after two and a half years and formed
Varsity Spirit in 1974, setting up camps in direct competition with
his old employer. In 1979, he started manufacturing uniforms, the
most lucrative segment of the business, generally accounting for
about 60 percent of revenues. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, Varsity began national competitions, which were picked
up by ESPN in 1984 and have been televised ever since, with an
average viewership of 500,000 households. Not to be outdone,
National Spirit's camp and competition division, the National
Cheerleaders Association, also developed national competitions that
are now televised on CBS, the USA network and Fox. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now those in the industry are looking to conquer other realms.
Both Varsity and National Spirit mention expanding into uniforms
for other women's and some men's sports. Varsity took a step in
that direction when it signed a U.S. licensing agreement last year
with Umbro, the British soccer uniform manufacturer. For the next
five years, Varsity will manufacture and sell soccer uniforms for
boys and girls, under the Umbro name, to American school and league
markets. Webb said the company hoped eventually to apply the same
cross-marketing model of camps, competitions and uniform sales to
soccer as they had to cheerleading.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soccer is more like cheerleading than any other sport,'' Webb
said, ``because it grew up outside the school and doesn't have all
the regulations. Most soccer is played at the club level in this
country. Kids travel to tournaments all the time. And they buy
their own uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``The school doesn't decide, he added. ``So there is a really
big fashion element to soccer. Fabric and trim and design are
really important.''
</P>
<P>
   Webb said that would fit well with the kind of custom uniforms
the spirit industry was in the business of providing. Just as it is
with cheerleading, he said, ``in soccer everyone wants to have a
really hot look.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
