<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3169 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HARVARD-HOSPITALS-BOS     07-16 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARVARD-HOSPITALS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARVARD TO DIP INTO $13B ENDOWMENT TO HELP TEACHING HOSPITALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Harvard University plans to inject more than $20
million into its four major teaching hospitals to prevent medical
students from getting short shrift in their clinical training.
</P>
<P>
   The 30 percent boost in funding, to be spread over five years,
will come from the university's burgeoning endowment, medical
school officials said _ unless the stock market falters.
</P>
<P>
   The money will help support the training of the 400 third- and
fourth-year Harvard medical students who are based in teaching
hospitals at any one time. In a time-honored apprentice system,
students learn at the bedside and in the clinic how to take
patients' medical histories and do physical exams _ the first steps
beyond textbook learning of medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard's largess is thought to be nationally unique _ largely
because no other university comes close to Harvard's $13 billion
endowment, of which more than $1.5 billion belongs to the medical
school. The medical school has the largest endowment of any Harvard
division.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard Medical School Dean Joseph B. Martin said the unusual
increase in endowment payout is designed to relieve pressure on the
financially beleaguered hospitals and on hospital-based Harvard
faculty, who are scrambling to see more patients in less time to
sustain their incomes and subsidize undergraduate medical training.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the past year we've seen that many of our best teachers
are also the most busy trying to earn their living by seeing
patients,'' Martin said in an interview. ``Each time they step
aside to see students or lecture, that puts increased pressure on
their livelihood.''
</P>
<P>
   The hospitals _ Massachusetts General, Brigham and Women's, Beth
Israel Deaconess and Children's _ are ``under incredible financial
pressures,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Medicare funding has been slashed, managed care's market
penetration has increased, and insurance reimbursements have either
remained flat or have fallen. . .making it difficult for our
hospitals and faculty to carry out their academic missions,'' the
dean said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hospitals are in very grave financial straits,'' he added.
``This isn't just an issue of crying wolf.''
</P>
<P>
   Although other medical schools' investments have also been
buoyed by rising investment portfolios, no other comes close to
matching the 102 endowed Harvard professors based in teaching
hospitals. The medical school has added 25 endowed chairs in just
the last seven years as part of a capital campaign that concluded
last month _ $25 million ahead of its $280 million target.
</P>
<P>
   Each endowed chair at Harvard Medical School is backed by $2.75
million. With the new increase in endowment payout, each chair will
produce $123,750 in annual income. But much of clinical professors'
incomes is derived from patient care.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Michael Rosenblatt, faculty dean for academic programs at
Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center, called the additional medical
school support ``substantial.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very important move, both in real dollars and
symbolically,'' Rosenblatt said. ``The dean is saying the academic
mission in teaching hospitals is important, and he's standing by us
and doing more than the medical school has done in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not clear, however, whether many other medical schools can
follow Harvard's lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``While other schools have hospital-based professors, in terms
of magnitude Harvard's endowed clinical faculty are substantially
greater than anyplace else,'' said Robert Dickler of the
Association of American Medical Colleges in Washington, which
represents the nation's 125 medical schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's terrific,'' Dickler said of Harvard's decision to
increase support for undergraduate hospital training. ``This is not
an inconsiderable sum of money, and the spirit is significant
because it shows how strong the partnership is.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the $4 million a year in additional endowment
funds, the medical school is freeing up as much as $1.9 million a
year in funds previously earmarked for professors' fringe benefits,
if the faculty members also have health insurance and other
benefits through their hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Martin said many clinical professors have had ``essentially
duplicate coverage'' of fringe benefits. ``We're allowing them to
use these funds for academic purposes now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Harvard seven months ago announced it will start
paying out annually an extra $95 million in endowment income
university-wide, of which $11 million will go to the medical
school. This additional payout is in addition to the $20 million
the school has newly earmarked for hospital-based teaching.
</P>
<P>
   The new $20 million endowment payout will be reviewed annually
over five years in light of the performance of the university's
stock portfolio, Martin said. ``If the stock market comes
completely apart, we'd have to modify it each year, but I think we
can be pretty optimistic,'' the dean said. ``I'd hope this would
become a five-year rolling commitment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
