<HEADLINE>
PILOTS MAY BE NEAR DEAL WITH AMERICAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ko) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   American Airlines and its pilots may be close to settling the
dispute that inconvenienced hundreds of thousands of passengers
earlier this year when pilots called in sick, forcing the airline
to cancel nearly 6,700 flights.
</P>
<P>
   The Allied Pilots Association, which represents American's 9,500
pilots, said its 18-member board would consider a proposed
agreement drawn up by George Nicolau, the federal mediator who has
been working with the union and American's parent, AMR Corp. The
seven-month-old dispute stemmed from AMR's acquisition of Reno Air,
a small Western airline, and disparity in pilots' pay.
</P>
<P>
   American, the nation's second-largest airline after United
Airlines, has already agreed to the proposal. But it is still
subject to a vote by the union's board, which will decide in the
next few weeks, said union spokesman Gregg Overman. ``The board
will debate and vote to accept or reject,'' he said. ``Until that
happens, we don't have an agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   He declined to say whether the union's leaders and negotiating
committee would endorse the proposal. Both American and the pilots
union also declined to say what was in the proposed settlement. Two
people with knowledge of the deal said, however, that it included
retroactive salary payments to Reno's 300 pilots and a subagreement
that would spell out how American would handle future mergers.
</P>
<P>
   After AMR took control of Reno on Dec. 23, pilots at American
accused the company of violating a key clause in their contract
that guarantees that all flying be done by members of their union.
They demanded that American immediately begin paying the Reno
pilots at the higher levels of American pilots.
</P>
<P>
   The airline said that pilots' demands would add as much as $50
million to the $124 million cost of the Reno acquisition. It said
that fully integrating Reno into the American network could take up
to 18 months and that it would gradually increase the pay of the
Reno pilots as they assumed their new American jobs.
</P>
<P>
   But hundreds of pilots, fearing that the company was trying to
set a precedent that might hurt them later if AMR acquired a much
larger airline, called in sick in February, and American canceled
thousands of flights at a cost of $200 million.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge declared the job action illegal and ordered the
pilots to return to work. He later found the union, its president
and vice president in contempt and ordered them to pay American
$45.5 million in damages. Earlier this week, the union gave formal
notice that it would appeal the order. Any settlement between the
company, which is based in Dallas, and its pilots would not affect
the fine and the court ruling.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed accord, which was reported on Friday by The Fort
Worth (Texas) Star-Telegram, would give the Reno pilots retroactive
pay raises dating to March 1 and June 1. A third increase on Sept.
1 would bring them to parity with American pilots. It is not clear
whether a 10 percent increase that the Reno pilots already received
from American on June 1 would count toward the raises negotiated in
the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the proposed accord is approved, other contentious
issues would remain. A big one is resolving how much seniority the
Reno pilots, who are represented by a different union, the Air Line
Pilots Association, will get at American.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seniority is everything,'' said one Reno pilot. It determines
where and when they fly, their pay and even the size of their
retirement benefits. The American pilots union has proposed simply
putting the Reno pilots at the bottom of their seniority list,
while the Reno crews want credit for their years at the smaller
airline.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
