<SLUG> BC-INVEST-BASS-SKI-ART-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PICKED UP AND DUSTED OFF, A SKI CHAIN STARTS ANEW 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Vt., N.Y., N.H.)   (ART ADV: Graphic of why Robert Bass bailed out American Skiing is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 18)  
 (af)  
 By JULIE FLAHERTY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   By late last week, word had spread around the Killington area in
Vermont, where the economy depends upon the ski trade, that
something even better than a heavy snowfall was on its way. It was
a heavy downpour of cash.
</P>
<P>
   An investment group controlled by the Texas billionaire Robert
Bass had agreed to buy $150 million of convertible preferred stock
in the American Skiing Co., the debt-laden owner of the Killington
ski area and eight other resorts in New England and the Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, it seemed to be a peculiar move for someone as
sharp as Bass, considering that the stock market value of the
company is slightly less than $150 million.
</P>
<P>
   The deal gives the group, Oak Hill Capital Partners, a 48.5
percent stake in the company and infuses enough money into the ski
conglomerate to help it finish some of its projects and pay off
part of its more than $400 million in debt.
</P>
<P>
   The deal came in the nick of time. Coming out of a rough winter
of little snow and few skiers, American Skiing was forced to cut
the pay of some employees in Killington and elsewhere and to lay
off others. It also put an inn, a golf course and other assets up
for sale. With $95 million in accounts payable as of April, and a
$7 million interest payment due this month, scant summer revenues
would not fill the gap.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Wall Street firms that American Skiing had hired to pin
down money, Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette and ING Barings, were
coming up empty.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had shopped around a similar deal, a convertible
preferred, to the usual cast of suspects _ other financial buyers,
strategic partners and existing shareholders,'' said Christine
Lumpkins, a ski industry analyst with Bear Stearns.
</P>
<P>
   For more than two months, nothing came through, possibly because
American Skiing's chairman and founder, Leslie B. Otten, who had
built up the company from one resort in 1994, did not want to give
up control. He currently owns 50.1 percent of the stock, and the
restructuring will reduce his stake to 26.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   David O'Leary, who follows American Skiing for Alpha Equity
Research in Portsmouth, N.H., said the deal was a necessary one for
Otten, but not a good one for some American Skiing shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you bought the stock at $18, you've got to be pretty angry
that they are selling half of the company for $5.25,'' he said.
American Skiing made its initial public offering in November 1997
for $18 a share. The stock dropped to a low of $2.375 in April and
closed at $4.8125 on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Although the stock market value of the company was only $146
million on Friday, ``the value of all of those assets is worth more
than that stock is selling for,'' said John J. Rohs, an analyst
with Schroder &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   American Skiing has begun millions of dollars' worth of
development on hotels and time-share apartments at many of its
properties, including Steamboat in Colorado and the Canyons in
Utah, which must be completed for the 2002 Winter Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Hollis Rafkin-Sax, a spokeswoman for Oak Hill, said Bass and his
partners were long-term investors who saw potential in the resorts
under construction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many are less developed than their competitors, and real
growth opportunities,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary noted that Oak Hill stands to make at least $63.75
million from an 8.5 percent dividend over the next five years,
after which it must convert its preferred stock to common stock.
And if American Skiing has another bad winter this year, he said,
the arrangement means that ``Oak Hill gets paid before Les Otten
gets paid.''
</P>
</TEXT>
