<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVIS-RYAN-COL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEWITT COMES THROUGH   THE FURNACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ George Bernard Shaw knew a lot about a lot,
but he didn't know much about sport.
</P>
<P>
   Youth, he should be informed, is not always wasted on the young.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Bill Russell once famously observed, ``Experience don't
mean (expletive).''
</P>
<P>
   If you're good, you're good. It's just that every once in a
while, you've got to do something for the first time, and in this
case it just so happened that this was ponytailed Lleyton Hewitt's
first taste of Davis Cup competition.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict?
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't wait to get out there and play again,'' beamed the
Adelaide-bred 18-year-old. ``It was a fantastic atmosphere out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Backed by a vocal, yellow-clad, face-painted band of Aussie
``fanatics,'' Hewitt ignored both the oppressive heat and the
nationalistic hoopla and simply played a superior brand of tennis.
Experience played no role in what Lleyton Hewitt did to Todd Martin
at Longwood Cricket Club Friday. It was all about talent,
athleticism, heart, and a rare gift for the game.
</P>
<P>
   Two professional tennis players met in triple-figure heat on a
hard court in the first match of the Davis Cup quarterfinals
between Australia and the United States, and the 18-year Australian
just plain whupped the 29-year-old American, and whupped him good.
It was 6-4, 6-7 (1-7), 6-3, and then a crushing 6-0, and if it had
gone on any longer, Martin might have been forced to resort to a
Hingis-like underhand serve in order to keep the match alive.
</P>
<P>
   There may be sports in which age helps, but tennis is not
necessarily one of them. We are numbed to female precocity in the
realm of sport, but in tennis, even the men can be early bloomers.
Boris Becker won Wimbledon at age 17. John McEnroe did most of his
damage well before his 25th birthday. If you are young, you are
likely to be quick, and if you are quick in this game, you have a
huge advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Martin has a way to go before he gets ticketed for the tennis
glue factory, but his legs had 11 more years of wear and tear, and
it showed. He couldn't reach half the balls young Hewitt could, and
that wasn't even the worst part. The kid actually out-moxied him,
thrice dropping clever, point-winning lobs over the 6-foot-6-inch
Martin's head.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, there's a tennis brain up there, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can generalize about young guys,'' mused
Martin, ``or even old guys. Lleyton has great nerves. He seizes big
occasions and attacks. He never reacts negatively to any situation.
He's like Pete (Sampras) in that way. It's not because of youth;
it's a nature thing. A 17-year-old can choke on his tail, and a
40-year-old can be a great competitor.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that it never entered Hewitt's mind that he wasn't
going to win. Was he nervous? Absolutely. ``It was actually pretty
tough to go to sleep last night,'' he admitted. ``I was trying to
have an early night, but then really couldn't get to sleep for a
couple of hours. I just got on the phone, called the folks back
home and all the mates.''
</P>
<P>
   He was also comforted by the presence of the irrepressible John
Newcombe as team captain. ``Newc kept me pretty calm,'' Hewitt
said.
</P>
<P>
   That's all well and good, but eventually the moment comes when
the support system lets go, and then it's just you and the other
guy, in this case a not-so-mobile American whom you played in
Sydney six months ago and whose deficiencies dovetail nicely with
your strengths. Yes, Martin won that match, but you were hardly
intimidated. In your heart, you knew you could beat this guy, and
you knew how.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took a lot of confidence out of that match,'' Hewitt
confided. ``I was pretty tired at that time and just made the final
at Adelaide; that was the quarterfinals of Sydney and then I came
back and really gutsed that out. I think that was in the back of
Todd's mind _ that I was not going to go away out there today.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hewitt game plan Friday was simple, direct, and relentless:
make Martin move. ``His biggest weakness is a lack of mobility,''
Hewitt said. ``I tried to jag him side to side.''
</P>
<P>
   That tactic, when combined with a big serving day and better
overall stamina in the blast-furnace heat, led to what was, in
truth, a rout. Hewitt never lost serve. What he did lose was a
tiebreaker in the second set, but even that buoyed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Todd started to get a little tired during that
set,'' said Hewitt. ``I lost, but I came away with a positive
feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   As Martin pointed out, nothing fazes Hewitt, not even losing the
fourth game of the third set to four straight Martin aces. ``That
happens,'' Hewitt shrugged. ``You can always lose a game like that
to a big server. That's what makes (Andre) Agassi great. He'll give
up some aces to a (Mark) Philippoussis or an (Goran) Ivanisevic and
just keep right on going.''
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the Hewitt response was to win the next three
games, blowing Martin away with his own serve, breaking Martin with
a powerful forehand winner in the next game, and then serving a
40-30 ace to construct an insurmountable 5-2 lead in the pivotal
third set.
</P>
<P>
   So let's not worry about this 18-year-old stuff. That's a man
out there.
</P>
<P>
   So what we know is that he's definitely got game. What we will
need to find out is how badly he wants to be great, because not all
of them do. At the moment, he's just an enchanting growth stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's certainly better now than he was in January,'' assessed
Martin, who has surely seen this type of prodigy before. ``I assume
that progress will continue. But it's hard to say if he'll wind up
as a top-5 player. He will always have the ability to beat top
players. But whether he will be a great player week in, week out
remains to be seen.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a conversation for another day. Friday, when his country
and his mates needed him, Lleyton Hewitt was a great player. To
quote another American coach of note, in the context of this
competition, the Australian future is now.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-99 1942EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
