<HEADER>
A3181 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRANCE-REMEMBER-ART-N     07-16 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-REMEMBER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A BREAK WITH TRADITION, FRANCE RECALLS PAST ATROCITIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ ``It is good for everyone to know how to forget,'' the
French historian Ernest Renan observed in 1882, and to preserve
national unity France has often chosen to overlook the most
uncomfortable moments of its past.
</P>
<P>
   But not President Jacques Chirac, who four years ago boldly
acknowledged French complicity in the Nazi-ordered roundup of
thousands of French Jews on July 16, 1942, in the Velodrome d'Hiver
stadium in Paris. And on Friday he went to a village that the
Germans wiped out in 1944 to say that barbarity was possible ``in
all countries and in all times.''
</P>
<P>
   Chirac inaugurated a visitor center in Oradour-sur-Glane, a
village whose ruins are preserved as the SS ``Das Reich'' Division
left them after killing 642 men, women and children on June 10,
1944. In his remarks, he put Oradour in a long list of other
brutalities beginning with the massacres of Protestants in Catholic
France in 1572 and continuing through the killings of Kosovo
Albanian civilians by Serbian forces in Kosovo this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Despite revulsion over the Holocaust, genocide had been
attempted again in Rwanda, he reminded his country. And like
Oradour in France and Lidice in Czechoslovakia, other places like
Srebrenica in Bosnia and the Sabra and Shatila Palestinian refugee
camps in Lebanon have become symbols of human brutality, he said,
alluding to the failure of European peacekeeping forces to stop
Bosnian Serbs from killing Muslims in 1995 and the failure of
Israeli forces occupying Beirut to prevent killings in the
Palestinian camps in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oradour and all the martyrs remind us that barbarity is
possible in all countries and in all times,'' Chirac said. ``Europe
has no higher meaning than to be the contrary of what happened in
Oradour by incarnating a dream of peace and a humanist ideal.''
</P>
<P>
   The SS division that laid waste to Oradour included volunteers
and conscripts from Alsace, a French territory annexed by the
Germans when they invaded. Nine years later, the citizens of
Oradour returned the decorations that had been awarded to the
village by the postwar French government after 14 Alsatians were
first tried and then, after mass protests in Alsace, the Parliament
in Paris voted to give 13 of them amnesty. An Alsatian volunteer
who was sentenced to death was later pardoned.
</P>
<P>
   As an American author, Sarah Farmer, pointed out in her book on
Oradour, ``Martyred Village,'' published by the University of
California Press this year, even Gen. Charles de Gaulle, the
Resistance leader and Chirac's political mentor, had pleaded for
understanding of Alsatian sensitivities in the interests of
preserving national unity.
</P>
<P>
   That concern remained paramount in France as long as Francois
Mitterrand, Chirac's predecessor, was in office; Mitterrand himself
had served in the French collaborationist government in Vichy
during part of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   But Chirac's speech in 1995 acknowledging French guilt, and the
trial and conviction of a prominent postwar official, Maurice
Papon, in 1997 and 1998 for crimes against humanity as a Vichy
functionary in Bordeaux, changed the climate.
</P>
<P>
   Last year was the first time elected officials in Oradour, where
2,000 people now live in a new village that was built beside the
ruins of the old one after the war, agreed to let the mayor of
Strasbourg, the Alsatian capital, come and make a gesture of
reconciliation. The French state provided $2 million of the nearly
$10 million it cost to build the visitor center, and gave more than
$200,000 last year to help keep the ruins from crumbling into
oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Lamaud, a guide in the village whose sister, who was 4 at
the time of the massacre, was among the people killed by the Nazis,
tells visitors the lesson of Oradour is the evil of fanaticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the young people among you will learn the lesson and
not let yourselves be indoctrinated,'' he told one group recently.
``What happened here can happen anywhere, and indeed it continues
in other places even today.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamaud, born a year after the massacre, said his parents were at
a wedding in a nearby village on the day of the massacre.
``Otherwise, I wouldn't be here,'' he explained.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
