<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3187 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOLE-INITIATIVE17-COX     07-16 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLE-INITIATIVE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dole wants more limits on Net
 &HT;    By Alan Judd
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Trailing badly in the polls and in fund-raising,
Republican presidential candidate Elizabeth Dole brought her
campaign _ and a new campaign issue _ to Atlanta on Friday,
advocating federal restrictions on access to Internet pornography
in public libraries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Librarians shouldn't use federal tax money to put pornography
on their shelves, and they shouldn't put it on their desktops or
laptops,'' Dole said during a news conference outside the
Atlanta-Fulton County Public Library's main branch.
</P>
<P>
   Dole, who appeared in Atlanta the same day as fellow GOP
contender Gary Bauer, endorsed a congressional proposal to require
pornography filters on computers used by children at the 26,000
U.S. schools and libraries that have received $1.7 billion in
federal grants for Internet connections. But she said the
legislation doesn't go far enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under this bill ... pornography is off limits to children, but
it's readily accessible to adults,'' Dole said. ``That's wrong.
That's not what libraries are for.''
</P>
<P>
   Librarians said Dole is trying to solve a problem that doesn't
exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Libraries have appropriate-use policies for the Internet, the
same way they have other policies governing appropriate library
use,'' said Linda Wallace, a spokeswoman for the American Library
Association. ``It's not a widespread problem. That's not what
people use libraries for.''
</P>
<P>
   About 15 percent of U.S. libraries have installed software on
their public-access computer terminals that blocks access to online
pornography. But the association contends that the software doesn't
always work as intended; one program, it says, blocks such sites as
one devoted to professional golfer Fred Couples and another on Mars
exploration (the Web address innocuously contains the word
``sex'').
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the Atlanta-Fulton County library did not respond
to requests for an interview Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Dole was undeterred by questions about the necessity of the
pornography ban, as she was by questions about her political
viability. A recent poll of Republican voters by CNN and USA Today
showed her running 51 percentage points behind the front-runner,
Texas Gov. George W. Bush. Through June 30, she had raised $3.5
million, including $75,600 in Georgia. Her total is less than
one-tenth of Bush's $37.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point in time, I'd say probably less than 5 percent of
the American public is even engaged in presidential politics,''
Dole said. ``I think that people, when they get involved in the
campaign, are going to be looking at who has the most experience to
bring to the table, not who has the most money.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauer, who held a news conference Friday outside Fort McPherson
south of Atlanta to advocate higher defense spending, noted that
his campaign had raised $3.4 million, almost as much as Dole's.
</P>
<P>
   But he said: ``Politics is about more than money. If it wasn't,
we would now be finishing Ross Perot's second term.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Bill Montgomery contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
