<DOCNO> NYT19990716.0265 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3199 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-U.S.-ART-575&AMP;A     07-16 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-U.S.-ART-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PRAISES BARAK'S COMMITMENT TO PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 1-888-603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(th) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The path to reconciliation in the Middle East can
fairly be said to have begun 21 years ago at Camp David, where
Egypt's Anwar Sadat and Israel's Menachem Begin agreed to end their
nations' enmity and live in peace as neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   The next recent stretch of that tortured road to peace may have
been mapped out at Camp David over the past 24 hours, as Israel's
new prime minister, Ehud Barak, described for President Clinton the
steps he intends to take to reach a comprehensive settlement with
the Palestinians and his Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton telephoned from a political trip to Iowa on Friday
afternoon to describe how he and Barak lingered Thursday night in
the cabin where Sadat and Begin concluded their bargain. Barak, the
most decorated soldier in Israel's history, pored over documents
from that time, many with the handwritten annotations of President
Jimmy Carter, who served as midwife for the Egyptian-Israeli
accord.
</P>
<P>
   ``He read it all with great care,'' Clinton said. ``He talked
about Sadat, what a gutsy thing he did when he came to Jerusalem to
talk to the Knesset even before the agreement was signed. He
described the scene and what an important effect it had.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he declined to talk in detail about what he had heard,
Clinton said he was moved by Barak's commitment to peace and by his
awareness of the risks it entails. Sadat was assassinated by Muslim
radicals in 1981. Barak's mentor, Yitzhak Rabin, was murdered in
1995 by an Israeli who opposed his efforts to make peace with the
Arabs.
</P>
<P>
   The visit to the cabin where the Sadat-Begin talks took place
was a part of a long evening for Clinton, Barak and their wives.
They talked over a dinner of cold fennel soup and fish for more
than two hours, then Clinton and Barak spent three and a half hours
together, breaking up well past midnight.
</P>
<P>
   They spoke of their families and their politics, history and
health, war and peace, Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We laughed about a lot of things,'' Clinton said, including
what he called the ``peculiarities of politics.'' He would not
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that despite Barak's reputation for dourness, he is
a ``generally cheerful person.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton believes that personalities and relationships can
fundamentally alter history, and he said he is hopeful that this
positive early start with Barak can help lead to substantial, rapid
progress in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   The president said he stood ready to do whatever is necessary _
even if that means stepping out of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Barak said this week that the United States had played an overly
intrusive role in Middle East talks over the last three years. He
said he would welcome American participation as a ``facilitator''
of dialogue, but not as an arbitrator of disputes or enforcer of
agreements.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Friday that he understood Barak's position.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best peace process is one where critical decisions are
made with parties that have to live with the consequences,''
Clinton said. ``When they hit a bump in the road, someone
facilitates the next step.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you want is for the U.S. to be a genuine facilitator, to
make whatever helpful suggestions we can and be there to provide
whatever support we can for making the most difficult decisions. I
think that is the right thing to do. We can be honest mediators,
fair and sensitive to concerns of both sides, of all the parties.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Both Clinton and Barak hope that a close political and personal
bond between the Israeli leader and the American president can be
forged once again.
</P>
<P>
   Relations were cool to the point of frost under Benjamin
Netanyahu, the former prime minister, who made no secret of his
resentment of American interference in Israeli affairs. The Clinton
administration made little effort to conceal its desire for Barak's
electoral victory over Netanyahu in May.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was warm in his assessment of Barak, saying, ``I like
him. I can get along with just about everybody. The main thing is
the Israeli voters basically said, `We want you to pursue peace
with security and we want it concluded.' Because of his
distinguished military career, they were saying to him, `We trust
you to try to put this deal together, to protect our security but
complete the peace process if you can.'''
</P>
<P>
   An Israeli official who spoke with Barak after his White House
and Camp David meetings with the president said the prime minister
was ``most satisfied'' with his discussions with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Barak described the two couples' dinner as ``intimate and
warm,'' and he said the Baraks were quite taken by the beauty and
serenity of Camp David, in Maryland's Catoctin Mountains about 80
miles northwest of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   After the dinner, the president and prime minister sat down
privately as their wives engaged in a talk of their own. Mrs.
Clinton and Mrs. Barak share an interest in women's health issues
and in programs for troubled youths. Mrs. Clinton said she would
like to visit Israel soon, according to the Israeli official who
was briefed on their discussion.
</P>
<P>
   They also spoke of their children. Chelsea Clinton is a student
at Stanford University; the Baraks have three daughters, one of
whom works at the New York law firm Skadden, Arps, Slate, Meagher &AMP;
Flom. The other two live in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The Baraks and the Clintons had a quick breakfast Friday at Camp
David before flying off in different directions, Clinton to Iowa
for political appearances, Barak to Washington and then to New
York.
</P>
<P>
   They resume their visit on Sunday, at an official dinner at the
White House for 400 guests.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I took away from it, frankly, was what a lively
intelligence this guy has and what incredible energy he has,''
Clinton said. ``He said a lot of people know a lot of facts about
history but often lose the forest for the trees. You have to
understand the big patterns in history and in politics to make the
right decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You know he is a passionate patriot,'' Clinton concluded. ``It
was fascinating to hear him talk about the history of Israel. I
could have stayed up all night listening to him, but we both got
tired.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-99 2009EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
