<DOCNO> NYT19990716.0266 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3202 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECON-COLUMN-$ADV18-NY     07-16 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-COLUMN-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT THE DESK, OFF THE CLOCK AND BELOW STATISTICAL RADAR  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 18) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mich., N.Y., Md.)   (af)  
 By LOUIS UCHITELLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Young assistant professors at Cornell University once had time
to paint their own houses. Now nights and weekends are devoted to
research and writing as they struggle to win tenure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Painting your own house is not something you even think about
anymore,'' said Robert Frank, a tenured Cornell professor today who
did his own painting as an assistant in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Software engineers at Xerox are similarly afflicted. A few
sometimes get their work done by 5 p.m., says Leslie Perlow, a
University of Michigan sociologist who has studied software
engineers at Xerox and other technology companies. But they dare
not go home, fearful that their bosses might conclude they are
shirkers who stick to the easiest assignments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know how to assess the value of a knowledge worker in
these new technologies, so we value those who work into the
night,'' Ms. Perlow said.
</P>
<P>
   There is much debate over whether Americans are spending more
time at work or at leisure, and which activities to call ``work''
and which ``leisure.'' But two things are clear: People on fixed
salaries for a 35-hour or 40-hour week are the fastest-growing
segment of the work force, and increasingly they work beyond their
weekly schedules for no extra pay.
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Department's surveys have found that workers who say
they toiled 49 hours or more a week have risen to nearly 19 percent
of the private-sector work force, from 13 percent in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Even John Robinson, a University of Maryland sociologist who has
challenged such data, is beginning to come around. He argues that
survey respondents tend to exaggerate when asked to recall how many
hours they have worked, and he prefers data from time diaries, in
which each day's activities are recorded that day. His diary-based
figures showed Americans spending fewer and fewer hours at work
until 1985, but gradually more since then.
</P>
<P>
   People are still exaggerating, Robinson said: they tell
pollsters they worked, say, 60 hours in a week when they actually
worked only 50. ``But there are more people now in the exaggerating
class,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   No sector of the work force is growing more rapidly than workers
on fixed salaries: managers, administrators, engineers,
technicians, lawyers, researchers, programmers, consultants. They
constitute roughly 40 percent of all workers today, up from 34
percent in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Such workers rarely get overtime pay, particularly those earning
more than $40,000 a year. And the changing nature of work in
America adds to the pressure on them to work more hours.
</P>
<P>
   The new pressures include some obvious ones: more competition;
more people vying for fewer tenured slots, like those at Cornell;
the reluctance of corporations to offer job security over a
lifetime. But there is also what sociologists describe as a shift
away from routine, repetitive work that can be packaged in
eight-hour days. The new mode is ``project'' work that must be done
in a hurry, often without clearly defined guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Senior managers at the technology companies studied by Ms.
Perlow often bid on software projects by promising to deliver in
two months when everyone knows three months are required, she said.
But even in routine trades like commercial baking, the new mode of
work appears.
</P>
<P>
   For example, many bakeries once filled standing orders from
neighborhood stores, said Richard Sennett, a New York University
sociologist who has studied bakeries. The work was routine.
Supervisors and workers knew their daily tasks. But now many
bakeries vie for orders from all over a city, and the supervisors
find themselves constantly changing work schedules or ingredients,
tasks that add hours to their workdays.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are manual labor in this process, it shows up in your
hourly wages,'' Sennett said. ``If you are a salaried employee, the
sky is the limit.''
</P>
<P>
   The growing number of hours worked by salaried workers is not
yet reflected in some key Labor Department statistics, leaving the
impression that America's economic performance is better than it
probably is. For example, the nation's productivity _ output for
each hour worked _ has risen rapidly in recent years, suggesting
that corporate America is becoming more efficient.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bureau of Labor Statistics calculates productivity using
the hours reported by employers, not employees. For salaried
workers, the bureau often is working with scheduled hours, not
actual hours. What's more, the bureau assumes that supervisory
workers in the service sector _ a category where hard numbers are
lacking _ work roughly the same amount of time as hourly,
nonsupervisory workers.
</P>
<P>
   The upshot is that the hours worked by as many as 16 percent of
all workers are probably underreported, bureau officials said.
Undercounting hours has the effect of exaggerating the nation's
productivity growth and hourly wages.
</P>
<P>
   That is the arithmetic. The psychological aspect is more
ingrained. ``We have incorporated the longer hours into our
self-image,'' said Stephen Rose, a labor economist, ``and we have
come to accept that to be really successful you have to work a lot
of hours.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
