<HEADER>
A3226 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOW-CHEMICAL-PLAN-ART     07-16 0452
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW-CHEMICAL-PLAN-ART-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL-WORLD LESSONS FROM A DRY RUN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mich., Texas)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 18)  
 (Eds: This is a sidebar to DOW-CHEMICAL-POLLUTE)  
 (af)  
 By BARNABY J. FEDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The novel collaboration between Dow Chemical and
environmentalists in Midland, Mich., to curb toxic chemical
releases, can be traced back to a 1991 gripe session over drinks in
a bar in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Greer, a policy analyst at the Natural Resources Defense
Council, and Richard A. Olson, then an environmental manager at
Dow, had been among the lobbyists locked in clause-by-clause combat
over proposed hazardous waste disposal regulations that the
government began developing in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had spent the last year fighting over the definition of
solid waste and agreed that neither of us was doing anything for
the environment,'' Ms. Greer recalled. They felt that the
regulations were not only too complex but also misguided,
addressing wastes after they were created instead of preventing
them.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Greer did not believe Olson, though, when he contended that
existing regulations actually prevented Dow from reducing its waste
production. She asked for real-world proof. And after some internal
debate, Dow and the NRDC agreed to study the company's polyurethane
factory at La Porte, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The study had many elements of the Michigan project, including
the central role of Bill Bilkovitch, an outside consultant hired to
ferret out pollution-reduction opportunities. It found that
pollution could be reduced profitably, and that business practices
_ not regulations _ were preventing the reductions. Still, none of
Bilkovitch's proposals were adopted.
</P>
<P>
   One weakness was that the proposals were filtered through the
factory's environmental, health and safety managers rather than
taken directly to the business managers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In retrospect, it looks amateurish,'' Ms. Greer reflected.
``We had no direct contact with the people who have to write the
checks.''
</P>
<P>
   David T. Buzzelli, who was a vice president in charge of
environmental affairs at Dow, told Ms. Greer that he thought the
company could do better if a project was designed with action
rather than research in mind. And Dow has proved that point in
Midland, Ms. Greer said. Now she is wondering how to insure
progress where environmental groups are not so directly involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to think about what kind of regulation might make it
happen with less hand-holding,'' she said. ``It's not obvious to me
yet.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
