<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3234 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TWINS-SEPARATED-BOS &LR;      07-16 1205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TWINS-SEPARATED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON DOCTOR SUCCESSFULY SEPARATES JOINED TWINS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- When they first arrived at Children's Hospital in
March, identical twins Hassan and Hussein Mohamed were a cranky,
crying pair of infants, said Dr. Hardy Hendren, the legendary
pediatric surgeon who treated them.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all,'' noted Hendren recently, ``they were in each
others' face all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   They had no choice. The infants, born last December, were joined
front-to-front from their chests to their genital areas. Only by
arching their backs could they gain some individual space. Inside
their bonded bodies, their abdominal tissues were fused, their
urinary tracts were tangled, and they had but one penis between
them.
</P>
<P>
   But in late June, the boys lay apparently content in individual
carriers being readied for the trip to their home in Abu Dhabi.
They now seemed much like any other six-month-olds: happy and
mellow, with shining eyes and cheerful gurgles.
</P>
<P>
   Hassan and Hussein were separated on April 5 in a complex,
25-hour operation led by Hendren, known for his skillful repairs of
some of the most severe birth defects.
</P>
<P>
   The dramatic case wasn't disclosed until Friday because the
parents agreed to release the story first to media in Abu Dhabi
upon their return.
</P>
<P>
   It was Hendren who performed the first separation of Siamese
twins in Boston 30 years ago at Massachusetts General Hospital.
Those twins, Maureen Ann and Marie Elizabeth Kobierski of Danvers,
Mass., were joined in a similar fashion as Hassan and Hussein. The
Kobierskis are still living in the Danvers area.
</P>
<P>
   The name Siamese twins comes from the most famous of
``conjoined'' male twins, Chang and Eng, born in Siam of Chinese
parents in 1811. They became exhibits in P.T. Barnum's circus for
many years; although never separated, they married and fathered a
total of 22 children. They died within 2 hours of each other in
1874.
</P>
<P>
   Separating conjoined twins remains a rare procedure. Hendren, a
former World War II Navy fighter pilot, has now separated 15 pairs
in his long career. He noted that his main operating room nurse at
the time of the Kobierskis' operation, Dorothy Estes, was on hand
to assist him in the surgery on Hassan and Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   Separating Siamese twins is always a difficult and risky
undertaking. The operation to free Hassan and Hussein from each
other was especially complex because the urinary and reproductive
organs were so abnormally situated.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are `thinking' cases,'' said Hendren, who at age 73 is
still renowned for his stamina and creative problem-solving in
treating the most devastating birth defects.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to see what you have to work with, and think about
what you're going to do. It's improvisation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The team led by Hendren included the chief surgical resident,
Dr. Ann Fischer, and the chief urological resident, Dr. John Park.
</P>
<P>
   The gruelling operation began at 7:30 a.m. April 5 and didn't
conclude until 8:30 a.m. the following day. ``You can't stop until
you get all the parts figured out,'' said Hendren, who said from
the surgeons' point of view it was like ``doing two liver
transplants back to back.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the twins' hearts were not joined. Still, Hendren
and his team had to separate the two livers and two stomachs as
well as two small intestines. They divided the single large
intestine and gave half to each infant.
</P>
<P>
   The most time-consuming part, said Hendren, was cutting and
reconnecting the ureters _ small tubes that carry urine from the
kidneys to the bladder _ which had been formed in the wrong
configuration, and solving the problems created by the absence of
one of the penises.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the surgical team needed to use a large expanse of
artificial skin to cover the extensive openings in the infants'
chests and abdomens resulting from their separation. The artificial
covering was removed as the infants' skin was stretched over the
wound, leaving only a long scar on each child.
</P>
<P>
   In a Solomonic decision, Hendren divided the sole penis
lengthways, giving one half to each boy: they'll have to undergo
considerable reconstructive surgery in the future, but the surgeon
believes they will have functioning male organs.
</P>
<P>
   The parents, Abdulla and Fatma Mohamed, learned that their twins
were conjoined when Fatma, 27, was four months pregnant. Siamese
twins are a rare event, occurring when a single fertilized egg
fails to completely divide to generate identical twins. Conjoined
twins can be attached to each other in many configurations.
Frequently, one or both twins die. But in some cases, they can be
freed from each other and live relatively normal lives.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking through an interpreter, Fatma said she believed that
God would guide their future. And she said that some family members
told her _ wrongly _ that the twins would separate naturally while
still in the womb.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors in Abu Dhabi, in the United Arab Emirates, initially
thought they could perform the surgery but later declined and
recommended the couple come to the United States. The US Embassy in
Washington steered them to Children's Hospital in Boston, the
couple said.
</P>
<P>
   Abdulla, who is a policeman, and Fatma said that the costs of
the surgery and transportation were being paid by the Abu Dhabi
government, and they are thankful to God and to Sheik Khalifa ben
Zayed Al Nahayan, the son of the president of the United Arab
Emirates. The son approved the couple's trip and authorized
government funds to pay all expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The successful outcome also came as good news to parents
belonging to Conjoined Twins International, a three-year-old
support group in Prescott, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have a separation in which both twins lives is very rare,''
said Will Degeraty, whose daughter, Michelle Roderick, had Siamese
twins that were separated in California three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The support organization includes about 40 sets of twins and
their families, and the group is in touch with some individual
survivors, said Degeraty. In four cases, the twins remain
conjoined, and the other 36 have been separated, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Conjoined twins occur in about 4 of every 400,000 births, he
said. ``Of those four, three will be born dead. Of the remainder,
about 70 percent will die or go through life with serious medical
problems. The 30 percent that are left is what we are dealing with
today,'' said Degeraty.
</P>
<P>
   His daughter said that her twins, Shawna and Janelle, nearly
three years old, are doing fine. ``They know they were together _
we have pictures on the wall of when they were together.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Shawna points to them and says, this is me and my sister when
were together,'' said Roderick. ``They have pride in the fact that
this is how they were.''
</P>
<P>
   But some of the stories are more grim, as in cases when one or
both twins dies. Degeraty said the support group knows of one woman
in her 20s who was the sole survivor of a pair of conjoined twins.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still a big loss for her,'' said Degeraty. ``She picks a
rose every day and puts it on her bed _ that's her sister for
her.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-99 2032EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
