<DOCNO> NYT19990716.0279 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3236 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-PBS-DONORS-BOS &LR;      07-16 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PBS-DONORS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW REVELATION UPS CONCERN OVER USE OF PBS DONOR LISTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A public television station in California admitted
Friday it exchanged donor lists with not only the Democratic
National Committee but also Democratic Senator Barbara Boxer,
heightening concern on Capitol Hill over a pattern of list-swapping
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Republicans in Congress increased their calls
for a formal investigative hearing, and Representative W.J.
``Billy'' Tauzin, chairman of the subcommittee that oversees
funding for public broadcasting, expanded his inquiry into
list-swapping to include stations in Los Angeles, Chicago and New
York.
</P>
<P>
   WGBH-TV, the Boston public television channel, and two other
stations admitted to list-swapping with political parties earlier
in the week. Only WNET in New York said its swapping included
Republican groups as well as Democratic ones.
</P>
<P>
   But a spokesman for Tauzin, a Louisiana Republican, said the
latest disclosure that KQED-TV in San Francisco worked directly
with a politician _ swapping donor names with Boxer's reelection
campaign twice in 1997 _ was the most troubling so far. Spokesman
Ken Johnson called it the equivalent of ``putting a billboard on
your head.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are beginning to hear disturbing reports that these lists
are being brokered to individual politicians around the country,''
he said. ``This may shake the foundations of donor-swapping
practices nationwide.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Boxer declined to comment. David Shaw, a
spokesman for KQED, said Friday's discovery of list-swapping with
the Boxer campaign, along with two exchanges of donor names with
the Democratic National Committee in 1996, prompted a review of
station policy. KQED officials immediately announced a tightening
of their rules and will no longer allow the station's list broker
to swap names with any political party or advocacy group, Shaw
said.
</P>
<P>
   KQED and several other stations also swapped donor names with
liberal-leaning advocacy groups, according to a ``list card,'' the
profile sheet used by list brokers to promote an organization's
demographics. KQED, for example, has swapped lists with the
American Civil Liberties Union. WETA-TV in Washington, in addition
to swapping lists with the Democrats, has also shared information
with Handgun Control Inc. and Planned Parenthood.
</P>
<P>
   The practice of trading donor lists between public stations and
political parties was thrown into the national spotlight on
Tuesday, when news that WGBH had swapped lists with the DNC was
circulated at a House Commerce subcommittee meeting. Republican
members immediately blocked plans to debate a $525 million funding
increase for the national public broadcasting system. Now, that
funding might be be sharply reduced.
</P>
<P>
   The Corporation for Public Broadcasting, the umbrella
organization that receives federal funding and distributes it to
member stations across the country, has asked its inspector general
to investigate the list-swapping.
</P>
<P>
   Several House Republicans said they also want the Internal
Revenue Service to examine whether the stations violated federal
tax laws, which prohibit tax-exempt groups from working exclusively
with one political party and not the other.
</P>
<P>
   The full extent of the list-swapping continued to unfold as the
House subcommittee prepares to hold a hearing Tuesday to question
various officials, including Robert Coonrod, president of the
Corporation for Public Broadcasting. House Republicans had
initially planned to call WGBH officials as the first witnesses.
After it became clear that at least one station had exchanged lists
with Republican groups, the panel changed plans and wants to
question the whole system and not just one station.
</P>
<P>
   As of Friday night, WGBH officials were not expected to attend.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Edward J. Markey of Massachusetts, the top
Democrat on the subcommittee, said he told Tauzin of the bipartisan
nature of the controversy. With both parties involved, Markey said,
there was a greater likelihood the subcommittee could reconsider
the funding increase for public broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might be able to return to the status quo,'' Markey said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But that seemed unlikely Friday night, as Republicans continued
to focus on the majority of list-swapping incidents that involved
Democrats. The news that Boxer's Senate campaign committee was
among the organizations that used KQED's donor list only fueled the
controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The DNC is a political organization trying to elect Democrats,
and Barbara Boxer is one Democrat trying to elect a Democrat,''
said Republican National Committee spokesman Michael Collins.
``What is apparent is that the Democratic Party regards public
broadcasting as a branch office, as a wholly owned subsidiary.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a spokeswoman for WBUR, a public radio station in
Boston, said the station has followed its longstanding policy of
not sharing its donor lists with any organizations. The Republican
National Committee and the Massachusetts Republican Party also said
they had not swapped lists with any public broadcasting stations.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, a spokeswoman for WGBH said the station had
dismissed its list broker, the outside manager who oversaw the
trading of some 32,000 donor names with the DNC between 1993 and
February 1999. The spokeswoman would not identify the firm and
declined to comment further.
</P>
<P>
   Alan D. Solomont, the former DNC finance chairman and a major
contributor to the Democratic Party as well as a member of the WGBH
board, said that compared with most campaign fund-raisers, ``GBH is
a prude.''
</P>
<P>
   Solomont _ whose wife, Susan Lewis, worked at WGBH for 15 years
and was last employed there full-time as its director of
development _ said if there had been any desire by WGBH to link
itself with the Democratic Party, station officials would have
approached him first. Despite their ties to both WGBH and the
Democratic Party, both Solomont and his wife said in interviews
this week that they never saw any partisan activity on the part of
the public station.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has absolutely nothing to do with any political
collusion,'' Solomont said. ``Direct mail is a business unto
itself. People trade lists all the time. There was a prohibition
against trading lists with a political organization at 'GBH and it
shouldn't have been done, but it was a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, people will try to now exploit this for
political reasons when there's really nothing of that nature here.
And a very, very valuable asset _ public broadcasting _ will be
damaged as a result.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
