<SLUG> BC-NAZI-HUNTERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL WOULD EXPAND HUNT FOR RIGHTS VIOLATORS IN US 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE FAINARU  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A bill introduced by Senator Patrick J. Leahy, a
Vermont Democrat, would expand the role of the US Justice
Department's anti-Nazi unit to hunt down other alleged war
criminals whose presence in the United States was documented in a
three-part Globe investigation last May.
</P>
<P>
   The Office of Special Investigations, which was created in 1979,
is authorized to pursue only Nazi war criminals who slipped into
the United States after World War II. But Leahy said the Globe's
findings demonstrated the need to expand the unit's
responsibilities to cover human rights offenders from countries
such as Haiti, Somalia and the former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just do not want the United States to be seen as a safe
haven for these war criminals,'' Leahy said in an interview. ``In
fact, I want the United States to be as inhospitable a land as
they'll face anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Leahy, the leading Democrat on the Senate Judiciary Committee,
said he expected the committee to hold hearings on the bill later
this year. No hearings have been scheduled, but officials said they
are hopeful the committee could take up the issue in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Leahy's pursuit of the bill stems in part from a Globe story
reporting that a 39-year-old Bosnian refugee living outside of
Burlington, Vt., is a former member of a notorious Bosnian Serb
paramilitary unit that has been accused of atrocities in the former
Yugoslavia. Zijad Music has denied his involvement with the group,
known as El Manijakos. He is under investigation by the Immigration
and Naturalization Service.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe also reported that a broad range of other immigrants,
including Haitians, Somalis and Salvadorans, have been granted
residency in the United States despite substantial evidence of
their involvement in human rights crimes, including torture. In
some cases, the alleged war criminals entered the United States
with the knowledge and assistance of US officals.
</P>
<P>
   The INS responded to the Globe investigation by tightening the
screening procedures for some 20,000 refugees admitted to the US
during the recent crisis in Kosovo. But INS officials contend that
they lacked sufficient resources to pursue human rights criminals
in the US and are hampered by immigration laws that make it
difficult to deport them once they are discovered.
</P>
<P>
   As introduced by Leahy, the Anti-Atrocity Alien Deportation Act
would:
</P>
<P>
   -- Allow US immigration officials to deny entry and deport all
``aliens who have engaged in acts of torture abroad.'' The
Immigration and Nationality Act is currently limited to
participants in Nazi persecutions and aliens who have engaged in
genocide.
</P>
<P>
   -- Greatly expand the role of OSI to investigate, deport,
prosecute and revoke the citizenship of any immigrant who
participated in torture abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1979, OSI has been regarded by its supporters as the most
effective anti-Nazi unit in the world. Information gathered by the
unit has helped strip 61 Nazi persecutors of their US citizenship,
has led to the deportation of 49 others and denial of entry to
another 150 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their mandate is limited,'' said Leahy. ``I don't want to
detract from that. But there are new Nazis.''
</P>
<P>
   Leahy said the bill would provide for additional funding for OSI
to meet its new responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation about the future of OSI has increased in recent
years as the remaining Nazi collaborators have continued to age.
The unit is currently handling some 20 cases, but OSI officials
acknowledge that at some point the unit will become obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights monitors have suggested expanding OSI's role to
address the growing problem of alleged human rights criminals who
have used the United States as safe haven from more recent global
conflicts. The scope of the problem is unclear. The Center for
Justice and Accountability, a San Francisco group funded by Amnesty
International, has compiled information on dozens of cases and
believes the numbers may be in the thousands.
</P>
<P>
   INS official believe the problem is less serious, but is
growing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-99 2038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
