<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRANIAN-PROTEST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYMPATHIZERS PROTEST RIGHTS CRACKDOWN IN IRAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EUN LEE KOH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Reacting to the crackdown on pro-democracy
supporters in Iran, thousands of Iranian-Americans demonstrated
near the Capitol Friday to decry the Islamic regime.
</P>
<P>
   The rally followed a weeklong wave of protests against Islamic
rule in Iran, where scores of students were arrested in a bloody
clash with government police.
</P>
<P>
   Waving Iranian flags and singing Iran's national anthem,
protesters called for the overthrow of President Mohammad Khatami,
the moderate Iranian leader who denounced the student protests.
Khatami, elected two years ago in a landslide, had been expected to
push for change in his country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all here in support of democracy,'' said Farzad Ghorbi,
37, of Boston. ``I owe it to my family. I owe it to my people. I
owe it to all the people in Iran who suffer everyday in the name of
freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   At the rally, several members of Congress urged the Clinton
administration to support Mujahedeen Khalq, the resistance group
that the State Department has labeled a terrorist organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``The State Department and the adminstration would like us to
believe this fairy tale,'' said Representative Ileana Ros-Lehtinen,
a Florida Republican. ``But siding with the tyrants who are
terrorizing the people of Iran will go absolutely nowhere.''
</P>
<P>
   While both Iranian leaders and the Clinton administration call
the Mujahedeen terrorists, Ros-Lehtinen said the majority of
Congress supports the resistance group.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Robert G. Torricelli, a New Jersey Democrat, told the
crowd he believed democracy will eventually win in Iran.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people want to stop this dictatorship in Iran and they
will succeed,'' he said. ``We stand with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Mina Entezari, 37, who came from Phoenix just to attend the
demonstration, said, ``The events of last week is proof that we
can't work with Khatami. He has shown his true self to us and we
know that he does not stand for what we stand for.''
</P>
<P>
   Tanya Kianfard, 17, of Atlanta summed up the protest: ``All we
are doing is fighting for freedom _ the one thing we don't have in
Iran. We want to free our country.''
</P>
<P>
   The clash between the Islamic fundamentalists and pro-democratic
students began July 8 after the shutdown of a liberal newspaper in
Tehran sparked a massive student protest. Security forces stormed
dormitories at Tehran University, throwing students out of windows.
As many as eight students died.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrations spurred a counterprotest by supporters of
Islamic rule, who marched in the streets of Tehran on Wednesday to
back Khatami and Iran's supreme leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's protest organizers criticized the US government for its
inaction following the student demonstrations in Tehran.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are the leaders in this country blind?'' said Soona Samsami,
of the Paris-based National Council for Resistance of Iran, the
group that oversees the Mujahedeen and the National Liberation
Army. ``How many years does this have to go on? How many people
have to die, be hanged in public and persecuted for the leaders
here to pay attention to what is happening in Iran?''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials, who have been trying to establish
dialogue with Khatami with little success, said they were concerned
about any appearance of US interference in Iran.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-99 2039EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
