<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3246 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-BRIEFS-$ADV18-NYT     07-16 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BRIEFS-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PEOPLE AND PERSONALITIES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 18) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   But What if It Turns Out It Only Runs on Windows? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bill Gates' golden touch reaches well beyond his personal
wealth, which edged up by $6 billion-plus last week to more than
$100 billion. It was also a good week for the stray cats and dogs
in Redmond, Ore., who may soon be sleeping more comfortably thanks
to the allure of a car Gates once owned.
</P>
<P>
   The burgundy Lexus LS400 sedan, a 1990 model driven 82,000
miles, was auctioned over the Web site of Carscene.com, with the
proceeds to benefit the Humane Society of Redmond, a fast-growing
town of 12,000 in central Oregon that is not to be confused with
the similarly named Washington State hometown of a certain software
enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   The car, making its second appearance in a charity auction since
Gates gave it up in 1995, was donated by Philip and Jo Weigand of
Powell Butte, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   Weigand bought the car a year and a half ago for $18,000 at a
society benefit in Portland, Ore., for Pacific Crest Outward Bound.
This time, a bidder in Pennsylvania made the top offer of $38,000.
Weigand said he would donate the proceeds, minus some expenses, to
the humane society, where his wife works in the thrift shop on
Mondays. The group, which is facing a potential rent increase to
$20,000 a year, from a nominal $1, hopes to relocate its shelter.
</P>
<P>
   So what does one get in a nine-year-old $38,000 car? Tan leather
seats, compact disk changer, built-in phone and antenna, original
Washington plates (696 CVV), additional Oregon tags (SOFTWR) and a
letter from the world's richest man attesting to his use of the car
from 1990 to 1995.
</P>
<P>
   A Microsoft spokeswoman would not say what Gates currently
drives, or whether he has a chauffeur, because of security
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe you have your own '90 LS400? The Kelley Blue Book sets
the trade-in value at $11,725 and the retail price at $18,030.
Gates premium not included.
</P>
<P>
   James G. Cobb &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He Just Keeps On Drilling &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John R. Stanley, whose oil-patch booms and busts echo more
loudly than almost anyone else's, is at it again. After a third
corporate bankruptcy filing in 20 years, he has lined up his
creditors behind a reorganization plan submitted on Friday that
would let him drill for natural gas once more. But they took his
biggest toy away.
</P>
<P>
   In April, his Trans Texas Gas Corp. filed for bankruptcy
protection under Chapter 11 as low energy prices kept it from
paying its bills. But now prices are bouncing back.
</P>
<P>
   As tenacious as Stanley, 60 and 6 feet 2 inches tall, may be, he
has lost control of a thousand-acre refinery in Norco, La., that he
had spent $2 billion improving. The largest addition to the
nation's refining capacity in two decades, it confronted cost
overruns. To complete the project, he had to give his creditors a
70 percent share, keeping the rest. Stanley, for whom the refinery
was a passion, has been reduced to a largely passive role as one of
five directors of the company that owns it.
</P>
<P>
   Agis Salpukas &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just Don't Expect a Coupon &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No, he wouldn't be so crass as to change his Web site's address
to Buydiana.com. But anyone wanting electronic suggestions on
buying the right clothing, jewelry and gifts can now rely on the
same man Princess Diana used as her personal shopping companion.
Roberto Devorik, the London retailing and fashion consultant (to
clients like Versace, Christian LaCroix, Missoni and Oscar de la
Renta) and man about town, has just joined Bestselections.com, the
New York-based Internet company.
</P>
<P>
   The Bestselections Web site modestly claims to sell ``only the
best of everything from around the whole world.'' As president of
the international division, Devorik will pick stores and
merchandise to feature on a site that already offers a $180 beaded
bikini and a $77,000 emerald and diamond ring.
</P>
<P>
   In turning his free advice into a source of income, Devorik said
in a telephone interview (using the royal pronoun), ``We're not
interested in just the priciest, but the best.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Princess Diana, he has regularly shopped for
Princess Michael of Kent, Jacqueline Bisset and Gordon Campbell
Gray, owner of the One Aldwych Hotel in the City of London.
</P>
<P>
   Devorik, 50, a native of Buenos Aires, grew up making shopping
trips with his mother to New York as casually as most folks would
go to the local mall. He plans to move within a month, with hopes
of buying a town house on Manhattan's Sutton Place for himself and
his Jack Russell terrier. No need to ask him what's the best breed
of dog.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Wolfe &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
