<HEADER>
A3247 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-PROFILE-GALBRAITH     07-16 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-PROFILE-GALBRAITH-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMIST LAUREATE, QUILL IN HAND  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 18) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By SYLVIA NASAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ At 90, John Kenneth Galbraith has just
published his 34th book, ``Name-Dropping,'' (Houghton Mifflin, $26)
a memoir featuring FDR and Eleanor, Jack and Jackie, Adlai and LBJ.
He has been speaking to packed auditoriums, and now he is ready to
hop on a plane to London, where he will be giving a speech on ``The
Unfinished Business of the Century.''
</P>
<P>
   And he is already hard at work on Book No. 35. ``I get uneasy
unless I've spent part of every day writing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Economics may have become a science, but for the better part of
this century, Galbraith has shrewdly insisted on treating it as a
branch of belles lettres. In several books over the last couple of
decades, Galbraith, who was perhaps the only economist at Truman
Capote's 1966 Black and White Ball, has been mining a rich vein of
history: his own.
</P>
<P>
   He writes from memory _ ``I never kept a diary,'' he says. His
beginnings belie his born-to-the-manor manner and the grand
Victorian, a few hundred yards from Harvard Square, where he lives.
</P>
<P>
   He describes himself as a southern Ontario farm boy who to this
day never wakes up without a feeling of satisfaction at having
escaped ``hard, tedious, boring toil.'' Interestingly, it was his
grasp of the realities of that life that gave him entree, back when
farm politics dominated American politics, into Washington and
Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   His memories are less of his long academic career than of his
glamorous political assignments. During the Depression, he was
briefly a junior speech writer for President Franklin D. Roosevelt.
An early sojourn at Cambridge University made him a disciple of the
British economist John Maynard Keynes, of whom he says, ``I
discovered that his advice was always right, but politically
disastrous.''
</P>
<P>
   An initial stint at Harvard in the '30s proved less than a
triumph. When he left briefly to visit Princeton, he got a telegram
from his dean saying, ``Accept any available offer!'' He did take
one, but the exile at Princeton _ ``still back in the
pre-Keynesian, classical era,'' he said _ was mercifully brief,
thanks to the outbreak of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Hired by the Department of Agriculture, he was ultimately
charged with keeping a lid on all prices. He recalls his experience
as price czar as the highlight of his career. ``In terms of
authority and power,'' he said with a grin, ``life has been
downhill ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   A few days after the war ended, President Harry S. Truman sent
Galbraith to Germany to interrogate Albert Speer, Hitler's economic
minister. In contrast to other Hitler henchmen, notorious drug
addicts and drunks, Speer proved to be a suave master of spin, in
command of snappy American idiom and, in Galbraith's eyes, the only
Nazi who made the enemy ``worth the wartime effort and sacrifice.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon back at Harvard, Galbraith wrote speeches and served as an
economics tutor to every liberal democratic presidential candidate
from Adlai Stevenson and John F. Kennedy to George McGovern. At one
point, Galbraith thought he might like to become a senator from
Massachusetts, though the idea didn't go far.
</P>
<P>
   His imposing height of 6 feet, 8 inches was always an advantage,
he acknowledges. So was the colossal self-assurance. When he once
complained to President Kennedy that he didn't see why The New York
Times had to call him arrogant, Kennedy replied: ``I don't know why
not, Ken. Everyone else does.''
</P>
<P>
   He came by his success as an author after relentless practice
and some false starts. When one of his first efforts, blaming the
rise of monopolies for the Depression, was still at the printing
press, he wanted to pull it back. As soon as he read Keynes, he
said, ``I decided the book was wrong, but it was too late.'' Later,
he quietly dropped it from his list of publications.
</P>
<P>
   It was ever upward from there, with classics of social criticism
like ``The Affluent Society'' (1958) and ``The New Industrial
State'' (1967). His biggest hit was ``The Triumph'' a novel of
State Department intrigue published in 1968 and optioned four times
by Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Time hasn't mellowed him much. Galbraith's new book, like so
many of his old ones, pokes at fellow economists and what he sees
as their erroneous but convenient beliefs. He plans to call it
``The Economics of Innocent Fraud.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he didn't think the 1990s were a lot like the
golden '60s, he sat up very straight. `There is no comparison!'' he
nearly shouted, launching into a riff on the dangers of unchecked
speculation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a much greater speculative bulge than in the '60s,''
he said. ``Prices are going up, so people buy. That justifies the
expectation, so they buy more. It's a classic bubble.''
</P>
<P>
   He refrains from predicting how the current economic boom will
end, explaining: ``All my wrong predictions will always be
remembered. My right ones not.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
