A3248 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-MAYOR-RADIOCALLER-     07-16 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MAYOR-RADIOCALLER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI SPARS WITH CALLER TO HIS RADIO SHOW
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The caller to Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's weekly radio
show Friday morning identified herself as Margarita from the Bronx,
the mayor's aides said, and told the station workers who screen his
calls that she wanted to talk about Con Edison, the utility that
the city is suing over a blackout in northern Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The caller, in fact, was Margarita Rosario, and while she is
from the Bronx, what she wanted to talk about was her son Anthony,
an 18-year-old robbery suspect who was shot dead by two police
detectives in January 1995. Her nephew, Hilton Vega, 21, was also a
suspect and was also shot dead.
</P>
<P>
   After a brief exchange of pleasantries, Mrs. Rosario identified
herself and what followed was a heated exchange in which Giuliani
lectured Mrs. Rosario and, by extension, other parents and society
in general about taking responsibility for raising children
properly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sure you remember me,'' Mrs. Rosario began.
</P>
<P>
   There was no doubt; Mrs. Rosario has become a fixture at
protests against police brutality, and she has loudly blamed the
mayor for the actions of the police. When she got on the air during
the mayor's hourlong call-in show on WABC-AM, she started by
accusing him of mischaracterizing her son's case.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani quickly cut her off. ``Maybe you should ask yourself
some questions about the way he was brought up and the things that
happened to him,'' Giuliani said, defending the detectives who shot
her son and his cousin. He added: ``Trying to displace the
responsibility for the criminal acts of your son onto these police
officers is really unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   The detectives had been called to an apartment in Morris Heights
4 1/2 years ago by two tenants who said three men had robbed them
the day before and had vowed to return that night. The detectives
waited for the men and confronted them. One of the three men had a
gun but never fired a shot.
</P>
<P>
   Although an autopsy found that Anthony Rosario and his cousin
were lying face down when they were shot multiple times by the
detectives, a grand jury declined to press charges and police
officials said they found the shootings to be justified. The police
said that the detectives felt they were in imminent danger of being
shot, and that the suspects did not obey orders to drop to the
floor.
</P>
<P>
   But the Civilian Complaint Review Board, which investigates
police brutality, expressed concerns that the detectives had used
excessive force by firing 22 shots at Rosario and Vega. The third
suspect, who was shot in the leg but not killed, said that they had
gone to the apartment not as robbers but to collect a debt.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said that he felt terrible for Mrs. Rosario but also
accused her of distorting the facts of the case, of ignoring her
son's criminal past and refusing to face her own responsibilities
as a parent.
</P>
<P>
   And later, at his daily news conference, Giuliani quoted remarks
Mrs. Rosario made on television last month during a congressional
hearing, in which she said New Yorkers should riot to protest
police brutality. He again expressed regret for her loss but
defended his remarks as ``quite sensitive and quite honest.''
</P>
<P>
   During the radio exchange, as Mrs. Rosario kept trying to ask
Giuliani questions, the mayor flashed some of the aggressive
prosecutorial skills for which he was famous as U.S. attorney.
``Mrs. Rosario, didn't he return to the place where he had robbed
these people the day before?'' the mayor asked. ``And he told them
that if they didn't have more money for them, he was going to kill
them, isn't that correct? And didn't your son have a criminal
record of violence?'' The police say that Rosario had had previous
arrests for robbery and assault.
</P>
<P>
   When Mrs. Rosario finally stopped trying to speak, the mayor
turned to his larger points of defending the police and of urging
parents to take more responsibility for their children. He said
society needed to confront such matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sorry that I have to be as definitive about it,'' he
said. ``But I think I also have an obligation to deal with the hurt
and the harm done to these police officers who were put in a
position where they had to kill your son because he was a criminal
that wanted to kill other people.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Rosario said that she was abruptly cut off during the
mayor's comments. In an interview later, she called the mayor's
remarks ``hurtful.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't know my family,'' she said. ``He never actually
came to even apologize or even find out who we are or what we are
about.'' She added, ``We did not raise our children to be
criminals, as he is saying.''
</P>
<P>
   His press secretary, Sunny Mindel, said the mayor does not
control the calls and would not have cut her off. She said that
when the show returned from a commercial break, Mrs. Rosario was no
longer on the line.
</P>
<P>
   After the commercial break, the mayor continued on the same
theme: ``Those are actually the basic fundamental questions that
need to be asked, that often aren't and then we displace the
responsibility to the police. What about the parents? How was the
child brought up? What values were they given? What ethics were
they taught? What happened in their church? What didn't happen?
These are the basic things that create a lawful society, a decent
society.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``So we have a real hard time in New York City and
elsewhere asking these questions because they are more difficult so
we displace responsibility to other things, which sometimes have
validity but most often they are escaping the more painful
questions that need to be asked.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani then seemed to remember his role as talk show host and
went to the next caller. ``Now,'' he said, as coolly as if he had
just been talking about potholes and cracked sidewalks, ``we are
going to go to Meshulam in Brooklyn.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
