<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN THIS SOFTWARE BE SAVED?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dear Dr. Bombay: I have a Sony PCV-90 that came with a recovery
CD that will reinstall everything, including Windows 95. I
currently have Win98 Second Edition. Every time I start my
computer, I get an error that causes me to start up in Safe Mode. I
need to install the original software, but the drive has been
converted to FAT32. I have asked Sony to help me on this, but they
said it is impossible to go back. I am not a computer genius, but I
am not computer-stupid. I do know it can be done. I think they were
just too lazy. _ Helpless
</P>
<P>
   Dear Helpless: No, ``lazy'' would indicate at least a modicum of
proficiency that the Sony tech was simply unwilling to employ to
help you. ``Grossly incompetent'' comes much closer to the mark.
</P>
<P>
   Without getting too technical, FAT32 is Microsoft's new,
improved way to store stuff on your hard drive, replacing FAT16.
Because data are stored more efficiently, you can fit more data on
the drive, and programs are supposed to start faster. Windows 98
and the latest version of 95 have a handy drive converter in the
System Tools menu. The only catch is that once you convert, you
can't go back to FAT16 without buying a third-party utility like
Partition Magic. If everyone will wake up now, we'll move along. I
think I may even write something nasty, so pay close attention.
</P>
<P>
   Your registry is hammered. Sure, you could go in and twiddle
with it, but chances are you'll goober things up even worse than
they are. It's time to drop the big one.
</P>
<P>
   First you need to get rid of any trace of FAT32. I like to start
with a bootable DOS 6.22 (or earlier) floppy, but a Windows
start-up disk will work as well. There's a utility to make one in
Add/Remove Programs in the Control Panel. The disk you make should
have Fdisk.com and Format.com on it. If you need drivers to make
your CD drive work, add them as well. The Win98 utility does all
that for you.
</P>
<P>
   Boot with the floppy and run Fdisk. Follow the menu, and remove
all partitions. Create a new partition, and make it active. Stop
whining, and read the on-screen instructions. Now reboot with the
floppy still in the drive. When the computer comes back up, type in
``Format C: /s'' at the prompt and have a beer while the drive is
reformatted. Don't type in the quotes. Did I really have to tell
you that? Sigh. ...
</P>
<P>
   You have a recovery CD-ROM, which quite possibly will eliminate
all the hard work. A few years ago, the better computer makers
started including these, knowing that users are idiots who will
invariably massacre their software. The recovery CD is a do-over.
Usually, you have to tell your computer to try booting from the CD
drive first (oh, go read your manual) or the CD will come with a
bootable floppy. Have another beer while the CD finishes its work.
You'll have a pristine set of software, and the computer is in just
about the same state as it was when you stole it from the loading
dock at work. Sorry, I was thinking about a little plan of my own
there.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, once your Sony is humming along on Win95, you'll have to
upgrade to 98 all over again. Then, when everything looks OK, run
the FAT32 converter and have some more beers. By this time you
ought to be feeling good enough to call Sony and give it a piece of
your mind.
</P>
<P>
   (Noted computerologist Dr. Emilio Bombay slipped a dirty word
into this week's column. Did you find it? He says the editors never
will. Send indignant complaints to drbombay\Nstar-telegram.com or
via snail-mail at Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth,
TX 76101. Fax: 390-7257. In real life, Dr. Bombay is Michael Gerst,
editorial systems director for the Star-Telegram. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
