<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-JETER-RUMOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 JETER RUMOR IS FULL OF HOLES, BUT HE ISN'T  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Yankee officials were concerned. There had been a
report on an unidentified radio station that the star shortstop
Derek Jeter had been shot. As 4 p.m. came and went Friday, the time
that most Yankees are expected to be in their Yankee Stadium
clubhouse for a night game, Jeter had not been sighted. But at
4:08, the clubhouse door opened and he walked through.
</P>
<P>
   ``Glad to see you,'' said Rick Cerrone, the Yankees' director of
media relations.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter nodded, but as he arrived at his locker, he noticed two
reporters approaching him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you know,'' one asked, ``that you were reported to have
been shot?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shot today?'' Jeter said, laughing. ``No, I didn't get
shot today.''
</P>
<P>
   In an olive T-shirt, jeans and black-trimmed white sneakers, he
strolled into the players' lounge, but soon he returned and sat at
his locker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shot? Where?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Informed that the report had emanated from Newark, he shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was asleep today, man,'' he said. ``I got up at 1 o'clock.
Maybe somebody got shot with the same name. Maybe I better call my
mom.''
</P>
<P>
   As he put on his Yankee uniform, Jeter chuckled. ``This is a
first,'' he said. ``Did I live?''
</P>
<P>
   Jeter turned to Jorge Posada, the Yankee catcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jorge, when we were in the car coming up here, did you hear my
name?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Posada shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard it,'' Jeter said. ``I didn't hear the first name. I
figured it was somebody with the same name. But sometimes they say
when you get shot, it takes a little time for you to feel it. But
now I know why, when I walked in, somebody said, `Glad to see you
today.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
