<HEADLINE>
REUTERS SHARES RISE AFTER INQUIRY ENDS  
(DW) 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Britain)   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Shares of Reuters Group &UR;  &LR; PLC rose Friday a day after
it said that federal prosecutors would not charge the company with
improperly obtaining information from a big competitor, Bloomberg
LP.
</P>
<P>
   Reuters American depository receipts _ each representing six
shares of the British company _ rose 62.5 cents Friday, to $86.625,
in Nasdaq trading. In London, Reuters shares rose 15 pence, to 918
pence.
</P>
<P>
   A federal grand jury in New York has been investigating the
relationship between a Reuters subsidiary, Reuters Analytics, and
Cyberspace Research Associates Inc., a New York company set up
several years ago by a former Bloomberg employee.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors were looking into whether Cyberspace Research
assisted Reuters Analytics Inc. in improperly obtaining Bloomberg
data that could have allowed Reuters to copy Bloomberg's analysis
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Reuters said on Thursday that the U.S. attorney had told the
company that prosecutors had closed the investigation. The U.S.
attorney's office in Manhattan declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   The chief executive of Reuters, Peter Job, told The Associated
Press the company was gratified that no charges would be filed.
</P>
</TEXT>
