<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-BILLIONS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT VALUE TOPS $500 BILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RICHMAN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Microsoft Corp. is the first company in history valued
at more than $500 billion.
</P>
<P>
   That's half a trillion dollars, nearly 50 percent more than the
assessed value of all the real estate in the state.
</P>
<P>
   It's the value of every U.S. dollar circulating throughout the
world on any given day. It's the cost of 1,100 Safeco Fields. Or
the Gross Domestic Product of Thailand, plus $45 million in change.
</P>
<P>
   The software giant hit that mark at about noon Friday, when the
price of its shares reached 97 31/32.
</P>
<P>
   Later its stock climbed even higher in heavy trading, to 99
7/16, adding another $7.5 billion to the company's market value.
</P>
<P>
   Market value is figured by multiplying the share price by the
number of shares issued.
</P>
<P>
   As the stock continues to soar, the Microsoft holdings of
chairman Bill Gates are nearing $100 billion. His 991.7 million
shares, representing 19.4 percent of the company, will hit the
$100-billion mark when the stock reaches 100 27/32. That could
happen Monday if the trend continues.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft ``continue(s) to drive the personal computer
revolution,'' said Robert Finch, a portfolio manager with Aeltus
Investment Management Inc., New York, which owns more than 7.9
million shares.
</P>
<P>
   ``They plan to go beyond the PC platform to drive the benefits
of microcomputing to a whole host of products and devices that
people are only just starting to talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock has been buoyed by reports that it will
issue a tracking stock to pay for and reflect the value of its
Internet businesses. Though its performance was damped earlier this
year by a pending federal antitrust suit, it recently rebounded.
</P>
<P>
   The stock was also helped when Microsoft won a legal battle
Friday. A jury unanimously found it didn't violate federal
antitrust laws in denying access to its source code to a small
Connecticut software company, Bristol Technologies Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's shares have risen almost 500-fold since it went
public in 1986, fueled by the explosive growth of personal
computers and the fervor of co-founder Gates, 43, the world's
richest person.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1985, Microsoft consistently posts earnings growth
and profits of 30 percent or more. Shares have more than doubled in
value over the past year. Its fourth-quarter results, to be
released Monday, are expected to beat analysts' estimates.
</P>
<P>
   The market has made Microsoft's value equivalent to the amount
of U.S. currency circulated worldwide every day, said Carol Eckert,
a spokeswoman for the Federal Reserve Bank of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   All of Washington State's private real estate was assessed at
$352 billion last year, $148 billion shy of Microsoft's value.
Safeco Field cost a relatively paltry $436 million to build. Only
15 countries have Gross Domestic Products greater than $500
billion. Australia, Sweden, Belgium and the Netherlands are not
among them.
</P>
<P>
   Gates co-founded Microsoft with school friend Paul Allen in
1975. Allen in June owned 135.9 million shares, or 2.47 percent of
Microsoft, valued at $13.5 billion at Friday's close.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Gates, Finch said, ``It's business acumen that's
driven his success, more than just raw technology. He's been able
to leverage good technology and make it the dominant technology.''
</P>
<P>
   The relentless rise of Microsoft stock has made millionaires out
of an estimated 5,000 current and former employees. An investment
of $100 made at the initial offering would be worth $50,000 today.
</P>
<P>
   The company's steady rise catapulted Microsoft ahead of General
Electric Co. as the world's most valuable company back in September
1998. GE is now valued at $388.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Material from Bloomberg News was included in this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
