<SLUG> BC-GLF-BROPEN-NOTES217-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Even triple-bogey doesn't thwart stormin' Norman
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARNOUSTIE, Scotland _ Maybe a shoulder rebuilt 15 months ago is
the difference. For the second time in three major championships
this year, Greg Norman is contending seriously entering the
weekend, standing three shots off the halfway lead through the
128th British Open.
</P>
<P>
   It is the major that has enabled Norman to find whatever
ingredient always seems to be lacking at the other three.
Continually thwarted in the Masters, where he finished third in
April, Norman is a two-time British Open champion. He shot a
1-under 70 in Friday's wind-blown second round, despite a
triple-bogey 7 at the perilous par-4 17th.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like I've always said, once you get yourself in position, you
feel like you get back on the bike, and a flood of good stuff comes
back your way,'' Norman, 44, said. ``All of a sudden, you have a
real aggressive swing going and you've got a wonderful touch with
your putter.''
</P>
<P>
   Out in the nasty rough of the Carnoustie Golf Links, it wasn't
always so wonderful. After driving only three yards off the fairway
at the 17th, Norman had to flail from high rough with a sand wedge.
The Shark swooshed, but the ball never moved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to have to classify it as an air swing, because I
didn't feel it hit the clubface,'' Norman said. ``I don't know what
happened to it. I think it just went back in the divot hole, and
either the club went right underneath it or the club never reached
the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman had no complaint with the width of the fairway _ just the
closeness of unplayable rough to the fairway.
</P>
<P>
   ``God (must have) come down and put fertilizer in this rough,''
Norman said. ``I've never seen grass this lush and this green that
(near) the edge of the fairway.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman's clubs have some history in them, literally. After two
sets were stolen by a construction worker from his Hobe Sound,
Fla., home recently, Norman is using the ones he brandished for his
victory in the 1993 British Open at Royal St. George's.
</P>
<P>
   Monty ready to move on
</P>
<P>
   Scotland's Colin Montgomerie has done a swift mental exit from
the tournament, considering last Sunday at Loch Lomond he termed
his game in perfect shape for Carnoustie. Deflated by a
second-round 76, but certainly not eliminated at 8-over 150, Monty
nonetheless declared himself finished. ``I'm out of the tournament
now,'' Europe's dominant player said, ``and now I look forward to
the U.S. PGA, the next major. This is gone now. I'm just playing
for numbers, unfortunately, now.'' After a birdie at the 14th,
Montgomerie bogeyed three holes in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Dunlap slips but makes cut
</P>
<P>
   Scott Dunlap slipped to a 77 but is in decent shape at 7-over
149. He double-bogeyed the par-3, 250-yard 16th hole, which was
downwind enough for a 6-iron that caught the right bunker. Dunlap
splashed to the rough, chipped to five feet and missed the putt.
``I'm still trying to figure out which one of the five shots that I
hit was bad,'' he said. During two days, Dunlap said, he has been,
``collectively off line by about four yards'' at the 16th hole and
lost three strokes to par.... Atlanta's Billy Andrade (75-84_159)
and Duluth's Stewart Cink (82-80_162) both missed the cut.... Nick
Faldo missed the cut for the first time in 24 appearances, and his
second-round 79 was his highest ever in this event. ``Played bad,
putted lousy, that's all I can tell you,'' Faldo said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
