<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BROPEN-ROUND217-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Carnasty' hangs tough
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARNOUSTIE, Scotland _ Finding a summation of the 128th British
Open required just a visit with Atlanta resident Billy Andrade late
Friday afternoon at the Carnoustie Golf Links. Andrade withstood a
13-over-par 84 to miss the cut by five shots, then left the course
for a root canal.
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' said Andrade, ``is the state of my golf right now.''
</P>
<P>
   It seemed to be an appropriate example. After 36 holes at the
place they are calling Carnasty, the leaderboard is almost as weird
as Andrade's week.
</P>
<P>
   Out in front by one stroke at 1-over-par 143 is 33-year-old
Frenchman Jean Van de Velde, a qualifier who managed a 3-under-par
68 in taking advantage of less wind in the morning hours.
</P>
<P>
   One stroke behind him at 2-over 144 is Argentine Angel Cabrera,
an obscure South American Tour player who had a 69.
</P>
<P>
   The first familiar name is Sweden's Jesper Parnevik, who added a
71 to his opening 74 and is at 3-over 145. Then comes the trio of
American Tiger Woods (72), two-time British Open champion Greg
Norman (70) of Australia and Sweden's Patrik Sjoland (72) at 4-over
146.
</P>
<P>
   The cut came at 12-over-par 154, ending play for defending
champion Mark O'Meara (83-74), three-time champion Nick Faldo
(78-79), 1996 champion Tom Lehman (76-80), 1975 Carnoustie champion
Tom Watson (82-73) and Spanish sensation Sergio Garcia, who
finished last in the field at 89-83_172.
</P>
<P>
   What happened Thursday did not necessarily affect Friday.
Australia's Rodney Pampling (71-86) became the first player in Open
Championship history to lead after the first round and miss the
cut.
</P>
<P>
   Americans Len Mattiace (74), Justin Leonard (74), the 1997
British Open champion, and 1998 runner-up Brian Watts are tied for
seventh at 147, along with Australian Bradley Hughes (71), just
four shots off the pace.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the order on the leaderboard, there's no doubt
about today's featured pairing _ Woods and Norman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in very good shape,'' said Woods, 23, who finished a
stroke out of the playoff at Royal Birkdale last year.
</P>
<P>
   Van de Velde, who lists Disneyland as a sponsor, started playing
golf as a youngster. He asked his parents during trips to their
summer home in Biarritz to drop him off at a nearby spot to play
``mini-golf.'' Or, as he called it, ``funky golf.''
</P>
<P>
   ``After a while,'' he said, ``they brought me to the real
game.''
</P>
<P>
   And now, this week, back to funky golf. Not that Carnoustie's
ribbonlike fairways and high rough have confounded Van de Velde,
who has the appearance of a French Fred Couples. Anyone playing in
the morning Friday had a great advantage over the afternoon, when
the wind stiffened heavily. However, the average score was down for
the day, from 78.3 to 76.9.
</P>
<P>
   Van de Velde, whose best Open finish is a tie for 34th in 1993,
seized the opportunity, making four birdies and a bogey. While
Woods and Norman faltered coming home, Van de Velde birdied Nos. 16
and 18, with a 45-foot birdie on the par-3 16th and a wedge to a
foot at the finish.
</P>
<P>
   Of the most significant weekend of his professional life, the
Frenchman said calmly, ``I heard that there is always a first
time.... I know it's a major championship, but it's just a golf
tournament.... It's just a matter of staying focused to what I have
to do, stay within myself and try not to do anything silly.''
</P>
<P>
   While unknown to the American audience, Cabrera is not without
credentials, finishing second to Garcia two weeks ago at the Irish
Open. Not without good fortune Friday, he was helped to a par at
the 18th when the wind blew a putt in from the lip.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can play with big names,'' Cabrera said, through an
interpreter, of the star players around him. ``I'm playing within
my game and I only see the course. I don't know who is behind me.''
</P>
<P>
   Parnevik, who has two seconds and a fourth in the British, said
he is suffering from a sore hand, a fever and hay fever and ``would
have taken a 78 or 79'' on Friday. ``To shoot 71 is beyond my
dreams, actually,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
