<HEADER>
A3264 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COSTPLUS-COSTPLUS_SFC     07-16 1251
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COSTPLUS-COST </SLUG>
 PLUS _ SF CHRON  
 Cost Plus' Quirkiness Pays Off  
 By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Ray Duplain, a history lecturer from Australia, stops in at the
Cost Plus World Market on Fisherman's Wharf every time he's in San
Francisco.
<P>
   Earlier this week, Duplain picked up a bottle of wine, some
Pelligrino, and two hand-carved figurines. ``You wouldn't find that
anywhere else,'' said Duplain, fingering a small wooden cat with
rope knees and dangling legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I`ve never seen another shop like it, and I've been all over
the world,'' said Duplain, who has visited the store periodically
since 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Duplain's purchases embody, in microcosm, the unique formula
that is propelling Cost Plus from a quirky California business that
was near insolvency five years ago to an up-and-coming national
retailer and Wall Street darling.
</P>
<P>
   Cost Plus, headquartered in Oakland, features two very different
categories _ gourmet comestibles and home furnishings with two
common qualities: they're eclectic and they're inexpensive.
</P>
<P>
   Although marrying two seemingly unrelated categories under one
roof is an unusual retailing strategy, it has a major, hidden
advantage: the wine, European cookies, Texas rice mixes and other
gourmet treats bring shoppers into the store more frequently than
if they were looking only for home furnishings.
</P>
<P>
   The edibles also attract the 50 percent of the shoppers that
doesn't generally relish looking for home goods: men.
</P>
<P>
   Once in the door, both male and female shoppers typically wander
through the store and pick up things for the house, like a
fish-shaped umbrella stand, a knickknack shelf from Indonesia, an
Italian butter dish, some wrapping paper or a wrought iron candle
holder.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is merchandise that appeals to a person who has their own
sense of style,'' said Murray Dashe, Cost Plus' chief executive
officer. ``It is unconventional because, frankly, conventionality
is the kiss of death for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The wine department is strategically located in the back of the
store to maximize impulse buying along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Impulse items ``are where the opportunity lies'' for Cost Plus,
said Helen Bulwik, director of global retailing for Anderson
Consulting.
</P>
<P>
   Bulwik regularly buys wine at Cost Plus and generally winds up
with more in her shopping cart. Recently, for example, she took
home a $100 deck umbrella. ``I had no intention of buying a deck
umbrella,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Retailing analyst Ralph Jean calls the food and beverage
department Cost Plus' ``secret weapon.'' The treats give Cost Plus
a competitive advantage over its closest rival, Pier 1 Imports of
Fort Worth, Texas, which carries similar home items but no food, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Another Cost Plus advantage is that prices of comparable
merchandise tend to run 10 to 15 percent cheaper than at Pier 1,
said Jean, with First Union Capital Markets.
</P>
<P>
   The Cost Plus formula seems to be working: Although 37 percent
of the Oakland retailer's revenues come from small-ticket food
products, its stores generate sales of $260 per square foot,
significantly higher than Pier 1's $200 per square foot.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Cost Plus is rolling out stores around the country, ``I
think Cost Plus will systematically take market share from Pier
1,'' Jean said.
</P>
<P>
   Jean's enthusiasm is typical on Wall Street, where Cost Plus
shares have more than tripled over the past 18 months. Shares have
risen to $46.50 at yesterday's close from $15 in January 1998, when
Dashe took the company's helm.
</P>
<P>
   Pier 1's shares, meanwhile, have fallen to &UR;  &LR; $9.69 from about $15
over the same period.
</P>
<P>
   That's largely because Cost Plus, with 94 stores, has ``huge
growth potential,'' said Elizabeth Pierce, an analyst with the
Siedler Companies.
</P>
<P>
   Cost Plus' store count is growing by 20 to 25 percent annually,
and Dashe aims to eventually hit 400 _ with possible international
expansion after that. It now operates in 16 states as far east as
Ohio and is on a steady march toward the Eastern Seaboard.
</P>
<P>
   Pier 1, meanwhile, operates 730 stores in 49 states and about 70
abroad. Pier 1 Chief Financial Officer Steve Mangum said his
company is shopping for a higher-end furnishings chain to satisfy
growth-oriented investors and revive its stock.
</P>
<P>
   Pier 1 is also taking on Cost Plus by lowering its prices, a
strategy that reversed sales declines in a few markets where it
competes with Cost Plus, said Mangum. However, in most markets
where the two companies both operate, Pier 1's sales have not been
affected, he added.
</P>
<P>
   As Cost Plus moves into more Pier 1 markets, Mangam forecasts
minimal impact. ``If they get uppity, maybe I'll buy them,'' he
said with a leisurely Texas drawl.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Pier 1 and Cost Plus share common roots. In the
early 1960s, when Cost Plus ran about a dozen locations, Tandy
Corp. bought a handful of Cost Plus franchise stores, renamed them
Pier 1 and expanded the chain quickly.
</P>
<P>
   While Pier 1 grew, Cost Plus, which was founded in 1958 with the
Fisherman's Wharf store, stuck closer to home.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln Bartlett and Jack Amthor, the chain's founders, ran Cost
Plus successfully until the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, Cost Plus changed hands twice and lost its
direction, accumulating $40 million in debt during a leveraged
buyout. Ralph Dillon, the president of Family Dollar Stores, was
named chief executive and began a turnaround in 1990. &UR;  &LR; However,
because of its debt load, Cost Plus was on the brink of insolvency.
</P>
<P>
   Two new investors, Goldman Sachs and ING Capital, bought the
debt and restructured it in 1994, and Cost Plus went public in
April 1996. Cost Plus' performance has exceeded the wildest
expectations of the early investors, said Ed Mul &LR; e(CQ accent over &LR; 
the e please) &LR; , a Goldman Sachs managing director and former Cost
Plus board member.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Pierce estimates that Cost Plus' sales will grow to
$389 million and hit $477 million in 2000. Net income is projected
to rise to $17.7 million in 1999 and $22.2 million the following
year. The company has exceeded analysts' earnings estimates for
five consecutive quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Cost Plus is not home free. Managing a national expansion
is a far more complicated endeavor than running 40 stores in and
around California, the position Cost Plus was in as recently as
five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   And it is always possible that Cost Plus, like any retailer,
could lose sight of consumers' tastes and start making bad
merchandising decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no glaring problem on the horizon that they they have
to be concerned about, but you always have risk with respect to
merchandising and execution,'' Mul &LR; e &LR;  of Goldman Sachs said.
</P>
<P>
   The company's management team, led by Dashe, is extremely
strong, said Mul &LR; e &LR; . For example, Kathi Lentsch, who has worked at
both Pottery Barn and Pier 1, runs the merchandising operations.
John Hoffner, the chief financial officer, is a veteran of Dayton
Hudson and Federated Department Stores.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  One change ahead is the company's name. Amthor and Bartlett
dubbed their first store Cost Plus because the merchandise was sold
at cost plus 10 percent. Today the World Market moniker seems more
fitting, and in new markets such as Indiana and Ohio stores are
simply called World Market.
</P>
<P>
   Bay Area stores may never do away with the Cost Plus name
altogether. But over the next 18 months, store signs will be
changed to highlight the World Market theme.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
