<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-TARIFF-730&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PASSES BILL TO HELP AFRICA IMPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Ind., Mich., Miss., Mo., N.C., N.Y., S.C., Texas) (rk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House Friday approved a far-ranging American
economic initiative for Africa that offers enhanced trade benefits
in exchange for the adoption of free-market practices by African
nations.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, passed by a vote of 234-163, would authorize
quota-free and duty-free imports from 48 sub-Saharan African
countries, including some of the world's poorest nations, for 10
years, with a particular focus on textiles and apparel.
African-made textiles currently face import taxes of 15 to 25
percent.
</P>
<P>
   If the legislation, known as the African Growth and Opportunity
Act, were to become law, it would be the first major
trade-promotion measure enacted in the United States since the 1994
North American Free Trade Agreement that established duty-free
commerce between Canada, the United States and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The African legislation has been quietly percolating along
through Congress for months. President Clinton, who has strongly
supported such a measure since he visited Africa in 1998, began a
concerted effort to push for passage earlier this year. House
Speaker Dennis Hastert of Illinois is also a strong supporter.
</P>
<P>
   But the legislation still faces big opposition in the Senate,
which rejected a similar measure last year. It also comes against a
backdrop of increased trade protectionism in the United States,
where companies in industries such as steel and textiles fear a
rising tide of inexpensive imports could hurt profits and jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of the African legislation argue that U.S. trade with
Africa is relatively small and any increased imports from Africa
would have no harmful effects on the healthy American economy.
American merchandise exports to the region totaled $6.7 billion in
1998 while imports from Africa amounted to $13.4 billion. By
comparison, U.S. trade with Japan alone totaled $180 billion last
year, according to Commerce Department figures.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's supporters also contend that removing all quotas and
taxes on African products would stimulate economic growth in the
region and nurture the increasing number of fledgling democracies
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will open a new era in for U.S. relations with
sub-Saharan Africa,'' said Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, who heads the
House Ways and Means Committee.
</P>
<P>
   After Friday's vote, Charlene Barshefsky, the U.S. trade
representative, said in a statement that the House had taken ``a
vital step toward promoting further economic growth and reform in
Africa.''
</P>
<P>
   The prospects for Senate passage are unclear, even though its
version of the bill is more restrictive. It would require, for
example, that African nations use American raw materials in the
manufacture of their textile exports to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate version is also incorporated into broader trade
legislation that includes a Carribean Basin Initiative, backed by
Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi, the majority leader.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``U.S. policy has virtually ignored Africa,'' said Sen. Richard
Lugar, R-Ind., who is the Senate's main sponsor of the measure.
``This bill encourages a transition from aid to trade for
sub-Saharan countries committed to economic and political reform.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill does not affect foreign aid to African countries.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition in the House and Senate comes largely from
Southeastern lawmakers whose districts have large numbers of
textile workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone here wants to help Africa, but we don't want to do it
on the backs of U.S. workers,'' said Rep. Richard Burr, R-N.C.,
whose district around Winston-Salem includes 22,000 textile
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Textile and apparel imports from sub-Saharan Africa represented
less than 1 percent, or $383 million of the $46 billion worth of
all such imports in 1996, according to the International Trade
Commission. A commission study found that even if all quotas and
duties were removed, African textiles would still likely remain
below 2 percent of total U.S. textile imports over the next 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents say they do not fear direct competition from African
businesses. Rather, they are concerned that large quantities of
inexpensive textiles from countries like China may be shipped
illegally through Africa to the United States. Supporters insist
the bill includes tough safeguards against that practice, called
transshipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a national holiday in China when we pass this
bill,'' said Rep. Lindsey Graham, R-S.C.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The trade bill divided House Democrats, many of whom complained
that the Africa legislation failed to include adequate protections
for African workers and the environment. In Friday's vote, 136
Republicans and 98 Democrats supported the bill, while 63
Republicans, 99 Democrats and one independent opposed it.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dick Gephardt of Missouri, the Democratic leader, voted for
the bill, while Rep. David Bonior of Michigan, the Democratic whip,
or No. 2 official, voted against it. Gephardt, however, opposes a
Caribbean Basin Initiative and would oppose combining it with the
Africa bill.
</P>
<P>
   The Congressional Black Caucus was also badly split over the
bill. Rep. Charles Rangel of New York, the ranking Democrat on Ways
and Means, has championed the Africa trade bill over the past
several years, and he personally lobbied several wavering
Democrats, House aides said.
</P>
<P>
   But 14 of the black caucus' 36 members opposed the bill Friday,
led by Rep. Jesse Jackson Jr., D-Ill. These critics say that
multinational companies will exploit African workers, and that the
bill did not address other key issues like debt relief and AIDS in
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell me where in this bill it says multinationals must hire
African workers?'' Jackson said during Friday's debate on the House
floor.
</P>
</TEXT>
