<SLUG> BC-EBAY-EBAY </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 EBay Frowns on New Online Auction Browser  &HT;     By David Lazarus 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
An Indianapolis software company has come out with an ``auction
browser'' designed to help eBay junkies track bidding contests and
to sound a warning if a particular auction is coming down to the
wire.
<P>
   EBay is not amused.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our lawyers are looking at it closely,'' Kevin Pursglove, a
spokesman for the San Jose online auctioneer, said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The auction browser _ essentially a modified version of
Microsoft's Internet Explorer _ was released via the Web on
Thursday night by ZCurve Software. It sells for $19.95, and a
30-day demo version is available in a free trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reaction has been extremely positive,'' said ZCurve
President Bob Hays. ``We've gotten a high amount of traffic.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the idea for the auction browser came from his own
experience bidding for movie and computer collectibles. He realized
that the real action came only in the last five minutes of bidding.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're away from your computer, you miss that,'' Hays
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   To remedy this situation, he said the auction browser will sound
an alarm when the bidding grows heated. It also will allow users to
combine separate auctions in a single tracking window, thus
permitting a bidder to keep tabs on both that hard-to-find Steve
Lawrence album and that must-have Wonder Woman Pez dispenser.
</P>
<P>
   Two special buttons on the browser are marked with eBay's name:
One takes users directly to eBay's site and the other takes users
to eBay's search window. There are also buttons for adding auction
items to the tracking window.
</P>
<P>
   Ebay's name is featured prominently as well in a press release
issued by ZCurve.
</P>
<P>
   Hays admitted that he never discussed either creation of the
browser or its marketing with eBay officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have appreciated the courtesy of advance notification
about using the eBay name so liberally,'' Pursglove said, noting
that the company's attorneys are looking into whether ZCurve may
have violated copyright or trademark laws.
</P>
<P>
   No less significantly, the auction browser allows users to
continue following an eBay bidding war even while visiting other
Web sites. This means ``eyeballs'' have left the auctioneer's
content _ and ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things that take people off our site are not good things,''
Pursglove said.
</P>
<P>
   ZCurve's Hays said he hadn't contacted Microsoft in advance
either, but in this case it doesn't seem to be a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We encourage developers to take bits and pieces of the IE code
for their own applications,'' said Mike Nichols, a Windows product
manager at the Redmond, Wash., software giant. ``We build the
software in such a way that you can build on top of it.''
</P>
<P>
   EBay may not be as understanding, at least if a recent company
announcement for a new eBay magazine and a pair of how-to books on
online auctions are any indication.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every mention of the firm's name is accompanied by a
trademark or copyright symbol, and the fine print sternly warns
that ``designated trademarks and brands are the property of their
respective owners.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
