<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROVIDIAN-PROVIDIAN </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Providian Withdraws Online Ad Contested by Rival NextCard  &HT;     By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Providian Financial Corp., the nation's ninth-largest credit card
company, has offered an olive branch to an online rival that sued
it for allegedly ripping off the look of its Internet ad.
<P>
   In a Thursday letter to NextCard's attorney, Providian's lawyer
said the company had stopped running the ad in question and hoped
``to discuss a possible accommodation to put this matter finally to
rest.''
</P>
<P>
   NextCard, the largest all-Internet credit card issuer, filed
suit in U.S. District Court in San Francisco Wednesday accusing
Providian of copying one of its online banners showing a
thermometer to symbolize falling interest rates. Banner ads allow
Internet users to click on an image and jump directly to the
advertiser's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The case has drawn wide attention because it could help
determine how copyright and trademark laws apply to online
advertising. Both NextCard and Providian are based in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Providian yesterday made available correspondence between its
attorney and NextCard's showing it had offered to settle the matter
before the suit was filed. At the same time, Providian said
NextCard's suit had no merit.
</P>
<P>
   In a press release issued yesterday, Providian said the
thermometer ad was one of more than 20 banners it tested. The
company said it dropped the banner after one week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no reason to believe that consumers associate
thermometers uniquely with any company or product,`` Providian said
in its release.
</P>
<P>
   A NextCard spokesman confirmed the company's attorney had
received Providian's Thursday letter and said the suit is still
pending.
</P>
<P>
   Providian launched Aria, its special Internet brand, in May. It
said it looked to Internet sales as one of its principal growth
avenues.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
