<HEADLINE>
RAUL SALINAS' SENTENCE IN MEXICO MURDER IS CUT TO 27{ YEARS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to correct coding.)   (ko) 
 By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ An appeals court Friday reduced the murder
sentence against Raul Salinas de Gortari, the brother of the former
president, by nearly half, to 27{ years, from 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   That bit of relatively good news for Salinas, who was convicted
on Jan. 21, came with another pleasant surprise. The highest court
in Switzerland announced Friday that it had overturned the
confiscation of more than $90 million of his money, a rebuke to
Swiss Attorney General Carla del Ponte.
</P>
<P>
   The Swiss court found that Mrs. del Ponte had no authority to
seize the money on the supposition that it included proceeds from
drug trafficking. But the ruling was based on the intricacies of
Swiss law and did not absolve Salinas of the money-laundering
charges.
</P>
<P>
   His money in Switzerland remains frozen, and local authorities
there can still prosecute him, even though the attorney general
cannot.
</P>
<P>
   In the Mexican ruling on his sentence, the appeals court in
Toluca, about 50 miles west of Mexico City, said it had halved
Salinas' sentence, which had been the maximum under Mexican law,
because the prosecution had failed to show any motive for him to
have committed the killing.
</P>
<P>
   Under Mexican law, the lack of a motive is not a basis for
acquittal in a homicide case but may, as in this one, lessen the
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Salinas was convicted in the 1994 assassination of Jose
Francisco Ruiz Massieu, a prominent politician who had once been
his brother-in-law. The appeals judge found that since Salinas had
been convicted as the instigator and not the gunman, he should not
be given the maximum sentence.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court also doubted the credibility of a witness on
whom the prosecution relied heavily, Fernando Rodriguez Gonzalez.
Rodriguez was convicted of murder for hiring the gunman. His family
received payments of about $500,000 from prosecutors just before he
changed his testimony to implicate Salinas.
</P>
<P>
   Salinas' murder conviction marked a historic break with a
tradition in Mexico of impunity for the rich and politically
powerful. But the case raised new doubts about Mexican justice,
because it relied heavily on witnesses who had been paid by
prosecutors or had been caught in clumsy attempts to frame Salinas.
</P>
<P>
   Eduardo Luengo Creel, Salinas' defense lawyer, visited him
Friday morning and emerged from prison to say Salinas had once
again insisted that he was innocent.
</P>
<P>
   ``They never came up with a motive for him to do it,'' Luengo
said Friday. ``He had nothing to do with that crime.''
</P>
<P>
   He said there would be a further appeal, which would eventually
end up in the Supreme Court. But he said that first he had to
restudy the 131,164-page record of the original case and the 7,819
pages of the appellate decision.
</P>
<P>
   He suggested that the final appeal might not be filed under
2001, when President Ernesto Zedillo, who ordered the prosecution
to go forward, leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   Luengo was especially pleased about the Swiss ruling that any
money-laundering investigation was a matter for cantonal
authorities and not federal ones like Mrs. del Ponte.
</P>
<P>
   The court barred Mrs. del Ponte from any further investigation
in the case and ordered her to pay $15,000 to Salinas' lawyers and
$3,000 in fees to the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``She acted as though we were living in the age of the
Inquisition,'' Luengo said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. del Ponte carried out her investigation in secret, giving
Salinas no opportunity to present a defense. She traveled several
times to the United States to interview jailed drug dealers who
said they knew of Salinas' ties to traffickers, finding 80
witnesses who said Salinas had met with traffickers and introduced
them to other Mexican politicians.
</P>
<P>
   But in the formal complaint that Mrs. del Ponte presented in the
proceeding in which she seized Salinas' money, most of the
witnesses were not identified by name.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
