<DOCNO> NYT19990716.0302 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3272 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHWAB-SCHWAB_SFCHRON     07-16 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHWAB-SCHWAB </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Schwab's Profit Nearly Doubles From Year Ago  &HT;     By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Charles Schwab Corp. said yesterday its second-quarter profit
nearly doubled from a year ago, as customers set up accounts and
moved money to the firm at a sizzling pace.
<P>
   But the San Francisco brokerage warned it will spend more on
advertising and technology in the months ahead, squeezing profit
margins. That spooked investors who pushed Schwab's shares down
yesterday $2.94 to $52.44.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab, the nation's largest discount and online broker,
reported net income of $151 million (18 cents a diluted share) for
the quarter ended June 30, up 98 percent from $76.3 million (9
cents) in the year-ago period.
</P>
<P>
   The firm's revenue leaped 54 percent as customers sharply
stepped up their trading activity compared with last year. During
the quarter, Schwab handled an average of 203,700 trades a day
compared with 127,400 a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Schwab's stock was vulnerable to the warning on
profit margins because it trades at such a lofty level, about 75
times estimated earnings or roughly three times the level of the
average stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people have the right business model, but when you have
a stock priced like that, there's always the potential for
weakness,'' said J.P. Morgan Securities analyst Michael
Freudenstein.
</P>
<P>
   The surge in Schwab's business reflected an accelerating stock
market boom that's been fueled by the growing popularity of online
trading. More than two-thirds of Schwab's trade orders were entered
by computer in the second quarter, the highest proportion ever.
</P>
<P>
   In the year ended June 30, assets held by Schwab customers
jumped 38 percent to $592 billion, including $242 billion in mutual
funds. Accounts grew to 6.2 million from 5.3 million a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab said its revenue grew so fast that it overwhelmed its
ability to reinvest cash in its business. That in turn kept profit
margins artificially high.
</P>
<P>
   ``More money fell to the bottom line, where we would normally
ramp up our investment program,'' said co-Chief Executive Officer
David Pottruck.
</P>
<P>
   The firm plans to step up spending for marketing, international
expansion and services to ethnic communities in the United States,
Pottruck said. For example, Schwab will boost the number of
branches targeted at Chinese language speakers to 12 from five over
the next year.
</P>
<P>
   While far above last year's levels, customer trading volume in
the second quarter actually fell 4 percent compared with the
beginning of the year. Propelled by Internet stock mania, stock
market volumes smashed all records during the first three months of
1999, overwhelming the ability of Schwab and other retail brokers
to serve customers.
</P>
<P>
   A trading dip in May and June gave Schwab a respite, during
which it upgraded its computers and hired hundreds of employees.
</P>
<P>
   Even though trading volume fell, Schwab increased its profit 5.7
percent from the first to the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   That's because other forms of income more than offset lower
commission revenue. Those income sources included higher mutual
fund fees, interest on margin loans extended to customers and
income generated as a wholesale stock trader for institutional
clients.  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
