<HEADLINE>
IN WEST VIRGINIA, THE ELDERLY LEAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo and graphic are being sent to NYT photo/graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUNBAR, W.Va. _ Ken Hechler may be the only active candidate in
the post-Monica era of American politics who gets away with
singling out female strangers in a crowd of constituents, holding
out his arms, and grinning as he gently asks, ``May I give you a
hug?''
</P>
<P>
   In receiving multiple hugs one day this week for his daring,
Hechler, West Virginia's elected secretary of state for the past 15
years, was helped by the fact that he is an 84-year-old political
legend who was wooing a gray-haired sea of retirees at the crowded
Kanawha Valley Senior Services picnic.
</P>
<P>
   The tableau was revealing. For West Virginia now has the oldest
per capita population in the union _ having overtaken Florida in
1996. Its senior residents, in the upper half of a population with
the median age of 38.6 (Florida's is 38.3), include a record tide
of returning natives who choose to come home to retire after
careers elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``A significant factor in their return is the intrinsic bond in
the Appalachian culture between the people and their land,'' said
Thomas Dudley, research director for the state Bureau of Senior
Services. Recent studies, he said, have established the state as
leading the nation in attracting back original residents for
retirement. They come in particular from urban areas in the East,
attracted by West Virginia's lower cost of living and its rural,
recreational spirit.
</P>
<P>
   The current estimate is that with the elderly now accounting for
15 of every 100 state residents, the graying trend will continue
upward to almost 25 per 100 by the first quarter of the new
century. The state, which is widely recruiting non-native retirees
the way Florida does, is making adjustments, with its seniors far
more politically active than its young.
</P>
<P>
   It's no wonder that Hechler, unfinished with a political career
seeded in the presidency of Franklin D. Roosevelt, has decided that
a politician as old as he is can be the wave of the future. Though
he would seem a shoo-in for state re-election, he has decided to
run once again next year for his old seat in Congress, which he had
retired from after 18 years in 1976 when he turned to statewide
politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life is a series of challenges and I don't want to just coast
along here,'' said Hechler, a classic maverick who already has
banjo-picking campaign ads on the radio. To counter any bias that
he is too old, he is offering his four younger primary challengers
free baseball throws at him next week when he sits in the dunking
stool at the Berkeley County Democratic picnic.
</P>
<P>
   He campaigns from a signature red jeep, always with young people
at his side, often mentioning the four games of tennis he plays
each week. ``I'm saving golf for my old age.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With the oldest age average in the country, we don't expect
any age bias in our politics,'' said Robert Perelman, the president
of the rapidly growing state chapter of the American Association of
Retired Persons. He is a 77-year-old former chemical plant
supervisor who teaches skiing in the winter.
</P>
<P>
   Hechler is not alone as a political patriarch. The state's
governor, Cecil Underwood, is 76 and a popular phenomenon himself,
having been the nation's boy wonder governor in 1956 at the age of
34, and then returning to politics in 1996 to be elected as the
oldest governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're learning seniors do vote, but also that politicians will
live longer and be more active, too,'' Earl Jarvis, director of
Kanawha Valley Senior Services, said of the evolving lesson of West
Virginia. ``I'm encouraging more of my people to run for public
office.''
</P>
<P>
   Hechler has lived a rich life as a college professor, researcher
for Roosevelt, speechwriter for President Truman, book writer
(``The Bridge at Remagen,'' a best seller about the World War II
crossing of the Rhine), and elective politician in Congress. There,
he bucked the state's coal industry and capped a career with the
landmark Coal Mine Health and Safety Act of 1969.
</P>
<P>
   He wants to go back to Washington for far more than the obvious
issues brought up at the seniors' picnic _ keeping Social Security
and health-care programs effective for the elderly. He passionately
campaigns for stronger controls on political fund raising and
handguns and for a half-dozen other issues, telling voters he can
hardly be seeking a long, safe House career anchored in
poll-tailored evasions.
</P>
<P>
   ``God will be setting my term limit,'' says Hechler rather
nonchalantly. ``But I don't want to be known as the candidate of
the seniors,'' he insists. As a native New Yorker, he moved here in
the 1950s, fresh from working in the idealistic campaigns of Adlai
Stevenson, to teach political science at Marshall College and try
to engender fresh interest in politics among the young.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a legend,'' said Bill Walker, a 24-year-old political
science student from Marshall working the picnic crowd at Hechler's
side as a summer intern. ``Just to someday look back and say I
learned politics from Hechler is a great honor,'' said the student.
He exuded the dedication of one of the young interns in the special
state program in which elderly mountaineers have been reinstilling
the art of fiddle playing lost by earlier generations who had to
emigrate for work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you, people my age are soured on politics lately,''
said Walker, who is determined to run for political office at the
earliest opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   As the elderly come to the fore, state politics are shifting to
consider issues like how the revenue base will hold up as more
retirees claim special tax abatements. ``Most studies show incoming
retirees are actually increasing the economic base,'' said Dudley
of state senior services. ``They bring in an average of $250,000 in
liquid assets, and they're a tremendous resource in volunteer work,
politics and civics.''
</P>
<P>
   Like all the states, West Virginia faces the potential trauma
from the retirement of a wide swath of talent when the baby boomer
generation hits 65. ``We'll feel it a little quicker,'' said
Dudley. But he noted there are all sorts of variables, including a
slow but promising downturn from the state's traditional loss of
young workers, plus a redefinition of retirement itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Close to half of the governor's Cabinet came out of retirement
to serve,'' noted Dudley, who is busy preparing for Underwood's
regional conference in September on the problems and opportunities
of the elderly. Next year, West Virginia will play a principle role
in the United Nation's International Year of the Older Person when
it hosts the conference on rural health.
</P>
<P>
   Hechler appreciates those issues but puts more passion into
railing against mechanized mountain-top coal mining and its effects
on the environment, citizenry and general attractiveness of West
Virginia now that all the retirees are flocking in. He has been
hiking the state on this issue, just as he has been hiking
nationally for campaign finance reform, a buoyant old New Dealer
come round one more time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, that's Ken Hechler,'' an elderly woman told her friend as
the candidate confronted them at the picnic. ``You ought to know
him _ he's been around 100 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Hechler, a whippet on the hustings, instantly responded: ``One
hundred years! Whoopee!'' And he asked if he might give the woman a
hug.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
