<HEADLINE>
PARNEVIK MANAGES PAR   AMID HIS SNIFFLING  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Sweden)   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARNOUSTIE, Scotland _ Jesper Parnevik usually plays well when
he doesn't feel well. He started Friday's second round of the
British Open with a high temperature and was bothered by allergies.
Little wonder that he shot an even-par 71, leaving him at 3 over
par for the tournament (145), just two strokes off the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was 2 over after six holes, and actually close to walking in
after five,'' said Parnevik, who has three top-five finishes at the
British Open since 1994 without a victory. ``I would have taken a
78 or a 79. To shoot a 71 is beyond my dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   Parnevik played most of his round with tissue stuffed in one
nostril to stop his nose from running.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal coming here was to give myself a chance,'' Parnevik
said. ``If I can be there on the back nine Sunday having a chance,
then I'm pleased with what I have achieved this week.''
</P>
<P>
   Just Happy to Be Here
</P>
<P>
   Patrik Sjoland, tied for fourth place at 4 over par through two
rounds, found himself in contention at a major for the first time.
But Sjoland never takes golf for granted. In 1992, he was nearly
killed when he was thrown through the sun roof of his car in an
accident. Sjoland spent a month in intensive care. His spleen was
removed, and his career was in jeopardy. But at 28, the native of
Sweden has developed into one of the top players on the European
Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the tournament all Europeans would like to win,''
Sjoland said. ``When I was injured in my car crash, it was moments
like this which kept me going. I never gave up. I didn't hit a golf
shot for five months. I said to myself I was lucky to be alive.
Playing good golf is a bonus.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval Can't Figure It Out
</P>
<P>
   David Duval (79-75) has endured a difficult two days, including
a terrible finish on his last four holes Friday _ bogey, bogey,
double-bogey, bogey. Having barely made the cut, the world's No.
2-ranked player will leave Carnoustie still looking to win his
first major championship.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he would take from his Carnoustie experience, Duval
said: ``The hope that you don't have to encounter it again. I don't
know what you can learn. Maybe sitting back later I might figure
something out, but I don't know right now. Obviously, I need to hit
it a lot better than I did and make more putts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't dislike the golf course. I just think it's really,
really tough right now. You can't judge your game on this course.
Good shots end up in the hay. Bad shots end up on the green. I
think my game's OK, but I really couldn't tell you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
