 _ SF CHRON  
<TEXT>
<P>
   These are the stories The San Francisco Chronicle Business
section plans to move for Monday, June 19, on the New York Times
wire. For questions, please call August Maggy at 415-777-7218 or
the business desk at 415-536-5172.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; DETECTIVES  &LR;  _ The Internet may be a godsend for people doing
research or managing their finances. But the ready availability of
online information has been a blow to those who make their living
snooping into other people's affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Some private detectives say their business has fallen off
dramatically as potential clients conduct their own investigations
on the Net. San Francisco's venerable Lipset Service, which has
been poking into the city's shadows for more than 50 years,
estimates that its business has declined 40 percent since ordinary
people have been able to conduct searches online. By David Lazarus
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AT&AMP;T _  &LR; On a recent visit to San Francisco, C. Michael
Armstrong, the chairman of AT&AMP;T, seemed remarkably calm about a
controversial issue that's pitted his company against America
Online in a nasty and public fight. Last month, a federal judge in
Portland, Ore., ordered AT&AMP;T to open its cable lines to competitors
in that city so others could offer high-speed Internet access over
AT&AMP;T's lines. AOL, along with other Internet service providers, is
a vocal proponent of ``open access'' which would allow the giant
service to give its customers a superfast on-ramp to AOL's content
and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But Armstrong, the visionary leader of what will soon be the
nation's largest cable operator, is unfazed. ``I'm not concerned
this ruling will stand,'' Armstrong said. ``It's against the law,
it's against any rational behavior and it's against the contract we
have with the city of Portland.'' By Deborah Solomon
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STAMPS &LR;  _ After months of testing, the Postal Service is set to
put its, er, stamp on a plan that would allow customers to buy
stamps over the Internet and print them directly onto envelopes and
mailing labels. PC Postage, the Postal Service's first big step
into electronic commerce, could be available nationwide by the end
of summer, Patricia Gibert, the agency's vice president for retail
sales, said during a demonstration on Wednesday.The program targets
an estimated 8 million small business and home office customers who
find stamps inconvenient, but don't want to buy or rent a mail
metering machine. By Henry Norr
</P>
</TEXT>
