<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVIS-SINGLES17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. in deep hole in Davis Cup
 &HT;    By Todd Holcomb
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Maybe it was the honorable thing to do,
keeping Pete Sampras on the bench Friday, but now the U.S. Davis
Cup team is in a hole that it hasn't dug itself out of in 65 years.
</P>
<P>
   With Sampras watching, using a towel to shade himself from a
brutal summer swelter at the Longwood Cricket Club, the pony-tailed
Lleyton Hewitt wore down Todd Martin 6-4, 6-7, 6-3, 6-0, and
two-time U.S. Open champion Patrick Rafter beat Jim Courier 7-6,
6-4, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. trails Australia 2-0, a deficit an American team has
overcome just once in 29 tries this century, most recently against
Australia in 1934.
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt, an 18-year-old in his Davis Cup debut, made the graying
Martin, 29, look old and tired in the opener. Martin gave Hewitt
most of his points on errors, 79 in all, and was unusually loose on
service returns. Hewitt routinely ran the slow-footed Martin from
corner to corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Best win I have ever had,'' said Hewitt, who also has
victories over Andre Agassi and Rafter (twice), but never on such a
grand stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first match was a key one for them,'' said Australian
captain John Newcombe, who theorized that the gravity of replacing
Sampras as the lead singles player weighed on Martin's mind
</P>
<P>
   Martin denied it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Pete weren't the initiator of all this, then I would be a
little bit uneasy,'' Martin said of Sampras' insistence on playing
only doubles here.
</P>
<P>
   Courier played OK, but Rafter showed why many regard him as the
best hardcourt player in the world, certainly the most gifted at
capturing the net.
</P>
<P>
   Rafter yielded only 13 points in his final 10 service games.
Courier won two-thirds of the points when he wasn't aced or when
Rafter was kept at the baseline, but there was no fending off the
world's No. 2 player, who won 30 points at the net (24 with clean
winners on overheads and volleys). Sampras enters the fray today,
paired with Alex O'Brien against Mark Woodforde and Sandon Stolle.
</P>
<P>
   Even after a winless opening day, U.S. captain Tom Gullikson
remained firm that the Sampras decision was sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning and losing doesn't change that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
