<HEADER>
A3290 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALTH-ASSESS-NYT &LR;      07-16 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: SOUND, FURY, STALEMATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mont., Okla., Mass.)  (With CONGRESS-HEALTH) 
(mk) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ By the time the Senate's four-day debate over
managed care ended Thursday night, each party had won something.
The Democrats had put the Republicans on record against some
emotional health care proposals _ stands which they expect to
highlight in the next campaign. The Republicans, for their part,
passed a modest health care bill that they believe will shield them
from attack next year.
</P>
<P>
   The ones likely to be left empty-handed were members of the
American public. President Clinton's threat to veto anything
resembling the Senate bill means there is little likelihood that
any legislation on managed care will become law this year unless
the House takes an unexpected course.
</P>
<P>
   As Sen. Max Baucus, D-Mont., said at one point Thursday morning:
``The debate that's going on now is one of the most partisan and
the most vacuous, the most devoid of effort to try to reach a
solution that I've heard in a long time _ and that's saying
something.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when the off-year between congressional
elections was considered the period in which political passions
cooled enough for serious work on legislation. But these days, with
an all-campaign-all-the-time atmosphere in the capital, that is no
longer the case.
</P>
<P>
   So managed care, for all the sound and fury, is more likely than
not to become just another example of the kind of stalemate
gripping this Congress. The sparring over the issue was so intense
that one measure on which everyone in the Senate chamber agreed _
an effort to bar insurance companies from forcing women to undergo
mastectomies as out-patient surgery _ could not gain a unanimous
vote. The Republicans voted for their amendment on the measure and
the Democrats voted for their own version.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a gun control bill collapsed in the House under
similar circumstances as Democrats chose to vote against a modest
Republican gun control measure that they considered flawed rather
than allow Republicans to say they had done something in the
aftermath of the Littleton, Colo., massacre.
</P>
<P>
   An overhaul of the Social Security system is stalled both
because the two parties violently disagree over how to change the
system and because each side resists giving the other any kind of
credit for saving the popular retirement program. And with the
Republicans once again making a major tax cut the crown jewel of
their legislative agenda, the parties have fallen into their
familiar fight, with the Democrats accusing the Republicans of
putting tax cuts ahead of protecting the Medicare system.
</P>
<P>
   This year's intense partisanship is partly caused by the
Republicans' slim hold on power in the House, where a Democratic
gain of just six seats next year could put them in the majority.
But it is also the case that the political mood of the country is
causing Democrats to be more aggressive and the Republicans more
defensive than in years past.
</P>
<P>
   And that has created its own odd dynamic on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   According to a recent poll conducted jointly by Ed Goeas, a
Republican, and Celinda Lake, a Democrat, congressional Democrats
currently hold their traditional advantage over Republicans on
issues like health care, Social Security, Medicare and education,
while Republicans in the aftermath of the Clinton scandal have a
sharp lead over Democrats on the issue of values.
</P>
<P>
   Because of such findings, Democrats have tried to push to the
fore their own agenda to draw public attention to issues where they
have a lead, and Republicans have tried to undermine the effort by
blunting the differences between the parties on such issues.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats have had the most leverage over the agenda in the
Senate, because the chamber's arcane traditions and rules allow the
minority to cause paralysis. So the Republican leadership has bowed
to Democratic demands that gun control and managed care come up for
consideration.
</P>
<P>
   But the subsequent debates have been less about legislating than
about shadowboxing for the next campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, the Republicans responded to the Democrats with
more limited measures designed to defuse the issue. But in the case
of the gun control debate, the amendments the leaders crafted were
so weak that enough Republicans bolted from their party to give the
Democrats victory in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   This week, on managed care, the Republicans were far more
masterful, in part because they had known they would face a battle
over this issue for months. Sen. Don Nickles, R-Okla., the majority
whip, assembled a health care task force and worked hard for weeks
to satisfy both Republican moderates and conservatives. His work
produced party unity, and on the final vote, only two Republicans
abandoned the party.
</P>
<P>
   But the bill they produced went nowhere as far as the Democrats'
version. While many consumer protections in the Republican bill
would not apply to most of the people in health maintenance
organizations, the Democratic version would have applied to all 161
million Americans with health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Clinton and his Democratic allies to weigh whether
to accept a small step and try again another year. But that would
mean giving Republicans an achievement they could cite in their
campaigns, even though they had done much less than what the
Democrats themselves wanted to do.
</P>
<P>
   So the president and Vice President Al Gore both signaled that
they would opt for a veto _ and a campaign issue _ unless some
markedly different bill emerges from the House. Said Sen. Edward M.
Kennedy, D-Mass., ``This isn't an issue that's going to go away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
