<HEADER>
A3294 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-TAX-NYT &LR;      07-16 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-TAX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE TAX PROPOSALS SHOW POTENTIAL FOR COMPROMISE
</HEADLINE>
   (ko) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republicans and Democrats in the Senate laid out
dueling tax-cut proposals Friday, but both sides said they saw room
for eventual compromise.
</P>
<P>
   The tone was a marked contrast to the fight over taxes in the
House, where both parties have laid out hard-line positions without
making any attempt at finding common ground.
</P>
<P>
   In a first move toward a possible deal, Democrats on the Senate
Finance Committee introduced a plan that would cut taxes by $295
billion over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic plan is far smaller than the $792 billion cut
proposed by Sen. William V. Roth Jr., R-Del., chairman of the
Finance Committee. But in a nod to Republican priorities, the
Democratic plan is built around a broad-based cut in personal
income taxes, an approach President Clinton has been resisting.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Breaux of Louisiana said Friday that he was one of a
number of Democrats open to a reduction substantially larger than
the $295 billion, though nothing as large as Roth had in mind. Like
other Democrats, he said a deal was possible in the end, although
both parties believe serious talks will come after Congress passes
and Clinton vetoes some version of the current Republican plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who has been around longer than five days in this
business knows that any kind of a major tax bill is ultimately the
result of compromises by everybody who is involved in writing the
package,'' Breaux said.
</P>
<P>
   The politics of any deal will be complicated. Not only are there
the obvious differences between the parties, but there are tensions
within each party as well. Among House Republicans a small band of
moderates is pressing the party's leadership to scale back their
$864 billion tax cut, saying money should remain available for
other issues including Medicare and spending programs.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said Friday that the House bill, which was approved
by the Ways and Means Committee on Wednesday, may well be trimmed
back to the size of the $792 billion Senate version.
</P>
<P>
   The main reason, they said, would be to avoid parliamentary
complications arising from a dispute between the House and Senate
budget committees over how large a tax cut this year's budget
outline provides for. But the chance to mollify moderate
Republicans in the House, where the party's slim 223-211 majority
means even a handful of defections can endanger its chances of
passing legislation, would be an added benefit, they said.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is just as complicated in the Senate, where Roth
laid out details of his proposal on Friday. It includes a reduction
of the bottom income tax bracket to 14 percent from 15 percent,
steps to eliminate the so-called marriage penalty that makes
two-income couples pay more taxes if they file jointly and
expansions of Individual Retirement Accounts and the 401(k)
retirement savings program.
</P>
<P>
   Roth said his plan was already a step toward compromise, since
in deference to Democratic preferences its income tax cut was
designed to benefit low- and moderate-income people as much as the
wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to put something together here that I thought
would appeal across the aisle, as well as with my own
Republicans,'' Roth said.
</P>
<P>
   The Finance Committee has a long history of bipartisan
pragmatism, and if there is to be a crucible for a compromise on
taxes this year, the committee is a likely candidate.
</P>
<P>
   But Roth has to watch his right flank, where conservatives are
grumbling about his decision to leave out of his bill some of their
priorities, including a reduction in all income tax rates and a cut
in the capital gains tax.
</P>
<P>
   By the same token, some of the most influential Democrats on the
committee, like Breaux and Bob Kerrey of Nebraska, are more open to
a big tax cut than many of their colleagues in the party as a
whole, and it is unclear how much resistance there will be among
Senate Democrats to a split-the-difference deal.
</P>
<P>
   The $295 billion proposal set out Friday by Democrats does not
move very far from the plan advocated by the White House, which
calls for a $250 billion tax cut in the form of incentives for low
and middle income households to save more for retirement.
</P>
<P>
   It is based on the principle that the projected budget surplus _
nearly $1 trillion over the next decade, excluding money earmarked
for Social Security _ should be evenly divided between tax cuts,
new spending and Medicare, said Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New
York, the senior Democrat on the Finance Committee. Clinton uses
much the same formulation.
</P>
<P>
   But its main component is one more attractive to Republicans
than the retirement savings plan offered by Clinton. It would
reduce the income tax bill for many taxpayers by substantially
increasing the standard deductions. For a married couple filing
jointly, for example, the standard deduction would increase to
$11,550 from $7,200, resulting in an annual saving of as much as
$650 for a family in the 15 percent tax bracket and as much as
$1,200 for those in the 28 percent tax bracket.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
