<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3295 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-FLAP17-COX     07-16 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-FLAP17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Forbes camp slams Bush on Iowa donations
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Six wealthy backers of George W. Bush, all
barred from giving more money to his presidential campaign because
they have reached the federal limit, have pitched in $50,000 to
help Bush at next month's Iowa straw poll.
</P>
<P>
   The news drew immediate fire from the Steve Forbes campaign,
which complained Friday that the Bush backers found a way to pump
more money into the already cash-rich Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The supporters sent checks of $10,000 or $5,000 directly to the
Iowa Republican Party to pay for the rally site leased by Bush near
the coliseum where the Aug. 14 event will be held.
</P>
<P>
   The $43,500 rental fee was set this month when the Bush campaign
was the high bidder in an auction for the sites. No other campaign
spent more than $8,000.
</P>
<P>
   Though the purchase was made by the Bush campaign and the site
will directly benefit his efforts, the fee is being paid by the six
donors, all of whom have made the $1,000 maximum contributions
federal law allows _ prompting questions of legality by the Forbes
camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``You had a campaign determine the value of that land by
bidding. They determined it was worth $43,500. Now they have
contributors write the checks,'' said Forbes aide Bill Dal Cal.
``They are using it for campaign activities. That's got to be a
campaign check to pay for it.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Bush campaign and the Iowa Republican Party say it's
legal, ethical and appreciated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Individual contributions were made to the Iowa Republican
Party. All of the money goes to the Iowa Republican Party. None of
it comes to the Bush campaign,'' said Bush spokeswoman Karen
Hughes. ``We were happy to encourage our donors to support the Iowa
Republican Party because strong state parties help all Republican
candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said the campaign looked for contributors who already had
hit the $1,000 limit ``and said they would be happy to help in any
other way.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to paying for the rally site, the money will be used
for other straw-poll related expenses, including paying the $25
admission fee for participants.
</P>
<P>
   Dee Stewart, the Iowa GOP's executive director, said the straw
poll is nothing more than a fund-raising event for the state party.
There are no limits on how much a person can donate to the party,
he noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not an election,'' he said. ``We appreciate presidential
candidates raising money for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart said the money from the Bush backers provides no direct
benefit to his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is not an election how does it directly benefit a
candidate?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Though it's not running an election, the Iowa GOP has been
generous in pitching the straw poll as a crucial landmark in the
2000 presidential contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will only succeed in the Iowa Caucus if you do well in the
straw poll,'' Iowa GOP Chairman Kayne Robinson said earlier this
year.
</P>
<P>
   A June 10 memo from the Iowa GOP told candidates the party would
accept ``individual, political candidate committee and political
action committee checks'' to cover the cost of rally sites at the
coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Four Bush backers each sent $10,000; Dallas investor Ray Hunt,
Los Angeles investment banker Bradford Freeman, Detroit businessman
Heinz Prechter and Michigan real estate investor C. Michael
Kojaian. Five thousand dollar checks were sent by Dallas investor
Louis Beecherl and Florida homebuilder John Collins.
</P>
<P>
   Bush reported Thursday that he has raised more than $37 million,
a record, for his campaign. He has about $30 million in the bank.
No other GOP contender has more than $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
