A3304 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APOLLO-MAIN17-COX     07-16 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APOLLO-MAIN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Apollo astronauts reunite for 30-year anniversary
 &HT;    By Timothy R. Gaffney
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ Thirty years from the day humans first
left Earth to walk on the moon, several Apollo astronauts gathered
here at Kennedy Space Center to remember the event _ including
Ohioan Neil Armstrong, the first man to walk on the moon.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, almost as famous for his intense privacy as his
historic first lunar footstep, even joined an afternoon press
conference with three Apollo comrades _ Buzz Aldrin, who landed on
the moon with him and was the second man to walk on the moon; Gene
Cernan, who commanded the last lunar mission in December 1972 and
was the last Apollo astronaut on the moon; and Walter Cunningham,
who checked out the lunar module in earth orbit on the first manned
Apollo flight.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong's privacy has become legendary in the three decades
since he stepped off the landing pad of the lunar module Eagle and
declared, ``That's one small step for man, one giant leap for
mankind.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the news conference, asked if he would trade his historic
achievement for more privacy, Armstrong said, ``Never.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong has long frustrated the news media for his extreme
reluctance to grant interviews. But Cernan chided the throng of
reporters for resenting Armstrong's privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would just like to say, you know, it could have been anyone
who walked on the moon. ... But I can't think of anyone _ anyone _
who having had that opportunity could have handled it with as much
grace and as honor and dignity as Neil Armstrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some of his colleagues, and to the disappointment of many
space-exploration advocates, Armstrong has never been a strong
public lobbyist for returning to the moon or sending people to
Mars.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a compelling reason for society to go back to the
moon. That case will not be made by anyone here,'' but by
scientists, Armstrong said.
</P>
<P>
   He said America is still making giant leaps in space
exploration, including the International Space Station. He added,
``If I picked one that was important to me, it would be going to
Mars.''
</P>
<P>
   The astronauts were in town for a gala anniversary dinner that
included an estimated 1,000 NASA employees and contractors who
worked on the program, and took part in a host of other activities
that will run through Tuesday, the 30th anniversary of the first
moon landing.
</P>
<P>
   The ground here shook at 9:32 a.m. on July 16, 1969, as a
towering Saturn V rocket rose majestically skyward with the Apollo
11 space vehicles perched atop it.
</P>
<P>
   Four days later, Armstrong and Aldrin landed the lunar module
Eagle on the Sea of Tranquility while Michael Collins waited in the
orbiting command module Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Three decades later, the pioneering astronauts and their
achievements still drew world attention.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong said the enduring interest has been ``a pleasant
surprise,'' but Aldrin said the juxtaposition of the anniversary
with the end of the millennium has combined to heighten interest
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham said Americans old enough to remember the flight of
Apollo 11 look back for a particular feeling it gave them.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think back to that feeling you had that Americans could do
anything,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The dinner was held in NASA's Saturn V Center, where tables were
set under a mighty Saturn V rocket just like the ones that hurled
humans to another world.
</P>
<P>
   A few miles to the east, space shuttle Columbia stood poised to
light the night sky just after midnight on Tuesday when it roars
off its launch pad to deliver the Chandra X-ray space observatory
into orbit.
</P>
<P>
   In marked contrast to the male-dominated Apollo era, Columbia's
five-person crew will be commanded by a woman, Air Force Col.
Eileen Collins. Another woman, former Wright-Patterson Air Force
Base research chemist Lt. Col. Catherine G. ``Cady'' Coleman, is a
mission specialist making her second shuttle flight.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong expressed no doubts about Collins' ability to do the
job.
</P>
<P>
   ``From everything I've heard, Eileen Collins is a very well
qualified and very able commander,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
