<HEADER>
A3310 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONVERTED-RABBI-TEX     07-16 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONVERTED-RABBI-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS RABBI IS JEWISH BY CHOICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TARA DOOLEY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In his early life, Rabbi Geoffrey Dennis felt God's presence
following him, just over his shoulder but out of immediate reach.
</P>
<P>
   God followed Dennis through his Protestant childhood _ one
influenced by a mother whose charity, spirituality and
understanding of the Bible modeled for him the characteristics of a
religious life.
</P>
<P>
   God was seated over his shoulder when Dennis, as a teen, needled
the pastor of the Lutheran church his family attended with tough
questions during Confirmation class.
</P>
<P>
   But God was also out of immediate reach as Dennis contemplated
the story of Jesus in Gethsemane, as depicted in church
stained-glass windows, and pondered why his suffering was
considered different from the suffering of others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to admit that right from the very beginning, I felt a
certain disconnect with the church,'' Dennis said. ``It was
difficult to find my connection to God through Christianity.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Dennis said, he found a connection to God at a local
synagogue, a discovery that marked an end of years of searching and
led him to convert from Christianity to Judaism when he was 23.
</P>
<P>
   The transition placed Dennis, 39, in an emerging group of
Americans who leave the faiths of their families to find a new
spiritual home among a variety of religious traditions imported to
a predominantly Christian United States by generations of
immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   For many who change faiths, this process is a journey to a new
spirituality, community and culture. Dennis, who this month became
the first full-time rabbi at Congregation Kol Ami in Flower Mound,
a Dallas suburb, is no exception.
</P>
<P>
   He looked, for example, to Sikhs, Taoists, Buddhists and
American Indian religions before finding a glimmer of a connection
after reading a book on Judaism while in college. The connection
was really ignited later, as Dennis plowed through the stacks at
the temple library at Congregation Albert in his hometown of
Albuquerque, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I had been a lost soul who found a place to come
home,'' Dennis said.
</P>
<P>
   Judaism's emphasis on moral responsibility and personal
accountability felt comfortable to him and also appealed to him
intellectually, an aspect of religion that wasn't communicated to
him in the churches he attended, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Judaism, God does not treat us like children,'' Dennis
said. ``He expects us to be adults and be responsible for our
actions.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Jewish understanding of family and community
and their importance as the centerpiece of a person's life ``spoke
powerfully'' to him, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In America, we are so individualistic that we lose sight of
the fact that human beings are communal animals,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After becoming what some call a Jew by choice, Dennis eventually
entered Hebrew Union College and committed himself to a life of
teaching and leading a Jewish community. He spent three years as an
assistant rabbi in Indianapolis before taking the Flower Mound
position.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was obvious that his process of conversion was more than
just a matter of fact, an element to fill some sort of
requirement,'' said Rabbi Paul J. Citrin, who was a mentor for
Dennis at Congregation Albert, where Dennis converted. ``He got
into it very personally and very deeply.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennis described converting to Judaism as a gradual process of
explanation, study and understanding. It does not come thundering
down as a revelation, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, scholars of Judaism have argued about whether the faith
really accepts converts, said Egon Mayer, director of the Jewish
Outreach Institute at the Graduate School of the City University of
New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically, Judaism is not a conversionary faith,'' Mayer
said. ``It has never sought converts, certainly not in the past
2,000 years. But that tradition has begun to change in a curious
way since about 1979. The principal reason is interfaith
marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   By 1990, a survey showed that up to 5 percent of American Jews
were Jews by choice, and the trend appears to be continuing, Mayer
said.
</P>
<P>
   But conversion is hardly a door-to-door enterprise for Jewish
congregations. Instead, it is part of the tradition that starts in
a way that would make the average evangelical blanch. The Talmud
specifically states that a rabbi's first obligation when talking
with someone who wishes to convert is to discourage the person.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis says he responds to potential converts by encouraging
them to first take a six-month class in which they read Jewish
texts. The study is also a time to let the passion cool and allow
reason and discovery of faith to set in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Judaism prefers its converts to come with a
reflective, informed consent,'' Dennis said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the lack of evangelistic ardor is that Jews believe
anyone can have a relationship with God, Dennis said, and
membership in a synagogue is not a requirement to know God.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Judaism, there is no need to make people Jewish,'' Dennis
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Talmud offers a five-part conversion process that follows a
formal discouragement with extensive education. Next, a Beit Din, a
community of at least three members, gathers to discuss Judaism and
witness the conversion. Then males are circumcised or are asked to
offer a ceremonial drop of blood. Lastly, the convert is immersed
in a bath, Dennis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baptism _ they got it from us,'' he said, referring to the
Christian initiation ritual.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of conversionary zeal also has a cultural side.
Converting to Judaism is taking on a community that has known
persecution but also enjoys a rich history and close bonds. Most
Jewish rituals are practiced in the home, and many require the
participation of other Jews.
</P>
<P>
   The family of Dennis' wife, Robin, helped to enrich his
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a cultural peace that comes with being Jewish that
one needs to learn,'' Dennis said. ``I had a very involved Jewish
family to be my mentors. They made my entree into Jewish life very
easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Since coverting to Judaism, Dennis says, God is not over his
shoulder, behind him or out of his reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the place where I felt I was speaking to God face to
face,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
