<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PANEL VOTES TO CUT FUNDING FOR F-22 FIGHTER JET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Subs to change wording in 2nd graf to `finance' from `build'
and move up comments from Rep. Bill Young. Adds transitional graf
after Hastert quote. No pickup.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphics clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(th) 
 By TIM WEINER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Leaders of both parties said Friday that the House
is prepared to cut off money to finance the Air Force's $70-billion
F-22 fighter program, a highly unusual decision that has stunned
the Pentagon and military contractors.
</P>
<P>
   The stage for a full House vote next week was set Friday when
the House Appropriations Committee unanimously approved a
$268-billion Pentagon spending bill denying the Air Force the $1.8
billion it sought to finance the first six F-22s. The cutoff is
supported by Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., Minority Leader
Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., and key Republican leaders who say the
fledgling fighter is simply too expensive to build at about $200
million a plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to concentrate on those things that work,'' Hastert
said.
</P>
<P>
   The move against the F-22 came from some of the most
military-minded senior Republicans in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Young, R-Fla., who is chairman of the Appropriations
Committee and a long-time champion of the F-22, said Friday in an
interview, ``The Air Force's money and everything in the Air
Force's mind is focused on the F-22.''
</P>
<P>
   But Young, who in 29 years in Congress has been a stalwart
advocate of defense spending, said the Air Force needs well-paid
pilots, spare parts and refurbished jets more than it needs the
F-22.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to fix it,'' he said of the Air Force. ``Now, can we
fix it if we put all our money into one basket? No, we can't. It
would be far better to stop, take a look at where we are, and to
make a decision that will last into the future.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon reacted fiercely. ``This decision, if enacted,
would for all practical purposes kill the F-22 program, the
cornerstone of our nation's global air power in the 21st century,''
Defense Secretary William Cohen said Friday in a letter to
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing quite like this has happened in decades, according to
senior members of Congress and veterans of Pentagon spending wars.
Congress almost never kills major weapons systems that are about to
reach the assembly line. And the F-22 is the biggest Air Force
weapons program of all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a remarkable occurrence, one of the rarest
imaginable,'' said Dale Bumpers, who retired from the Senate in
1998 after 24 years, and now heads the Center for Defense
Information in Washington. ``I'm absolutely amazed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force wanted to buy the first F-22 fighter jets this
year, even though its flight tests have barely begun, its on-board
computers are not ready and its cost has grown to $200 million
apiece, roughly four times the cost of the F-15, the plane it was
intended to replace.
</P>
<P>
   The House Appropriations Committee tried to cut off funds for
the F-22 10 years ago, calling it a financial disaster waiting to
happen. But that was when the plane was in the early stages of
research and development, not on the verge of full production.
About $20 billion has been spent on research and development since
the plane was first proposed in 1981, and two test models have been
built.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon and Congress occasionally scuttle planes, bombs and
missiles on the drawing board, or choose to build fewer weapons
than originally planned once production has started. But very
rarely, if ever, do they block the initial production of a major
weapons system deemed ready to build.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, the House tried to kill funds for the B-2 bomber, but
the bill was defeated on the floor. Defense Secretary Dick Cheney
killed another Air Force program, the A-12, in the research and
development phase in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The move to kill the F-22 has flabbergasted the Air Force, the
Pentagon and military contractors, who were expecting widespread
congressional support for significant military spending increases
after the war in Yugoslavia. They are already heavily lobbying
senators to countermand the House's move when the military spending
bill comes to a House-Senate conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand how they arrived at this specific
decision,'' said Bob Rearden, program manager for the F-22 at
Lockheed Martin, the military contracting giant that is to build
the plane.
</P>
<P>
   Why is this happening? Money, senior House members said.
</P>
<P>
   The recently retired chairman of Lockheed Martin, Norman
Augustine, once predicted: ``In the year 2054, the entire defense
budget will purchase just one tactical aircraft.'' Maybe he wasn't
joking, Congress is now realizing.
</P>
<P>
   The $70-billion price tag on the F-22 program far exceeds this
year's entire budget of $53 billion for buying weapons and
represents roughly 25 percent of the annual cost of every
government agency outside the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   And the F-22 is only one of three different fighters the
Pentagon wants to buy for the four armed services. They would cost,
all told, $350 billion _ far more than the entire annual defense
budget.
</P>
<P>
   There may be more to the decision than money alone. It might
never have happened if Newt Gingrich were still the speaker,
members said. The plane is to be built in Marietta, Ga., in
Gingrich's old district.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   And there are deeper issues involved, some of which may be
personal and political.
</P>
<P>
   The House Appropriations Committee's report on the proposed
Pentagon budget, released Friday, suggests that the Air Force may
have been less than forthcoming with Congress about the F-22's
costs and capabilities, and the urgency to build it.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force told Congress 10 years ago that it could build 750
F-22s for $67.5 billion. It now appears that a similar sum would
buy no more than 339 planes. The cost per plane has gone from $90
million to roughly $200 million, auditors say, and the Air Force
has understated the F-22's true cost by $9 billion or more.
</P>
<P>
   The House report said there have been problems with the plane's
wings, brakes, fuselage, fuel lines and engines, and that its
on-board computer systems remain untested. Senior Air Force
officials acknowledged no technical problems with the F-22.
Rearden, of Lockheed Martin, said they have been fixed. ``There are
no show-stopping technical issues,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force officials said they face a threat from foreign
aircraft like the Russian MiG-29 that they cannot overcome without
the F-22. ``We can no longer guarantee that we'll be able to
dominate the sky,'' said Maj. Gen. Bruce Carlson, director of Air
Force operational requirements.
</P>
<P>
   But the committee report said that, 10 years from now, ``the
United States will have a 5-to-1 numerical advantage of advanced
fighters against our most challenging adversaries without the
F-22.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee said the F-15, which the F-22 was supposed to
replace, has at least 15 or 20 years of life left in it, and that
the Joint Strike Fighter, which is being developed for the Air
Force, Navy and Marines, will be in service by then.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money's not there,'' said Rep. John Murtha of
Pennsylvania, the ranking Democrat on the Appropriations Committee.
``There's no threat like the Soviet threat hanging over us. The
time is right to stop this thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
