<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mission is giant step for women
 &HT;    By Timothy R. Gaffney
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ NASA will be launching more than a space shuttle
when it sends Eileen Collins into orbit Tuesday to command her
first space mission.
</P>
<P>
   NASA Administrator Dan Goldin said Friday he has directed NASA
to work closely with a locally based organization to encourage more
women to take up aviation or technical careers.
</P>
<P>
   Peggy Baty, president of Women in Aviation International Inc.,
met with Goldin in Washington, D.C., on Wednesday to discuss a
``partnership'' with NASA to prepare educational materials that
members will distribute in school programs around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Baty runs the organization from her home and private airstrip in
West Alexandria.
</P>
<P>
   Goldin said the partnership was an idea he put to Women in
Aviation last march when he spoke at their annual convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I challenged them to have each one of them spend an hour a
week going to schools around the country to talk to students,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Goldin called the lack of scientists and engineers in America
``a national problem,'' but he said women represent a virtually
untapped pool of talent because they make up only a small
percentage of the professionals in those fields.
</P>
<P>
   Baty said she plans to attend the shuttle launch Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's historically significant because this is the first time a
woman has served as commander of a space shuttle mission,'' Baty
said. ``I think this will serve as an inspiration to young people,
particularly young women, to pursue careers in aviation and
aerospace.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins, who will be making her third space shuttle flight, was
the first woman to be trained as a space shuttle pilot, and she has
been active in Women in Aviation since 1994, Baty said. Baty joined
Collins at the White House last year when First Lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton announced Collins' assignment as mission commander.
</P>
<P>
   Goldin said he is still considering the idea of flying an
all-female space shuttle mission, but he said it's still under
review.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he doesn't want to offend some women astronauts by
proposing something that might be regarded as a political stunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of women who fought hard to get into the
astronaut corps, and we don't want to demean their roles.''
</P>
<P>
   THE COLUMBIA MISSION AT A GLANCE
</P>
<P>
   Launch Vehicle: Columbia
</P>
<P>
   Mission: STS-93, Chandra X-ray Observatory
</P>
<P>
   Launch: Tuesday, July 20, 12:36 a.m. EDT
</P>
<P>
   Launch window: 46 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Mission duration: 4 days, 23 hours
</P>
<P>
   Orbit altitude: 176 miles
</P>
<P>
   Landing: Kennedy Space Center, July 24, 11:31 p.m. EDT
</P>
<P>
   CREW
</P>
<P>
   Eileen Collins, USAF Col., commander
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey S. Ashby, pilot
</P>
<P>
   Catherine G. ``Cady'' Coleman, USAF Lt. Col., mission specialist
1
</P>
<P>
   Steven A. Hawley,
</P>
<P>
   mission specialist 2
</P>
<P>
   Michel Tognini, France,
</P>
<P>
   mission specialist 3
</P>
<P>
   HIGHLIGHTS
</P>
<P>
   Chandra will be the equivalent of the Hubble Telescope in
imaging the X-ray universe. This will be the first mission
commanded by a woman. Coleman is a former Wright-Patterson Air
Force Base research chemist.
</P>
