<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LENDERS REGARD MEXICAN ECONOMY WITH SUSPICION
</HEADLINE>
  (ko) 
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Mexico's stock market and economic statistics are
among the healthiest in Latin America. But the failure of two major
companies to meet debt payments this week focused attention on the
plight of scores of other heavily indebted businesses, marooned
without credit by the country's four-year banking crisis.
</P>
<P>
   One of Mexico's largest construction companies, Bufete
Industrial SA, announced that it could not meet a $100 million debt
payment that had been due on Thursday. Grupo Dina, the country's
largest bus and truck manufacturer, missed a $6.6 million bond
payment the same day.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's largest steel maker and its other two largest
industrial builders have also either defaulted on debt payments or
announced major losses in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the developments illustrated how Mexico's economy
was increasingly divided into a robust sector of elite companies
that have free access to foreign credit and scores of lesser ones
that can attract capital only at disadvantageous terms or are cut
off altogether.
</P>
<P>
   The string of defaults here this year could make the financial
challenge faced by most Mexican companies even more formidable as
foreign lenders look with increased suspicion at the Mexican
economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Telmex, Cemex, Alfa, Televisa, huge companies like that are
really special cases because they have long histories of dealing
with foreign banks, and have no problem getting foreign credit,''
said Pedro Javier Gonzalez, an economist at Mexico City's Institute
of Political Studies. ``But there are dozens of businesses in good
condition that will have more difficulty getting credit because of
the reputation Mexico now has for defaults.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's economy grew by 4.8 percent in 1998 and is expected to
grow perhaps 3 percent this year, showing more robust strength than
any other major Latin economy. The Mexican stock market's main
index is up nearly 58 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   But the banking and construction sectors still have not
recovered from the 1994 peso crisis, said Damian Fraser, head of
Mexico research at Warburg Dillon Read.
</P>
<P>
   The government has spent $65 billion since 1995 to clean up 13
collapsed banks, and last month authorities announced that they
would have to inject huge new sums into two more, Grupo Financiero
Serfin SA and Bancrecer SA, to restore their solvency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yet credit has fallen every year, and there's still no sign of
recovery by the banks,'' Fraser said. ``Construction companies,
which need to borrow heavily to finance projects, have been hit
hard by the lack of credit, by a squeeze in public sector
investment and by foreign competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Grupo Tribasa SA, the country's second-largest builder, missed a
$26 million payment on a $150 million bond in March. Over the weeks
since, Tribasa has sought to restructure its debts by selling
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Altos Hornos de Mexico SA, the country's largest steel
manufacturer, announced that it had missed a $39 million loan
payment. The company, burdened by $1.8 billion in debt and plunging
steel prices, is negotiating a merger with a Monterrey
conglomerate, Grupo Imsa.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Bufete Industrial announced that it would seek to
restructure $140 million in short-term debt, but on Wednesday it
announced that it could not meet a $100 million Eurobond payment
due on Thursday. The company specializes in building oil rigs and
electric power stations, and one of its biggest customers, the
state-owned electricity generating company, CFE, has been short of
cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oil prices have been low, and the government has cut the
budgets of Pemex and the CFE, Bufete's biggest clients,'' said
Sobani Warner, a construction industry analyst at Bear Stearns in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   Grupo Dina, the bus and truck manufacturer, also has been
attempting to restructure a crushing debt load. In June it sold a
61 percent stake in MCII Holdings, a motor coach company based in
Des Plaines, Ill., raising $125 million.
</P>
<P>
   The string of missed payments is aggravating nervousness among
foreign lenders about the solvency of all but the largest Mexican
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's having trouble getting foreign credit now, and
weaker companies really may have trouble financing,'' said Victor
Manuel Herrera, a managing director of Standard &AMP; Poor's in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``When there are defaults, it affects the image of the
country,'' he said. ``Healthier companies will have to convince
investors and banks that there's no generalized problem in
Mexico.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
