<HEADER>
A3328 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX     07-16 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVE WOMEN A SPORTING CHANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I think I played kickball once.
</P>
<P>
   As I understand it, that isn't exactly the same as soccer, but
it's the closest I'll ever get to the game that put America on top
of the world this month.
</P>
<P>
   And you might say it's as close as I'll ever get to being an
athlete. I think I was OK with that until the U.S. women's soccer
team defeated China to win the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Girls rule! Boys drool! Soccer's cool,'' the chant went.
</P>
<P>
   I haven't cared much for sports since I stopped drooling for
Jimmy Carstafnur and stopped cheering for the McComb High School
Tigers back in 1975. But while watching the replays and the
jubilation surrounding the U.S. team's victory, I had this sudden
urge to play a sport, to be part of a winning team.
</P>
<P>
   I think I played softball once. What I remember most is that no
one wanted me on their team.
</P>
<P>
   Briana Scurry. Brandi Chastain. Sunday, I was one of them,
albeit much older and with a lot less athletic talent. They and
their teammates are America's new female role models and heroes.
There are even two 31-year-old mothers on the team, real soccer
moms. We've come a long way. Or have we?
</P>
<P>
   You think so until something like this happens, and you're
reminded of how slowly the clock ticks for us. Women's sports still
get less news coverage and female professional athletes (and, I
might add, women in general) still make less money than their male
counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   A news story said that these pioneers, for instance, will make
less for winning the World Cup (a $12,500 bonus) than Los Angeles
Dodgers pitcher Kevin Brown gets for retiring one batter.
</P>
<P>
   And at the 1996 Atlanta Olympics, women's soccer was deemed not
ready for prime-time television. The United States defeated China
2-1 before 76,000 to win the medal, but NBC aired only 10 minutes
of previously taped highlights.
</P>
<P>
   That isn't the sort of thing you want to read about if you're a
mother of two little girls. Not in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, you soothe yourself with the gains that have been made.
The triumphant women in the photographs, smiling at you from the TV
screen, that's you and what you might become.
</P>
<P>
   That's your hope for your little girls. If you have lived long
enough, though, you know from experience that some doors are still
shut because of gender. Because it happened to you, someone will
look at them, and whether they say it or not, decide that a man
needs the job more because he's got a family to support.
</P>
<P>
   A guy told me once to ``stop b-------.'' Funny, we still live in
a world where men offer ``constructive criticism,'' but a woman is
called a complainer or worse for doing the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   When I got off a plane from Seattle and saw Scurry and Chastain
and their teammates on the front page of this newspaper, for a
brief moment thought I might be dreaming.
</P>
<P>
   I wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   I can't play soccer, but maybe my daughters will one day. Maybe
they'll be paid the same respect, the same dollars as men. Maybe
one day I can imagine people opening ALL the world's doors to them,
as a mother imagines for her sons.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe one day I won't have to dream. It'll just be.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
