<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3331 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      07-16 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   France: Libya Pays $31 Million for Bombing Plane &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Libya has transferred $31 million to France to compensate
families of the 171 people killed when a French airliner was blown
up over the African desert in 1989, officials said. A French court
that convicted six high-ranking Libyan officials in absentia this
year ordered Libya to pay compensation for the bombing, which
occurred at a time of tension between the two countries over Chad.
The French Foreign Ministry said the payment was acknowledgment by
Libya that its officials were responsible for the deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Russia: Journalist Denies Treason &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Grigory Pasko, a journalist and former naval captain charged
with selling state secrets after he filmed reports for Japanese
television on the navy's dumping of nuclear waste, said at his
trial that his prosecution is the act of ``a Stalin-like regime.''
Pasko, whose release has been sought by international human rights
groups, said he is guilty only ``of honestly doing my duty as a
journalist.'' A verdict is due on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Spain: Move to Ease Racial Tension &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The government's chief spokesman, Josep Pique, appealed for calm
after a week of racial violence in Terrassa, near Barcelona, where
residents from Morocco and other North African nations were
attacked, resulting in several injuries and property damage. Tens
of thousands of Africans have sought jobs in an
economically-buoyant Spain in recent years, and the spokesman said
Spaniards should remember their own past lean times, when many were
forced to seek work elsewhere in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil: Cardoso Shuffles Cabinet &QL;
</P>
<P>
   President Fernando Henrique Cardoso shuffled his Cabinet for the
second time in seven months to regain authority in an
administration plagued by infighting. Cardoso moved ministers in
several economic posts and named a new official to negotiate with
Congress, yet kept Pedro Malan as finance minister to ease concern
over possible disruptions in economic policy. The changes are seen
as enlarging the influence of Cardoso's Social Democrat Party
within the governing five-party coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Key Baja Aide Quits &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general of Baja California, Marco Antonio de la
Fuente Villarreal, has resigned after a series of street protests
over the violent crime that is rampant there, with more than 300
murders so far this year, most drug related and unsolved. The Baja
legislature confirmed his replacement, Manuel Salazar Pimentel, the
brother-in-law of Gov. Alejandro Gonzalez Alcocer. De la Fuente's
predecessor resigned in 1997 after drug gunmen, in an assassination
attempt, wounded a Tijuana publisher whose newspaper accused the
attorney general of collusion with traffickers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   Congo: U.N. Peacekeeping Plan &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Secretary General Kofi Annan of the United Nations proposed a
``large and expensive'' peacekeeping operation for Congo and
recommended the immediate dispatch of up to 90 military personnel,
followed by up to 500 military observers. He warned in a report to
the Security Council that a peacekeeping operation in Congo will
``require the deployment of thousands of international troops and
personnel.''
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   East Timor: Talks at U.N. End &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Officials from Indonesia and Portugal ended two days of talks at
the United Nations on maintaining security in East Timor, a former
Portuguese colony, after a planned referendum on independence from
Indonesia. A U.N. mediator, Jamsheed Marker of Pakistan, said he
was concerned about possible disturbances after the result of the
vote, on Aug. 21 or 22, is announced.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
