nationalists have used tactics ranging from endless negotiations to
rock-throwing mobs to prevent the town council from meeting. But in
a scene difficult to imagine only a few months ago, two dozen
Muslim politicians calmly sat down with 20 of their Serb
counterparts in the lobby of a local hotel on June 29 and held the
inaugural session of the town council of what they called the ``new
Srebrenica.'' By David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   EMBASSY-CLOSINGS-REVIEW (Washington) _ The closing of American
embassies, those flag-flying symbols of American power and
influence, was once about as common as a snowstorm on the
palm-shaded beaches of Madagascar. But in the year since terrorist
bombs destroyed American embassies in Kenya and Tanzania, 67
American embassies and consulates have been closed for some period
of time for security reasons. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   RECYCLED-TV-REVIEW _ These days, it's no longer a question of
which television shows, no matter how crummy, become movies. The
question now is which ones don't. And the answer, increasingly, is
precious few. By Thomas Vinciguerra.
</P>
<P>
   PUNITIVE-DAMAGES-REVIEW _ Sending messages is the purpose of
punitive damages, defined by law as punishment for especially
outrageous conduct. But do juries go too far? By William Glaberson.
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINE-SAFETY-REVIEW (Washington) _ Pleas for justice are
routine after an airplane crash, and they are generally played out
in civil courts, where survivors and relatives of victims sue for
damages. But last week, in a surprising move, prosecutors won
criminal indictments against a maintenance company, two mechanics
and a superior in the crash of a Valujet plane in the Everglades in
1996. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-CARE-REVIEW (Washington) _ After listening to the
rancorous debate in the Senate over health-care reform last week,
it would seem obvious that differences between Democrats and
Republicans are profound. But removed from the context of
election-year politics, combatants on both sides make it clear
there is plenty of room to compromise on a way to give Americans
some protection from health-care plans that wrongly skimp on
coverage. By Michael Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-BILLBOARDS-REVIEW _ Whether it rains or freezes, and
even if you don't have a plastic Jesus on the dashboard of your
car, you might have a hard time avoiding reminders of the Lord on
highways across the country this summer. Since last fall,
billboards and signs bearing specific messages have appeared on
roads in some 40 states from Alaska to Texas. But not everyone's
ecstatic. By Tom Kuntz.
</P>
<P>
