<SLUG> BC-GA-Y2K17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Y2K status of key services uncertain
 &HT;    By Julie B. Hairston
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A summary of 8,000 reports to the state on the readiness of
computer systems for the next millennium appears to raise concern
about such critical institutions as hospitals and law enforcement
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   But Gov. Roy Barnes and state officials who reviewed the summary
report Friday expressed confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm comfortable enough in this process that I'm not digging a
bomb shelter out at the Governor's Mansion and stocking it with
water and rice cakes,'' Barnes said.
</P>
<P>
   Only a third of police, fire and 911 units statewide returned
the surveys. Gary McConnell, director of the Georgia Emergency
Management Agency, said he is meeting with police chiefs and
deputies around the state about their Y2K readiness. He predicted
that by Sept. 15, when the next report is issued, the response rate
will be between 80 percent and 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals had a high response rate, but almost a third of those
responding received red, or ``danger,'' scores, while less than 4
percent received green, or ``ready,'' scores. The Georgia Hospital
Association is working with its members to improve the outlook,
according to Executive Director Joseph Parker.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the green range were most water systems, electric
companies and telephone systems.
</P>
<P>
   The State of Georgia Citizens' Y2K Task Force, appointed by the
governor, sent 8,000 surveys to organizations in 29 categories
statewide, including emergency services, law enforcement agencies,
utilities and pollution control plants. The surveys asked how much
progress had been made toward dealing with the ``Y2K bug.''
</P>
<P>
   Some computers and computer programs are designed only to
recognize the last two digits of the year. So, when the year 2000
clicks in, they will recognize it as 1900. This could cause
computer problems ranging from miscalculations to complete
shutdown.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes said Georgia is unique among states in its effort to
compile, analyze and disseminate comprehensive data on the state of
Y2K preparations for essential services.
</P>
<P>
   The surveys are intended to determine what local governments and
utilities are doing to prevent the Y2K bug from interrupting
essential services, including hospitals; police and fire
departments; power, gas and water companies; and water and
wastewater departments. ``If you're not ready for Y2K, or if you
did not respond to this survey, so that we can make sure that
you're ready, it is time to get to work,'' Barnes said. ``The
people of Georgia are going to hold all 8,000 of these entities
accountable on January the first.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes said the task force will issue two more reports before
the end of 1999 and agencies that refuse to respond may be subject
to legal sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   The worst response rate was among police and fire departments.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes speculated law enforcement officials may have been too
busy to worry about filling out the survey. ``I don't think it's a
matter of intent,'' he said. ``It's just a matter of priorities.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's police, fire and 911 agencies were all rated in the
red, as were Gwinnett County's police and 911 departments.
</P>
<P>
   Utilities not only had a high response rate, but most,
particularly the state's largest electric and telephone companies,
reported they are either Y2K compliant or soon will be.
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals, heavily laden with high-tech equipment, are working
feverishly to become Y2K compliant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very confident that we are on track for our target date
of Sept. 30, `` said Pat Bowers, communications director for
Atlanta's Northside Hospital. ``We're taking care of people's
lives, so we're making sure we're ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Information from the surveys has been posted on a Web site at
www.year2000ga.org ``so that all citizens of this state can hold
their providers of essential services responsible and accountable
for where they stand in regard to Y2K,'' Barnes said. Barnes said
overall he is comfortable with the level of Y2K readiness _ and
plans to spend New Year's Eve in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
