A3338 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SERIAL-KILLER-HNS &LR;      07-16 1279
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERIAL-KILLER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPECT DOES NOT BELIEVE TEXAS LAWMEN `BETRAYED' HIM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional ending) 
 
By STEVE BREWER 
and MARIA LUISA PEREZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Mexican authorities said Friday that accused serial
killer Angel Maturino Resendez told them he did not feel Texas
law-enforcement officials had ``betrayed'' him by not ruling out
the death penalty in return for his surrender.
</P>
<P>
   He said, rather, that he had been promised `humanitarian'
treatment and did not believe that includes the death penalty, said
Marco Dosal, press attache for the Mexican Consulate in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Maturino Resendez's brother told reporters Thursday that the
family felt the officers who arranged the surrender had
``betrayed'' them by not taking the death penalty off the table.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Consul Jose Mendoza Caamano and Federico Guerra from the
consul's protection office met with Maturnio Resendez and his
attorney, Allen Turner, for two hours Friday in the Harris County
jail in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Maturino Resendez, a 39-year-old Mexican citizen previously
known as Rafael Resendez-Ramirez, is charged in Harris County with
the burglary of the home of Dr. Claudia Benton, but he is expected
to be charged with her murder soon. He has also been linked to
eight other slayings.
</P>
<P>
   Tanner acknowledged Friday that the betrayal his client's family
feels was probably rooted in a disagreement over semantics, a
difference in cultures and their naive lack of understanding of
Texas law.
</P>
<P>
   Tanner said the family has told him that no Texas lawmen ever
promised that the death penalty would not be pursued. As strange as
it sounds, he said, they simply feel that the word ``humanely''
means no death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people in Texas and around Texas know that it's a big
death penalty state,'' Tanner said. ``A lot of people in Mexico
might not know that.''
</P>
<P>
   Dosal said the two consular officials had a ``cordial''
interview with Maturino Resendez, whom they described as ``very
calm'' and ``non-expressive.''
</P>
<P>
   The subject of his guilt or innocence did not come up, he said.
``The main objective was just to talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Dosal said he asked the consulate to help his defense and was
told that officials would observe the legal process and ensure that
he is treated the same as any defendant.
</P>
<P>
   The two officials also asked him how his last name is spelled
and were told ``Resendiz.'' Maturino Resendez said he had several
names because his family registered in Mexico under different
names, for ``personal'' reasons that he declined to explain.
</P>
<P>
   But in court papers, the formal charge still spells it
``Resendez.''
</P>
<P>
   Dosal said Maturino Resendez had asked to be served kosher food
while in jail ``because he described himself as
''Christian-Jewish.''
</P>
<P>
   Tanner has said he hopes the consulate can make some type of
legal or diplomatic plea to help Maturino Resendez avoid the death
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Also Friday, the FBI denied that there was any arrangement that
Mexican authorities ignore U.S. efforts to capture the fugitive or
get him to surrender on U.S. soil.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely not,'' Don K. Clark, head of the FBI's Houston
office, said. ``In fact, I personally kept in contact with the
consul general here in Houston to advise him, to the extent that we
could, on what transpired so the Mexican government would not be
surprised. We had talked to the Mexican government, but this was
not a turn-your-back type of situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexican police said Maturino Resendez never tried to surrender
to them, which could have started an international dispute over his
extradition.
</P>
<P>
   The state judicial police commander in Ciudad Juarez, Armando
Castillo, said, ``We tried to interview him, but we didn't find him
or even see him.''
</P>
<P>
   Castillo confirmed that his officers tried to find Maturino
Resendez in Juarez after receiving reports that he had been seen
there.
</P>
<P>
   Although there was no arrest warrant in Mexico for Maturino
Resendez, Castillo said authorities had been asked by the Interpol
office in Mexico City to detain him long enough to determine his
identity.
</P>
<P>
   He denied any prior knowledge that Maturino Resendez was going
to surrender. He also said he never heard of any bounty hunters
searching for Maturino Resendez.
</P>
<P>
   He has also been charged with a capital murder in the East Texas
town of Hughes Springs, is a suspect in five others in Texas,
including two in Harris County, and has been linked to murders in
Kentucky, where he has been charged, and in Illinois, where he has
not.
</P>
<P>
   Harris County is holding him in the Dec. 17 burglary of the West
University Place home of Benton, who was stabbed, raped and beaten
to death. West University Place is an enclave of Houston.
Prosecutors are not going to charge him with her murder until they
receive DNA test results, although Anderson says fingerprints
already have placed him at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   The DNA tests also could link Maturino Resendez to the death of
Noemi Dominguez, 26, who was killed in her Houston home in June.
Prosecutors also could file capital murder charges in that case,
but the evidence is more likely to be used in the punishment phase
of a trial for Benton's murder, if there's a conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Harris County Assistant District Attorney Lyn McClellan, who
will likely help lead prosecutor Devon Anderson in the case, said
Maturino Resendez complaint about ``humanitarian'' treatment is
just symptomatic of what a lot of criminal defendants experience _
a regret at having cooperated in any way with authorities.
</P>
<P>
   A promise that Maturino Resendez would not get the death penalty
would only be a problem for prosecutors if he had given authorities
a confession based on that, McClellan said, but that did not
happen.
</P>
<P>
   McClellan said someone's nationality makes no difference in
prosecuting any case, and pleas from other governments for leniency
don't do any good either.
</P>
<P>
   McClellan said he knows of no state law that requires local
authorities to advise foreign nationals of their right under the
1963 Vienna Convention on Consular Relations to ask their
government for help.
</P>
<P>
   But in this case, Maturino Resendez was advised of that right
twice _ once in El Paso after he surrendered and again Thursday in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was done out of an abundance of caution because that
issue is being raised all the time now,'' McClellan said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Advising people of those rights was an issue in the case of Joseph
Standley Faulder, the first Canadian in almost a half-century to be
executed in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Faulder was executed in Texas in June despite pleas from the
Canadian government and U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
   Faulder's attorneys tried to argue that Canadian officials
should have been told sooner of his arrest and detention and Texas
authorities should have informed Faulder of his right to contact
the Canadian government for help.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1998, Arizona executed Jose Roberto Villafuerte, a
45-year-old Honduran, for killing a woman in 1983. His government,
the Vatican and the State Department maintained he was denied his
rights as a foreigner under the Vienna Convention.
</P>
<P>
   A similar case in Virginia reached the U.S. Supreme Court.
Paraguayan national Angel Francisco Breard argued that his death
sentence for stabbing a woman to death was illegal because his
country did not know of his arrest or conviction. The Supreme Court
refused to block his execution.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Chronicle reporters Armando Villafranca and James Pinkerton
contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
