<P>
   (NYT30) ATLANTA -- July 16, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 18 --
MULES18-1-COX, 07-16 -- Men's brown leather mule/slide. Dog days
got you sniffing around for a way to cool your heels this summer?
Then consider the stylishness and simplicity of the hottest and
coolest trend in footwear: the mule. (Jean Shifrin/Atlanta
Journal-Constitution Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) HEBRON, West Bank -- July 16, 1999 --
BARAK-PALESTINE17-COX, 07-16 -- An Israeli soldier gives
instructions to a Palestinian man at the end of Hebron's Shuhada
Street. The road, in the heart of the Palestinian city, was spruced
up by the United States but the Israelis have not allowed
Palestinians to drive on it. (Larry Kaplow/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) UNDATED -- July 16, 1999 -- FULLER-ARCHIVE-B&AMP;W, 07-16 --
The architect Buckminister Fuller in 1930 with a model of his
Dymaxion House. Perhaps the most illuminating impression one gets
from a stroll through the Buckminster Fuller Institute, a cramped
warren of offices in the balcony of an old movie theater here, is
how familiar all the artifacts produced by this great thinker seem
today. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) NASHVILLE, Tenn. -- July 16, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY
18 -- BIZ-FOR-ME, 07-16 -- At 95, Frank W. Fletcher is older than
most of the buildings he passes on his way to work as a stockbroker
at Wiley Bros./Aintree Capital, a firm in Nashville. ``I can't see
what all the fuss is about,'' says Fletcher. ``My father was
pushing a hand mower well into his 90s.'' (Jana Curcio/New York
Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) UNDATED -- July 16, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 18 --
CAR-SMART-ROADSTER, 07-16 -- The $62,500 Panoz AIV Roadster takes
off like a rocket, with tight accommodations to match. The Roadster
is designed to be driven without top or windows. A cloth and
plastic contraption, rather like a pup tent, is stored in a duffel
bag in the diminutive trunk and can be used to cover the occupants
in a hailstorm. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) BRASELTON, Ga. -- July 16, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY
18 -- ABOUT-CARS-PANOZ-ROADSTER, 07-16 -- The aluminum-bodied
Esperante convertible at the Chateau Elan winery. With a
320-horsepower V8 from Ford's Special Vehicles Team, a handcrafted,
heavily leathered interior, and styling cues from Jaguar and a
half-dozen other European sports cars, this ``great American
roadster'' is set to go on sale later this year for about $80,000.
(New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- July 16, 1999 --
SUIB-HADASSAH-LIPTON-PROFILE, 07-16 -- On July 27, Bonnie Lipton,
seen here in Hadassah's offices, will take over as the
organization's president. Hadassah, which with 306,000 members is
the largest women's and Jewish organization in the United States,
will be presenting Hillary Rodham Clinton an award on that same
day. (Librado Romero/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. -- July 16, 1999 --
SPRINGSTEEN-CONCERT, 07-16 -- From left, Clarence Clemons, Nils
Lofgren, Bruce Springsteen and Steve Van Zandt in concert Thursday
night in East Rutherford. If Springsteen's work is a journey, then
Thursday's three-hour, 26-song show - which began his first
American tour with the E Street Band in 10 years - stopped at
nearly all points on the map. (Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) GUN HILL (POINT 4875), Kashmir -- July 16, 1999 --
INDIA-KASHMIR-2, 07-16 -- Soldiers of the Indian army pose
victoriously for photographers with the Indian tricolour flag
hoisted on top of the peak of Gun Hill 16. The Indian Army buried
five more bodies on Friday near the crown of a mountaintop 16,500
feet high, a spot recently re-named Gun Hill on military maps
because of the intense mortar fire that has been lobbed from its
rocky summit. (AFP for the New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) GUN HILL (POINT 4875), India -- July 16, 1999 --
INDIA-KASHMIR-1, 07-16 -- Ikraz Nabi, a junior commissioned officer
in the Indian army, reads prayers during a funeral service for
Pakistani soldiers on Friday. The Indian Army buried five more
bodies on Friday near the crown of a mountaintop 16,500 feet high,
a spot recently re-named Gun Hill on military maps because of the
intense mortar fire that has been lobbed from its rocky summit.
Just as they have with the bodies of others, the Indians offered
them to Pakistan, but Pakistan, caught in what much of the world
believes is an elaborate fiction, cannot accept the dead from an
invasion force it has disavowed. (AFP for the New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- July 16, 1999 -- HADASSAH-LIPTON-PROFILE,
07-16 -- On July 27, Bonnie Lipton, seen here in Hadassah's
offices, will take over as the organization's president. Hadassah,
which with 306,000 members is the largest women's and Jewish
organization in the United States, will be presenting Hillary
Rodham Clinton an award on that same day. (Librado Romero/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) MAHOPAC, N.Y. -- July 16, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 18
-- PERFECT-LAWNS-2, 07-16 -- Robert Esernio on his John Deere GT275
sit-down mower with a 48-inch cutting deck atop his lawn in
Mahopac. ``I like the straight lines,'' says Esernio, 40, an
accountant with three children who has spent thousands of hours and
tens of thousands of dollars, including a $3,500 underground
sprinkler system, to recreate, in effect, a portion of the outfield
at Yankee Stadium. (Rebecca Cooney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) SOUTHPORT, Conn. -- July 16, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY
18 -- PERFECT-LAWNS-1, 07-16 -- Christopher Rosow of Southport
Village inspects his modest front lawn, a far cry from the four
acres he had to mow at his parents' home. ``My father was more into
not mowing the lawn,'' Rosow, 28, recalls. ``He was more interested
in me mowing it.'' (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) SEATTLE -- July 16, 1999 -- STADIUMS-REACT, 07-16 --
Protesters against the use of public money for the construction of
Safeco Field, demonstrate outside the stadium on Friday. Safeco
Field, the most expensive single-use stadium in North America,
opened for Major League Baseball this week. What was once touted as
a grand civic celebration of the national pastime in the Pacific
Northwest, has been soured by protests, legal threats and a growing
squall over how over much the public should have to pay for arenas
that enrich private owners. (Dan Lamont/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) UNDATED -- July 16, 1999 -- CONGRESS-SPEND, 07-16 -- The
F-22 ``Raptor,'' built buy Boeing, along with Lockheed Martin and
Pratt &AMP; Whitney, during its first flight on Sept. 7, 1997. The
House will vote next week to cut off funds to produce the $70
billion aircraft, an act unprecedented in modern times, House
leaders said on Friday. Congress almost never kills major weapons
systems that are about to reach the assembly line. Nothing like
this has happened in modern memory, according to senior members of
Congress and veterans of four decades of Pentagon spending wars.
(Boeing/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) WASHINGTON -- July 16, 1999 -- CONGRESS-TAX-2, 07-16 --
Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., facing camera, the ranking
minority member on the Senate Finance Committee, listens to Sen.
John Breaux, D-La., second from left, during a news conference on
Friday. From left are Sens. Max Baucus, D-Mont., Breaux, Moynihan
and Kent Conrad, D-N.D. Republicans and Democrats in the Senate
laid out dueling tax-cut proposals on Friday, but both sides said
they saw room for eventual compromise. (Justin Lane/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WASHINGTON -- July 16, 1999 -- CONGRESS-TAX, 07-16 --
Sen. William Roth, Jr., R-Del., chairman of the Senate Finance
Committee, during a press conference on Friday. Republicans and
Democrats in the Senate laid out dueling tax-cut proposals on
Friday, but both sides said they saw room for eventual compromise.
The Democratic plan is far smaller than the $792 billion cut
proposed by Roth. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) CHARLESTON, W.Va. -- July 16, 1999 --
WEST-VIRGINIA-AGED-2, 07-16 -- Ken Hechler in his campaign Jeep
near the West Virginia Capitiol. West Virginia has surpassed
Florida as the state with the oldest per capita residents in the
union, and no one knows this better than Hechler, the 84-year-old
elected secretary of state who has decided he can be the wave of
the future and is running for his old House seat that he retired
from in the '70s. (Bob Wojcieszak/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) DUNBAR, W.Va. -- July 16, 1999 -- WEST-VIRGINIA-AGED-1,
07-16 --Ken Hechler in his office. West Virginia has surpassed
Florida as the state with the oldest per capita residents in the
union, and no one knows this better than Hechler, the 84-year-old
elected secretary of state who has decided he can be the wave of
the future and is running for his old House seat that he retired
from in the '70s. (Bob Wojcieszak/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) ROME -- July 16, 1999 -- VATICAN-BOOK, 07-16 -- Rev.
Luigi Marinelli in his Rome apartment during a recent interivew.
When ``Gone with the Wind in the Vatican,'' first appeared in
bookstores last February, few readers noticed the anonymous
authors' account of intrigue, homosexuality and corruption within
the Vatican bureaucracy. The Vatican, however, did pay heed. Ever
since a church tribunal ordered Marinelli, one of the authors, to
cease publication and explain himself before church judges, the
book has become a runaway bestseller. (James Hill/New York Times
Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) WASHINGTON -- July 16, 1999 -- ISRAEL-U.S., 07-16 --
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak, left, walks with Defense
Secretary William Cohen following a full honors ceremony at the
Pentagon on Friday. Earlier, Barak met with Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright at her home in the Georgetown section of
Washington. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) PHILADELPHIA -- July 16, 1999 --
TEN-DAVIS-DYNASTY-BOS-B&AMP;W, 07-16 -- Dwight Davis and his wife in
1940. During tennis's postwar days, when only nonpros were eligible
to knock about for Dwight Davis's ornate punch bowl, Australia
ruled the scene. (Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) BOSTON -- July 16, 1999 -- TEN-DAVIS-STOLLE-BOS, 07-16 --
Sandon Stolle, of the Australian Davis Cup team, works out on
Friday at the Longwood Cricket Club. When the year began, Stolle
knew he wanted to be a part of the Davis Cup. Last week, after
successful doubles competitor Todd Woodbridge announced his
withdrawal, Stolle was named the replacement, promoting him from
practice partner to participant in the historic tie. (Barry
Chin/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) RUE BEACH, N.H. -- July 16, 1999 -- FALUN-GONG-BOS, 07-16
-- June Kirk, center, practices the art of Falun Gong with other
students. Falun Gong, a form of Qi Gong, the
more-than-4,000-year-old Chinese exercise and meditation system
that purports to channel energy (or Qi, pronounced ``chee'') to
different parts of the body, is poised to become the next exercise
and consciousness-expanding craze of New Age America. (Michael
Robinson-Chavez/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) WASHINGTON -- July 16, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 18 --
DOW-CHEMICAL-POLLUTE, 07-16 -- Linda Greer, a senior scientist at
the National Resources Defense Council, near the U.S. Capitol where
she formerly walked the halls as a lobbyist. Working secretly with
environmentalists, Dow Chemical has found scores of ways to reduce
pollution at its plants and save money in the process. The novel
collaboration between Dow Chemical can be traced back to a 1991
gripe session over drinks between Greer and a Dow executive. (Shana
Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) RYE BROOK, N.Y. -- July 16, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY
18 -- INVEST-SERIAL-ACQUIRE, 07-16 -- Robert A. Olstein, a
financial analyst and mutual fund manager, says investors should
dig behind the numbers a company reports. He practices his golf
stroke with his wife, Karen, at their home in Rye Brook. (Rebecca
Cooney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) MILWAUKEE -- July 16, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 18 --
INTERNET-DAYTRADERS-2, 07-16 -- ``I always wanted to own my own
business, but I don't want to bake bread or frame pictures - I'm
just not very good that,'' says Karen Schwenke, 38, a partner in La
Salle Street Trading in Milwaukee. ``This is a business I have
really grown to love.'' (Steve Kagan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- July 16, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 18 --
INTERNET-DAYTRADERS-1, 07-16 -- The frenzy has diminished since
Internet stocks fell, but many day traders are still in the game.
``Everyone wants to get into it and make a fast buck,'' says Kirk
Kazazian, 23, a day trader since 1996, who trades at Tradescape in
Manhattan. (Jeffery A. Salter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
