<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Friday, 07/16/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT37) UNDATED -- July 16, 1999 -- FULLER-ARCHIVE-B&AMP;W, 07-16 --
The architect Buckminister Fuller in 1930 with a model of his
Dymaxion House. Perhaps the most illuminating impression one gets
from a stroll through the Buckminster Fuller Institute, a cramped
warren of offices in the balcony of an old movie theater in Santa
Barbara, Calif., is how familiar all the artifacts produced by this
great thinker seem today. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT36) SHELLMAN, Ga. -- July 16, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 18
-- NEW-NOVELIST18-COX, 07-16 -- Sonny and Joy Sammons sit on the
front porch with their daughter Laura, 2, and dog Chester. Mr.
Sammons made the heavy wooden furniture they sit on and most of the
furniture in his historic house. ``It took me two months to write
the first draft and three months to correct the spelling,'' he says
of his 1995 autobiographical first novel, ``The Keepers of
Echowah.'' (Phil Skinner/Atlanta Journal-Constitution Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) NEW YORK -- July 16, 1999 -- MARKS-SILK, 07-16 -- Leo
Marks with a silk scarf used to carry codes in World War II. Marks
has written a book, ``Between Silk and Cyanide: A Codemaker's War,
1941-1945,'' about his wartime exploits. Working for the mysterious
Special Operations Executive, he created secret codes for British
agents gathering information behind enemy lines. (Sara Krulwich/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) LONDON -- July 16, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 18 --
TRAVEL-LONDON-THEATER18-COX, 07-16 -- The Theatre Royal Haymarket
in London. Even more than painting is to Paris, or music to Vienna,
theater is the steady flame of London's spirit, burning as bright
today as it did 100 or 400 years ago. (London Tourist Board/Cox
News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) NEWARK -- July 16, 1999 -- NJ-NEWARK-BASEBALL, 07-16 --
Ryan Gorecki, of the Newark Bears, a minor league ball club,
welcomes members of the Orions, a local little league team, before
opening celemonies at Riverfront Stadium on Friday. Baseball
returned after 50 years to the state's largest city with the
opening of the 6,014-seat Riverfront Stadium. City officials hope
the minor-league ball park will revive the city's past glory as the
nation's top minor league team and help this battered city move
toward a rebirth. (Chang W. Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) WASHINGTON -- July 16, 1999 -- ISRAEL-U.S.-2, 07-16 --
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak, right, walks with Defense
Secretary William Cohen while reviewing an honor guard at the
Pentagon on Friday. Earlier, Barak met with Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright at her home in the Georgetown section of
Washington. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
