</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Smoltz's return set vs. Phillies
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Given his good outing on Thursday night and the way
he felt Friday, the Braves plan to move ahead with the idea that
John Smoltz will be activated from the 15-day disabled list and
pitch the second day the Braves are in Philadelphia, on Saturday,
July 24.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Bobby Cox and Smoltz talked three times by telephone
Friday to set up what happens next as Smoltz makes his way back
from an inflamed elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz pitched two perfect innings for the Class AA Greenville
Braves in his rehabilitation assignment on Thursday, including four
strikeouts, using all his pitches. He is planning to go a couple of
more innings today. If all goes well, he'll join the Braves in Fort
Lauderdale on Wednesday, throw a side session there and then start
next Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that is subject to change, but with the way he threw and
how he feels today, he's ready to go,'' Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   Cox is planning to use rookie Bruce Chen in the second game of
the doubleheader in Philadelphia on Friday. Chen will likely be
sent back to Class AAA Richmond when Smoltz is activated.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez may wait to catch
</P>
<P>
   Cox may scrap his original plans to have Javy Lopez catch today,
waiting instead until the Braves are in Toronto on Sunday or
Monday, or even as late as Florida next Wednesday and Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   After playing for the first time in three weeks on Thursday
night as the Braves' designated hitter, Lopez said his knee was
fine. The only problem he had was feeling tentative on the
basepaths. His hard single in his first at-bat, he said, normally
would have been a double. Lopez went 2-for-4 in the game with two
RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Swinging was no problem at all,'' Lopez said. ``I can play DH.
I can hit without any pain.... I was careful running the bases.
That's not the way I run the bases. It's all about getting used to
it. Once I lose the fear of running the bases, I'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez ready for second half
</P>
<P>
   Odalis Perez will be making his first start today in almost two
weeks _ since July 5. He was sick the last time his spot was up in
the rotation. Perez pitched on the side at home in the Dominican
Republic over the All-Star break and said he's ready for a better
run in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   The rookie pitcher finished the first half without a win in his
last five starts to fall from 4-2 with a 4.48 ERA to 4-5 with a
5.28 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter how long it's been,'' Perez said. ``The
second half is my time to let them know I'm here and I want to do
better for the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Thrill for McGlinchy
</P>
<P>
   Rubbing the head of the Babe Ruth statue in Monument Park was a
good memory for Braves rookie reliever Kevin McGlinchy, but he got
a better one on Thursday night when he struck out Derek Jeter. He
came back from a 2-0 count to strand Chuck Knoblauch at third base
and save the Braves a run in the seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first two pitches I was probably trying to throw too
hard,'' said McGlinchy, who threw Jeter all fastballs working both
sides of the plate. ``After the break, I was feeling pretty
good.... I knew I had a good fastball. I was going to go with it no
matter what.''
</P>
<P>
   For McGlinchy, who grew up in Malden, Mass., a Red Sox fan and
therefore a Yankee hater, it was his first time pitching in Yankee
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always good to beat the Yankees,'' McGlinchy said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
