<DOCNO> NYT19990716.0337 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3345 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-DAVIS-COLLINS-COL     07-16 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVIS-COLLINS-COL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE LATE FOR SAMPRAS TO DOUSE AUSSIE FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Today only: Pete Sampras.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four hours late.
</P>
<P>
   When United States Davis Cup captain Tom Gullikson gets around
to dialing 911 and asking for Sheriff Sampras, the burglars named
Hewitt and Rafter are already sitting in the Aussie gang's hideout
counting the loot. It adds up to Australia 2, USA 0.
</P>
<P>
   It also adds up to a destructive blaze consuming the US Davis
Cup team at Longwood Cricket Club, where Friday 5,342 witnesses
were toasted like marshmallows on a 97-degree afternoon, and it was
even more Hadesian for the toilers on a hard-paved court, where
thermometers registered 126.
</P>
<P>
   Into this blaze, at this late date in a best-of-five series,
goes Sampras _ reduced to a mere fire extinguisher when he could
have been a a rescuing hook and ladder truck.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the best tennis player on the planet sat on the
sidelines as the US burned just about to the ground. Is this as
weird as a wombat, or what? Sampras, who should have been the
firemaker himself, grilling a few Australians over the weekend,
appears in a cameo role: a doubles player alongside Alex O'Brien.
Presumably they have been introduced to one another, although
that's not certain. What's certain is they've never coalesced on a
tennis court.
</P>
<P>
   This is playground pickup-game stuff. They walk onto the court.
One guy says, ``Hi, I'm Pete Sampras. Which court would you like to
play?''
</P>
<P>
   The other guy says, ``Oh, I've heard of you. I'm Alex O'Brien.
Say, don't you play singles anymore?''
</P>
<P>
   Not this week.
</P>
<P>
   Only a cameo. Sampras and O'Brien, trying to keep their side
breathing, though unlikely. It's Arnold Schwarzenegger and Don
Knotts, in tandem, hoping to save the farm from Aussies swarming
like locusts. In this 100th year of the Davis Cup, we have the
strangest American drama of all with Sampras cast as an extra.
Wilfred Brimley when he might have been Gielgud.
</P>
<P>
   His colleagues have voted Pete the greatest ever in their game,
but he didn't make his reputation in doubles.
</P>
<P>
   Pete says this is his choice. ``I didn't want to horn in on Jim
Courier and Todd Martin's show. I said if they'd have me I'd play
doubles. My decision. I made it. Not Gully.''
</P>
<P>
   A bad decision _ and acceptance by Gullikson. It's Nomar
Garciaparra, before a playoff series, saying to Jimy Williams, ``I
think I'll just pinch hit.'' Williams replies, ``Fine, Nomar. It's
pretty hot out there, starting and playing nine innings.''
</P>
<P>
   Or Luciano Pavarotti showing up for a performance of ``Aida'' at
the Met and telling the boss, ``I'm tired of being Rhadames. Guess
I'll just sing in the chorus, or carry a spear.''
</P>
<P>
   Puh-leeze!
</P>
<P>
   In their hour of need, prior to the opening-round series in
Birmingham, England, and after much pleading, Gullikson and the
team were turned down by Sampras. Then Martin and Courier waged
that magnificent 3-2 victory, and it became Sampras's hour of need.
``Inspired by those guys,'' Pete said, he wanted to enlist. But, he
insisted, only for the doubles cameo.
</P>
<P>
   But once they took the prodigal back into the fold, saying, as
Courier did, ``He'll strengthen us,'' he should have been a team
member in good standing. Not a spare part.
</P>
<P>
   For my money, Martin settled the issue after his Wimbledon
defeat by Patrick Rafter by saying, ``Pete should play singles in
Boston in my place.'' Extraordinarily selfless. Very Martin. But
also correct, if this is, as I understand it, a very well-paid
professional team. You need 3 points to win, and Sampras is a
potential 3-pointer as he was in the splendid 3-2 title-round
victory over Russia in Moscow four years ago. Sampras won both
singles plus the doubles with Martim, a solid mix.
</P>
<P>
   Gullikson was in the captain's chair. He should know that when
you've got a Pedro Martinez in the house, you don't put him on
short relief.
</P>
<P>
   Gullikson is an admirable guy, a fine ambassador for his
country, but he's the captain. Captains are supposed to lead, not
listen too much to the enlisted men such as Pete. Once Martin
cleared the way for Pete, you expected Gullikson to say, ``Pete, we
may need you to go three days, like Moscow. If you can't offer more
than doubles, check back with us next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine how this played out in, say, Davenport, Iowa, (possibly
named for Wimbledon champ Lindsay Davenport?)
</P>
<P>
   Maw and Paw are watching the US being torched on ESPN. Maw says,
``I'm a little puzzled, Paw. Remember Wimpleton and how good those
two guys Agassi and Sampras was. Ain't they Americans?''
</P>
<P>
   Paw says, ``I thought so. But, yeah, Maw, so why ain't they
playing today for the USA if they're good enough to do that at
Wimpleton? Sampras was fantastic. Ain't he on this team?''
</P>
<P>
   Not that you'd notice, but it's a good question, Paw.
</P>
<P>
   However, today only: Pete Sampras.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-99 2148EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990716.0338 </DOCNO>
