<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
(HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
  c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STRONG CORPORATE EARNINGS PUSH STOCK GAUGES HIGHER
</P>
<P>
   Stocks ended a week of record-setting sessions as Wall Street
cheered good corporate earnings. The technology-laden Nasdaq
composite index gained 25.11 points, or 0.9 percent, to 2,864.48,
its third consecutive record finish.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average rose 23.43 points, to
11,209.84, beating Monday's record of 11,200.98. And, the Standard
&AMP; Poor's 500-stock index set its second consecutive record, rising
9.16 points, to 1,418.78.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE APPROVES AFRICAN INITIATIVES
</P>
<P>
   The House approved a far-ranging American economic initiative
for Africa that authorizes quota-free and duty-free imports from 48
sub-Saharan African countries.
</P>
<P>
   DEAL CLOSER IN AMERICAN AIR DISPUTE
</P>
<P>
   American Airlines and its pilots may be close to settling the
dispute that inconvenienced hundreds of thousands of passengers
earlier this year when pilots called in sick, forcing the airline
to cancel nearly 6,700 flights.
</P>
<P>
   CHALK UP A VICTORY FOR MICROSOFT
</P>
<P>
   A jury in Bridgeport, Conn., found that Microsoft had not
violated antitrust laws in its dealings with Bristol Technology.
Despite the differences between that case and the federal antitrust
case brought by the Justice Department and 19 states, Microsoft has
been portrayed in both cases as an overreaching monopolist who used
its market power as a club. Steve Aeschbacher, a senior corporate
lawyer at Microsoft, said that the verdict strongly suggested that
the jury was ``impressed by all the evidence in the record of the
intensity and dynamism of competition in the software industry.''
</P>
<P>
   INDUSTRIAL OUTPUT JUMPED IN JUNE
</P>
<P>
   Output at the factories, mines and utilities rose 0.2 percent in
June, the seventh month without a decline, led by increased demand
for automobiles, computers and electricity.
</P>
<P>
   SEC SUES ON STOCK PROMOTIONS
</P>
<P>
   The SEC filed suit in federal court in Miami accusing Globus
Group of Miami and its principal, Anthony DiMarco, of fraudulently
promoting the shares of a dozen tiny thinly traded companies by
issuing phony press releases and creating bogus reports from
leading brokerage firms.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICAN COMPANIES STILL SCARRED
</P>
<P>
   Despite Mexico's strong stock market and economy, some big
companies are still suffering from the country's banking crisis.
</P>
<P>
   DEALERS SUE FORD MOTOR IN CANADA
</P>
<P>
   Ford dealers in Canada are suing Ford Motor of Canada over plans
to convert more than 100 Lincoln-Mercury outlets to the Ford name.
The dealers contend the plan breaches their contracts by creating
new competition within a 10-mile radius.
</P>
<P>
   COLUMNIST SUSPENDED IN SHARE DEAL
</P>
<P>
   The San Jose Mercury News suspended a business columnist
indefinitely for accepting a friend's offer to buy 500 shares of
autoweb.com at the initial offering price of $14. She sold them two
days after the offering at a $9,000 profit.
</P>
<P>
   AIR PRODUCTS SAYS EARNINGS WILL LAG
</P>
<P>
   Air Products and Chemicals warned that its third-quarter
earnings would not meet analysts' estimates because of weak demand
for chemicals and equipment. Air Products expects profit from
operations of 48 cents a share in the quarter ended June 30, below
the average estimate of 56 cents from analysts.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA'S GDP EXPANDED BY 7.6 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   China's gross domestic product expanded by a
slower-than-expected 7.6 percent in the first six months of the
year, as extra state spending on investment projects failed to spur
growth in other parts of the economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-99 2151EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
