<HEADLINE>
`RETAIL POLITICS' IN IOWA INDICATES BUSH CAMPAIGN IS THE REAL
THING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Verv is cq) 
 
By CRAGG HINES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ As Gov. George W. Bush walked away, Gregg
White assessed his performance: ``He was good. He's a natural.''
</P>
<P>
   Good politician? Natural campaigner? No. Good, natural pancake
flipper.
</P>
<P>
   And baby-kisser and hand-shaker and autograph-signer and patient
listener _ even when a young man insists on discussing the
esoterica of soil conservation.
</P>
<P>
   After the tumult of his first presidential campaign trip to
Iowa, Bush on a second swing through the state Thursday and Friday
settled into ``retail politics,'' which even in the television age
is considered a requirement as the presidential season kicks off in
the small, manageable states of Iowa and New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's refusal to set foot in either state until the Texas
Legislature adjourned at the end of May gave his competitors hope
that perhaps the governor's high-flying campaign was a political
chimera. But now, Bush declared in eight stops across Iowa, his
effort is clearly the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   So he showed up at a pancake breakfast in Tower Park on Friday
morning to ``mix and mingle,'' as the schedule called it, and flip
a few with White, a professional pancake master. For the record,
Bush landed six on the plate of Kelly Engenberger of the Des Moines
park department before one went awry and landed on the concrete
slab.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on, George, get out of the way, we want some pancakes,''
a man in the lengthening line called out.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a voter, I'm getting out of the way,'' Bush shouted
back.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he has told his campaign officials he wants to meet
people when comes to Iowa, not ``give the speech and retreat as
soon as possible,'' as he told a drive-time interview with radio
station WHO Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that shaking hands with as many people as are willing
to come out in the hot sun to say hello to me is retail politics,''
Bush said Thursday in Waterloo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first trip was much more kind of an event,'' Bush said.
``This one is much more grass-roots politics in the sense that I've
gotten to shake a lot of hands.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to look them in the eye,'' he said. ``I want to
hopefully confirm that I'm their man.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not hard to do in the audiences that gathered for Bush's
appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte Huff was impressed in Waterloo, even more so after
Bush gave her a kiss as he finished shaking hands with almost 250
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helped,'' said Huff, a former schoolteacher who is not
often involved in partisan politics.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he was already talking about a number of issues and
would get to more over the months ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a pace to a campaign that's important to maintain,''
said Bush, who has been giving he same basic stump speech for six
weeks. ``We've got a strategy, and by the time the main events
begin, I will have laid out what I intend to lay out.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if Bush were to camp out in Iowa until the Aug. 14
Republican presidential straw poll, there would be several
candidates who would top his number of campaign days in the state.
Bush offers no apology for remaining in Texas through the
legislative session, although he now takes pains to tell Iowans how
their state has now seized his attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want you to know that I'm coming to your state a lot,'' Bush
said as he started his tour Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Off the Bush bus (dubbed ``Asphalt One``), it's not hard to find
local Republican officials who are not committed to any
presidential contender and who are not awed by or sold on the
governor _ at least yet.
</P>
<P>
   Verv Davidson, GOP chairman in Hardin County, said he wondered
where Bush's strong polling numbers were coming from, and ventured
a guess that it was the work of the media and Republican
establishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you what's happening,'' said Hardin, a retired
speech and English teacher. ``I feel like that this is all being
controlled too much from the top. They don't think the grass roots
out here has anything to do with it anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Earl Winter, co-chairman of the Winneshiek County Republican
Party, said many in his area regard Bush as ``the glamour boy, the
idol of the media, who doesn't give a hang about Iowa. ... They
feel he's in the pockets of big oil.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the straw poll next month would reveal how his Iowa
campaign was progressing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am told by my people that we are pretty darn well-organized,
and that a lot of people have been contacted,'' Bush said. ``But
that's going to be the interesting part of (the straw poll), to see
how well candidates are organized.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Hare, a member of the Black Hawk County Republican
central committee, said Bush's approach is ``retail'' if compared
with seeing a candidate only on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes the groups are smaller than this,'' Hare said,
surveying the couple hundred folks gathered in front of the
Veterans Memorial Hall for the first stop on Bush's two-day tour.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller, indeed. When Bush's father started making the
presidential rounds in Iowa 20 years ago, he would often meet with
fewer than 10 folks in a crossroads coffee shop and consider
himself lucky.
</P>
<P>
   Even four years ago, this early in the process, Hare said, ``you
wouldn't have seen this many people.'' And it may be candidate
specific, Hare argued: ``Four years ago, we didn't have anyone as
exciting as Bush, frankly.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
