</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-U.S.-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PRAISES BARAK'S COMMITMENT TO PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Subs for complete writethru for new top, to recast
throughout. No pickup.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 1-888-603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(th) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After years of sparring with Benjamin Netanyahu,
there was a palpable sense of embrace in President Clinton's
description Friday of his first extended encounters with the new
prime minister of Israel, Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
   The two men _ the president eager to seize some final
accomplishment as his term nears its end, and the prime minister
seeking peace and pursuing it _ lingered together Thursday night
amid the history at Camp David in the cabin where Anwar Sadat and
Menachem Begin concluded the brave bargain 21 years ago that set
the course for Middle East peace.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, the most decorated soldier in Israel's history, pored
over documents from that time, many with the handwritten
annotations of President Jimmy Carter, who served as midwife for
the Egyptian-Israeli accord.
</P>
<P>
   ``He read it all with great care,'' Clinton said in a telephone
interview Friday afternoon from Iowa. ``He talked about Sadat, what
a gutsy thing he did when he came to Jerusalem to talk to the
Knesset even before the agreement was signed. He described the
scene and what an important effect it had.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he was moved by Barak's commitment to peace and by
his awareness of the risks it entails, for him personally and for
the Israeli people. Sadat was assassinated by Muslim radicals in
1981. Barak's mentor, Yitzhak Rabin, was murdered in 1995 by an
Israeli who opposed his efforts to make peace with the Arabs.
</P>
<P>
   The visit to the cabin where the Sadat-Begin talks took place
was part of a long evening for Clinton, Barak and their wives. They
talked over dinner for more than two hours. Then Clinton and Barak
spent three and a half hours together, breaking up well past
midnight.
</P>
<P>
   They spoke of their families and their politics, history and
health, war and peace, Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We laughed about a lot of things,'' he said, including what he
called the ``peculiarities of politics.'' He would not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that despite Barak's reputation for dourness, he is
a ``generally cheerful person.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton believes that personalities and relationships can
fundamentally alter history, and he said he is hopeful that his
positive early start with Barak can help lead to substantial, rapid
progress in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   The president said he stood ready to do whatever is necessary _
even if that means stepping out of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Barak said this week that the United States had played an overly
intrusive role in Middle East talks over the last three years. He
said he would welcome American participation as a ``facilitator''
of dialogue, but not as an arbitrator of disputes or enforcer of
agreements.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Friday that he is happy to play a less central
role.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best peace process is one where critical decisions are
made with parties that have to live with the consequences,''
Clinton said. ``When they hit a bump in the road, someone
facilitates the next step.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you want is for the U.S. to be a genuine facilitator, to
make whatever helpful suggestions we can and be there to provide
whatever support we can for making the most difficult decisions. I
think that is the right thing to do. We can be honest mediators,
fair and sensitive to concerns of both sides, of all the parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Clinton and Barak hope that a close political and personal
bond between the Israeli leader and the American president can be
forged once again. Relations were cool to the point of frost under
Benjamin Netanyahu, the former prime minister, who made no secret
of his resentment of American interference in Israeli affairs. The
Clinton administration made little effort to conceal its desire for
Barak's electoral victory over Netanyahu in May.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was warm in his assessment of Barak. ``I like him,'' he
said. ``I can get along with just about everybody. The main thing
is the Israeli voters basically said, `We want you to pursue peace
with security and we want it concluded.' Because of his
distinguished military career, they were saying to him, `We trust
you to try to put this deal together, to protect our security but
complete the peace process if you can.'''
</P>
<P>
   An Israeli official who spoke with Barak after his meeting at
the White House on Thursday and his stay at Camp David said the
prime minister was ``most satisfied'' with his discussions with
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Barak described the two couples' dinner as ``intimate and warm''
and said the Baraks were quite taken by the beauty and serenity of
Camp David, in Maryland's Catoctin Mountains about 80 miles
northwest of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   After the dinner, Clinton and Barak sat down privately as their
wives engaged in a talk of their own. Mrs. Clinton and Mrs. Barak
share an interest in women's health issues and in programs for
troubled youths. Mrs. Clinton said she would like to visit Israel
soon, according to the Israeli official who was briefed on their
discussion.
</P>
<P>
   The Baraks and the Clintons had a quick breakfast Friday at Camp
David before flying off in different directions, Clinton to Iowa
for political appearances, Barak to Washington and then to New
York.
</P>
<P>
   They resume their visit Sunday, at an official dinner at the
White House for 400 guests.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I took away from it, frankly, was what a lively
intelligence this guy has and what incredible energy he has,''
Clinton said. ``He said a lot of people know a lot of facts about
history but often lose the forest for the trees. You have to
understand the big patterns in history and in politics to make the
right decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the new prime minister possesses a bracing
combination of ``energy, intellect and leadership capacity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You know he is a passionate patriot,'' Clinton concluded. ``It
was fascinating to hear him talk about the history of Israel. I
could have stayed up all night listening to him, but we both got
tired.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
