<SLUG> BC-NY-HEAT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK CITY BRACES FOR ANOTHER HEAT WAVE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By NEIL MacFARQUHAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York City, barely recovered from a deadly heat
wave that plunged whole neighborhoods into darkness 11 days ago,
braced for more scorching weather this weekend with its Emergency
Operations Center on alert and Con Edison trying to assure a
jittery population that its engineers could avert a blackout this
time.
</P>
<P>
   Officials say the demand for power is not expected to hit the
record levels reached earlier this month, largely because the brunt
of the heat wave is to come during the weekend, when office
buildings and businesses are operating at less than full capacity.
</P>
<P>
   The thermometer was predicted to hit 98 on Saturday and 96 on
Sunday, which, when combined with high humidity, makes it feel like
105 degrees, said Todd J. Miner, a meteorologist at Penn State
University.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis of early July had a combined heat and humidity
reading, known as the heat index, of more than 110 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Many city residents are feeling especially vulnerable now
because a combination of high temperatures and a surge in demand
for electricity led to an 18-hour blackout on July 6 for 200,000
people in Manhattan north of 155th Street.
</P>
<P>
   OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   Both city officials and Con Edison said no specific
neighborhoods are considered vulnerable to a blackout this weekend.
But they said they would be closely monitoring the situation in
Washington Heights, where 7 of 14 of Con Edison's high voltage
cables called feeders had failed the last time.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Con Edison said they were in better shape going
into this heat wave than the last one, with just six feeder cables
down in the entire system of more than 1,150 such cables _ two in
suburban Westchester County and four in scattered parts of the
city. The officials would not specify which neighborhoods those six
cables served.
</P>
<P>
   On July 2, before the previous blackout, 13 feeder cables were
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will make every effort to insure that it doesn't happen
again,'' said R. William Donohue, the vice president for
distribution engineering at Con Edison. ``But there are no
guarantees in life.''
</P>
<P>
   END OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   The city of New York filed suit against Con Edison this week,
without seeking a specific amount of damages, arguing that the
power failure was caused by the utility's failure to properly
maintain its cable network.
</P>
<P>
   The city Medical Examiner's Office attributed 31 deaths to the
last bout of blistering temperatures. To help people endure the
heat, the city is again opening 80 cooling centers at its public
housing projects and has offered to transport anyone deemed
vulnerable to the nearest such room.
</P>
<P>
   Fire, police and emergency medical services officials who
gathered in the emergency center in the World Trade Center complex
were also prepared to open 15 air-conditioned schools at night if
those afflicted by the heat needed a cool place to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Police Commissioner Howard Safir said Friday that his department
had put enough off-duty police officers on call to be able to
deploy 500 to any area of the city within an hour. Several hundred
plainclothes officers already scheduled to work this weekend have
also been asked to don uniforms in case they were needed for street
patrols during a blackout.
</P>
<P>
   Trucks with lights and generators have been deployed in various
neighborhoods, and extra 911 operators are ready to work if needed,
Safir said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said other steps being considered included asking the
owners of large buildings like the Empire State Building,
illuminated throughout the last crisis, to lower their lights, and
even muting the glitter of the Great White Way of Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   There was some evidence that customers, especially those without
air-conditioners, were feeling a bit exposed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be somewhere where there is AC, probably at the movies,''
said Mary Catanzaro, 29, a party planner from Brooklyn who does not
have any form of cooling device in her home, car or office. ``Last
heat wave I tried to go to the movies, but the theater's AC broke
down, so I could find no refuge.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
