<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVIS-COURIER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURIER'S TROUBLES BALLOON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE _ The display of frustration started with a
controversial line call and concluded when Jim Courier rolled his
eyes upon leaving his postmatch press conference. A
brightly-colored blimp floating above the Longwood Cricket Club and
a reporter digging for dirt on the Pete Sampras situation did not
escape outbursts by the red-headed, red-faced Courier.
</P>
<P>
   Friday was not Courier's day _ a 7-6 (7-5), 6-4, 6-4, loss to
Australian Patrick Rafter attested to that. And it was also a
difficult day for the US Davis Cup team _ an 0-2 deficit at the end
of Day 1 did nobody on the home side proud. It took only 2 hours 19
minutes for Courier to fall from savior-in-waiting to the second
example of American singles failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I had a task to handle, and I knew it was going to be a
difficult one _ regardless of what happpens in the first match,
I've still got to go out and play,'' he said. ``So I am prepared to
play either way. I felt fine when I woke up this morning. I felt
fine when I went on the court. I feel fine now. Somewhere in the
middle there, something went askew.''
</P>
<P>
   The first sign that something failed to follow a straight line
came in the ninth game of the third set, with the score four games
apiece. With Courier hoping to hold serve and soon thereafter take
a set from Rafter, a return by the American was called out.
</P>
<P>
   Courier thought the ball was good and spent 20 seconds staring
down the line judge. Once he lost the game and went down a decisive
break, he served a ball in the direction of the lineswoman before
switching sides. Rafter held serve in the 10th game and won the
match.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know on the tape it is going to be good, because my eyes are
a lot better than the linespeople. Otherwise, they would be
playing,'' said Courier. ``If their eyes were as good as mine, they
would be playing for a living instead of calling lines. It's funny
how players are rarely wrong. But it is pro tennis. It happens, and
unfortunately it went against me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally on a home Davis Cup tie, I am going to get those
calls. Seems like when we play away ties, I never get them. I think
that would balance out. But it didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   The next object of Courier's wrath was the Monster.com blimp.
The airship spent the day dipping over the show court and
distracting servers. No one was more disturbed than Courier, who
thought of a new website address for the company. He referred to
the blimp as ``that Monster (expletive).com.'' When the player
learned the site helped people find jobs, he rolled his eyes and
held up his left hand as if he wanted to hear no more. The press
laughed, and Courier said, ``Whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of the press conference, the questions focused on
Saturday's doubles match, pairing Americans Alex O'Brien and Pete
Sampras against an Australian pair that might now include Rafter.
But the American audience wanted to know whether Todd Martin might
replace O'Brien. The query was addressed to team captain Tom
Gullikson, but Courier decided to answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hold on a second,'' said Courier, practically cutting off
Gullikson. ``Who is the captain? Are you the captain?''
</P>
<P>
   Gullikson went on to calmly answer questions about the doubles
pairing. To his right, Courier tossed the cap to his water bottle,
crossed his arms, and tapped his hands impatiently on his elbows.
The captain recapped the tough American start. Courier shook his
head and rolled his eyes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
