<HEADLINE>
WHAT PRICE THE MOST EXPENSIVE DIAMOND OF ALL? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa., Wis., Wash., Calif., Minn., Ariz., Ill.)  (ART ADV:  Photo  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 (af)  
 By TIMOTHY EGAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Safeco Field, the most costly single-sport stadium in
North America, opened for Major League Baseball on Thursday night,
a $517 million expanse of art and green grass cradled by the marine
air of Puget Sound and the hopes of fans long blanketed in misery.
</P>
<P>
   But what was once heralded as a grand local celebration of the
national pastime is now soured by protests, legal threats and a
growing squall over how much the public should pay for stadiums
that enrich private owners.
</P>
<P>
   The focus of the battle here is the Seattle Mariners' ownership
group. The owners, who include Microsoft billionaires, promised to
cover all cost overruns on the new park but have now stunned even
the team's strongest allies by asking for tax dollars to pay for
most of an overrun totaling $100 million, on top of $372 million
that taxpayers have already contributed to the stadium's cost.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, team owners including Ross Perot Jr., who is using
tax money to build an arena for his Dallas Mavericks basketball
team, and George W. Bush, who saw the value of his stake in
baseball's Texas Rangers rise to $15 million from $600,000 after
the public financed a new stadium for the club, have figured in a
debate that entwines the emotional threads of sports with the
strands of politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the public is at its limit,'' said Thomas M. Finneran,
the Speaker of the Massachusetts House of Representatives, who led
the fight to curb the amount his state would pay to keep the New
England Patriots. The team is staying in Foxboro, Mass., with the
help of $70 million in state road improvements, after backing out
of a $375 million stadium deal with Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our hearts are with the home team,'' Finneran said. ``But more
and more, people are saying enough of this kind of corporate
welfare. And I think the sports owners asked for the backlash,'' by
making exorbitant demands.
</P>
<P>
   The new home of the Mariners, with its Internet kiosks, views of
the Olympic Mountains and signature sculptures of baseball symbols,
has been hailed by fans and design critics alike as a wondrous
addition to Seattle. The 47,000-seat stadium _ which replaces the
drab, 23-year-old-Kingdome _ has a retractable roof, grass that can
be automatically heated to bring it out of its dormancy in the
spring and, hanging in a rotunda behind home plate, a chandelier of
1,000 translucent bats.
</P>
<P>
   Without the new stadium and the additional revenue that is
expected as a result, it is unlikely that baseball could have
remained in the city, said Bud Selig, the baseball commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   But Safeco Field also has the distinction of being the first
ball yard built with public money after voters said no to paying
for it. It is a kind of dubious forerunner to stadiums that are
scheduled to open in Milwaukee next year and in Pittsburgh in 2001,
each built with tax dollars despite overwhelming, though
nonbinding, votes against using taxes for them.
</P>
<P>
   In Pennsylvania, what started as an effort to give one team, the
Pittsburgh Pirates, a new stadium to keep it from leaving one of
baseball's oldest venues ended up this year in the state's approval
of public financing for a new home for each of four teams _ two in
Pittsburgh, two in Philadelphia. The four stadiums will cost about
$1 billion, at least two-thirds of which will be public money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pennsylvania is a major league state, and we proved it
today,'' Gov. Tom Ridge, a second-term Republican, said after
guiding the stadium financing package through the legislature.
</P>
<P>
   But many others were outraged, particularly in the Philadelphia
region, which had not been given a chance to vote on spending local
tax dollars for new stadiums, and in Pittsburgh, which had been
given the chance and rejected the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``It boils down to politicians' giving more money to certain
special interests that outweigh whatever voters may say,'' said
Jake Haulk, director of the Allegheny Institute, a conservative
public-policy organization in Pittsburgh. ``They used to justify
this on the grounds that these new stadiums were great economic
generators, but they have abandoned that line. Now they just say,
`We need to be a world-class city, and taxpayers will have to pay
for it.'''
</P>
<P>
   At least 15 major sports complexes around the country are to
open in the next three years, all but one, in San Francisco,
financed by the public. Through the 1990s, nearly $11 billion in
public money has been spent building and renovating sports centers.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, both the Yankees and the Mets have asked the public
to underwrite new baseball parks for them, although it appears that
the Yankees will now most likely stay put in 76-year-old Yankee
Stadium if $189 million in renovations are made in and around it.
</P>
<P>
   Prompted by the runaway stadium plans of his home state, Sen.
Arlen Specter, R-Pa., has introduced a bill that would require
Major League Baseball and the National Football League to pay at
least 50 percent of the construction costs of new stadiums for
their teams. For parks already being built, the owners are
generally paying 10 percent to 30 percent, with the lone exception
of San Francisco, where the Giants are privately financing the
entire cost of $255 million Pacific Bell Park.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Specter's bill has bipartisan support on the Senate Judiciary
Committee but is strongly opposed by baseball and football owners,
and other senators say it has only a slim chance of winning
passage.
</P>
<P>
   But a revolt, of sorts, is under way in a number of states. Gov.
Jesse Ventura of Minnesota, for instance, has drawn a line against
state financing of a new stadium for the Minnesota Twins despite
ownership's repeated threats to move the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``No pushing things down people's throats,'' said Ventura, who
last month set up a fund for Minnesotans who want to apply their
state tax rebate toward construction of a new stadium. ``This will
be the state's contribution,'' the governor said. ``It's called put
your money where your mouth is.''
</P>
<P>
   And in May, Arizona voters turned down a request by the owners
of the Cardinals to finance a new football stadium. The vote
followed by a year the opening a $354 million stadium in Phoenix
for baseball's Diamondbacks, a park financed largely by a sales tax
increase.
</P>
<P>
   The economics of major league sports, in which even mediocre
players demand long-term contracts of $50 million or more, is
largely behind the need for new stadiums and their
revenue-enhancing features, like luxury boxes, corporate suites and
innovative, interesting designs that can swell attendance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could owners build and pay for their own stadiums?'' said
Allen Sanderson, a professor of economics at the University of
Chicago, who has written extensively about sports financing. ``Yes,
of course they could. But then they would make less money. So they
go to the public instead.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle's voters in 1995 narrowly turned down a proposal to
raise the sales tax to build a new home for the Mariners. But later
that year the team went on a magical run, coming from 13 games out
of first place late in the season to win the division title and
then beating the Yankees in the first round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   A fan frenzy and the Mariners' demand for a new stadium prompted
an emergency session of the legislature, which gave the green light
to a new taxing proposal. That proposal then went not to the voters
but to the governing King County Council, which approved it.
</P>
<P>
   The team's owners, a consortium of 16 members whose wealth is
drawn largely from local high-technology enterprises and the
Japanese-owned Nintendo Co., agreed to pay $45 million toward the
new stadium _ most of which they raised by selling to the Safeco
Corp. the right to name the park _ plus any cost overruns.
</P>
<P>
   The owners say they have been losing more than $10 million a
year, and with the prospect of $20 million in new annual revenue
generated by Safeco Field, they ordered it rushed to completion.
</P>
<P>
   Then, just three weeks before it opened, they declared that tax
dollars should be used to pay at least $60 million of the $100
million overrun. They are threatening suit for that amount against
the Public Facilities District, the public agency that owns the
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Political and business leaders who supported the team are
furious. ``I think all the unmitigated gall on the face of the
earth right now resides at Mariner headquarters,'' said Cynthia
Sullivan, a member of the King County Council.
</P>
<P>
   Although they earlier promised to cover overruns, the team's
owners say a close legal reading of the stadium financing contract
supports their claim for additional public money. They have refused
to respond in detail to questions about their position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize there are a lot of people who don't agree with us,''
said Howard Lincoln, a Mariner director who is chairman of Nintendo
of America. ``But even baseball owners are entitled to their day in
court.''
</P>
<P>
   The baseball commissioner, Selig _ whose family, owner of the
Milwaukee Brewers, is getting its own publicly financed stadium
next year _ praised the Mariner owners, saying they were ``heroes''
who had lost $80 million since they bought the team seven years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, they are the people that saved baseball in Seattle,''
Selig said. ``Without them, there's no team here.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, protesters marched outside the Mariners'
inaugural game at Safeco Field, holding signs reading, ``No More
Corporate Welfare'' and ``Keep Your Word.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Gary Locke offered advice to fans who feel conflicted. ``It
is not a contradiction,'' he said, ``to say we love this stadium,
and it's gorgeous and going to make people of the Pacific Northwest
love baseball, but still insist that a contract is a contract, a
deal is a deal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
