<HEADER>
A3370 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-VERDICT-1ST     07-16 1325
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-VERDICT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-670&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT PREVAILS IN SUIT BY SOFTWARE MAKER
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to insert missing word in 7th graf.)  
 (ATTN: Calif., Conn.)   (See also MICROSOFT-WEALTH) 
(rk) 
 By STEVE LOHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a David versus Goliath case, a courtroom confrontation
between a struggling little software maker and the mighty Microsoft
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft was accused of befriending the fledgling company when
it suited its interests and then callously casting the company
aside when it was no longer useful, denying it access to
Microsoft's technology on fair terms. The tactic, the plaintiff's
lawyers argued, was a violation of federal antitrust laws and all
but a death sentence for Bristol Technology Inc., of Danbury, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Friday, as an uptick in Microsoft's stock price lifted the
personal wealth of Bill Gates to nearly $100 billion, a Connecticut
jury of five men and three women, ranging in age from 21 to late
60s, whose job status ran the gamut from unemployed to corporate
executive, sided with Goliath.
</P>
<P>
   The jury in U.S. District Court in Bridgeport, Conn., found that
Microsoft had not violated antitrust laws in its dealings with
Bristol.
</P>
<P>
   The private suit in Connecticut has no direct impact on the
major antitrust challenge Microsoft faces _ the federal case
brought by the Justice Department and 19 states. The charges and
evidence are different.
</P>
<P>
   But antitrust experts said Friday's verdict would certainly
hearten the Microsoft legal team in Washington. Despite the
differences, Microsoft has been portrayed in both cases as an
overreaching monopolist who used its market power as a club _ a
characterization supported by piles of Microsoft e-mail and
internal documents that spoke forcefully of destroying rivals and
leaning on partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a decisive triumph for Microsoft, and it has to be a
shot of adrenalin for the Microsoft lawyers working on the
government case,'' said William Kovacic, a professor at the George
Washington University law school. ``This verdict may not have any
direct effect on the government case, but it shows Microsoft that
it can win these cases, even when much of the evidence in court is
unflattering.''
</P>
<P>
   In celebrating their victory, the Microsoft lawyers certainly
echoed the same themes of the company's defense in the government
case _ that its business practices are merely the rough-and-tumble
of modern capitalism, and that the computer software market moves
so rapidly that Microsoft can scarcely be considered an entrenched
monopolist.
</P>
<P>
   ``The considered opinion of the community in which Bristol
operates is that Microsoft did nothing wrong,'' said David Tulchin,
a partner at Sullivan &AMP; Cromwell who was Microsoft's lead trial
lawyer. ``All that Microsoft did was compete hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Aeschbacher, a senior corporate lawyer at Microsoft, said
that the verdict strongly suggested that the jury was ``impressed
by all the evidence in the record of the intensity and dynamism of
competition in the software industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Bristol had sought a stiff financial penalty against Microsoft _
damages ranging from $130 million to $263 million, which, if
Microsoft was found to violate antitrust laws, would be tripled.
</P>
<P>
   The jury did find that Microsoft had violated a Connecticut law
prohibiting ``deceptive practices,'' like making misleading
statements to a business partner. But for that unspecified
transgression, the jury awarded Bristol a mere $1.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not even a parking ticket,'' observed Kovacic of George
Washington University.
</P>
<P>
   Not even that for Microsoft, which has nearly $22 billion in
cash on hand, according to its most recent financial statement.
</P>
<P>
   Bristol said it disappointed by the outcome and that it was
``exploring'' the option of appealing the verdict. ``We still
firmly believe that Microsoft engaged in anti-competitive behavior
against Bristol,'' said Keith Blackwell, the chief executive of
Bristol.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Lynch, a partner at O'Melvany &AMP; Myers and lead counsel
for Bristol, said: ``This is a case of great importance to the
entire computer industry. While the ruling is disappointing to
Bristol, this is an issue that is not going to go away. Microsoft's
abuse of its dominant position has to be addressed.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Still, antitrust experts say the Bristol suit was a high-risk
legal case from the outset. First, they say, the case focused on
the software markets for computer work stations and so-called
server computers, which feed data out to desktop machines in
computer networks. In those markets, Microsoft is not nearly as
dominant as it is in the market for desktop operating systems for
personal computers, where its Windows software runs more than 90
percent of PCs sold.
</P>
<P>
   Second, antitrust experts note that Bristol relied on the
antitrust theory that Microsoft had a ``duty to deal'' with
Bristol. And the experts point out that duty-to-deal cases, which
regard the plaintiff almost as a regulated utility, have been
difficult to win in recent years. The main exceptions, they note,
have been in industries with traditions of regulation, like
telecommunications, or businesses involving natural assets, like
ski slopes.
</P>
<P>
   Significantly, for its sweeping antitrust case, the government
did depose Blackwell of Bristol. But the Justice Department chose
to focus instead on Microsoft's use of its market power derived
from its dominance of the PC operating system market. The
government has charged that the company used its Windows monopoly
to stifle competition from the rise of Internet software. And the
government also steered clear of any duty-to-deal claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bristol chose to bring a case in one of the most pro-defendant
areas of antitrust,'' said Robert E. Hall, a professor at Stanford
University. ``Courts have been very reluctant to say that companies
must share their intellectual property.''
</P>
<P>
   Bristol makes software that allows programs written for
Microsoft's Windows to run on work stations or servers that use
Unix, an industrial-strength operating system popular among
corporate users. In 1994, when Microsoft was still having trouble
cracking into the market for corporate computing, it signed a
three-year licensing deal with Bristol. It allowed Bristol broad
access to Microsoft's Windows technology.
</P>
<P>
   But three years later, when Microsoft's own powerful operating
system, Windows NT, was making strong inroads into the corporate
market, the deal offered to Bristol was very different. Microsoft
wanted corporate customers to switch from Unix to Windows NT, and
Bristol alleged that its ``translation'' software _ once an asset
for Microsoft _ was now seen by Microsoft as a potential impediment
to the migration of customers to Windows NT.
</P>
<P>
   So when renegotiating the contract, Microsoft offered Bristol a
new license, but at four times the price and with far less access
to Microsoft technology. ``Microsoft's dealings with Bristol are a
classic bait-and-switch,'' Lynch, the Bristol lawyer, asserted
before the trial began in June.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft did not deny that its license terms had changed, but
it explained that was because the market conditions changed.
Besides, Microsoft says that another company, Mainsoft Inc.,
accepted the same terms that were offered to Bristol. Microsoft
argued that Bristol was trying to elevate a garden-variety contract
dispute into an antitrust case.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Inc. magazine ranked Bristol 140th among the 500
fastest-growing companies in the nation, with a payroll of 70
people and estimated revenues of $8 million. But the failure to
renew its Microsoft license has placed Bristol's future in doubt,
and it has spent heavily on its suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bristol's mistake was that it chose to litigate instead of
negotiate,'' said Aeschbacher of Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   The jury in Connecticut agreed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
