<SLUG> BC-BBA-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: MAKING A CASE FOR BOOMER
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Roger Clemens was back in Boston on Tuesday evening, but not to
play in the All-Star Game. Instead, the former Red Sox-turned-Blue
Jay-turned-Yankee was on hand to share a larger honor. He was being
introduced as a member of Baseball's All-Century Team. When his
name was called, Clemens, who for 13 seasons was the Red Sox' best
pitcher since Babe Ruth, was roundly and harshly booed.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens has got used to being booed in Boston, but the more
bothersome boos were the ones that cascaded down on him at Yankee
Stadium on Thursday evening after he was knocked out and lost, 6-2,
to Tom Glavine and Atlanta. Asked whether he noticed the booing,
Clemens quickly and tersely said, ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a time earlier this season when even polite boos would
have been considered blasphemous. After all, the Rocket is a future
Hall of Famer. But in a shrine like Yankee Stadium, only a few
icons are beyond the fray _ and they are all in bronze. Anyone else
is fair game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just doesn't seem like he's in a comfort zone,'' Yankee
Manager Joe Torre said of Clemens. ``It's taken him longer than he
expected to fix this thing.''
</P>
<P>
   In the surest sign yet that the concern had reached the top of
the organization, George Steinbrenner paid Clemens a visit before
Friday night's game to see how he was doing.
</P>
<P>
   There is talk about the fans' patience wearing thin. The team is
in first place but not playing the flawless baseball it did last
season. Yankee fans ought to stop. After what the Yankees
accomplished last season, the good graces will last for another
season at least. Complaining about the Yankees takes fan
entitlement to a level of silliness unbefitting sophisticated
baseball followers.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, much of the fan rancor is directed at Clemens, not the
team. Clemens said he came to New York to win a championship. Right
now, the team is simply marking time until the playoffs; then and
only then will we see whether Clemens is part of the solution or
part of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens has been erratic, and the fans' patience is definitely
wearing thin with his lack of control. They have waited half a
season for the Rocket to pitch like the Rocket. But Clemens is
following a tougher act than he realized. He comes to a storied
franchise, plays in a legendary stadium on a team coming off the
greatest season in baseball history. He is also playing in a city
of dreams and drama where night after night actors and actresses
outdo themselves on and off Broadway with transcendent
performances.
</P>
<P>
   Fans have come to baseball's theater and waited for Hall of Fame
performances, waited for Clemens to respond to big moments the way
David Wells responded before being traded to Toronto for Clemens.
Fans are waiting for the magic. So far, Clemens has brought neither
magic nor inspiration. Inspiration, of course, was Wells' forte.
</P>
<P>
   Now fans scratch their heads, wondering ``what's wrong'' with
the Yankees and ``what's missing.'' But nothing is wrong; Wells is
what's missing. He has what the Yankees need this season: soul.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, for all their Clemens-esque efficiency, have become
the American League version of the Atlanta Braves: cold and
calculating, but without fire. If you think I'm saying that Wells
needs to be back in New York, you're right. Wells needs to be back
in New York. But not in the Bronx with the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   David Wells needs to be in Queens with the Mets. He is the spark
than can push this scuffling Mets franchise over the barrier that
has blocked the way for far too long. If Mets General Manager Steve
Phillips is the whiz kid he was cracked up to be _ and we haven't
seen all that much yet _ the Mets will find a way to make Toronto
part with Wells before the July 31 trading deadline. Yes, get Wells
even if it means parting with Roger Cedeno.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of Mike Piazza, there are no untouchable
players on this Mets team. The Mets are not the Yankees coming off
a World Series victory and having to think about improving on near
perfection. These are the haven't-won-a-World Series-in-13-years
Mets.
</P>
<P>
   The argument against trading a young player like Cedeno is that
he represents the future. The Mets' future is now. Cedeno, with all
his talent, will not take the Mets to a pennant this year. Wells,
backed by stellar defense, motivated by wounded pride, just might.
More than his pitching, the Mets need Wells' unpredictability and
irreverent presence.
</P>
<P>
   For the last decade the Mets have sat and watched and wondered
how to steal the Yankees' thunder. Now they have their answer:
bring in the Boomer!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
