<HEADLINE>
US FALLS BEHIND, 2-0, IN SWELTERING DAVIS PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ The day straight off the charcoal grill
sizzled to an end with Australian Patrick Rafter tossing, throwing,
and drop-kicking tennis balls into the stands filled with wilted
Americans, followed by Rafter's shirt. Tennis buffs loved the
souvenir balls, women the shirt, and Australians the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to get any better than this,'' said Rafter,
after dispatching one of the few Americans who didn't wilt under
the heat or pressure, Jim Courier. ``We're going to have a great
dinner and a couple of laughs, that's for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe some chuckles, too, being up on the United States Davis
Cup team, 2-0, after Day 1 of the Cup quarterfinals Friday at the
Longwood Cricket Club. Rafter overcame Courier in deceptive
straight sets, 7-6 (7-5), 6-4, 6-4, while 18-year-old Lleyton
Hewitt immediately put the US in dire straits by toppling Todd
Martin in the opening match, 6-4, 6-7 (1-7), 6-3, 6-0.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Sampras _ yes, that Pete Sampras, the Pete Sampras who sat
on a very hot seat behind the American bench all day _ will team
with Alex O'Brien in Saturday's doubles match the US must win. But
since this is Longwood, where history oozes, consider this bit of
Americana: Only once (in 1934) has a US Davis Cup team extricated
itself from an 0-2 abyss.
</P>
<P>
   As wilted as any fan, as wilted as Martin, as wilted as the
American hopes was the US's approach of having a player tell the
coach who should play. But Sampras _ the world's best player _
insisted on playing just doubles out of deference to his teammates,
who have devoted more of their time to the Davis Cup than he.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision was made on principle,'' said US captain Tom
Gullikson, after the grim results guaranteed question after
question about his best player sitting out the first day's matches.
``Whatever you want to write or whatever you want to think is fine
with me.''
</P>
<P>
   The asphalt court was frying at temperatures as high as 126
degrees when Martin and Hewitt opened their equipment bags shortly
after noon. The strategy for Martin was clear, for both physical
and psychological reasons. He had to jump on the nervous Australian
youngster quickly so as not to deplete his stamina and not allow
Hewitt to begin feeling comfortable in this pressure-packed
atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game plan was for (Martin) to go out and dominate the kid
in his first Davis Cup,'' said Gullikson. ``We figured he would be
a little bit nervous and hopefully Todd would get off to a good
start and attack (Hewitt's) second serve and play more aggressive.
But the ball was flying on (Martin).''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, an early turning point for Martin came when he was up,
2-1, in the opening set with three break points. It appeared he was
ready ``to dominate the kid.'' But Martin could not capture the
decisive point and instead of being up, 3-1, he lost that game and
then was broken by Hewitt to go down, 2-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``First set, I was up, love-40 on his serve and he got out of
that game and broke me right away,'' said the American. ``That was
a big momentum change.''
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt not only went on to win the first set, he had won the
confidence that he belonged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, it was pretty tough for me to go to sleep (Thursday
night),'' said the Australian. ``I was trying to have an early
night but then I couldn't get to sleep for a couple of hours. So I
just got on the phone, called the folks back home and all the
mates.''
</P>
<P>
   By now, the fans, some 20 of whom were treated by Brookline
paramedics, were wilting in the heat. But Martin persevered in the
second set, escaping triple break point at 5-5, his final save
coming when he was finally able to get to one of Hewitt's magical
lobs and backhand a return that the 18-year-old drove into the net.
The two finally reached a tiebreaker and the American, to the
surprise of most, cruised to the first 6 points and won, 7-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won that set,'' said Martin, ``but listen, it would have
been much better to have won that set holding my serve throughout
the rest of the set than playing a very good tiebreaker.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin and Hewitt were 2-2 in the third when the American
crashed four winning serves, all the momentum apparently his. But
that pinnacle was followed by a sudden and steep fall over the
cliff as Martin could win only one more game the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I was feeling the momentum,'' said Martin, ``more
because I had won the second set than because I was able to hit
four aces. Four aces is dumb luck, but the next game was where I
got broken. I thought I might have let down there just a couple of
percent.''
</P>
<P>
   At that point, said Hewitt, ``I felt Todd was starting to get a
little bit tired. I was thinking that whatever I am feeling, I am
sure he is feeling a lot worse than I am. So I went out there with
that attitude the rest of the match.''
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt (``I think Lleyton is one of the very few people in the
tennis world that have very, very great nerves,'' said Martin) then
dominated, taking the remainder of the third set easily and the
final at love.
</P>
<P>
   When Courier and Rafter took the court for the second match,
former president George Bush had fleed his first-row seat in search
of shade.
</P>
<P>
   The first set between Courier and Rafter was the brightest of
tennis jewels. Courier broke Rafter to go up, 3-1, but Rafter
lifted his play and won the next three games. At 5-6, Courier took
a splendid deuce point after a long and vigorous rally when his
shot apparently clipped the back of the baseline. Rafter didn't
agree, one of several calls the players would question. Courier
took the next point, the game, and stepped reached the tiebreaker.
</P>
<P>
   A tiebreaker, said Rafter, that ``was a comedy of a lot of
unforced errors. We were both trying to give that tiebreaker away
there for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   The play had improved when the crucial point came at 5-4
Courier. A Rafter shot to the baseline was ruled in, while a
Courier return of that shot was called out. Rafter thought
Courier's shot was in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We both had some bad line calls at some really crucial
times,'' said Rafter. ``His turned out to be more crucial than
mine.'' Courier said Rafter's ball ``just skidded off the back of
the line. That was a good call.''
</P>
<P>
   Courier gave the sixth point to Rafter on another unforced error
and then Rafter took the set with a winning serve. ``I think if Jim
had won that first set,'' said Gullikson, ``he would have gotten
some momentum going and hopefully the crowd would have gotten into
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The second set went to Rafter, 6-4, and the next crucial call
came at 4-4 in the third when another deep shot by Courier was
ruled out. Courier advanced to the net and stood there staring at
the lineswoman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see the videotape on that one,'' he said. ``I know
on the tape it's going to be good because my eyes are a lot better
than the linespeople. Otherwise, they would be playing.''
</P>
<P>
   So the US is down, 0-2, and the best advice _ the only advice _
to give the team was bestowed by Sidney Wood, a member of the 1934
team that is still the only US team to recover from being down two
matches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Win the doubles, first of all,'' said Wood.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
