<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-CHINA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEARS OF MILITARY CONFRONTATION WITH CHINA SHAKE TAIWAN FINANCIAL
MARKETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Fears of a military confrontation with China swept
through financial markets in Taiwan Friday, causing the biggest
single-day plunge in the stock index in nine years.
</P>
<P>
   In a panicky wave of selling that began on rumors of Chinese
military action against Taiwan, the Taipei stock index fell 6.4
percent, or 506 points, to close at 7,411. The jitters spread
across the region, with stock markets' dropping in Tokyo, Hong
Kong, and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions between China and Taiwan have been growing since last
weekend, when President Lee Teng-hui of Taiwan unexpectedly dropped
the long-held premise that Taiwan and China are separately governed
parts of the same country. Lee declared that the countries ought to
negotiate on a ``state-to-state'' basis.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese government responded with denunciations of Lee and
warnings that it was ready to use military force to stop Taiwan
from declaring independence from China. The warning led newspapers
in Hong Kong to report that China might seize a couple of islands
off Taiwan as a show of force.
</P>
<P>
   Military officials in Taiwan flatly denied the reports, saying
they had detected no Chinese military movements. But the damage was
done. Despite aggressive buying of shares by the government this
week, Taiwan's market has fallen more than 13 percent since the
dispute erupted.
</P>
<P>
   Domestic politics has deepened the instability. A popular former
governor of Taiwan, James Soong, announced Friday that he would
break away from the governing Nationalist Party and run for
president next year as an independent. Although Soong's move was
widely expected, it exposed a fissure in the Nationalists, who have
governed Taiwan for 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts said they worried that prolonged instability could
derail the economy, which managed to get through the Asian crisis
largely unscathed and had been picking up steam lately.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're expecting a low-intensity confrontation across the
straits, which could last until the presidential elections next
year,'' Dong Tao, a regional strategist at Credit Suisse First
Boston in Hong Kong, said. ``Obviously, the longer it lasts, the
more negative the impact on the economy would be.''
</P>
<P>
   Tao said Taiwan was more vulnerable to a crisis of confidence
than other countries, because a large percentage of people's wealth
is tied up in stocks. So a further drop in share prices could cause
a decline in consumer spending.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan's economy is driven by exports, particularly
semiconductor chips and other computer components. A growing
confrontation could prompt computer companies in the United States
to cancel orders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happened in 1995, it could happen again,'' Tao said,
referring to a dispute in which China conducted military exercises
and tested ballistic missiles near Taiwan. That crisis, defused
after President Clinton sent two aircraft carrier groups to the
region in 1996, had measurable negative effects on the country's
growth.
</P>
<P>
   Before the verbal fireworks this week Taiwan had emerged as the
economic star of Asia. Although the country never fell into a
wrenching recession like its rivals Hong Kong and Singapore, its
growth slowed, from 6.8 percent in 1997 to 4.8 percent last year.
After a shaky start this year, analysts said, Taiwan's domestic
spending and exports had picked up strongly.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Credit Suisse First Boston predicted that Taiwan's
economy would grow 3.5 percent in 1999. In May, it raised its
forecast, to 5.2 percent. Tao said the firm had been on the verge
of raising it again, to 6 percent. Now, however, he said it would
hold off until the end of the current crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``From time to time, China finds ways to make Taiwan feel
uncomfortable,'' Tao said. ``I don't think it would go so far as to
fire missiles.''
</P>
<P>
   Few experts said they believed that the tension would escalate
into a shooting war. Some even said the sharp drop in the Taiwanese
market is a good opportunity to invest. But the sell off was a
reminder that the Asian recovery is a fragile phenomenon, driven by
market psychology, as well as economic fundamentals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
