<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN IOWA, CLINTON MAKES CASE FOR SCHOOL SPENDING 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ President Clinton on Friday pitched his $24.8
billion plan to modernize 6,000 schools, saying students could not
do their best work in buildings ``where kids walk up the steps and
they see broken windows every day, where there are rooms, in some
cases whole floors they can't even go on.''
</P>
<P>
   He also commiserated with Iowa's small farmers who have been hit
hard by crop prices that have fallen below the cost of production
in some cases.
</P>
<P>
   Joking that he was the only noncandidate Iowans had seen in
weeks, Clinton spoke in a newly refurbished, but sweltering,
gymnasium at Amos Hiatt Middle School, a 74-year-old building where
recent repairs were paid for through an $18 million federal
demonstration project. A line about how some schools do not even
have working heating and air-conditioning systems got a huge laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton tied the need for school construction, through
interest-free bonds, to the broader debate about how to spend the
budget surplus. ``I believe before we pass a big tax cut we should
save Social Security and Medicare and add a prescription drug
benefit to Medicare,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the outlook for Clinton's proposal in Congress is uncertain.
It was defeated as an amendment to a tax bill this week in the
House Ways and Means Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a time of confidence and pride,'' Clinton said of the
current economic boom. ``But the time to fix the roof is when the
sun is shining, and that is literally true in the case of school
construction.''
</P>
<P>
   These are not boom times in Iowa, though, and Clinton
acknowledged that farmers were among those who have not shared the
wealth. Only a day earlier, he was criticized by George W. Bush,
the Texas governor and Republican presidential candidate, for
ignoring the plight of farmers during his cross-country tour last
week to highlight pockets of poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Clinton said, ``The big problem on the farm is we've had
four years in a row of worldwide record harvest for the first time
in history, and an economic collapse in 1997 in Asia, so markets
shrink, the products go, prices collapse.''
</P>
<P>
   At that point, a woman in the crowd shouted out, ``Freedom to
Farm!'' referring to the Freedom to Farm Act, a 1996 law that
phased out most direct crop subsidies and encouraged high
production at a time when the Asian financial crisis had limited
the buying power of overseas customers.
</P>
<P>
   After the speech, Bill Sherman, a local lobbyist for the
teachers' union, said the farm crisis had, among other things, made
it much harder to pass bond issues for school construction. ``Until
farmers can make a decent living, it will be very difficult to get
decent facilities, especially in rural areas,'' Sherman said.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the afternoon, Clinton had a closed meeting with a
group of farmers who planned to talk to him about the importance of
pushing for changes in the Freedom to Farm law, with the soft
prices and bumper crops causing a repeat of the farm crisis in the
1980s, but with much less national attention.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was also to appear at two evening fund-raisers for Sen.
Tom Harkin, who said in an interview that it was important for the
president to come to Iowa to hear about the farm crisis firsthand.
``This is the worst I've seen,'' he said. ``It's worse now than in
the mid-'80s.''
</P>
<P>
   A recent report by the Agriculture Department projected the
average prices for corn and soybean for this year at about half the
prices of only a few seasons ago.
</P>
<P>
   With commodity prices falling below production costs, Harkin
said, an aid package for struggling grain farmers and livestock
producers was desperately needed. ``Every day we wait is going to
cost us more,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
