<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH-OPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRENCH QUALIFIER IS OVER PAR, BUT AHEAD OF THE FIELD  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: France, Australia, Sweden)   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARNOUSTIE, Scotland _ The final four holes at Carnoustie may be
the toughest finishing holes in the world. Ask Greg Norman, who
triple-bogeyed No. 17 Friday. Or Tiger Woods, who bogeyed No. 16
and No. 18. But on the same holes where Norman and Woods faltered,
an unexpected leader emerged.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Van de Velde, a 33-year-old Frenchman who won a Monday
qualifier just to earn a spot in the British Open, is leading the
tournament and living a dream. Shooting the best round of the Open
so far, a 3-under-par 68, Van de Velde was 1 over for the
championship after two rounds (143). He was also 1 stroke ahead of
Angel Cabrera of Argentina, who shot a 69 Friday, and 2 ahead of
Jesper Parnevik of Sweden, who shot a 71. Norman and Woods, who
will be paired Saturday for the first time in a major, were tied
for fourth place with Patrik Sjoland of Sweden at 4 over par. A
host of players will begin the weekend in contention, including
Justin Leonard (5 over) and Davis Love III (6 over).
</P>
<P>
   Van de Velde became the first 36-hole leader at a major
championship to be over par since the 1974 United States Open at
Winged Foot Country Club in Mamaroneck, N.Y., when the leaders were
tied at 3 over par. Van de Velde had the highest 36-hole leading
score at the British Open since 1968 at Carnoustie, when Tony
Jacklin, Bob Charles and Brian Barnes shared the lead at even-par
144, when Carnoustie was par 72.
</P>
<P>
   However, the hopes of many players were answered Friday, as the
wind, which gusted to 30 miles an hour Thursday, subsided to 10 to
15 m.p.h. throughout the morning before increasing later in the
day.
</P>
<P>
   Not that playing Carnoustie was easy. It never is. Rodney
Pampling, the only player to shoot as well as even par on Thursday,
became the first opening-round leader in British Open history to
miss the cut, falling apart today with an 86. But at least standing
on the tee box didn't feel like standing in front of an airplane
propeller. Friday's average score was 76.9, compared with 78.3 on
Thursday. Van de Velde, Cabrera, David Frost (69) and Costantino
Rocca (69) all broke 70, and players who were at their best showed
that it was actually possible to make birdies.
</P>
<P>
   Van de Velde saved his best work for last, making birdies at
both No. 16 and No. 18 to snatch the lead and to gain the golf
world's attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I was not that nervous,'' said Van de Velde, who
could become the first player from France to win the British Open
since Arnaud Massy in 1907. ``I know it's a major championship, but
it's just a golf tournament. Now, I have to try not to do anything
silly. If it's my week, it's my week.''
</P>
<P>
   The week has been embarrassing for many of the world's best
players, who have lost their games and their composure on a
demanding course that can control your mind. The 36-hole cut was a
mind-boggling 12 over par, yet many of the game's top players did
not make it, including Phil Mickelson (13 over), Tom Lehman (14
over), the defending champion Mark O'Meara (15 over), Jose Maria
Olazabal (15 over), Steve Elkington (15 over), Mark Calcavecchia
(17 over) and Vijay Singh (19 over).
</P>
<P>
   Nick Faldo (15 over) missed his first British Open cut in 24
appearances Friday, shooting his highest Open round, a 79. The
five-time Open champion Tom Watson (13 over) was also rudely
dismissed. And 19-year-old Sergio Garcia's score looked like a
misprint: 30 over par.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will try to forget this,'' said Garcia, who followed his
first-round 89 with an 83 Friday and finished last. ``I can't
remember when I last shot an 89. For the first time in 10 years, I
don't think I will watch the British Open on TV. I don't think it
deserves it. You have probably the toughest golf course in the
world and 12-yard-wide fairways. I almost hurt my wrist on No. 7. I
missed the fairway by 2 yards and it was unplayable.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Van de Velde danced around Carnoustie's potential trouble
like Fred Astaire, avoiding the engulfing rough, playing the
shifting winds to perfection and completing a beautiful round that
included 4 birdies and just one bogey.
</P>
<P>
   Van de Velde has enjoyed a solid year on the European Tour, but
who expected this? Fatigued after Monday's qualifying event, he
played just one practice round at Carnoustie before Thursday's
first-round 75. Perhaps that was a blessing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the place, because I played in the Scottish Open,''
said Van de Velde, who has two top-10 finishes in Europe this year
but has never contended in a major. ``I don't think the more you
play Carnoustie, the better you're going to play. The more you play
it, the more fairway you're going to miss, and the more you're
going to worry.''
</P>
<P>
   The highlights of Van de Velde's round came at the par-3,
250-yard No. 16 and the par-4, 487-yard No. 18. Van de Velde made a
45-foot putt for birdie at No. 16 that brought a huge roar from the
gallery. Then at No. 18, which played downwind, he hit a
magnificent 2-iron approach shot that nestled 3 feet from the cup
for an easy birdie and sole possession of the lead. Meanwhile,
Norman and Woods had tougher finishes.
</P>
<P>
   Starting the day at 5 over par, Norman made a vintage charge. He
was spectacular through the first 16 holes, playing them 4 under
par and leaving himself tied for the lead. But Carnoustie's
intimidating No. 17 _ par 4, 459 yards into the wind _ got the best
of Norman. His drive drifted just into the right rough, settling in
deep hay. Norman took a wedge and hacked at the ball on his next
shot. The ball barely moved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either the club went underneath it, or the club never reached
the ball,'' Norman said. ``I don't think hitting a tee shot off the
fairway by 9 feet deserves something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   He hacked across the fairway into the left rough on his next
shot, hacked back into the fairway, hit an approach shot that
landed short, then chipped and putted for a 7.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Woods, who hit a 6-iron shot through the green at
No. 16, chipped to 15 feet, then missed the putt. At No. 18, his
8-iron approach shot also went over the green, and after his chip
to 10 feet, he missed another putt that would have saved par. Yet,
just 3 strokes off the lead, Woods liked his chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in very good shape,'' he said. ``This golf course is going
to penalize you whether you hit good shots or bad shots. It's just
the way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   It will not change this weekend, which means almost anything
could happen with two grueling rounds to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether you win or lose, we're playing some beautiful shots
that we really don't practice at all,'' Norman said. ``We'll
probably wake up Monday morning and say, `God, I had a lot of fun.'
But right now, in the heat of the moment, we don't like it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
