<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVENUES CAN GROW WITH TAX CUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Capitalism's critics must have suffered a good deal of cognitive
dissonance as a result of efforts over the past two decades to
shrink capital gains tax rates. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, pro-government liberals are generally happy
about anything that enhances government revenue. They are, however,
generally opposed to any tax break perceived to be inordinately
generous to the rich. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With capital gains tax relief, however, less has proved to be
more, which creates a problem for anyone framing the capital gains
tax debate in a class warfare context. The hard-core class
warriors, though, overcome their cognitive dissonance by pretending
that capital gains tax cuts neither add to Uncle Sam's coffers nor
enhance economic fortunes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some dismiss the latest GOP bid to ease the capital gains tax
bite as welfare for the country clubbers. The most comprehensive
initiative is that of House Ways and Means Chairman Bill Archer,
whose tax-relief package includes a proposal to pare the top
individual capital gains tax to 15 percent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The estimate of tax savings for those who would take profits
under the proposed lower rate is nearly $52 billion over 10 years.
Some critics use this number to justify their opposition, saying
affluent investors don't deserve this sort of government
generosity. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As a budget expert noted recently in The Wall Street Journal,
however, a cut in the capital gains tax rate is likely to increase
the capital gains revenue take rather than diminish it. At least
that's been the experience in the aftermath of previous cuts in
capital gains tax rates. Moreover, when the capital gains tax rate
was increased, revenue collections suffered. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Moore, director of fiscal policy studies for the Cato
Institute, pointed out that as a result of the 1981 capital gains
rate cut from 28 percent to 20 percent, revenues from this tax
surged by nearly 50 percent from 1980 to 1983. Coincidentally, both
the recession and the bear market bottomed out in 1982. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, Moore recalled, when the 1981 capital gains
reduction was sacrificed to the Tax Reform Act of 1986 and the
capital gains tax rate went back up, capital gains revenues
plummeted. The $50 billion capital gains tax take of 1986, the last
year of the 20 percent rate, had fallen to $25 billion by 1991,
presumably due to the higher rate. Meantime, the economy went into
recession from mid-1990 to the spring of 1991. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After the rate was returned to 20 percent in 1997, Moore said,
revenues from capital gains realizations surged again. Capital
gains receipts rose by 27 percent in 1997, and an analysis by
economist Lawrence Kudlow shows a two-year rise of 40 percent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As for the collateral benefits of a lower capital gains rate,
Moore says one study credits 25 percent of the stock market's rise
of the past two years to 1997's capital gains tax relief. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The argument that capital gains tax relief benefits only the
rich is anachronistic. While it's true that the rich may benefit
more, growing affluence and the increasing investment pursuits by
average Americans have expanded the effects of capital gains
taxes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The benefits of relief include not only a lower tax burden, but
also the growth that makes the U.S. economy the envy of a
struggling world. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
