<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-UMPIRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINOR LEAGUES HAVE A PLAN WITH REPLACEMENT UMPIRES
</HEADLINE>
   (ko) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Faced with an implicit threat of an umpires strike of their own,
the minor leagues have made arrangements for replacements, a
high-ranking official said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Pat O'Conner, vice president for administration for the National
Association of Professional Baseball Leagues, said that the minor
leagues would proceed with their ``normal course of business'' but
that presidents of the 16 leagues under the association were
instructed to have replacements ``available as needed.''
</P>
<P>
   The replacements may be needed as early as next week because
umpires from each minor league are scheduled to have a conference
call Monday with Richie Phillips, the Philadelphia lawyer who heads
the Major League Umpires Association and the newly formed Minor
League Umpires Association.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips said he and the umpires had a one-hour conference call
Friday and decided to talk again Monday. The umpires, who are
signed to individual one-year contracts, are expected to decide in
that call whether to walk out.
</P>
<P>
   The discussions involving the minor league umpires follow the
announcement three days ago by the major league umpires that they
would resign effective Sept. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips said minor league umpires were ``fighting a battle for
better pay and improved working conditions.'' He said umpires in
the lowest level of the minors earned $4,500 a year and received
$15 a day for meals. At the highest level, he said, the annual
salary is $12,500 and meal money is $20 a day.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, he said, the AHL, which is a minor league for the
NHL, pays officials a $41,000 starting salary and $59 a day in meal
money.
</P>
<P>
   O'Conner said a letter from Phillips that was received July 9
contained ``an implicit threat that some sort of job action might
take place. Based on that, we've made arrangements for
replacements.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that as a matter of course, each league had alternate
umpires available in case an umpire missed a game or was summoned
to work in a higher league.
</P>
<P>
   Triple-A leagues, like the major leagues, use a four-umpire
system. Double-A leagues have three umpires, and all other leagues
use two. Phillips has said 220 of 228 minor league umpires voted to
form a union. In his letter, O'Conner said, Phillips said he
represented the new union.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a good-faith doubt that claims Phillips made are
accurate,'' O'Conner said, ``and we've asked him to go to the
National Labor Relations Board and file a petition. If there's a
union certified by the NLRB, we have a commitment to deal with that
union in good faith.''
</P>
</TEXT>
