<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLUSH BUSH TURNS TO SOFT MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Iowa) (mk) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Although George W. Bush has amassed a huge
political war chest from small donations, he has apparently found a
novel way to give major Republican donors an opportunity to support
his campaign with large amounts known as soft money.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the Texas governor and candidate for the Republican
presidential nomination, bid a remarkable $43,500 earlier this
month to rent a prime spot to court participants in next month's
Iowa straw polls. But to pay that amount, Bush did not tap into the
$37 million he has raised in donations that are restricted by law
to $1,000 or less.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, his campaign said Friday that the money was paid by six
donors, four of whom gave $10,000 and two who gave $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's perfectly legal,'' Karen Hughes, his spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hughes said the straw poll, to be conducted in Ames next
month, is essentially a fund-raising event for the Iowa Republican
Party. As such, she said, it falls under the part of the law that
allows donors to provide unlimited contributions for party-building
activities. Such donations are commonly called soft money.
</P>
<P>
   Dee Stewart, the executive director of the Iowa Republican
Party, agreed. ``From our perspective it is a fund-raiser,''
Stewart said in an interview. ``We're well within the law in taking
these funds.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign of Steve Forbes, a Bush rival, did not see it quite
the same way.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Appell, a Forbes spokesman, accused the Bush campaign of
abusing the fund-raising rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``This raises a serious question about how ethical a Bush
administration would be,'' Appell said, ``especially when we know
he's raised a gazillion dollars from Washington special-interest
lobbyists.''
</P>
<P>
   All of the campaigns have leased space outside of Hilton
Coliseum in Ames to throw parties for supporters showing up for the
straw poll, considered an early test of candidate strength. Bush
secured the prime plot outside the arena after outbidding Forbes by
$600. Forbes wound up paying $8,000 for a smaller space, and other
candidates spent from $1,000 to $5,500.
</P>
<P>
   To cover Bush's bid, the Iowa party received pledges of $10,000
from Ray Hunt, Bradford Freeman, Heinz Prechter and C. Michael
Kojaian, as well as $5,000 donations from Louis Beecherl and John
Collins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
