<SLUG> BC-Y2K-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEVERAL CITIES WILL CUT Y2K REPAIRS CLOSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HAYES and FINN BULLERS  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nearly half of the nation's 21 largest cities won't complete
work on their Y2K computer repairs until the final three months of
the year, according to a a congressional report released this
week. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two cities, Dallas and Boston, have finished work to ensure that
their computers will continue to function on Jan. 1, 2000. Nine
others expect to be fully ready by Sept. 30, and 10 cities say they
will be ready between Oct. 1 and the end of the year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City is roughly 80 percent complete. Although not
included in the survey by the General Accounting Office, Y2K
coordinators in Kansas City say they will be ready by Oct. 1, at a
cost of $17.5 million. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Don Eatherton, the city's Y2K coordinator, concedes that not
all departments will meet that target date. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Work at Kansas City International Airport won't be complete
until December. It's the same story at the Public Works Department,
where the greatest challenge is fixing 231 traffic signals with bad
software or clocks. Plan B calls for all signals to default to
four-way flashing red, or for four-way stop signs to be rolled out
at main intersections. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The city also reports that work at Metropolitan Ambulance
Services Trust won't be complete until Nov. 1. Of the 15 critical
areas to fix, none have been completed, the city reports at its Web
site _ {www.kcmo.org//y2k.htm}. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Y2K work is well under way at MAST, says Associate Director
Jim Jones. The ambulance service is awaiting software upgrades to
its billing and collection systems before it can be certified as
Y2K-compliant, he said. The upgrades are expected in September. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still on the Kansas City to-do list: securing backup generators
to power the airport for up to four months; developing new software
for animal licenses; completing wiring and testing of emergency
police fuel pumps; continuing to monitor emergency preparedness,
bioterrorism and communicable-disease responses; contingency plans;
and reconstructing the Mayor's Christmas Tree database for
charitable giving. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, federal agencies are generally thought to be in good
shape, but Y2K watchers in Washington are more concerned about the
efforts being made by state and local governments. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kansas, Missouri and 44 other states entered fiscal year 2000 on
July 1 without big problems. Kansas City, too, experienced few
problems when it faced the 2000 fiscal year on May 1. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The GAO report noted that although most cities won't be totally
prepared until later in the year, many have made substantial
progress. El Paso, Texas, and Baltimore are the only cities
expecting December completion dates. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cities saying they will be Y2K-ready by Sept. 30 are New York;
Houston; Philadelphia; San Diego; San Jose, Calif.; Indianapolis;
Jacksonville, Fla.; Memphis, Tenn.; and Milwaukee. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Those that will finish work in the final three months of the
year are Los Angeles; Chicago; Phoenix; San Antonio; Detroit; San
Francisco; Baltimore; Columbus, Ohio; El Paso; and Washington,
D.C. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City's mission-critical contingency plans will be worked
on right up until Dec. 31. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who stops working on it and says they're done is a
fool,'' said Eatherton. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Russian roulette &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Only one-third of Russia's vital computer systems are ready for
the millennium, and the government probably won't have the money to
fix the rest in time, officials said this week. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Finance Ministry officials told a Cabinet meeting that Russia
needs at least $187 million to prepare its computers for the Year
2000, reported the ITAR-Tass news agency. The figure was
dramatically lower than previous figures, which said Russia would
need $1 billion to $3 billion. The Finance Ministry did not explain
the discrepancy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, the money will be hard to find. Moscow probably will have
to give priority to defense and security sectors while withholding
money from other agencies, Finance Minister Mikhail Kasyanov said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Russian government agencies have 28,000 vital computer systems,
one-third of which are Y2K-compliant. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Russia plans to reduce the number of airplane flights Dec. 31,
halt some hazardous industrial processes and switch others to
manual control. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bug byte &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Irony of ironies. The prosecutor who hunts down bad checks in
Monroe County, Ind., is the same man responsible for issuing two
whopping rubber checks in June _ one for $50 million and another
for $49 million. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Blame the bug. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It seems the decimal point bounced around a bit after the county
installed new software designed to fix Y2K problems. The numbers in
the upper right-hand part of the checks were correct _ in this case
$50 and $49.01. But the wording ``fifty million'' and ``forty-nine
million'' appeared on the center lines. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I dearly love this,'' said wrecker service owner Gary Koontz,
who is considering framing the check he received. ``I told my wife
we were millionaires for a day.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
