<SLUG> BC-MONKEY-PET-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDEPENDENCE, MO., WOMAN DETERMINED TO KEEP PET MONKEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TRISHA L. HOWARD  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some people stand up to City Hall. Mellisa Chapman danced around
it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Told by the city of Independence, Mo., that she had to get rid
of Lucy, her long-tailed macaque, Chapman decided to build a
separate house for the animal in unincorporated Jackson County. The
house is in a neighbor's yard, just beyond the Independence city
limits. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By next week, Lucy should be in her own house. It's no dump,
either. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chapman is spending nearly $3,000 on an 8- by 8-foot structure
complete with a large cage, a skylight, air conditioning and a
television. Jungle wallpaper, too. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Lucy is a beloved family pet,'' she said. ``I couldn't just
give her to someone else.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   City and county officials say the new digs are legal, unless
Lucy returns to Independence for a visit. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chapman knew when she bought Lucy that she couldn't keep a
monkey in Independence. So last year, her family moved to a house
with a Blue Springs mailing address. That city does not ban
monkeys. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The catch: Chapman's house is within Independence. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Faulk, Jackson County's animal control officer, said he
had seen stranger pets than Lucy _ but not a stranger solution. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing to compare to this little facility she is
going to be erecting,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Once Lucy moves, Independence will have no jurisdiction, said
Tom Heinkel, manager of the city's animal control department.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If that monkey is outside city limits...there is not much I
can say,'' Heinkel said. ``But if the monkey comes over to visit,
that's illegal.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
