A3433 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ACTOR-PRIEST-KAN &LR;      07-16 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACTOR-PRIEST-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTOR, DANCE, SEMINARIAN: A YOUNG MAN FINDING HIS PLACE IN LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE POPPER  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a hot summer day in 1997, Kent O'Connor, a young actor and
dancer then appearing in ``Gypsy'' at the New Theatre Restaurant in
Overland Park, Kan., had a strange experience with a familiar
song. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the time he was driving on Interstate 435 listening to a tape
of mixed music made for him by one of his brothers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the songs was one by REO Speedwagon that included the
repeated line, ``I can't fight the feeling anymore.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``That line caught me so off guard I almost had to stop the
car,'' O'Connor said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For at the moment the song began, O'Connor was pondering the
resolution of a quandary that had begun in his childhood. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It had begun with a feeling he could no longer fight. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This summer O'Connor is appearing at the New Theatre, playing a
featured role in ``Hello Dolly.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But he is playing another role as well, and his photograph
appears not only in the theater program. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is displayed as well on the bulletin board at Holy Cross
Church in Overland Park. The wording beneath his picture there
identifies him as a seminarian and future Catholic priest. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now living in the church rectory for the summer, O'Connor
devotes the time between stage performances to working with the
church's summer youth program. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday morning, for example, he helped lead a group of
elementary-school children as they prepared for an upcoming musical
show. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He sang along as they rehearsed, and despite the fact that his
singing was subdued, his strong tenor voice reached from the altar
to the rear pew. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His is a trained voice, for although he is only 24, he has been
working in the theater for 17 years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When he was 7 and growing up in Topeka, when his mother asked
``if I'd like to be in the Nutcracker Suite. And I said, `Sure,'
without even thinking about it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He began dance training that year and soon was involved with
community theater, sometimes with as many as three productions at a
time. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a busy kid,'' he said. ``I was always in dance classes
or rehearsals. And I loved it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He threw himself into performing with such vigor and elan that
his mother, Marilyn O'Connor, sometimes feared that he would hurl
himself off the edge of the stage. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time his theatrical fervor began to blossom,
another seed was planted, one that grew more slowly but whose
roots, perhaps, went deeper. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was 7 or 8, I was sitting in church as the priest was
talking about religious vocations,'' O'Connor said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember looking into a flickering candle in the sanctuary
and thinking, yes, I'll be a priest. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't mention it to anybody, because I didn't really know
what it was all about. But I sensed it was a lasting commitment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``And that seemed strange to me, because my church life was
limited then. I did little except go to Mass. And yet that day I
began to feel something that has never gone away, and that I'm
still trying to understand.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While O'Connor was in high school, he began to believe that what
he was experiencing was a ``calling,'' an almost inexplicable
summons to the priesthood. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that I literally heard God call my name,'' he said
recently. ``It was more of a constant nagging in the back of my
head, an endless questioning: Am I on the right path? Is my life
going to be complete?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His mother, sensing something, joked that if he chose dance as a
career he could always become a priest when his legs gave out. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But though he laughed, he still wouldn't talk about that idea
with anybody. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``For one thing, I wanted a social life,'' he said. ``And what
girl would date a guy who says he's going to be a priest?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, the theatrical world still beckoned. And so instead
of entering a seminary, O'Connor went to the University of Kansas,
where he studied dance and theater. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   During spring break in 1997, his senior year in college,
O'Connor traveled to New York City to try his luck in the
cattle-call world of theatrical auditions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I went with this funny notion that the theater actually needed
me,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His reception was positive, his talent recognized. After five
auditions he made the final cut for one show, was called back for
another, and received a job offer from a ballet company. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But despite that success, he reached an unexpected conclusion. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not doing anyone a big favor by being here,'' he thought.
``The theater will do just fine without me.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly frustrated with what he calls the ``self-centeredness''
of the dance world, feeling like a trained dog performing tricks,
he began to think he was wasting his other talents. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I was spending so much time training my body that my intellect
was going to pot,'' he said. ``Something important was missing. I
decided I needed to make a change in my life.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And so he attended a religious retreat in Atchison, Kan., and
then visited Mundelein Seminary near Chicago. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I fell in love with it,'' he said. ``I knew immediately it was
where I needed to be. And so I applied.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He soon discovered that simply applying to Mundelein, a seminary
devoted to training diocesan priests, is a rigorous process. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Every candidate first has to be approved by his own diocese,''
said Thomas Tank, a Catholic priest and vicar-general of the
Archdiocese of Kansas City in Kansas. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``And that involves a twofold process of discernment. One is on
the part of the individual, who is counseled in ways to examine his
personal sense of calling.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The other, he said, is undertaken by church committees that
evaluate a number of qualities to determine whether the candidate
has the aptitude to serve the church. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All candidates go through extensive psychological evaluation and
are then screened by both diocesan and seminary acceptance
committees. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After running that churchly gauntlet, O'Connor was finally
accepted and has now completed his first sequence of seminary
course work. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still not positive about my choice,'' he said this week. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I have four more years before taking any vows, and I may
discover I should be doing something else. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm in the right place. And I know that however it turns
out, the nagging question will have been answered.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
