r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SENATE-COURTESY-KAN &LR;      07-16 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-COURTESY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURTESY AND GRACIOUSNESS IN SHORT SUPPLY IN SENATE, ANALYSTS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ To hear some people talk Friday, members of that
exclusive and powerful club known as the U.S. Senate should pay a
visit to Miss Manners. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Scholars and others who study or practice politics said at a
forum sponsored by the Robert J. Dole Institute for Public Service
and Public Policy that civility had declined in the Senate and that
deliberation was more rancorous. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Civility does make a difference,'' said Burdett Loomis,
interim director of the institute, which is based at the University
of Kansas. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Civility will draw better people to politics and improve the
decision-making process, he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some speakers at the daylong forum in a Senate office building
said senators today tended to be more partisan, publicly critical
of each other and more consumed with getting re-elected than with
working together. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Senators increasingly use filibusters and other divisive
maneuvers to stifle legislation, such as budget bills, speakers
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to confess to being worried and concerned about the
future,'' said Sen. Pat Roberts, a Kansas Republican elected in
1996 after serving 16 years in the House. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately the tendency to fuss, cuss and fight rather than
discuss has become a reflex for legislators,'' Roberts said. ``Some
approach legislation almost like a campaign for election _ you
either win or lose. Debate suffers; policy suffers; people lose.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ten scholars submitted papers at the conference Friday on the
subject of civility and deliberation in the Senate. The Dole
Institute, which holds his congressional papers, will make a report
based on the scholars' papers and the forum. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Loomis said Dole, the retired senator from Kansas, was an
example of civility and deliberation in the Senate of old. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He could get people in a room, get them to deliberate, get
them to decide and come out in a reasonably productive and civil
way,'' Loomis said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dole said the trend toward less civility and more deliberation
in the Senate was no surprise at a time when Senate debate is
televised live and when there is 24-hour news coverage of
politics. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We are, after all, a representative democracy _ a mirror held
up to America,'' Dole told the gathering of about 50 persons
Friday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He said there was nothing wrong with senators having
disagreements. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``In a democracy, differences are not only unavoidable, (but) if
pursued with civility as well as conviction, are downright
healthy,'' Dole said. ``Put another way, I'd rather deal with
honest contention than creeping cynicism. Yet that's exactly what
afflicts our society today, when millions of citizens regard all
politicians as puppets on a string, dancing to the music of
spinmeisters.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Roberts said the decline in civility in the House and Senate
reflected a similar decline in society in general, an argument
several other speakers made Friday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Roberts said another reason might be that lawmakers do not
spend as much time getting to know each other as they did years
ago. Today, most of them go home every weekend and are in
Washington only when votes are taken. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many in Congress today do not develop close relationships
with colleagues and others in the policy process,'' Roberts said.
``They do not develop an appreciation of senators, let alone their
views on issues.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dole said he learned during his years in the Senate ``that an
adversary is not always an enemy.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Keith Kennedy, former longtime staff director of the Senate
Appropriations Committee who is now in private law practice, said
partisanship was taking a growing toll on the Senate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are losing is productivity,'' Kennedy said. ``There
seems to be almost as much of a premium on being an obstructionist
as on producing something.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Sam Brownback, a Kansas Republican who succeeded Dole, said
the Senate proved it could be civil and nonpartisan at the
impeachment trial of President Clinton last winter. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All 100 senators met in private to work out a trial schedule and
then managed to hear the case with much less public bitterness and
partisanship than the House. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The impeachment trial actually built more communication,''
Brownback said. ``I think that trial was conducted on a civil,
bipartisan basis.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Harry C. McPherson, former special counsel to President Lyndon
B. Johnson and now a partner in the Washington law firm where Dole
is employed, challenged the idea that civility and deliberation
were paramount. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Voters usually are not focusing on the most polite candidate
or the one who takes the most time making up his or her mind on
legislation,'' McPherson said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the greatest senators have been persons of such force
of personality, such power of will, such intellectual arrogance and
such irresistible energy that they were able to ram their work
through the ranks of much more polite and willful members. And the
nation benefited from that.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
