<HEADLINE>
FRANCE'S SIMON IS STILL SECOND IN SIBLING RIVALRY  
(DW) 

</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. FLOUR, France _ Francois Simon has something that none of
his three brothers achieved as professional bicycle racers: the
blue, white and red jersey of the French national champion. But
they have something he has not yet achieved: a stage victory in the
Tour de France.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year-old Simon, who rides for the Credit Agricole team,
gave it his all Friday but fell short of the achievements of his
brothers Pascal (1982), Regis (1985) and Jerome (1988).
</P>
<P>
   He finished 25 seconds behind David Etxebarria, a Spaniard with
ONCE who completed the hilly 201.5-kilometer (125-mile) jaunt from
bucolic St. Galmier to the perched village of St. Flour. Etxebarria
was timed in 4 hours 53 minutes 50 seconds, or an average speed of
25 miles an hour in sunny and warm weather.
</P>
<P>
   The race's leaders let low-ranked riders gambol for the second
successive day, and there was only a small change at the top.
</P>
<P>
   Lance Armstrong, the leader of the U.S. Postal Service team,
remained in the first-place yellow jersey by 7:44 over Abraham
Olano, a Spaniard with ONCE, who lost two seconds, and by 7:47 over
Alex Zuelle, a Swiss with Banesto.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
