<SLUG> BC-COLUMNIST-SUSPENSION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWSPAPER COLUMNIST SUSPENDED FOR BUYING STOCK THROUGH FRIEND
</HEADLINE>
  (ko) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A San Jose Mercury News business columnist was suspended
indefinitely Friday for taking advantage of a friend's offer to buy
shares of a fledgling company at a price not available to the
general public.
</P>
<P>
   The columnist, Chris Nolan, told one of her editors about the
offer before she bought 500 shares of Autoweb.com at the initial
offering price of $14, but he offered no explicit approval or
disapproval, Ms. Nolan said. The columnist, whose ``Talk Is Cheap''
column focuses on the gossip of Silicon Valley's high-tech
industry, said she made about $9,000 by selling her stock in the
first two days after Autoweb.com first offered stock for sale to
the public in March.
</P>
<P>
   David Yarnold, the executive editor of the Mercury News, said
Friday that he felt ``she clearly placed us in a situation where
the public could perceive the Mercury News to have a conflict of
interest.''
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper's ethics policy forbids staff writers to ``make
news decisions about companies in which they have a financial
interest.'' It also stipulates that business writers should not
invest in local businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Nolan's situation, which was first reported in The Wall
Street Journal, reflects the way quick profits from initial stock
offerings has become a routine part of Silicon Valley life. It also
shows the value of being invited to be one of the small group of
investors who can buy stock at the offering price.
</P>
<P>
   What has not changed, however, are newspaper and newsmagazine
ethics policies. They remain strict in forbidding business
reporters and editors from having any financial stake in the
companies they cover.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Nolan's case troubles some because she did seek her editors'
guidance and permission. Ms. Nolan said in an interview that the
chief executive of Autoweb.com, Dean DeBiase, ``has been a friend
for many years'' and that ``I felt this was an offer from a
friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Nolan is a member of the local chapter of the Newspaper
Guild, and a union executive confirmed that he is investigating the
situation.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Nolan also said Friday that she had also sold Fortune
magazine a first-person account of her experience with Autoweb.com,
a freelance arrangement that she said her editors had approved.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Yarnold said Friday night that while Ms. Nolan had mentioned
the article to editors ``in a passing way,'' she ``did not have
affirmative permission to sub-mit the article to Fortune.''
</P>
<P>
   While some colleagues said there was some sentiment among
reporters that the editor's reactions were overly harsh, the one
reporter who spoke on the record, Jonathan Rabinovitz, the
economics correspondent, said: ``I like Chris. I think Chris is a
great reporter. But you don't do that. It's that simple.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
