<SLUG> BC-PRIMARY-STATES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATES SEEK TO PUSH FORWARD PRESIDENTIAL PRIMARIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1976, the presidential campaign was so long and arduous that
a book about the race was titled ``Marathon.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The book on the 2000 race surely will have a different name _
like ``Sprint'' or ``Dash.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eager to wield influence in the nomination process, or just
excited about grabbing some of the big money that presidential
campaigns toss around, states are stumbling all over themselves to
schedule early primary dates. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   California, tired of waiting until June to award its huge caches
of delegates, leaped to March 26 in 1996 but found out the race was
over by then. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Next year, California will try March 7. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michigan wants to jump from March 19 in 1996 to a date in
February. Ohio is advancing from March 19 to March 7. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Iowa, which conducts the traditional kickoff, probably will move
its caucuses from February to January. New Hampshire, now slated
for Feb. 8, just adopted a new law allowing it to move to 1999 if
necessary to keep its first-in-the-nation primary status intact. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We're committed to making sure we remain a week before any
other state,'' said New Hampshire Gov. Jeanne Shaheen. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Carl Levin, a Democrat pushing to advance Michigan's date,
thinks that's unfair. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``No state should be allowed to dictate that they go first every
time,'' he told The Associated Press. ``It's wrong.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in South Carolina and Delaware are looking at a Feb.
19 date, and Virginia may go to Feb. 29. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana, which held its largely ignored caucus even before
Iowa's last time around, may try to get out front again this year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have to, we'll be singing `Jingle Bells' while we're
selecting the next nominee,'' said Louisiana GOP Chairman Mike
Francis. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absolutely out of control,'' said Kansas Secretary of
State Ron Thornburgh about the rush to the front of the calendar. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Ridiculous,'' chimed in Massachusetts Secretary of State
William Galvin. ``The problem is, everybody can't be first. When
everybody is first, nobody is first and there is no process.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In all, about 15 states and territories wanting more say in
presidential selection are seeking to push forward, and how the
parties handle the crush remains to be seen. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Missouri switched from a caucus to a primary for 2000, but kept
the same March date. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kansas did not have a primary in 1996; in 2000, its primary is
relatively late _ April 4. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The nomination process, effectively over in about six weeks in
1996, could be over in four this time. By the end of February,
about 40 percent more delegates will have been chosen than by the
same time in the last elections. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Too fast, experts say. Voters don't have enough time to look
over the field. Candidates don't have enough time to learn about a
state or region. And what happens, some wonder, if a fatal flaw is
exposed in a front-runner a few weeks into the race? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Democrats and Republicans could face the prospect of being stuck
with a critically wounded candidate from March until Election Day
in November. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no chance for reconsideration,'' said Galvin. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Others point to an even bigger problem. Candidates are being
forced to raise huge amounts of cash early so that they literally
can run a national contest and compete in all of the early states
at once. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As a consequence, well-heeled candidates, such as Texas Gov.
George W. Bush, who recently reported raising more than $36
million, are deemed formidable although millions of Americans know
little about him. Others, such as Elizabeth Dole, Lamar Alexander
or Pat Buchanan, who trail far behind in the money race, are deemed
longshots. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some advisers to Alexander, the former Tennessee governor who
made a respectable showing in 1996, are now urging him to drop out
to save face _ long before a single vote is cast. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And candidates who are not well-known nationally? Experts say
the days of a Jimmy Carter, George H.W. Bush or Bill Clinton
emerging from the pack may be over. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be Chicken Little and say the sky is falling,
but if this continues for another decade or two I really do think
democracy is at stake in the way we elect our presidents,'' said
Thornburgh. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The front-loaded nomination schedule is helping to turn a
seemingly innocuous event _ the Aug. 14 Iowa Straw Poll _ into a
significant political date. Normally a glorified fund-raising tool
for that state's Republican Party, the event is now viewed as make
or break for second-tier GOP contenders, who are said to have to
finish near the top or drop out. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While Iowa and New Hampshire cling to tradition, there's more at
stake in being first. Nearly one in five of New Hampshire residents
got to meet a presidential candidate and the tiny state saw more
than $200 million pumped into the local economy by the campaigns,
according to some estimates. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the overvalued significance of Iowa and New Hampshire (69
Democratic delegates combined) was what irked California. Its 367
delegates represent more than 10 percent of those needed to win the
nomination, yet the state often ended up being irrelevant for
primary candidates. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Because California has moved to March 7, the same as New York
and 10 other states, some 30 percent of all convention delegates
will be awarded that day. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Michigan, Republicans are tentatively planning their primary
for Feb. 22. The national Democratic Party, however, just nixed a
plan of Michigan Democrats to hold their caucus 10 days earlier.
When that party will hold its election next year is unclear. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After much hand wringing over the 1996 process, Republicans
adopted a system for 2000 that awarded bonus convention delegates
to states that held late primaries. Only three states took the
bait, and the plan has been viewed as a failure. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now Jim Nicholson, the GOP National Committee chairman, who
complains that the current schedule is so compressed that ``it goes
off like a string of firecrackers once it starts,'' has appointed a
panel to look again at ways to spread out the process in 2004. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One plan backed by the National Association of Secretaries of
State calls for four regional primaries spaced about a month apart.
The schedule would rotate every four years to allow each part of
the country a chance to be first. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Iowa and New Hampshire would be allowed to remain first out of
respect for both states' political traditions and in appreciation
for the type of one-on-one, ``retail'' campaigning that candidates
must employ to win there. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Every state, however, would have to sign off on the idea. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a big fan of turning it over to Congress,'' Thornburgh
said. ``But if the next election cycle is as big a train wreck as I
think this one will be, Congress may be forced to take action.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
