<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAACP-GUNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAACP SUES GUN MAKERS FOR SHOOTINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Joining a parade of cities and gunshot victims, the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People Friday
filed the latest lawsuit that places the blame on gun makers for
shootings with illegally obtained handguns.
</P>
<P>
   But the action _ filed in U.S. District Court in Brooklyn and
naming nearly 100 gun manufacturers as defendants _ does not seek
monetary damages, as the other suits generally have. Instead it
asks the court to order the manufacturers to change marketing and
distribution practices that the NAACP says foster an underground
market in illegal handguns.
</P>
<P>
   Among the gun makers named are some of the biggest in the
country, including Smith &AMP; Wesson, Colt's Manufacturing, and Sturm,
Ruger &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   The group asked the court to prohibit gun wholesalers and
retailers from selling more than one handgun to the same person in
any 30-day period.
</P>
<P>
   It also asked that the manufacturers be ordered not to supply
dealers who sell handguns at gun shows, where, critics of such
shows say, regulations of gun sales are often skirted. And the suit
asks that the gun makers be ordered to conduct quarterly
inspections of their wholesalers and retailers to insure compliance
with the restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   The steps are needed, the civil rights group contends, because
the manufacturers have been ``failing to regulate, supervise and
otherwise exercise reasonable control over the marketing,
distribution and sale of their handguns.'' Because of this failure,
the group says, many of the guns eventually end up in the hands of
illegal traffickers who sell them to ``criminals, juveniles, the
mentally ill'' and others not authorized to have them.
</P>
<P>
   The suit was filed for the NAACP by the law firm of Weitz &AMP;
Luxenberg. The court papers say that the NAACP, which announced
this week that it would file the suit, is bringing the action ``to
protect the well-being and security of its membership, which has
been disproportionately injured'' by illegal handguns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NAACP is particularly concerned about the level of handgun
violence in African-American communities,'' the court papers say.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for one defendant, Glock Inc., said that the
allegations underlying the suit were baseless. In any case, said
the lawyer, John F. Renzulli, a court is not the place in which to
seek the kind of changes the suit asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would appear to me that the relief they are requesting
should be directed to the Legislature and not the court,'' Renzulli
said. ``When you are talking about restrictions like one sale a
month'' to individuals, ``isn't that something that should be
debated in the Legislature?''
</P>
<P>
   Over the last year, more than a dozen cities and counties have
filed suits against the gun industry that generally seek to recoup
law enforcement and hospital costs stemming from gun violence. And
in February, in the same court where the NAACP filed its suit
Friday, a jury in a precedent-setting verdict ordered several gun
makers to pay more than $500,000 to a Queens teen-ager, Steven Fox,
who was shot and severely wounded with an illegally obtained
handgun.
</P>
<P>
   Although the gun used in that shooting disappeared, the jury
found that the companies _ which all make .25-caliber guns like the
one that ballistics evidence indicates was used to shoot Fox _ were
collectively liable because of negligent marketing and distribution
practices. The verdict is being appealed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
