<SLUG> BC-COHEN-TRIP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEAR OF ATTACK CANCELS COHEN'S TRIP TO ALBANIA
</HEADLINE>
  (ko) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Defense Secretary William Cohen canceled a trip to
Albania this week, in part because of fears of a terrorist attack
there by followers of Osama bin Laden, Clinton administration
officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The officials would not say if there was evidence of a
particular threat against Cohen, but they said Albania had long
been seen as a potential terrorist staging area because of the
presence of followers of bin Laden, the Saudi exile accused of
masterminding the bombing of two U.S. embassies in East Africa last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials have said the United States foiled a
plot last August by Islamic militants loyal to bin Laden to attack
the U.S. Embassy in Tirana, the Albanian capital.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of visiting Albania, where he had been expected to meet
with U.S. troops serving near the border with Kosovo, Cohen
traveled to Bosnia, where he spoke to American soldiers serving in
the peacekeeping mission there.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with reporters on his return to the United
States after a six-nation trip to Europe, Cohen was asked if the
threat of an attack had played a role in the decision to cancel his
visit to Albania. The defense secretary acknowledged there had been
security concerns but said they were not the sole reason for the
cancellation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have always taken into account the threats,'' Cohen said.
``That is why we have such security wherever we go.'' He said the
``principal reason'' for the decision to shift the trip to Bosnia
was the presence of so many American soldiers ``who have served
there so long.'' Many of the U.S. troops now assigned to Albania
have been in that country only a short time and will soon leave.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
