<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MERCYKILLING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAND JURY REFUSES TO INDICT MAN IN AN ASSISTED SUICIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Conn.)  (af) 
 By BARBARA STEWART   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A Manhattan grand jury has declined to indict an
Upper East Side veterinarian who admitted to the police last fall
that he injected a dying colleague with a fatal dose of
phenobarbital at her request, a day or so before she was to be
moved from Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center into a hospice.
</P>
<P>
   The veterinarian, Dr. Marco Zancope, would not comment, except
to express his gratitude. But his lawyer, Robert G. Smith, called
the grand jury's refusal to indict his client ``a breath of common
sense.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not talking about Jack Kevorkian here,'' Smith said.
``He was drawn into a situation; she was ravaged by cancer and
asked someone to help her.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision also drew praise from George Delury, a New York
writer and editor who was also arrested for assisted suicide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thankful the grand jury had more sense there,'' said
Delury. He eventually pleaded guilty to attempted manslaughter and
served four months in jail for giving his wife, Myrna Lebov, who
suffered from multiple sclerosis, lethal amounts of drugs and
suffocating her with a plastic bag in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The Manhattan district attorney's office sent out a terse
statement, saying the grand jury had arrived at its decision after
listening to 48 witnesses. District Attorney Robert M. Morgenthau
could not be reached, and press officers at the office would not
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Zancope was accused of hastening the death of Cara Beigel, 33,
his office manager and friend, as she lay in a hospital bed,
terminally ill with the breast cancer she had struggled with for 13
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was in tremendous pain and agony,'' said Phillip Beigel,
her father, a retired television producer and businessman from
Connecticut, in an interview shortly after Zancope's arrest last
October. ``She said, `I don't want to carry on like that. It's
over, it's over.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Beigel could not be reached at his home in Connecticut Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In a videotaped statement to police, Zancope said he injected
the barbiturate into an intravenous drip tube that fed into Ms.
Beigel's arm on Aug. 28, 1997. Zancope said he was ``solely
responsible'' for administering the drugs. Law enforcement
officials say he was alone with her at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Zancope told the police that her family and friends were aware
of her decision to end her life and had gathered by her bedside
shortly before her death. In the October interview, Beigel
indicated that the veterinarian had acted in accordance with his
daughter's wishes, saying: ``If Cara could have, I think she would
have done it herself.''
</P>
<P>
   Though very few cases are reported to law enforcement officials,
medical experts say that many terminally ill people seek help in
ending their lives, especially people who, like Ms. Beigel, are in
intractable pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it happens frequently,'' said Marilyn Webb, whose
book, ``The Good Death: The New American Search to Reshape the End
of Life'' explores the legal and moral aspects of
physician-assisted suicide. ``These are rational decisions people
make. Doctors quietly help people. It has to do with `don't ask,
don't tell.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Usually, she said, the decision is made in secret, a painful,
private pact often involving the dying person and some combination
of family members, close friends and a trusted doctor.
</P>
<P>
   In Delury's opinion, a major reason that Zancope was able to win
the sympathy of the grand jury was the support he had from Ms.
Beigel's family. ``The whole family backed him,'' he said. ``I
didn't have that.'' Also, he said, Ms. Beigel was terminally ill,
in the final stage of cancer, whereas Ms. Lebov would probably not
have died from multiple sclerosis for years, though it might have
left her blind and paralyzed.
</P>
<P>
   Zancope's role in the death of Ms. Beigel went undetected, or at
least unreported, for nearly a year. He was arrested after the
medical examiner's office received a report from officials at
Memorial Sloan-Kettering that phenobarbital, a drug frequently used
to euthanize pets, had been found in a toxicology report from an
autopsy performed five months before. It is not clear what caused
the delays.
</P>
<P>
   Avice Meehan, a spokeswoman for the hospital, would not comment
on the grand jury's decision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
