<SLUG> BC-STATES-watch-PA </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  pennsylvania votechart
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON WATCH VOTE CHART Questions regarding this
transmission should be directed to 202-628-3100, ext. 224.
WASHINGTON, July 16 -- The following chart shows how senators and
representatives voted on key bills and amendments within the last
week. A ``Y'' means the member voted for the measure; an ``N''
means the member voted against the measure; a ``?'' means the
member did not vote; and a ``P'' means the member voted
``present.''
</P>
<P>
   SENATE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: BREAST
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Wednesday approved, 55-45, an amendment to larger
health care legislation that would require managed-care plans to
cover a woman's stay in the hospital following breast cancer
surgery. Supporters said it would ensure that her medical need will
dictate how long a woman stays in the hospital after undergoing
surgery. Opponents said the amendment does not go far enough in
giving women options concerning treatment for breast cancer. A
``yes'' vote favors the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: ACCESS
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Wednesday rejected, 48-52, an amendment to larger
health care legislation that would ensure that the so-called
``Patients' Bill of Rights'' applies to all patients with health
insurance. Supporters said that it would give all insured patients
access to the rights they deserve. Opponents said expanding the
rights to all patients would only raise insurance premiums. A
``yes'' vote supports the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   3) BILL NUMBER: SPECIAL
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Wednesday rejected, 47-53, an amendment to larger
health care legislation that would give patients easier access to
specialty care. Supporters said there are too many hurdles between
patients and the specific care they may need. Opponents said the
amendment would increase health care costs and interfere with the
rights of states to set their own health care regulations. A
``yes'' vote supports the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   4) BILL NUMBER: PATIENTS
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Thursday approved, 53-47, a Republican-sponsored
``Patients' Bill of Rights'' that gives 48 million people expanded
rights when dealing with their health insurance providers by
setting up an appeals process when care is denied. The bill also
provides easier access to emergency room medical specialists and
enables women to stay in the hospital longer after breast cancer
surgery. Supporters said the bill improves health care without
raising insurance premiums. Opponents said the protections are not
strong enough and do not cover enough people. A ``yes'' vote favors
the bill.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2 3 4
</P>
<P>
   --- --- --- ---
</P>
<P>
   SANTORUM (R-PA) Y N N Y
</P>
<P>
   SPECTER (R-PA) Y Y Y Y
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: MINING
</P>
<P>
   The House on Wednesday approved, 273-151, an amendment to the
Interior Department spending bill that would limit mining on
federal lands by requiring companies to heed the 1997 Interior
Department ruling that limits the disposal of mining waste to five
acres. Supporters said mining operations need to be limited on
federal lands. Opponents said the amendment is yet another assault
on the mining industry and that the Interior Department does not
have the jurisdiction to make such laws. A ``yes'' vote supports
the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   The House on Thursday passed, 306-118, a bill that protects
religious activities from government interference. The bill
protects an individual's right to follow their religious practices
even if it violates state or local laws. Supporters said the bill
will stop the erosion of religious freedoms that is taking place
across America. Opponents said the bill would let people use their
religious practices as an excuse to subvert other civil rights
laws. A ``yes'' vote favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   3) BILL NUMBER: SALARY
</P>
<P>
   The House on Thursday passed, 276-147, a measure that would
raise House members' salaries by $4,600. The amendment, which
increases members' salaries to $141,300, is the first time
lawmakers have raised their salaries since 1993. The amendment
sparked little debate on the House floor. A ``yes'' vote favors the
amendment.
</P>
<P>
   4) BILL NUMBER: PRESIDENT
</P>
<P>
   The House on Thursday rejected, 82-334, an amendment to the
Treasury and Postal Service spending bill that would have stricken
a provision to double the president's salary to $400,000.
Supporters of raising the salary said the president, who has not
received a raise since 1969, deserves it because he has the most
important job in the country. Opponents said the president's
current salary is adequate because the job has many perks. A
``yes'' vote opposes giving the president a raise.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2 3 4
</P>
<P>
   --- --- --- ---
</P>
