<SLUG> BC-NY-NIGERIA-SLAVE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMAN IN SERVITUDE CASE WAS CLEARED IN '88 INQUIRY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JACQUES STEINBERG    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A New York City child abuse investigator accused this
week of keeping a Nigerian girl in servitude was exonerated in a
1988 investigation of possible neglect involving a second Nigerian
girl, child welfare officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The investigator, Ifeoma Ezeonu Udogwu, was named in a complaint
of possible child abuse in 1988 after fire marshals investigated a
fire in her home which the second girl was suspected of starting,
fire officials have said. The marshals called a state child-abuse
phone line, suspecting that the girl, then 13, whose identity has
not been made public, was not properly supervised and not enrolled
in school, fire officials said.
</P>
<P>
   City officials began investigating the complaint in August 1988
_ soon after the fire, and soon after the hiring of Ms. Udogwu as a
caseworker at the city's child welfare agency.
</P>
<P>
   The case was closed six months later, in February 1989, after
investigators interviewed the girl and determined that the
marshals' concerns were ``unsubstantiated,'' said Leonora Wiener, a
spokeswoman for the agency, now known as the Administration for
Children's Services. ``She asserted that she was not being
mistreated and that she was doing well with the family,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wiener said child welfare officials were still trying to
piece together the records regarding the 1988 complaint and did not
yet know whether the investigators had spoken to anyone other than
the 13-year-old girl in pursuing the accusations. At some point the
girl is believed to have returned to Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wiener said it was not clear whether the girl started the
fire.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Udogwu, who is in her 30s, and her husband, Prosper Udogwu,
48, were charged on Wednesday with keeping Beatrice Okezie, a
Nigerian who is now 23, in forced servitude in their Bronx home for
nine years and beating her. Lawyers for the Udogwus deny the
charges and cite records showing that Miss Okezie, who graduated
from Evander Childs High School in the Bronx in 1994, had an
attendance record of better than 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Udogwus, originally from Nigeria, are accused of luring her
into the United States in 1989, when she was 13, by promising to
send her to trade school, only to force her to work as their
unpaid, live-in maid, according to a complaint filed in U.S.
District Court here.
</P>
<P>
   The Daily News reported Friday that an anonymous letter alleging
abuse against Miss Okezie had prompted child welfare officials to
investigate Ms. Udogwu again in 1992, a case in which she was also
cleared. A person with knowledge of that case, who insisted on
anonymity, confirmed that account, but would provide no details.
Ms. Wiener said her office had yet to unearth any information
related to that complaint or its outcome.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
