<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CONGRESSMAN-DEFECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP CONGRESSMAN EXPECTED TO DEFECT TO DEMOCRATS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Rep. Michael Forbes, a Long Island, N.Y., Republican
who has regularly found himself at odds with his party leaders in
Washington, is expected to defect to the Democratic Party,
Democrats in Washington and New York said Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   The highly unusual defection creates a complication for
Republicans _ who hold a six-seat majority _ as they prepare for
elections next year in which control of the House of
Representatives is at stake.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, who was elected to Congress in 1994, told Democratic
Party leaders in New York and Washington Friday that he would
disclose his decision at a news conference in Suffolk County, Long
Island, Saturday afternoon. He refused Friday night to discuss his
intentions with a reporter, other than to acknowledge that he had
scheduled a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is all kind of speculation out there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The reported defection by Forbes, who observed his 47th birthday
Friday, comes after what has been three years of up-and-down _
though mostly down _ relations with Republican leaders in Congress.
He was the first Republican to oppose Newt Gingrich's selection to
a second term as House speaker in 1996, an act of defiance that
poisoned his relations with many of the party's most influential
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, even given Forbes' difficult history, the notion
that an experienced politician would leave the party that controls
the House baffled both Republicans and Democrats in New York and
Washington on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't figure it out,'' said one astonished House Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes reportedly decided to make the change after intense
lobbying over the last 18 months by Reps. Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., the
minority leader in the House, and Charles Rangel, D-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Rangel, who is from New York City, declined to
say whether Forbes had agreed to switch parties, saying that it was
``an extremely private matter'' that should be left to the
congressman to announce.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are very sensitive decisions and it takes a lot of time
and courage to make these decisions,'' Rangel said. ``I will say
that I have become increasingly aware of the discomfort of many
Republican members of the New York delegation to the right-wing
dogmatism of their leaders and the attempt to whip into line all
Republicans whether they agree with their leaders or not.''
</P>
<P>
   While a Republican defection would move congressional Democrats
closer to their goal of regaining control of the House, there were
indications Friday night that some Democrats in New York were not
in complete agreement on what Forbes might add to the party.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes is generally viewed as conservative, even in Republican
circles. He is opposed to abortion rights and has voted against
many gun control measures. He also voted in favor of the articles
of impeachment against Clinton last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one that would be done holding our noses,'' a senior
New York Democratic official said. ``When you have a pro-gun,
pro-life, pro-tobacco, pro-articles-of-impeachment congressman,
that's not quite the Democratic way.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Judith Hope, the Democratic state chairwoman,
expressed cheer at Forbes' anticipated announcement. ``We welcome
him into the Democratic Party,'' she said. ``It's a bellwether of
what's going to happen in the year 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   There had been growing sentiment among Democratic officials in
Suffolk County that they might be able to defeat Forbes in an
election next year.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Bullock, a former Suffolk County legislator who is chief of
staff to Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., had been considering
seeking the Democratic nomination to run against Forbes next year.
As soon as he learned of Forbes' planned news conference, Bullock
called a reporter to make clear that if he could not run against
Forbes in a general election, he was more than prepared to
challenge him in a Democratic primary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
