<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-CONTRACT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KC SCHOOL BOARD, DEMPS AGREE ON CONTRACT PROPOSAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PHILLIP O'CONNOR  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Benjamin Demps Jr. reached agreement Friday night with the
Kansas City Board of Education on a two-year contract worth about
$200,000 annually. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Board members voted 7-1 with one abstention to approve the
11-page agreement, which includes an annual base salary of
$156,420. Demps could earn $17,380 more each year if he meets
certain performance goals, such as improving student test scores
and attendance. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's over,'' board member Connie Clark shouted, raising her
hands in triumph shortly after the vote. ``This has been a trying
time for the board and for Mr. Demps. We need to take a long, deep
breath and contemplate what lies ahead.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The court-appointed Desegregation Monitoring Committee must
still approve the deal, and Demps won't sign until after that.
Board members did not know when the committee would act, but they
expected it to do so before a court hearing scheduled for 10 a.m.
Monday before U.S. District Judge Dean Whipple. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Charles McClain, a member of the monitoring committee, declined
to comment late Friday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   School board members said they wanted to introduce Demps to the
judge at the hearing. Demps would not make any community
appearances until after the hearing, they said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A selection committee spent months identifying and interviewing
applicants before recommending four finalists to the school board.
Demps was the third person to be offered the job in the past three
weeks. The two others _ retired Air Force Maj. Gen. Jay T. Edwards
and former U.S. education commissioner Pascal Forgione Jr. _
withdrew after they could not agree on a contract. The other
finalist, Grandview superintendent John Martin, also withdrew. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Board members Clark, Lee Barnes Jr., Lance Loewenstein, Sandy
Mayer, Helen Ragsdale, Terry Riley and John Rios voted for the
contract. Board member Patricia Kurtz voted against. Board member
Fifi Wiedeman did not attend the meeting at the offices of
Blackwell Sanders Peper Martin, a law firm for the district. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The vote ended a day of discussions between district lawyers and
Demps over contract language. Demps also received about a four-hour
briefing on the status of the desegregation lawsuit and court
orders aimed at improving academic performance in the district. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Board members then spent about an hour in private, reviewing the
proposed contract. About 7:15 p.m. Demps entered the meeting. The
doors opened a few minutes later, and board members surrounded
him. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kurtz, the board's vice president, said Demps had the
``confidence, support and blessing'' of the school board. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Demps said that he was looking forward to working with the board
and that he was excited to get started. He declined to comment
further and was quickly escorted from the room. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Demps, 65, is a retired Federal Aviation Administration official
who also served as director of the Oklahoma Department of Human
Services in the early 1990s. The Harlem native is semiretired and
living in Oklahoma City, where he operates an aviation consulting
business. He is married and has two grown children. He said his
wife, a lawyer, intended to stay in Oklahoma City. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kurtz, who cast the lone dissenting vote, said she was concerned
whether Demps' personality, which she described as somber, would be
a good fit for Kansas City. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the district is a sick entity that needs healing and
uplifting,'' she said. ``I don't sense an energetic spirit. Maybe
it's there. I just didn't see it in the interviews.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She also said she thought Demps became the superintendent by
default. But she said she would do everything she could to support
him. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ragsdale said she understood Kurtz's frustration with the
selection process. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They can continue to be disgusted at the process _ so am I,''
said Ragsdale, who served on the candidate screening committee with
the three-member monitoring committee. ``It's been a long struggle
to bring forward someone qualified and that this board could
accept. But now we need to concentrate on educating the
children.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his base salary and incentives, Demps would
receive a car allowance up to $600 a month, and the district would
pay $12,000 into a tax-sheltered annuity. The district would also
provide a $300,000 life insurance policy and pay a disability
insurance premium of up to $5,000 annually. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Demps would be eligible for annual raises of no more than 5
percent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He would receive 20 days of sick leave and 20 days of vacation.
He would be required to take an annual medical exam. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The district hired Henry Williams as superintendent in 1996 at a
base salary of $164,500 plus benefits that brought the package to
about $190,000. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unlike previous superintendents, Demps got no days to do
independent consulting work. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Demps got the board to remove language giving it final approval
over all appointments at the department director level and above.
Demps must consult with the board before such selections but does
not need its approval. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Board members said they would immediately begin compiling a list
of goals for Demps. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mayer thanked the judge for extending the school board's
deadline for naming a superintendent. She said the extra time
allowed board members to visit Oklahoma City this week to meet with
Demps' associates, co-workers and others. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``What we found out,'' she said, ``is that this is the man that
we need at this time.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
