<SLUG> BC-CONN-POLITICAL-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR TRUMP, A RACE SO SHORT AND SWEET  
 IN SEARCH OF A FIGHT ...  
 ... AND STUMBLING INTO ONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ It was one of the shortest presidential
campaigns in history.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a Democratic polling firm released a survey of
members of the Reform Party showing Donald J. Trump tied for third
place among its possible nominees for president. Then on Sunday,
puffing up a single paragraph from its new issue, Newsweek put out
a news release with the headline, ``Friend: Trump Thinking about
Reform Party Nomination for President.''
</P>
<P>
   Trump says he had given no thought to the possibility, but he
decided to play along. On Monday, he issued his own news release,
lauding the Reform Party, founded by Ross Perot, and criticizing
the two major parties. ``If the Reform Party nominated me, I would
probably run and probably win,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   News organizations around the world ran with the story. A
headline in The Washington Post said, ``Trump Ready for Call From
Reform Party.''
</P>
<P>
   The possibility was especially delicious in Connecticut, since
Trump had a boisterous feud with a former governor, Lowell P.
Weicker Jr., who is seriously considering seeking the Reform Party
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1994, when Trump wanted to build a casino in the state,
Weicker referred to Trump as ``that dirt bag,'' and Trump called
Weicker ``a fat slob who couldn't get elected dog catcher.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Trump-for-president stories proliferated, Trump, a
Republican who also supports Democrats, finally decided he had had
enough fun. He has never been known for subtlety, but his statement
did include the sentence, ``If I won, I would ask for an immediate
recount.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth, he said by telephone from the 68th floor of Trump
Tower in Manhattan, is that he has no plans or desire to run for
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so unlikely that you shouldn't bother asking the
question,'' he said. ``I'm honored and I'm flattered, but the fact
is I've never had more fun than I'm having right now, building the
most spectacular buildings in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Then in his inimitable style, he went on to enumerate why he
would be a formidable candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Weicker, on the other hand, is pressing ahead with his Reform
Party exploration, and said he would make a decision about whether
to run in the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   He disclosed Friday that he would not attend the Reform Party
convention in Michigan next weekend. Although party leaders have
said that attending would elevate his standing among members, he
said he did not want to be become embroiled in the leadership fight
to be hashed out at the convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not touching that with a 10-foot pole,'' he said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Search of a Fight ... &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bill Curry, a Democrat who has been a Connecticut state senator
and the state comptroller, plans to announce a new campaign before
summer's end. But what to run for?
</P>
<P>
   He is torn, he said, between a bid for governor in 2002, and a
challenge next year to Rep. Nancy L. Johnson, the nine-term
Republican from the sixth district.
</P>
<P>
   Either race could wind up being a rematch for Curry, who lost
narrowly to Mrs. Johnson in 1982 and to John G. Rowland in the 1994
governor's race.
</P>
<P>
   The state has no term limits for a governor. Rowland, a moderate
Republican who is broadly popular, says he has not decided whether
to run for a third term, but many Republican leaders doubt he will.
</P>
<P>
   Curry, of Farmington, is one of the few prominent Democrats who
have been willing to criticize Rowland publicly on any topic,
including his generous stadium deal with the New England Patriots,
which ended in humiliation for the state when the team walked away
in April. (``If John Rowland had been at Yalta,'' Curry would say
with relish, ``we'd all be speaking Russian.'')
</P>
<P>
   Curry, 47, said he planned some intense soul-searching in a few
weeks, after he finishes a book _ a combination of memoir and
policy critique _ about his two years in the White House as a top
political adviser to President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Curry already has a catchy, if debatable, story line for a
congressional race: ``Former presidential adviser runs against
impeachment-voting Republican impostor.'' But he added, ``What's
always been in my heart has been the governorship.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ... And Stumbling Into One &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Michael P. Peters of Hartford, a former city firefighter,
is hoping to win a fourth term this fall, but he faces at least one
challenge at a Democratic nominating convention on Thursday. He has
rocky relations with the city's minority groups, and 10 billboards
around town promote his challenger as ``Leadership for the Next
Generation.''
</P>
<P>
   Then last week, Peters was served with a lawsuit by a former
city council aide who accused him of discussing sexual acts he
would like to perform on her, ``placing his hand under her dress on
one occasion'' and displaying Playboy magazines in her presence.
</P>
<P>
   Peters, 50, issued a statement calling the allegations
categorically untrue. But the case has received heavy news
coverage, and the timing could be politically costly.
</P>
<P>
   The challenger with the billboards, Juan A. Morales, 34, said
the issue should help bolster points about credibility and morality
he had long planned to make at the convention. ``Bring your
football helmet and shoulder pads,'' he said gleefully.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
