<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVIS-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAT IS ON U.S. TEAM AS AUSSIES WIN TWO
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHESTNUT HILL, Mass. _ The Australians wore ponytails and white
war paint under their baseball caps, immune to the 126-degree
swelter on the hard courts and to the dress code at the
122-year-old Longwood Cricket Club.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Rafter and Lleyton Hewitt, along with the green-haired,
yellow-faced fans they call the Fanatics, were not here to make a
fashion statement Friday. And they were immune to the desperate
attempts of Jim Courier and Todd Martin, on whose behalf Pete
Sampras benched himself, to prove their worth as the United States
singles players for the weekend's Davis Cup quarterfinal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every match is historic, mate, in Davis Cup,'' Rafter said
after downing Courier, the Davis Cup iron man, who has never played
for a losing squad in 13 previous appearances, to give Australia a
2-0 lead over the United States.
</P>
<P>
   This was a Davis Cup centenary celebration in which the most
celebrated star who was present sat out while two lesser lights _
both of whom had done more for the United States' Davis Cup cause
lately _ fought valiantly but ineffectively. The host nation was
left facing elimination in the best-of-5-match format, which
continues Saturday when Sampras and Alex O'Brien face Australia's
Mark Woodforde and Sandon Stolle in doubles.
</P>
<P>
   The only time a U.S. Davis Cup squad recovered from such dire
straits was 1934, when the Americans came back to defeat Australia
by 3-2; overall, the United States is 1-28 when facing a deficit
like the one that Hewitt and Rafter inflicted on them Friday.
</P>
<P>
   First came a swaggering Davis Cup debut from the 18-year-old
Hewitt, a scrambler whose 6-4, 6-7 (1-7), 6-3, 6-0 demolition of
Martin reduced the American veteran to an immobile puddle of
perspiration by the final set. Then the second-ranked Rafter, whose
two U.S. Open titles make him a perfect fit for these hardcourts,
smoothly served and volleyed his way past the pugnacious Courier,
7-6 (7-5), 6-4, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   Though Rafter described their first-set tie breaker as ``a
comedy of errors'' in which the returner wielded all the power, he
won it with a service winner and then kept his momentum intact by
breaking Courier in the ninth games of the second and third sets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Psychologically it can get tough out there if you get down in
all that heat,'' Rafter said. ``It was brutal.''
</P>
<P>
   Rafter described his teammates as ``very up'' and added: ``Not
going to get any better than this. We want to try to do this
three-nil.''
</P>
<P>
   Rafter felt that Hewitt benefited from facing Martin, and not
Sampras, at No. 1 singles. But Sampras remained a sanguine
cheerleader.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice enough for Jim and Todd to let me be a part of the
team; it is Todd's show and Jim's show,'' Sampras said.
</P>
<P>
   But Saturday, in a make-or-break doubles encounter that will
clinch the competition for Australia or prolong it until Sunday for
the reverse singles, it will be Sampras' show.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can keep us alive,'' said Tom Gullikson, the U.S. captain,
who reiterated that his decision to use Sampras for doubles was
only a matter of principle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just can't see how he can walk out there and believe he can
play good doubles,'' said Woodforde, Australia's doubles anchor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously he's a great player, but I much prefer to see him
across the net in doubles than in singles,'' said Stolle, a regular
partner of Alex O'Brien's, Sampras' doubles teammate for this cameo
appearance in the quarterfinals. ``I don't think Pete is as
comfortable playing doubles. We will see on the day how he plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if Sampras, 3-1 in Davis Cup doubles, plays the hero
Saturday and rescues the United States from its predicament, Martin
implied that the team would sink or swim on Sunday with him and
Courier, the same singles players who delivered the United States
to the quarterfinals by upsetting Britain in round one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all where we feel like we should be, and go about our
business,' Martin said. ``If we're good enough, we're good enough,
and if we're not, better luck next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin admitted that until the team held its final meeting this
week, he felt Sampras was a lock for a singles slot.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the decision was made for me to play singles, and I wanted
to play,'' Martin said. ``As for what everybody else thinks, I
don't know how to put it without digging myself a bigger hole. If
Pete weren't the initiator of all this, yeah, sure, then I'd be a
little bit uneasy. As soon as I hit the first ball today, I forgot
Pete wasn't playing singles; it was all just my match.''
</P>
<P>
   To be more accurate, it was all Hewitt's match.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Lleyton is one of the few people in tennis with very,
very, very great nerves; he sees big occasions and he attacks
them,'' Martin said. ``It's like Pete. One of the reasons Pete is
such a great player is he has got fabulous nerves.''
</P>
<P>
   But they went to waste today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
