<SLUG> BC-EMBRYO-CUSTODY-CASE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J., N.Y.)  
 JUDGE RULES FOR BLACK PARENTS IN EMBRYO MIX-UP CASE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A justice of the state Supreme Court in Manhattan
ruled Friday that a black baby who was born to a white Staten
Island woman after an embryo mix-up at a fertility clinic belongs
in the permanent custody of his biological parents.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Diane S. Lebedeff ruled that the biological parents,
Deborah Perry-Rogers and Robert Rogers, a black couple from
Teaneck, N.J., should have custody of the 8-month-old boy they have
named Akiel.
</P>
<P>
   The baby's birth parents, Richard and Donna Fasano, had filed
suit to force the Rogerses to live up to a visiting agreement. Mrs.
Fasano gave birth to the boy and to her own biological son last
December after a Manhattan fertility clinic mistakenly placed
fertilized embryos from both couples in her womb. The Fasanos said
they wanted the two boys to know each other as brothers, and they
had reached a visiting agreement with the Rogerses before they
turned the boy over in May.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Fasano and her lawyers contended in court that the boy
should be considered both her son and Mrs. Perry-Rogers' son. But
Justice Lebeduff ruled Friday that the Rogerses were the sole
parents. Lawyers for the Fasanos said they would not contest the
judge's decision.
</P>
<P>
   But one aspect of their dispute remains unresolved. In a
short-term victory for the Fasanos, Lebedeff ruled that the two
babies should visit each other for four hours every other week for
the next two months. During that period, psychologists chosen by
each couple will determine whether the two boys formed links as
``brothers'' during nine months in the womb and five months in the
Fasanos' home.
</P>
<P>
   The Fasanos have claimed that the two infants reached out to
each other during visits, and contended that they should maintain
contact as they grow up. Lawyers said the psychologists would
determine whether the visits were constructive or destructive based
on the infants' body language during and after the visits.
</P>
<P>
   Lebedeff scheduled a hearing on the visits for Sept. 24.
</P>
<P>
   The justice thanked both couples, and tried and to put the best
face on a difficult case. ``I've talked with both sets of
clients,'' Lebedeff said. ``All four are very impressive people and
I'm struck by how they've handled a very difficult situation.''
</P>
<P>
   But outside the courtroom, the two sides continued to snipe over
what, exactly, was the relationship between Mrs. Fasano and the
baby she had carried for nine months. Ivan Tantleff, the Fasanos'
lawyer, insisted she had a tie to the child.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can call them whatever you want,'' he said. ``The boys
were brought into life by Mrs. Fasano. Whatever legal terms you
want to say, she'll always in her heart feel she is the mother.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rudolph Silas, the Rogerses' lawyer, said the biological
mother was the child's only true mother. Mrs. Rogers, he said, was
unfairly punished for a clinic's error.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone made a terrible mistake,'' he said. ``To diminish Mrs.
Rogers' right as a parent as a result is not fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Both families have filed negligence lawsuits against the
fertility clinic involved, IVF New York. A state inquiry released
in April found that the embryologist, Michael Obasaju, knew that
another couple's embryos were being implanted in Mrs. Fasano's
womb, but failed to inform anyone at the time or move to correct
his mistake.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuits accuse Obasaju, the clinic and two other
physicians, Dr. Lillian D. Nash and Dr. Dov B. Goldstein, of
malpractice, negligence and breach of contract.
</P>
<P>
   The state inquiry found that soon after Obasaju told Nash of the
mistake in May 1998, she informed both couples. The dispute over
what happened next continued Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the Rogerses again accused the Fasanos of having
avoided contact with them after learning that one of the children
Mrs. Fasano was carrying might not be hers. They said the Fasanos
had agreed to discuss the matter only after the Rogerses filed a
lawsuit in March seeking custody of the child.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the Fasanos denied any wrongdoing. After DNA tests
showed the baby belonged to the Rogerses, the Fasanos turned the
child over to them in May, and both sides agreed to have him spend
one weekend a month with the Fasanos.
</P>
<P>
   But lawyers for the Rogerses said the visits went awry when Mrs.
Fasano insisted on calling the baby by the name she had given it _
Joseph _ and on referring to herself as the boy's ``mommy'' when
speaking to him. They said such conduct would not be tolerated
during future visits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We strongly object to that,'' Silas said. ``We will fight that
to the end.''
</P>
<P>
   But both sides expressed the hope that the intense publicity and
turmoil surrounding the case would now subside and that the two
children would be allowed to grow up in peace. Douglas Reiniger,
another lawyer representing the Fasanos, said their only remaining
wish was that the two boys remain in contact.
</P>
<P>
   Silas said the Rogerses, too, were interested in moving forward.
If their psychologist concludes that visits between the two boys
are beneficial, he said, the Rogerses will not object. ``If they
say it's truly in the child's best interest,'' he said, ``we're all
for it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
