<SLUG> BC-LPGA-PAK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAK   MANAGES TO MAINTAIN HER LEAD AND HER COMPOSURE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Korea)   By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ROCHELLE, N.Y. _ By the time Se Ri Pak reached her final
green Friday, the crowd had grown at least five deep on every side.
After a bogey that left her with a one-stroke lead in the Japan
Airlines Big Apple Classic, she was pushed through the gallery by
security guards. A crowd of Asian journalists waited, and then a
long session with the American news media.
</P>
<P>
   But Pak smiled her way through it, just as she had her missed
putt on the ninth green. The pressures that came with being a
mythic figure back home in South Korea before she turned 21 no
longer haunt her. She smiles, accommodates the crowds and goes back
to her hotel to prepare to do it again.
</P>
<P>
   For the second day in a row, Pak headed the field at Wykagyl
Country Club, following up a 66 in Thursday's first round with a 69
Friday and maintaining her tenuous lead. Two of the LPGA Tour's top
players, Karrie Webb and Meg Mallon, made rushes and were among
four players in second place at 6-under par. Even though a pair of
bogeys in the final three holes reduced her cushion, Pak maintained
an air of confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am getting more confident,'' Pak said. ``I think I am
getting closer and closer. That's why I am here. Win or not, I
don't need to push myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Friday, the tournament's biggest crowds had been for the
U.S. women's soccer players Mia Hamm, Julie Foudy and Brandi
Chastain. But Pak knows what it is like to be the center of
attention, after winning a pair of majors in a dominating rookie
season last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people say I am, in my country, more than Michael Jordan
is here,'' Pak said. ``I didn't know that until someone told me.
Last year, after the win, I'd wear a different hat, clothes,
glasses, try to make myself not like Se Ri, but still people know.
It's pretty amazing. Sometimes it's pretty good. I go to a
restaurant and they make me special food.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, it seemed as if the pressures might ruin Pak
as she struggled on and off the course. She fired her coach and
business manager and did not crack the top 10 in her first 12
tournaments. But Pak, who speaks regularly with her father, who has
been the biggest influence on her performance, and who was joined
here this week by her sister, did not crack. She hired the
International Management Group to handle her off-course affairs and
slowed the pace of her hectic schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Pak remained confident that success would come again. It has,
with a fourth-place finish in the Wegman's Rochester International,
her first victory of the season at the Shoprite LPGA Classic, a
seventh-place finish at the McDonald's LPGA Championship and then
another victory in the Jamie Farr Kroger Classic.
</P>
<P>
   She remains focused on the task at hand. On Thursday she said,
``Every week is the same: golf course, hotel, dinner, golf course,
hotel, dinner.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a schedule she will keep this weekend, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-16-99 2324EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
