<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 23:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3583 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-NOYER-NYT &LR;      07-16 0303
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-NOYER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
M. LAWRENCE NOYER JR., WHO PROSECUTED BROTHER OF D'AMATO, DIES AT
40  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Conn.)   By ANTHONY RAMIREZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   M. Lawrence Noyer Jr., a former federal prosecutor who headed
the mail fraud case against Armand P. D'Amato, the brother of
former Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, died July 7 at the Albert Einstein
Medical Center in the Bronx. Noyer, who lived in Larchmont, N.Y.,
was 40.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was a pulmonary embolism, his mother, Mary Noyer,
said.
</P>
<P>
   Noyer was best known for his four-year-long investigation of
Armand D'Amato, a Long Island lawyer and the younger brother of the
senator. Armand D'Amato was convicted in 1993 of mail fraud, but
the conviction was later overturned on the ground of insufficient
evidence. Senator D'Amato was never a defendant in the case, which
nonetheless prompted a two-year Senate Ethics Committee
investigation of allegations that he engaged in influence peddling.
</P>
<P>
   Noyer was born on Aug. 11, 1958, in Manhattan, a son of Maurice
L. Noyer, a lawyer, and Mary Noyer, a real estate broker. A 1980
graduate of Georgetown University, Noyer was editor of the law
review at Fordham Law School and a clerk for Joseph McLaughlin,
then a judge for the Eastern District.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, Noyer joined the U.S. attorney's office for the Eastern
District, where he spent eight years. In 1994, he returned to
private practice, and eventually became general counsel of Barclays
Bank PLC.
</P>
<P>
   Noyer is survived by his mother, Mary Noyer of Westhampton
Beach, N.Y.; his wife, Pamela Davis; a son, Griffin; a daughter,
Claire; his brother, Charles Noyer of Larchmont, and four sisters,
Christine Seaver of Palo Alto, Calif., Elizabeth Feld of Plandome,
N.Y., Mary Ann Noyer of Westport, Conn., and Nadine Rote of
Larchmont. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
