<SLUG> BC-NY-STATE-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGREEMENT AT LAST IN ALBANY ON $73 BILLION BUDGET DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ko) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Three-and-a-half months after the state budget
was due, legislative leaders and Gov. George E. Pataki have agreed
to the outlines of a $73 billion deal, legislators and top aides
said Friday. The plan would salt away $1.8 billion to pay for
future tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly speaker, Sheldon Silver, and the Senate majority
leader, Joseph Bruno, told legislators Friday to return on Monday
to convene conference committees to draft a detailed budget over
the next week or two.
</P>
<P>
   The news follows one of the most rancorous iterations of what
has become a uniformly rancorous process. For months, Silver has
accused the governor of sacrificing New York's needs to his
ambitions for national office, while Pataki has charged that the
speaker was trying to spend so much that the state would rack up
huge deficits and have to forgo promised tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   This year, for the first time, a state law provides that
legislators' salaries will be withheld as long as the budget is
overdue, adding friction to an already heated atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Legislature passed a spending plan that pleased
nearly everyone, only to have the governor veto $1.6 billion worth
of items in it, most of them programs prized by the Democrats. That
experience cast a long shadow over this year's budget talks, with
Silver determined not to repeat it.
</P>
<P>
   This week's breakthrough, officials said, rested in part on
Pataki's assurances that he would not make widespread use of his
veto pen this year _ though some vetoes remain likely _ as long as
the Legislature remains within the agreed-to boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   The legislative leaders had agreed weeks ago to spend about $1.1
billion more than Pataki proposed in January, but the governor had
indicated that their figure was a few hundred million dollars too
high. In the last few days, Pataki agreed to the $1.1 billion in
additions, but how one arrives at that number relies heavily on
widely varying estimates of what some programs will cost, and he
insisted on calculating more conservatively than Silver had hoped.
There is still no accord on precisely how to reach that number, and
officials warned that the agreement could fall apart on this issue.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki appears to have achieved one of his two primary goals for
this budget: the state's $1.8 billion surplus from the fiscal year
that ended March 31 will be saved, not spent, to ensure that the
state will have enough money to absorb tax cuts that are already in
law, and are to go into effect over the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether he reached his other goal, to keep the
spending increase under the rate of inflation. It is an important
claim for a man who would like the national Republican Party to
consider him for the vice president's spot on next year's ticket
and who, after last year's 6 percent overall spending increase, is
trying to reassert his credentials as a fiscal conservative.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Pataki called for a 1.8 percent increase. Officials
are saying the budget outline that the leaders have agreed to raise
spending by more than 3 percent. But state lawmakers routinely
overestimate expenses when drafting budgets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
