<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GUNCONTROL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: BREAKING A GUN-CONTROL BARRIER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, July 17:
</P>
<P>
   A group of about 95 Colorado teen-agers visited the Capitol this
week to talk about the shootings at Columbine High School and the
need for more stringent restrictions on firearms. They left with
the unmistakable impression that the Republican-led Congress has
yet to grasp the devastation caused by gun violence. Fortunately,
the Democratic presidential contenders do grasp the problem.
Marking a possible turning point in the gun-control debate, Vice
President Al Gore and former Sen. Bill Bradley have offered
gun-control plans that go beyond anything being considered by
Congress and even beyond the sound but limited measures put forth
by the administration.
</P>
<P>
   Braving a longstanding political taboo, the two contenders have
begun to broach the core issues of gun licensing and registration.
Last week Bradley laid out an agenda that includes a ban on the
cheap handguns known as ``Saturday night specials,'' a requirement
that all would-be gun purchasers first pass a safety course and
obtain a license, and another that all guns be registered with the
government.
</P>
<P>
   Gore stopped short of Bradley's call for universal gun
registration. Instead he proposed a new system of photo licensing
and testing for handgun purchasers, and a system that requires
dealers to report the serial numbers of all handguns sold, in order
to help police trace guns used in crimes. But presumably the names
of the purchasers would not be furnished, so the police would still
have to rely on gun-shop owners to do any records searches _ a
potentially time-consuming step that Bradley's full-fledged
registration plan would avoid.
</P>
<P>
   Gore apparently believes that his plan will be more palatable to
voters in those states where the National Rifle Association is most
influential. But the NRA cares little for such differences. It has
already attacked Gore's plan as a step toward an all-out handgun
ban.
</P>
<P>
   The existing system for regulating guns is an inefficient
patchwork. National polls show that there is extensive support for
the dramatic changes that both Democratic candidates have now
endorsed, and the Gore and Bradley camps are betting that it is
good politics to respond aggressively to the widespread hunger for
real reform.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican front-runner, George W. Bush, has so far taken
another approach. Portraying himself as a moderate, he has
nonetheless backed the watered-down gun-show provision offered by
the NRA's friends in Congress. He recently signed a measure in
Texas to bar localities from suing gun manufacturers for
irresponsible marketing practices. Bush says such suits are based
on exotic legal theories concocted by greedy lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, these suits have applied traditional negligence
standards to hold gun makers accountable for the damage caused by
their products _ a point U.S. District Judge Jack Weinstein
underscored in his recent ruling upholding last spring's jury
verdict against gun dealers in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Bradley have added something new to the Democratic
race. They have also made it harder for Bush to ignore the strong
popular support for strict gun control.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
