</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-DEVILRAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS,   9, DEVIL RAYS, 7, AS REED HOLDS ON  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Luck must be on Rick Reed's side this
season because he sure hasn't been all that good.
</P>
<P>
   A 16-game winner a year ago, Reed earned his seventh victory
Friday night after the Mets hung on to beat the Tampa Bay Devil
Rays, 9-7, at Tropicana Field.
</P>
<P>
   In his first game after the All-Star Game break, Reed (7-3) was
hoping for a fresh start. Instead, it was more of the same problems
that plagued him during the first half of the season: inconsistent
control, untimely hits, another big home run.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Reed won, as the Mets (52-39) improved to 25-11 since
June 6.
</P>
<P>
   Reed allowed eight hits and five runs in six innings. The
33-year-old right-hander squandered leads of 3-0 and 5-3, but the
Mets' offense, which banged out 15 hits, kept bailing him out.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Piazza had three hits and drove in two runs, and Matt
Franco hit a two-run home run. But the Mets' offense really turned
on the tandem of Rickey Henderson and Roger Cedeno.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson, batting leadoff, and Cedeno, hitting ninth, combined
for five runs, five stolen bases, three walks, four singles and a
double.
</P>
<P>
   Cedeno's two steals give him 50 in the Mets' 91 games, tying him
for third most in a season in franchise history. Lance Johnson
stole 50 bases in 1996, and Mookie Wilson stole 54 in 1983 and a
club-record 58 in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone, Henderson stole three bases Friday night. It
was the first time he had done so since Sept. 7, 1997, and he has
27 steals for the year.
</P>
<P>
   The two have hit top and bottom the last two nights thanks to
the designated hitter in the American League park. Henderson even
drove in Cedeno with the go-ahead run in the sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   That was fortunate for Reed, who has a 4.96 earned run average,
which is almost a run and a half worse than his ERA last season,
when he struggled the final month.
</P>
<P>
   Reed's signature, his pinpoint control, has been anything but
precise this year. After issuing a pair of walks Friday night, Reed
has walked 34 in 98 innings, more walks than he gave up in 1998 (29
in 2121/3 innings) and 1997 (31 walks in 2081/3 innings).
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, he analyzed his problem. ``I really think it's just
been mechanics,'' said Reed, who allowed a two-run, game-tying
homer to Herbert Perry in the fifth. ``One game, I've got it. The
next game, I don't. If I could just string together two or three
good games, that might get me on a roll.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Mets to make a run at a post-season berth, they will
probably need just that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
