<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-N.Y.-POWER-LAWSUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS BACK SUING OF CON ED  
</HEADLINE>
  (ko) 
 By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Lawmakers from both major parties have proposed
legislation that would make it easier for New York City to sue
Consolidated Edison over the power failures that darkened upper
Manhattan last week.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's administration filed a
lawsuit against Con Edison, seeking to recover the costs of
providing additional police officers, firefighters and other city
employees during the blackout. The administration also accused the
utility of gross negligence.
</P>
<P>
   But it is unclear how the courts will respond to the suit. The
state's highest court ruled in 1984 that Con Edison did not have to
pay the city the roughly $20 million that it was seeking in a
similar lawsuit for the additional police and fire protection it
provided during the blackout of 1977, during which riots and
looting broke out.
</P>
<P>
   It cited litigation involving the 1979 reactor accident at the
Three Mile Island nuclear plant in Pennsylvania and other cases in
ruling that there was no explicit legislative action authorizing
recovery of such public expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   So lawmakers here in the state capital are seeking to insure
that the city's current lawsuit moves ahead, proposing legislation
that would require all utilities to pay for additional public
services that are provided during power failures resulting from
``gross negligence.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill's main sponsors are leaders from both parties: Assembly
Speaker Sheldon Silver and Guy J. Velella, the senior deputy
majority leader in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Velella, who represents part of the Bronx, said the legislation
would remove the most significant legal hurdle to the city's
lawsuit against Con Edison. He said taxpayers should not be
required to pay for additional city services that were needed as a
result of the utility's failure.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Liipfert, a spokeswoman for Con Edison, declined to
comment on the matter, saying she had not reviewed the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   More than 200,000 people in upper Manhattan lost power at the
height of an intense heat wave last week, when underground power
lines that bring electricity from substations to the neighborhoods
failed and several power lines caught fire. Con Edison said it was
forced to shut off all electricity north of 155th Street in
Manhattan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
