<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-A&AMP;P-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COETZER DEFEATS KOURNIKOVA AT A&AMP;P CLASSIC 
</HEADLINE>
 (ko) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAHWAH, N.J. _ Amanda Coetzer ignored the pleas of a partisan
crowd yelling encouragement for Anna Kournikova Friday night, and
with a steady game won, 6-4, 6-4, to advance to the semifinals of
the A&AMP;P Tennis Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Coetzer, at 5 feet 2 inches, is 6 inches shorter than
Kournikova, but she does not give up on her shots.
</P>
<P>
   And while the 19-year-old Kournikova is 9 years younger than
Coetzer, she was unable to develop a power game Friday. Her
forehand strokes were not formidable enough to allow her to charge
the net.
</P>
<P>
   Kournikova also appeared to be in physical distress most of the
evening. She bent often to stretch her legs, or squatted as if she
was trying to stretch her muscles. After the match she received
medical treatment, and did not appear at the news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had severe dehydration,'' said John Korff, the event's
director. ``She practiced a lot today and has cramps from both her
feet to her whole body. They're giving her lots of fluids.''
</P>
<P>
   The weather was in the 90s during the day when she practiced and
in the 80s when the match began. Still, it was uncomfortable for
spectators, let alone players.
</P>
<P>
   It almost seems as if Kournikova brings her own cheering section
_ young men who root for the tall and tanned Russian teen-ager. One
group of four shirtless young men, in fact, spelled out her first
name, each with a letter emblazoned on his chest.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Kournikova's popularity, Coetzer said with a smile,
``Nobody painted my name on their chest.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter. Coetzer, a South African, overcame Kournikova, though
Kournikova nearly forced a third set. She was down, 5-1, in the
second set when Coetzer began to tire. Or perhaps Kournikova
finally began to hit winners instead of the unforced errors that
hounded her through much of the match.
</P>
<P>
   Kournikova pushed Coetzer to five match points before losing.
Coetzer faces Chanda Rubin on Saturday in one semifinal, while
Jennifer Capriati meets Erika deLone in the other. DeLone toppled
Nicole Pratt, 7-5, 7-6 (7-1), Friday. The first semifinal starts at
noon.
</P>
<P>
   Coetzer said she was hitting the best strokes of her life right
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm among the oldest players,'' said Coetzer, the world's
ninth-ranked player, ``and what keeps me going is the fact I
haven't reached my full potential. I've made some racquet changes
and over the last few months I'm hitting the ball harder.''
</P>
<P>
   This event used to count toward the WTA Tour point standings but
became an exhibition in 1990, when Steffi Graf won it for the
fourth time.
</P>
<P>
   Graf, who won her sixth A&AMP;P Tennis Classic title last year,
returned to her home in Florida Friday after her withdrawal because
of illness in a quarterfinal match with Capriati on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Graf's agent, Phil de Picciotto, said Graf was still suffering
from the effects of bronchitis.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it is no more serious than it was,'' de Picciotto said of
Graf's condition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
